<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GAZA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WATCHES AS PALESTINIANS VOTE TO RESCIND 1964 PROVISION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip _ In a dramatic but symbolic gesture for
peace applauded by President Clinton, members of the Palestine
National Council raised their hands Monday to show support for
removing charter provisions calling for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, cloaked in security in this desert city that has seen
so much violence, became the first U.S. president to visit
Palestinian territory as he championed peace with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He convinced Palestinian Chairman Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu to meet with him at a border
checkpoint Tuesday to try to revive a stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a remarkable day,'' Clinton said, thanking the
Palestinians for recommitting themselves to peace. ``I know that
the Palestinian people stand at a crossroads: behind you a history
of dispossession and dispersal; before you the opportunity to shape
a new Palestinian future on your own land.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu continued to signal that Israel will delay
withdrawing its troops from portions of the West Bank, a move
required by Friday under the 2-month-old Wye River Memorandum.
Although Netanyahu called the council's action Monday significant,
he made new demands of the Palestinians that he said must be met
before Israel agrees to cede more territory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent his second day in the Middle East trying to sort
through shifting signals and brash pronouncements by Arafat and
Netanyahu, who are trying to settle internal political disputes as
well as negotiate with each other.
</P>
<P>
   At the council meeting, Arafat spoke to the hundreds of
delegates ``from my heart to your hearts.'' He asked them for a
show of hands to remove the organization's 1964 charter provision
calling for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   They first raised their hands, then stood spontaneously, some
forming a ``V'' for victory with their fingers. Only a small
segment remained seated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that this will close this chapter forever, for we have
carried out our commitments and obligations. And we are determined
to continue our quest for peace .. and coexistence on the basis of
respecting justice and international legitimacy,'' Arafat said in
Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   Like Netanyahu the previous day, Arafat voiced his commitment to
the Wye River Memorandum and to peace with Israel. But he also
listed a series of moves by Israelis, from their refusal to release
political prisoners to their continuing to build Jewish
settlements, that he maintained violated the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Israel had demanded the symbolic vote despite forecasts that
Arafat might be unable to muster the required PNC support. The
Palestinian leader had declared in 1996 that the charter provisions
were nullified and restated that commitment in a letter in January
to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to seek a vote as part of the Wye River accord, which
also called for Israel to cede portions of the West Bank in return
for security guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, who on Monday accused the Palestinians of meeting
none of their Wye agreement obligations, offered conditional
support for the vote, saying it was but one step.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important step. I welcome it. It is a positive
step. But you have to recognize that it is only the first step, and
further steps are needed,'' he said in Jerusalem. ``Words are
significant, but if they are opposed to deeds, then that's not
enough. There have to be acts as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu again demanded that Arafat renounce the Palestinians'
stated intention to declare an independent state next year with
Jerusalem as its capital. Israel will not proceed with the Wye
River plan unless there is such a renunciation, the prime minister
said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Arafat reiterated his call for a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   The United States maintains that statehood and Jerusalem are
issues to be discussed in final peace-status talks.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright confirmed that Israel
probably will not meet Friday's deadline for a second phase of
troop redeployment that would turn more West Bank land over to
Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Key provisions in the Wye accord call for Israel to withdraw
from 13 percent of the West Bank land it controls. Israel made the
first withdrawal, a 2 percent pullback, and was scheduled to make
its second Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there are indications that it will not happen on
schedule; but we hope very much that it can be as close to the
schedule as possible,'' Albright said. She said the redeployment
will be one the key topics when the three leaders meet today.
</P>
<P>
   They will convene at Erez, the main Israeli-Palestinian
checkpoint between the Gaza Strip and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye River Memorandum has faltered in recent weeks. An
Israeli refusal to release political prisoners, for example,
prompted Palestinian youths to provoke violent clashes with Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu, confronted by hard-liners opposed to the accord,
narrowly averted his government's collapse last week. He appears in
no hurry to implement peace provisions while the political
situation is turbulent.
</P>
<P>
   At the council meeting, Clinton spoke movingly of meeting
Palestinian children whose fathers are Israeli prisoners and of
meeting Israeli children whose fathers died in violent
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way for both sets of children to get their
lives back and to go forward,'' Clinton said. ``Palestinians must
recognize the right of Israel and its people to live safe and
secure lives today, tomorrow and forever. Israel must recognize the
right of Palestinians to aspire to live free today, tomorrow and
forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's appearance was an enormous triumph for Arafat, whose
Palestine Liberation Organization the United States refused to
recognize until a decade ago because of its terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The president cut a red ribbon opening the new Gaza
International Airport that Palestinians hope will fuel economic
development in this impoverished area.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, dressed in his trademark kaffiyeh, greeted Clinton with
enthusiasm, hailing him as a peacemaker. The representatives of the
Palestinian organizations clapped loudly and rhythmically for
Clinton and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton. Daughter Chelsea
also sat in the audience.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. flags were pinned to cinder block hovels and were carried
by school children.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous posters of Clinton and Arafat lined shop windows. Signs
read: ``Welcome to Palestine, Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   On the down side, security forces arrested scores of suspects
whom they feared might cause trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
