<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPITZER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N . Y . 'S NEW ATTORNEY GENERAL: A CENTRIST WITH A PASSION FOR
IDEAS
</HEADLINE>
  (See also VACCO-CONCEDE, EDIT-NY-ATTY-GENERAL) 
 (nk) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To most New Yorkers, Eliot Spitzer, the state
attorney general-elect, is a largely unfamiliar figure, known, if
at all, more as the scion of a wealthy family than as a man driven
by serious ideas.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Spitzer about complicated issues like utility regulation
or milk pricing, and he can discourse at length, with a grasp of
detail that might well bring to mind that more famous policy wonk
in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ideas _ and the question of how best to apply them _ have always
engaged and energized Spitzer, his friends say. As a student at
Harvard Law School in the early 1980s, for example, he teamed with
legal scholar Abram Chayes to publish an article about arms control
in space. A few years ago, to put some of his ideas into practice,
he helped to found a public-interest law firm with a centrist
ideology. It tries to serve as a counterpoise to groups like the
New York Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Given the odds of beating an incumbent in a statewide race _ and
polls that consistently showed Spitzer, a Democrat, behind Attorney
General Dennis Vacco, a Republican _ even Spitzer's closest
advisers were surprised on election night when he seemed to be
inching toward victory. But people who have known Spitzer for many
years say he can always be counted on to achieve his goals, no
matter how far-fetched they may seem.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for example, the time he and two law school
classmates, all merely casual runners, decided on a whim to
participate in the New York City Marathon. The event was a scant
two months away, and none of them had begun to train for it. ``Very
quickly, two of the three of us fell by the wayside,'' recalled
Clifford Sloan, now a lawyer in Washington. ``But Eliot kept at it
and ran in the marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was in law school, Spitzer got his first taste of the
attorney general's office as a summer intern. ``He was the best law
student I ever had,'' said his then-boss, Lloyd Constantine, who
headed the antitrust bureau for 11 years and is in charge of
Spitzer's transition team. ``He was very smart, very precocious,
and he clearly wanted to have a career in public service.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, when Constantine set his up his own law firm, Spitzer
became one of his partners.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Spitzer, a former assistant district attorney in
Manhattan, had already made one unsuccessful attempt to win the
Democratic nomination for attorney general. The only political
newcomer in the race, he finished last in a field of four
candidates after spending more than $4 million of his own money on
his campaign. Many New York City lawyers wrote him off as a child
of privilege _ his father, Bernard, is a successful real estate
developer _ who was trying to buy his way into state office. The
younger Spitzer is also a product of the Riverdale Country Day
School, Horace Mann School and Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   Many lawyers were also turned off by his support of the death
penalty, a position that puts him at odds with his wife, Silda
Wall, a lawyer who belongs to New York Lawyers Against the Death
Penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Some were also unhappy with his campaign pledge to strengthen
the crime-fighting role of the attorney general's office. Under
Robert Abrams, who served as the state's top lawyer from 1979
through 1993, the office had gained prestige for its efforts in
enforcing environmental, civil rights and consumer laws.
</P>
<P>
   To blunt some of the criticism, Spitzer spent much of 1996 and
1997 traveling around the state in a van, getting to know the
state's political infrastructure and making friends. If a speaker
at a political dinner canceled at the last moment, Spitzer was
always ready to serve as a stand-in, said John Marino, a strategist
for Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer probably made even more friends by contributing
generously to other campaigns around the state, doling out $50,000,
for example, to the local party machine in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   But in influential legal circles, his negatives still dogged
him. He was considered the weakest of the four candidates running
in this year's Democratic primary election for attorney general.
About 100 lawyers who had worked for Abrams supported one of
Spitzer's opponents, state Sen. Catherine Abate. Many Democrats saw
him as too much of a centrist and gave him only grudging support in
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   He alienated some liberals in May 1995 when he helped set up a
branch of a nonprofit, nonpartisan group now known as the Center
for the Community Interest. ``In a nutshell,'' said Dennis Saffran,
the center's regional director, ``we are the common-sense counter
to the ACLU on crime and quality-of-life issues, without going to
the other extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   The center has defended the state law allowing the police to
publicize the whereabouts of released sex offenders and the New
York City ordinance banning strip clubs and shops that sell
sexually explicit material from residential neighborhoods. The
group also helped promote legislation to require hospitals to
notify mothers and doctors when newborn babies test positive for
HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the organization's positions have led critics like
Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties
Union, to conclude that Spitzer, like his predecessor, will seek
``to transform the attorney general's office into a super state
district attorney's office, with a focus on criminal law
enforcement, rather than protecting civil rights.''
</P>
<P>
   While Spitzer has drawn criticism from the New York City bar
association's more liberal faction, he has impressed other lawyers
with his pragmatic approach to criminal justice and other urban
issues.
</P>
<P>
   His supporters say that Spitzer's rejection of many traditional
liberal values stems from deeply held beliefs, not just the desire
to win public office. ``This guy is a passionate centrist,'' said
Ryan Karben, who managed Spitzer's campaign in Rockland County.
``He hugs the center, not only out of political expediency. It's an
intellectual imperative for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer's most serious misstep during the campaign was his lack
of candor about how much help he had received from his father, who
lent him millions of dollars to repay the bank loans for his 1994
campaign. ``He thought it was a very personal thing,'' said Marino,
who, like the other advisers to the campaign, thought Spitzer
should have addressed the issue earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In the final weeks, the attorney general's race was conducted
mainly through television advertising and faxed press releases. On
the campaign trail _ what there was of it _ Spitzer's inexperience
showed, and he often seemed ill at ease. Instead of kissing a
baby's cheek, he was more inclined to hand the infant a campaign
flier.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet, who was Spitzer's boss in
the mid-1980s, said his former clerk has the right stuff for an
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is really required,'' Sweet said, ``is a grasp of the
issues, a definition of the concept of the office, an understanding
of what the office can accomplish, and some sense of vision. I
think he has all those things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
