<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LAWMAKERS RAISING NEW OBJECTIONS TO TERMS OF NFL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Legislative leaders' hopes for trouble-free
passage of a stadium deal with the New England Patriots were set
back today when several Democrats said they would fight for the
state to retain the right to sell the stadium's name, which could
be worth tens of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut General Assembly will hold a special session on
Tuesday to consider a tentative agreement between Gov. John Rowland
and the Patriots to move the team from the Boston area to a new
stadium in downtown Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the state would build the $375 million
stadium, and the Patriots would use it rent free for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland and legislative leaders had predicted swift approval
after owner Robert Kraft agreed on Sunday to reduce the state's
potential financial liability if the National Football League team
is unable to sell all of the stadium's luxury seats and boxes.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, several Democrats in the House of Representatives
lobbied colleagues to build support for an amendment to strip the
Patriots of the naming rights, which were among the many sweeteners
in the deal that led stadium economists to say that Connecticut had
handed Kraft one of the most lucrative deals in American sports.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Alex Knopp, D-Norwalk, called the naming rights ``another
unfortunate example of the lack of balance in the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The state bears all the risk and the owner reaps all the
profits,'' Knopp said. ``There is still a lot of unsettledness
among legislators about the lack of investigation and public
participation in the details of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Moira Lyons, D-Stamford, warned that the
deal was set and that any further tinkering ``obviously puts a
question mark on the ability to bring the Patriots here.''
</P>
<P>
   While any further changes to the deal would allow the Patriots
to walk away with no penalty, Jonathan Kraft, a son of the owner
who is the team's chief negotiator, said he would continue to
consider legislators' concerns even as the bill was debated on
Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
