<HEADLINE>
SPIKE LEE MOVING; MAILER STUDYING  

</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Spike Lee made Brooklyn the backdrop for such films
as ``Do the Right Thing'' and ``Jungle Fever,'' and his production
company has a Brooklyn telephone number. But Lee is getting a new
home number. He is leaving his old Brooklyn neighborhood for a $7
million town house on the Upper East Side of Manhattan, brokers
familiar with the deal say.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's old house, a five-story town house in Fort Greene, has
been on the market for several weeks. The broker who listed the
21-foot-wide Victorian house refused to comment, but has been
circulating a color brochure that describes the towel warmers in
the bathroom and the ground floor garden. Other brokers said the
price was in the $900,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was in his new neighborhood Monday. ``I go to the gym around
the corner,'' said another real estate person familiar with the
deal, ``and he was working out next to me, trying to be incognito
with a baby blue ski cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Mailer vs. Goethe?
</P>
<P>
   Norman Mailer is many things: a literary icon; a Brooklyn-born
braggart who has feuded famously with other well-known writers; the
septuagenarian author of mind-bogglingly complicated best sellers
that many critics consider operatic-quality songs of himself.
</P>
<P>
   In English.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, he is studying German at Berlitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still that fire in his eyes,'' said Jeff Lackey, an
instructor who encountered Mailer at Berlitz, on West 51st Street
near Fifth Avenue. ``He has that take-no-prisoners,
I'll-tear-your-heart-out attitude projecting from his eyes.''
Lackey said the word was that Mailer wanted to read Goethe the way
Goethe wrote it. No translations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He speaks three languages badly: Spanish, French and German,''
said his assistant, Judith McNally. ``Every three years he tries to
freshen up one of the three. This year it's German's turn.''
</P>
<P>
   A Third Helping &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tina Brown, who left The New Yorker for a magazine venture with
Miramax, saw the Miramax film ``Shakespeare in Love'' on Saturday
night. This was not one of those premieres that celebrities are
always going to, but the 9:50 at Cinema I on Third Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My third time,'' she said. She took her husband, Harry Evans,
who had been away for the premiere, and said she liked it so much
she might go back for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Did he like it? She handed the telephone to him. He called it
``funny, witty and droll'' and was saying something about ``a
razzle-dazzle romp'' when she took the telephone back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't talk too long,'' she said. ``This is a reporter you're
talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrap Him Up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Morgenstern wondered what the crowd outside at Barneys was
staring at Monday. ``My mom pulled me to the third one,'' she said,
referring to one of the fastidiously decorated windows. ``She was
clutching hard. Normally she does that when she sees a famous
person. I was looking toward the left and he was towards the
right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He'' was her boyfriend, Bill Webber, sitting in the window and
holding a sign asked her to marry him.
</P>
<P>
   Webber had asked Barneys to let him propose this way because he
and Ms. Morgenstern are fans of the window designer Simon Doonan,
who, among other things, made a Christmas tree of Tic-Tac mints.
The store helped Webber, a 27-year-old financial analyst, with his
hair and makeup. But his clothing was his own, a Barneys spokesman
said, ``and he fit right in.''
</P>
<P>
   After she finally noticed him, they kissed through the plate
glass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It tastes a lot better in person,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
