<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV SPORTS: SEIFERT NUDGED ASIDE, BUT WILL HE BE ALONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the news reported Sunday on CBS's ``The NFL Today,'' Jim
Nantz reported nothing of the network's benching of George Seifert
from the studio program.
</P>
<P>
   The former San Francisco 49ers coach is on hiatus, like a sitcom
in trouble, until the playoffs. His pine vacation is CBS's first
admission that at least one of its three neophyte analysts _
Seifert, Brent Jones and Marcus Allen _ has performed well below
expectations. But they all have. Their inexperience has forced
Nantz to control the program too much rather than rely on strong
partners, an advantage enjoyed by ESPN's Chris Berman and Fox's
James Brown.
</P>
<P>
   For a network to tell one of its studio stars to stay home
during the crucial last weeks of the regular season is
extraordinary. But telling Seifert not to come to work says more
about his role in the show than about rumors that he will leave to
coach Seattle or Cleveland. After all, CBS held on to Lou Holtz as
a college football studio analyst _ and even had him analyze a
National Football League game on Dec. 6 _ until the moment he left
to coach the University of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unusual, but everybody's goal is to work to put on the
best show there is,'' said Leslie-Anne Wade, a spokeswoman for CBS
Sports.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, hiring Seifert, Jones and Allen was
questionable, especially with the availability of Craig James, the
network's college football studio analyst, as well as Cris
Collinsworth, Randy Cross and Paul Maguire. Collinsworth went to
Fox, Cross became CBS's No. 2 game analyst, and Maguire moved to
ESPN. Creating a show with untried analysts made no sense if proven
spark plugs were available.
</P>
<P>
   What has gone wrong? Seifert's reserved demeanor, no secret to
even a casual fan, does not fit into an atmosphere in which
extroversion thrives. Seifert's ability to offer a coach's
perspective _ which Wade said would be used during the playoffs _
has been drowned out in the competition for time, and attempts to
play to his strength on a regular basis were not plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has brought an obnoxious, disingenuous type of banter to
the show, and his craving for the last word makes him look greedy.
(And can he stop smiling?) Allen's penchant for stumbling over his
words indicates a failure to find a comfortable way to express
himself. Also, viewers get little sense that Allen and Jones are
obsessively telephoning league and team contacts for news.
</P>
<P>
   Seifert's benching led CBS to bring James on in relief; James is
a seasoned pro with a definite presence who elevated ``The NFL
Today.''
</P>
<P>
   If CBS viewed Seifert as dispensable _ and is admitting the show
is an evolution-in-progress _ will Jones or Allen be next to take a
forced leave?
</P>
<P>
   Fox's Antics
</P>
<P>
   Heading into its final season of carrying National Hockey League
games, Fox Sports seems bent on irking the league. Fox has produced
a series of promotional spots that extol fighting _ an image the
NHL has tried to flee _ instead of using the sort of edgy, usually
humorous sketches it used in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a montage of glorious shots is accompanied by an
announcer saying: ``Maybe it's the pageantry of this glorious game
that's born on the frozen ponds of youth. Maybe it's the great ones
who amaze us forever, providing those golden moments that will be
permanently etched in our minds and on the Stanley Cup.'' The
imagery then shifts to fighting, with the words, ``Maybe it's two
guys beating the bleep out of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Solomon, the league's chief operating officer, said, ``I
think it's not the right message, or the appropriate message for
promoting the NHL.'' He said he has unsuccessfully complained to
David Hill, president of Fox Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon does not know why Fox has taken this tack, and he
refused to speculate whether it was anger over the negotiations
that led to ABC's snaring the league's network deal from Fox
starting next season, or Fox's disappointing NHL ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Said Vince Wladika, a Fox spokesman: ``We've promoted hockey for
four years in many ways, but they didn't boost ratings. So we
thought, `Let's go back to the basic instinct and see if it
works.''' The spots will start running regularly during Fox's
broadcasts of the NFL playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   There are no fights in the ad campaign for Keith Olbermann's
Jan. 5 start as the star anchorman for cable's Fox Sports News. In
one spot, he parodies Charles Barkley's Nike commercial claim that
he is not a role model. ``Just because I say, `From way downtown _
bang!' that does not mean I should raise your kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In another, he says that during his news stint at MSNBC, he
missed coining ``absolutely meaningless catch phrases'' and racing
through obscure sports names like Zenon Andrushyshyn and Vitaly
Potapenko.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
