<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISKIND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE REPORT DETAILS NIGHTMARE AT ABORTION CLINIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER AND SUSIE STECKNER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A doctor too busy eating his lunch to check on a
patient who was bleeding heavily. Staff members so inexperienced
that they didn't know where the pens were. An administrator who
asked for medical help 20 minutes away rather than from the
hospital across the street.
</P>
<P>
   And when it was clear the patient was in serious trouble, the
doctor's phoned-in advice: ``Well what do you want me to do? Call
911.''
</P>
<P>
   A Phoenix police investigation report, obtained by ``The Arizona
Republic,'' painted a picture of medical chaos on the day
33-year-old Lou Anne Herron died after going to the A-Z Women's
Center for an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' also obtained copies of a police investigation
into a full-term fetus who was nearly aborted at the clinic two
months after Herron's death.
</P>
<P>
   The Maricopa County Attorney's office is looking at the reports
to decide whether to charge Dr. John Biskind, 72 _ the doctor who
performed Herron's abortion April 17 and delivered the unidenti
fied baby _ and Carol Stuart, 61, the clinic administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind and his lawyer could not be reached for comment. Stuart
and her attorney declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   The police investigation included interviews with patients,
clinic workers and former employees. It found:
</P>
<P>
   _Staff members did not believe their own blood pressure
measuring instruments because Herron's readings were so low.
</P>
<P>
   _Herron asked for pain medication but staff couldn't give her
any because she was supposed to bring it herself.
</P>
<P>
   _Clinic records showed Herron had relatively low to normal blood
pressure readings minutes after employees called 911. Dr. Patricia
Graham, a medical reviewer working with the police, believed the
records were faked.
</P>
<P>
   What happened at A-Z to Herron was ``so far below acceptable
levels, it was scraping rock bottom,'' Graham said. Herron ``would
have survived with a minimal amount of care and treatment from Dr.
Biskind,'' Graham told investigators. Graham is director of
ambulatory services and perinatal addiction clinic at Maricopa
Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind in August gave up his Arizona medical license, avoiding
a BOMEX probe into Herron's death. In September, he surrendered his
medical license in his home state of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Herron arrived at A-Z, 1002 E. McDowell Road, at 8 a.m. April
17. She had been told to get there early and wait her turn.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't her first visit. On April 9, she went to A-Z looking
for an abortion. A test showed that the baby was 26 weeks along.
Herron was distraught because the clinic would not do abortions
past 24 weeks, Sylvia Aragon, a clinic employee, told police.
</P>
<P>
   Herron went back for another sonogram _ maybe one that would
show she wasn't past the legal limit. Another test was performed at
the Family Planning Institute, A-Z's sister clinic in Glendale.
That sonogram, employee Tammy Lomas told police, showed her at 24
weeks and four days _ still four days past the legal limit. Lomas
told police that she told clinic administrators that Herron was too
far along. Lomas said she never thought Herron would come back to
A-Z.
</P>
<P>
   But Herron went back a third time and got at least three more
sonograms. Michelle Price, an employee who took the sonograms, said
she believed the most accurate reading was 24 weeks and two days.
</P>
<P>
   She also knew that Biskind wanted the sonogram to come within
legal limits.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle told police that Biskind had told her ``when you do an
ultrasound you can turn the probe at different angles and get
different results.''
</P>
<P>
   Many employees recalled the flap over Herron's series of
sonograms but few remembered the woman who came in for the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Mabel Lopez, who had worked at the clinic for seven years,
remembered Herron as a ``nice girl'' _ one of maybe as many as 20 a
day who went into A-Z for abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Aragon told police that she asked Biskind why he was performing
an abortion on a woman so far along in her pregnancy. Biskind and
Stuart told Lopez that it was none of her business, she told
police.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Herron returned to A-Z. The night before, she had
called a friend, Barbara Blanc, for a ride to and from the clinic.
Even though she had known Blanc for 15 years, she hadn't told her
that she was pregnant. She didn't want anyone to know, Blanc told
police.
</P>
<P>
   Herron had already paid $1,250 to A-Z, either in cash or by
credit card. She was the first person in the clinic that day.
</P>
<P>
   While Herron was waiting for the procedure to start, Stuart was
telling personnel that they were going to be short-staffed.
</P>
<P>
   Employees said they knew that Lois Morengo, the clinic's
registered nurse, had told Stuart weeks in advance she was only
working a half day.
</P>
<P>
   According to A-Z's operating records, Herron went into surgery
around 12:30 p.m. Her abortion took longer than normal, about 45
minutes, employees told police.
</P>
<P>
   Herron was taken to the recovery room where Theresa Jimenez, who
had been working at A-Z for a week and half, was stationed. A-Z was
Jimenez's first job as a medical assistant. She had been hired to
answer phones and draw blood, not to work in the recovery room,
where usually a registered nurse watched over patients. Jimenez
told police she didn't even know where the recovery room's records
or pens were kept.
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez told police it was obvi ous from the start that Herron
was having problems. Georgina Obeso, another medical assistant who
had worked at A-Z for a month, said Herron was bleeding so heavily
that the blood was down to her knees.
</P>
<P>
   The more senior clinic employees saw how heavily Herron was
bleeding and went to tell Biskind. Lopez said he got mad that she
interrupted his lunch. ``Go talk to Carol,'' Biskind told Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Biskind went in to check on Herron, Jimenez said. He got
an intravenous tube started and told his patient there was nothing
to worry about, Jimenez said. Biskind told the staff to clean up
the bloody sheets and put down fresh bedding so they could tell if
she was bleeding any more, medical assistant Michelle Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Also during this time, Stuart called the Family Planning
Institute in Scottsdale, a sister clinic, asking an employee from
there to drive to A-Z to help out because they were having
problems. Two Scottsdale employees said Stuart's call came around 2
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The police timed how long it took to get from the Scottsdale
clinic to A-Z: 20 minutes and that was with one red light,
according to the police report.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time, Herron's friend Blanc had returned to the
clinic. While in the waiting room, she could hear Herron saying
``Help me, my legs are numb.'' She then heard someone tell Herron,
``There's nothing wrong with you. The bleeding has stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimenez told police she remembered talking with Blanc, telling
her that everything with her friend was fine. Jimenez told police
she wished she would have told Blanc ``Something is wrong, and you
should get &UR; her out of here.''
</P>
<P>
   Employees remember clustering around Herron as she grew more
pale. Jenil Begay, a three-year clinic employee who performed
ultrasounds, said they could barely hear a heartbeat and told
Stuart to call 911.
</P>
<P>
   Both she and Deryl Whitlock, the employee who drove in from
Scottsdale, again told Stuart to call 911. Stuart looked at them
like they were ``looney,'' Begay told police.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart wanted to call Biskind. No employee was sure when Biskind
left the clinic. Pager records subpoenaed by the police show that
he was paged by A-Z at 4:12 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   When he called in, Price told him that they couldn't find a
pulse and Herron's breathing was really slow. ``Well what do you
want me to do? Call 911,'' Biskind told her.
</P>
<P>
   Aragon made the 911 call at 4:17 p.m. According to the 911 tape
obtained by police, employees also asked ``Can we have you come to
the side door, right on 10th Street and try not to use the
sirens.''
</P>
<P>
   When paramedics arrived at A-Z, Herron was on a gurney and the
sheets underneath her were soaked with blood, said Capt. Arnie
Barajas of the Phoenix Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Herron appeared completely pale, cold and dead, he told police.
She had probably been dead for a while, Barajas said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Stuart contacted employees and told them not to
talk about Herron's death. Stuart told them they had done the best
they could.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks after Herron's death, at least three employees
resigned. At least two employees, including Whitlock, wrote
detailed notes _ obtained by police _ about the botched abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Whitlock, the Scottsdale medical assistant called in for help,
cried to her sister about the death, her sister said. A co-worker
said Whitlock told her she was having trouble sleeping at night and
dreamed about Herron.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cried a lot over that,'' said her sister, who asked to
remain anonymous. ``Not because she didn't do her job, but because
there was nothing she could do to save her when she got there. She
(Herron) was already dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitlock died in a May 3 traffic accident near Loop 303 and
Olive Avenue. She had a blood-alcohol level of about 0.23 percent,
according to an autopsy report. Her notes from the abortion were
found on the floorboard of her car and turned over to police. When
the family buried Whitlock, they also buried a set of notes with
her.
</P>
<P>
   About two months after Herron's death, the A-Z clinic was rocked
again _ this time by a botched abortion on a 17-year-old patient.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind was performing an abortion on a Cottonwood girl June 30
and had a test that showed the teen to have been pregnant for about
23.6 weeks. But the girl was actually 37 weeks along and ended up
giving birth to a baby girl.
</P>
<P>
   The test _ one of six ultrasounds performed by an employee
trained on the job _ was conducted with a broken machine, the
employee told police. Obeso, the medical assistant, took separate
ultrasound photos of the teen, Stuart picked out the best one and
Obeso then discarded the rest, Obeso said. The police report does
not indicate the condition of the machine.
</P>
<P>
   The baby girl was adopted immediately and taken to Texas, where
she remains, Phoenix police Detective Mike McCullough said. She is
evaluated regularly, but does not appear to have any lasting
injuries from the near-abortion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to police, the Cottonwood teen had broken up with a
boyfriend in February and was pregnant. She and her mother decided
she would have an abortion and picked out A-Z from a phone book ad.
</P>
<P>
   They traveled to the Phoenix clinic, with $1,250 cash in hand,
and told Stuart that the teen was probably just over four months
pregnant. But some staff members at the clinic weren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   The teen was large and looked much further along, Obeso told the
girl, and later, the police. But Millie Davis, a registered nurse
at the clinic that day, later told police that the teen didn't
appear to be full term, either.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the abortion, the teen was first on the schedule
and her mother was told the procedure would take 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   An hour passed. The mother, in a waiting room, worried about her
daughter. But staff members assured her the teen was all right, and
``it was just taking longer than expected,'' she said. She wanted
to see her daughter, but was told to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she told police she began to hear her daughter crying
loudly from a back room. Again, she asked to see her but was told
no.
</P>
<P>
   According to accounts by clinic staff, the teen was placed in a
recovery room and Biskind went back and forth between the recovery
room and operating room. He performed at least one abortion in the
meantime, if not more.
</P>
<P>
   The teen continued to cry out, so loudly Stuart at one point
told her to stop because she was scaring the other patients,
medical assistant Marianna Pierce told police.
</P>
<P>
   The contractions were coming and, Pierce thought, the baby would
follow any minute. Why, she asked Davis, was the teenager still at
the clinic instead of a hospital?
</P>
<P>
   Biskind assured them that when the teenager was ready to give
birth, he would deliver the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Sometime later, the teenager gave birth. Pierce and other
employees said they wanted to call 911, but were told not to by
Biskind. He reportedly said he didn't want any ``hysteria'' at the
clinic and didn't want to ``make a scene.''
</P>
<P>
   The baby, wrapped in a sheet with injuries to her head _ a skull
fracture and several lacerations _ was taken by employees across
the street to Good Samaritan Regional Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The police report said the baby was full term. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(This article's reporters can be reached at jodie.snyder(at)pni.com
and susie.steckner(at)pni.com via e-mail.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
