<P>
   ANGOLA-REBELS (Luanda) _ The sale of diamonds enables Angolan
rebels to keep fighting, and a U.N. embargo to cut off the sales
isn't working, according to a new study. By Suzanne Daley.
</P>
<P>
   QUEBEC-ENGLISH (Quebec) _ On dark days when the river broods and
mists hang heavy on outlying hills, it is easy to think of Quebec
as it once was, a distant outpost of the British Empire where hardy
people dreamed of doing great things that would not soon be
forgotten. Much of what they did has withstood the tides of time,
because for the last 174 years, the Literary and Historical Society
of Quebec has dedicated itself to preserving the memories and
achievements of the early settlers of one of North America's oldest
cities. These days, however, it is the society itself that is most
in need of preservation. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT16) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-DEPORTATIONS (New York) _ In the two years since Congress
passed tough anti-immigration laws to stem the flow of illegal
immigration to the United States, federal authorities have deported
almost 300,000 immigrants to countries all over the world, more
than twice the number of people who were sent back in the two years
before. The unprecedented high number of deportations have been
possible because for the first time the INS has both the
congressional mandate and the financial resources to investigate
and prosecute violators of immigration law, arrest immigrants with
criminal convictions as well as would-be immigrants at the border
and swiftly deport them from the United States _ sometimes in less
than 12 hours. By Mirta Ojito.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT17) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWYER (Undated) _ How one tobacco lawyer, fearing that
his fees would be slashed because of an overall cap on payments,
pumped up his bill from $50 million in hopes of getting a bigger
piece of the pie. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   PUERTORICO-ASSESS (San Juan, P.R.) _ An analysis of Sunday's
vote in Puerto Rico that backed the staus quo. By Mireya Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-CHINA-CONTRIBS _ After a two-year investigation of
Chinese political contributions to the 1996 election, federal
authorities have unearthed new evidence that Beijing's efforts were
part of a broader campaign to obtain access to American high
technology, according to lawyers and investigators. By Jeff Gerth,
David Johnston and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   REGULATING-DERIVATIVES (Undated) _ Arthur Levitt, the chairman
of the Securities and Exchange Commission, called on some of Wall
Street's leaders in the summer of 1994 with a warning. Congress was
asking pointed questions about whether complex financial contracts
called derivatives could topple a major financial institution or
even threaten the financial system. Wall Street, he said, should do
something. It did. Now Congress is considering how to oversee the
booming derivatives market. By David Barboza and Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphics have been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Goldman Sachs, stung by overseas
financial turmoil, reported Monday that its fourth-quarter profits
dropped 81 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CULTURE (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POLLOCK-NAMUTH (New York) _ The figure of Jackson Pollock _
action painter, dancing dripper, sullen rebel _ was made by Hans
Namuth's camera. Namuth's camera helped make Pollock famous and
Namuth's camera was blamed for Pollock's demise. Now, on the
occasion of Pollock's retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art,
Namuth's camera is there again. Namuth himself died eight years
ago. But his photographs and films are being used to strip away the
layers of paint and lore that have covered Pollock since the 1950s.
Of course, the stripping is tricky, because Pollock's tortured
relationship with Namuth is itself part of the myth. A critic's
notebook by Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STYLE (Moved in ``l'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ASSISTANTS-FASHION (Undated) _ Assistant designers are the
figures behind the famous names who often do much of the creative
work, as well as bringing fashion houses important social clients.
We look at assistants at the houses run by Bill Blass, Oscar de la
Renta and others. By Ruth LaFerla.
</P>
