   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MIRROR-TECH (Undated) _ Scientists at MIT recently announced
what may be the most significant advance in mirror technology since
Narcissus first became entranced by his image reflected on the
surface of a still pool of water. Their new invention, which they
are calling the perfect mirror because it combines the best
features of the two previously known types of mirrors, promises to
have significant applications in a vast variety of fields,
including higher bandwidth fiber optics, more efficient cellular
phones, energy conservation, medicine, spectroscopy and even,
perhaps, cake decoration. By Bruce Schechter. (ART ADV: Photo
[NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BODY-CLOCKS (Undated) _ In one of the weirdest-sounding
experiments in recent times, scientists at Cornell University
reported last spring that they had been able to reset human
biological clocks by shining intense light on the backs of people's
knees. This was, however, only one in a burst of stunning
experiments, that are revealing new insights into the ways that
biological organisms keep and tell time. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WIT (Undated) _ A doctor's view of sitting through the drama
``Wit,'' off-Broadway play about terminal cancer and chemotherapy,
where the patient is the hero. By Abigail Zuger, M.D.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT4) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AMELIA-EARHART (Undated) _ The latest trail of detective
work on Amelia Earhart has led to an official document in London
describing a lost collection of weather-beaten bone fragments. The
bones themselves have vanished, but measurements suggest the
subject was a woman, European and about 5'-6'' tall. This and some
other circumstantial evidence seemed interesting enough to
organizers of the American Anthropological Association that the
association acted as host for a recent news conference in
Philadelphia presented by the recovery group. Still, authorities
say, the mystery is far from being solved. By Malcolm Browne.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PATCH-ADAMS (Washington) _ The real Patch Adams reflects on
the movie ``Patch Adams'' that is about to make him famous. Like
the doctor in the movie, played by Robin Williams, the real-life,
53-year-old physician has spent his adult life thumbing his nose
(often Pinocchio-long or red and bulbous in clown's makeup) at the
medical establishment and at what he sees as its cancerous hunger
for profits. By David Stout.
</P>
