<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUNOTE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEARIN TO JOIN UNLV STAFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ During the annual coaching-staff turnover, Jeff
Kearin held Cal State Northridge's football program together.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as though head coach Ron Ponciano will give the
Matadors stability through this offseason, but Kearin is moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, an assistant head coach and coach of special teams and
quarterbacks, is leaving CSUN to rejoin former head coach John
Robinson at UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great opportunity to work for someone the caliber of
John Robinson,'' Ponciano said. ``(Kearin has) been our stabilizing
force. He's been the constant through three different coaches. He's
brought a sense of continuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano also said he expected linebackers coach Kevin Singleton
to accept a position with a shoe company and leave CSUN. Singleton
was in his second season with the Matadors.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin couldn't be reached for comment because he was in transit
from Los Angeles to Las Vegas on Monday. He's expected to be named
UNLV's tight-ends coach and special-teams coach this week.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin spent the last four seasons at CSUN, the longest stint of
any coach. He began his service under Dave Baldwin, which lasted
two years, and worked for Jim Fenwick one season. Kearin was a
finalist for the head-coaching position when Ponciano was hired.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin, who coached with Robinson at USC for four seasons, was
instrumental in the staff transitions during the changes at CSUN.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been the glue between football and academics, football
and compliance,'' Ponciano said. ``When you lose someone of Jeff's
caliber, it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kearin also served as CSUN's recruiting coordinator. Ponciano
said offensive line coach Aron Gideon might take over that role. He
added that he might elevate defensive-line coach Terrance Johnson
to full-time status. During the season Ponciano occasionally lauded
the job Johnson did.
</P>
<P>
   __ Season-ending awards: CSUN held its season-ending banquet
Sunday, with most categories broken into defense and offense. The
award winners:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Marcus Brady was named the offensive Most Valuable
Player, rush end Brennen Swanson was the defensive MVP and kicker
Manny Marquez grabbed the special-teams award; Newcomers of the
Year were running back Jaumal Bradley and cornerback Chazz Moore;
the Coach's Award went to offensive lineman David San Vicente and
linebacker Shayne Blakey; Most Improved were wide receiver Jimmy
Greninger and Blakey; Most Inspirational were Bradley and defensive
lineman Sean Beard; Iron Man awards were given to wide receiver
Eric Carpenter and safety Vito Clemente, and the Black Shirt award
for scout-team duty went to running back Alan Taylor and defensive
back Isaac Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   Also, cornerback Donnell Day won the Sefton Award as the player
who excelled in both athletics and academics; tight end Ryan Schatz
won the ``Big Team, Little Me'' award and was CSUN's
scholar-athlete award winner, wide receiver Drew Hill was voted the
Triple-A winner for achievements in academics, athletics and
attitude, and Levi Line was selected Defensive Lineman of the Year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
