r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-TAXES-2takes-LADN     12-15 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-TAXES-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S TAX PROPOSAL SEEKS TO KEEP L.A. COMPETITIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in 6th graf refers to Tuesday.) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Five years after his campaign to make the city
more business-friendly, Mayor Richard Riordan has released his
long-awaited proposal to reduce and simplify the city's tax
structure to make it more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The far-reaching proposal calls for reducing the number of tax
categories from 64 to 10 and cuts overall business taxes by $23
million a year _ an 8 percent reduction he hopes will be made up by
getting thousands of noncomplying small businesses to pay city
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The reform package exempts enterprises generating less than
$5,000 in gross receipts from the city business tax, gives new
businesses a one-year exemption and seeks to make better use of
state programs to divert more money to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan, in a meeting Monday with Daily News editors and
reporters, said the proposal is another step in his efforts to send
a message to the business community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are saying to businesses, we love you, we want you and we
want to make the city business-friendly,'' Riordan said. ``We think
this goes a long way to address the concerns we have had from
businesses and a way we can keep them here and attract new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals _ which will be publicly announced today _ must be
approved by the City Council and the voters to take effect. Riordan
said he wants the plan to go on the June 1999 ballot along with a
charter reform proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want it to be the year of reform,'' said Deputy Mayor
Noelia Rodriguez. ``Charter reform, tax reform and, hopefully,
school reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax proposals were developed over the course of the past two
years by a task force headed by Riordan, Councilman Richard
Alatorre as chairman of the City Council's Budget and Finance
Committee and a team of city officials. It contracted with Arthur
Anderson Co., the Milken Institute and others to analyze the city's
tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Those findings showed Los Angeles business taxes are higher and
more complicated than those in other cities. Business taxes provide
a higher percentage of city revenues _ 10 percent _ than in other
jurisdictions, accounting for $290 million of the city's general
fund.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of this is in lost businesses based in Los Angeles,
city officials said. One of the studies found that 66 percent of
those businesses leaving the city moved to another location within
Los Angeles County.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said one of the goals of the tax reform effort is to
spur growth among new businesses, achieve greater compliance with
the city business taxes and make a more common-sense tax system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already been talking with some businesses in neighboring
cities who are interested in moving here,'' Riordan said. ``If this
is approved, it will make us competitive with (neighboring) Culver
City, Beverly Hills and Santa Monica. We won't be lower than
Glendale or Burbank, but they charge their residents more than we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Under his plan, the filings for business permits would be phased
over to a fiscal year basis to help companies better coordinate
their payments rather than requiring them to be on a calendar year.
It also would help the city phase in a new approach.
</P>
<P>
   All businesses would have to take out a $20 permit, but firms
making under $5,000 a year would pay no city tax and start-ups
would have a one-year exemption from the business tax.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also wants to start an educational program for
businesses that pay a use tax to the state, to have them direct the
money back to the city. The study estimated it could bring in $29
million a year to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Under this program, firms that buy goods from out of state are
required to pay the equivalent of the sales tax. However, unless
they specify the money to go the city, it goes to the county
government. In turn, the county gives one-third of the money to the
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that alone amounts to $29 million a year,'' Riordan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Riordan wants to have a one-year program, called Amnesty
2000, to allow firms to pay back taxes without penalty. The mayor
said he believes the program would generate a first-year windfall
of $30 million and $10 million a year after that.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the report projects that businesses will save a total
of $23 million a year in reduced taxes. That would be covered with
the additional taxes from the use taxes, greater compliance and
efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, the report said, the revenue would come from the
success of new businesses and attracting other businesses to the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's major proposal is reducing the number of tax
categories to 10 for businesses and cutting the tax rate from a
high of $5.91 per $1,000 in gross receipts to $5.40 per $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the lowest rate would be $1.20 per $1,000 in
gross receipts. It would apply to such industries as agriculture,
fishing, mining, oil drilling, furniture, greeting cards,
telephones, advertising, computer programming, schools and
education services.
</P>
<P>
   The second category of $1.40 per $1,000 would include building
contractors, apparel products, newspapers and publications, metal
industries, auto dealers, food stores and transportation equipment,
among others.
</P>
<P>
   In the $1.60 per $1,000 category would be media broadcasting
services, general merchandise stores, garden supply, building
material, auto supplies, home supplies, restaurants, hotels and
motels.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   In the $2.50 per $1,000 category, businesses covered include
trucking and warehousing, car rental, motion picture production and
distribution services, dance studios and commercial sports.
</P>
<P>
   In the $3.10 per $1,000 category, transportation firms such as
taxis, bus charters and air transport firms would be included as
well as direct-mail advertising, real estate subdividers and repair
shops.
</P>
<P>
   The $4.35 per $1,000 category includes tobacco products,
trucking services, data processing, computer facilities management,
nursing homes, hospitals and amusement facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In the $5.20 per $1,000 category are veterinary services, real
estate agents, beauty shops and court reporting.
</P>
<P>
   The highest category of $5.40 per $1,000 would include oil
pipelines, gun sellers, security brokers, insurance agents, medical
services and accounting.
</P>
<P>
   Another major change is in the mayor's proposal to modify how
the film industry is taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Presently, it pays a maximum of $12,700 for a film depending on
its cost.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new proposal, companies that produce films costing
$50,000 or less would pay $133 and those with productions under
$100,000 would pay $266.
</P>
<P>
   Those higher-end productions would pay more, however. Films
costing up to $4.5 million would pay $11,970, up to $30 million
would pay $200 per $500,000 and those over that would pay a maximum
of $22,370.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
