<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-IMPEACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CONGRESSMEN GO PARTISAN ON IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER AND IVAN SCIUPAC  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The vote on whether to impeach President Clinton
won't come until Thursday at the earliest, but the six congressmen
in L.A's San Fernando Valley area say they've already made up their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   And they have decided _ to a man _ to stand by their parties.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans representing parts of the valley said Monday they'll
vote to try Clinton in the Senate on accusations of committing
perjury and obstructing justice. Their Democratic colleagues said
they won't.
</P>
<P>
   All took pains not to criticize each others' positions, but the
reasons for their decisions reflect a seemingly unbridgeable
divide.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue that letting Clinton go unpunished would wreck
the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he isn't accountable to our laws, why should a plumber be
or a journalist or anyone?'' asked Rep. Elton Gallegly, R-Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said allegations that Clinton tried to conceal an
affair with a former White House intern, while appalling, do not
warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, the corrosive effects of the president's
wrongdoing are far exceeded by the corrosive effects on America of
nullifying the people's choice (of Clinton) in 1996,'' said Rep.
Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills. ``The American people don't want
that choice nullified.''
</P>
<P>
   Public sentiment against impeachment has not gone unnoticed in
Congress. Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Los Angeles, said he will vote
against all articles of impeachment and is dismayed the Republicans
are voting party line rather than in the direction of public
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to be most responsive to their core, right-wing
conservatives who have always hated President Clinton,'' said
Waxman.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said they understand they could provoke
public wrath by pushing for impeachment. But the situation, they
said, demands that they vote their conscience regardless of the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Howard P. ``Buck'' McKeon, R-Santa Clarita, said he
is planning to vote for impeachment because he believes the
evidence is overwhelming that the president did lie under oath and
obstruct justice.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said he feels the president should not be able to get
away with crimes an ordinary citizen could not get away with. ``We
can't have two systems of justice in this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James E. Rogan, R-Pasadena, who represents a district with
more registered Democrats than Republicans, admitted his vote for
impeachment could affect his political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The solemnity of my own oath of office obliges me to do what
the president has failed to do: defend the rule of law despite any
personal or political costs,'' Rogan said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Several representatives said the vote's outcome remains too
close to call. While the Valley's House delegation may have already
decided on the issue, other representatives have yet to announce
their intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Two undecided congressmen, Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., and Jon D. Fox,
R-Pa., are accompanying Clinton on his diplomatic trip to the
Middle East. In an interview from Jerusalem on Monday, Rep. Brad
Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, also on the trip, said the two men
haven't been placed under intense presidential pressure while in
Israel, despite the situation's high stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis and Palestinians encountered on the trip, Sherman
said, seem impressed that Clinton would come to their land to push
for the peace process at a time when he is under serious attack at
home. And they don't understand why the impeachment process has
come this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone outside the country thinks we're nuts for doing so
much damage to ourselves over this issue,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clinton, Sherman said the president seems exhausted but
completely focused on the diplomatic issues at hand. Together, they
watched the Palestinian National Congress revoke elements of its
charter calling for the destruction of Israel, a moment the Jewish
Sherman said moved him even more than did visiting Jerusalem's
hallowed Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Palestinians' historic vote, fueled by enthusiasm
over Clinton's visit, shows the president can still perform his job
in spite of the scandal. Sherman said he plans to vote against
impeachment once he returns and hopes the Democrats can muster the
218 votes needed to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton needs 218 Hanukkah presents and I'm going to
give him one,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
