<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-FOLLOW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANNING THE FIRE   
 CARDS HAVE PLAYOFF FEVER, HOPE VALLEY DOES, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - For the first time in their 10-year Valley
history, the Cardinals enter the final two games of the season in
control of their playoff destiny.
</P>
<P>
   Home wins over New Orleans on Sunday and San Diego on Dec. 27
send them to the dance. It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   And, for that matter, if Tampa Bay loses to Washington on
Saturday, the Giants tie or lose to Kansas City on Sunday and the
Cardinals win, Arizona will clinch a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the latter scenario coming to fruition. Imagine fans at
Sunday's game celebrating wildly the team's first playoff
appearance since the strike-shortened 1982 season in front of
33,000 empty seats.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Cardinals' worst fear, but they insist the turnout will
have no bearing on the franchise's long-range future in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's meeting with the Saints simply boils down to a must-win
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   It's being greeted with raging apathy at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   For openers, the Saints have historically been among the
Cardinals' worst draws, largely because they have no local
following _ 37,778 in October 1993, 27,735 in October '92, 30,928
in December '91. That, plus the fact that Cardinals fans have grown
accustomed to taking December off for the holidays, coupled with
the team's modest season-ticket base, have led to an advance sale
only in the high 30,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals reported ticket sales as being ``brisk and
consistent'' Monday, but hardly the stuff from which sellouts are
made. It's a fact that hasn't escaped team members or its coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for closet Cardinals fans who have been afraid to
admit it to come out,'' tackle Lomas Brown said. ``It's time for
them to wear their hats, T-shirts, paint their faces red and do all
that stuff. We need all the support we can get. It's a huge game,
for our playoff lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully fans aren't looking at us saying, `Same old
Cardinals; they'll blow it.' Hopefully, they'll be optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is backing his mouth with his wallet, purchasing 75
tickets for donation to the Valley Big Brothers-Big Sisters.
</P>
<P>
   It's only the fourth time in the past 15 seasons that the
Cardinals (7-7) have been at .500 after 14 games. On the three
other occasions, they were either out of the hunt or didn't control
of their playoff chances. Perhaps the roller-coaster nature of a
young team has left fans more shocked than rabid about its playoff
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about the playoffs, playoff fever and playoff
intensity, and that's really what this game is going to be,''
Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin said. ``If New Orleans beats us and we
finish with the same record, they'll have the tiebreaker on us.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, we control our destiny. It can't get more exciting
if you like pro football and the playoffs. There's something
exciting and different about playoff-type football. A tension in
the air and in the stadium. I just hope fans come out on Sunday.
It's what the home-field edge is all about your fans making it
difficult for the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of response from the ticket-buying public doesn't
lessen the Valley's standing as a NFL market in Tobin's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good market,'' Tobin said. ``Things have to build, and
there are a lot of factors. Some people have plans, and it's the
Christmas season.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety Tommy Bennett, whom Tobin credited with playing his best
game last week in Philadelphia, believes Valley fans will respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``They responded for the Dallas game when we had a chance to
take the NFC lead,'' he said. ``Hopefully, they will again. It's a
big-time game. There hasn't been a situation like this before in
Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Aaron Graham is grateful for the loyal fans who have
attended games all along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the people in town are as excited as we are,'' he said.
``But we know the fans who will be there will be loud. It's the way
our fans have been. There have been times when the stadium wasn't
close to full, but their noise level has had an impact. We'll be
happy with whoever is there . . . as long as they're wearing
red.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
