<HEADER>
A9982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLAMES-45     12-15 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLAMES-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' POWER PLAY MAKES THE DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Late in the first period Monday night, Steve Smith,
the Calgary Flames' veteran defenseman, stood over Marc Savard's
stick. As the Rangers center tried to pick it up, Smith shoved him
aside, and when Savard got close to his stick, kicked it away.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who was the Flames' assistant coach, might have been
trying to frustrate Savard, or at least spread around the Flames'
frustration. When Savard had the stick in his hand, he and the
Rangers took advantage of most of their opportunities, capturing a
5-2 decision at Madison Square Garden to snap a two-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers (11-11-7) were without Todd Harvey, who was serving
a one-game suspension for roughing Buffalo's Vaclav Varada in the
final seconds of a 2-0 loss to the Sabres last Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers made nearly every chance with the man advantage
count Monday night by scoring three power-play goals, matching
their season high. Savard scored first, Adam Graves scored on an
assist from Savard and Petr Nedved scored in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' special teams worked the other way, too, stopping
all six of the Flames' power-play opportunities. And then when the
Flames (11-16-2) added a man in the final minutes, sending off
goaltender Jean-Sebastien Giguere with just more than 1 minute 20
seconds remaining, Wayne Gretzky picked up the puck in the Rangers'
end and found Mathieu Schneider skating up the middle for an
empty-net goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our penalty kill's been playing really well for a little while
now,'' said Rangers goaltender Mike Richter, who had 35 saves.
``We've been playing pretty strong and solid in that department.
The forwards are doing a good job of helping out the defense, which
certainly helps the goaltender out.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach John Muckler added: ``Special teams played very well. The
first group and the second group played very well and we got three
goals off of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers felt this victory was critical because it came after
two tough defeats and the next seven games are against teams in
first- or second-place in their divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Despite controlling the action for much of the time, the Rangers
led by 3-2 heading into the final period.
</P>
<P>
   The Flames took charge early in the third, outshooting the
Rangers by 4-0 over the first five minutes and 18-5 in the period.
The Flames, who went on the power play at 7:01, spent nearly the
entire two minutes in the Rangers' end, producing four shots on
Richter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers stopped that power play and went on their own a
half-minute later. John MacLean passed behind the Flames net to
Gretzky, who fed Nedved swooping from the blue line to the right
circle for a goal and a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the game with just one power-play goal in
their last five games, and that came from Harvey.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers converted on their first two opportunities
Monday night as their special teams helped build a 3-2 lead through
two periods.
</P>
<P>
   First, with seven seconds remaining in a minor penalty in the
first period, Savard poked in a loose puck after a blast by
Schneider.
</P>
<P>
   Savard then got another break, sending the puck in along the
boards from outside the blue line. But the puck hit a gap in the
glass and caromed to the front of the net, where Adam Graves was
skating in unmolested. He quickly banged it in with just two
seconds left on the power play to give the Rangers a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just tried to rim it,'' Savard said. ``I don't know how
Graves read it. I got two good bounces. I didn't look where that
pass hit the boards.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flames' first goal was also unlikely. It came in the second
period by Smith on a pretty backhand crossing pass from Valery Bure
_ Smith's first goal since Jan. 27, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers answered just 1:22 later, with Knuble redirecting
Ulf Samuelsson's shot from the right point. Gretzky also assisted.
</P>
<P>
   But the Flames closed the gap to one goal entering the final 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary's Theoren Fleury jostled the puck free from Gretzky
after a slightly errant pass from Nedved, took it up the left side
and Fleury wristed a shot past Richter.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury's name has come up as a possible addition to the Rangers
and the unassisted goal was just the sort of play that has created
the interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it happens, it happens,'' he said of the possibility of a
trade. ``The No. 1 priority for me is to stay in Calgary. But if it
happens, New York would be a nice place to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
