<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-CANADIENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE GOALS GIVE COYOTES SATIS FYING TIE  
 TKACHUK HURT AS UNBEATEN STREAK REACHES 5 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Celine Dione, Canada's diva version of Madonna,
brought down the house Sunday night during a standing-room-only
concert at the Molson Centre. But that was just the opening act.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes did her one better on Monday, collapsing the house
on the shell-shocked Montreal Canadiens by rallying for a 2-2 tie
with two goals in the final five minutes of regulation, pushing
their unbeaten streak to five games.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after Dione sang her hit from the movie ``Titanic,''
``My Heart'' ``Will Go On,'' the Canadiens' hearts, and those of
the 20,413 fans who jammed the arena, almost collectively stopped
when Daniel Briere and Teppo Numminen each jammed in clutch goals
on a woozy Jeff Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   Briere, the rookie center from nearby Gatineau, Quebec, scored
on a rebound at 14:53 to tie it at 1. Numminen, the veteran
defenseman from Finland, finished it up with a game-tying slap shot
at 18:07.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a couple minutes away from a win,'' said Montreal
forward Shane Corson, whose club is winless in its past seven games
(0-4-3). ``Obviously, we're disappointed. We really need to start
getting some wins.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes (17-3-4) were satisfied to skip out of town
salvaging a point. For the second straight game on this four-game
trip, they were outworked and basically outplayed. Only an inspired
third period allowed them to improve to 3-0-2 in their past five.
They have managed at least one point in 19 of their past 20
(15-1-4) and reclaimed the best record in the NHL with a
league-high 38 points.
</P>
<P>
   They lost Keith Tkachuk in the second period, however. The
team's leading goal scorer, Tkachuk aggravated a recent groin
strain and did no return. He said he hoped to play Wednesday,
though, when the Coyotes make their final appearance at Maple Leaf
Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't panic. We tried to play the same way we have all
year, playing the system, and that's why good things are happening
for us,'' said Numminen, who tallied his fifth goal. ``But still .
. . it was a sluggish game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin, coming off an impressive 42-save performance
during a 2-0 shutout Saturday in Ottawa, kept them in it with
another outstanding effort. He stopped 33 shots, including what
seemed like a gazillion short-handed scoring chances by Montreal
during Phoenix's four scoreless power plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little mad about that,'' Khabibulin said, ``but I know
it happens to everybody. Probably if I wouldn't have stopped all
those (short-handed chances), I'd get more mad. But we didn't lose,
which was good.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had goals taken away from them.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the first period, the Coyotes' Oleg Tverdovsky
inadvertently tipped an errant shot from Martin Rucinsky into his
own goal. Luckily for Phoenix, Rucinsky's forward momentum carried
him into the crease before Tverdovsky's deflection and the goal was
waved off after a short review.
</P>
<P>
   It took just a little longer for the officials to take away a
goal by the Coyotes. They were on the power play in the second
period, and after Montreal had another couple of short-handed
scoring chances, Jyrki Lumme slid the puck over to Jeremy Roenick,
who was straddling the bottom of the right faceoff circle.
</P>
<P>
   From an almost impossible angle, Roenick one-timed a slap shot
that somehow went between Hackett (29 saves) and the post and found
the back of the net. But replays showed Rick Tocchet had the edge
of his skate over the line at the top of the crease. Instead of a
tie game at 1, it was a tie game at none.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the rule. If the skate's in the crease, there's no ifs,
ands or buts about it. That's the breaks,'' said Roenick, who would
have had his 10th goal and 30th point. ``We had to scratch and claw
again. We didn't play very well tonight, but we battled and got a
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Saku Koivu, who's one of Montreal's better skilled players,
scored the first goal that actually counted. It couldn't have been
prettier, either _ a series of dekes that fooled both Gerald Diduck
and then Khabibulin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many respects, I'm happy to get out of here with a tie,''
said Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld, who was perturbed at all the
short-handed giveaways afforded the Canadiens. ``That's something
that hasn't happened all year. We had more tonight than we've had
combined all season long.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
