<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NL WEST: BIG BUCKS, BIG DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO Gomez  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE _ Now that the dust has settled at baseball's winter
meetings _ what little was created from the least productive
meetings ever _ it's become fairly evident just how much muscle
resides in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks managing general partner Jerry Colangelo lobbied
long and hard to get the Diamondbacks into the NL West. To his
credit, Colangelo has shown he is not afraid to play ball with the
big boys where it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   The division is no place for the faint of heart. With Rupert
Murdoch's FOX group owning the Los Angeles Dodgers, Jerry McMorris
and his ample checkbook heading Colorado and Colangelo in Arizona,
this is most definitely a division of big spenders.
</P>
<P>
   Add the fact that San Francisco will open a new ballpark in 2000
and San Diego two years later _ moves that traditionally allow
clubs to spend more money _ and it's simple to see just how
competitive the NL West is and can be.
</P>
<P>
   Recent events clearly illustrate why many baseball executives
are likening the NL West to the American League East, where the
game's biggest money players _ Baltimore, Boston, the Yankees and
Toronto, even though they're somewhat dormant now _ have resided
for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking from the outside in, it certainly appears the NL West
is the next monster division,'' Detroit General Manager Randy Smith
said. ``There seems to be an awful lot of money in the NL West.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the last two weeks, the division added the two most
prized pitchers on the free-agent market, Randy Johnson and Kevin
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the two pitchers will earn a mind-boggling $157.4
million from the Diamondbacks and Dodgers. Here's a little
perspective on that amount of money: It's half of what Murdoch paid
to purchase the Dodgers last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have no idea if they will remain in the NL West
in 2000. Their fate is tied to the other owners, who can vote to
move Arizona into the AL after next season as part of an expected
major restructuring of the two leagues.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, we'll assume they'll stay.
</P>
<P>
   And if these five teams continue together, the NL West could
pass the AL East in spending habits. The expected payrolls of the
five NL West clubs in 1999 is projected to be a staggering $309
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a division of teams that obviously have the wherewithal
to reach for big pieces,'' said Diamondbacks General Manager Joe
Garagiola Jr. ``The future health of this division has some pretty
serious firepower, which should be exciting for fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The five AL East teams combined to pay $270 million in payroll
last season. They appear to be headed toward a combined payroll of
around $305 million, a figure that is even more astounding
considering Tampa Bay and Toronto will probably be under $35
million each.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape of baseball has definitely changed. It's a game
where spending money appears to be the only way to ensure
contending. Of the eight clubs that qualified for the playoffs this
year, all had payrolls over $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Only Anaheim, Toronto and San Francisco, which were all over $43
million, managed to produce winning records without reaching the
$50 million threshold last season.
</P>
<P>
   The big-league scene is in serious trouble when more than half
of the 30 clubs will enter spring training knowing they have
absolutely no chance of reaching the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It's a problem that could shut the game down for an indefinite
period in the near future. Until then, only the rich seem capable
of playing competitive baseball.
</P>
<P>
   While all of the poorer revenue-generating clubs cry out for
change, the five big boys in the NL West all shoulder up wanting a
piece of each other.
</P>
<P>
   The game is definitely in need of change. In the meantime, it
appears Arizona fans will be the recipients of a good,
old-fashioned western shootout, National League style. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 444-2364 or pedro.gomez(at)pni.com
via e-mail.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
