<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IOC-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEED FAVOR? GO TO WORK FOR OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's obvious now why we didn't get the Winter Olympics
and Salt Lake City did.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake Organizing Committee has admitted that while
making its pitch for the 2002 Games, it provided members of the
International Olympic Committee _ the fossils who vote _ with free
dental work, surgical procedures and college scholarships for their
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   We handed out Cardinals tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix didn't bid on the Winter Games, for obvious reasons. We
don't have snow. Even if we did, there are enough winter visitors
in the Valley without importing more from Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine plane loads of healthy-looking fellows named Hans and
Ernst arriving at Sky Harbor Airport with their skis and bobsleds
and perfect white smiles and asking us in broken English how to get
from the 101 to the 202 and what the distance is in kilometers.
</P>
<P>
   Where would we put the luge?
</P>
<P>
   And who would pay for it?
</P>
<P>
   But Salt Lake City coveted the world's winter sports carnival.
So did nine European cities. The IOC chose Utah's capital. &QL; 
What's your price? &QL; 
Salt Lake City is a great place. People are upstanding, friendly.
Proud of their community. Kevin White begged Rick Majerus, the Utah
basketball coach, to leave for Arizona State. He wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   But now folks in Utah and Switzerland are wringing their hands
in the wake of embarrassing allegations of vote-buying and payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A respected member of the IOC inner cabinet blew the whistle,
loudly. Marc Hodler claimed the last four Olympic elections were
corrupted by bribery.
</P>
<P>
   What is unclear is how these Salt Lake City favors were offered.
</P>
<P>
   Did someone sidle up to a visiting IOC member during a fancy
banquet and say, ``Pssst, want a free root canal?''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible, I suppose, that some IOC executive was putting
off gallbladder surgery for lack of funds or insurance. Then
someone in the know, someone well-connected, whispered that he
could arrange the procedure free of charge (in exchange for his
vote). The Olympic guy listened, thoughtfully, finger pressed to
his lips. ``If you'll throw in a Harvard scholarship for my nephew,
sure . . .''
</P>
<P>
   IOC policy prohibits members from receiving gifts worth more
than $150.
</P>
<P>
   You can't get a porcelain crown for that. Forget bridge work. &QL; 
Nice work if you can get it &QL; 
IOC members have the best jobs in sports, which is probably why
it's such an exclusive club. Hard to get in. Like Augusta National,
there's probably a 20-year waiting list.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC headquarters aren't in Waco, Texas. They are in
Lausanne, the quaint Swiss town on the shore of Lake Geneva. These
gentlemen gather around the fireplace. Sipping brandy, they discuss
Olympic issues of the day while wondering whatever happened to
Sonja Henie.
</P>
<P>
   They also visit the cities that bid on the Games. Limos whisk
them to a five-star hotel where the general manager greets them
with open arms while bellhops scurry about the lobby, knocking each
other over fighting for the luggage. Chambermaids drop polite
curtsies, and fluff their pillows.
</P>
<P>
   They are wined. Dined. Toasted. Courted. Flattered. Fawned over.
</P>
<P>
   These guys probably eat more hors d'oeuvres than any organized
body in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City tried for many years to get the votes to stage
the Winter Games. So when it finally happened, 40,000 poured onto
the streets. The Mormon Tabernacle Choir sang ``America the
Beautiful.'' Fireworks lit the sky.
</P>
<P>
   People wept.
</P>
<P>
   Now come allegations of impropriety. No surprise. The IOC wields
incredible power. Olympic votes are worth millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine having that kind of influence.
</P>
<P>
   You're an IOC member, standing on a street corner.
</P>
<P>
   You don't even have your hand out. A stranger walks up, winks
and puts a brand new set of dentures in your blazer pocket.
</P>
<P>
   No questions asked. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 0108EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
