<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-CUMMINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUMMINS FROZEN OUT  
 COYOTE WAITS FOR OPENING IN LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The Zamboni driver leaned against the glass, arms
folded in front of his chest, impatiently waiting for the last
Coyotes player to get off the ice Monday morning so he could
resurface it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In another five minutes,'' a Molson Centre security guard
said, ``they're going to turn the lights out on that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Cummins wouldn't have cared. After being a healthy scratch
in 13 straight games, including Monday night's date against the
Montreal Canadiens, he'd skate in the dark to get more ice time.
For now, the only extra minutes the 6-foot-2, 216-pound right wing
can get come during practices and morning skates.
</P>
<P>
   Cummins, to his credit, refuses to publicly bemoan his
situation, saying he doesn't want to create a distraction while the
team is on a roll. Privately, he is beside himself, but he politely
declines interview requests on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Jimmy isn't playing has nothing to do with Jim
Cummins,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``Jimmy could play on any
team in the league, including ours. But it doesn't take a hockey
scholar to see there are very few places where Jim could fit into
the lineup right now. He's not on the top two lines, he's not a
penalty killer, and he's not a defensive specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   The only way Cummins can get back into the lineup is if
Schoenfeld decides to sit youngsters Brad Isbister or Shane Doan.
Or if an injury pops up. Neither scenario has happened. So Cummins,
28, keeps biding his time, waiting as impatiently as the Canadiens'
Zamboni driver to get back to work.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld has told him he doesn't have to suit up and take
pre-game warmups. But Cummins is out there every night, a half-hour
before opening faceoff, skating with his teammates until it's time
to walk back to the dressing room and change into his suit and tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a great soldier all year,'' Schoenfeld said. ``He's
never complained. He's worked hard every day. His teammates have a
high regard for him. Fortunately for us, we haven't had any
injuries. But who knows? Once Jimmy gets back in, he might be the
hard guy to take out.''
</P>
<P>
   It had to have been extra hard on Cummins to miss Monday's game.
He played his first NHL game in Montreal in 1991-92 when he was in
the Detroit organization. He didn't score, but after a three-hour
truck drive from Adirondack, N.Y., where he was playing for the Red
Wings' farm club at the time, he did get into a fight and record
seven penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard because every athlete wants to play,'' Schoenfeld
said. ``There are guys ``in'' the lineup who you'd like to find
more ice time for. But who do I take it away from?''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes can't assign Cummins to a minor league club in order
to give him some playing time. He'd have to clear waivers, and
another NHL team surely would gobble him up in a second. The team
doesn't want to trade him, either. But what about throwing the
physical Cummins into a game against a rough-and-tumble team simply
to ensure protection?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Schoenfeld said. ``I don't think it would be fair to
Jimmy to say, `OK, we're expecting a tough game. Go in there and
beat somebody up tonight.' I don't think he wants to be that. He
wants to be a hockey player. He's more than willing to handle that.
He's more than willing to stick up for his teammates. He's done
that his whole career. But our teammates all stick up for each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great team toughness. We have great team courage. When
teams start to try and tough it up, man, we just grit our teeth all
the more. We love it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
