<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9995 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-UC-IRVINE     12-15 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-UC-IRVINE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TERRY, UA SHOW IRVINE WHO'S BOSS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ UC-Irvine's Jerry Green may be a talented young player
and his team's leading scorer, but he's still a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Which means he still has a few things to learn, including what
is better left unsaid. Arizona's Jason Terry provided a little
reminder of that Monday night, leading Arizona to a convincing
93-70 blowout of the Anteaters at McKale Center.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who came into the game averaging 13.5 points, told a
Tucson newspaper this week that he was looking forward to playing
Arizona. And he claimed he was not at all intimidated by Terry, the
Wildcats' senior point guard and a notoriously tenacious defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's human, just like me,'' Green reasoned.
</P>
<P>
   And he was right. But the comparison ended about there Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Terry dominated Green and the Anteaters as the eighth-ranked
Wildcats pushed their record to 5-0. Green didn't score a point
until five minutes into the second half, and then he needed a lane
violation by the Wildcats while he was shooting the second of two
free throws to get on the board. He finished with six points, and
five came during mop-up time after Terry called it a night.
</P>
<P>
   Terry, meanwhile, was magnificent, scoring 21 points, handing
out nine assists and making five steals. ``I didn't see what he
said, but the coaches told me about it right before the game,''
Terry said, grinning. ``That kind of sparked me up. I like looking
at the roster and seeing a freshman guard. I start to smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played hard, but our defense pretty much took them out of
what they wanted to run, and (Green) wasn't much of a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 11 first-half points to stake the Wildcats to a
43-30 lead, Terry settled the issue early in the second half. He
had a hand in 12 of Arizona's points in a 21-9 run that pushed the
lead to 64-39. He scored eight points and handed out a pair of
assists during the burst, and Irvine (2-4) was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough playing against Jason Terry,'' Green said. ``He's
a future NBA player, and I'm just a freshman. It was definitely a
learning experience playing against their guards. I'm going to keep
my head up after this game and just keep going. (Terry) played good
defense. I just have to learn to play through that kind of
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The game provided just what it was supposed to - a nice stretch
for the Wildcats in the middle of final exams. It is the only game
the Wildcats play during a 13-day span because of finals, and it
wasn't meant to be too taxing.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a Wildcats team still in the making, despite a lofty
national ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lute Olson used his fifth starting lineup in five games,
this time moving freshman Richard Jefferson from the small forward
spot to shooting guard. And Olson moved 6-foot-7 sophomore Justin
Wessel to small forward.
</P>
<P>
   With 6-10 A.J. Bramlett in the middle and 6-6 Eugene Edgerson
returning after a one-game suspension to the power-forward
position, the Wildcats put an imposing lineup on the floor.
Edgerson, whose suspension was imposed by Olson because of an elbow
that knocked out Brigham Young center Bret Jepsen, started in place
of freshman Michael Wright. But it didn't matter which combination
Olson used; the Anteaters were out-manned.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, the 6-6 product of Moon Valley High School, didn't
appear to have much trouble adjusting, offensively at least. He
scored Arizona's first seven points of the game, hitting a pair of
free throws, connecting from three-point range and then dropping in
a pull-up jump shot from 17 feet. Jefferson went on to score a
season-high 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   The big lineup led to a whopping 47-23 edge for the Wildcats on
the boards. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
