<HEADER>
A0048 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      12-15 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DECEMBER, AND MARINERS ARE ALREADY DONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Angels added Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners added Tom Lampkin.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers added Rafael Palmiero and Todd Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners added Matt Mieske and Butch Huskey.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the local club, baseball is not boxing, where
the lack of a counterpunch is often immediately career-ending. The
Mariners won't see stars and little birdies from this offseason
until, oh, May or so.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's trade with the New York Mets for right fielder Butch
Huskey _ who fits perfectly the Mariner profile of the big-swing,
no-glove, lead-legged strongman that has served the club so
inadequately _ meant the Mariners ended baseball's winter meetings
as they entered.
</P>
<P>
   On cat's feet.
</P>
<P>
   The only stir caused by what was once one of baseball's more
glamorous teams was a curious news story last week that said the
Mariners four months ago offered contract extensions to Ken Griffey
Jr. and Alex Rodriguez worth $70 million each.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out there were no offers, no figures and certainly no
acceptances. The Mariner superstars each have two years left on
their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Given the standard swelling in the player-payroll market this
winter _ which apparently was a surprise to no one but the
Mariners' Woody Woodward _ Griffey and Rodriguez would have to be
re-named Laurel and Hardy if they even looked at offers this
prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   The story looked as if it were planted by the Mariners in order
to make it seem as if the club was actually doing something this
offseason other than wringing hands. A member of the organization
said yesterday that there was no such scheme.
</P>
<P>
   The months-ago conversation was to let Griffey and Rodriguez
know, in light of the Randy Johnson debacle, that they were indeed
wanted. The club also needed to know if the players' feelings were
mutual.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they are. But in the first two months of the Hot Stove
League, Griffey and Rodriguez have to notice the obvious _ the
Mariners are even lower in the standings than they were in the
American League West.
</P>
<P>
   In Lampkin, Mieske and Huskey, the Mariners have acquired the
'99 season's Rick Wilkins, Rico Rossy and Glenallen Hill _
borderline major leaguers who came cheap.
</P>
<P>
   The club's pre-meeting rhetoric was about acquiring a starting
pitcher, some leadoff speed and a right fielder. While those
acquisitions could happen between now and spring training, it's
apparent that the Mariners have no real prospects for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   If the fact that Woodward spent barely 24 hours at the meetings,
while many other club executives were there five days, means
anything, figure that the Mariners' shuffle of mediocre journeymen
is about it for the '99 roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed, I really am,'' Mariner manager Lou Piniella
said Friday after the first day of meetings about the lack of
Mariner acquisitions. ``We're in a position now where we need to
get some things done in fairly quick fashion, because after the
holidays, heck, spring training's here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hard to imagine Piniella's tune changed after the acquisition of
Huskey, whose first name perhaps is an abbreviation for the
description of his defensive skills.
</P>
<P>
   A lifer in the Mets' organization, Huskey was moved from third
to first to the outfield when it was apparent he was a danger to
himself and others in the infield.
</P>
<P>
   With Huskey starting in right, Jay Buhner moving to first base
from right, and David Segui moving from first to left field, the
Mariners have a good chance to add to their 125 errors last year
that was the AL's third worst total.
</P>
<P>
   All that Huskey cost the Mariners was one of their brighter
young pitching prospects, something that was deemed virtually
untouchable. Although information on Lesli Brea is limited, the
fact that the Mariners have traded him suggests at the latest,
he'll be in the 2004 All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   The upshot has been apparent for months: Unless serendipity
strikes, the Mariners are non-factors for '99. And the franchise
used up most of its supply of serendipity in '95.
</P>
<P>
   What is less obvious is another twist in the foolish cruelty of
baseball's system. While it is well-known that ownership refuses to
run with the big dogs of Fox, Disney, Turner and Steinbrenner, the
franchise, with baseball's 10th-highest gross revenues last year,
is obligated to be a payer in baseball's revenue-sharing plan.
</P>
<P>
   For this season, the Mariners' portion of the pot going to
poorer teams is estimated to be more than $4 million, after paying
$3.7 million in 1997 and $613,000 in '96.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is the Mariners are helping subsidize at least
half of the major league teams, while falling further behind the
clubs whose payrolls permit championship contention.
</P>
<P>
   As Dave Niehaus likes to say: unbeLEEVable.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners are in an economic no-man's land, which doesn't
sound like a place Griffey and Rodriguez would want to play out
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
