<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Santa Claus may be lots of fun, but Wall Street is real
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Too many of us think Santa Claus has moved to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Gallup Poll sponsored by PaineWebber showed investors
expect 15 percent returns from the stock market in coming years,
and new investors think returns could go as high as 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not likely. ``The last three or four years, a return of 20 or 25
percent was reasonable,'' said Billy Williams, president of the
Atlanta Council of the National Association of Investors Corp.
``But over the long term, that's not a reasonable expectation.''
</P>
<P>
   What we can reasonably expect is what we have seen over many
years: some Santa Claus years, some so-so years and some Grinch
years.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 through 1997, large-company stocks have more than
doubled in value. This year, the S&AMP;P 500 index is up another 24
percent, even after the dog days of August and September.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not normal. Over 25 years _ which includes the Grinch
years of 1973-74, 1981, 1987 and others _ returns have averaged
13.1 percent. Take it back through 1926, and the record shows that
stocks will return 11 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson: Santa Claus is fun, but Wall Street is real.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of unreal expectations can be painful. ``You
can't stay unreasonable,'' said Elizabeth Jetton, a certified
financial planner with Financial Vision Associates. ``One of the
things people do when high expectations aren't met is that they
think there's a problem. They panic and get out of the game. That's
the worst thing they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   So what can you do to lock onto reality?
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to recognize the stock market is not a
get-rich-quick scheme. Here's an old adage from cynical investors:
``Bulls make money. Bears make money. Pigs get slaughtered.''
</P>
<P>
   The numbers on the chart are not hypothetical. They are factual
reports on the real world. They are also about the best estimates
you can get of how that world will behave in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some ways to help keep your feet on the ground:
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure you have a safe harbor. Every family should have an
emergency fund. You may also need a short-term savings program, for
things like buying a house two years from now, or putting children
into college next fall. Only long-term investments should be in the
stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the reason: Over that 72 years of Ibbotson data, you
would have lost money in 20 of them. In the worst year, a $100
investment would have turned into $43.34. That's too much
volatility for savings you know you will need soon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deal with your panic potential. You might ask yourself, what
if I put $2,000 into an IRA in August, and my stock is now worth
$1,600? Am I embarrassed? Suicidal? Would I just sell the stuff and
tell a broker or banker to buy something safe?
</P>
<P>
   The point is to establish a level of volatility you can live
with, in good times or bad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Examine some real-world investments. You could go to the
library, pick up Value Line and check the record of a stock you
like. Or pick up the Morningstar reports and look up the mutual
funds in your retirement plan. You will probably find they have
good years and bad years, just like most other investments, most
marriages and some football teams.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stop listening to the daily, even hourly market chatter in the
media. All it can do is make you antsy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go back to basics. The ideal is to figure out how much money
you need to meet your goals, how much risk you're willing to take
along the way, and how long you have to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can start comparing those personal needs with the
impersonal performance of stocks, bonds and other investments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what happens if all of your 401(k) contributions go
into stock mutual funds? ``Let's look at what that has returned
over a long period of time,'' said Jetton. ``We'll put that data in
and see if it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it will show a moderately risky set of stock investments
will raise the money you want. ``If it doesn't,'' Jetton continued,
``I'm going tell you to save more money, change your goals, work
longer or take more risk.''
</P>
<P>
   However it works out, you have developed a rational idea of what
you need to do. That's better than waiting for Santa Claus.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, it's better than waiting for the Grinch.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. E-mail:hezell(AT)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
