<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 09:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0247 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BATTLE-BULGE-SURVIVOR     12-15 2279
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTLE-BULGE-SURVIVORS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surviving Battle of the Bulge was a matter of luck and
circumstance
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ George Fisher will raise a glass at 3
p.m. Wednesday in salute to the good men who died around him 54
years ago at the Battle of the Bulge. He knows thousands of other
veterans around the country will do the same, but not as many as
last year.
</P>
<P>
   World War II veterans are dying faster in retirement than in
battle: 31,500 a month and rising. ``Someday, there won't be anyone
left to tell of the horror,'' Fisher says.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that, feeling it in the gut, is driving Fisher and his
comrades to do something that once seemed impossible for most of
them. They are talking about the war.
</P>
<P>
   He is particularly eager to talk about The Bulge, Hitler's last,
furious drive across Europe. Fisher left too many friends in the
frozen fields of Belgium and Luxembourg to let one of the war's
bloodiest battles be remembered as a comic line in diet
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   So Fisher, 74, traveled from his home in Palm Beach to
Tallahassee, Fla. early this year to record his story for the World
War II archives at Florida State University. Then last month, he
and some buddies who retired here went back to Providence College
in Rhode Island with a bronze plaque commemorating 37 of their
classmates killed in the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those of us who survived this thing _ I don't know how to
explain it, but there's a kind of glue between us,'' Fisher says.
``We were all just a breath away from that plaque.''
</P>
<P>
   He learned early that survival would be a matter of luck and
circumstance. He didn't expect to be in battle at all.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after he was drafted, Fisher passed the test for the Army
Specialized Training Program that was supposed to keep the service
stocked with doctors, lawyers and other professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher wanted to be a dentist. He was sent off to Providence
College with the government's promise of a second lieutenant's
commission. But when plans for D-Day brought the demand for fresh
troops, he and about 500 classmates got privates' stripes instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``They woke us up in the middle of the night and told us we were
going,'' he says. ``They put us on a windowless train and dumped us
in the middle of a field in Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   A hefty sergeant greeted them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `OK, college boys, you have your choice: Do you want
to be a rifleman, a machine gunner or a mortar man?'''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher chose rifleman. So did classmates Larry Treff and Leon
Davidow. They arrived in France with the 26th Infantry, the Yankee
Division, on Sept. 8. They trudged past the wreckage of Normandy a
little more than three months after the invasion.
</P>
<P>
   By October, they were on the front lines and stayed there for
more than 60 days of shooting and being shot at _ without a shower
or a hot meal or a full night's sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Then they got word that fresher troops had arrived. That meant a
break from the front, a chance to rest far from the front in the
recently liberated French city of Metz.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last, we got a hot meal and a hot shower,'' Fisher says.
When he was cleaned up, Fisher had a photographer take a picture to
send home as proof he was fit and well. The idyll lasted just two
days.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, someone woke him up in the middle of the night. ``We
were told to move out quickly,'' he says. ``All we knew is that
something happened. We had no inkling.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened was a thunderous breach of the Belgian front by
German Panzer tanks and 250,000 troops. The 75,000 Allied defenders
spread thin along the German border were overwhelmed, falling back
into a deep pocket in the Ardennes forest that left a bulge in the
line.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was as surprising as Japan's raid on Pearl Harbor for
reasons as mysterious and hotly debated. The Allies' failure to
detect such an enormous buildup a few miles away has been called
one of history's greatest intelligence failures.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure of military and political leaders, who had begun
to take victory for granted, was even greater.
</P>
<P>
   Their embarrassment may help explain why the Battle of the Bulge
doesn't instantly conjure the glorious image that D-Day does.
Normandy was a battle the generals and politicians could boast
about. The Bulge was a battle that shouldn't have happened.
</P>
<P>
   Both were victories of common soldiers rising to an
extraordinary challenge. This was America's greatest surprise for
Germany: Regular Joes could fight like hell.
</P>
<P>
   Hitler had failed to learn that lesson, even after his Wermacht
was pushed from the Atlantic and chased back into Germany. He was
convinced that his December offensive would cut straight through
the Allied forces all the way to The Netherlands, leaving them so
demoralized that they would either surrender or agree to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson was driven home when the Nazis rolled up to Bastogne,
at the crossroads of important routes through Belgium. Ordered to
surrender, Brig. Gen. Anthony McAuliffe issued the most famous and,
to the Germans, perplexing reply of the war: Nuts.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe and the 101st Airborne held tight while Gen. George
Patton's Third Army rushed north to relieve them. Of more than
600,000 men the Allies eventually threw into the battle, nearly all
were Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were three college boys/riflemen roused from leave in
Metz: Fisher, Treff and Davidow.
</P>
<P>
   Treff, 73, and now of Boynton Beach, Fla., and Davidow, 74, of
Wellington, Fla., are among the local Bulge veterans who found each
other at reunions over the years and renewed their friendships.
</P>
<P>
   They met for one of their occasional lunches shortly before this
year's battle anniversary and talked about their sudden return to
combat on Dec. 16, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put us in trucks and we headed north,'' Fisher says.
``Our only order was to engage the enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidow remembers the ride clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard shells, small arms fire,'' he says. ``It gets
louder, and you know you're getting closer. You know soon they'll
dump you off.''
</P>
<P>
   The trucks stopped as shells exploded all around. The troops
were ordered out, lined up and set marching. ``We didn't know where
we were, or where we were going,'' Fisher says. ``I have no idea
how far we marched or how long.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers that it was terribly cold and snowy. Hitler planned
his attack for the worst weather, expecting it would add to the
Americans' misery and ground their planes. He was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a horrible experience,'' Fisher says.
</P>
<P>
   It took days to reach where the bodies lay, where the cold men
who'd come before were already fighting. Each rifleman unfolded his
pack shovel and began stabbing at the frozen ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't dig, but you had to,'' Fisher says. ``If you
didn't dig a foxhole, you'd die.'' So they dug, they chopped, they
set off explosives. When there were holes big enough, two men
jumped into each one.
</P>
<P>
   They performed the ritual over and over. The Battle of the Bulge
was a tortuous, six-week campaign through dense woods and ruined
towns. It was as much a battle against the snow and cold as against
the enemy; casualties from infected or frost-bitten feet rivaled
those from bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't trained to deal with any of it,'' Fisher says.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans improvised as they fought, wrapping themselves in
paper and blankets, and bed sheets for camouflage. They used their
body heat to keep their ammo and medicines from freezing. And still
their guns jammed, their engines froze, their teeth chattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd do anything to warm up just for a little while,''
Davidow says. Sometimes, they did the wrong thing and paid for it.
He remembers walking into an abandoned house and seeing a big, soft
bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must have been a dozen of us who jumped in to get
warm,'' he says. ``The mistake we made was taking off our boots.''
</P>
<P>
   The crackle of small-arms fire rousted them, but by then it was
dark. There was no way, no time, to sort through the pile of boots.
Davidow managed to grab one of his own, but the other was too small
and soaking wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I limped through the rest of the war with an infected foot,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   The talk turns to other injuries, and Fisher recalls the
ambivalence men felt about wounds. He's fond of a quote about
riflemen by Gen. Omar Bradley, who directed the battle: ``After
weeks or months in the line only a wound can offer him the comfort
of safety, shelter and a bed.''
</P>
<P>
   Every soldier feared death but secretly wished for a wound just
bad enough to get him sent home. They called that a Million Dollar
Wound, almost too much to hope for when most anyone who could walk
was patched up and sent back into action.
</P>
<P>
   Davidow had the chance for a Purple Heart when an explosion
tossed him through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how long I was knocked out, but I was dazed for a
long time after,'' he says. ``I looked down and saw I was bleeding.
I had little pieces of shrapnel all over my stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidow made his way to an aid station, but stopped when he saw
others ahead of him dying. ``I felt embarrassed to ask for help,''
he says. ``I couldn't ask for a medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing how much others were suffering kept most men from giving
in, Fisher says. ``You had plenty of company, and you knew you
weren't the worst off,'' he says. ``You also knew that someday it
had to be over.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking about home was a comfort but also a worry. No one
wanted his folks to know how bad things really were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a beautiful house near the fire,'' Fisher wrote from
his freezing foxhole.
</P>
<P>
   Treff drew strength from the silver Star of David that hung from
his neck. His maternal grandmother gave it to him for his bar
mitzvah. ``People kept telling me to get rid of it because of what
might happen if I got captured,'' he says. ``But I wouldn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three college boys held up as long as he had to.
None lasted until the end of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher got his Million Dollar Wound on the morning of Jan. 3,
1945, while advancing on a German position outside the town of
Wiltz, Luxembourg. An exploding shell drove shrapnel through his
left leg. He was still in a hospital in England when Germany
surrendered in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Battle of the Bulge had reached the turning point when
Fisher fell. Treff and Davidow kept up the fight. The Germans were
back in Germany by Jan. 28, decimated and on the run. More than
10,000 Americans had died in the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Treff got his Million Dollar Wound later, while chasing the
enemy across the Rhine. He was a master sergeant by then, leading a
patrol when he was hit in the right leg by machine gun fire.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't bleed much because the bullets were so hot the wounds
were self-cauterizing, but his bones were shattered. Weak and about
to pass out, he made a sudden, painful decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled off the Star of David and threw it as far as I
could,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He was captured moments later. He was a prisoner of war for 13
days in a make-shift care center. He heard a rumble as hiscaptors
abandoned the place and the Americans marched in.
</P>
<P>
   An American captain, thinking the wounded men were Germans,
tried speaking in a language they might understand. Treff called
out: ``Captain, your German stinks, but your Yiddish is
beautiful!''
</P>
<P>
   Davidow's ticket home was a virulent case of hepatitis from
drinking water someone had forgotten to purify. Through the
differing circumstances of the three comrades' survival ran a
common determination to focus on anything else in the world but
what they'd been through.
</P>
<P>
   Each went back to college. Each got married. Each had a good
career: Fisher in real estate management, Treff in textiles,
Davidow as an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never talked to my children about the war,'' says Treff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never even told my wife I was in combat,'' echoes Davidow.
``I was so sick of the idea of people killing each other. I didn't
even think about it until the reunion.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 10 years ago, about the same time Treff was interviewed
by the author of a book about The Bulge. When he discovered he
could talk about the war, and that people would listen, Treff
joined a prisoner-of-war speakers group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to middle school kids about what it's like to lose
your personal freedom,'' he says. ``I only lost mine for 13 days,
but I'll never forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher was struck by a letter published last month in a
veterans' bulletin. A Wisconsin woman wrote that her father had
died without ever telling her about his war experience. She asked
other veterans to talk while they had time.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher wrote to tell her she's right. Yet it's only at the end
of a two-hour interview, and only in response to a direct question,
that Fisher acknowledges his own war-time heroics. He was awarded
the Bronze Star for crawling toward a German machine gun nest and
tossing in a grenade.
</P>
<P>
   He says only, ``You do foolish things when you're 19.'' He
prefers to talk about the 37 names on the plaque. ``They deserve to
be honored.''
</P>
<P>
   Davidow hopes that by talking about the misery of war, veterans
can make an impression on young people. ``They have to see that it
makes no sense to keep having wars, that there has to be a better
way.''
</P>
<P>
   He's quick to add that he has no regrets, no second thoughts
about fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It built in us a sense of confidence, self-reliance,'' he
says. ``You know you can face anything. It gives you an
appreciation of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
