<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BRIEFS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History made in cord blood transplant
 &HT;    (Eds: A compilation of health stories that moved from Cox News
Service in the past week.)
 &HT;    Staff reports
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Medical history unfolded at Egleston Children's
Hospital last week with the world's first cord blood transplant for
sickle cell anemia.
</P>
<P>
   The blood recipient, Keone Penn, was sleepy from 10 days of
chemotherapy to kill his unhealthy bone marrow, and painkillers.
But he awoke long enough to help pediatric nurse practitioner Ellen
Olson squeeze stem blood cells into his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors will know in three to four weeks if the transplant has
taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   Should the procedure work, it could help many severely ill
children with sickle cell anemia who do not have a relative with
matching bone marrow. Bone marrow is the spongy liquid inside bones
where blood cells form and mature. The experimental procedure poses
great risk because the patient's immune-fighting white cells are
wiped out, leaving him open to infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This protocol is ahead of its time,'' said Dr. Angela Ogden,
one of the specialists treating Keone. ``But he's not your typical
sickle cell kid. Taking the additional risk . . . is acceptable in
his case, until we know that umbilical cord transplant will work
for sickle cell. If it does, we can offer it to kids with less
severe disease.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old Keone received the equivalent of about eight
tablespoons of stem cell blood. It came from an anonymous woman who
consented to have her placenta and umbilical cord donated to the
New York Blood Center. Rich in stem cells that grow into the three
components of blood, cord blood has been used in nearly 600
procedures around the world in patients suffering from leukemia and
other immune and genetic disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure has never been tried on sickle cell disease, which
affects 70,000 people nationwide, most of whom are
African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   New decontaminant for anthrax
</P>
<P>
   Researchers recently announced test results for a new
decontaminant against anthrax and other significant biological
warfare agents. Dr. James R. Baker Jr., and his colleagues at the
University of Michigan have found that their new product, known as
BCTP, safely and effectively destroys a number of the most
dangerous bacteria and viruses. In addition, a second team at
Sandia National Laboratories in Albuquerque, N.M., has produced a
new decontaminating foam that's as nontoxic as hair conditioner.
</P>
<P>
   These two products may revolutionize the way we think about
killing viruses and bacteria and may help to reduce the terror and
the threat of biological warfare, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Modern science has been seeking to produce an agent with
bleach's decontaminating power that could be spread on guns, poured
onto clothes, sprayed into eyes and nostrils, rubbed into wounds
and even consumed.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent meeting of the American Society for Microbiology,
the Michigan researchers announced they had tested such a substance
_ BCTP _ on live animals. Over a four-hour period, the fatty, bland
solution _ which you can drink like a milkshake or rub on your skin
like sunscreen _ killed up to 99.4 percent of anthrax bacteria in a
test tube, the researchers said. That's about the same
effectiveness as concentrated bleach. In addition, Baker and his
colleagues reported that rats fed BCTP actually gained weight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
