u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX     12-15 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ever have one of those days ...
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The day was off to a bad start. Barely five
minutes out of bed and I had already poured the juice of two
freshly squeezed oranges down the sink and dumped a handful of
vitamins into the trash. My morning routine was running amok. Then
the cat went fishing in my bowl of shredded wheat.
</P>
<P>
   Things would get better, I assured myself as I wheeled into the
middle school parking lot. No room for sloppy work here. Moments
later I was turning the corner into the teacher's lounge when the
science teacher zipped past me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outta' my way!'' she warned. ``Too much coffee and too long a
drive.'' She swept into the restroom with a sigh of impending
relief but the door had barely slammed behind her when she was out
again, wearing a puzzled frown and grappling with her skirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a kid on the teacher's toilet,'' she gasped. I asked
her who it was. ``Joey. He's just sitting there grinning, with his
jeans around his ankles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' I agreed, ``Joey never was much of a talker.'' The
science teacher split for another facility. I punched some numbers
into the copy machine and planned what I was going to say to Joey
when he emerged. I needn't have bothered. He never came out.
</P>
<P>
   Second period I checked, but he was gone. And then the fire bell
rang.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of it being my conference period, and no matter it was
just another drill (schoolhouses don't burn down much any more), I
had to hustle to collect my grade book and get outside before the
big guy with the stopwatch declared me
</P>
<P>
   in violation of something or other. On the way out I tripped
over Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing in that corner?'' I asked. ``The school
might be on fire and you'd be trapped.'' Martin said that was
better than the alternative. As I hustled him down the hall, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey's going to kill me. He told me so on the bus.'' By way of
conversation as we rushed down the stairs and past the scowling man
with the stopwatch, I asked him why. ``I told him Hornsby was
ugly,'' he confessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joey has a brother named Hornsby?'' I asked with an
ill-concealed chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naw,'' Martin grumped, ``Hornsby's his dog.''
</P>
<P>
   I explained to Joey that guys were more sensitive about their
dogs than they were about their sisters, so if he wanted to live
until Christmas, he'd better apologize. He agreed.
</P>
<P>
   By seventh period, the day was looking up until I spotted a
sixth-grader scrunched down in the doorway next to his classroom. I
stopped and stared. This rosy-cheeked cherub had apparently
stumbled into a wealth of reinforcement rings for loose-leaf
notebook paper. A linen circle was pasted on each earlobe, one on
the end of his nose, three across his mouth, and a few more stuck
to his chin in a makeshift goatee. He saw me staring and peeled in
a hurry. Don't ask, I told myself.
</P>
<P>
   And my day wasn't over yet.
</P>
<P>
   After the last bell, I wistfully climbed into my battered old
Bronco for our last run. It was trade-in day and I was feeling a
mite sentimental as I pulled into the car dealer's. ``Hi,'' I said
to the man in the third cubicle from the door _ the one where I'd
made the deal for a new car. ``I'm here to pick up my Explorer.''
He just stared. ``The black one,'' I added by way of pointless
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   He looked a little puzzled, even after I asked to speak with
Tom. All he said was, ``Tom who?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Watkins,'' I answered a little annoyed with his
foolishness. The guy grinned and told me they'd fired Tom the day
before. I told him that was impossible since Tom was the owner's
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ma'am,'' he said finally and with a chuckle, ``there's nothing
I'd love better than to sell you a new truck, but this is the Chevy
dealership.'' I swore the wiseguy to secrecy and climbed back into
my Bronco for a short ride down the road to the Ford place, happy
this day was almost over.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning as I apprehensively slipped into my faculty
parking spot not knowing what this day was going to bring, I
spotted Joey waiting for me. ``Ms. Schuett, can we work a deal?''
he asked hopefully. ``I promise not to kill Martin if you won't
tell I was in the teacher's bathroom. I just couldn't wait. I had
to go right then.''
</P>
<P>
   I agreed and we shook on it. Things are looking up for today.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett, a writer and teacher in Gibsonburg, Ohio,
writes for Cox News Service. Address mail to: 320 West Madison,
Gibsonburg 43431 or e-mail to eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
