A0253 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN16-COX     12-15 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He won't resign, so Congress will take what it can, by the pound
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Richard Nixon resigned before giving us a chance
to see what it was like for a full House to consider articles of
impeachment. So we can only speculate on what would have been.
</P>
<P>
   But, ladies and gents, there'll be no speculation this time.
Bill Clinton is about to slide, gym shorts first, down a mile-long
razor blade into a barrel of turpentine. Cowabunga, dudes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton isn't going to resign. The Senate isn't going to have
the two-thirds majority to remove him. What we have before us is
everything in between: a ritual bloodletting, which early healers
asserted would make a body feel better.
</P>
<P>
   Of flesh are Bill Clinton's sins, and so will be his remittance,
in pounds.
</P>
<P>
   What we have lined up is an old military-school paddle whack,
only with meat mallets.
</P>
<P>
   We can dispense with comparisons. Watergate? This doesn't
compare:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Clinton's case we are arguing the definition of sex. In
Watergate, no one was arguing the definition of burglary.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Watergate, special prosecutor Leon Jaworski produced a set
of findings and stepped out of the way to let others decide.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Kenneth Starr ``produced'' a set of findings. You
bet, he produced. He sang. He danced. He conducted the Hallelujah
Chorus. He tugged at ropes and pulleys as trumpeting angels danced
across the backdrop. Starr's production caused ex-Watergate
investigator Sam Dash to resign in disgust from his team.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Constitution sets forth ``high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Starr investigation has uncovered low crimes and Miss
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Watergate the question was: ``What did he know and when did
he know it?''
</P>
<P>
   In this scandal the question is: ``He did WHAT?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Watergate inspired young people by the hundreds of thousands
to become journalists. The Clinton scandal has caused journalists
by the hundreds of thousands to consider finding another craft.
</P>
<P>
   _ During Watergate, Americans sat glued to their television sets
watching the proceedings. Americans are glued to their television
sets this time as well, just not to the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Watergate, leaders in the House approached their task with
hushed solemnity and a sense of history.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the tribunal is less than hushed. Listen and
you'll hear that impeachment is something you can do any old time.
</P>
<P>
   In comments roundly criticized by others who see the House's
responsibility as far more weighty, House Republican Whip Tom DeLay
said this:
</P>
<P>
   ``All impeachment is, is like a grand jury that looks at the
evidence, and the House decides whether the evidence warrants
sending it to the Senate for a trial. That's all it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Th-th-that's all, folks.
</P>
<P>
   _ A New York Times editorial, counting the votes in the House,
said that Clinton would spare himself a trial in the Senate if he'd
admit he lied under oath. That's probably right.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, one more major difference between this scandal and
Watergate: Would Nixon have saved himself if he admitted, ``I knew
about the burglary. I ordered the cover-up''? Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   The Times also is right when it says that Clinton's misdeeds as
alleged ``do not meet the constitutional standard for impeachment.
But politics and human nature enter into this matter as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they do. And that's why when this chapter is over, and
Clinton, still president, has been cut down several sizes, history
will remember this scandal not as a villainous chief executive who
flouted the law and abused his office, but as a reckless oaf who
gave his enemies a chance to whack him.
</P>
<P>
   And everyone will feel better. Oh, yeah.
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
