u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BENGALS-FUTURE16-     12-15 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BENGALS-FUTURE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fresh start for Bengals in '99 will depend heavily on '98
rookies
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Mention the 2-12 record and you get cold, hard
stares. Say the word ``future'' and you see a gleam in their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about Bengals rookie starters Takeo Spikes, Brian
Simmons and Artrell Hawkins isn't just their burgeoning talent.
It's their positive attitude.
</P>
<P>
   All three will be leaned on heavily for their leadership skills
as the Bengals seek a turnaround season in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like we're on a train with me and 'B' (Simmons) in
front,'' Spikes said. ``We'll take turns being the engineer. If
you're coming, you better hop on. If you're not, get the hell
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Spikes, a consensus All-American linebacker at Auburn in 1997,
promises fans that the losing will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to change and it's going to change next year,'' he
said. ``I'm taking all the responsibility. I'm not going to stand
up and say, 'I'm going to be the leader.' I'm going to lead by
example and by my play. You get your respect faster that way. And
then everything else will fall in right behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing I'm going to start with are the little things _
getting in the huddle, getting your mind right, not talking, going
ahead and breaking the huddle and then playing with reckless
abandon.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmons, an All-American at North Carolina, said he's
``definitely'' ready to join Spikes as co-engineer on the
leadership train.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a position where we need to be leaders,'' he said.
``We need to take over that type of role.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins wants to hop on board, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a goal of ours, to establish ourselves as leaders,''
the rookie cornerback from the University of Cincinnati said.
``Right now, it's hard because we're rookies. You need to gain
respect of the older guys and make plays. Right now, we're
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing is going out every week, trying to stay upbeat
and I'm sure those guys (Spikes and Simmons) are, too. I still play
with emotion. I'm going to do my dances. When I make a play, I'm
going to let everybody know I made a play and that's so my
teammates can feed off it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, in the years to come, I'm going to be a leader
here. I want to go to the Pro Bowl. I want to win championships. I
love this city. It's just kind of tough right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong safety Myron Bell, who played his first four seasons in
Pittsburgh, said 30 to 40 Steelers got paid $250 a week to
participate in an offseason program. He said a similar program
would benefit the Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money,'' Bell said. ``It's about building
unity. That's something we're missing here. We have young guys, old
guys and in-the-middle guys. You need that extra time to get that
gel together. The main thing is chemistry.'
</P>
<P>
   Chick Ludwig writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
