<HEADER>
A0255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIVINGLONGER16-COX     12-15 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIVINGLONGER16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH: Baby boomers boost market for anti-aging treatments
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ A half-hour drive west of the flame-throwing
fountains outside Caesar's Palace in this oasis built on fantasy
and hustles, a 60-year-old retired Chicago radiologist with Charles
Atlas shoulders and the zeal of an evangelist is pitching
deliverance.
</P>
<P>
   Not from gluttony or deceit, but from age. For $1,700 a month,
Dr. Alan Mintz says, he can turn back the hands of time _ and get
rid of the spare tire around your belly to boot.
</P>
<P>
   He calls his venture Cenegenics _ Greek for ``new life.'' Less
than a year old, it's one of just a handful of anti-aging clinics
that have popped up around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Though nutrition and exercise make up two of the three prongs of
Cenegenics' treatment, it is human growth hormone, or HGH, that
draws many through the six three-story Greek pillars that mark the
clinic's entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-aging practitioners claim that HGH can have sedentary
septuagenarians hiking over hilltops in two months. It's created
such a buzz that at the sixth conference of the American Academy of
Anti-Aging Medicine (A4M) here last weekend, it was difficult to
find one of the roughly 1,000 doctors in attendance who did not
either use or prescribe HGH.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say it tightens skin, increases libido, improves
cardiovascular capacity and boosts lean muscle mass. Critics say
the benefits are exaggerated and the dangers haven't been fully
documented.
</P>
<P>
   Such questions are common about the growing array of anti-aging
treatments _ from eating raw spinach and drinking oxygenated water
to liposuction and cutting-edge anti-oxidants _ being introduced as
Baby Boomers hit 50. That group is eagerly experimenting with
so-called ``alternative'' medicine: According to a recent study in
the Journal of the American Medical Association, about half of the
country's population between 35 and 49 uses some form of
alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the perceived stodginess of traditional
medicine, and the public's increased awareness of alternative
treatments. The combination is supporting clinics like Cenegenics.
But few treatments are as controversial as HGH.
</P>
<P>
   Mintz, a competitive bodybuilder for a decade, has been
injecting the drug into his thighs for more than a year. He said it
is as close to the fountain of youth as man has found.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel unbelievably good,'' he said on Thursday. ``I almost
never get sick, I have boundless energy, I exercise every morning,
my sex life is better than it was five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the claims and the growing use in certain social
circles, not everybody is convinced the drug is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd have to be out of your mind to take that
stuff,'' said Dr. Richard Sprott, executive director of the
Bethesda, Md.-based Ellison Medical Foundation and a former
director of the National Institute on Aging. ``I think they are all
running a much bigger risk then they think they're running.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally extracted from the pituitary glands of corpses to
stimulate the growth of child dwarves, HGH was synthesized for the
first time in 1985 and approved by the FDA for treatment of rare
pituitary disorders in August 1996. But for movie stars in
Hollywood, business executives in Manhattan and anybody else who
can afford the almost $20,000 yearly cost, it is rapidly becoming
the Holy Grail of extended youth.
</P>
<P>
   Mintz claims that Cenegenics has 200 patients in 30 states and
estimates there are 10,000 patients using the drug nationally under
doctor supervision. But, he adds, there are countless others _
mostly bodybuilders _ buying knockoff versions on the black market.
</P>
<P>
   Though Cenegenics is among the only clinics of its kind in the
country, it seems doubtful it will hold that status much longer.
Among more than 200 vendors at the A4M conference, a half-dozen
were successfully selling equipment to enable physicians to test
the ``biomarkers'' of age. Taken together, these machines _ which
assess lung capacity, vision, hearing, strength, reflexes and
mental acuity, among other tests _ pinpoint a person's biological
age compared to his chronological age.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors running anti-aging clinics compare patients' biomarkers
from year to year to gauge the effectiveness of treatments.
</P>
<P>
   And in coming years, anti-aging medicine will revolutionize what
it means to grow old, doctors at the Las Vegas conference
predicted. On Friday, when Dr. Ronald Klatz, the academy's
president, said he would kick himself if he didn't live to be 150,
nobody batted an eye. Among this crowd of decidedly-not-mainstream
Ph.D's and medical doctors, the talk of living to see one's
great-great-great-grandchildren is considered very attainable.
</P>
<P>
   This new wave of technology and enthusiasm couldn't come at a
more profitable time. With 75 million Baby Boomers beginning to
ache with the first twinges of arthritis, the market for wrinkle
cream and its more sophisticated brethren has never been larger or
grown faster.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Tepper, the editor of The Journal of Longevity, estimates
the market of nutritional supplements alone is upwards of $15
billion. Treatises on how to live forever, and look good doing it,
line the bookshelves at neighborhood bookstores. Cosmetic surgeons
who attended the conference talked of month-long waiting lists.
</P>
<P>
   But discerning legitimate therapies from bunk is becoming an
increasingly Herculean task. The academy is trying to broaden the
scope of tools used in the West, but Klatz acknowledges that there
are a lot of false claims being made which potentially undermine
the academy's credibility. He drew a sharp line between the vendors
at the conference and the reports presented by the doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This stuff just pays the bills (for the conference),'' Klatz
said. ``It's one of my great frustration that the two are often
confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Packed into four exhibit halls, the vendors hawked everything
from soda pledging to make you smarter to supplements that promise
to clean out your colon. In between were magnets to relieve pain,
spinal pumps to improve posture, organ detoxifiers,
battery-operated brain stimulators, high-tech air filters, memory
boosters, muscle builders, massagers touted to give you a
two-minute face lift, creams that promise to increase your
bustline, water ionizers, oxygen chambers and high-tech
antioxidants _ including one that may soon be injected into the
filter of cigarettes to reduce the harmful effects of nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the products have solid scientific research behind them.
Some have none and are being sold, as one conventioneer put it, by
people who sold cars last month and will be selling shoes next
month.
</P>
<P>
   But with its almost bionic claims, HGH was foremost on the minds
of many at the conference. Likened to a master hormone regulating
metabolism, the production of HGH peaks in adults between 25 and
35. Every decade thereafter, the body's output dwindles by about 15
percent. By supplementing one's natural supply, proponents say they
can maintain the hormone levels of a 30-year-old in the body of
80-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Hueseman, a pharmacist from Colorado selling one of the
half-dozen brands on the market to doctors, said despite the cost _
which is not covered by insurance in most cases _ the number of
people taking HGH is projected to double every year for the next 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is exploding,'' Hueseman said. ``And it's not going
to stop any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   This explosion comes six months before a series of potentially
definitive double-blind tests paid for by the National Institute on
Aging is expected to be released. And that leaves skeptics like
Sprott labeling people who use the drug crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it is a risk? Sure, it's a risk,'' said Julio Garcia, a Las
Vegas plastic surgeon who, at 41, takes a hormone to stimulate HGH
production and plans to take HGH itself in the future. ``But
everything we know about it points to the positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Though membership in the A4M has increased from a mere 12 in
1993 to 4,000 this year, the board is not recognized by the
American Board of Medical Specialties, the government's
organization that regulates specialized medical organizations. The
A4M is viewed by critics as too quick to endorse unproven therapies
like HGH. Klatz chalks up much of the criticism to politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicine is an awful lot like the church,'' said the bearded
43-year-old. ``There's an orthodoxy and if it ain't part of the
orthodoxy, guess what . . . it's going to be pooh-poohed until it
does start making money for the people on the inside. And then
there is going to be a great discovery by the medical
establishment, and it will be the best thing since sliced bread.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
