<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STERLING16-COX     12-15 1668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STERLING16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Writer maintains a devoted following with visions of a chaotic
21st century
 &HT;    By Patrick Beach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ He's the leading cyberpunk science fiction
author going, with eight novels and two story collections. He's
just published a ninth novel that, although set almost 50 years in
the future, can be read as contemporary political satire. He cranks
out bomb-throwing futuristic essays at an alarming pace and
distributes them via e-mail. And just now Austin author Bruce
Sterling has a real problem:
</P>
<P>
   ``No bacon? Fraud! Scandal!''
</P>
<P>
   In the new millennium, maybe Julio's _ the Hyde Park joint with
the best chicken taco plate in town _ will never run short of
genetically enhanced pork products. But it's practically noon, and
they're out, even for a regular like Sterling, who gets greeted by
name.
</P>
<P>
   And so the Futurist of Just South of Hyde Park Proper agrees on
a side of rice as a sad substitute, shoves a fork in his migas and
opens the gate on a conversational bull-ride. He talks about his
career as a science fiction novelist of considerable renown. About
his work for Wired magazine. About his futurist guru status. And
what's up with this weird weather?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very interested in greenhouse issues _ I was radicalized
by the summer's bad weather,'' he says. ``We shouldn't be sitting
here in shorts and sandals in December. This is freakish. There's
no place to hide from CO2. Everybody's under the same sky. This is
a stupid problem to have, like marinating in your own trash.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time this child of the Texas oil industry
has gone on record about global warming. The post-greenhouse world
provided the setting for ``Heavy Weather,'' his 1994 work that beat
the pants off ``Twister.'' And his new novel _ ``Distraction,'' _
has the Dutch throwing an international hissy fit just because the
rising sea is making their country disappear. (In the book,
greenhouse typhoons have already done a major number on portions of
Louisiana. Fortunately, the populace there has a Huey Long-style
governor for diversion.)
</P>
<P>
   Sterling cracks that the novel is as ``humiliating as today's
headlines,'' and, since it's got sex, power, corruption and
governmental disarray, it could hardly be more timely.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't picked up a science fiction novel in the past 15
years, Sterling's insistence on extrapolating contemporary concerns
and spinning futuristic novels out of them may not be your idea of
science fiction. Your idea of science fiction may be retrograde
space opera stuff where swashbuckling male pilots colonize galaxies
of planets full of busty alien women in stainless steel brassieres.
You may still labor under the delusion that science fiction fans
are exclusively adolescent boys who read the cheap novels _ comic
books without pictures, really _ while eating fish sticks, drinking
Tang and absent-mindedly popping their zits. And if that's what you
think, you've missed a lot.
</P>
<P>
   You missed ``Neuromancer,'' William Gibson's 1984 eponymous
novel that's widely credited with popularizing the sci-fi aesthetic
Gibson dubbed ``cyberpunk,'' with its famous opening sentence:
``The sky above the port was the color of television, tuned to a
dead channel.'' Cyberpunk combined technical savvy with an antic
rock 'n' roll energy and ditched rocket ships and phasers for
computers, artificial intelligence, biotech, nanotech and the Net.
In this world, virtual reality was often preferable to the
old-fashioned kind (though fraught with its own peculiar hazards),
and aliens were rendered irrelevant: Human characters in cyberpunk
were often surgically enhanced and genetically tweaked to the point
where they looked way weirder than little green men.
</P>
<P>
   A few years earlier, after graduating from the University of
Texas, Sterling was reading and writing science fiction for fun _
and getting published _ while working a day job at the Texas State
Capitol. He saved up enough to take a year off to write and never
looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Gibson and Sterling, whose earliest work had predated
Gibson's by seven years, emerged as the brightest lights of this
purported movement. They even collaborated on a novel, ``The
Difference Engine.'' But a marked contrast emerged between the two:
Gibson was stylistically dazzling, but there wasn't all that much
under the hood, while Sterling's works had more meat on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered him and discovered he took his science fiction a
lot more seriously, as speculative fiction, and there were a lot
more and deeper ideas than most authors care to grapple with,''
says Chris Waltrip, a local fan who maintains a Sterling Web site
(http://lonestar.texas.net/(tilde)dub/newfront.html). ``I was
really into cyberpunk when I got into him. Most people get into
Gibson first _ real flashy and glittery. Sterling is the opposite.
He's not flashy, but there's more to chew on.''
</P>
<P>
   True. In person, in book form and through his e-mail essays,
turbocharged ideas pour out of Sterling. But he claims that, at 44,
he's actually slowing down. This is slowing down?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, man,'' he says. ``There's gonna be the Sterling
version of the grave, too. I can't get any smarter. And I can feel
that already. I can feel things starting to slip just a little. I
have a harder time with names. Dates I've always had a hard time
with, but now I'm catastrophic at them. I get up every morning
feeling the way I did when I was 20 and I was on a bender the night
before: 'What is this? What have I done? Oh, I'm 40. I get it.' And
that's just a metabolic truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Resigned to not getting smarter, Sterling is cultivating better
taste.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be interested in things just because of how trashy
they were _ cool and punk and trashy,'' he says. ``Now I read
design magazines and fuss about architectural doctrine. I've lost
my fondness for trashy things. I've even lost my fondness for
postmodernity. I don't want to start out the 21st century on the
bones of the 20th century because you know what? The 20th century
stinks. It just plain does. It stinks so bad that now the whole sky
stinks. I'm sick of going out on my porch and smelling Mexico on
fire. What the hell is that about? We're doing something wrong
here. We need to take some responsibility of the shape of the world
here. We need clean power. Every time I boot up my computer or send
somebody some e-mail, there's an evil little gush of soot
somewhere. I'm sick of that. I've had it with that. It gives me a
sense of moral and aesthetic revulsion.''
</P>
<P>
   And what does he do about the problem? ``Just sit in an office
moving my fingers up and down.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. Sterling has numerous vents for his passionate
opinions. And he has a ravenous intellect to feed. He subscribes to
dozens of magazines and turns news into science-fiction fodder.
Today in his laptop bag he's got a big double issue of Science,
National Defense Weekly, the galleys of a friend's book and
something called the Global Business Network's ``Guide to the
Millennium Bug.'' ``This is the stuff I really like, stuff that's
printed out on a laser printer and held together with a staple,''
Sterling says. ``This is the stuff. This is it here.''
</P>
<P>
   People always ask authors of speculative fiction where their
wild ideas come from. Sterling's standard answer is they come from
his mailbox.
</P>
<P>
   Sterling also keeps a hand in nonfiction, applying the
journalism degree he earned at the University of Texas 20 years
ago. His 1990 book, ``The Hacker Crackdown: Law and Disorder on the
Electronic Frontier,'' was one of the first and still the best
examinations of the subject. And he's become an occasional
correspondent for Wired magazine, turning up everywhere from
Phoenix to Paris to the Burning Man festival in the Nevada desert.
``So what do you do for a living, Mr. Sterling?'' he's invariably
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write science fiction novels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, what are you doing (BEGIN ITAL)here(END ITAL)?''
</P>
<P>
   ``My niche,'' he says, ``is to have my hand in a lot of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The chronic gripe of genre authors _ even best-selling ones such
as Sterling _ is that they're viewed as being on the other side of
the literary tracks, but this futurist claims ``scarily large
acceptance'' from readers other than ``your basic culture-swapping
pomo hipster types.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always running into guys who come up and profess they're
big fans of mine and they're multimillionaires _ they're
Dellionaires or Microserfs, the digerati, rich, influential, crazy
SOBs who read science fiction. I have plenty of influence. It
frightens me in a lot of ways. I'm not that eager for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he's seen the what-goes-up-must-come-down celebrity
curse that attaches itself to most mainstream successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me writing is a contest about how good I can get before I
die,'' he says. ``It's not about being the most famous or the most
rich or the best-known or the most influential or the most
universally read. It's about being as Sterlingian as possible
before you're mulch.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Sterling can hang out at Julio's and walk around the
neighborhood looking like a UT professor or professional student
without getting accosted. He enjoys hefty sales _ there are about a
quarter of a million copies of his best-selling book, 1988's
``Islands in the Net.'' But he can walk anywhere, in fact, except
science fiction conventions. And sometimes he can even get away
with it there. He can hang out in the house he built _ not on 37th
Street, but close enough that at Christmas time he feels little
pressure to keep up with the holiday lights excess for which that
street is famous. He can Web surf, churn out essays and books and
hang out with his wife and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real futurists have children,'' he says. ``I believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Beach writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
