<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-DONATIONS _ There was an old ad campaign, ``It Takes A
Tough Man to Make a Tender Chicken.'' By the same token , it takes
a resourceful woman to give airline food a good name. Delta Air
Lines flight attendant Susan Powell has done that, persuading the
Atlanta-based carrier to donate left over snacks to food banks. The
airline gives away about 1,000 pounds of food a week. (Scott,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVING IN LIFESTYLE AND
BUSINESS WIRES.
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ It never occurred to me to be
sensitive about my tradition of tacky Christmas trees. A misshapen
pine or cedar from the woods was as dear to my heart as the finest,
most symmetrical spruce imported from New England and sold at great
price. And I scorned electric lights and storebought ornaments.
This to the consternation of the children in the family who love
bubbly, on-and-off lights and a lot of sprayed-on snow. This year I
have been vindicated. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HYPNOSIS _ Done properly by a behavioral health professional,
hypnosis has proven to be so safe and effective for chronic pain
treatment that even the orthodox Journal of the American Medical
Association has endorsed it. Hypnotic trances not only can divert
people's minds from their pain, but also trigger physiological
responses that actually blunt the pain. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HYPNOSIS-WARNINGS _ Hypnosis is not for everyone. (Lamb, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BATTLE-BULGE-SURVIVORS _ George Fisher and friends set off for
college in 1943 and wound up in combat at the Battle of the Bulge,
one of the fiercest of the war. They were promised commissions but
got rifles and private's stripes instead. Each survived the war,
but not unscathed. George was dropped by shrapnel, Larry by machine
gun bullets and Leon by hepatitis. They came home with a powerful
bond and painful memories that kept them from talking about the war
for nearly a half century. But since a reunion 10 years ago,
they've been talking not only among themselves but to their
friends, their families and total strangers. They all feel a sense
of urgency in telling the stories of their war before the last of
them falls silent. The battle started on Dec. 16. (Kalajian Palm
Beach Post.) 40. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIVINGLONGER _ LAS VEGAS _ A half hour west of the
flame-throwing fountains of Caesar's Palace in this oasis built on
fantansy and hustles, a 60-year-old retired Chicago radiologist
with Charles Atlas shoulders and the zeal of a true believer is
pitching deliverance. Not from sin or deceit, but from age. For
$1,700 a month Dr. Alan Mintz says he can turn back the hands of
time and get rid of the spare tire around your belly to boot.
(Belkin, Palm Beach Post.) 40. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   SYNDICATED-RADIO _ ATLANTA _ Atlanta's two top-rated radio shows
are about to go national. Beginning Jan. 4, WSB-AM will begin
syndicating libertarian loud-mouth Neal Boortz and consumer adviser
Clark Howard to other radio stations across the country. It could
be the start of a huge career boost for both talk hosts, and propel
the Atlanta duo into national players on the talk radio scene.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SALIERS _ DECATUR, Ga. _ Emily Saliers, who could afford to have
people wait on her 24 hours a day, instead has taken to tending
bar, waiting tables and sweeping floors in her own new
bar/restaurant in Decatur. Saliers is half of the Indigo Girls. If
you're a fan, you can drop by the restaurant and chat her up.
(Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING _ AUSTIN, Texas _ He's the leading cyberpunk science
fiction author going, with eight novels and two story collections.
He's just published a ninth novel that, although set almost 50
years in the future, can be read as contemporary political satire.
He cranks out bomb-throwing futuristic essays at an alarming pace
and distributes them via e-mail. An interview w/Bruce Sterling
about his new book. (Beach, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
