<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Dec. 15, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-REPORTER (Undated) _ A search for Philip True, Mexico
City-based correspondent for the San Antonio Express-News, resumed
Tuesday with Mexican government helicopters looking for him in a
remote area of the Sierra Madre. By JOHN MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-DEATHS (San Francisco) _ Nearly 160 homeless men and
women died in San Francisco within the past year, the most deaths
recorded since the city began keeping track in 1987, according to
the Department of Public Health. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   SF-PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ Gay elected officials in San
Francisco have joined other gay community leaders to call for a
national boycott of United Airlines until the air carrier agrees to
drop its opposition to the city's domestic partners ordinance. By
RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   SF-JUDGES (San Francisco) _ Lawyers practicing before San
Francisco's 49 local judges rate the judges in a confidential
survey. The attorneys say some judges are dumb, lazy or biased.
Others are seen as bright, hard-working and impartial. Lawyers say
the quality of justice in a particular case depends as much on the
jurist presiding as the law itself. By SCOTT WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   LUNG-CANCER (Albany, N.Y.) _ Lung cancer is killing women in New
York at a rate 40 percent higher than just 20 years ago, according
to the New York Department of Health. The causes are clear: the
decades-old boom in the ranks of women smokers. By PAUL ZIELBAUER.
</P>
<P>
   PETE-WILSON (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Retiring Republican Gov. Pete
Wilson ponders a possible presidential run. If he decides to go for
it, Wilson faces expensive, grueling campaigns in states that
hardly know him, and rivals that could include Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, former Vice President Dan Quayle, millionaire Steve Forbes,
former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and former vice presidential
nominee Jack Kemp. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HOLIDAYS-RULES (Undated) _ The crazed holidays are here, but
it's not too late to get your money house in order. Want to save
more? Give clever investment gifts? Pay less to Uncle Sam? Here are
10 tips on year-end finances for consumers and beginning investors.
By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   BURGER-WARS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The fast-food chains are dangling
the promise of wristwaches and toys as marketing schemes to entice
the key influence peddlers in families: the kids. So in TV
commercials, just promise them toys based on popular children's
film and television characters, and then they'll plead with their
parents to take them out for fast food. By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-REVIEW-BLUE (New York) _ The sizzle in ``The Blue Room''
isn't all onstage. Yes, David Hare's new adaptation of Arthur
Schnitzler's turn-of-the-century play ``Reigen'' (more commonly
called ``La Ronde'') is, like the original, all about sex. But most
of the buzz has centered on the performance of film star Nicole
Kidman in her major theatrical debut. By ROBERT HURWITT.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-REVIEW-TOWN (New York) _ ``On the Town,'' the
invigoratingly nostalgic George C. Wolfe revival of Leonard
Bernstein's famed first musical, at the Gershwin Theatre, swings
with the infectious energy of jazz in the early '40s. ``Side Man,''
Warren Leight's poignant drama at the Golden Theatre, traces the
private lives of increasingly marginalized jazz players in the
1960s and '70s with the mournful notes of a prolonged trumpet solo.
By ROBERT HURWITT.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Hey, wait a minute. Is this
really happening? It is. It's time to wake up and enter the
national nightmare. Frankly, I have better things to do _ eggnog to
drink, Niners to watch and homeless to write about. I haven't even
finished my Christmas shopping and suddenly there are only three
more arguing days until impeachment. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Anyone who was surprised at Joe
DiMaggio _ angrily ripping himself off of death's door last weekend
_ doesn't know much about The Yankee Clipper. Of all the
84-year-old DiMaggio's celebrated achievements, his most dazzling
is his ability to preserve, for more than 60 years, his godlike
stature. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The victory of the right-wing
of the Republican party is complete and assured. After months of
endless probes and public hearings, they have made certain that all
future presidents of the United States are exposed to a
vulnerability which their zealotry to get Bill Clinton has
invented.There is no going back. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
