<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 12:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWSTAND15-COX     12-15 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The not-so-funny side of Bob Hope
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Hope made generations of Americans laugh, but the comedian's
private life has not always been so funny. In a superb profile in
The New Yorker ($3), John Lahr describes Hope as a driven man who
became one of the most recognized entertainers in the world but
remained a stranger to his family. ``I don't feel that I really
know him,'' daughter Linda Hope says. And Dolores, Hope's wife of
64 years, accepted his notorious womanizing because, ``I thought I
was better-looking than anybody else.'' As for Hope's career, Woody
Allen tells the magazine that the comedian was a seminal influence
on his own screen performances. He was best in films, Allen says.
On television, ``he was not very good. He was lazy, and nobody
cared.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The fairest of them all: Following the trend of ``sex sells,''
Vanity Fair ($3.95) spotlights supermodel/actress Charlize Theron
on its cover and in a splashy layout inside with Annie Leibovitz
photographs. Theron, who appears in Allen's ``Celebrity,'' will be
seen in four big films: ``Mighty Joe Young,'' ``The Astronaut's
Wife,'' ``The Yards'' and ``The Cider House Rules.'' Elsewhere in
the magazine are well-crafted articles on NBC's Brian Williams and
Whitewater indictee Susan McDougal, and a delightful, gossipy essay
by Dominick Dunne on 1960s TV hunk Gardner McKay. Dunne, who
discovered McKay and cast him in ``Adventures in Paradise,'' talks
to the former actor about his life in Hawaii and his debut novel,
``Toyer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clinton under fire: Predictably, the big story in the
newsweeklies is the impeachment hearings. Newsweek ($2.95) offers
three opinions on the outcome, from ``impeach and convict'' from
William Kristol, editor of The Weekly Standard, to ``censure and
move on'' from Newsweek's Jonathan Alter. Former Clinton aide
George Stephanopoulos guesses that the president will agree to
censure and a fine of as much as $4.5 million. One thing he won't
do, Stephanopoulos says, is admit he lied.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. News &AMP; World Report ($2.95) looks at the swing votes and
fence-sitters and suggests that the Senate could vote to dismiss
the trial as soon as it begins and vote for censure instead. A
motion to dismiss requires 51 votes in a Senate with 55
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Time ($2.95) lays out the scenario of a Senate trial and
revisits the 1868 impeachment trial of Andrew Johnson, in which
Kansas Republican Sen. Edmund Ross cast the swing vote to keep
Johnson in office. And, on a lighter note, the magazine picks the
best and worst of the year in arts, sports and entertainment. Not
surprisingly, Tom Hanks and Mark McGwire are among the best, while
the final episode of ``Seinfeld'' makes the ``worst'' list. In
books, Tom Wolfe's ``A Man in Full'' takes the top spot along with
David Remnick's ``King of the World: The Rise of Muhammad Ali'' and
Edward Ball's ``Slaves in the Family.'' The worst book was a
bodice-ripper of a different sort: ``The Starr Report.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Back to Vietnam: Georgia Trend ($2.95) scores a coup this
month with Vince Coppola's compelling profile of Georgia political
activist Charles Searcy. A former publisher of the Athens Observer,
Searcy is now the Vietnam director of the Vietnam Veterans of
America Foundation _ a group that sponsors humanitarian projects in
war-scarred countries. Accompanying Searcy on a visit to Hanoi,
Coppola describes the scene at a school and rehabilitation center
where a 13-year-old Vietnamese girl with cerebral palsy proudly
takes a few halting steps for ``Mr. Chuck.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Entertainment Weekly ($2.99) and People ($2.99)
fuel the publicity for the romantic comedy ``You've Got Mail'' with
cover stories on Tom Hanks and Meg Ryan. People's profile of Ryan,
which delves into the actress' estrangement from her mother and
husband Dennis Quaid's drug use, is by far the more substantive.
The Entertainment Weekly article is simply a gossipy,
behind-the-scenes look at the making of the film. . . . P.O.V.
($2.95) offers a handy guide to instant entrepreneurship, and
Michael Finkel's entertaining first-person account of the circus
atmosphere surrounding the million-dollar search for bombing
suspect Eric Robert Rudolph. As one local tells the writer, ``Right
now, I guarantee you, Rudolph is just sitting on top of some
mountain, laughing at all of you fools.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
