<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOST-CHILDREN-DIRTY-W     12-15 1339
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-CHILDREN-DIRTY-WAR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAGEDY LIVES ON IN THE CHILDREN OF THE DISAPPEARED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By TOMAS ELOY MARTINEZ  
 c.1998 New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In August, Javier Vildoza, 20, the son of a retired Argentine
navy officer, found on the Internet a photograph of his father and
two others who had taken part in torture and kidnapping during the
military's ``dirty war'' of 1976 to 1983, when, it is estimated,
more than 30,000 people were killed or disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Vildoza's father had been a member of the so-called Task Groups
stationed at the Navy Mechanics School in Buenos Aires (ESMA), a
secret detention center, which was commanded by former Adm. Emilio
Eduardo Massera.
</P>
<P>
   The photograph awakened something that had long bothered the
young man. He bore no physical resemblance to either of the people
he knew as his father and mother.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several days, he found related Web sites that
increased his uneasiness. Members of the Grandmothers of the Plaza
de Mayo _ a group of women who lost their sons, daughters, nieces,
nephews or grandchildren during the junta _ had registered more
than 200 children, kidnapped by the military after being born in
prisons and torture chambers. These babies were given away, often
to military and police couples in the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people they were looking for was one who matched
Vildoza's age and facial features, a child born to a young
political dissident in a torture chamber of the ESMA. It was enough
to convince him to take an usual step.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a federal court in Buenos Aires and said: ``My name
is Javier Gonzalo Vildoza, but it is possible that I am another
person. I want to know who I am. I may be a son of the
`desaparecidos''' _ the people who disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   His history as recounted over several weeks led to the Nov. 26
arrest in Buenos Aires of Massera, now 73, one of whose personal
aides had actually raised Vildoza. The story added stunning new
details to what surely ranks as one of the 20th century's most
unbelievable atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Massera had been among the many past South American officials
being investigated by Baltazar Garzon, the Spanish judge whose
efforts also resulted in the recent arrest in London of Gen.
Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
   In his days of megalomaniacal glory, Massera _ who denied any
knowledge of the kidnapped babies _ called himself Commandant Cero,
or The Supreme. Along with other top military officers, Massera was
pardoned in 1990 by Argentina's President Carlos Menem for deeds in
the ``dirty war;'' that amnesty, however, did not cover any
possible involvement in kidnapping the children of victims.
</P>
<P>
   For more than seven years, the Argentines were subject to
violence imposed by a government that claimed for itself the rights
of God. It took the lives of thousands of people without prior
trial or sentence, refused to divulge the whereabouts of those who
were kidnapped, buried persons of known identity in anonymous
graves and tombs, stole their property and children and gave them
to other parents and other owners.
</P>
<P>
   These facts are widely known and often denounced, but they have
lost none of their unspeakable nature. The more we think about
them, the more reprehensible they become and the more unworthy of
being ranked as part of the human condition.
</P>
<P>
   When Vildoza's parents were kidnapped by Argentine security
forces in 1978 and locked in the ESMA, Cecilia Vinas, his mother,
was seven months pregnant. Nothing more is known about the real
father, Hugo Reynaldo Penino.
</P>
<P>
   At least four months after Raul Alfonsin was elected president,
Cecelia Vinas was still able to contact her parents from a secret
telephone, watched by her guardians, but, it seems, they finally
killed her. She never saw her infant son or knew his fate.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Javier is a young man with curly dark hair who lives with
one of the elder (and real) sons of the Vildoza couple. He has
formed an affectionate relationship with an uncle, the brother of
his real mother, and with 11 cousins living in Mar del Plata. He
has a past he never wanted, an education and a value system that
was acquired not through his parents, but through the possible
murderer of his parents.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most vicious and unforgettable legacies of the past
dictatorship was its almost incredible violence against the sacred
right of identity. Thousands of human beings were suddenly
not-beings, without a place, without a name, without existence and
without destiny.
</P>
<P>
   I closely followed these cruel stories thanks to Victor
Penchaszadeh, chief of the genetic medicine division of the Beth
Israel Medical Center in New York, who has helped the Grandmothers
of the Plaza de Mayo since 1982, when some of them traveled to the
United States to denounce the disappearance of their grandchildren
before the United Nations and the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the women didn't know that technology existed to
identify the living grandchildren without a blood analysis _ which
was impossible _ of the parents. Penchaszadeh himself had been
miraculously saved when he was kidnapped in 1976, and lived in
exile after that. He told the grandmothers it was possible to trace
identities through grandparents and other close family members.
</P>
<P>
   Penchaszadeh has kept his ties with the group and presented
scores of papers at international conferences about the kidnapping
of children of the disappeared. Traveling to Buenos Aires four or
five times each year, he has met some of the young people who were
found. Of the many stories he has known closely, another made
recent headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Ximena Vicario was eight months old in February, 1977, when her
parents were apprehended in the offices of the Federal Police,
where they had gone to obtain passports. All three of them vanished
in thin air until, eight years later, the girl was adopted by a
nurse in an orphanage, and this was brought to the attention of the
Grandmothers of the Plaza del Mayo.
</P>
<P>
   There followed a very publicized trial and, even after it was
proved genetically that Ximena was the daughter of Juan Carlos
Vicario and Stella Maris Gallichio _ who were almost surely
assassinated _ the girl refused to live with her real grandparents,
who claimed her custody. It was a long and agonizing battle.
</P>
<P>
   Her false mother forced her, at age 10, to scream before TV
cameras that she would not go to her real relatives. But it had a
fortunate outcome. Ximena came to terms with her true family and
grew up at home; she is now a very bright economics student with a
clear idea of who and what she is.
</P>
<P>
   Penchaszadeh has seen her more than once in the offices of the
grandmothers, right in front of the Market of Buenos Aires, working
on cases very similar to her own.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, in the infinite history of humankind, men imagine a
new way to express their hatred even beyond the limits of death.
The consequences were rarely as cruel as in Argentina between 1976
and 1983. This past is still alive in the womb of the country and,
in spite of the punishment for some of the major culprits,
Argentines haven't been able to grasp its immense evil.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tomas Eloy Martinez is the distinguished author of ``The Peron
Novel'' and ``Santa Evita.'' He is chairman of the Latin American
studies department at Rutgers University and travels widely as an
editor and journalist.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
