into Russia's banking system.
</P>
<P>
   Such a relatively balanced budget would result in a monthly
inflation rate of 5 percent to 8 percent through March. But it
would not lead to hyperinflation, and it would still enable us to
reach agreement on foreign-debt restructuring. In my view, this is
the most realistic option.
</P>
<P>
   _ Option Three: To meet the opposition's populist demands, the
government could try to solve all its problems, including those
that cannot possibly be solved, such as paying off all its debts by
December. This would call for a printing of 150 billion rubles or
so. In this case, inflation would be no less than 10 percent a
month through March.
</P>
<P>
   I think this option would be unworkable. First, it would not
promote economic development; second, it would be fraught with
serious social tensions.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, importantly, I believe that Russia has no economic
problems that cannot be solved. Everything hinges on the political
problem _ the government's weakness in the absence of any accord in
our society over the goals, means and price of reform.
</P>
<P>
   Many say that the democratic movement in Russia has suffered a
big defeat. There surely has been a political recoil. But even if
the idea of building a democracy is defeated, this does not mean
that a normal market economy cannot be built.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as spring, when I was prime minister, I thought the
main thing was to set ourselves an economic task that we could
tackle. I did not realize that in the final analysis, everything
would hinge on politics _ on the stability, wisdom and
trustworthiness of our politicians.
</P>
<P>
   We have made many mistakes, especially in grossly
underestimating the difficulty of remolding social consciousness.
One can speed up the implementation of an economic plan, but one
cannot speed up the remolding of social consciousness in the
various levels of society. All our economic theories, though
correct, tripped over this.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Russia has never seen a mere seven consecutive
years of economic reform. We simply mark time, taking two steps
backward for every forward step. What is important, however, is
that over this time of trial and error, everyone has realized that
no road exists other than the one leading to a free-market economy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Sergei Kiriyenko is Russia's former prime minister, appointed
by President Boris Yeltsin. His duration in office was five months,
preceding the appointment of current Prime Minister Primakov. This
commentary is adapted from an interview conducted by Yefim Barban,
a special correspondent to Moscow News.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
