<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0547 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD-MAN     12-15 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HOLLYWOOD-MANIA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD, D.C. 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELLIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By R.W. APPLE JR.  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    I came to Washington, I always thought, with all the right
stuff: an Ivy League degree, a job on a big-time newspaper, a belly
full of skepticism and a brain littered with assorted information
on throw-weights, T-bills and reapportionment.
 &HT;    I knew who George W. Norris and Arthur Vandenberg and Rexford G.
Tugwell were, and I knew the difference between grands crus and
grand larceny.
 &HT;    I had once had tea at Alice Roosevelt Longworth's.
 &HT;    That pretty well did the trick in the 1970s and 1980s, but not,
alas, in the 1990s. I'm out of some pretty important loops now,
status-wise, because I know little about television and less about
movies. Now that Hollywood narcissism has displaced Rhodes-scholar
earnestness as Washington's controlling ethos, with Barbra
Streisand and David Geffen supplanting George Stephanopoulos and
Robert Reich as prototypical Buddies of Bill, you have to have a
Tinseltown-size appetite for celebrity to keep up in the capital.
 &HT;    Time was, a stiff, black-on-ecru invitation to one of the
soirees given by the grandes dames of Washington was the premier
status symbol. At Evangeline Bruce's or Pamela Harriman's houses,
you might meet the head of the CIA or the members of the permanent
Establishment, those people who had long outlived the
administration that first brought them to town. You might impress
them by your knowledge of the minutiae of politics and government.
 &HT;    The Clintons were launched into Washington by a gala dinner at
Harriman's, come to think of it, but they have long since turned
their backs on most of the people listed in the Green Book,
choosing the glamorous over the grandees.
 &HT;    Me, I still get invited to the British Embassy once in a while,
and before relations between The New York Times and the Clintons
turned testy, I even got asked to the White House a time or two.
But when I failed to recognize Annette Bening at a star-studded
reception at the time of the Clinton inaugural, some of my friends
pitied me. And when I expressed doubts about colleagues who were
trying to turn themselves into celebrities through the pundit
circuit, others dropped me.
 &HT;    The litmus paper changed color especially quickly at the annual
springtime black-tie dinners for Washington reporters and their
guests. They used to be an occasion for us groundlings to chat with
publicity-averse administration officials. (I remember getting Bob
Haldeman in a corner once, the only time I ever talked to him.)
 &HT;    Now, in an effort to make the other guests forget the cheap wine
and the lame jokes, the newsies ask Robert De Niro and Kim Basinger
(and one year, disastrously, the New York shock-jock Don Imus) as
well as Lloyd Cutler and Colin Powell.
 &HT;    The new Washington ought to adopt Suzanne Stone as its mascot.
She was the rapacious small-town weather girl in ``To Die For''
(played by Nicole Kidman, I think) who said you're nothing if
you're not on television. ``What's the point of doing anything
worthwhile,'' she asked, ``if nobody's watching?''
 &HT;    Good question, thinks Washington, vintage 1998, and it has made
Larry King, Tim Russert and Sam and Cokie _ or rather their air
time _ the real forum of American political discourse, eclipsing
the Senate and the House.
 &HT;    During the debate in October about impeachment hearings, Rep.
Robert Wexler, a Florida Democrat, gave the game away. He said that
he wanted to tell his colleagues, ``in the most friendly and
respectful way that I know,'' that he and Rep. Robert Barr, a
Georgia Republican, were scheduled to appear that evening on the
``Crossfire'' program, so he planned to postpone his comments in
the House ``in an effort not to ruin the show.'' No wonder it's
been said that Washington is Hollywood for ugly people.
 &HT;    Everybody's avocation in America is show business, said the man
who wrote ``To Die For,'' Buck Henry. So I guess it's not all that
surprising that President Clinton has got into the game, playing
his sax and discussing his underwear on TV. Or that he spends
almost as much time at fund-raisers in the ballroom of the Century
Plaza as producers, stars and starlets spend in the Lincoln
Bedroom.
 &HT;    Plenty of other Washington heavy-hitters have been fascinated by
Hollywood. But past Presidents kept their psychic distance. John F.
Kennedy was always the star, not the Rat Pack. Bill Clinton, the
unabashed fan of Elvis, is the first star-struck president. I
didn't know Marilyn Monroe, but I know Markie Post is no Marilyn
Monroe.
 &HT;    The president does favors for movieland friends, like arranging
for his national security adviser, Sandy Berger, to brief a group
led by John Travolta on the administration's stand on Scientology.
They, in turn, do favors for him. It's all very chummy.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, former presidents such as Jimmy Carter and Gerald
Ford and eminent senators such as Daniel Patrick Moynihan don't
waste their breath defending Clinton. To the chattering classes of
Georgetown and Cleveland Park, Washington seems critically short of
political heroes these days. But maybe they don't listen to the
right people or read the right publications.
 &HT;    For Hollywood has a whole different take on Clinton's
difficulties. Discussing the president with Elle magazine this
fall, the actress Sharon Stone said this: ``I think Clinton's a
fantastic president. He's done so much good in the world. And
people do not want to assign him the successes of his office. They
only want to assign him the failures. It's really ugly.''
 &HT;    Marshall Herskovitz, executive producer of ``Thirtysomething,''
said recently that Hollywood was more forgiving of Clinton than
other people because it does not see marriage as ``a monolithic
simple entity.''
 &HT;    And Bette Midler told Larry King: ``I feel that he and his wife
have been hounded for the past six years, actually, since they
walked in the door. ... I think he's the smartest guy we ever
had.''
 &HT;    Nowhere else, except in the Congressional Black Caucus and among
the trial lawyers _ surely not among his former aides and onetime
enthusiasts in the universities _ does Clinton get that kind of
unconditional praise.
 &HT;    Maybe it's not surprising that in Washington and in California,
the gossips _ the same ones, now that politics is a subset of
celebrity _ keep whispering that Clinton will go to work one day
for Dreamworks, the entertainment company that Geffen runs with two
other Clinton enthusiasts, Steven Spielberg and Jeffrey Katzenberg,
and live next door to Tom Hanks.
 &HT;    He certainly won't move to Georgetown, where I live, along with
a lot of other people who don't quite fit the new mold. I admit
that I'm of two minds about the status revolution in Washington. I
rather enjoyed playing the old game _ when inside information was
the coin of the realm _ and so naturally I wish I knew more about
the new rules and the redrawn playing field.
 &HT;    But I fear, square that I am, that the whole culture of
celebrity worship has tainted the country, its politics and my
trade as well. In Washington, as elsewhere, fame and fortune, not
talent and perseverance, are now what's most widely respected.
Ex-actors and ex-athletes and relatives of ex-politicians occupy
more and more seats in Congress.
 &HT;    They have instant ``name recognition,'' which is almost as
useful in campaigns these days as money, which propels other people
into high office. You have to wonder whether Abe Lincoln _ homely,
provincial and poor _ would have had a shot at the modern White
House.
 &HT;    Note too that candidates have adopted the techniques of show
business and of marketing, its comrade in hoopla. Both politicians
and producers know that violence sells; as with car chases and gory
murders in movies, TV commercials filled with distorted and
negative language dominate our barren campaigns.
 &HT;    Candidates for important offices no longer proclaim programs and
ideas first and invite people to support them. They take polls to
discover what people think and then develop policies. In other
words, they convene focus groups (cf. sneak previews in Hollywood)
before editing their ideas (cf. recutting the picture).
 &HT;    Politicians' debilitating and humiliating loss of privacy is, of
course, related to the celebrification of politics; we eavesdrop on
Leonardo DiCaprio's love life _ why not on Bill Clinton's? The
voyeur that lurks in each of us has been given more room to do his
stuff, denying it all the while.
 &HT;    Similarly, journalists' loss of standing must have something to
do with the fact that they have emerged from relative anonymity,
reporting less and talking more, part of an ever-growing mountain
of commentary resting on an ever-shrinking base of fact.
 &HT;    I don't blame the man in the street for making very little
distinction between what I do and what Geraldo Rivera does, and
thinking little of either of us. But I don't pretend to like that
particular change in status.
 &HT;     c.1998 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (R.W. Apple Jr. is senior international correspondent for The
New York Times.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
