<HEADLINE>
DOROTHY DAY: TOO SAINTLY FOR SAINTHOOD? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By PAUL ELIE  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    When she died, a multitude came down to the old dwelling off the
Bowery to pay their respects, the way people had come to Catholic
Worker houses for soup ever since the Depression. There were
Catholic Workers, social workers, migrant workers, the unemployed;
addicts, alcoholics, anarchists; Protestants, Jews and agnostics;
the devout and the strident and the curious, there to see what a
saint looked like.
 &HT;    Dorothy Day died in 1980, at the age of 83. She was one of the
greatest religious figures of the century, and one of the most
paradoxical. She was a Catholic and she was an anarchist. She
condemned poverty and she advocated it.
 &HT;    She founded the Catholic Worker, a loose aggregation of ``houses
of hospitality,'' communal farms, newspapers and round-table
discussions for ``further clarification of thought'' _ and called
her memoirs ``The Long Loneliness.'' The movement was wary of
authority, yet revered her as its leader. She humbled herself
before God and sat for a portrait by Richard Avedon.
 &HT;    ``Don't call me a saint _ I don't want to be dismissed that
easily,'' she once said, to no avail. A year ago, to mark what
would have been her 100th birthday (Nov. 8 would have been her
101st), John Cardinal O'Connor of New York, a lifelong admirer,
announced that he would take up the cause for her canonization.
``If anybody in our time can be called a saint, she can,'' he said.
 &HT;    It was an honor, and it was another paradox. For the prospect
that Dorothy Day might be declared a saint was welcomed by
everybody except the Catholic Workers, the very people pledged to
emulate her sanctity today.
 &HT;    The old-time Catholic Workers who were close to Day support the
canonization effort wholeheartedly. But many Workers, especially
the younger ones, see the church remaking a rebel for its own
purposes, and find her synthesis of rock-ribbed Catholicism and
radical politics impossible to attain today.
 &HT;    They find it twisted that Day, a pacifist who opposed even World
War II, should be celebrated by Rear Adm. John J. O'Connor,
retired, a former head chaplain to the U.S. Navy. They object to
his notion that Day _ who became a Catholic after having an
abortion _ could become a poster saint for the church's
anti-abortion efforts.
 &HT;    ``People feel that Dorothy's too good for the church, and are
afraid of what will happen once the church gets its mitts on her,''
says Robert Ellsberg, a former Catholic Worker, now the editor in
chief of Orbis Books, a progressive Catholic press.
 &HT;    When Day's sainthood was first brought up 15 years ago, one of
her nine granddaughters called the idea ``sick.''
 &HT;    Then the high priest of the Catholic left weighed in. ``Her
spirit haunts us in the violated faces of the homeless in New
York,'' Daniel Berrigan wrote. ``Can you imagine her portrait, all
gussied up, unfurled from above the high altar of St. Peter's?''
 &HT;    The conflict has since taken shape as a battle over property,
with the Workers claiming squatter's rights to Day's legacy while
the church exercises its power of eminent domain. Those in favor of
sainthood depict her as ``a loyal servant of the church Jesus had
founded'' (her words) who prayed the rosary on the barricades.
 &HT;    Those opposed are afraid the Vatican's saint-making priests will
evict her from the underworld of tenements, flophouses, rallies and
jails and recast her as the Patron Saint of Soup Kitchens, a
kindhearted woman who dabbled in anarchism on the side.
 &HT;    ``They're going to take the best of Dorothy and remove it, like
a lobotomy,'' says Jeff Dietrich, a Catholic Worker in Los Angeles.
 &HT;    Saints, in the Catholic tradition, are holy people who call
forth the devotion of the faithful, even after they are dead. Since
becoming pope in 1978, John Paul II has canonized 280 saints, more
than any previous pope. And the Vatican has simplified the process,
reducing from four to two the number of miracles needed (say, the
inexplicable cure of a person who prayed for the saint's aid) and
doing away with the ``devil's advocate,'' who argued against the
prospective saint's cause.
 &HT;    Why so many saints? John Paul doubtless has a number of
objectives. The new saints reflect the worldwide presence of the
church and stand in contrast to the modern cult of the self. But
mainly they embody John Paul's view of history. Whereas many popes
have seen the church as above or outside of history, he sees the
church in the thick of it. So he has made saints of people who made
history, however controversially.
 &HT;    In October, for example, when he canonized Edith Stein, a Jewish
philosopher who converted to Catholicism, became a nun, then was
killed as a Jew at Auschwitz, he affirmed _ defying scruple _ in
effect that the church was on the right side of history during the
Holocaust, suffering with the Jewish people.
 &HT;    The ensuing controversy hung on whether Stein died as a Catholic
or as a Jew. The controversy over Day is different. Nobody would
deny that she was a Catholic, and most people think she was a
saint, even those who care little for the church. What complicates
matters is that these people don't agree about what it was that
made her saintly.
 &HT;    The tussle over her legacy is no simple tug-of-war between the
Catholic left and the Roman right. It involves a range of
conceptions of what it means to be Catholic, and the one that
prevails very likely will be the prevailing form of Catholicism in
the next century.
 &HT;    O'Connor went to Rome in September, taking a sheaf of
recollections of Day written by her old friends. Meanwhile, in
flats and tumbledown farmhouses and ``houses of hospitality,''
Catholic Workers are watching his every move. Their friend and
foundress is their pearl of great price. Each day she passes
further out of their hands and into those of the church. If they
are a touch possessive, who can blame them?
 &HT;    Before she was a saint, Day was a bohemian in Greenwich Village,
drinking all night and wandering into strange churches at dawn. She
rallied for the masses, went to jail, married on the rebound, wrote
a novel, fell in love and bore a child, all before she abruptly
became a Catholic at age 30 in 1927. Her lover scorned her. So did
her radical friends.
 &HT;    Twice a year, the patrons of the Radical New York Walking Tour
pause at St. Joseph House on East First Street to hear this story
of Dorothy Day.
 &HT;    One afternoon in 1932 she returned home to find Peter Maurin, a
French ``troubadour of God,'' waiting for her. They founded the
Catholic Worker there and then.
 &HT;    Day called her Catholic Worker column ``On Pilgrimage,'' and she
crisscrossed the country by bus to visit Catholic Worker houses,
taking her breviary, her diary and a jar of instant coffee. She
went to Cuba to meet Castro and to Rome to fast in St. Peter's
Square for peace, yet was so identified with the Lower East Side
that people would invariably show up at St. Joseph House and expect
her to greet them at the door.
 &HT;    The house still looks the way it did when Day was in charge,
furnished with beat-up chairs and a cast-iron stove out of a Grimm
tale. A pot of coffee brews perpetually. The movement names no
leaders; in New York, the closest thing is Carmen Trotta, a
musclebound 35-year-old man with thick brown hair.
 &HT;    He and I set out to join a few old-time Workers for further
clarification of thought at a local bar. ``In the old days,'' he
says, ``the Workers would stand on the corner selling copies of the
paper until they had enough change for a drink. You'd have to sell
an awful lot of papers today.''
 &HT;    The Catholic Worker newspaper still costs a penny a copy. It is
still a broad sheet full of articles about labor, politics and the
life of faith, with a statement of ``Aims and Means'': yes to
``personalism,'' manual labor and a green revolution, no to usury
and bureaucracy. But the subject between the lines is change.
 &HT;    While Day and Maurin aspired to ``build a new society within the
shell of the old,'' today a new society is being built in the shell
of the old Lower East Side. Galleries and boutiques have replaced
the junk shops and flophouses. The Workers used to serve 300 meals
a day; now they serve half as many.
 &HT;    Some people have suggested that the Catholic Workers have
outlived their mission in the Village, but they are there to stay,
questioning change. How should they respond to gentrification _ by
protesting, by homesteading or by founding a satellite house in the
Bronx? Should they welcome Ivy League volunteers who want to pad
their resumes, or insist on poverty as a way of life?
 &HT;    These questions are usually answered through further
clarification of thought. So Trotta spends many hours with the
old-timers asking them what Dorothy would have done.
 &HT;    Yet Day's refusal to institutionalize the movement has left
Catholic Worker houses elsewhere free to experiment. Unity Kitchen
Committee in Syracuse offers ``lavish hospitality'' _ dinner with
china, cutlery and fresh flowers _ as a response to Day's adage
that ``nothing is too good for the poor.'' Casa Juan Diego in
Houston provides English classes, sanctuary for illegal aliens,
first aid for battered women and coffins for the dead.
 &HT;    After the Archdiocese of Los Angeles announced plans to build a
new cathedral _ estimated cost, $163 million _ Catholic Workers
broke into the old one and hung a banner out the bell tower: ``We
Reclaim the Church for the Poor.''
 &HT;    So it is no great surprise that the Catholic Workers have as
many ways of being Catholic as of serving soup. A house in
California sponsored ``a gay marriage'' (the two men later
``divorced''), and one in Denver held a mock Mass led by some
Sisters of Loreto. ``There are some crazy joints out there, some
things that would turn a bishop's hair a little whiter,'' says Tom
Cornell, an old Worker who now lives at Peter Maurin Farm in
upstate New York.
 &HT;    How vital is the Catholic faith to the Catholic Worker's
mission? Ann O'Connor of Unity Kitchen thinks the Worker must be
more faithful to the church. Jeff Dietrich thinks the church must
become more like the Worker, strengthening its ``prophetic
dimension'' through street protests.
 &HT;    And while Mark and Louise Zwick of Casa Juan Diego in Houston
think prayer and worship are as vital as rice and beans (when
supplies run low, they pray), the Workers at St. Francis of Assisi
House in Chicago say that they are first and foremost anarchists.
 &HT;    The Catholic Worker is Catholic, but it is unsure how or why.
Its members hold beliefs ranging from traditionalism to the radical
fringe, with each deciding for himself or herself what the faith
is. It is like the Catholic Church throughout the United States,
that is, and the question _ in the movement, and in the church _ is
whether this diversity is a form of strength or a kind of religious
decadence.
 &HT;    ``Dorothy Day was a romantic of poverty _ she saw poverty as a
sign of God's presence,'' says Francis Cardinal George, the new
archbishop of Chicago. ``Her view is important. It will always be
important. But it will always be on the fringes of the church as a
corrective, not as mainstream Catholicism. Anarchy is not
mainstream Catholicism.''
 &HT;    And one would expect this view from a traditional Catholic
churchman, celebrating a holy woman for her fidelity to the church.
 &HT;    Indeed, Day must be held up as an ordinary, decent Catholic whom
the people in the pews can emulate, even as they vote their
pocketbooks. ``For Catholic Workers, the soup line is the think
tank and the seminar room,'' says Patrick Jordan, an editor of
Commonweal and a former Catholic Worker. ``That's where you make
policy.''
 &HT;    When Day became pregnant in 1919, the father threatened to leave
her unless she aborted the child. She did so, but he left her
anyway. When she became pregnant again, this time by a man she
loved, ``I knew that I was going to have my baby baptized a
Catholic, cost what it may,'' she said. It cost her her lover. Her
conversion followed.
 &HT;    Today, while many, even most, Catholic Workers see abortion as
an act of violence that must be resisted, they see the church's
campaign against legal abortion as an attempt to enlist the state
to enforce holiness.
 &HT;    When USA Today reported O'Connor's remark that Day might become
``the patron saint of the pro-life movement,'' many Workers were
alarmed.
 &HT;    At a meeting in Nashua, N.H., an old Worker named Jack Cook rose
in his chair and denounced the plan as ``a form of spiritual
abuse.'' He was applauded. ``She could have, at any time, come out
publicly and politically against abortion,'' Cook explained. ``She
did not. ... When she spoke of abortion, it was in terms of
forgiveness, not criminality.''
 &HT;    Day's response to abortion is crucial to the canonization
process because she is a role model for thousands of Catholic women
in the United States, an American Mother Teresa. The two figures _
who met in India in 1970 _ are often cast as the two archetypes of
contemporary Catholic activism: one a nun who stressed charity, the
other a lay woman who called for justice.
 &HT;    In a talk last year, though, the Jesuit priest Thomas Reese
stressed what they had in common _ not as women but as devout
Catholics who had devoted themselves to fixing the world rather
than reforming the church.
 &HT;    Reese went on to ask why so many Catholics are bent on the
latter, why the conflicts among Catholics often seem like quarrels
over a brand name, with the players so worked up over what it means
to be Catholic that they lose sight of the holy.
 &HT;    The obvious reason is that the church stands in need of reform.
But there are reasons behind the reasons. It may be that the
Catholic leaders who would confront society _ the Mother Teresas
and Dorothy Days _ are in short supply.
 &HT;    The experts expatiate on the shortage of priests, but the real
shortage is of authentic Catholic leaders of any kind _ of the
saints among the living, that is.
 &HT;     c.1998 Paul Elie  
