<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP UNDERMINES THE PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HARRY ROSENFELD  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The victory of the right wing of the Republican
Party is complete and assured.
</P>
<P>
   After months of endless probes and public hearings, they have
made certain that all future presidents of the United States are
exposed to a vulnerability which their zealotry to get Bill Clinton
has invented.
</P>
<P>
   There is no going back. It doesn't matter if the House finally
votes censure rather than impeachment. It doesn't matter if the
House votes impeachment and the Senate votes not to convict. The
precedent has been established, through the relentlessness of
deep-seated partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   The consequence is to redefine the separation of powers among
the executive, legislative and judicial branches of government,
weakening the presidency. Future presidents will govern in a world
in which they know that at any moment their political opposition
could endanger their term of office through a menu of techniques
enshrined by the success of radical Republicans sitting on the
House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Most tiresome to bear were the ideologues as they portrayed
themselves as heavy-hearted, bearing an unbearable burden, for
having been compelled to vote articles of impeachment. Contrary to
their claim that they were seeking only the higher public good, the
way they conducted the hearings was plainly unfair as they adopted
the prosecution's case without testing it. The staunch
conservatives made it transparently clear that they had stumbled
across a golden opportunity to do undo what two national elections
had imposed on them.
</P>
<P>
   Now whether and how Clinton survives politically is merely
temporal. What will abide is that future political factions,
seeking to enervate the executive, will have a handle on the
tactics courtesy of the Republicans. What is frightening is the
skimpiness of the issues, pellucidly partisan in sum and substance,
that the Republican exploited to achieve their success.
</P>
<P>
   They also established a new, low standard as to what merits
impeachment of a president. Thereby, they set the bar extremely low
for emulation. Not only that, but the success of the Republicans
today means that future presidents will undertake their
responsibilities in the light of the new susceptibility. This poses
the danger that they will reshape policies opposed by the factions
lest they trigger the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   That would distort the balance of powers between Congress and
the president. In this context, what is alarming is the quality of
the accusations against Clinton. They trivialize the purpose for
which the Framers included impeachment in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars, including those of Republican persuasion, have
testified that impeachment was meant to deal with a president whose
conduct impaired the affairs of state. Impeachment, by their
testimony, was not designed to deal with private-life affairs,
which may also violate law.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual misbehavior and its cover-up do not rise to
impeachability. As the president is not above the law, he or she
must answer for any legal transgressions, in a court of law after
the incumbency is completed. This provides for equity under law
without undermining the institution of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The charges upon which articles of impeachment have been voted,
in a party-line vote, show how exposed future presidents will be.
President Clinton came under investigation by the office of
independent counsel for his dealings in the Whitewater real estate
ventures in Arkansas while he was governor. Of this charge, he was
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of misusing the FBI in shaking up the White House
travel office when he took office, a serious charge. He was
cleared. Then the independent counsel cleared him of wrongdoing of
the most serious accusation, that he made illegal use of FBI files
on Republicans that some White House staffers had in their
possession.
</P>
<P>
   The serious accusations having fallen by the wayside, Clinton is
impeached for perjuries and obstructions in attempting to hide his
consensual relationship with a White House intern. The Lewinsky
affair only was dragged in at the last moment by the independent
counsel, when the more weighty accusations against Clinton were
fading.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Lewinsky affair mattered only because of the Paula
Corbin Jones civil suit against Clinton, for allegedly
propositioning her while she was a state employee and he was
governor. Jones' lawyers wanted Lewinsky's testimony to support
their case. But a judge ruled the Lewinsky matter was not material
and rejected the Jones claim as not valid because she did not
suffer any penalty for having rejected Clinton's overture.
</P>
<P>
   The Jones case had been launched at a right-wing political
function, and conservatives underwrote her legal effort (finally
concluded by Clinton paying an $850,000 settlement). The lies
Clinton is accused of telling in the impeachment articles are
related to his testimony in the Jones case, and his subsequent
appearance before the independent counsel's grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   If such a jerry-built construction is permitted to undermine a
presidency, for a malfeasance that ordinary people are only
sometimes punished for, then, of course, adventurers in years to
come need only employ their imaginations to attack other chief
executives again and again.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Harry Rosenfeld is editor-at-large of the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
