<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YANKEE CLIPPER REMAINS AN INDEFATIGABLE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Anyone who was surprised at Joe DiMaggio _
angrily ripping himself off of death's door last weekend _ doesn't
know much about The Yankee Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the 84-year-old DiMaggio's celebrated achievements, his
most dazzling is probably the least acknowledged. What may be more
awesome and amazing than any of his professional baseball feats or
his long, loyal love for Marilyn Monroe, is DiMaggio's ability to
preserve _ for more than 60 years _ his godlike stature.
</P>
<P>
   How has he managed it? By taking a page from the legendary Greta
Garbo's book and guarding his private life with a diligence and
ferocity that defy this perniciously nosey culture of ours.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he couldn't stay in a coma and just go quietly into
the night in a Hollywood, Fla., hospital. Never mind the lung
cancer, the breathing tube, the last rites, the debate over a ``do
not resuscitate'' order. Screw all those warm-up obituaries
everybody has been printing of late.
</P>
<P>
   Regular updates to the news media? About the personal, physical
condition of Joe DiMaggio? Hell no. Heaven can wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allowed Joe to talk this morning (Sunday) and he was very
angry,'' one of DiMaggio's doctors said. ``He said `No more
press.'''
</P>
<P>
   Protecting his privacy, retaining some mystery and maintaining
legend status are astounding accomplishments, especially when you
think of them in the context of us, the world's most photographed,
videotaped, profiled, examined, analyzed and over-exposed
population.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: DiMaggio was born in 1914, reached the pinnacle of
professional success and retired when Harry Truman was still in the
White House. Other than endorsing an electric coffee maker and a
New York savings bank in the 1970s, he hasn't worked publicly at
anything for the past 47 years.
</P>
<P>
   He never married another sex goddess, never bought a baseball
team or movie studio, never slapped his name on a casino or
fast-food chain, never ran for political office, never became a
regular on a quiz show, never wrote a tell-all autobiography or
announced that he needed a new liver.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the mention of the man's name never fails to bring
recognition, and rarely fails to inspire a reverence and wistful
longing in people of all ages.
</P>
<P>
   And when the man happened to enter a room ...
</P>
<P>
   No matter the audience, the effect of Joe DiMaggio's mere
presence on adult men and women remains unparalleled; he reduces
most of them to speechless, starry-eyed kids. Just the word that
DiMaggio might attend a fund-raiser or tribute, or drop into a
favorite joint for a nightcap in San Francisco, was enough to raise
the energy level of any crowd. On the rare occasion he actually did
show up, as he moved across the room _ self-contained and wary _ he
was followed by excited whispers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's him!'' ``There's the Yankee Clipper.'' ``Jesus, Joe
DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Italians have a term for what DiMaggio first created when he
donned those flannel Yankee pinstripes and what he has miraculously
maintained until this very day: bella figura. It means ``beautiful
image'' and is used to describe everything from the way a person
looks in a polished pair of expensive shoes to the near-perfect
existence some folks at least appear to have lived.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's celebrated batting swing is the epitome of bella
figura. Marrying Marilyn Monroe, then staying loyal and devoted to
her even after divorce _ in a mysterious, low-profile way _ is not
a bad example either.
</P>
<P>
   But the most beautiful DiMaggio image is the one we have now: A
very old, ill man somehow occupies the collective mind's eye of
America as a gorgeous and virile superhero. And he is a man who
will stay forever right where we most want and need him to be _
just beyond our reach.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
