<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BURGER-WARS-HNS &LR;      12-15 0503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURGER-WARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KID POWER: BURGER TITANS AIM LOW FOR MARKET SHARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Whoever has the best and most toys sells the fast
food.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Burger King outlets are dangling the promise of
wristwatches and toys based on characters in the recent ``Rugrats
Movie'' and cable television series, while bigger rival McDonald's
fights back with merchandise based on the movie ``A Bug's Life.''
</P>
<P>
   This shows how complex burger marketing is these days. If you
want to attract more customers, the food outlets figure, you have
to entice the key influence peddlers in families: the kids.
</P>
<P>
   So in commercials, just promise them toys based on popular
children's film and television characters, and then they'll plead
with their parents to take them out for fast food.
</P>
<P>
   This strategy works, said Ted Potrikus, who occupies the dual
role of father of two and vice president of the Retail Council of
New York State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meal premium is a considerable factor in the decision of
what fast-food restaurant to go to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other parents are similarly influenced, it appears.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the stores are very busy. We are constantly shuffling
watches to make sure the stores have even supplies,'' said Mike
Neuhaus, district supervisor for Carrols Corp., which operates 21
Burger King franchises in the Albany area.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus expects especially brisk demand this week, when the
Rugrats' Talking Tommy character is featured in the collection of
four wristwatches. The little timepieces sell for $1.99 with a
so-called ``value'' meal.
</P>
<P>
   The watches, along with 12 character toys given away with Kids
Club meals, have already done quite a bit for the greater good of
Burger King, said Charles Nicolas, a company spokesman in Miami.
The promotion started Nov. 18 and in the first week national unit
sales of kids meals doubled, and Whopper Junior orders went up 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Also, orders for chicken tenders shot up 27 percent. Burger King
has been able to make the chicken snacks in the shape of Rugrats
characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little kids get a kick out of them,'' Neuhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   Burger King may have an edge over rival McDonald's in this
particular toy competition, Neuhaus said. That's because the
Rugrats TV show has already built up a wide following, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had years of cultivating fans for the Rugrats,'' he
said. The recent movie just adds fuel to the fire.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, ``A Bug's Life,'' the competitive media offering
from McDonald's, has only its recent movie audience to pull from,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that film is influential too, said Potrikus, whose
daughters have seen ``A Bug's Life'' and then wanted the toys. ``My
6-year-old knew which restaurant to go to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The McDonald's promotion of ``A Bug's Life'' merchandise is
scheduled to last through Dec. 24, and the Burger King-Rugrats
promotion is scheduled to run through Jan. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
