<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-JIHADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLO MILITANT'S SON PURSUES PEACE PEACEFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAZA _ The Palestinian Authority's point man responsible for
coordinating President Clinton's visit, Jihad Wazir, handled the
crush of last-minute details flawlessly Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There were phone lines to worry about, satellite links, and
security protocols. It took all of Sunday night to choose which
symbol of Palestinian sovereignty to mount behind the podium at
which President Clinton and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat would
speak.
</P>
<P>
   And throughout the historic day in the Palestinian march toward
self-determination, Wazir thought of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Khalil Wazir was Arafat's closest aide and chief military
commander of the Palestine Liberation Organization from its
creation in 1964. His nomme de guerre was ``Abu Jihad'' _ he father
of Jihad, or holy struggle.
</P>
<P>
   But to the United States and Israel, he was one of the world's
master terrorists. He was assassinated in 1988 by masked Israeli
commandos who broke into his home in Tunis and sprayed him with
bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Father and son could not be more different. The father wore
fatigues and carried a machine gun. The son prefers pinstripes and
carries a mobile phone. The father believed in armed resistance,
the son in economic empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   The two generations show how the Palestinian fight for
independence has evolved from orchestrated killing to business
development. And they tell of Jihad's painful reconciliation to the
forces of history that led to his father's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me when I saw the American and Palestinian flags flying
together. It gave me a chill to think how far we've come,'' said
Jihad, 35, who is the director of Gaza's new World Trade Center.
``I suddenly realized it's really happening. I thought how happy my
father would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Jihad is the oldest of six children. His father's militant
activities made it dangerous and difficult for them to see each
other, but they remained close nonetheless. When his father was
killed, Jihad was a student at Marquette University, where he
eventually received his degree. He is now as committed as his
father to the creation of a Palestinian state but in a completely
different way.
</P>
<P>
   He knew his father well enough to be sure that he would have
been thrilled with the symbolism of the Clinton visit but concerned
that the Palestinians still do not have control over their own
destiny. To acquire it, he knows, will require financial
independence as well as political sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This growing recognition of the Palestinian state means a lot
to us,'' he said. ``But having a real state means being able to
travel freely _ not to be told by 18-year-old Israeli soldiers to
remove my belt, my shoes, every time I want to leave Gaza. It's
about dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have that yet, but it will happen,'' Jihad continued.
``We've all sacrificed too much for it not to happen. I'm going to
make sure it happens for my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Jihad has named the 18-month-old after his grandfather.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
