<HEADER>
A0596 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-POLLS-BOS &LR;      12-15 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-POLLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S RELIANCE ON POLLS COULD BACKFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One of President Clinton's key arguments against
impeachment is that polls show most Americans oppose it. But
relying on polls is a high-risk strategy that could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, for example, an ABC News poll found that 58 percent of
Americans think that if Clinton is impeached, he should resign
rather than fight at a Senate trial. While polls still show the
public overwhelmingly opposes impeachment, the ABC finding
indicates the public's willingness to stand behind Clinton may be
much softer than the White House realizes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides had hoped that as the public realized the House
Judiciary Committee approved four articles of impeachment last
week, more Americans would become outraged and oppose impeachment.
Thirty-eight percent of those surveyed in the latest ABC poll over
the weekend favored impeachment. But that was up from 33 percent a
week ago and 27 percent six weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Republican pollster Neil Newhouse marveled at the way Clinton's
defenders have urged GOP members to look at the polls and vote
against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm incredulous that polling has come up as much as it did in
the hearings,'' Newhouse said, referring to remarks by Democrats on
the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Newhouse, like a number of analysts, said he wonders whether
most Americans understand that a House vote for impeachment does
not result in the removal of a president. It takes a two-thirds
vote of the Senate to convict and oust a president.
</P>
<P>
   At least two polls taken in October show that Newhouse is right
to wonder. According to a Fox News poll, only 40 percent of those
surveyed knew that a House vote for impeachment did not result in
the removal of the president. The poll found that 42 percent
thought a president was removed after a House impeachment vote and
18 percent were not sure.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the intense media coverage presumably has helped
inform the public that House impeachment leads to a Senate trial,
and some polls now spell out the process before asking questions
about it. Indeed, that might be one reason support for impeachment
rose last week. With widespread speculation that the Senate would
fall short of the two-thirds vote and acquit the president, many
people may see impeachment as a form of rebuke the president
deserves, especially since the House appears unlikely to allow a
vote to censure Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't appear that the actual passing of the articles of
impeachment has affected people's views on Clinton,'' said David
Moore of the Gallup organization, which polls for CNN and USA
Today. ``You might think that might have a negative effect on
Clinton, but in fact that doesn't appear to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlyn Bowman, an expert on public opinion at the American
Enterprise Institute, said the polls show a ``deeply conflicted''
public. With the majority of those surveyed approving of Clinton's
job performance, she said, many people are just now focusing on the
impeachment debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been pulling away from the debate for so long that
it is hard to know how hard the numbers are,'' Bowman said. A close
reading of the polls shows that while a majority of those surveyed
still oppose impeachment, a minority said they would be ``angry''
if Clinton were impeached. In other words, the lack of public
passion that appeared to have helped Clinton for much of the year
now could hurt him as the House heads toward an impeachment vote on
Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican, said
he is surprised the public hasn't risen up against impeachment. ``I
am not hearing this great outcry,'' Shays said Monday. ``What was
helping the president before was the blase attitude. Now you have
the same attitude again, so there is no strong counterforce to
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, speaking to reporters on Sunday in Israel, cited polls
in urging the House to allow a vote on a censure resolution.
``Apparently some three-quarters of the American people think it's
the right thing to do,'' Clinton said. But if the public sees
impeachment as a ``super censure,'' as it has been characterized by
some, then support for censure might translate into more support
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The polls may indicate hidden problems for Clinton. For example,
a CNN survey found that 67 percent of those surveyed believe
Clinton committed perjury, and 56 percent think he should admit it.
Clinton has adamantly denied he committed perjury.
</P>
<P>
   One White House official said recently that internal polls may
have lulled Clinton aides into a false security. White House
officials said they were not prepared for the way Republicans
ignored the surveys and marched ahead with impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   During the Watergate crisis, President Nixon often took heart in
polls that showed a majority of those surveyed did not favor
impeachment. But, according to the Gallup Poll's David Moore, that
changed after the release of the famous ``smoking gun'' tape, in
which Nixon approved a plan for the CIA to block an FBI Watergate
investigation. For Clinton, if any new incriminating material
surfaces, perhaps during a Senate trial, his support could crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking finding in the current batch of polls may be
the way the public thinks members of Congress should do their job.
While Republican leaders have said members should base their
impeachment vote on their conscience, a CNN poll found that the
public wants such votes to be based on the views of constituents.
The poll found that 70 percent of those surveyed think the
impeachment vote should be influenced by the people they represent,
while only 27 percent said the vote should be based on a member's
conscience.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the poll said that members of Congress should
pay more attention to the polls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
