<HEADER>
A0600 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UDALL-HUMOR-BOS &LR;      12-15 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UDALL-HUMOR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR UDALL, DEFEAT, MUCH ELSE, BEGAT WIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When presidential candidates fail, they usually curse the fates
or cry foul.
</P>
<P>
   Morris K. ``Mo'' Udall, the lanky Arizona congressman, did
neither when he lost the 1976 Democratic nomination to Jimmy Carter
after a series of narrow, second-place finishes in the primaries..
Like the old professional basketball player he was, Udall
attributed his defeat to the breaks of the game. ``The people have
spoken,'' he said, and added with a smile, ``damn 'em.'' Then he
went on to work diligently for Carter's election.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he complain when first diagnosed with Parkinson's
disease, the malady that crippled him for most of this decade and
finally killed him in his 77th year Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   When he became aware of the symptoms 20 years ago, several
members of Congress were reeling from accusations that they had
been romantically involved with a lobbyist named Paula Parkinson.
``There are two kinds of Parkinson's diseases,'' Udall said. ``They
both cause you to lose sleep, and both leave you shaking all
over.''
</P>
<P>
   He mocked his illness. He actually suffered, he claimed, from
``the dread disease, presidentialitis.'' It could only be cured, he
said, with embalming fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 1980s, when he pondered another presidential
campaign, Udall handled his decision-making in the best tradition
of another wry Westerner, Will Rogers. ``I'm waiting for a sign,''
Udall said. ``Perhaps a comet or a new star rising in the east.
Perhaps three Democratic senators, riding to my house on camels
bearing gifts of mirth, frankincense and Extra-Strength Tylenol.''
</P>
<P>
   No sign appeared, and he abandoned his last dreams of the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   But as chairman of the House Interior Committee, he counted as
his accomplishments the passage of the Alaska Lands Act, which
protected millions of acres of wilderness from development, his
moves to support the rights of American-Indians, and a landmark
bill to curb strip mining.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his legislative skills and his presidential race in
1976 that rallied liberals around the country, Udall is best
remembered for his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   During his New Hampshire primary campaign, he told of stopping
in a barbershop to introduce himself: ``I'm Mo Udall, running for
president.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the barber replied: ``We know, we were just laughing
about that this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   He also told crowds of a billboard he claimed to have seen in
front of a church in New England. The sign's message said: ``If
tired of sin, come in.'' Underneath, Udall said, someone had
scrawled, ``If not, call 765-4321.''
</P>
<P>
   Udall loved to tell of the mythical politician who visited an
Indian reservation to promise forthcoming goodies from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The residents seemed enthusiastic. They chanted: ``Goom-wah!
Goom-wah!'' So the politician made additional promises, and his
audience again chanted, ``Goom-wah. Goom-wah!''
</P>
<P>
   On his way out, the politician was led to a corral to receive a
ceremonial pony, and Udall said the chief warned the visitor,
``Watch out and don't step in the goom-wah.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a liberal Democrat, Udall enjoyed bipartisan friendships.
John Anderson, a Republican congressman who mounted a third-party
campaign for the presidency in 1980, was a close associate.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John McCain, a Republican member of the Arizona
delegation, remembers Udall as a wise and helpful mentor on Indian
affairs. In recent years, as Udall lay helpless, McCain quietly
visited him regularly in the hospital to hold his hand and talk to
him. ``I don't know if he knew I was there, but it was something I
felt I should do,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Udall's longtime aide, Bob Neuman, reflected Monday on the
former congressman's death. ``Mo was intelligent, a visionary; he
had a great feeling for what he was doing and he had a real sense
of self. He was capable of civility and compromise you don't see
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuman said he heard Udall died with a smile on his face. ``I
have a hunch he was watching the Judiciary Committe on C-Span and
died laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   Udall might also have been smiling at the prospect that the name
lives on. His son, Mark, will be sworn in next month as a
congressman from Colorado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
