A0603 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-15 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I WISH I MAY, I WISH I MIGHT . . . 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Andy Gaus of Boston can't understand how two little words _ may
and might _ can cause so much trouble for writers. He points to a
recent Globe story that said President Kennedy ``may have welcomed
a more candid overview of his administration'' than the Kennedy
Library offers. Wrong, says Gaus. ``Things that definitely didn't
happen and are only being imagined as unreal scenarios'' _ in this
case, Kennedy's giving an opinion on the exhibit _ ``are things
that `might have happened.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Another reader, back in October, had also weighed in on might,
sending me a column with ``you may have learned'' corrected to
might _ without further comment. I wasn't convinced that may was
wrong, but I hadn't yet investigated; Gaus's complaint, and his
testimony to the spread of the misplaced may, prompted me to hit
the books in search of the answers.
</P>
<P>
   And for once, it was no pleasant task. Some usage guides
commented on one aspect of may vs. might, some on another; a few
ignored it entirely. But sorting through the evidence, it seems
that only one of the may/might constructions is truly troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Among the usage mavens, the most widespread dictum is that might
indicates slightly less likelihood than may: ``We may go to Greece
next summer'' means you've bought the travel guide, ``we might go''
means you're considering Scotland, too. But it's a mystery how a
rule so subjective has stayed on the books: The speaker, surely,
has one idea of the likelihood of the event, the listener another.
And the sliver of difference between the two verbs is probably
overshadowed, in real life, by other clues: tones of voice, facial
expressions, whether the discussion progresses to golf or Greek
islands, ouzo or Lagavulin.
</P>
<P>
   I suspected that any consensus on this distinction had long
since evaporated, and a quick survey of fellow editors deepened
that suspicion. ``I grew up in the South, and use might every
time,'' said one. Another felt that might called for further
explanation: ``I might go to Sally's party _ if I know for certain
my first wife isn't going to be there.'' A third reversed the
traditional distinction, using may for a more speculative plan,
might for a concrete, close-to-home possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Next, the experts tell you that might is the past tense of may,
as indeed it once was. But may and might are now used only as
auxiliaries _ in combination with other verbs _ and they appear in
contexts describing both past and future. You may have learned and
you might have learned are equally correct in a speculative
context, if the speaker doesn't know whether you did or didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The past/present distinction does show up in one kind of
sentence: If the main clause is in the past, might will follow
along like a good, obedient past tense: ``Jerry feared that he
might chicken out,'' not may. But that's not where most people go
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only may/might problem causing any significant
trouble is the one Andy Gaus points out. If you write ``The
operation may have saved her,'' you're implying that the patient is
still alive, whether the surgeon's skill or some other treatment
did the trick. If you know the patient died, only might, suggesting
the facts are otherwise, is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   So my colleague who sticks to might every time may be on to
something. If you'd like to be equally safe in past-tense
situations, just remember: If you're talking about something that's
entirely hypothetical, quite unlikely, or definitely not the case,
only might makes it right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Must be the season of the merch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been insider jargon for more than a decade, but this season
the merch is going mainstream: Newsweek, which likes to package
trendy language for mass consumption, used the slang _ short for
merchandise, of course _ in two different stories in one November
issue. (Geoffrey Beene on Vogue: ``Even the ads used to be quite
beautiful. Now it's merch, merch, merch.'') Editrix, in the same
issue, is clearly a limited-edition word (Anna Wintour and Tina
Brown may have earned it, but not many others); and telcos, for
telephone companies, may or may not catch on. But I'd put a small
wager on merch to make it in America; it captures nicely our range
of feelings, from fond to neutral to contemptuous, about the heaps
of stuff we buy and sell one another.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1338EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
