<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENDANGERED SPECIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Caught up in the impeachment maelstrom are two of the most
admirable men in the House of Representatives. Benjamin Gilman of
New York, first elected in 1972, is chairman of International
Affairs Committee. James A. Leach of Iowa, first elected in 1976,
is chairman of the Banking Committee. Both are currently listed as
being undecided.
</P>
<P>
   They are men of stature, reminders of when Republicans were the
party of business. They symbolize the broad bipartisan approach
that put Dwight Eisenhower, Richard Nixon, and Ronald Reagan in the
White House. Now they are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, my colleague John Ellis wrote that the
Republican Party had been divided into three parts. One was the
dominant wing of cultural conservatives, representing 55 percent to
60 percent of the party: ``religious, patriotic, and hyperactive in
state and local politics,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A second faction is made up of economic libertarians,
exemplified by publisher Steve Forbes and the editorial page of The
Wall Street Journal. Ellis put them at 7 percent to 10 percent of
the party: ``Small in number, their voice is broadcast across
hundreds of megaphones.''
</P>
<P>
   These distinctions are real; Ellis understands them better than
most. But alliances among factions make them confusing. Together, I
think of these two as making up the ``Taliban Wing'' of the GOP,
after the Islamic fundamentalist movement that staged a successful
insurrection in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   A third group of ``traditional Republicans,'' comprising about
33 percent of the party, is internationalist, pro-business, and
more moderate on social issues. ``Above all, they believe in
America's mission and preeminence in the global community,'' Ellis
wrote. I'm not sure about his numbers _ he knows the GOP better
than I do _ but I know that Leach and Gilman belong to this third
camp. How they vote will have much to say about whether Clinton is
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   To understand the campaign for the president's ouster, it is
necessary to go back to 1990. That was when the Taliban Wing first
split from George Bush, criticizing his decision to seek to trim
the federal deficit on the eve of the Gulf War, asserting that they
were the true inheritors of the ``Reagan Revolution.'' Their
defection cost the Republicans victory in 1992, and did even
greater damage in 1996, when they turned on Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   It is this Taliban Wing that is now trying to undo the results
of these two presidential elections _ to gain through special
prosecutors what they had lost at polls. Even more remarkable, they
are trying to do it as a lame-duck Congress, flouting the results
of the last election.
</P>
<P>
   I think of myself as a conservative Democrat. I never admired
Clinton; until very near the last of the campaign, I preferred
another term for Bush. I gave up only after it became clear he had
lost control of the Taliban faction within his own administration.
Now, however, I believe that the improbable hero of the 1990s will
turn out to have been Bill Clinton, once we get a little distance
from events.
</P>
<P>
   Two events loom large. The first was the decision in January,
about a week after news of the Lewinsky matter first broke, to
forgo candor. The second was Aug. 17, when an angry Clinton stalked
out of his grand jury testimony and addressed the nation that
evening, admitting an affair with the young intern and attacking
independent counsel Kenneth Starr. Both decisions are widely taken
to have been mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   People keep saying he brought it on himself, but that's not so.
All he did was to insist that his sex life was none of Starr's
business. It was the Taliban that brought the inquisition _ they
and their allies in the press.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal has long been rabid on the subject of
impeachment; indeed, it can be fairly said that it started it all.
Howell Raines, editorial page editor at The New York Times, has
been characterized aptly as a vicious bulldog snapping at Clinton's
pants. Sally Quinn wrote in The Washington Post about that nice
Kenneth Starr and the shame that Clinton has brought upon
Georgetown society. Even as wise a head as David Broder of the Post
last week called upon Clinton to resign. History will not deal
kindly with these positions.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any other spokesman for responsibility? Business
leaders, not surprisingly, are silent. Bush has lost his voice.
Dole is making commercials for Viagra. Candidates for the
Republican nomination in 2000 are avoiding the issue. So decent men
like Ben Gilman and Jim Leach are all that are left. How they vote
will determine whether their ``traditional Republican'' species
will survive.
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
