<SLUG> BC-CALIF-WITNESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATALITY CASE IN CALIFORNIA MELDS RELIGION, LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, Calif. _ The odds caught up with Keith Cook the night he
got drunk and slammed his truck into two cars, sending them
smashing into four people who stood nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The chance that one of his victims would be a Jehovah's Witness
and that she would die was 52 million to one, according to a
statistician. But Jadine Russell did die, after refusing blood
transfusions because of her religious beliefs. Time after time, she
shouted ``No blood!'' to paramedics and doctors working to repair
her ruptured spleen, cracked ribs and other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a case that intersects religion and law, both Cook and
Russell's behavior are on trial. The prosecution accuses him of
murder. Defense attorneys accuse her of essentially killing
herself. The jury will have to decide whether the death of a woman
whose religion compelled her to refuse basic medical treatment can
be blamed on the man responsible for her injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is responsible for the injury; he is not responsible for
the death. . .'' said defense attorney Charles Unger, who wants the
charges reduced to driving under the influence and causing an
accident with injuries. ``It's really inappropriate that he could
end up spending his life in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, pitting cause against effect, is unusual but not
unprecedented, legal observers said. For instance, robbers whose
targets died of heart attacks during commission of the crime have
been convicted of various forms of murder. And in a case with
circumstances similar to Cook's, a drunk driver who hit a Jehovah's
Witness who also declined blood was convicted of vehicular
manslaughter, according to Laurie Levenson, associate dean at
Loyola Law School. A Louisiana appeals court upheld that decision
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general rule is that you take the victim as you find
them,'' Levenson said. ``If you have the bad luck of hitting a
victim who happens to be very fragile, then you'll be responsible
for more harm.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in Los Angeles Superior Court in Pomona denies that Cook,
a 32-year-old auto mechanic who was on probation for drunk driving,
was drunk again the night of the accident. His alcohol level was
more than twice the legal limit. Instead, during the week-long
trial, medical experts have debated why exactly Russell died. The
case is expected to go to the jury Monday after closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   One doctor testifying for the prosecution called it
``ridiculous'' to claim that she died only because she rejected a
blood transfusion. ``What killed her was the injury and the
consequences of the injury,'' said Dr. Jordan Goodstein. Yet the
trauma surgery specialist also said he would have tried to persuade
Russell to accept blood, and gave her a 70 percent to 80 percent
chance of surviving her injuries if she had.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. James Keany, an emergency room doctor testifying for the
defense, said Russell's hospital charts indicated that she had no
other life threatening injuries beside a ruptured spleen that
leaked blood into her abdomen. Asked if patients die from ruptured
spleens, he replied, ``Yes, they die from blood loss.'' He added
that he believed the 55-year-old mother of four could likely have
been saved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to put my mom on trial,'' said Janet Hefti, one
of Russell's daughters. ``Blood would not have saved her life. And
she was in that position because of Mr. Cook's choices and
decisions. This did not start at USC Medical Center. It started on
Sierra Madre Road.''
</P>
<P>
   The night she died, Russell and another daughter were returning
home from a movie when she was involved in a minor traffic accident
in Azusa, about 25 miles west of Los Angeles. Both cars were pulled
roadside when Cook came barreling down a hill. He crashed into the
cars, knocking them into Russell, her daughter and two law
enforcement officials who had stopped at the accident scene. No one
else was seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
   Russell was transported by helicopter to County-USC Medical
Center, where she could not be persuaded to accept blood. The
daughter involved in the accident testified that enroute Russell
had even tried to pull out an intravenous line. By the time she
reached the hospital, deputy district attorney Larry Larson said,
Russell had lost half her blood. She died six hours later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision made wasn't made that night,'' said her husband,
James Russell. ``It was made for Jadine 45 years ago when she
dedicated her life as one of Jehovah's witnesses. . .It's
scriptural law we're obeying.''
</P>
<P>
   James Pellechia, a spokesman at church headquarters in New York,
said Chapter 5 of the Book of Acts directs the faithful to
``abstain from blood,'' an admonition the church interprets to
proscribe transfusions. Several years ago, Russell had a
hysterectomy without a transfusion, her husband said, and also
carried a medical directive card in her wallet near her insurance
card so doctors would be sure to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Jehovah's Witnesses do, however, allow a treatment called auto
transfusion, Pellechia said. In that procedure, a ``cell saver'' is
used to remove and filter blood before returning it to the patient.
Russell said his wife would have considered the treatment, had
doctors offered it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cook's lawyers, insist he is not responsible for her
death because he could not have ``reasonably foreseen'' her refusal
of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Only one million or so people in the United States are
practicing Jehovah's Witnesses, making the fatality a statistical
aberration, he said. Unger had hoped the jury would hear from a
psychologist and statistician who put the probability of driving
drunk and killing a Jehovah's Witness pedestrian at one in 52
milion. But Judge Reginald Yates refused to allow his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jehovah's Witnesses are not on the endangered species list. .
.,'' Yates said when jurors were out of his courtroom. ``If Mr.
Cook could not fairly be expected to collide with a Jehovah's
Witness who could he fairly be expected to collide with?''
</P>
<P>
   If convicted of second-degree murder, Cook faces a maximum
sentence of 15 years behind bars, compared to four to eight years
for the lesser charges that his lawyer is seeking. Unable to make
his $1 million bail, he has been in jail since the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Cooks and Russells have been in court every day, often
exchanging pleasanties. Cook's sister, Dodie O'Keefe described her
brother as ``very sorry for what happened. He knows he has a
responsibility for his actions.'' Pending the outcome of the trial,
she declined to be more specific about that responsibility. The
Russell family has no such qualms.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to be driving drunk and say what happened is my wife's
fault is ridiculous to the extreme,'' said James Russell. ``I am
totally offended by it. She died for one reason -- because of
him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
