<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE REPUBLICANS' OVER-THE-CLIFF GANG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and k coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; WASHINGTON _ The House Republican leadership _ at last out of
the closet and pushing hard to kick President Clinton out of office
_ is asking its undecided brethren to take a third walk off a cliff
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, right about now, they said: Vote with us on our
revolutionary budget, and push the president to the wall; we will
prevail, and you won't suffer.
</P>
<P>
   They were flat wrong. The government shut down, Clinton
prevailed, and the Republicans lost half their majority.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they said: Support us on our national campaign to
make the president's conduct our major issue down the stretch, and
we can increase our majority and make impeachment a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   They were flat wrong again. The campaign blew up in their faces,
and the Republicans lost another half of their shrunken majority.
</P>
<P>
   Off that sterling track record of taking care of their own, the
Republican leadership is now selling impeachment as proper, moral,
politically cost-free, simple, and quick. The undecided Republicans
who fall for the sales pitch again will give new meaning to the
concept of credulity.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main risks ahead for the roughly two-dozen
congressmen who remain truly undecided and incommunicado, roughly
triple the current margin Majority Whip Tom DeLay enjoys among
members with public positions:
</P>
<P>
   --The first is that DeLay's operation is blowing smoke at the
undecided by cooing that a yes vote will be simple and more of a
process vote than a vote to kick the president out of office. In
fact, it will require several additional voting acts, each of which
will tie the hoodwinked member even tighter into precisely the role
of presidential prosecutor that the undecided seek to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   --The second is that DeLay and Judiciary Committee chairman
Henry Hyde are also blowing smoke in trying to assure the undecided
that nothing in the evidentiary case will come out or come back to
bite them. In fact, the holes in this Swiss cheese case get poked
daily.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence that should scare the bejeezus out of the undecided
should come first, and two examples will suffice:
</P>
<P>
   1. In the perjury case based on Clinton's grand jury testimony
last August, the Senate trial an undecided House member will be
responsible for would have to focus on the ``nature and details''
of the infamous relationship. That means smut, and that means above
all Monica Lewinsky's contention that the president was as
amorously attentive as she was, and his that he was not.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to have even a shot at perjury on this grand issue
is through contemporary Lewinsky statements to others, some of whom
Ken Starr found. The problem _ apart from the obvious, human
interest she would have in not telling friends that it was all her
and no him _ is that Lewinsky also told her friends lies.
</P>
<P>
   The whoppers she told Linda Tripp about her first lawyer and
Vernon Jordan are bad enough. Imagine a Senate trial where one
friend recounts Lewinsky's assertion that the Secret Service
brought Clinton to her apartment; where two others say she told
them the president and she went at it in the Oval Office naked as
jaybirds; where a steward says she told of being invited to
Martha's Vineyard; where job contacts in New York said she told of
lunching with the first lady, who had offered to help her find an
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   2. Or, as Representative William Delahund discovered late last
week, imagine the Senate trial on the return-of-gifts issue. With
no direct evidence, the Starr-Hyde inference is that Clinton told
secretary Betty Currie to call Lewinsky, who handed them over on
Dec. 28 after getting the call from Currie's cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Just one problem, leaving aside the fact that Currie and Clinton
contradict her. Delahunt found an FBI report of a chat with
Lewinsky in which she puts the time of the gifts transfer at two
hours minimum before the phone call from Currie allegedly to
arrange it. Neither Starr nor Hyde ever lifted a pinkie to clear up
this flagrant contradiction.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP leadership persists in telling their undecided they
are simply to be ``grand jurors'' finding probable cause in someone
else's case.
</P>
<P>
   Baloney. If articles of impeachment pass, any yes vote will have
to be followed by several others this year and next, to appoint and
reappoint managers for the Senate trial and to pay for it with
taxpayers' money.
</P>
<P>
   The result will make a yes vote in fact a vote to become part of
the prosecution, to sign onto the effort to remove the president
from office, to be responsible for a case Hyde was too lazy and
partisan to even investigate. Talk about walking off a cliff!
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
