<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-INTERESTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY PHONE AND E-MAIL, THE PUBLIC LOBBIES HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Phone lines to the Capitol were so jammed Monday
that the National Organization for Women urged its members to call
lawmakers in their home districts. Electronic mail was so heavy
that it overwhelmed two of Congress's computers. Over the weekend,
so many people called Washington that they threatened to shut down
a main switch on Bell Atlantic Corp.'s phone network.
</P>
<P>
   As the House moves toward a scheduled vote Thursday on whether
to impeach President Clinton, the capital is awash in phone calls,
e-mails, and petitions from the public. And the lobbying will get
only heavier, as interest groups and media outlets generate even
more calls in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no evidence yet that the lobbying has swayed
lawmakers, the group People for the American Way, which opposes
impeachment, is running phone banks in Boston, New York, and Los
Angeles to urge its 300,000 members to contact their
representatives. The group Monday also unveiled a $75,000 radio ad
campaign in four cities that is aimed at 11 undecided Republican
House members.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO, long quiet on impeachment, Monday called on union
leaders to oppose Clinton's removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   From Berkeley, Calif., a husband-wife team has amassed thousands
of petitions over the Internet _ more than 300,000, by their count
_ that urge Congress to censure Clinton and allow the country to
``move on.'' Paper copies of the petition, which can be found at
www.moveon.org, will be delivered to lawmakers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing for impeachment, the Christian Coalition says it has
collected more than a quarter-million signatures on a petition that
calls on Congress to ``hold President Clinton accountable'' for his
actions. The coalition has posted the petition on its Web site,
www.cc.org.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our members are phoning, e-mailing, faxing, making personal
visits to the district offices,'' said Randy Tate, executive
director of the group. ``We haven't had to do much to push them.
That would be like trying to speed up a rock slide.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains unclear, however, is whether all this lobbying is
changing any minds.
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional offices are so swamped they are logging calls
only from the lawmaker's own constituents. ``I can guarantee the
effect from people who are not in Iowa is zero,'' said Barbara
Levering, press secretary to Representative Greg Ganske, an Iowa
Republican. ``He doesn't even know about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, many lawmakers, such as Ganske, have already announced
their position on impeachment, and they are unlikely to change
their minds. ``I hate to say anything is impossible, but he put a
great deal of thought into it already,'' Levering said of Ganske,
who favors impeachment. ``He's already talked to an awful lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Neil Volz, who works for Representative Bob Ney, an Ohio
Republican who is undecided on impeachment, said Ney ``is not
necessarily going to stick his finger in the wind'' as he makes up
his mind. The congressman is talking to legal scholars as well as
to constitutents, and he has asked to speak with Clinton's own
lawyer, White House counsel Charles F.C. Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   Volz said Ney's office received 7,000 e-mails and hundreds of
phone calls over the weekend, and opinion has been running 8-to-1
in favor of impeachment. However, when staff Monday morning began
giving callers a list of options that included censure, 60 percent
chose censure over impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Levering said 70 percent of callers to Ganske's office favored
impeachment, with 30 percent opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The major business lobbies in Washington say they are staying
out of the impeachment battle. Labor unions, however, are becoming
active. At the AFL-CIO, President John Sweeney Monday night faxed a
letter to union leaders to urge them to fight impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been staying out of this on the premise that it was
going to be a reasonable process, but the process has gotten so out
of control and become totally partisan,'' said Peggy Taylor,
legislative director for the labor organization.
</P>
<P>
   Social activists have been the most vocal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defend Truth. Defend Honor,'' said a pro-impeachment group
called American Renewal in a full-page ad in Monday's Roll Call, a
newspaper read by Capitol Hill staff and lawmakers. American
Renewal is led by Gary Bauer, best known as a domestic policy
adviser to President Reagan and president of the conservative
Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   American Renewal has also sent faxes to 4,000 of its most active
supporters, urging them to call lawmakers, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, president of the Rainbow/PUSH Coalition,
announced a ``prayer vigil'' outside the Capitol on Thursday as
lawmakers debate the impeachment articles. ``We're calling to stop
the impeachment process,'' said Dina Anderson, spokeswoman for the
group.
</P>
<P>
   NOW, which opposes impeachment, has asked its local chapters to
urge its 200,000 members to call lawmakers. The women's group also
says it has sent an alert to 8,000 members by e-mail and to several
hundred people by fax.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday and Saturday, so many people called lawmakers and
media outlets in Washington that Bell Atlantic could not handle all
the traffic. Overloaded phone circuits are not unusual in
Washington, but a Bell Atlantic spokesman said the volume was so
heavy those two days that it threatened to shut down a switching
center. At one point, the company logged 15,000 calls in 5 minutes,
compared to about 500 calls normally.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Daley, the Bell Atlantic spokesman, said most of the
traffic was generated by C-Span, which posted phone numbers for
viewer opinion lines during the House Judiciary Committee
impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, People for the American Way was sponsoring a
toll-free number that allowed callers to reach the Capitol
switchboard and lawmakers' offices. People had used the number to
make 86,000 calls as of Friday evening, a spokeswoman for the group
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Shields, president of People for the American Way, said
the group would run radio ads Wednesday and Thursday in
Philadelphia, New York, the District of Columbia, and Columbus,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The ads aim to sway the following Republican lawmakers to oppose
impeachment: Representatives Michael Castle of Delaware, Jon Fox
and James Greenwood of Pennsylvania, Christopher Smith of New
Jersey, Rick Lazio of New York, Nancy Johnson of Connecticut,
Constance Morella of Maryland, and Deborah Pryce, David Hobson, and
Ney of Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
