<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-NEWYORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NINE N.Y. HOLDOUTS COULD COME TO CLINTON'S RESCUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - President Clinton has long treated New York as if it
were his favorite state. Now New York has the chance to return the
favor.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton avoids impeachment by the House of Representatives
this week, he may owe his escape to New Yorkers _ not least,
curiously, to New York Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 47 House Republicans reported to be wavering or opposed
to impeachment, nine _ more than one-fifth _ come from New York,
far more than from any other state.
</P>
<P>
   New York has always been a little different from the rest of the
country, so it only stands to reason that New York Republicans
should be a little different, too.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is unusually popular in New York. In the 1996 election,
he won 60 percent of the state's vote. More than that, he won all
of its 31 congressional districts, even the 13 that sent
Republicans to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every survey that's been conducted, locally and statewide,
indicates that New York State residents are opposed to the
impeachment of the president,'' Alan Eysen, spokesman for the
Republican committee in Suffolk County, Long Island, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   During last month's congressional elections, Eysen noted, no
Republican here dared bring up the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mercurio, a leading Republican political consultant,
observed that few of the state's Republicans would risk much, from
either their voters or the local party leaders, by letting Clinton
stay in office.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki, Sen. Alfonse D'Amato (recently defeated but
still influential), and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani _ all
Republicans with national reputations _ have spoken out against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``So how much cover do they need?'' Mercurio said of the state's
congressional Republicans. ``It's a comfortable environment to cast
a vote of conscience,'' as opposed to a vote of party-line
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, fully understanding the importance of the New York
Republicans, invited two of them _ Michael Forbes and Rick Lazio,
both Long Islanders _ to join him on his trip to the Middle East.
Forbes turned him down, but Lazio went. He told Long Island Newsday
on Sunday that Clinton came back to talk to him during the flight
over, but not about impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   While few of the nine New York waverers could fairly be called
``liberal,'' all of them hold moderate views compared with the
Republicans who dominate Congress today _ and they have voted
against the party leadership, and with Clinton, on a number of
high-profile issues.
</P>
<P>
   Even more than most, New York is a state of immigrants _ Pataki
himself is a second-generation American _ so almost no politician
here can afford to buy into the national party's policies which
many immigrants and their advocates find offensive.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a state where unions are still powerful and where the
economy _ especially upstate and on Long Island _ has not
experienced the full benefit of the national recovery from
recession. So few politicians _and none of the nine waverers _ can
swallow whole the national party line on the minimum wage, welfare,
or health care.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nine also come from districts dominated by water _
Forbes from the eastern shore of Long Island, Sue Kelly and
Benjamin A. Gilman from the reservoirs of the Hudson Valley _ so
they have also been inclined to vote with Democrats on
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Gilman and Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, another of the nine, are
among the last of the ``Rockefeller Republicans,'' the label given
to GOP moderates who modeled their positions on longtime New York
Gov. Nelson Rockefeller's. It's a wing of the party that is nearly
extinct in most of the country, but it still flies in large
sections of this state.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman of the House International Relations Committee and a
diehard opponent of his party's isolationist tendencies, Gilman has
also supported Clinton's position on foreign aid and free-trade
treaties.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three firm impeachment opponents, Rep. Jack Quinn,
from the Buffalo area, has voted against his party not only on
labor issues but also on gun control. In 1994, he briefly signed on
to Newt Gingrich's ``Contract with America,'' and started voting
accordingly, but returned to his independent stances after local
opponents started winning points by calling him a Gingrich clone.
</P>
<P>
   Another opponent, Rep. Amo Houghton, is a former chief executive
officer of Corning Glass Works, and not only holds liberal views on
trade, abortion rights, gun control, and the National Endowment for
the Arts, but was one of only 11 Republicans in the entire House
who opposed the GOP's 1995 tax-cut package.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter King, the third anti-impeachment stalwart, is more
conservative than the others, but he is also an Irish-American who
supports the Irish Republic Army above much else and is beholden to
Clinton for his work on a settlement in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine, these three have set their opposition to
impeachment in stone, but the other six confirmed through aides or
spokesmen Monday that they remain undecided. Their political views
and the nature of their constituencies indicate that they are
accustomed to bucking the party line now and then _ but this does
not mean they will do so this time. A few, including Lazio and
Forbes, are rumored in some Republican circles to be leaning in
favor of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Aides in all six offices reported Monday receiving ``a lot'' of
phone calls from constituents. Most said they had not yet tabulated
the results, but aides for Forbes and Lazio calculated the calls as
running 60-40 against impeachment. An aide to Forbes added that his
office had received, by late Monday afternoon, about 1,400 calls.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican county leader, who asked not to be identified,
said he doubted any of the nine would see their careers decided,
one way or the other, by the impeachment vote. First, the next
election is two years' off. Second, all nine won their last
elections by huge margins _ most carrying around two-thirds of the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, another Republican noted that the state Conservative
Party was pushing for impeachment and, in several districts, it is
hard for a Republican to win conclusively without winning that
party's endorsement, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
