A0629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-DEATH-BOS &LR;      12-15 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAIN PEARS'S COLORFUL PLOT AND CREEPY STEW OF CHARACTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FIONA LUIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
DEATH AND RESTORATION 
By Iain Pears 
Scribner, 223 pp., $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sustaining the tension inherent in the taut plot lines of a
mystery novel can be something of a tightrope act. Weaving an
entertaining yarn whilst performing this feat is an act of even
higher grace, and it is one Iain Pears pulls off deftly in ``Death
and Restoration.'' The sixth installment in his Jonathan Argyll
mystery series, it stands solidly on its own, not requiring
previous introduction to the character of Argyll, an art dealer
turned lecturer in Baroque studies.
</P>
<P>
   Pears, an English journalist and art historian, employed his
canny knowledge to pen the five previous art-world crime novels,
forebears to ``Death and Restoration.'' He is also the author of
``An Instance of the Fingerpost,'' a literary thriller published to
raves last year.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaim is well deserved: Pears exhibits quite a masterful
touch at suspenseful storytelling. Here, he has melded the story of
a relationship between Argyll and his fiancee _ Flavia di Stefano,
who works for Rome's Art Theft Squad _ with the mystery of an icon
missing from the chapel of the monastery of San Giovanni.
</P>
<P>
   When di Stefano receives a tip that a theft is imminent, Argyll
is keen to lend his expertise. The target, all assume, must be a
painting attributed to Caravaggio, since the monastery's only other
art holding is a seemingly ordinary Madonna. But of course the plot
thickens.
</P>
<P>
   First, there is the prickly matter of dissension within the
ranks of San Giovanni's monks. Their leader, Father Xavier, 39th
head of the Order of St. John the Pietist, wants to rebuild the
order; but to do so he needs to raise money by selling the
monastery's assets, the supposed Caravaggio among them. His
proposals cause turmoil, with the monks diverging into two camps.
</P>
<P>
   Second, a notorious English art thief named Mary Verney arrives
in Italy, raising the hackles of Argyll and di Stefano, whose paths
have crossed Verney's before. Could Verney be in Rome
professionally, sniffing out the treasures of the monastery rather
than as a mere tourist? Is she motivated by a more personal, dire
need?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the couple is unclear about the role of Daniel
Menzies, dubbed ``the Rottweiler of Restoration.'' Menzies has been
hired to return luster to the Caravaggio in the dusty chapel, which
also shelters the icon of the Virgin and Child, long revered by the
locals for its powers of protection. Adding to the creepy stew of
characters is one Peter Burckhardt, a French gallery owner known as
a top-notch expert on icons.
</P>
<P>
   Like daubs on a canvas, these colorful plot strokes blend
together against the backdrop of a city rendered as ancient,
secretive, and grudge-driven. Pears smartly allows each character
to connect disparate areas of dots, as it were, and a picture of
sorts begins to emerge.
</P>
<P>
   A brutal attack on Father Xavier in the chapel at San Giovanni
heightens the tension, and Argyll and di Stefano kick into high
gear; while di Stefano tails Verney and fills in a few blanks,
Argyll's sleuthing leads him to Father Charles, an elderly and
senile member of the order who weaves a fantastic tale: the stolen
painting of the Madonna, raves the priest, is one that was
reputedly painted by St. Luke, and it is in fact the supreme emblem
of the Byzantine empire.
</P>
<P>
   As Pears distinguishes fact from fiction, crimes, misdemeanors,
and history combine to unleash a series of events that culminate in
tidy resolution. It is to Pears's great credit that the textured
paths of modern-day mystery, ancient empires, and religious faith
collide so effortlessly. Clearly, his training as both journalist
and art historian make for a finely tuned duet. He writes clearly,
persuasively, and with a hand guided by touches of sentimentality
as well as mischief.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, once all the dots are connected, ``Death and
Restoration'' leaves a memorable, satisfying imprint. We have
Pears's subtle technique of mixing intrigue with intelligence to
thank for that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
