<HEADLINE>
GIFTS ABOUND FOR YOUR FAVORITE TRAVELER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everyone travels. Even if it's just ``over the river and through
the woods to grandmother's house.'' So, whether you know a world
traveler or just a family traveler, giving the gift that says
``travel'' is easy and fun, especially since this gift can bring
memories for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   For many, the gift of travel means spending lots of money, but
it doesn't have to. It can be a simple gift: a map, a flashlight, a
guidebook, a gift certificate toward travel, a game, a camera. When
it comes to travel, there's no limit to the ideas that will benefit
last-minute shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   I like small items that are easy to pack, handy, and useful for
lots of occasions. That's why the Olympus 35mm Stylus Epic Zoom 80
fascinates me. It's a real stocking stuffer, so small it fits in
the palm of your hand, but so big on features. Olympus says it's
the smallest 35mm camera in the world. This camera zooms from 38mm
to 80mm, takes great photos, is weatherproof, and does just about
everything, including autofocus, that those big, bulky 35mm cameras
do. It's a go-everywhere, do-everything camera. I thought I had
bought a great Olympus miniature camera years ago, but this one
outdoes that earlier Stylus. The Stylus Epic Zoom 80 retails for
$325; a DLX model for panorama shots lists at $345.
</P>
<P>
   For a much lower price, and a great gift idea, there are those
``throwaway cameras'' from Kodak and others, especially the
underwater models that are great for people snorkeling in the
Caribbean or elsewhere. The cameras, which list for about $20 on
down (I just bought a couple of gift ones at Stop &AMP; Shop selling
for $7.99, and with coupons from the Sunday paper cut the price by
$2 more).
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be lavish, get your traveler one of the new
digital video cameras that can fit in a pocket yet are packed with
features. Santa, I've seen them for around $1,000, if you get the
message. Another camcorder choice would be an 8mm one, a lot
smaller than those VHS models, just as easy to use, and with two
hours or more of recording on one tape. These start at under $500.
</P>
<P>
   Since family travel means kid travel, getting something to keep
them amused in the back seat is the key to a great outing. One idea
is a hand-held electronic game that can be played by one or more.
Hasbro has some nice ones out this year: kid favorites like Mr.
Potato Head and Candy Land Adventure designed for small hands to
entertain and teach skills such as counting. For older kids, there
are Monopoly, Pro Drag Racing _ with trackside sounds and
vibrations _ and one that can be enjoyed by the whole car, Trivial
Pursuit Electronic Hand-Held Best of Genus Edition with 3,600
trivia questions. The games retail for $13.95 to $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   Flashlights may not seem a gift item, but they can be very
useful on the road. Lumatec offers some great ones that are
credit-card size called FlashCard. They offer lots of light, even
have a pocket to carry a credit card or other item, and come in 45
designs. The FlashCards are $6.95; buy three and you get a free
T-shirt, plus there's a contest that offers a trip for two around
the world. If you can't find FlashCards in a store, call
800-776-7945.
</P>
<P>
   Maps are another great gift idea. Rand McNally has a MapGuide
series to popular destinations. These offer both a map and a guide,
and can fit in a pocket. The guides are $5.95 each.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of travel-related gift ideas can be found from Travel
Smith (800-950-1600) and Magellan's (800-962-4943), two large
California-based catalog firms specializing in travel-related
items. You name it, if it's for travel, more than likely they have
it _ from clothes and luggage, to first-aid kits, to comfort items.
</P>
<P>
   New luggage, especially a carry-on, would be a welcome gift.
With new carry-on limits of one or two bags, depending upon the
airline, and new limits on size, a carry-on that meets the new
rules is a great idea. Tilley Endurables, a Canadian manufacturer
of travel and adventure wear, claims its Tilley Travel'Aire bag
meets airline specs while offering a ``cavernous'' main compartment
along with extra pockets for small items. It's designed to be worn
over the shoulder or as a backpack. It's one of six bags priced
from $39 to $175. For details, call 800-ENDURES.
</P>
<P>
   To make the trip more enjoyable, Rockport, the footwear company,
offers the New Comfort Travel Kit ($40), filled with lotians and
other items to refresh and rejuvenate a weary traveler.
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers are heading for the Internet to do their
last-minute, a- click-or-two-away shopping. Both Travelocity.com
and MSN Expedia are reporting higher-than-ever sales on the Web.
Expedia, which reported $8.5 million in weekly revenue following
Thanksgiving, feels such sales are indicative of consumers'
increasing comfort in purchasing on line. Expedia says it is
offering special prices on packages and cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Still stuck? A gift certificate can solve the problem quite
nicely. These are easy to pack, can be bought at the last minute,
and can be used toward a vacation or travel item. One company,
1-800-GIFT CERTIFICATE (800-443-8237), can handle requests for
certificates with one call, and they can be used at participating
stores, Hyatt and Marriott hotels, American Airlines, and others.
Hyatt, for example, offers both Hyatt Stay Certificates beginning
at $159 for stays at their properties and Check Certificates from
$25 to $500 for goods and services, including rooms (call
800-555-9655). Travel agents, cruise lines, and other hotel chains
also offer certificates your traveler will love.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still hesitating abut a travel-related gift, consider
a recent TeleNation survey that indicated 60 percent of Americans
want to receive memorable experiences over expensive objects. Given
a choice between travel, concert tickets, sports club memberships,
and free dinners, more than half of Americans (54 percent) said
travel tops their wish list.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
First Night
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First Night, created in Boston 23 years ago, promises once again
to dazzle the senses with 50 indoor and outdoor venues offering
more than 250 performances and events ranging from music and giant
street puppets to fireworks over Boston Harbor. Many hotels feature
First Night packages. Everything can be seen and enjoyed with the
purchase of a $10 button.
</P>
<P>
   Call 888-SEE BOSTON (888-733-2678) for a listing of all of
Boston's happenings along with a free Family Friendly ValuePass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ferry delayed
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Florida's new high-speed ferry service between Fort Myers and
Key West has been delayed. The service by Buquebus is now expected
to begin sometime early next year. For information, call
941-461-0999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toronto theater
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stages '99 is on in Toronto and continues through Feb. 28. It's
a festive theater season with special discounts, gifts, and value.
Some 40 Toronto hotels are offering special rates ranging from $59
at the Days Inn to $225 at the Four Seasons _ and that's Canadian
dollars, which means American visitors will be getting up to a 40
percent discount because of exchange rates. To participate, call
Tourism Toronto at 800-363-1990 or 416-203-2500, and a
representative will provide information on all the events and
packages, help in selecting a hotel and on purchasing tickets to
Stages '99 _ including such great shows as ``Phantom of the Opera''
(most tickets are discounted 25 percent for added savings).
Participants will also receive a free guided tour of Ed's Market of
the Absurd, the Unusual and the Ridiculous, the only museum where
everything is on sale; here you can see items collected by theater
impresario Ed Mirvish that range from costumes worn by famed stars
to posters to penny arcade machines. During check-in at hotels,
guests will also receive a VISA VIP book with special offers good
when redeemed with a Visa card.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Disney celebrates
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, what can you expect at Walt Disney World in Florida this
holiday season? A lot. Take 130 tractor-trailer truckloads of
decorations; 126,000 red, white, and pink poinsettias; 5.2 miles of
garland; 1,200 Christmas trees; 760 feet along Residential Street
at Disney-MGM Studios, where you can view the Spectacle of Lights
that includes two 30-foot-tall holiday carousels, 20 giant candles,
20 snowmen, 50 Mickey Mouse figures, 50 bells, 178 angels, 100,000
bulbs illuminating the 70-foot Tree of Lights, and 4 million
holiday lights; 11 countries dressed for ``Holidays around the
World'' at Epcot; a 50-piece orchestra with a live mass choir for
Disney's Candlelight Processional at Epcot; 18,000 decorated red
apples at Fort Wilderness Resort; a 100 percent chance of snow
flurries during Mickey's Very Merry Christmas Party; 5,000 square
feet of outdoor ice-skating rink frozen solid; great shows; lots of
fun; and a lot more for a great holiday getaway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Polar Express
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate this holiday season through the eyes of a child as
Chris Van Allsburg's festive and heartwarming Christmas tale, ``The
Polar Express,'' comes to life at Steamtown National Historic Site
in Scranton, Pa. The Polar Express runs Dec. 14 through Dec. 28,
with three trips from 4:30 p.m. through 7:30 p.m. Tickets are $7.50
and can be obtained by calling 888-693-9391.
</P>
