<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WHALE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHALEBONES AND COBBLESTONES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK LEHR  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BEDFORD, Mass. _ ``He's the old guy with a white beard and
white hair,'' said a scrimshaw artist in the national park district
of this seaport city, pointing the way to the whaling museum where,
downstairs, there he was, on his knees working among the giant
bones of a 65-foot blue whale.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Konnerth was positioning one of the whale bones on an
oversized scale to record its weight when he stood to take a short
break. His is no ordinary line of work: ``freelance osteological
and paleontological preparations.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: He assembles skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   The man and the whale will be the buzz of New Bedford for months
to come, and have been since the whaling museum came into
possession of the dead whale earlier this year. Now Konnerth and
his wife, Jean, who are septuagenarians, are painstakingly
assembling the skeleton for permanent display in a planned new
lobby.
</P>
<P>
   The skull alone, Konnerth found, weighs 3,470 pounds, and the
blue whale skeleton is expected to be the biggest such exhibit in
the world, a fitting addition to this city so steeped in the
history of whaling. The assembly, a work in progress unfolding in
open view, was reason enough for a day trip here, but there was
also much more to see.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year especially, if the weather cooperates and the
day is clear and blustery, is a good time to wander about the
historic whaling park, which is now overseen by the National Park
Service. It's easy to get here by car, easy to park, and easy to
take in in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a historic district that's still finding its way.
There are the quaint cobblestone sidewalks, the red-brick and
granite museums and other historic sites, but some of the
district's buildings are boarded up and for sale. That, however, is
part of the appeal. Instead of the high-gloss of some tourist
centers, instead of wall-to-wall T-shirt and novelty shops, there
remains a rough-hewn atmosphere to the historic whaling district.
</P>
<P>
   Within a 13-block area, there's a mix of museums and the real
working world, so that it's easy to dabble in history, shop for
scrimshaw or maritime art, dine at any of a handful of seafood
spots, and then walk along the waterfront. The piers that line the
harbor right off the park still constitute a vital port for the
region's fishing trawlers and boats.
</P>
<P>
   In the center of the park district is the Custom House, a
handsome Greek Revival building completed in 1836, where ship
captains came to clear their cargo. Less than a block away stands
the Seamen's Bethel, a chapel where whalers prayed before heading
out to sea. Like the city itself, the simple-looking chapel is
featured in Herman Melville's classic whaling novel, ``Moby-Dick,''
and hanging inside on the walls are tablets in memory of men who
died while at sea.
</P>
<P>
   During the slanting afternoon sunlight of a recent late fall
day, with leaves swirling along the grounds of these 19th-century
buildings, and with a church bell ringing out on the hour, it was
not hard to imagine this city in its whaling heyday more than a
century ago, when the New Bedford area was the nation's
fourth-largest seaport (behind New York, Boston, and New Orleans in
terms of the combined tonnage from its whaling and merchant
fleets). Just beyond the park district itself, up a hill, stand a
number of grand old mansions, including the Rotch-Jones-Duff House
and Garden Museum on County Street. The mansion was built by a
whaling merchant in 1834, and its formal gardens cover a city
block.
</P>
<P>
   Though we came in search of a dose of whaling history and lore,
we were surprised and interested to find that work is under way to
further explore and document the city's substantial role in the
Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   National Park Service rangers last summer began combing through
old records to compile lists of antislavery organizations and the
names of antislavery residents and the neighborhoods where they
lived. Tunnels have been located and, in some mansions, secret
hiding areas have been revealed. Eventually, the Park Service hopes
to add such sites to walking-tour maps.
</P>
<P>
   Given its large port, New Bedford was a key stopover for slaves
en route to Canada, particularly those from South Carolina and
Georgia. Frederick Douglass and his wife lived for three years
here, from 1838 to 1841, after their escape from slavery. Two years
ago, a monument was dedicated outside City Hall to Douglass, who by
the mid-1840s was a leading abolitionist.
</P>
<P>
   But the work-in-progress with the highest profile these days is
the Blue Whale project. ``From my bench here I could look out my
window and watch them scrape the bones clean,'' says scrimshaw
artist Albert L. Doucette about the cleaning phase late last
summer. ``The bones were all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Doucette's shop, Whale's Tale, is on North Water Street, in back
of the whaling museum. And last summer, before the work moved
inside and into the hands of the assemblers, the Konnerths, a
number of volunteers scrubbed bones on the back lawn of the museum.
``It's going to be a big deal, no question about it,'' says
Doucette.
</P>
<P>
   Hit and killed by a tanker early this year, the blue whale was
discovered lodged against the tanker's bow as it entered
Narragansett Bay. Plans were already under way at the whaling
museum here for a new wing, and the National Marine Fisheries
Services agreed with the museum's pitch that a mostly intact
skeleton of the largest animal in the world would best be exhibited
hanging in its new lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Andrew and Jean Konnerth, who began consulting with museum
officials last spring. It was on Andrew's advice that the whale's
bones, stripped of most flesh, were then immersed in sea water
until September, to allow tiny isopods and zooplankton to pick the
bones clean. The couple works in an open space on the lower floor
of a museum already filled with harpoons, lances, tools, and even a
large scale-model whaling ship.
</P>
<P>
   The blue whale's bones still give off an oily smell, and these
days the Konnerths are weighing and arranging the bones into four
large, ``anatomically correct'' sections. Steel pipes will be used
to assemble the skeleton, and given the whale's weight _ each lower
jawbone is 640 pounds _ the bones will be ``mounted so the weight
is carried by steel.'' The couple will be positioning the bones for
the next several months, but the skeleton won't be hung for
permanent exhibit until the new wing is completed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   This is the seventh _ and largest _ whale skeleton Andrew
Konnerth has assembled. Ten years ago, he assembled a humpback
whale for the New Bedford museum, and he has put together skeletons
for aquariums in Boston, Baltimore, Nantucket, and Hawaii. His wife
is an artist, while he is a biologist who specializes in skeletal
anatomy. Since the mid-1960s, he says, he's probably ``done 200 to
300 skeletons, from an 8-inch fish to a horse and a cow and now a
blue whale.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his competition in the field of whale skeleton
assemblers, Konnerth smiles and says, ``I've heard about a guy in
Florida. There aren't many of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple came from Dallas to work in New Bedford, but both
shrug when asked where they are now from. They are not really from
anywhere anymore, they say, having moved often in recent years to
work on skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of us are of the philosophy that if we can move, we'll
work,'' says Jean Konnerth. ``We're gypsies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
