<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLIDAY-RULES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME HOLIDAY GIFTS THAT MAY BE LESS TAXING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The crazed holidays are here, but it's not too late to get your
money house in order. Here are 10 tips on year-end finances for
consumers and beginning investors:
</P>
<P>
   1. School yourself: Instead of stuffing your face, try feeding
your mind. Put down the egg nog and pick up Worth, Money or
SmartMoney _ three financial magazines with jazzy writing and
strong reporting. Watch ``Wall Street Week'' or CNBC market goddess
Maria Bartiromo.
</P>
<P>
   2. Give the gift of stocks: Not exactly frankincense and myrrh,
but precious nonetheless. Play Santa Claus on Wall Street by giving
friends and family some shares in blue-chip companies.
</P>
<P>
   Children and adults might enjoy getting stocks of their favorite
companies, such as Walt Disney, McDonald's or Microsoft. Instead of
throwing money at department stores, give retail stocks as gifts.
Retail shares could be good buys now, since they tend to dip in the
fourth quarter, then rise in January after positive retail sales
are announced.
</P>
<P>
   3. Trash those credit cards: Dump that plastic, which makes it
way too easy to buy until you die. One or two credit cards at most
are fine for emergencies and important purchases. Pay for
everything in cash, even though it's painful to watch that thick
wad of fresh bills vanish from your hands.
</P>
<P>
   Or practice safe shopping by using credit card condoms _ plastic
baggies to wrap your cards in. You'll think twice before going all
the way and buying.
</P>
<P>
   4. Help your favorite charity: Build up good karma and send a
check to a church, hospital or other nonprofit cause.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity's Charitable Gift Fund and Vanguard's Endowment Trust
are unique investment vehicles for the holidays. You can write off
a gift to the funds, watch the money grow for a few years, then
give the money to a charity of your choice.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can give a family member or friend shares of a stock
you've owned for more than one year. The share value is deductible,
and you dodge capital gains taxes on the stock sale.
</P>
<P>
   5. Eyeball your taxes: What spreads good cheer more than the tax
code of the Internal Revenue Service? Sorry, but this topic is
vital if you want to thrive financially.
</P>
<P>
   If you hate numbers, your tax expert can estimate your 1998
income, deductions, credits and exemptions. The goal: to shrink
what you owe the IRS. Tax pros do this in three ways: By deferring
your taxes to another year; by lessening the tax bite on your
investments; or by shifting your income to family members in lower
tax brackets.
</P>
<P>
   6. Bless your children and grandkids with financial security:
There's a wealth of investment and legal vehicles for passing on
money to loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   You can put a tax-free annual gift of cash and stocks up to
$10,000 into a custodial account under the Uniform Gifts to Minors
Act.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents start education funds for their young ones. Fred
Bellero, assistant vice president for investments at Piper Jaffray
Inc., a securities firm in Minneapolis, recommends a college fund
using conservative zero-coupon Treasury bonds. Investors buy the
bonds at a deep discount _ about 50 cents on the dollar right now _
and cash out at maturity.
</P>
<P>
   Also look at ``529 plans,'' the new state-run programs that let
parents invest tax-deferred money in their child's education.
</P>
<P>
   7. Polish your portfolio: Even though the holidays get frantic,
it's wise to review your financial portfolio for year-end tax and
investment strategies, said Annette Evans, vice president and
branch manager for Fidelity Investments in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Other basic advice from Evans: Invest the maximum amount in your
employer's tax-deferred 401(k) or 403(b) retirement plans. And if
you're older than 70 1/2, make sure you meet your tax deadline for
minimum required distributions from your retirement funds.
</P>
<P>
   8. Look into flexible spending for child care or elderly care:
It's a gift from employers to wage slaves _ a helpful, pro-family
benefit called a ``flexible spending account,'' or FSA.
</P>
<P>
   According to Leonard W. Williams, a CPA in Sunnyvale, Calif., if
you're single or married and filing jointly, you can trim your
taxable income by moving up to $5,000 in pretax earnings from your
paycheck into an FSA. The cap is $2,500 if you are married and
filing separately.
</P>
<P>
   Then you can use that money for dependent-care expenses, such as
day care for your baby, or payments to a nursing aide watching your
elderly parent. You also can claim a federal tax credit for up to
$480 for care of one dependent, or up to $960 for two dependents if
you're married and filing jointly.
</P>
<P>
   The only catch of an FSA: If you don't tap all of the money by
the end of the year, the IRS says you must forfeit it to your
employer.
</P>
<P>
   9. To Roth or not to Roth? In general, singles qualify for the
full $2,000 a year contribution if they earn less than $95,000,
while married couples must make less than $150,000 combined.
</P>
<P>
   What sets a Roth IRA apart from a traditional IRA is that after
retirement, you withdraw your money tax-free. However, you must pay
taxes upfront.
</P>
<P>
   As a one-time carrot for consumers, Congress is allowing people
to spread out over four years the tax bite on converting their
traditional IRAs to Roth IRAs _ but it must be done this year.
</P>
<P>
   Beware, though, rules on the Roth IRA are confusing even tax
professionals. Check with your accountant or financial adviser.
</P>
<P>
   10. Buy absolutely nothing: Be bold, get radical. Don't blow a
cent on holiday shopping. Instead, pour that cash into a safe
mutual fund, and watch those dollars grow in the new millennium. It
beats a fruitcake or a Furby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
