<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKERS TURN TO UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as Massachusetts basks in economic prosperity, an
increasing number of workers have elected to organize to improve
their own economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
   During the past year, the national AFL-CIO reports, more than
175,000 workers across the nation joined AFL-CIO affiliated unions.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, between Nov. 9 and Dec. 11 a number of
elections took place to determine whether more than 1,000 workers
would become members of various unions. Most of the elections were
held under the auspices of the National Labor Relations Board.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, workers at the Westin Hotel in Boston voted, by a
margin of 294 to 190, to become members of Firemen &AMP; Oilers Local
3, a Service Employees International Union-affiliated union.
Workers at the hotel requested the union's help in their quest for
better wages and improved working conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Union activists consider the Westin Hotel workers' decision to
join the union, which hotel management fought staunchly, the most
significant union victory of the past two months. It is notable
because it was the first hotel in Boston to go wall-to-wall union
in at least a decade. ACORN, a community-based activist
organization, also did volunteer work to help the successful
organizing drive.
</P>
<P>
   Early last month, some 250 workers at Somerville Hospital voted
to join the Laborers Union. During the last week of November, 261
workers at NutraMax Inc. _ the largest cough drop maker in the
United States _ voted to join United Food and Commercial Workers
Local 328.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 3, some 234 service and maintenance workers at Whidden
Hospital in Everett voted to join SEIU Local 285. About a dozen
workers representing two smaller technical units voted to remain
nonunion.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, 35 workers at Bay State Gas in Springfield
voted to join United Steel Workers of America. At Ace Glass in West
Roxbury, about a dozen workers recently filed with the NLRB a
request to hold a union representation election that, if
successful, will bring them into District Council 35 of the
Painters and Allied Trades Union. Also that week, 56 employees at
the Hanover Public Schools voted to join AFSCME Council Number 93
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at King Painting Inc. of North Andover were scheduled to
vote on Nov. 17 to determine whether they would join District
Council 35. But the vote was delayed pending an NLRB investiation
of unfair labor practice charges. The vote also awaits the outcome
of a scheduled Jan. 26 hearing in Lawrence District Court on
alleged assault and battery charges against the company's owner.
</P>
<P>
   All of the elections, however, did not result in workers
organizing. In a close vote last Thursday, workers at Trendlines
Distribution Center in Revere voted 93 to 87 not to join Union of
Needle, Industrial and Textile Employees. Largely immigrant and
non-English speaking, workers there requested UNITE's help to
organize them, noting that many of the employees are barely above
minimum wage, although working at Trendlines for more than 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason an increasing number of workers have elected to
join unions during these good economic times may be that national
unions are communicating their message: Whether times are good or
bad, it is better to have a union as a source of strength.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these workers are also aware that during the good times
there has been a lot of downsizing and reengineering of companies,
resulting in many of them losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Also, most economic booms _ including the one currently in the
Bay State _ leave behind many lower-paid workers unable to
participate in, or benefit from, the prosperity. Perhaps the Bay
State workers who decided to become members of organized labor in
the past two months see unions as a vehicle that will help them to
at least catch the tail of the boom.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1358EST &QL; 
