<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIGNS OF THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPNTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travel across America and you'll see beauty, grandeur . . . and
silly signs.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Eyrich can testify to that. As editor and publisher and
writer of the offbeat quarterly publication, Two-Lane Roads, Eyrich
has driven his motor home more than 125,000 miles in six years.
And, oh, the signs he's seen. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   --``Jody's Used Tires, Guaranteed, One Mile.'' (North Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   --``May Pop Used Tires.'' (Mississippi.)
</P>
<P>
   --``D &AMP; H Barbecue, Next to Hospital.'' (South Carolina.)
</P>
<P>
   --``Our bait is guaranteed to catch fish, or die trying.''
(Florida.)
</P>
<P>
   --``Fishing Bridge _ Closed to Fishing.'' (Wyoming.)
</P>
<P>
   And then there was the Florida sign that said ``No Sleeping on
Pavement.'' ``Do we really need to tell people this?'' Eyrich
wondered. Nonetheless, he liked that last sign so much that he used
it as part of the title of his new book: ``No Sleeping on Pavement:
Silly Signs and Offbeat Stuff from America's Two-Lane Roads.''
Along with dozens of signs, many of them displayed in photographs,
there are stories about fabulous characters such as ``Five Dollar''
Frank Thomas of Fayetteville, W. Va., who offers scenic flights
over the New River Gorge for just $5. And there is information on
where to find such oddities as America's smallest working Post
Office building (Ochopee, Fla.) and the world's largest catsup
bottle (Colinsville, Ill.).
</P>
<P>
   For a copy of the 112-page book _ a paperback, with the pages
printed on something less than deluxe paper _ send $13.95 to
Two-Lane Roads, PO Box 23518, Fort Lauderdale, FL 33307-3518 or
call 888-TWO-LANE. (The price includes shipping and handling, but
add sales tax if shipped to a Florida address.) For information
about Eyrich's publication, visit www.two-lane.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Travel Trivia: Which country doesn't border the North Sea:
Norway, Finland, Denmark, or Great Britain? (Answer at end of
column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a name: Buffalo, N.Y., wasn't named after the animal. The
name is derived from the French ``beau fleuve,'' meaning
``beautiful river.'' Indians confused the words with ``buffalo,''
and the name stuck. (With thanks to frequent contributor Mike
Schuster of Foxborough and MailBits.com.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a phrase: We say ``playing telephone tag.'' Britons say
``playing Cox and Box.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
