<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KYLE MCLAREN MAKES STRIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While awaiting a new contract, Bruins defenseman Kyle
McLaren missed nine exhibition and 15 regular-season games before
signing a three-year deal Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, McLaren, the team's first-round selection
(ninth overall) in the 1995 draft, has played 11 games (two goals)
and is just now feeling sharp. In particular, he has felt better
the last three games _ closer to tip-top shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rate it after each game I play and see how I feel after and
before the games,'' said McLaren, who last season had career highs
in assists (20) and points (25) and tied his high in goals (5).
</P>
<P>
   He missed all the hard skating involved in training camp, as
well as the time spent adjusting to your teammates, new and old. It
adds up to a special blend.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that you miss training camp, your
chemistry is off and everything's off, your timing's off, and when
you step right back for a regular game, it's kind of a shock
because it's the next level,'' said McLaren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys in training camp are trying to make the team, trying to
get their energy and conditioning up for the regular season and
they're ready to go. It's coming along. My timing is a little off.
When to jump or not, I need to play more games. It's picking up,
getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough with no training camp, but I feel I'm a more
experienced player, a more patient player, and I can take things
other teams do. I'm still young (21) and I'm still learning, and it
can only go from here. I have a great teacher in Ray Bourque and
every day I learn something new from him and as long as that
continues, I won't be where I want to be for a couple of more
years.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an added benefit that the Bruins are 8-2-1 since McLaren's
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the team's winning, I think it's not a bad game,'' he said.
``I don't really set any personal goals right now after missing 15
games. It's kind of hard to. I just want to see the team win. If
I'm playing as well as I can, maybe I can help the team. There have
been ups and downs, like everybody else. I still have a lot of time
to pick it up and take it to another level. There are a lot of
games left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's because of me or whether the team's
picking it up. I'm just a small part of this team, all 20 players
are doing it at once.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly helps McLaren's cause that he's accustomed to coach
Pat Burns's defensive-style system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't changed their coaching style one bit,'' he said.
``They expect 120 percent from you each game and if you don't give
it, you're not going to play. They're always on you, they always
want you to be at your best. You can have one bad game off and
that's not good enough for them. You need to be at your best for 82
games. They demand a lot out of you, so you learn to give it to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 4 inches, 219 pounds, McLaren wants to be more
physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not playing physical, it's not my game style,'' McLaren
said. ``While I was watching the team while I was out, they were
getting banged around a little too much, and adding my size the
last couple of weeks, the team's been hitting more and getting more
confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
