<HEADER>
A0668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     12-15 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE KNOWS BETTER THAN TO MAKE A SNAPPLE JUDGMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SAYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's funny how the timing of these things works out.
</P>
<P>
   Monday Learning Co. said it would sell itself to number one
toymaker Mattel Inc., a deal engineered in part by Boston buyout
king Tom Lee and his partners. On the same day The Wall Street
Journal had a page one story on how another Lee company _ Snapple _
was finally bouncing back, four years after Lee sold it to Quaker
Oats Co. for an extraordinary $900 million profit in just 2 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   Lee didn't even get a mention in the Journal's report, but even
casual business-page readers know how the Snapple story came out.
In short, the 1994 sale of Snapple became a monument to how not to
make an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Quaker paid $1.7 billion for a quirky little beverage company
just as the trend for its New Age drinks was topping out and
competition was pouring in. Then Quaker proceeded to do almost
everything wrong by dumping management, fouling up the distribution
network, and even cutting the amount of juice in the product.
Quaker eventually pushed out its chief executive and sold Snapple
for $1.4 billion less than it paid.
</P>
<P>
   Monday the market seemed nonplussed about the Learning Co. deal,
and some institutional shareholders grumbled that Mattel had gotten
the company on the cheap. Shares of Learning Co., which a year ago
sold a 15 percent stake to Lee and two other buyout firms, was down
12 percent, dropping 3 5/16 to 25; Mattel's stock was down a
stunning 27 percent, off 8 1/8 to close at 22, its biggest one-day
drop in 16 years. The Mattel sell-off wiped out any premium for
Learning Co. shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Is Lee again bailing out at just the right time, leaving another
big company holding the bag?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Monday's swoon in the stock, this has been one sweet
deal for Lee, Bain Capital Inc., and a third buyout firm: The $123
million they put into the company in August 1997 will be worth
roughly $500 million in the Mattel buyout.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the Snapple deal, where Lee took the cash and went
home, Lee &AMP; Co. are sticking around. Lee and his partners, like
other Learning Co. investors, are getting Mattel stock for their
stake in the Cambridge software company and they are betting the
combined company has a strong upside in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Toys are a tough business these days. Toys ``R'' Us and other
retailers are reducing inventories dramatically and putting
pressure of toymakers' margins. The Mattel sell-off was prompted by
the company's warning that retailers had reduced sales by $350
million this year. The company also reduced its profit outlook.
</P>
<P>
   Together Lee and Bain hold three seats on the Learning Co. board
and they think each company offers much to the other. On one hand,
Mattel has some of the biggest names in toys _ Barbie, Hot Wheels,
to name just two _ that Learning Co. can turn into software
products. On the other hand, Learning Co. has its own big brand
names _ Carmen Sandiego and Reader Rabbit among them _ that can be
pushed through Mattel's distribution channel, domestically and
abroad. The Internet offers particular opportunities for the
combined companies and their brands, executives say.
</P>
<P>
   Dealmakers, of course, tend to like their children and their
deals. Quaker loved the syngeries with Snapple, and then they
started merging the distribution networks and killing the ad
campaign that had worked so well for Snapple. Scott Sperling, a Lee
partner and Learning Co. board member, says that won't happen here.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two great companies that have an even greater
potential together on a go-forward basis,'' says Sperling.
</P>
<P>
   (These guys are no fools: Knowing bad numbers were coming out of
Mattel, Learning Co. negotiated an unusually flexible arrangement
that will allow the exchange ratio for the deal to rise as much as
20 percent, depending on Mattel's stock performance.)
</P>
<P>
   The Learning Co. score is the product of a Lee-Bain
collaboration that worked before. Two years ago the buyout firms
combined for a profit of $400 million in less than a year when they
bought, then sold, Experian Information Solutions, a provider of
consumer credit reports. The same partners who put that deal
together _ Sperling and Anthony Dinovi from Lee and Mark Nunnelly
and Robert White from Bain _ also did the Learning Co. deal.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Lee &AMP; Co. knew when to take the dough and leave.
Now they are betting they have found a way to make their sweet
Learning Co. investment even sweeter. And that means staying put.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
