<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLINT FINDING HIS ZONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bruiser Flint knows that the word association game most people
play with UMass stilll ends with John Calipari.
</P>
<P>
   He also knows that despite winning 40 games in his first two
seasons as the Minutemen's head coach, he can still walk into the
living room of a recruit he is going after and be dismissed with a
wave and a smile as too young, not experienced enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see it,'' said Flint the other night, following a
solid 75-45 win by UMass over Boston College. ``I would go into
people's homes and you could tell, I didn't have a chance. John was
gone and UMass wasn't Kentucky or Duke or North Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Cal is three seasons gone now and Flint is finally
beginning to feel comfortable with what he's doing, as well as who
he is.
</P>
<P>
   That comfort zone has him smiling, even though the Minutemen are
2-4 after their first six games, with the chances of them going 2-5
after Tuesday's game at Villanova.
</P>
<P>
   That comfort zone lets him assert himself as he did on Saturday
night when he benched starting center Lari Ketner for breaking team
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Flint knows his players are watching what he does and how he
does things. He knows that he will be judged by a different
yardstick. Cal's recruits are fading from the scene and now Flint
must stand--or fall--on the strength of not only his coaching, but
his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure people judge you,'' he said with a smile. ``You expect
that. And if anything negative happens, you can bet they'll use it
against you in a heartbeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why the situation with Ketner is dangerous. Flint can
not be too tough or the word will go out that he can not handle his
players. He can not be too easy or the word will filter down that
UMass is a program that has lost control of its players, who can do
anything they want.
</P>
<P>
   Flint has tried different things with Ketner. He has been in his
face and he has backed off, offering words of advice and
encouragement. In the face of Ketner's latest misstep, Flint
offered some soft words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying too hard,'' said Flint.``He knows what people
expect.But in a lot of ways we're still dealing with someone who is
still maturing, we're still dealing with a kid in a lot of ways. He
knows there is pressure on him. He reads the papers.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Bruiser. He reads that his success of the first two
years was because Calipari left a program stocked with Top 20
talent. He reads that he has yet to prove himself as a coach--two
one and done NCAA tournament appearances have raised some eyebrows.
His recruits have yet to prove themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Starting 2-4 and perhaps 2-5 has not helped. Let's face it.
Calipari set a high standard of expectations at the Mullins Center.
His play anywhere, anytime theory of basketball worked to get UMass
into the national spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   When Calipairi left, lots of people thought UMass would fall
back down into the mid-major level type of program, where gaining
the Top 20 was more of a surprise than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what people were saying when Cal left,'' said Flint,
who received a two-year contract extension from UMass athletic
director Bob Marcum last week.``That the program would never be
what it was. It would fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Who knows? UMass may not ever get back to another Final Four. It
may be what it appears to be right now, a nice program that will
have winning records and make an occasional splash in March.
</P>
<P>
   But remember this. A decade ago, UConn was in a similiar
position. Jim Calhoun, who is still working to clear the last major
obstacle of never having been to a Final Four, has turned UConn
into a program that kids not only know about, but want to be a part
of as well.
</P>
<P>
   UMass can do the same thing. The Mullins Center is a first rate
campus facilitiy. The Atlantic 10 is a big-time league.
</P>
<P>
   And Bruiser Flint can be a successful big time coach.
</P>
<P>
   It will just take some time -- and patience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1403EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
