<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0673 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WHIPPLE-2TAKES-BO     12-15 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WHIPPLE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIPPLE EFFECT AT WORK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMHERST, Mass. _ Use your play time wisely, children. Work
diligently at your hobbies. Don't take moments like recess and
Saturday afternoons in the backyard for granted. Truth is you never
know what talents may come to the fore amid extracurricular
activity, or how far you might go in life just because you're the
best kid on your block when it comes to saying:
</P>
<P>
   (itals)``OK, you go long, out toward that tall tree. You go left
and then cut to the middle when you reach the fence. You stay back
to block, because I'm going to fake it to you. And you go up the
middle 10 yards then turn around and wave like you're open. Ready?
Break.''(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, there was this sixth grader from Phoenix who used to
call plays just like that while playing sandlot football. His name
was Whipple. Mark Whipple. The kid had a passion for wide-open,
score-a-minute football. Only he discovered early on that he
couldn't run very fast. So he began figuring out the best ways to
get the ball to kids who were quick enough to run down the field
and get open.
</P>
<P>
   The kid's schemes worked so well in sandlot games that when he
began playing organized football, coaches allowed him to call the
plays. True story. From Pop Warner all the way through his senior
year at Brown.
</P>
<P>
   From there he decided to make a career out of calling plays and
honed his talents through various assistant and head- coaching
jobs. With his passion for the pass intact, he developed the
strategy while working under former NFL coach Roman Gabriel when
the two were assistants with the Arizona Wranglers of the United
States Football League.
</P>
<P>
   He bolstered that attack with run schemes he learned from the
late George Allen, former Wranglers and Washington Redskins coach,
and working as an offensive coordinator under University of New
Hampshire coach Bill Bowes.
</P>
<P>
   It is that same Mark Whipple who occupies the coach's office at
the University of Massachusetts, the program he took over last
December following the school's worst 11-game finish this century
(2-9).
</P>
<P>
   Whipple is responsible for one of the most dramatic turnarounds
in college sports history, as he guided the beleagured Minutemen to
a school-record 11-3 mark and a trip to Saturday's Division 1-AA
national championship game against 14-0 Georgia Southern in
Chattanooga, Tenn. (2 p.m.).
</P>
<P>
   It marks the second time in seven seasons Whipple has guided a
program to a national championship game. In 1992, he led the
University of New Haven to a 12-1 mark and the Division 2 finals,
where it lost to Jacksonville State. That team led the NCAA in
scoring offense (50.2 points per game) and total offense (587.7
yards per game).
</P>
<P>
   Whipple's 1993 team, which finished 11-1 and advanced to the
Division 2 semifinal, was named Sports Illustrated's Best Offense
in College Football, averaging 52.5 points and 557.6 yards total
offense a game.
</P>
<P>
   He also resurrected the Brown program, guiding it from four
losing seasons to 7-3 marks in 1994 and 1997 and 5-5 marks in 1995
and 1996. Last season, his Brown team set an Ivy League record for
total offense (474.3 yards a game) and Brown season records for
passing yards (317.9 yards a game), first downs (233), and
single-game total offense (629 yards against Columbia).
</P>
<P>
   Already UMass has set 30 regular-season offensive records and 24
postseason offensive records. It entered last week's game as the
third-best offense in 1-AA. The Minutemen have scored at least 21
points each game and have gone over the 40-point mark five times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It all got started when Whipple played countless hours of
backyard, five-on-five, two-hand touch football when he was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back, I've always called my plays,'' said Whipple, who
used to go solely on instinct until one of his assistant coaches at
Camelback High School, Bill Saunders, showed him how to set up the
run with the pass, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just kind of made them up, told guys to go here, go there,
go that way, and then I just made up names for them. The same
things we do now.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach garnered a basic philosophy to the game, and he hasn't
deviated. ``What it comes down to is this: If we throw the ball
well, if the quarterback plays great, we will not lose,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he plays great, we will be ahead by 35 points and then we
will run the ball. We throw to get ahead. We run to win. I heard
that said somewhere, and I guess that's what we try to do.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has worked. One of the primary reasons UMass is four
quarters away from a national championship is that very few teams
can match its offense score for score. Few defenses have been able
to contain the Minutemen for consecutive drives, let alone
consecutive quarters. They pass and they pass until eventually
something opens up _ and then the kicker marches onto the field for
the extra point.
</P>
<P>
   ``His biggest achievement with UMass is that he has taken what
was predominantly a running team and gotten a run-oriented
offensive line quickly adjusted to pass protection,'' said
Villanova coach Andy Talley, who was an assistant at Brown when
Whipple played.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed the whole concept of what they were doing. Now
those run blockers knew they were going to be exposed to pass
rushers. It's hard to sell somebody on something like that. It's
hard to sell a running back like Marcel Shipp that he's not going
to get 41 carries a game, like (UNH running back) Jerry Azumah. But
he sold them on it early, and then they started having success
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Said fullback Matt Jordan, ``It's a complex offense in many
ways, but the comprehension of what's going on isn't if you know
what's going on in each play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot different from a lot of what he had in the past,
which was primarily a running game. This way it's a lot more pass
protections and releasing on routes. It's different, but the way he
teaches it, it's not difficult to understand at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all his attention to the pass, Whipple usually fields
teams with exceptional running backs and runs a comparable amount
of rushing plays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
