NYT-12-15-98 1404EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WHIPPLE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-15 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WHIPPLE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 AMHERST, Mass.: ... rushing plays.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still it is not surprising that after its gut-wrenching 33-30
season-opening loss to then No. 3 Delaware, the only team to beat
UMass was Connecticut, which claimed two victories over the
Minutemen.
</P>
<P>
   UConn had the only offense that could match UMass point for
point. And Whipple, who rolled up 1,054 yards total offense in both
games combined, still believes UMass would have won both had it not
turned the ball over in each.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no different from when you play in the street,'' said
Whipple, about his offense. ``You want to win, you get your best
players the ball. And man must know his limitations. I was never
that fast or that talented athletically. So, hey I was never going
to be able to run 50 yards, but I better get the ball to someone
who can to get it into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``And how do you get that guy matched up? You run the out-and-up
(pattern) and then you run the out-and-out, and then you run the
up. Or you see things on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would see a lot of Arizona State games on TV, when they were
averaging 40 points a game. They were throwing it and you would see
the wide-open offense and the athletes they had. And then you would
go outside and put their plays in when we were playing street
football.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The drawing board behind Whipple's desk contains a partially
erased offensive play. When the coach is asked to put a fresh one
on the board, for the purpose of explaining the basics of his
offense, he is initially reticent. It is understandable: UMass is
on the eve of its 1-AA semifinal game against Northwestern State.
</P>
<P>
   So Whipple is asked to diagram a play he doesn't care for, one
he's never likely to use again. ``There is no such play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, how about a play you absolutely will not run against
Northwestern State, or anyone else this season?
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' said Whipple, approaching the board. ``This play is
called Dig 39 Cross Shoot. This play worked very well against
Villanova.'' He draws 11 circles on the board, placing wide
receiver Jimmy Moore to the far right, receiver Adrian Zullo a few
inches away. Jordan is a few inches behind Zullo and Shipp is
behind quarterback Todd Bankhead. Tight end Kerry Taylor is to the
far left.
</P>
<P>
   The play is set in motion by several arrows: Moore's arrow is
drawn up the board. The arrows for Zullo and Jordan cross, with the
former going up and then to the right, and the latter curling to
the right. Shipp's arrow slants left then curls around left tackle.
Taylor's arrow is a long left hook.
</P>
<P>
   The play is designed to react to zone, man-to-man or blitz
packages without audibilizing. Any one of the skilled players can
receive the pass, depending on coverages. Bankhead, after taking a
five-step drop, must read the defense and judge the best matchup
within two seconds.
</P>
<P>
   And if one player runs the wrong route, if one offensive lineman
fails to block properly, the entire formation is thrown off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I tell them this play I have no idea what Bankhead is
going to do,'' said Whipple. ``I know what the coverage is, and I
know what he should do with certain coverages.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I'll say, `Why did you throw the ball to Taylor?' and he
should tell me, `He had outside leverage.' The free safety was
deep. So you throw the ball underneath. If he's up, you have a
one-on-one matchup, Zullo on the rover, as well as Taylor. So which
guy do you want? It's a matter of what he feels good with.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they're all covered? If the play is run well, and no one
manages to get open?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I got to go recruit,'' said Whipple. ``And that's what I
tell them. I'm just trying to take my best guy and put him on their
worst guy. But what we run is really not that much different from
what (Drew) Bledsoe is doing or other NFL guys are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is why Whipple is so confident in his offense. It is
adapted from some of the most successful offenses in pro football,
and learned from some of the best offensive minds.
</P>
<P>
   That includes Gabriel, who was an assistant on teams that ran an
offense similar to the popular West Coast attack. ``It was a
combination of what the Buffalo Bills did with Jim Kelly and Ted
Marchibroda and what (Tom) Landry did with the Cowboys,'' said
Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same thing you would see at Green Bay and San
Francisco, only 60 percent of the time we would run the ball using
a tight end, two outside receivers, and a running back out of the
backfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Whipple said working under Gabriel was like ``being in a lab
with a scientist.'' Gabriel, now a color commentator with the
Carolina Panthers, isn't surprised by Whipple's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would keep stats for me on and off the field,'' he said.
``He would do a lot of it on his own time, and he wasn't getting
paid a whole lot to get involved. We would be there at 2 in the
morning, breaking down film.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Whipple entered his senior season at Brown, he didn't call
his own plays. The highly touted quarterback was having a miserable
season when the coaching staff asked if he wanted to go back to
calling plays. He did, and Brown finished second in the Ivy that
season (1978).
</P>
<P>
   Talley said it wasn't so much his schemes as much as Whipple's
ability to get his teammates to believe his calls would work best
for the team. ``His greatest asset was that he was an outstanding
leader,'' said Talley.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the players, especially the offensive line, were very much
behind him. He would step into the huddle and whatever he called
the players would follow him.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, Whipple said getting UMass players to buy into
what he was selling hasn't been that difficult. They did even
before they saw the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing with this group, and I don't know why, is
that they haven't been satisfied,'' he said. ``That was my biggest
fear when I walked into the locker room after we lost to Delaware,
that they would be happy we played well against a team everyone
said we would lose by three touchdowns to. But everyone was sad and
heartbroken, so I said, `This is good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had gone 6-5, everyone would have said they had a
great year. The Lehigh game was one of the biggest in school
history; they could have just celebrated and packed it in after
that against another team we were supposed to lose to. But there's
been no complacency. As time goes on, I'll look back and enjoy it a
lot more than I do now. They are just a special group.''
</P>
</TEXT>
