<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATISTUTA ON EQUAL FOOTING WITH RONALDO, ZIDANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the buildup to the France '98 World Cup, the Brazilian
striker Ronaldo was receiving more publicity than any athlete in
the world, much of it generated by a US sports apparel company.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Brazil met France in the World Cup final, Ronaldo
was unfit to perform. The speculation was so strong that coach
Mario Zagallo had been pressured to place Ronaldo in the starting
lineup that Nike had to issue a denial of any involvement in the
decision. Nike had a strong financial stake in the Brazil-Ronaldo
combination, and had greatly influenced the agenda of the Selecao
in the months leading to the World Cup. At the very least, the
residue of that influence affected the decision to include Ronaldo
in the starting lineup for the disastrous final game.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Argentina's Gabriel Batistuta was gaining
comparatively little attention. National team coach Daniel
Passarella actually diminished Batistuta's role in the World Cup,
and Argentina was eliminated by Holland following the 5-foot-7-inch
Ariel Ortega's incredible head-butting of 6-7 Edwin Van Der Sar.
</P>
<P>
   While Ronaldo has been force-fed to the media and the public,
Batistuta has kept as low a profile as has been possible for the
leading scorer in Argentina's history. Batistuta has been in the
background while FIFA and Champions League galas have featured
Ronaldo and France's Zinedine Zidane.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the awarding of the Pallon d'Or, European footballer of
the year, is imminent, a campaign supporting Batistuta has started.
Zidane is the favorite, and not just because the voting is
conducted by France Football magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But Batistuta backer Reebok has chosen to see if his actions
will speak louder than advertising dollars. After Batistuta scored
his 13th goal in 13 games in Fiorentina's 1-0 win over Zidane's
Juventus Sunday, the campaign could be gaining momentum. Fiorentina
surprisingly retains a 4-point lead over Milan in Italy's Serie A.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Batistuta will play for a FIFA World All Star team
against Italy in an exhibition at Rome's Stadio Olimpico. The other
strikers will be Ronaldo and Milan's George Weah, both former
Pallon d'Or winners, and Real Madrid's Davor Suker, leading scorer
in the World Cup with Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   Batistuta will receive top billing, since his team is dominating
the standings and threatening the traditional power structure.
Ronaldo, who also converted the winner for Inter in a 1-0 victory
over Udinese, is still being coddled while recovering from France
'98. Batistuta is perceived as the dominant figure of Italian
soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if their roles have reversed, Batistuta told journalists:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a question I can't respond to. If you think so, you
have to have the courage to write it.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate recalls classic Argentina-Brazil rivalries. Who was
the better player, Maradona or Pele'? Which style is better,
Argentinian pragmatism or Brazilian jogo bonito? Tango or samba?
</P>
<P>
   But neither Batistuta nor Ronaldo are of transcendent status,
like Maradona, Pele', or Alfredo Di Stefano. They are simply
attacking, go-to-goal strikers who would score goals in bunches in
any era.
</P>
<P>
   Fiorentina has discovered a winning combination with Edmundo,
who was slated to replace Ronaldo in the France '98 final, and Lulu
Oliveira, a Brazilian-Belgian, alongside Batistuta.
</P>
<P>
   They are guided by Giovanni Trapattoni, who earlier this season
replaced Edmundo with a defender, incurring Edmundo's wrath and
leading to the squandering of a lead against AS Roma. In the
Juventus game, Edmundo played the entire match, indicating
Trapattoni's policies have changed to fit his players. Edmundo and
Oliveira provided the pyrotechnics, but Batistuta made the
difference, heading in Oliveira's cross early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Batistuta then celebrated with what has become his trademark
machine gun imitation, though it now seems to be evolving into a
rock-style guitar pose.
</P>
<P>
   Inter president Massimo Moratti offered nearly $30 million for
Batistuta, hoping to pair him with Ronaldo this season.
Fiorentina's Vittorio Cecchi Gori refused the deal, hoping to
accomplish a unique ``double'' _ the Italian Serie A championship
along with an Academy Award as producer of La Vita e' Bella (Life
is Beautiful).
</P>
<P>
   Moratti was stuck with another former Pallon d'Or winner,
Roberto Baggio. In the last two weeks, Baggio has come off the
bench to score twice against Real Madrid in the Champions League
and to assist Ronaldo's 89th-minute winner against Udinese.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV debate
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major League Soccer commissioner Doug Logan apparently offended
executives at ESPN-TV with his remarks following D.C. United's
victory in the InterAmericana Cup competition.
</P>
<P>
   Logan accused ESPN and other mainstream English-language media
of ignoring the accomplishment of D.C. United, which overcame Vasco
da Gama of Brazil, 2-0. He also raised questions about hidden
agendas, hinting at conspiracies.
</P>
<P>
   At least, Logan opened a channel for discussion.
</P>
<P>
   He contended that United's win was a first-rate upset, which it
was. United is in its third year of operation, Vasco da Gama in its
100th year and ranked second in the world. Problems arise when the
nature of the competition has to be explained. The InterAmericana
Cup has little currency in the world, though this result could go
far in promoting it.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN responded to Logan's charges by saying that MLS and other
soccer events are low on their ratings scale. And though ESPN and
ABC are contracted to MLS, the InterAmericana Cup rights were held
by Fox Sports Network.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Logan has the execs' attention, he should bolster his
contentions with some ratings of his own, some concrete figures
derived from FIFA and/or the Soccer Industry Council of America.
</P>
<P>
   As for conspiracies _ yes, other sports leagues have conspired
to restrain the business of soccer. NASL v. NFL in Federal District
Court in New York is the case that allowed cross ownership by
groups such as Anschutz, Hunt, and Kraft in the MLS.
</P>
<P>
   Sports leagues in the US operate as cartels within very strict
limits, and most mainstream coverage also operates within those
limits. Whatever Sports Center reports simply reflects a business
policy as a marionette responds to a puppeteer.
</P>
<P>
   There are some incredible soccer events going on world-wide.
Many of them are actually available on US television, though the
Corinthians-Cruzeiro final in Brazil sadly is not. Before the USA
'94 World Cup and the establishment of the MLS, soccer coverage was
even more uneven and the forum for discussion even more limited
than now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones honored
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midfielder Cobi Jones was honored Monday as Honda player of the
year, presented annually to the top performer on the US men's
national soccer team. He received 67 first-place votes and 271
points from a panel of more than 200 print and broadcast soccer
reporters. Goalkeeper Kasey Keller was second with 238 points and
48 first-place votes, and defender Eddie Pope, the 1997 winner, was
third with 145 points and 21 first-place votes.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 28, played in 15 of the national team's 16 matches,
starting 14. He did not have a goal or an assist as the US finished
6-6-4, including an 0-3 mark in the World Cup, finishing last in
the 32-team field. His 19 goals and 51 points for the LA Galaxy
were second in MLS.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Belated title
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Hermosillo gained his championship, though not with the
Los Angeles Galaxy. Hermosillo played for Necaxa in its 2-0 victory
over Guadalajara for the Mexican Torneo de Invierno title Sunday.
Necaxa, named for a hydroelectric power plant, has been ``the team
of the '90s'' in Mexico, thanks to the play of Ecuadoran midfielder
Alex Aguinaga and Argentinian forward Sergio (El Raton) Zarate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Celtic misfiring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics might not be playing in Boston, but Celtic FC is
struggling in Glasgow. It had to rally to tie Dundee United, 1-1,
on Henrik Larsson's late goal and fell 7 points behind Rangers. Dr.
Joszef Venglos, the Slovakian who will guide the FIFA All Stars in
Rome Wednesday, is apparently struggling in his first year as
Celtic's coach. The Scottish league season could be decided as
early as Jan. 2, when Rangers and Celtic meet at Ibrox Park.
</P>
</TEXT>
