<HEADLINE>
LUNG CANCER DEATHS AMONG WOMEN RISE DRAMATICALLY IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Lung cancer is killing women in New York at a
rate 40 percent higher than just 20 years ago, according to new
data from the state Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1976 and 1995, the number of women in New York who died
from lung cancer jumped from 19.8 per 100,000 to 32.4, while the
disease's rate of death among men, though still roughly twice that
for women, dropped slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the biggest and most meaningful cancer trend
that there is over the past 20 years,'' Mark S. Baptiste, the
Health Department's leading epidemiologist, said in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
   And the causes behind it are clear: the decades-old boom in the
ranks of women smokers. That trend began in earnest shortly after
World War II, Baptiste said, when legions of women took over jobs
vacated by men _ and also took up what had been a decidedly male
pastime: cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   One of those women was Deborah Cowser, a state worker who lives
in Nassau. Though she now regrets ever getting hooked on tobacco,
Cowser clearly remembers the day in 1964 when she and her best
friend made up their minds to become smokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a conscious decision on my part. I remember my father
was against it, but my mom said, `As long as she can afford it,'''
Cowser, now 50, recalled. ``When I started, everyone around us
smoked.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, with her parents' consent, she plopped down on her bed
with her best friend, Patti, and the two 16-year-olds giddily
peeled open their first pack of Tarrytons.
</P>
<P>
   Cowser still remembers that first, not-so-glorious lungful of
smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``We choked. But that didn't stop us,'' she said. ``It made us
feel big.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even as many men were quitting, Cowser and millions of
other young women like her kept on puffing, unknowingly
contributing, health experts and anti-smoking advocates say, to
what decades later is a full-fledged scourge of deadly lung cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco is killing more women through cancer,'' Baptiste said.
``It's clearly the smoking epidemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1955, the number of American men who smoke has steadily
decreased from 52.6 percent to almost half that. But women smokers
defied that steady decline, and their numbers swelled until 1965.
That year, one in three women smoked regularly, according to
federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women started smoking en masse as a group a lot later in time
than men did, and we're seeing that reflected now in their
increasing (cancer) incidence,'' Baptiste said. For some people,
smoking leads to lung cancer in a matter of years. For others, the
disease may not appear for decades, if ever.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking in the '60s, smoking rates among women have
declined to about 23 percent, compared to 28 percent of men.
</P>
<P>
   Lung cancer is still the greatest cancer killer of both sexes.
It is one of four types of the disease claiming more lives of women
statewide now compared to 20 years ago, an analysis of the Health
Department data shows. The other growing cancer mortality rates,
though dwarfed by lung cancer, stem from liver and bile duct
cancer, non-Hodgkins lymphoma and multiple myeloma.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in the death rate for each cancer has a working theory
attached to it, Baptiste said.
</P>
<P>
   Increased statewide deaths of women from liver cancer, for
instance, are probably due to the growing number of immigrants from
Asia, where hepatitis and liver ailments are more common, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates for death from non-Hodgkins lymphoma, which tends
to attack people with weak immune systems, are linked to the
increase in HIV, the immunity-destroying virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple myeloma, though, is more of a mystery to scientists.
Studies have linked the cancer, which also arises because of weak
immune systems, to exposure to certain chemical and occupational
hazards, but its causes remain largely uncertain, Baptiste said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A new multiyear effort to increase epidemiologists' power to map
cancer rates and identify its causes took shape this year.
</P>
<P>
   Led by the state Health Department, the Cancer Surveillance
Improvement Initiative held its first meeting of epidemiologists,
prevention advocates, environmentalists, doctors and business
executives two weeks ago in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   One of the project's first goals is to publish cancer data
current through 1996, which cancer-patient advocates and
environmentalists are eager to see.
</P>
<P>
   The new cancer data were published in ``Cancer Incidence and
Mortality in New York State,'' a three-volume report released by
the Health Department last month. The report, based on the state's
58-year-old cancer registry, offers the most comprehensive
county-by-county data on cancer incidents and mortality rates for
21 types of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Among other notable trends in the report was that for the same
20-year period, the rate of all new cancer cases statewide rose by
15 percent for men and 12 percent for women but remained below the
national averages for both sexes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
