<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0695 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-REVIEW-BLUE-H     12-15 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-BLUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BLUE ROOM' ABOUT SEX, NOT SEXINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT HURWITT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The sizzle in ``The Blue Room'' isn't all onstage.
Yes, David Hare's new adaptation of Arthur Schnitzler's
turn-of-the-century play ``Reigen'' (more commonly called ``La
Ronde'') is, like the original, all about sex.
</P>
<P>
   And yes, the London import that opened Sunday at the Cort
Theatre features two, mostly scantily clad, briefly naked, actors
engaged in 10 acts of seduction over the course of 95 minutes
(without intermission).
</P>
<P>
   But most of the buzz, in the New York and national press at
least _ as it was in London, where scalpers were reportedly reaping
$1,600 per ticket during its Donmar Warehouse run _ has centered on
the performance of film star Nicole Kidman in her major theatrical
debut. And on the amount of nudity, especially Kidman's, it would
contain, though one would think New Yorkers and Londoners would be
inured to star turns and stage nudity by now.
</P>
<P>
   Still, most of the actual sizzle derives neither from Hare's
script nor the two eminently capable performances, but from a
rather rudimentary special effect.
</P>
<P>
   In Schnitzler's 1900 play _ banned for 20 years in Vienna
because of its sexual explicitness _ a hiatus in the text indicates
each sex act. In Hare and Donmar artistic director Sam Mendes'
version, the stage goes dark, the loud sound of electricity zapping
across a gap reverberates throughout the theater and a projected
title announces the length of this particular copulation (``3
minutes,'' ``45 seconds,'' ``32 minutes'').
</P>
<P>
   It's a clever device, the first few times anyway. But it isn't a
sizzle most people would describe as erotic. Nor is it meant to be.
</P>
<P>
   Schnitzler's use of sex in the original was meant to be as
satiric as shocking. His daisy-chain of infidelity _ one character
from each scene appears in the next with a new partner, that new
person with a new partner in the next, until the chain has run full
circle _ satirized class distinctions and sexual hypocrisy in
turn-of-the-century Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Hare's adaptation follows suit. The characters have been
modernized, as have the language and attitudes about sex. But the
basic structure remains the same, right down to the class, power
and age differences between the transitory lovers and the dynamics
of each interaction.
</P>
<P>
   The principal difference, as Hare explained in a recent New York
Times essay, is what he called a less cynical, ``maybe more
romantic view of sexual yearning.'' For all the betrayal and
disillusionment, as one character says, ``This way, at least we're
alive.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't add much depth. Hare has become almost a permanent
presence on Broadway of late with one star-bedecked adaptation
(``Ivanov'' with Kevin Kline) or new play (``Skylight'' with
Michael Gambon, ``The Judas Kiss'' with Liam Neeson, ``Amy's View''
with Judi Dench expected in the spring) after another. But ``The
Blue Room'' is Hare in a distinctively minor key.
</P>
<P>
   It's light and bright. It's an entertainingly cautionary look at
what Hare has called ``Every Ghastly Sexual Situation You've Ever
Been In.''
</P>
<P>
   It's inventively staged by Mendes, also represented on Broadway
by his caustic reinterpretation of ``Cabaret.'' And it's performed
with considerable versatility by Kidman and London stage star Iain
Glen (like Kidman, making his Broadway debut), each playing five
distinct and sharply delineated characters in the course of 10
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   As Irene, Kidman is a touchingly naive, vulnerable young
streetwalker falling for Glen's bitter, casually manipulative cab
driver, Fred. As Marie, in a clinging blue minidress, she's a
sharper, mischievous au pair, more of a match for Fred in their
quickie in a back room at a disco, though radically disappointed
and ill-used as she succumbs to the temptation of a fling with her
employers' law student son.
</P>
<P>
   Glen's snottily shy student more than meets his match, to his
great benefit, in Kidman's sophisticated, inquisitive, slightly
sardonic Emma, a politician's wife looking for something safe on
the side. Her sexual reconciliation scene with her husband, Glen's
self-important conservative Charles, is one of the play's more
edgily touching interludes. Charles' seduction of Kidman's ditzy,
drug-numbed teen-age model, Kelly, is among the play's funnier
moments.
</P>
<P>
   So, too, is Kelly's comical fling with Robert, a pompously
disheveled playwright who wields big words as erotic foreplay.
Robert's rural tryst with Kidman's take-charge, theatrically
mercurial actress leavens the comedy with a sophistication that
takes a philosophically poignant turn when she takes on Glen's
world-weary, alcoholic aristocrat, Malcolm. The poignancy carries
over to the final scene, when Malcolm wakes up after a bender with
the still dreamily vulnerable Irene.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes keeps the action flowing briskly on Mark Thompson's
scrupulously crisp set _ a sharply defined box of bright blue
walls, edged in neon strips. Increasingly detailed, high- and
low-fashion unit sets slide onstage to match Hare's escalation to
more sophisticated interactions, as Hugh Vanstone's moody lights,
Paddy Cunneen's pulsating, sax-infused score and Thompson's frumpy,
chic and revealing costumes help set the bemused, sexually aroused
tone.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, the characters who are aroused, not the audience
_ despite that now-infamous London Daily Telegraph review that
dubbed Kidman's performance ``pure theatrical Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   Sexuality is almost clinically portrayed in ``The Blue Room.''
As for the nudity, it's minimal, a bit comic and appropriate _ more
so than the gratuitous and more pronounced nude scene that opened
``Judas Kiss,'' and less explicit than other versions of ``La
Ronde.''
</P>
<P>
   Steamy, Hare's ``Blue Room'' is not. A lightly witty look at
affairs that leave us sadder and not necessarily wiser is what it
is, and one that feels as ephemeral as the flings it portrays.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Nicole Kidman and Iain Glen perform ``The Blue Room'' at the
Cort Theatre, 138 W. 48th St., New York, through March 7;
800-432-7250).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
