<HEADER>
A0723 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANTI-IMPEACH-BRAINS-I     12-15 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-IMPEACH-BRAINS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTELLECTUALS RAIL AGAINST IMPEACHMENT `COUP D'ETAT'  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 450-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If someone has a video of the rally held at the New
York University School of Law this Monday evening, they should give
a copy to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they denounced the Republican drive for his
impeachment and removal from office _ historians, writers, Nobel
prize winners and one Hollywood actor.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, nobody among the Republicans may pay heed. This was an
intellectuals-for-Clinton kind of deal _ all warmth for the
embattled President and angst for the Republic and its
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   But these were intellectuals of stature, except for the
Hollywood hard man Alec Baldwin. For the 750 souls who crammed in
to listen, it was a night of electrifying eloquence and high
indignation.
</P>
<P>
   The writer E.L. Doctorow, his voice quavering at the
microphones, had this message for those who would overthrow the
President and undo the 1996 presidential election. What they are
preparing to commit, he said, ``was the unseating of a
democratically elected president with all the legitimacy of a coup
d'etat.''
</P>
<P>
   The very soul of America was being threatened, Doctorow
insisted. ``If Mr. Clinton is impeached, or tried or forced to
resign, American puritanism, with its punitive lust and autocratic
and theocratic vision, will be reborn for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going through this constitutional crisis because this
President lied to the American people. I've been trying to think of
a president in my life who didn't lie to the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Evoking the handling of illegal arm sales to Iran to fund
right-wing contras in Nicaragua by Presidents Reagan and Bush, and
the distortions from Lyndon Johnson during the Vietnam War,
Doctorow offered this: ``Perhaps the problem with President
Clinton's lie is that it lacked grandeur.''
</P>
<P>
   Likening the impeachment to a coup d'etat was a common theme of
the night, Jerry Nadler, a Democrat representative who belongs to
the House Judiciary, said he saw one silver lining in the prospect
of a trial of the President in the Senate next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a trial starts in the Senate we may be able to find out who
started this coup d'etat and who paid for it,'' he thundered to
mighty applause.
</P>
<P>
   For Nobel Prize winner Eli Wiesel it is the battering of Clinton
that must end. To Republicans, he said: ``We appeal to you to put
an end to the relentless humiliation that President Clinton has
been subjected to for three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public humiliation is a sin equal to bloodshed. For the sake
of our collective honor, we plead with you to do what so many of us
wish you had done earlier: censure the President for his
actions.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 450-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
