<HEADER>
A0727 &Cx1f; tab-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RWANDA-WHITEWASH-INDE     12-15 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-WHITEWASH-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY CLEARS FRANCE OF COMPLICITY IN RWANDAN GENOCIDE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 500-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
 By JOHN LICHFIELD  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A French parliamentary inquiry Tuesday cleared France of
any direct complicity in the Rwandan genocide of 1994 in which
800,000 people are believed to have been slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   A nine-month investigation by a parliamentary committee _ the
first of its kind in French history _ criticized the French
authorities for blindly supporting the racist Hutu-led government
and armed forces of Rwanda before the massacres began.
</P>
<P>
   But the report said that France was ``in no way involved,''
either actively or passively, in the mass murder of the minority
Tutsis and moderate Hutus which followed the assassination of
Rwanda's Hutu president in April 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first point that should be recalled is that those who
killed Rwandans were other Rwandans,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The French MP's say that the wider blame for the slaughter _ the
first officially recognized genocide since the Holocaust _ must
rest with the international community as a whole and especially
with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report says that scores of thousands of lives could have
been saved by the deployment of a United Nations peacekeeping force
but international action was blocked by Washington, which was still
numbed by the failure of its intervention in the conflict in
Somalia the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The result of the nine-month inquiry will be a disappointment,
but no great surprise, to those both inside and outside France who
have pushed for a full investigation of the French role in Rwanda
before and after the massacres began.
</P>
<P>
   A series of investigative articles in the newspaper Le Figaro
earlier this year claimed that the French authorities were aware _
or ought to have been aware _ that the Hutu-dominated government
and the French-trained Rwandan armed forces were preparing to
slaughter the Tutsi community.
</P>
<P>
   The articles also claimed that Paris continued to supply arms to
the Rwandan government in Kigali after the massacres began.
</P>
<P>
   It was also claimed that the then-French President Francois
Mitterrand operated a clandestine Rwandan policy from the Elysee
Palace in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Although France was publicly committed to peace negotiations
between the two Rwandan ethnic, or social, groups, President
Mitterrand was deeply suspicious of the Tutsi rebel leaders, who
were based in neighboring Uganda.
</P>
<P>
   Since they had lived mostly in exile, speaking English, under
Ugandan and American influence, he believed they posed a threat to
French interests and the survival of the French language in south
central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   The report of the parliamentary inquiry _ actually a study group
rather than a full-scale investigation _ accepted this argument and
condemned the ``institutional dysfunctions'' in the then French
government.
</P>
<P>
   It said France found itself ``trapped by its own (pro-Hutu,
anti-Tutsi) strategy.'' As a result, Paris allowed itself to be
manipulated by the extremists in power in Kigali, instead of
pressuring them to adopt a more pacific and democratic approach.
</P>
<P>
   But the report says that these criticisms do not support the
``unacceptable accusation'' that France was complicit in the
genocide. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article, it must be purchased from New
York Times Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York
at 1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0729 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RWANDA-WHITEWASH-INDE     12-15 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RWANDA-WHITEWASH-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY CLEARS FRANCE OF COMPLICITY IN RWANDAN GENOCIDE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 500-word ``separate buy'' article is from The Independent
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333, or fax her at 212-499-3382.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' general news and ``i'' international news files.)  
  
