<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-REPORTER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCH CONTINUES FOR MISSING REPORTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The search for a missing journalist in a mountainous region of
western Mexico continued Tuesday, with the Mexican government
promising helicopters to reinforce family members and others
looking for the man.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Mexican Attorney General's Office said
they would send helicopters to the remote Sierra Madre Occidental
range to search for Philip True, the Mexico City-based
correspondent for the San Antonio Express-News.
</P>
<P>
   True did not return to Mexico City on Dec. 9 as scheduled and
his wife said she last heard from him on Nov. 29, when he set off
on the solo hike.
</P>
<P>
   State police in the region already are searching for True, and a
party of more than a dozen Huichol Indians joined the search in the
deep canyons of the Sierra Madre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very grateful for the work the Mexican government and the
U.S. Embassy have done. They have worked for 72 hours,'' said Marta
True, wife of the 50-year-old journalist.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rivard, executive editor of the San Antonio newspaper,
met with representatives of the U.S. Embassy and the staff of
Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo late Monday at True's apartment
in Mexico City. After that meeting, the Mexican attorney general's
office agreed to assist in the search.
</P>
<P>
   True set out Nov. 29 on a hiking trip in the Sierra Madre
Occidental back country. He had hoped to photograph and write about
the Huichol Indians who are native to the states of Jalisco and
Nayarit.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Simon, of the Washington-based Committee to Protect
Journalists, said Monday he appealed to both Zedillo's office and
the State Department to enlist military help in finding the missing
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the expertise of the Mexican military in
search-and-rescue missions, their familiarity with this rugged
terrain, and the sophisticated equipment available to them, they
stand the best chance of locating True and bringing him to
safety,'' Simon wrote to Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   An experienced hiker of the Mexican back-country himself, Simon
said the region True planned to explore was not necessarily the
most dangerous in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any significant drug trafficking there
and that is probably the biggest risk in hiking in rural Mexico,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most likely scenario is that he is either lost or
immobilized by a twisted ankle. He could be sitting in some
peasant's hut and he couldn't even explain to them what a telephone
is, since they don't speak Spanish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have to sit there until someone comes. That's what I am
hoping,'' Simon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
