<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-REVIEW-TOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZY NEW BROADWAY SHOWS ARE A DELIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT HURWITT  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Taken together, two of the more delightful new shows
on Broadway add up to something of a chronicle of the decline of
jazz as the dominant popular musical form from the big band era
through bebop.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Town,'' the invigoratingly nostalgic George C. Wolfe
revival of Leonard Bernstein's famed first musical, at the Gershwin
Theatre, swings with the infectious energy of jazz in the early
'40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man,'' Warren Leight's poignant drama at the Golden
Theatre, traces the private lives of increasingly marginalized jazz
players in the 1960s and '70s with the mournful notes of a
prolonged trumpet solo.
</P>
<P>
   Each play, in its own way, is an ode to a period fading into the
past, and each uses music to make its case. Though ``Side Man'' is
one of five non-musicals on Broadway today, Leight's memory play of
a musician's dysfunctional family reaches its epiphany in a long
passage in which four horn players simply listen to a trumpet solo.
In ``On the Town,'' the whole crazy saga of three sailors' 24-hour
shore leave in New York is defined by Bernstein's brilliant score.
</P>
<P>
   Classic or no, Wolfe's Joseph Papp Public Theater/New York
Shakespeare Festival revival of Bernstein's musical has been a
pretty tough sell from the beginning, even in an age when revivals
have been one of Broadway's dominant forms. Wolfe staged it at the
NYSF's outdoor theater in Central Park in the summer of 1997 to
fairly lukewarm reviews _ tepid enough to cause the Public's
potential commercial producing partners to take a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the negative reaction was based on the performances. But
much more focused on the new choreography by Eliot Feld. ``On the
Town,'' after all, had not only been Bernstein's Broadway debut but
also Jerome Robbins' _ the concept for the show spun off from
Bernstein and Robbins' ballet ``Fancy Free'' _ as well as that of
book and lyrics writers Betty Comden and Adolph Green.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe and the Public decided to make the move to Broadway alone,
taking on Los Angeles choreographer Keith Young and replacing and
retaining a few key performers. The result opened at the Gershwin
in late November to still mixed but generally more positive
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   It deserves it. Wolfe's production could stand some tightening,
better executed slapstick and other improvements. It's not quite
the knockout it could be. But it's a genuine delight for most of
its 2 1/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Side Man'' hasn't suffered mixed reviews. It's received raves
from its Off Broadway Weissberger Theater Group production last
spring to its summer run at the Roundabout Theatre, staged by
Michael Mayer, to that production's commercial transfer to the
Golden in October, co-produced by the Weissberger (the show
originated at New York Stage &AMP; Film Company two years ago). But its
position is precarious nonetheless. New American plays on Broadway
are rarer than gigs for jazz trumpeters.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is ``Side Man'' an explosive drama or flashy star vehicle,
though it does feature Christian Slater as the memory play's
narrator, trying to come to terms with his childhood as the son of
a distant, disconnected trumpet player and an explosive, half-mad,
alcoholic mother. But Slater's role isn't the lead in ``Side Man.''
No role is. Part of the quiet beauty of Warren Leight's
semi-autobiographical reverie on jazz is the degree to which its
structure mirrors its subject.
</P>
<P>
   The play is the dramatic equivalent of an extended jazz ballad,
its narrative delivered in almost free-form, chronologically
fractured riffs and solos for each of the principals. Slater's
quietly troubled, eloquently unassuming Clifford virtually
disappears for long stretches of the two-hour play as his parents'
lives and their friends' stories take over.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Wood, who originated the role, plays Clifford's
ever-inattentive father as a slate so blank that you're drawn ever
deeper into trying to fathom what makes him tick. Wendy Makkena, of
the Roundabout cast (leaving Jan. 8, to be replaced by the original
mother, Edie Falco), is astonishing in the play's most demanding
role, riding a roller coaster of giddy, wary, disillusioned,
maddened and vituperative emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lyle Taylor, eager Michael Mastro and strung-out Kevin
Geer, and Angelica Torn as the oft-married, supportive Patsy,
contribute sharply defined performances.
</P>
<P>
   Reveries, clashing dissonances and up-tempo riffs flow smoothly
in Mayer's sensitive staging, illuminated by brilliant snatches of
jazz classics _ Ella Fitzgerald, Louis Armstrong, Miles Davis, with
Benny Golson's ``I Remember Clifford'' (performed by Lee Morgan) as
a recurrent theme. In the end, it's Clifford Brown who holds the
key to the enigma of the absent father and the hidden passion that
keeps him and his cronies pursuing their art as the gigs become
fewer and more humiliating.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Wood, as he listens with exhilarating rapture to a tape
of Brown's tour de force solo on Dizzy Gillespie's ``A Night in
Tunisia,'' the ineffable lure of jazz becomes something palpable,
immediate and indispensable.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``Side Man'' plays the Golden Theatre, 252 W. 45th St., New
York; 800-432-7250. ``On the Town'' is at the Gershwin Theatre, 222
W. 51st St. 800-755-4000.)
</P>
</TEXT>
