<HEADLINE>
CAUTIOUSLY, TRAVELERS SHOP ON THE INTERNET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ADAM BRYANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Booking travel over the Internet has long been touted as a
cottage industry with huge potential, with projections that sales
will grow from $827 million last year to $8.9 billion by 2002. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But that can only happen if more consumers overcome concerns
about security while making credit card purchases. And those
concerns are significant: A recent survey by Phocuswright, a
research and consulting company specializing in online travel,
found that among 500 people who have traveled by air in the past
year and visited a Web site in the past month, 80 percent have
looked at Internet travel sites and 58 percent have checked fares.
But only 18 percent have used the Internet to book travel online. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of nonbuyers of online travel say they are
unlikely to change their ways soon. The main reason for their
reluctance? Credit card security. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To airlines and online travel companies, such worries are
unfounded. These companies say that credit card transactions over
the Internet are safer than handing a credit card to a waiter at a
restaurant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, perception is reality in such matters. ``Most
people in the industry think that credit card security is an old
issue,'' said Terrell Jones, chief information officer for the
Sabre Group, which operates Travelocity, a popular site
(www.travelocity. com). ``But in the minds of consumers, it is very
much an issue.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Airlines and travel reservation companies are scrambling to
address problems of perception. Their incentive to do so is clear:
Airlines can pocket commissions they would otherwise pay to travel
agents, and it is cheaper to have computers, instead of people,
make reservations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not limited to the travel industry. Last month the
Clinton administration announced a number of steps to promote
electronic commerce globally and provide adequate consumer
protection. Vice President Gore said that consumers made 27 million
purchases every day on the Internet, and that electronic commerce
was expected to grow to $300 billion annually in a few years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to buy, say, a sweater over the Internet. But
air travel is often an expensive purchase, adding to the
trepidation. Booking a ticket can also be complicated, and fares
are often nonrefundable. Many people would also rather deal with a
person, if only to get reassurance that the fare they are buying is
the lowest available at the time. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One recent development introduced by Travelocity, and quickly
adopted by other travel sites, is a guarantee that if a credit card
number is stolen, the airline or reservation company will pick up
the $50 deductible that consumers are usually required to pay
credit card companies for purchases made with their stolen cards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't paid a dime, and we don't expect that we'll have
to,'' Jones said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To bolster consumer confidence, some sites post the logo
BBBOnline, to signify that the company that administers the Web
site meets standards set by the Better Business Bureau. Many also
said they buy the latest encryption, or data-scrambling, software
as soon as it becomes available. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines said that to insure security of Internet
transactions, it verifies every credit card purchase to make sure
the card has not been reported stolen or lost. If customers buy
electronic tickets, the airline requires them to show photo
identification at the gate as well as a credit card to make sure
signatures match. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that credit card security is becoming less
bothersome. United Airlines, for example, found in a recent
customer survey that sensitivity to security issues had dropped
from the first to the third most important concern behind ``ease of
use'' and ``functionality.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other surveys also show rapid growth in use of Internet travel
sites. The Travel Industry Association said recently that among
Internet users 48 percent of travelers and 52 percent of frequent
travelers use their computers for travel plans or reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures represent a sharp jump from its 1997 survey, when
28 percent of travelers and 31 percent of frequent travelers used
the Internet. It also found that 92 percent of the people it
surveyed were either satisfied or extremely satisfied with their
use of the Internet for travel plans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some common uses of travel Web sites, even for people who do not
book online, include checking fares to reassure themselves that
prices quoted by a travel agent are indeed the lowest available.
And many Internet sites offer virtual tours of hotels or resorts. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
