<HEADLINE>
SOME ANSWERS TO QUESTIONS ON TRAVEL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I'm going to Hawaii, the Big Island, for my honeymoon this
winter. Are there tours of the volcanoes, especially on horseback?
_ Juliette D. Fisher, Riverside, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. The Big Island's biggest attraction is certainly Hawaii
Volcanoes National Park, which extends from the sea to the summit
of Mauna Loa, the world's most massive volcano. On the eastern
flank is the 4,000-foot Kilauea, the most active volcano in the
world; Crater Rim Drive runs 11 miles around Kilauea Caldera, the
park's fiery centerpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The road makes it easy to tour the park by car or bike, but
there are no bike rentals. Hilo Bike Hub, near the airport, rents
mountain bikes for $25 to $35 a day, $100 to $140 a week; (808)
961-4452, fax (808) 934-9097.
</P>
<P>
   The park also has many easy walks and day hikes, and gives
permits for overnight treks. It is open 24 hours a day all year;
the Kilauea Visitor Center is open 7:45 a.m. to 5 p.m. An admission
ticket, good for a week, is $10 a car or $5 for a biker or hiker.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Hawaii Volcanoes National Park, Post Office Box 52,
Hawaii National Park, Hawaii 96718; (808) 985-6000, fax (808)
967-8186 or www.nps.gov/havo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are many standard bus tours, but only one licensed
horseback tour, according to the park superintendent's office.
Hauoli Trails, run by Uilani and Nathan Domingo, takes no more than
five riders on daily outings, using Arabians, thoroughbreds and
quarterhorses. They last two and a half ($120) or four and a half
hours ($180), and are open to all levels of riders.
</P>
<P>
   Riding is mainly in the rain forest, but there are opportunities
for cantering and a hike through Thurston Lava Tube, a tunnel of
hardened lava, Mrs. Domingo said.
</P>
<P>
   Tour guides discuss the geology, history and culture of the
area. Tours leave daily at 9 a.m. from Volcano Village, just
outside the park. Hauoli Trails, Post Office Box 630, Volcano,
Hawaii 96785, (888) 985-8100, fax (808) 985-7263;
www.gtesupersite.com/volcanohorse.
</P>
<P>
   The horses don't get close to flowing lava, but at least one
hiking tour does. Arnott's Lodge and Hiking Adventures, 98 Apapane
Road, Hilo, Hawaii 06720, offers several tours, including an
eight-hour outing that visits Kilauea Caldera by van before an
evening hike to see lava entering the sea. This tour, on Sunday and
Thursday, costs $50 ($36 if you stay at the lodge).
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday and Friday, Arnott's leads a tour to Mauna Kea's
summit, 13,796 feet up, and the space observatory there. The trek,
which includes a quarter-mile hike to the summit, is $75; parkas
are provided.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott's offers a variety of accommodations, from tents to a
suite for five, for $9 to $105 a night. Call (808) 969-7097, fax
(808) 961-9638; www.arnottslodge.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a different view of the lava flow, Blue Hawaiian
Helicopters, (808) 961-5600, has daily 50- or 65-minute flights
from Hilo for $130 and $175 a person, and from Waikoloa, on the
west, for $290 for two hours.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about tours, contact the Hawaii Convention and
Visitors Bureau, 250 Keawe Street, Hilo, Hawaii 96720; (808)
961-5797, fax (808) 961-2126; www.gohawaii.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q. My brother and his family live in Minneapolis, and our
families are looking for a summer vacation spot halfway between us.
We both have children and we like hiking, biking, etc. We need
pools and amusement parks for the kids. Any ideas? _ Paulette
DeRito, Ridgefield, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Using driving directions from the Web site www.mapquest.com,
the halfway point of the 1,267-mile drive between your homes is
somewhere near Toledo, Ohio. That may not be a place that comes up
much in vacation planning, but a little to the east, toward
Sandusky, Ohio, is the Lake Erie Islands region, a center of
outdoor activity, especially fishing, and historical sites.
</P>
<P>
   Among the area's attractions is East Harbor State Park, on
Marblehead Peninsula. Its 1,152 acres offer a campground, boating,
fishing in the ``walleye capital of the world,'' seven miles of
hiking trails, a beach and picnicking. At the eastern end of the
peninsula is the oldest operating lighthouse on Lake Erie.
</P>
<P>
   In between is Lakeside, a Chautauqua-like village that offers
recreation, concerts and educational seminars in the summer. Four
miles into Lake Erie is Kelleys Island, which includes Glacial
Grooves _ ancient hieroglyphics carved in rock by the Erie Indians
_ and hiking, boating and a tram tour of the island.
</P>
<P>
   Another boat ride can take you to Put-in-Bay, a Victorian
village on South Bass Island, where most people travel by golf cart
or bicycle. Among the places to ride to are the Put-in-Bay Historic
Fish Hatchery, with free tours, and the Perry's Victory and
International Peace Memorial, a 352-foot Doric column with an
observation platform commemorating Commodore Perry's War of 1812
triumph at the Battle of Lake Erie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Back on the mainland, the kids can seek thrills at Cedar Point
Amusement Park and Resort, in Sandusky. This park has rides for all
ages, including 12 roller coasters, and next door is Soak City
Water Park. There are two hotels and a campground at the complex.
</P>
<P>
   To learn more, contact the Ottawa County Visitors Bureau, 109
Madison Street, Port Clinton, Ohio 43452; (800) 441-1271, fax (419)
734-9798, www.lake-erie.com.
</P>
<P>
   To equalize the driving even more, you could take a slightly
more northerly route _ to Flint, Mich., exactly 690 miles from each
of your towns, according to Mapquest.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen state recreational areas are within an hour's
drive of Flint, and Chris Groff, a spokesman for the state's Parks
and Recreation Division, said several offer excellent mountain
biking and hiking. These include Seven Lakes State Park in Monroe,
Brighton Recreation Area in Howell and the Ortonville Recreation
Area in Ortonville.
</P>
<P>
   Among attractions in or near Flint is Crossroads Village and
Huckleberry Railroad, a simulated 18th-century village with
blacksmithing demonstrations, old-time rides like a Ferris wheel
and a carousel, a paddlewheel riverboat and a narrow-gauge train.
Flint has a children's museum and the Museum of African-American
History-Flint.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the many attractions of the Detroit-Dearborn area are
about an hour away by car.
</P>
<P>
   Contact the Michigan Travel Bureau, Post Office Box 30226,
Lansing, Mich. 48909, (800) 543-2937, and www.michigan.org; or
Flint Area Convention and Visitors Bureau, 519 South Saginaw
Street, Flint, Mich. 48502; (810) 232-8900, fax (810) 232-1515, and
on the Web, flint.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
