<HEADLINE>
CAR USERS FACE INCREASING FEES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the densely printed ``cardmember agreement'' arrives with
your charge- and credit-card bills, read it if the type is not too
small, or at least save it to read when the light is better.
</P>
<P>
   These sheets contain a certain amount of news, which is to say,
bad news, for you as a consumer, if you are using your cards to pay
charges overseas or if you are carrying a balance on big-ticket
items like air tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Holders of the 68 million Citibank Mastercards and Citibank Visa
cards issued in the United States are learning that the fee for
converting such transactions as a dinner in Tuscany or a car-rental
in Paris will rise. Holders of these cards _ Citibank says it has
the largest total of any bank card in the country _ are getting
notices of changes from the issuing bank, Citibank South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   The fee added to the bill for foreign charges, previously 1
percent, is rising. For the moment, charges that appear on the bill
in December will be 2 percent, a Citibank spokeswoman said. But the
bank has left itself the option of raising this to 3 percent
without further notice.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the impact is not overwhelming. A bill of 826,500
lire for a hotel room, or $500 at a rate of 1,653 lire to the
dollar, which was subject to a $5 fee, would be increased by $10
now, possibly $15 at a later date. The fee is not broken out, so it
is not apparent in a casual look at the bill.
</P>
<P>
   But it is another small nibble by what Consumer Action, an
advocacy group, calls an aggressive strategy of increasing bank
yield on cards.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the dollar is steady against the currency of the
country where the charge was made, this fee increase does not alter
the basic counsel that charging hotels, meals, cars and merchandise
overseas is a better deal than converting dollars or traveler's
checks to a local currency and paying in cash.
</P>
<P>
   This principle is particularly worth remembering if you consider
converting dollars to local money at a currency-conversion counter,
where the rates are less favorable than at banks or post offices.
The conversion to dollars that the credit-card banks make before
billing you is at a more favorable rate than an individual gets; it
will be about the same as the rate banks give each other for bulk
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for charging an expense is more emphatic when there
is the possibility the value of the dollar may improve against the
local currency in the time between the eating of the meal and the
day the bank credits the restaurant's account.
</P>
<P>
   The use of electronic transmission, where the cashier swipes the
black strip of the card through a reader, is shrinking this time
lag, of course. When my card is swiped, I imagine I can hear my
Velcro wallet tearing open and money sliding out.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank is not calling attention to the new charges; Michael P.
Prince, executive director of the Goodspeed Opera House in East
Haddam, Conn., spotted the 3 percent note in the bank's ``Notice of
Changes in Terms to Your Citibank Card Agreement'' and mailed a
copy to The Times.
</P>
<P>
   Most other charge cards are apparently staying with a 1 percent
fee for conversion from foreign currencies. Consumer Action, a
nonprofit advocacy group in San Francisco, pointed out that the
Providian Bank, of San Francisco, had gone to 5 percent for
foreign-currency conversions on its cards, but that it knew of no
other bank adding that much.
</P>
<P>
   American Express is still at 1 percent, where it has been for at
least 10 years, according to Emily Porter, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several other modifications _ upward _ in the
cost of using charge cards. After an annual survey, Consumer Action
and another national nonprofit organization, the Consumer
Federation of America, reported jointly last month that the banking
industry was acting widely to increase credit card income.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although the report said that the average annual interest rate
in late 1998, 15.25 percent, was only slightly higher than in
recent years, banks are steadily pushing up other charges to get
more out of the credit cards they issue.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Mendler, a spokeswoman for Citibank, explained that up to
now, the Visa and Mastercard organizations have been levying a fee
for converting a charge to dollars that amounts to 1 percent of the
amount charged. The two card brands define it differently, but the
impact is the same. The yield from this fee has been retained by
Visa and Mastercard.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Mendler said, the bank wants to ``offset the higher
cost'' of doing such business, and has announced the fee increase.
</P>
<P>
   Other changes in Citibank card fees will affect those who carry
big balances, often for airline tickets or tours. Finance charges
on the unpaid balance are now to be calculated by a daily
compounding method, rather than on a monthly average. This raises
the cost to the consumer, Ms. Mendler said.
</P>
<P>
   The charge for cash advances _ on top of the finance charge for
an unpaid balance _ has been raised to 3 percent, from 2.5 percent,
of the outstanding amount, with a minimum of $5 a month, up from
$2. Credit-card cash advances obtained at ATMs in the United States
may also incur a one-time charge of up to $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the pileup of charges these fees could produce,
Ms. Mendler said that Citibank discouraged the use of cash advances
through a credit card except in emergencies. ``We still do not have
an annual fee,'' Ms. Mendler said, noting that some cards did,
particularly those with double brands offered by airlines. ``But we
have seen other fees rise.''
</P>
<P>
   When I opened a recent mailing from American Express, it noted
changes under the heading ``Charges Made in Foreign Currencies,''
but the change was not in the 1 percent conversion fee. Rather, it
involved the company's way of establishing an exchange rate for its
foreign-currency charges, Ms. Porter said.
</P>
<P>
   American Express has gone from using a particular interbank rate
for the day the charge is recorded to setting a ``competitive''
daily rate of its own, based on interbank rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes this will be better for card members than before,''
Ms. Porter said. ``Sometimes it will be better for the company.''
Card holders are being notified now, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The fee increases that Consumer Action found in its survey are
all levied on accounts that are not paid in full every month, on
time. Some of these may explain why some people sense that their
cards are costing more.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, grace periods for those who have not been carrying
an unpaid balance have been shortened by some banks from the
customary 25 days to 20, which means that interest will be charged
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Late-payment fees have also risen, some to $29, from $25. The
survey found that 39 banks surveyed in 1995 and 1998 had raised
their late fees considerably _ to an average of $21.82, from
$12.53.
</P>
<P>
   The Credit Card Survey, based on information gathered in August
and September, can be obtained by sending a self-addressed envelope
with 55 cents postage to Consumer Action-CC, 717 Market Street,
Suite 310, San Francisco, Calif. 94103. It is also available on the
Web at www.consumer-action.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
