<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-TRAVEL-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWSING THE WEB'S NEWSSTAND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By L.R. SHANNON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you visit a city, the local newspaper can give you a feel
for what the people there are talking about, shopping for, living
in. Weather forecasts can be vital on a vacation, theater and movie
listings can take you out of the rain, and the doings of the local
sports teams provide a conversational entry with strangers.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays you don't have to wait until you get to a city to buy
the newspaper. Many newspapers are on the World Wide Web in full or
abbreviated form. I sampled a bunch in or near places where
visitors are likely to go, to see how useful they were.
</P>
<P>
   Usefulness varied widely, of course, as did ease of navigating
the sites, but all were handy and up-to-the-minute guides even when
they were not primarily aimed at travelers. Newspaper Web sites
should be available on any of the search engines.
</P>
<P>
   The path in Yahoo is News and Media, Newspapers. In Excite, the
path is News, U.S. Newspapers. If you are persevering you can even
find the sites on Alta Vista, where the path is Media and
Entertainment, News and Magazines, News and Newspapers. Best of
all, perhaps, is newspaperlinks.com, which provides connections to
more than 1,700 newspapers in the United States and Canada. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic, at www.azcentral.com, cares about the
weather. There are forecasts for 27 cities, including such familiar
names as Phoenix, Tucson and Flagstaff, and such outre ones as
Bullhead City, Quartzsite and, yes, Tombstone. There is also a
calendar of events, a city guide, articles about the state and a
list of places to hike.
</P>
<P>
   The city guide section leads to the independent sites of 28
communities, with information and favorable views of
accom-modations, dining and recreation. A further click takes you
to Arizona Guide, the site of the Arizona office of tourism, with
topics ranging from the Grand Canyon to deserts.online &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Across the country in the Southeast, The Miami Herald,
www.herald.com, offers a large selection from the previous Sunday's
travel section. Not all the articles are local, but the day I
dropped in there was one about a Peruvian art exhibition at St.
Petersburg's Florida International Museum.
</P>
<P>
   A ``traveling cheaply'' section was divided into bargain fares,
off-season travel, special deals and ways to accu-mulate miles
without actually flying. But look in the Living/Arts section, not
travel, for places to eat, music to hear and movies to see. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Mercury News, www5. mercurycenter.com, is huge. A
lengthy index runs from A (the A's Strike Zone) to Y (the Yellow
Pages). The icon I thought would take me to the travel section
actually connected to an independent site, www. sfbaytraveler.com,
emphasizing Northern California but with destinations as
wide-ranging as Alaska and Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   I did eventually find articles from the previous travel section
(``Overnight flights are called red-eyes for a good reason''), and
a news library enables you to ``search the archives of the San Jose
Mercury News and more than two dozen Knight-Ridder and other
newspapers.'' The index is also the place to look for entertainment
news, under both Entertainment and Just Go.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't find where accommodations are hidden in this vast
space, if they are, but a search for the word ``hotels'' brought up
49 articles, from ``How not to run online reservations'' to ``Probe
of girl's fall may wrap up soon.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't find a section named Travel in The Rocky Mountain
News, which is at www.insidedenver.com, but under Recreation there
was a snow section with nearly 30 resorts listed. There were also
close to 30 headlines leading to such news stories as ``Gart-Vail
hookup eases buying passes'' and ``Skiers asked to stay within
bound-aries.'' The Going Out section has movies, dining, theater
and music. Under dining there were 15 recent restaurant reviews. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the lowdown for a visit to New York, connect to The New York
Times companion site, New York Today, www.nytoday.com, where
restaurants, bars, night-clubs and other such tourist-friendly
places are highlighted.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
