<HEADER>
A0814 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1216-     12-15 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-1216-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON LEAVES MIDEAST WITH NO PROMISE OF TROOP WITHDRAWAL,
PEACE PROCESS STRUGGLING HIS WAKE
 &HT;    With CLINTON-PASTOR-1216.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Mixing powerful symbols of historic sacrifice and
seasonal hope, President Clinton wrapped up a difficult visit to
this turbulent region on Tuesday, conceding that the heart of the
imperiled Mideast peace process is barely beating and faces added
strains in the weeks ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to gird that process for further stress, Clinton pulled
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat together for a 90-minute meeting at the border town
of Erez, south of the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing of substance could be resolved, however, and the two men
could agree only to activate a handful of committees to take up a
host of thorny security and law enforcement issues and, ostensibly
at least, to try to speed the flow of the economic and social
benefits of peace to some increasingly restive pockets of
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the clock ticking on a May 4 deadline set five years
ago for negotiating a comprehensive Israeli-Palestinian peace
agreement, Clinton was unable to persuade Netanyahu to proceed with
additional promised troop withdrawals from parts of the occupied
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to resolve a number of issues in order for the
redeployment to go forward,'' said Clinton. ''I hope we can keep
pretty much to the schedule that's here. But, obviously, that
remains to be worked out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Distrust between Netanyahu and Arafat remained so deep, however,
that little progress appeared likely without the direct involvement
of Clinton, who said he would send U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright back to the region early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll just keep at it,'' Clinton told reporters. ''We'll have
fits and starts . . . but we'll get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was to return to Washington -- and an impending
impeachment vote -- late Tuesday night, after an historic three-day
visit to Israel and Palestinian-controlled Gaza. Following a day of
sightseeing, the president and his family climbed aboard Air Force
One and headed home, due back at the White House just 34 hours
before the full House opens debate on four articles of impeachment
that could lead to his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides held Wednesday's schedule open for Clinton to
meet or talk by phone with any lawmakers seeking last-minute
answers or assurances. The Senate will decide Clinton's fate if the
House approves any of the impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the grave threat to his presidency, Clinton did not seem
particularly troubled as he spent the day Tuesday visiting the
supposed site of the birth of Christ, in the nearby
Palestinian-controlled city of Bethlehem, and Masada, a craggy
mountain plateau where Jews in revolt against Roman occupation
forces staged a bold, but ultimately tragic, last stand nearly
2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The time Clinton spent noting the origins of Christianity and
the long and often painful history of Judaism lent dramatic
symbolism to three days of tough diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The visit was agreed upon by both sides as part of the interim
peace accords Clinton brokered between Arafat and Netanyahu last
October at the Wye River Plantation retreat in rural Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the visit was Clinton's journey on Monday to
Palestinian-controlled Gaza and his address there to several
hundred members of the Palestinian National Council, who affirmed
the removal from the Palestinian charter of a host of decades-old
provisions calling for the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   What was meant to be a largely ceremonial step in cementing the
accords, however, turned into a rescue mission, with Clinton
applying the diplomatic equivalent of CPR to try to keep the peace
process alive.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to manage that, but White House officials made clear
that little progress is expected in the peace process until
Netanyahu's precarious political position is worked through, one
way or another.
</P>
<P>
   The embattled Israeli prime minister faces a critical test next
week, with Israel's parliament, the Knesset, expected to take up a
possible no-confidence vote as early as Monday. A loss could result
in elections in three months, a process that would again place on
hold the prospect of meaningful progress toward peace, particularly
on the issue of Israeli troop redeployments from occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
   That issue lies near the heart of a peace process based on the
transfer of certain Israeli-occupied territories to Palestinian
control.
</P>
<P>
   At Wye, Netanyahu agreed to transfer an additional 13 percent of
the occupied West Bank to Palestinian control. The transfer was to
take place in three phases. The first redeployment went forward
last month; the second was to be completed by this Friday, but
Netanyahu suspended that phase last week in the face of mounting
street demonstrations and attacks on Israelis by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to resolve a number of issues in order for the
redeployment to go forward,'' Clinton said. ''I hope we can keep
pretty much to the schedule that's here. But, obviously, that
remains to be worked out here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, though, patience is wearing thin.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of an Israeli-Palestinian agreement signed on
the White House lawn in 1993, both sides are supposed to complete a
comprehensive peace accord -- that would settle once and for all
the toughest issues between them, including the future of Jerusalem
and the question of a Palestinian state -- by May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has repeatedly warned that he would unilaterally declare
a Palestinian state in areas of Palestinian control, and perhaps
other territories now occupied by Israelis, if that deadline isn't
met. Netanyahu has responded by threatening to annex
Palestinian-controlled lands if Arafat tries to create a state on
his own.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, voiced hope that diplomacy can avert a
showdown, but he made clear that tough work lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ''The proof is always in what happens tomorrow, not what happens
today,'' Clinton said, ''but I think at least we've got a process
set up and we can go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
