   Cowen's own logic doesn't necessarily lead to his conclusion. If
the point is to have the widest possible range of cultural choice,
a variety of economic systems might be preferable. Feudalism in its
death throes produced great 19th century Russian literature as well
as blues music, which Cowen is very fond of. Communism shaped the
writing of Alexander Solzhenitsyn, Joseph Brodsky, and Milan
Kundera as well as the most interesting films of the 1980s. In
Eastern Europe, especially, political and economic freedom appear
to be failing to produce the equal of what emerged under Communism.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't an argument for oppression. But it is an answer to
Cowen's theory that capitalism automatically produces the greatest
art. In reality, art is unpredictable and may flourish under the
most unlikely conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But the larger way Cowen is mistaken is in his flawed
presumption that cultural vitality is synonymous with variety. If
you hold the position that the healthiest civilization is the
biggest supermarket of cultural products, then all you need is an
Amazon.com for consumer capitalism to triumph. But there are more
aspects to a nation's cultural life than this quantitative view
encompasses.
</P>
<P>
   Cowen's approach gives you no sense, for example, of whether and
how much art matters to most Americans. Though probably more a
cultural optimist than pessimist, I would argue that there is too
little overlap between what's great and what's popular. High
culture in the United States is a relatively successful niche
product. What we lack is a flourishing common or national culture.
Contemporary classical music goes unperformed, foreign films have
no audience, and hardly anyone reads contemporary poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, pap abounds. Even Cowen doesn't get around to
defending our true ``commercial culture''--television, video games
and Hollywood movies. In terms an economist might understand, the
supply side of our cultural life looks pretty good. It's demand
that ought to give one pause.
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Jacob Weisberg is the senior critic for Slate.)
 &UR; Copyright 1998 Slate &QL;  Visit Slate on the Web at:
http:www.slate.com &QL;  (Distributed by New York Times Special
Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
