<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-15 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'TIS THE SEASON FOR IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Is this really happening? It is. It's time to
wake up and enter the national nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I have better things to do _ eggnog to drink, Niners to
watch and the homeless to write about.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't even finished my Christmas shopping and suddenly
impeachment looms.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us have been telling ourselves, ``It's only a dream.''
Unfortunately, we're bit players in ``Nightmare on Pennsylvania
Avenue,'' and it won't end. It will only get worse.
</P>
<P>
   If the House votes for impeachment, here are some things we have
to look forward to:
</P>
<P>
   Monica and Linda will testify under oath before the Senate.
While these tabloid stars talk about oral sex and secretly
tape-recording friends, senators will be forced to perform the
unnatural act of being silent.
</P>
<P>
   That'll be the only redeeming part of the national nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   The distinguished senators will submit written questions about
blue dresses, cigars and the definition of ``sexual relations'' to
William Rehnquist, the chief justice of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   We can only pray that Rehnquist doesn't catch the flu and get
replaced by Clarence Thomas, keeping his whistle wet by drinking
from a can of Coke.
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC, CNN and all the other networks are designing their
impeachment logos and impeachment theme music right now. They've
already deployed their legal analysts and political pundits, and
now are hiring fashion critics for the Monica and Linda portions of
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The networks will have full national nightmare coverage 28 hours
a day, 9 days a week, 40 days a month until it's over.
</P>
<P>
   But it will never be over, even if the right wing achieves the
goal it's had for six years, which is to put the word ``impeached''
after President Clinton's name in the World Almanac.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton leaves office or not, the Republicans will try
to charge him with perjury in criminal court, take his pension away
and force him to sit in rags on a street corner with a cardboard
sign saying, ``Will apologize profusely for food.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, Clinton should stop apologizing and shut up.
Words have failed him, and he has failed plain English, even basic
words like ``sex'' and ``is.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Clinton should just focus on the work of the presidency,
like keeping the Dow Jones high and ignoring weapons violations by
Iraq. He should just let the Republican Party destroy itself.
</P>
<P>
   These are radicals, not conservatives. The more isolated the
Republicans get from public opinion the more extreme they get, much
like the Weathermen in the '60s, who ended up isolated in small
rooms wondering why the public never joined them in making bombs to
overthrow the government.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wingers in Congress are just as isolated from the public,
but have a slightly better chance of overthrowing Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Then what happens? In trying to destroy a president who cares
too much about his place in history, Republicans have forgotten
about their place in history. Come the 2000 election, they may be
history.
</P>
<P>
   The craziest thing to come from the Republican loony bin in the
last couple of days is the notion that Americans will forget about
the impeachment madness by the 2000 election, and Republicans won't
pay a political price.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Alan Simpson of Wyoming said, ``The attention span
of Americans is, `Which movie is coming out next month?' and
whether the quarterly report on their stock will change.''
</P>
<P>
   This is very cynical, and perhaps true about most events. But we
have a long attention span when it comes to presidents. We may not
remember much about them, but we remember how they left office.
</P>
<P>
   The last 35 years haven't been good to presidents. Kennedy was
assassinated. Johnson decided not to run for reelection after the
Tet offensive. Nixon was driven from office in shame for dirty
political tricks. Ford pardoned Nixon, hit some people with golf
balls, and disappeared, never having been elected president. After
a hostage fiasco in Iran, Carter left to become a good
ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan served out two terms successfully, defeating the Evil
Empire. Bush? Well, shifts in public opinion happen.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton resigns, as many Republicans want, Americans will
remember. They'll remember that a political party went crazy and
ran a president out of office for such threats to the constitution
as fooling around with an intern and lying about it.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have to explain it to children for generations to come _
that is, if impeachment doesn't become a standard way of getting
rid of presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I don't like Bill Clinton very much, but I don't want him
thrown out of office. He may be slippery, but his enemies are toxic
slime.
</P>
<P>
   These are people who've had ``Impeach Clinton'' bumper stickers
on their cars since January 1993, and have been looking for a
reason, finally finding her.
</P>
<P>
   No, I don't want to see Monica and Linda raising their right
hands, except to take swings at each other. I don't want to see the
three branches of government in one room talking about the
definition of ``sexual relations'' for the benefit of MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the eggnog, not the impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
