<P>
   &UR; BILL'S WORLD &QC;  &LR;   &UR; By Bill Tammeus, The Kansas City Star &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The last impeachment trial of a president _ Andrew Johnson _
took 74 days. But back then there were fewer TV soap operas to
interrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clinton says we must do more for our farmers. Yes, but in
this holiday season we're already eating as much as we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can build a future on hope,'' Mr. Clinton told Israel on
his Middle East trip, ``that is different from the past.'' However,
it's unclear whether he can do that for himself in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a holiday TV special we bet would get a lot of viewers:
``A Very Monica Hanukkah.''
</P>
<P>
   At last count three House Democrats have said they'll vote for
impeachment. Or, as they may be known in the White House,
Damnocrats.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to say how the impeachment vote will go in the House.
But you have to wonder why there's been no similar push to impeach
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been condemned by my accusers with harsh words,'' Mr.
Clinton says. And by himself with weaselly words.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better to be hated for what you are,'' says Al Gore,
``than to be loved for what you are not.'' Right, but here's our
corollary: It's even better to be hated only by nincompoops.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Kerrey of Nebraska has decided not to run for president
in 2000. So have we, but it didn't make the wires.
</P>
<P>
   Crime rates continue to fall in the country. Maybe more and more
potential criminals are waiting until they get elected to office.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPENING REMARKS FROM THE ``LATE SHOW with DAVID LETTERMAN'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I love New York City, it's very festive. This morning, for
example, my cab driver, bless his heart, instead of wearing a
turban, he had his head gift wrapped.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a warning for you folks if you're in town for the
holidays. There's a guy over on Eighth Avenue and he's using a blow
dryer on rats and he's selling them as Furbys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``...to kick of the holiday season, tonight, the hairpiece I'm
wearing is made from the pelt of a Furby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting ready to do my shopping and I'm thinking, who are
we kidding? This Christmas, why don't we all quit playing around,
quit goofing around and get dad exactly what dad wants. Let's get
dad his own intern.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who come from out of town and want to stay at a nice
hotel and want to see a Broadway show, it's very expensive. Here
now is a piece of advice, a free tip for out-of-towners when you
come to New York City. Do what I do many times, instead of wasting
all that money on a hotel and a show -- just sleep through Cats.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's representatives now have been given 30
hours to defend him. Thirty hours? Man! You couldn't defend the
college years in 30 hours!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Love em or hate em, you've got to give these Clinton attorneys
a lot of credit. Talk about no rest for the weary. Okay, they're
done with this, now they're getting ready for his next sex
scandal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're considering now a fifth Article of Impeachment and
this charge is pretty serious...--'Bad taste in girlfriends.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton, of course, is still saying what he and Monica
Lewinsky did was not sex. He's also still saying that lying under
oath is not perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton would really rather not be impeached...When
this guy gets out of office and he's walking around looking for a
job, trying to find a gig, right there on his resume it says that
he was impeached, that's bad!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you know what's in the mail now? The White House
Christmas card. It's a wonderful piece of work, I saw one earlier.
It depicts Bill and Hillary after the impeachment and they're
moving into the stable.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I had arranged to meet my daughter, Tali, on Third Avenue, and
as I approached I could hear police cars screeching to the curb,
sirens blasting and red lights flashing. I spotted my daughter
rushing toward me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look Mom,'' she said, laughing and pointing across the street.
``It's a chicken!''
</P>
<P>
   To my surprise, there was a very alive, very frightened chicken,
the scrawniest creature I had ever seen. The poor chicken was
pacing back and forth on the sidewalk, undoubtedly trying to decide
whether to brave Third Avenue traffic or stay and face the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the police were facing a dilemma of their own. Once
within reach of the chicken, the officers realized they were not
sufficiently equipped to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, one of the more daring took action. Armed with an old
cardboard box grabbed from a grocery stand, he lunged at the
chicken and managed to scoop the box over it. Now things were back
at stalemate, with the chicken only temporarily confined.
</P>
<P>
   Hunger and the passing of time finally got the better of us. We
decided to leave. At last glance, the police cars were speeding
away, and three anxious police officers were guarding the box. We
passed up the chicken dishes on the lunch menu.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSANA SEDGWICK
</P>
<P>
   Linda Blum was walking uptown on Madison Avenue on Halloween
when she was mesmerized by a dachshund ambling along on a leash.
His sides were covered by two tan oval cushions and a wavy line of
yellow felt trailed down his back. The dog's owner spotted Ms.
Blum's amused expression and explained. ``It's his Halloween
costume,'' she said. ``He's a hot dog. ''
</P>
<P>
   Requirements listed on a recent ``help wanted'' sign in a bakery
on 17th Street intrigued Norman Oder: Honest, Hard Working,
Engaging or Relatively Engaging, or Appear To Be Relatively
Engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent most of my 47 years running on Manhattan's
unforgiving sidewalks, I knew to look for dogs, and often a
retractable, impossible-to-see-at-night fish-line leash attached.
</P>
<P>
   This tiny dog was under a car, sniffing a tire, not visible
until it was too late. The owner was, of course, looking in a
window, oblivious to the fact that her leash was like a trip wire
across the entire width of the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Even before I hit the ground hard, bloodying my knees, palms and
head, she was screaming, ``Oh, my God, are you OK? Tell me you're
OK!'' At least she seemed contrite! I muttered, ``Yeah, I'm OK.''
She responded: ``Not you! Biscuit! You could have broken her
neck.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ISAAC S. HERSCHKOPF
</P>
<P>
   As a member of the Museum of Modern Art, Susan Striker was
savoring the luxury of a members-only opening of the Jackson
Pollock exhibit without being jostled by the usual crowds. She
noted that the overheard conversations were on a level above ``My
3-year-old can paint better than that,'' and that it seemed
everyone was serious about art. Then one elderly woman turned to
another and said, ``The best thing about Jackson Pollock is that
when I look at his paintings I don't see the floater in my eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a Queens-bound N train stood at 57th Street with its
doors open. Three minutes grew to five and then 10. Finally, the
driver took to the intercom, explaining that the train was stuck
because the one ahead was experiencing ``passenger interference.''
</P>
<P>
   A short silence ensued as the well-behaved passengers digested
the information. Then one man delivered his opinion. ``Shoot him,''
he suggested. JoAnn C. Gutin noted that he got his laugh, but
another rider stepped in with something more appropriate. ``Nah,''
he said. ``Passenger interference is only a 15-yard penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Simpson was pleased when Eric, her highly active
7-year-old pupil arrived for his piano lesson and greeted her with
enthusiasm. However, she wondered whether she'd be able to hold his
attention that day _ she was going to explain how to count dotted
rhythms, a formidable concept for any child. He sat perfectly
still, eyes glued to her face. ``Oh boy,'' she thought. ``He's
taking it in. We'll be making real progress now.''
</P>
<P>
   She then asked Eric if he had any questions. There was a
thoughtful pause, and he lifted his gaze above her eye level.
Forget dotted rhythms. He had obviously been concentrating on what
he considered a less than perfect coiffure. ``Would you like me to
find you a hairbrush?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gordon Mahler was in Zion National Park, Utah, standing
on the canyon floor admiring the surrounding spectacular mountains,
when a fellow tourist addressed a friend: ``This is just like New
York City. My neck hurts from looking up.''
</P>
<P>
   An amused grandmother reassured her visiting 7-year-old
granddaughter that tooth fairies were everywhere and that the two
teeth under her pillow would be taken care of. Indeed, the next
morning, the tooth fairy had left some money, and also granted the
request in the girl's note: I woold like it if I kod pleas keep my
teeth. ThankU. Love Elaine.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Earlier today, President Clinton's lawyers began defending
President Clinton before the House Impeachment Committee. I'm not
sure they did much good because their main argument was, 'Come on,
she was wearing a thong.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night at the White House, President Clinton threw a
Christmas party for all 535 members of Congress. During the
festivities several congressmen told the President, 'This is great.
Now we don't have to have a going away party.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new survey, 46 percent of Americans say they're
tired of all the focus on gifts and commercialism during the
holidays. The other 54 percent are selling Furbies for $300 each.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Rodman filed for an annulment from Carmen Electra only
nine days after he got married, but now he says he hopes the
marriage will work out. In fact, he said that some day down the
road he wants to get really drunk and marry her all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, one million people in San Francisco were without
power after a worker shut off a power switch. The worker apologized
for the mistake saying he didn't realize Kathie Lee's Christmas
special wasn't until Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, scientists announced they discovered a skeleton
that could reveal secrets of human origins. Then today, scientists
realized that all they had actually found was Calista Flockhart
taking a nap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This week Hillary Clinton attended a movie premiere and she
said she hasn't been in a movie theater for years. Meanwhile,
President Clinton said he hasn't been in a movie theater since they
cleaned up Times Square.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, President Clinton's defense team rested after a
10-hour session. When asked to comment Monica Lewinsky said,
'That's weird. The President used to rest after a 10-minute
session.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today in California, a logging protester is celebrating his
one year anniversary of living in a giant redwood tree. The man
said at first it was hard, but then they opened a Starbuck's in the
tree next to him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Long Island auction company is auctioning off a love letter
that Jimmy Carter wrote to one of his girlfriends over 50 years
ago. Apparently Carter was quite a romantic. He asked the girl to
run off with him and build low income housing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman is suing McDonald's claiming that she found a condom
in her chicken sandwich. A spokesman for McDonald's said, 'That's
just our new sandwich: McRibbed.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``This afternoon, after hours of deliberating, the House
Judiciary Committee took their first vote. The result was 21 to 16
in favor of pepperoni with extra cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton made a speech to the American people a few
minutes after four o'clock this afternoon. The President may not
have helped his own cause because he opened the speech by saying,
'Sorry I'm late but I was getting some.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``During a speech to the American people, President Clinton
admitted to being 'deceitful.' The President went on to say, 'And
just now when I said I was deceitful, I was lying.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S 'THE TONIGHT SHOW WITH JAY LENO' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``New law. It seems a federal appeals court has ruled it is
legal for the city of Kent, Washington, to require a 10-foot buffer
zone around nude dancers at strip clubs. If we can get this in
strip clubs, why can't we get this in the Oval Office?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's some sad news: One of my favorites, boxer Archie Moore,
passed away, 84 years old. The sad thing, he was scheduled to fight
the winner of the Holmes/Foreman bout.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A Republican superior court judge in North Carolina announced
that he's gay. First Michael Huffington, now this guy. I think
G.O.P. stands for 'Gay Old Party.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pharmaceutical giants Astra and Zeneca are working on a 30
billion dollar merger deal. Experts say it's the biggest drug
merger since Courtney Love married Kurt Cobain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy Fisher wants a mistrial. She claims she had sex with her
lawyer during the trial. Just when you thought she couldn't stoop
any lower than having sex with Joey Buttafuoco, she had sex with
her lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The lawyer is saying it never happened. I bet his wife is
thinking twice before opening the door these days.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cindy Crawford was in a car accident the other day. She's
okay. I guess the paramedics flushed her eyes with water, as a
precaution against possible glass fragments. And then they also
hosed down her T-shirt, just to be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven-Eleven announced it will start serving a classy wine
list. Do you drink red or white wine with a Slim Jim?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The city of Baltimore has the highest rate of gonorrhea in the
country. Which explains their new slogan: Baltimore Fever. Catch
it!'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Police in Colorado have charged a 70-year-old grandmother with
robbing banks. 4 feet 11 inches. She walked into the bank with a
trash bag over her head and robbed the bank. She would've gotten
away except she stopped to show the tellers pictures of her
grandchildren.''
</P>
