 PageExpress budget for the week of Dec. 14, 1998
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site and you can use them just as they are or customize
any or all of the elements -- text, fonts, photos and graphics --
to suit your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call John
Gardner, pagination consultant for The New York Times Syndicate, at
917-224-4381 or e-mail him at pages &LR; nytsyn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m.
Tuesday, Dec. 8
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT: A YEAR IN REVIEW -- Available after 2 p.m.
Thursday -- There was plenty to ponder, mock, praise and puncture
in the arts in 1998. From movies to pop music to a television
season where it was hard to tell whether you were watching ``Jerry
Springer'' or ``Meet the Press,'' it's always fun to recall the
highlights and low lights from the 12 months gone by. WITH: RINGEL
ON VIDEO -- The movies of Christmas are as familiar as our favorite
tree ornaments; but sometimes you want something a little less
obvious, a little less traditional.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS -- Available after 2 p.m. Friday -- The Panama Canal is
more than an engineering wonder of the world, it is a symbol of the
ingenuity and determination of the United States. At high noon on
Dec. 31, 1999, under terms of the 1977 treaty negotiated by
then-President Carter, the Panama Canal will become the sole
property of Panama. Many in Washington have called for a continued
U.S. military presence in Panama after 2000. But Panama recently
slammed the door on negotiations to allow either a U.S. presence or
the installation of a proposed anti-narcotics center. WITH: CANAL
HISTORY -- A brief history of the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL -- Christmas -- especially the weekend of Grand
Illumination, always the first Sunday in December -- is the busiest
time of the year in Colonial Williamsburg; and there's no mystery
as to why. There are few seasonal destinations more magnificent
than the 500 restored or re-created public buildings, houses,
taverns and trade shops brilliantly decorated for the holidays.
WITH: TRAVEL NOTES -- One thing you can almost count on when you
revisit Walt Disney World is that something new and nifty will have
sprung up. A summary of what's ahead or has just arrived at the
ever-expanding Florida resort. WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Next year
will bring less variety among U.S. airlines' frequent-flier
programs and the disappearance of miles that expire, an expert on
loyalty programs predicts.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD - SOUP -- The power of soup is more than folklore. Think
about the healing taste of chicken soup, the camaraderie of sharing
a pot of chili on a cold winter afternoon, even the souped-up
recipe enhancements of the ubiquitous canned cream of mushroom.
Comforting stuff, soup. Comforting for the cook, too. After the
rigors of preparing a multi-course Thanksgiving dinner, there's
something seductively simple about just fixing soup. WITH: SOUP
RECIPES WITH: CYBERSPICE -- A number of sites on the Internet offer
innovative possibilities for gifts of food.
</P>
<P>
   WHEELS -- SAAB -- Not content with turning its 5-year-old 900
models into the frisky 9-3 coupe and sedan for 1999, Saab moves in
the automotive race toward the millennium with mid-model-year '99?
versions. It's not just a marketing or public relations ploy,
either. Saab has made significant changes -- mostly underneath and
inside -- to the front-drive cars. WITH: SHARP DRIVING -- This
holiday season, Volvo is one of several automakers, including BMW,
Mercedes-Benz and Saab, that are offering European delivery.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY -DVD -- Remember the day you walked into the
record store and there weren't any records? Don't be surprised 10
years from now if you walk into a video store and there aren't any
videotapes. Digital video discs, commonly known as DVDs, are
gaining a foothold by outperforming VCRs the way CDs outperformed
vinyl records. WITH: DVD COMPUTERS -- In addition to its
development as a home-theater component, DVD is expected to be an
important force in personal computers. WITH: DIGITAL DIVIDE: While
many high-tech companies continue to spend hundreds of millions of
dollars to supercharge the connection between education and
technology, the larger companies have a new focus -- on the
teacher. WITH: TECH BRIEFS -- Swatch, the company that made the
plastic watch cool, has launched a cool new line of plastic pagers.
The beeper comes in three colors: airmail blue, black grape and
round table orange. WITH: TECHNOBUDDY -- Telecommuting is fine for
performing many work-related tasks; but it can never be a real
substitute for actually being there.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS -- JORDAN -- Long before fretting about ``moral
authority'' in public life became a national pastime, people sensed
that Barbara Jordan symbolized the quality. As Mary Beth Rogers,
her latest biographer, notes, she spoke with the authority of an
Old Testament prophet, using her stirring deep voice, impeccable
diction and studied reasoning to electric effect. WITH: NEWS TEAM
-- MacNeil and Lehrer are together again, this time on bookshelves
rather than on television. For almost 15 years, Robert MacNeil and
Jim Lehrer co-anchored PBS' hourlong evening newscast. MacNeil left
in 1996, primarily to write, and Lehrer soldiers on alone. These
two genteel journalists have published new novels simultaneously,
and while neither is going to prompt Updike or Roth to check his
heels to see who's nipping there, both are brisk, engaging reads.
WITH: ON THE SHELF -- Gift books represent a special category of
Christmas present -- each requires a sizable cash or credit
investment and a full sheet of wrapping paper, not to mention a
strong back if you plan to buy more than one or two. Here's a list
of books you may consider giving as presents this holiday season.
WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH -- BACK TO MARS -- NASA, seeking more clues
about whether Mars might once have supported primitive life, is
embarking on a new chapter in its Martian Chronicles. Over the few
weeks, the space agency is taking advantage of the favorable
alignment of Earth and Mars to launch two spacecraft to the Red
Planet. They are the latest in a decade-long series of planned
missions that began with last year's successful landing of the
Pathfinder spacecraft and its robot rover Sojourner. WITH HEALTH
CARE -- Eyeglasses often make it on the list of holiday purchases
-- not as presents, but as a way for patients to squeeze out the
last dollars of their yearly health benefits. WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS
-- Concerned about the danger of Web sites that offer Viagra
prescriptions without any face-to-face doctor-patient contact,
Florida officials say doctors who prescribe the drug online could
face criminal prosecution or board discipline. WITH: IN SCIENCE --
Newly discovered records of bones found in 1940 on a remote island
in the South Pacific indicate that the remains might have been
those of aviator Amelia Earhart.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look ahead at some topics to be covered in PageExpress.
</P>
<P>
   Personal technology, Dec. 29 -- Y2K bug, one year out.
</P>
<P>
   Focus page, Dec. 31 -- 2,000 years of Christianity -- the first
of an occasional series through 1999 on Christianity's impact and
growth over 2,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Travel, Jan. 5 -- Travel opportunities next New Year's Eve --
where to go to see the first sunrise of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Travel, Jan. 21 (special Thursday delivery) -- Things to see in
Miami, pegged to the Super Bowl.
</P>
