   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (New York) _ During most of December, and most
definitively during the Cena della Vigilia, the ritual dinner of
the vigil on Christmas Eve, my childhood home in Buffalo, N.Y.,
could have been beamed to Sicily without a single Sicilian noticing
anything peculiar about it. Alfred Portale of Gotham Bar &AMP; Grill
recreates his Sicilian Christmas Eve feast.
</P>
<P>
   With 4 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   CHOCOLATE (Undated) _ First, the aroma beckons. The intense
scent drawing you in is unmistakably that of rich chocolate, but
you detect exotic hints of clove, coffee, orange peel, even cedar.
The bar is dark and shiny, scored into sections. It breaks cleanly,
with a definite snap. At this point you don't even need to taste it
to know you're dealing with extremely fine chocolate. A look at how
to truly appreciate chocolate; what makes the really good stuff
worlds away from Hershey's. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 recipes
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-BITS&AMP;BYTES (Undated) _ The column: Chocolate off the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-KITCHEN (Undated) _ It started out a carpenter's tool _ a
rasp _ an efficient device meant to file wood. Who could have
guessed it was an epiphany away from greatness in another arena:
the kitchen. The tale of the Microplane, the homely tool that
became the greatest lemon zester. Plus other stocking stuffer
gadgets for the kitchen. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Cookies are always easy,
but around the holidays, with time short and demand high, even they
can use streamlining. One solution is to whip up a single batter _
the food processor is the easiest way _ and finish it in different
ways. You can flavor some and roll some, and then bake the cookies
at different temperatures to give a plate variety. By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   LATKE (Undated) _ Anything-but-potato pancakes. By Joan Nathan.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With 3 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   PASTRY-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews Rose Levy
Beranbaum's pastry bible.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
