<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0898 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      12-15 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS, BOTTLES AND OTHER OFFERINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Writing about wine gifts is like preaching to the converted.
Anyone who loves wine knows what an endless fount of inspiration it
can be _ anything from a single bottle to a full set of glasses can
be gift-wrapped with the certainty that it will be put to good use.
</P>
<P>
   It is the wine-fearing who don't realize that a simple, elegant
answer to their gift-giving problems is as close as the nearest
good liquor store. Wine is a welcome gift in just about any price
range, from a couple of bottles of Beaujolais nouveau for around
$10 to a case of 1995 Bordeaux for more than $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   A case of the great 1995 Robert Mondavi Reserve Cabernet
Sauvignon is just less than $1,000, but a couple of bottles of the
same wine at around $165 is still a superb gift.
</P>
<P>
   The best gift is one you know the recipient would never buy for
herself, like a fine vintage port. A Taylor 1983, about $150, or a
Graham 1977 for $125, or a Taylor from the legendary 1963 vintage
at $350 would make an unforgettable gift.
</P>
<P>
   My choice would be an old tawny, say the 26-year-old Colheita
from the Quinta do Noval at about $60, or Taylor 40-year-old for
$110.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, older rarities turn up in wine shops.
Trefethen Vineyards in the Napa Valley recently released some of
its 1992 cabernet sauvignon at about $40 a bottle. The extra three
or four years it spent in the cellars made a difference, one very
few people will get a chance to appreciate, unless they get it as a
gift.
</P>
<P>
   Most good shops will keep some older Bordeaux on hand that can
make a generous gift. A single bottle of the famous St.-Emilion,
Chateau Figeac, from the great 1982 vintage can be found in a few
shops for less than $250. Chateau Latour from the same year goes
for $800. Personally, I would love to get a few bottles from 1988
or 1989, great years at approachable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Other California labels bound to excite wine fans include
Pahlmeyer Vineyards Red, at about $65, and Christian Moueix's
Dominus, $100, both from the 1995 vintage, and Francis Ford
Coppola's Rubicon, 1992, at $50. Joseph Phelps' Insignia, 1995,
$70, is one of the great California classics.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to get dramatic, buy a big bottle, and I mean really
big. A six-liter bottle is the equivalent of eight regular
750-milliliter bottles, and often it can be an excellent value.
</P>
<P>
   Zachy's Wine and Liquor in Scarsdale, N.Y., specializes in big
bottles, but most good shops have some on hand. A six-liter bottle
of 1995 Chateau Gloria sells for about $350. The 1995 Chateau
Meyney in that size is about $300, and Chateau Larose Trintaudon is
$200.
</P>
<P>
   With Champagne, a magnum _ a double bottle _ is impressive. A
magnum of Dom Perignon 1990, the essence of luxury, is less than
$250. Other excellent Champagnes in magnums, like Nicolas
Feuillatte and Perrier-Jouet, are $50 to $60.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them also come in handsome wooden boxes, but remember,
the packaging does nothing for the wine but push up the price.
Champagne makers have a weakness for overpriced satin-lined boxes,
most of them made of cardboard, that pair their wine with a couple
of glasses. Who needs only two glasses? If you want to send wine,
send wine; if you want to send glasses, send glasses. Combining the
two is a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   Glasses on their own, however, are a great gift. The best can
cost more than $100 each, but good ones can be found for less than
$10. Try not to give fewer than six and consider what kind of
glasses your friends prefer before you buy. Glasses are like
silverware; they may have a pattern they prefer.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't afford Baccarat, then Riedel glasses, particularly
the Vinum line, are good values at $15 to $20 each. The Riedel
Overture line, also of very good quality, sells for about $8 a
glass and is shipped in sets of 12.
</P>
<P>
   For wine wannabes, think of books and classes. One of the
longest running wine courses in New York is Kevin Zraly's school in
the sky at Windows on the World at the World Trade Center, which
has turned out some 9,000 graduates over 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-session course is $695. Zraly undercuts himself to
some extent with his book, ``Windows on the World Complete Wine
Course'' (Sterling Publishing, $25), which he updates every year.
It is one of the best wine primers available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wine for Dummies,'' an instant success several years ago and
still a big seller, has spawned a shameless imitator, ``The
Complete Idiot's Guide to Wine.'' Dummy or idiot, it comes down to
your own level of self-esteem, or how you feel about the person
who's getting the book But these do seem to help the complete
novice.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when asked about wine courses and how-to books, the late
Alexis Lichine used to say, ``There is no substitute for pulling
corks.'' In other words, spend the money on wine. I won't go that
far, but I do prefer to read wine books more for fun than
instruction. Some books offer both, and among those I prefer the
older vintages.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Johnson's ``World Atlas of Wine'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $50),
``Wine Atlas of California'' by James Halliday (Viking, $50), ``The
Great Domaines of Burgundy'' by Remington Norman's (Henry Holt,
$45), and Clive Coates' monumental ``Cote d'Or'' (University of
California, $55), are all in this category. Don't let words like
atlas and monumental put you off: These are beautiful books, filled
with information, and they are also fun to read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1551EST &QL; 
