</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GALLO CHARDONNAY DISPLAYS ITS INTENSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marcelina Vineyards Chardonnay 1996, Napa Valley. About $19. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surprise, surprise. This excellent chardonnay is a Gallo wine.
It is part of the giant winery's concerted effort to become a
player in California's fine wine business, and it is an unqualified
success.
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic North Coast chardonnay, full bodied and
intense, with 14.3 percent alcohol. It has a sizable oak presence,
not unexpected in a wine fermented almost entirely in new French
oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   About 85 percent of the grapes are from Gallo's Marcelina
Vineyards in the Napa Valley, the rest from Dry Creek Valley and
the Russian River Valley in Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   The wine's intensity is traced to the short grape crop in 1996,
which led to lower yields that usually produce intensely flavored
fruit. The wine was made from free-run juice, which means it was
lightly pressed to minimize tannins.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize its softer finish, the wine underwent a second, or
malolactic, fermentation. It was aged 11 months before release.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
