<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PASTOR-1216-C     12-15 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PASTOR-1216-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PASTOR AND CLINTON FRIEND GIVES PRESIDENT, FIRST LADY SUPPORT IN
ISRAEL VISIT
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-CLINTON-1216.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ While several hundred Palestinians
waiting outside Tuesday wondered why President Bill Clinton spent
an hour inside the Church of the Nativity, Clinton's old friend
says he knows.
</P>
<P>
   The cavernous church is over 1,600 years old, with several
chapels inside and a dim grotto below with a shrine over the
supposed spot of Christ's birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know just from his heart he would want to spend time there
and pray,'' said the Rev. John Anthony, who lives in Israel but
went to kindergarten and first grade with Clinton in Hope, Ark.
``With so much bombarding them and so many questions from everybody
around him, I think he needed some quiet time.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony was not with the Clintons during their visit to the
church on Tuesday. Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
daughter Chelsea made it a side trip during their three-day visit
to the Middle East. They went through the Door of Humility, so
called because one must bend over to pass through and, presumably,
because even a president of the United States is not the most
important person to ever have been here.
</P>
<P>
   After they emerged, the three looked happy and sang Christmas
carols with a Palestinian choir.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony was not with them, but he said he knows they consider
the church important.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, he greeted Clinton along with the line of
Israeli dignitaries at Israel's Ben-Gurion International Airport.
Clinton smiled broadly and gave his buddy a big hug, all captured
on Israeli television.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Anthony is using his moment of fame, having been
interviewed by several Israeli media, to ask Americans to pray for,
rather than impeach, their president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though he did sin . . . we need to forgive him and more,''
Anthony said. ``Pray for the man and look at the good things he's
done. We are all fallible, flawed people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Anthony lived just two streets from each other as
children and they have kept in touch.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony, 52, has been a minister in Israel for 25 years. He last
saw Clinton in 1994, when the president invited him to attend the
signing of the Israel-Jordan peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House is expected to vote as early as Thursday on
whether to impeach Clinton for his cover-up of an affair with a
White House intern. That made Anthony especially eager to show
support for his old friend at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could not attend his Jerusalem Baptist Church service
Sunday morning -- Sundays are work days in Israel and Clinton had
to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu -- but
Clinton invited him to the VIP table at a large dinner that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about Arkansas and I told him we were praying for
them. Hillary really appreciated that and said prayers are what
have sustained them,'' Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   Even amid Clinton's efforts to jump-start the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, he has been dogged by the issue
of the impeachment. At times Clinton has looked tired and glum, and
people have wondered how he and the first lady are getting along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are holding up very well,'' Anthony said of the
couple. ``They do not seem at all distant.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
