<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Several Republicans who have
expressed ambivalence about voting to remove President Clinton from
office now say they will vote for at least some of the articles of
impeachment, making the White House push for a compromise more
remote. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ALTERNATIVES (Washington) _ As Democrats search for
alternatives to impeachment, White House officials embrace a
proposal by 1996 Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole for a
joint House-Senate resolution of censure against President Clinton.
By STEWART M. POWELL and MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   PERJURY-PRIMER (Washington) _ The first two impeachment articles
to be debated Thursday by the House charge that President Clinton
committed perjury. In Q&AMP;A form, we explore what perjury is and
review White House and Republican arguments on whether he perjured
himself. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   BOEHLERT-IMPEACHMENT (Washington) _ One uncommitted House
Republican, Rep. Sherwood L. Boehlert of New York, finds his office
the target of scores of calls, faxes and other lobbying efforts
trying to influence his decision on how to vote this week on
impeachment. By JUDY HOLLAND.
