<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO LEARN THIS YEAR'S LESSONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA YIP 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As we approach the end of the year, the evaluation of your
investment portfolio is more important than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The rise, fall and rebound of the stock market this year has
taught a harsh lesson in investment management to professional
money managers and individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who thought you should have diversified your
portfolio before this summer's market swoon, now's your chance.
</P>
<P>
   Consider taking some money out of stocks and putting it in bonds
and cash investments such as money market mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   True, the market has come back from its severe fall in the
summer and is up 11.6 percent for the year as of last Friday. But
there are some troubling signs out there.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, the darlings of investors are still large-company
stocks and technology stocks. Tech stocks were also the fair-haired
children before the market started its skid in July. Internet
stocks have once again soared to unbelievable levels, as any
company with ``.com'' in its name is attracting investors like
flies to honey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, if the (market) decline is truly over, you get a
change in leadership in a new bull market, and we did not get a
change in leadership,'' said Richard J. Fruth, a Houston portfolio
manager. ``The market went right back to the old favorites.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CORPORATE EARNINGS LOOK BLEAK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The outlook for corporate earnings also isn't very good.
</P>
<P>
   We're heading into the end of the quarter and during the end of
any quarter, corporations enter the so-called ``confessional
period'' when they warn about profit disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it hard to justify high prices of stocks, some
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Coca-Cola joined a growing list of large companies
that have lowered their earnings forecasts for the fourth quarter
due to the volatility of global financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Although the international scene has improved somewhat, it's far
from settled. You've got a deepening recession in Japan and
potential trouble in Latin America if Brazil, the region's largest
economy, falls.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Latin America, things have definitely deteriorated since
the situation in Brazil,'' said Ed Larsen, chief equity officer of
Aim Capital Management in Houston, a mutual fund company.
``Everything isn't just hunky-dory just south of the border.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``We are advising no more than 30 percent in the
market now because the risk is so high,'' said Geraldine Weiss,
publisher of Investment Quality Trends in La Jolla, Calif., an
investment newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   The dividend yield of the Dow Jones industrial average is about
1.6 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The yield, which is the annual percentage of return earned by an
investor on a stock, has an inverse relationship to a stock's
price. The lower the yield, the higher the stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the dividend yield of the Dow is ``the lowest in
history,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of the fact that the market is
strenuously overvalued,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the price/earnings ratio of the benchmark Standard
&AMP; Poor's index of 500 large-company stocks is about 30 times
earnings, Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   That's about where it was in June and before the market started
falling in July.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with an average of about 14.9 times the last
year's earnings since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   The price/earnings ratio represents how much investors are
willing to pay for a company's earnings power. The higher the
number, the more investors expect of a company.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should sock money away in intermediate-term bonds with
maturities of five to eight years and also consider junk bonds and
municipal bonds, Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that a lesson from the summer is that bonds became a
very positive element in diversifying a portfolio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
INVESTORS LIKE LOW INTEREST RATES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees that stocks are overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   The price/earnings ratio of the S&AMP;P 500 index may appear to be
expensive, but low interest rates have made stocks more attractive
to investors, said Henry Lartigue, chief investment officer of
Chase Bank of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing affects the P/E ratio more than interest rates and
inflation,'' he said. ``The high P/E is justified because the
economic environment is so positive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we ought to be worried, and people do themselves
a disservice by worrying about it (the market),'' said Bob Scraper,
a money manager at Frost Bank in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pamela Yip can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to pamela.yip(at)chron.com, or call
(713) 220-2000 and enter access code 1003. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
