<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0965 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PSYCHO-VAN-SANT-NYTSF     12-15 2199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PSYCHO-VAN-SANT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS GUS VAN SANT GONE PSYCHO? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By R.J. SMITH  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    It's audition night at the Bates Motel. In a large, darkened
room on a studio lot in Southern California, three women are
interpreting a pop standard. On a movie screen before them, a
blonde showers.
 &HT;    In succession, each of the trio emits a brutal string of screams
becoming moans shifting to last-desperate-gasps that are meant to
complement the sight of the shower curtain being ripped away, the
knife, the blood swirling down the drain.
 &HT;    Each scream is recorded, and the best will end up in the final
picture. The scene rolls repeatedly, each of the trio able to
withstand two, maybe three takes before her vocal cords are frayed
and unable to release the curdled fear demanded.
 &HT;    ``I want more ... gasping,'' the director says from the corner
of the room.
 &HT;    ``Not enough whimpering?'' the vocalist asks.
 &HT;    ``Yeah. But the scream was really good.''
 &HT;    ``More pain?''
 &HT;    The director thinks a minute, his eyes tracking slowly across a
spread of cold meats and cheeses on a table. ``Wrestling,
struggling, whimpering, breathing,'' he says finally.
 &HT;    ``I'm not going to sleep tonight,'' the vocalist says, walking
back to the couch. Gus Van Sant, the director, chuckles softly.
 &HT;    His career began with the downcast, beautiful ``Mala Noche'' in
1985, and continued on to such defining modern independent films as
``Drugstore Cowboy'' (1989) and ``My Own Private Idaho'' (1991),
movies that put him at the forefront of a wave of independent
filmmakers that included Steven Soderbergh, Allison Anders, Todd
Haynes and Hal Hartley.
 &HT;    Last year he achieved industrywide stature with the
Oscar-nominated ``Good Will Hunting.'' It's his ``moment,'' a time
when he's especially set up to close dream deals and get backing
for pet projects. And maybe that's what he's doing here, foraging
among the shrieks.
 &HT;    But not even Van Sant seems to know for sure. ``This is ...'' he
begins, before giving up. ``I don't know what this is.'' This time
the chuckle is louder.
 &HT;    Maybe the woman in the shower better illustrates the story. The
actress Anne Heche sports a short cut that makes you think first of
Janet Leigh, who 38 years ago met precisely the same end. For Van
Sant isn't filming just a remake of Alfred Hitchcock's ``Psycho.''
He is bringing it back to life shot by shot, using an only slightly
updated script. A new cast, you almost get the feeling, is a
lamentable expedient; this time, it is Vince Vaughn who wears the
dress.
 &HT;    The production is so by-the-book that there is even a director's
cameo: not the fit and square-jawed Van Sant, but an actor
prosthetically made to look like Hitchcock. It seems the largest
concession is that his version is in color _ that's not chocolate
syrup flowing down the drain.
 &HT;    A pair of whys hover over this endeavor. First, why copy a
perfect movie? Dany Wolf, an executive producer, says they had the
blessing of Hitchcock's daughter and of his estate, and that the
master remade himself over the years. Besides, if Hitchcock were
alive today, he too would doubtless be revisiting the Bates Motel.
 &HT;    ``For people like us,'' Wolf says, ``the cinephiles, there's a
controversy. But the kids, they haven't seen the other one and to
them, this movie is 'Psycho.'''
 &HT;    But the other big why involves Van Sant. Why has someone whose
work made the fringe seem so vibrant turned so decisively to the
mainstream? Of course, Van Sant does not look at it that way.
 &HT;    ``Psycho,'' he insists, is a kind of research project, an
attempt to follow every step the master took yet end up in a
different place. ``In its way it's an experimental movie,'' he
says, before hiding behind a pause that qualifies as Hitchcockian.
``A funny kind of experiment that has applications in the
marketplace.''
 &HT;    A couple of days after the looping session, Van Sant kicks his
sneakers off and puts his athletic-stockinged feet up on the desk
next to a new, translucent iMac computer in his office on the
Universal lot. Hanging on the walls are production photos for
``Psycho'' and pictures of the pop group Hanson. Van Sant filmed a
video for the teen idols earlier this year, and still hopes to make
a movie with them.
 &HT;    ``Psycho'' is not an ordinary movie, he explains, and it is not
_ contrary to what has been reported _ anything as crass as a
sequel.
 &HT;    The project seems to have started out as a conceptual art piece
shaped by ideas Van Sant picked up studying painting and film at
the Rhode Island School of Design in 1971. About the first thing
Van Sant learned was the legacy of Marcel Duchamp and the idea of
the readymade, the artwork you make by simply labeling it so. Put a
bottle rack on a pedestal and it's a sculpture. Context determined
meaning, the argument went, and the artist was nothing more lofty
than a furniture mover.
 &HT;    That tradition was taught in the classroom, but around RISD at
the time there was also a circle of artists and performers who
injected a broad streak of irony and humor into their conceptual
gestures. Partly this was the influence of Andy Warhol. (Van Sant
went on to write a screenplay about Warhol's life, and wanted to
cast River Phoenix in the lead.) But part of it was pure
Providence.
 &HT;    Fellow students at RISD had formed the band Talking Heads. (He
saw them play their first show.) One of their acts was lip-synching
``Mustang Sally'' on video _ that made it ``art.'' Also present was
a cluster of art bands inspired by the comic Martin Mull (who in
the '60s was a painter at RISD and leader of the band Soup). The
same musicians would play for an audience, then change costumes,
assume another band identity and perform music from a series of
distinct eras.
 &HT;    There, in the early '70s, gestures of appropriation weren't
exercises in artistic anonymity, as earlier found-object creators
imagined; changing the context had the power to reveal something of
the sensibility of the person in charge.
 &HT;    ``'Appropriation' in some ways just doesn't exist,'' Van Sant
says now. ``As soon as you put something in a different context,
you're imparting your own style. Just by touching it, you become
part of it and it becomes a part of you.''
 &HT;    It was in 1989 when Van Sant, fresh from the success of
``Drugstore Cowboy,'' met with Universal executives, who raised the
idea of remaking a movie from their vaults. They were thinking, Van
Sant says, perhaps of some obscure B-movie to which he could
provide a modern gloss.
 &HT;    He countered with the idea of appropriating ``Psycho,'' and
argued that like a lot of filmgoers he was tired of seeing classic
movies bungled in the update. ``My retort was, 'Let's just not
change it.' And their answer was, 'So let's just not do it.'''
 &HT;    Eight years later, however, Van Sant was no longer one more
indie-movie maker with an offbeat idea in his back pocket. ``Good
Will Hunting,'' a commercial and critical success, demonstrated his
knack for getting stellar performances out of young talent such as
Ben Affleck, Matt Damon and Minnie Driver.
 &HT;    ``He comes up with 'Good Will Hunting,''' says Brian Grazer, the
movie's producer, ``and every person is throwing tons of money,
bags of money into his car, and into his face.'' Grazer, the most
influential producer at Universal, was one of the main
money-flingers. When he tried to interest Van Sant in making a
picture for the studio, the director said he wanted to do a
Universal picture, albeit one that had already been filmed.
 &HT;    Now, Van Sant might not like to see it this way, but
carbon-copying a classic offers insurance against the kind of
career-wounding disasters that can follow a big success. If
``Psycho'' fails _ commercially or critically _ Van Sant can't
really be blamed. And if it's a success, he'll get even more
credibility as an artiste and a businessman.
 &HT;    Van Sant's manner is beyond deadpan and in conversation with
him, you feel as if you could take off your socks and shoes and put
your feet up on the desk too. Except possibly when raving about
Hanson, Van Sant seems weirdly believable, his becalmed voice
underplaying the wide roamings of his mind and the subversiveness
of his ideas.
 &HT;    His father began as a traveling salesman and wound up running a
garment company. And while the son is following the same arc, he
proclaims that he's still living out of his car. He's clutching for
dear life to the high-minded ideas he has long held _ but now he's
the found object, and as his context has shifted, from indie
festivals to the Academy Awards, he refuses to acknowledge any
difference.
 &HT;    His fourth film ``Even Cowgirls Get the Blues'' (based on the
Tom Robbins novel), featured pansexual heroines, drug-taking
characters on the road, elliptical storytelling devices _ it was a
Van Sant film. And yet it got drubbed by critics and ignored by
audiences, a response that did Van Sant damage. It stopped his
forward motion and forced him to think hard about his next step.
 &HT;    So too did the passing of a friend. One night in 1993, River
Phoenix collapsed on a street corner in West Hollywood and died of
a drug overdose. Phoenix was one of the stars of ``Idaho,'' and Van
Sant calls the young actor's death one of the worst moments in his
life. This spring, another member of the cast, Rodney Harvey, died
of a heroin overdose.
 &HT;    Stories of wild living on the ``Idaho'' set have long
circulated, and a recent story in Premiere depicted Phoenix,
Harvey, Keanu Reeves and other cast members living at Van Sant's
house during the shooting and partying so hard the director had to
sleep at another address. It has been suggested that the director
was at least a nonjudgmental voyeur _ watching all the psychodrama
while declining to intervene _ if not a participant himself.
 &HT;    Van Sant says he had no knowledge of drug use in his home. ``I
don't really think of 'Idaho' as a time when there were bad seeds
sown,'' he says. ``If things were really getting out of control,
I'm sure I would have never been able to stand for that. But they
weren't out of control.'' He pauses, and looks away. ``Maybe they
were and I didn't know it.
 &HT;    ``Our little world was pretty tame, compared to 'the legend of
Idaho.' The legend of Idaho is kind of ominous, but it really
wasn't like that.''
 &HT;    After the disaster of ``Cowgirls,'' Van Sant rebounded with the
first of his pictures that anyone could call ``calculating'': ``To
Die For,'' an amusing yet distinctly minor work. If Phoenix's death
ignited old stories of high life on the ``Idaho'' set, ``To Die
For'' seemed designed to show Hollywood that Van Sant could play
ball _ the director himself calls it ``a cleaned-up version of one
of my films.''
 &HT;    It did the trick, bolstering his reputation, and next came
``Good Will Hunting,'' the career maker that presented Van Sant to
the world as a dependable director who could bring an indie flavor
to mainstream fare. The picture boosted his fee to the level of
hit-action-film directors. Van Sant says he got about twice for
``Psycho'' what he made on ``Good Will Hunting.''
 &HT;    During the filming of ``Psycho,'' Van Sant fetishized
Hitchcock's shooting schedule, hewing closely to an economical
32-day plan.
 &HT;    On the screen in the studio, a luxury car is winched out of
bubbling swamp water, the last scene in the movie. Within the
vehicle's trunk the police will find the body of Marion Crane and
the $400,000 she stole from her job the day before she died in the
shower.
 &HT;    The scene repeats as background sounds are recorded. In the next
room Van Sant is on the phone, discussing the logistics of
purchasing and transporting a Lotus from a guy in Portland, Van
Sant's hometown. It is not cheap.
 &HT;    In the end, maybe the director he most resembles isn't
Hitchcock, but Warhol, who never saw a contradiction between high
art and the finer things in life. Warhol too made multiple versions
of the same work, a concept Van Sant says he's considering.
 &HT;    Even now, he jokes that he'd like to remake ``Psycho'' again.
``We'd tell the same story but with different attitudes. I was
thinking we could do a punk 'Psycho,' or a black 'Psycho,' or a gay
'Psycho.' But they would be the same story _ you'd want it to be
the same story. It wouldn't be different, but it would just be
changed.''
 &HT;     c.1998 R.J. Smith  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (R.J. Smith is a staff writer at Spin magazine.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _________ &QC;
</P>
