<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAHN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREASE THAT NEARLY COOKED MY GOOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JON HAHN  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the memories evoked by holiday lights, music and warm
smells, none touches me so deeply as a particular Christmas goose.
</P>
<P>
   It near 'bout killed me.
</P>
<P>
   Every family has a story about a holiday mishap: the year the
dog's collar caught in the tree lights and he pulled the whole
shebang down on the living room floor. Or the time Uncle Henry
slipped and broke his arm as he carried the green-bean casserole up
the front walk.
</P>
<P>
   Out on our branch of the family tree, this is the time of year
they tell the story of Jon and the Goose Grease. 'Tis a tale that
to this day causes involuntary quivering deep in my gut.
</P>
<P>
   As children, we reveled in a household full of warm and
wonderful cooking smells during the holidays. Cookies and
fruitcakes and fresh breads and Christmas stollens were baked and
stored away within easy reach of any adventurous child. Hand-dipped
chocolates and tins of nutty fudge were never too far away.
</P>
<P>
   The main Christmas meal was a happy feast that left at least a
week of wonderful leftovers, and we indulged in such delicacies as
pickled herring sandwiches, stuffing and gravy lunches and turkey
soup. And there was leftover pie, cake and cookies enough to carry
us well into the new year.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest treat was leftover goose grease. And although we
almost always had a turkey, our Great-Aunt Margaret and -Uncle Bill
upstairs never varied from the traditional Christmas goose. Nor
from the traditional German fare of goose grease sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   They always found the fattest goose available, so that they were
sure to end up with a goodly amount of grease. This was the golden
egg, so far as we were concerned, because the traditional German
delicacy issued therefrom.
</P>
<P>
   Aunt Margaret and Uncle Bill would carefully pour off the
accumulated grease and save it on the unheated back porch for a few
days. They never had to announce the special day, because we could
smell the grease being rendered, all the way down in the basement
of our two-flat.
</P>
<P>
   They would heat the congealed grease and separate out any other
liquids. In a big black frying pan, they'd cook up bacon bits and
chopped onion, which were drained and then added to the clear, hot
goose grease. Then the whole smear was poured into small butter
crocks and set back on the porch to congeal.
</P>
<P>
   By the next day, it hardened to the consistency of a grainy lard
and emitted a very noticeable eau de G &UR; gfumlaut &LR; ansenschmalz. And
there was great ceremony made of the first partaking, in which a
big glob of hardened goose grease was spread over a hunk of Jewish
rye bread and sprinkled with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the memory of it used to cause pangs of hunger in my
nostalgic stomach. And for years after they died, no one in the
family dared try to duplicate this special dish.
</P>
<P>
   It was as though goose grease had become a special memorial that
had passed along with them _ until the year my older sister decided
that she would accept the mantle of Mother Goose Grease.
</P>
<P>
   My wife and I lived in Michigan at the time, and knew nothing of
this as we drove home for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   On the afternoon we were to drive back to Michigan, she
presented us with a small covered butter crock. I knew without
looking, from the delicious smell, that it was my own special
allotment of goose grease.
</P>
<P>
   I stopped at the supermarket nearest our apartment in Michigan
and bought a cold 12-pack of beer. And even before I had the car
completely unpacked, I stood at the kitchen counter and cut several
big hunks of bread and spread goose grease on it like a
do-it-yourself remodeler on his first wallboard taping-and-seaming
project.
</P>
<P>
   Damn, it was good! So I cut more bread, popped a few more cold
ones and sat down in front of the television. Finally, Wife Person
said: ``It's getting late and there's school tomorrow and I'm beat.
I'm going to bed!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there in a minute,'' I said as I went back into the
kitchen for a few more hunks of grease-slathered bread.
</P>
<P>
   When she got up the next morning, I didn't stir. I couldn't. I
felt like a goose-grease mine ready to explode. And the sound of
her making breakfast caused the explosion. When I finally stumbled
into the kitchen in my jammies, she was horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're green!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel green. Where's our Alka-Seltzer?''
</P>
<P>
   The seltzer didn't help. It didn't even stay down where it was
supposed to help. Everything came up. The Ghosts of Christmas
passed, and I was a green, quivering, porcelain-hugging wretch for
two semi-solid days.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost a decade before I could even look at goose grease.
Even just the words caused stomach rumblings when a family member
or friend would ask: ``So, are you gonna have goose grease again
this Christmas?''
</P>
<P>
   But this somewhat wiser man, having been visited by the Angel of
Near Death, has heeded the warning and returned to the Land of the
Living by a more moderate way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1630EST &QL; 
