<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL BUTTER COOKIES, BUT IN DISGUISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cookies are always easy, but around the holidays, with time
short and demand high, even they can use streamlining. One solution
is to whip up a single batter _ the food processor is the easiest
way _ and finish it in different ways. You can flavor some and roll
some, and then bake the cookies at different temperatures to fill a
plate with variety.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one batch of dough will yield four types if you
just divide the batter and add lemon juice and zest to one quarter,
chopped walnuts to the second, raisins to the third and coconut to
the fourth. The basic batter can also be varied with spices or
chocolate chips.
</P>
<P>
   But it's great plain, made with white sugar or brown, or even
with a tablespoon of molasses added to the white sugar. It can also
be rolled out and cut; just chill it to make it easier to handle.
</P>
<P>
   The standard _ and perfectly wonderful _ butter cookie contains
equal weights of flour and butter, sugar to taste (usually about
half as much as flour), an egg for every two cups of flour, milk as
necessary to produce a batter and any flavorings.
</P>
<P>
   The proportions of the basic ingredients, the flour, butter,
sugar, egg and milk, determine the underlying taste and texture of
the cookies. Make them with more flour and they're cakey; use more
butter, as I do here, and they're delicate, with better flavor.
</P>
<P>
   I've refined the classic recipe to do all the mixing in the food
processor. Because it's such a powerful machine, it's easy to over
develop the gluten in the flour, which leads to tough cookies.
</P>
<P>
   My solution is to replace a quarter of the flour with
cornstarch, which develops no gluten and, as a bonus, adds a silken
quality. Even so, it's important to process the ingredients gently.
</P>
<P>
   This is also a problem with electric mixers, but rarely with
cookies made by hand. To make the cookies with a mixer or a wooden
spoon, cream the butter and sugar together before adding the dry
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   The baking procedure is determined by the way you like your
cookies. At 375 degrees, the edges brown nicely and the centers
remain pale and tender after about 11 minutes; at 350 degrees,
there will be no browning and the cookies will take a minute or two
longer. Slightly longer baking times will produce crisp cookies.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, check the cookies every minute or so after eight
minutes have passed. Note the timing of the first batch and the
rest will require less attention. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE MOTHER OF ALL BUTTER COOKIES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 30 minutes, or more if cookies are baked in batches &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   { cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   } cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   2 sticks chilled unsalted butter, cut into bits
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   { cup milk, approximately. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Combine flour, cornstarch, sugar
and salt in a food processor, and pulse once or twice. Add butter,
and pulse 10 or 20 times, until butter and flour are well combined.
Add vanilla and egg and pulse 3 or 4 times. Add about half the milk
and pulse 2 or 3 times. Add the remaining milk a little at a time,
pulsing once or twice after each addition, until the dough holds
together in a sticky mass.
</P>
<P>
   2. Remove the dough from the machine to one or more bowls. Make
cookies as described in Step 3, or make any of the variations
below.
</P>
<P>
   3. To make cookies, drop rounded teaspoons of dough (you can
make the cookies larger or smaller, if you like) onto a nonstick
baking sheet, a sheet lined with parchment paper or a lightly
buttered sheet. If you want flat cookies, press the balls down a
bit with your fingers or the back of a spatula or wooden spoon.
Bake 11 minutes, or until the cookies are done as you like them.
Cool on a rack, then store, if necessary, in a covered container. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: about 4 dozen cookies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All Butter Cookies, but in Disguise &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Variations on the flavor of these butter cookies are limitless.
Here are a few suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Butterscotch cookies: Substitute brown sugar for half or more
of the white sugar, or simply add 1 tablespoon of molasses along
with the egg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Citrus cookies: Omit the vanilla, and add 1 tablespoon of
lemon or orange juice and 2 teaspoons grated lemon or orange rind
along with the egg. A couple of tablespoons of poppy seeds can also
be added.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chocolate chip cookies: Stir in about 1 cup of chocolate
chips. (The butterscotch variation is good with chocolate chips.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Other chunky cookies: To the finished batter, add about 1 cup
of M&AMP;M's (or similar candy), roughly chopped walnuts, pecans or
cashews, slivered almonds, raisins, coconut, dried cherries or
cranberries. Or combine any chunky ingredients you like.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ginger cookies: Add 1 tablespoon ground dried ginger to the
dry ingredients. For even better flavor, add \ cup minced
crystallized ginger to the batter by hand (this works well in
addition to or in place of the ground ginger).
</P>
<P>
   _ Spice cookies: Add 1 teaspoon ground cinnamon, \ teaspoon each
ground allspice and ground ginger and 1 pinch ground cloves and
mace or nutmeg to the dry ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Or you can make rolled cookies by freezing the dough for 15
minutes or refrigerating it for at least 1 hour. Working half the
dough at a time, roll it out on a lightly floured surface; the
dough will absorb some flour at first but will soon become less
sticky. Do not add more flour than necessary. Roll about \ inch
thick, and cut with cookie cutters; decorate as you like. Bake as
above, reducing the cooking time to 8 to 10 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
