<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0983 &Cx1f; tth-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPED-SPERRY-CLINTON-S     12-15 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SPERRY-CLINTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEAVES HIS BEST SUPPORTERS VERY LITTLE TO DEFEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SAM SPERRY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The photo comes to mind even now. A young Bill Clinton gazing
adoringly into the face of President John F. Kennedy. Two flawed
men. One a war hero who had risked his life to save his comrades.
The other a draft dodger who deceived his colleagues to cover up
his lust.
</P>
<P>
   One was a leader who others _ including Clinton _ could follow.
The other, now a man, would let his followers down. Two flawed men.
One a president still revered for his accomplishments. The other a
president diminishing before his countrymen's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, as the House Judiciary Committee by rote conducted
its process of approving articles to impeach him, Clinton tried one
more time to say he was sorry. It was a sorry performance. Hollow.
Unconvincing. Arrogant. No wonder the so-called moderates on the
Republican side are shifting toward support for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, when responding to reporter's questions, Clinton
repeated again what few believe: That he did not lie under oath.
No, he would not resign, he said. Hadn't thought of it. From the
Middle East, his obdurate tone left little for opponents of
impeachment to defend.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, as badly as the Republican puritans have behaved,
there is no escaping the fact and the political reality that
Clinton brought all this upon himself and the nation. Moreover, as
the nation is dragged into this Beltway Theater of Politics, the
central character is focused upon himself.
</P>
<P>
   These are the two inescapable facts of this impeachment: that
Clinton is the perpetrator, not the victim, and that his actions
are directed at saving his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   The youth of promise in the photo became the man of the con.
Listening to Clinton Friday, the flim flam became all the more
obvious: ``Mere words cannot fully express the profound remorse I
feel for what our country is going through, and for what members of
both parties in Congress are now forced to deal with,'' he said
just before he left for the Middle East and what might have been a
celebrated venture to salvage the eternal peace process there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what we are going through and what the Congress is
forced to deal with is an entirely unnecessary episode brought on
not by a lust for power and some political purpose but, for _ what
the nuns used to call _ his concupiscence.
</P>
<P>
   People who voted for Clinton, Democrats who supported him, the
women and men who joined his administration have been let down. For
as he squandered his personal stature,
</P>
<P>
   so too did he diminish himself as a moral
</P>
<P>
   figure.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunate are the Democrats for Sen. Joe Lieberman, the man from
Connecticut with the courage to take the Senate floor and in
unforgiving terms rebuke Clinton. Lieberman's condemnation provides
a beacon by which Democratic ships can safely navigate this
political storm.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunate are the Democrats for a citizenry that can separate
the offense of their president from the proper business of the
nation. For those who believe the recent voting in November was not
a referendum on Clinton and his possible impeachment, the fact that
the Dems gained seats offers a portent for Republican policy. Not
since 1822 had the party with a minority in Congress gained seats
during the second term of the president of the same party.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is to be defended, then, it is not on moral grounds
but on political grounds. That is why the outcome in the House
Judiciary Committee was so predictable. And because impeachment by
design is a political process, it is clear that political
considerations govern it, Clinton's moral failings notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The hollowness of Clinton's forced mea culpa Friday rang all the
more so with a statement that he would agree to a motion of
censure.
</P>
<P>
   How good of him. How accommodating. How political. How
self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, this perpetrator now says scold me but don't
impeach me. It is not his call.
</P>
<P>
   This is properly the province of the Congress. And the Congress
is in the hands of people who want Clinton's hide nailed to the
fabric of history as a stained garment, despite Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's misconduct and unethical investigation. Clinton
lied under oath. He betrayed his most prized companions in Hillary
and Chelsea. He violated the loyalty of his colleagues in
government.
</P>
<P>
   He has left those who would help him with little to embrace.
They must defend on grounds of the national interest and the abuse
of the impeachment process itself. But, Bill Clinton the man? He
has left them nothing to defend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1630EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
