<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTMAS-COMMENT-AZR     12-15 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-COMMENT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS? I'D RATHER NOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's that time of year once more when the frogs on TV
beer commercials all wear jingle bells and even mortgage lenders
get all warm and fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   It is the time of the commercial onslaught: a relentless
television tattoo of ads and endless Kmart Christmas carols.
</P>
<P>
   But I no longer get upset by it, for, even though the
hucksterism is themed for the holidays, it is no different from the
hucksterism we see year-round. Anyone who has not learned to tune
out the commercials had better just give up his U.S. citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   No, it is not the commercialism I mind. What bothers me about
the holidays is what people call ``the true spirit of Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   I can hardly bear all the bright faces and good cheer. And every
time I hear someone say, ``Peace on Earth, goodwill to men,'' I
wince.
</P>
<P>
   It is a wonder to me that ``The Little Drummer Boy'' hasn't led
to more serial killings.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the world I know and love; it is some fantasy world
where each of us gets along and no one is miserable.
</P>
<P>
   My complaint isn't just that Christmas posits a fantasy world,
but worse, the fantasy is not, when properly considered, desirable.
</P>
<P>
   I am bedeviled by well-meaning people who seem to think that it
would be a good thing if the Christmas message were heeded
year-round. That what we all need is not just that nations no
longer be at war, but that each of us, personally, would be freed
from our rancor and stress and a dove of universal peace might
descend upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly a peace that passeth understanding; but what passeth
my understanding is why anyone would think this a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   It ignores the basic realities of life on the planet and human
psychology.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, if all rancor and striving were eliminated, we
would not be happy, but instead bored beyond toleration. Perpetual
happiness is the land of the lotus-eaters.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not arguing for war. War is the extreme that we should
at all costs avoid.
</P>
<P>
   But so is peace. Peace is only another extreme. By ``peace,'' I
mean that kind of peace that certain popular religions propagandize
for, wherein our torn, ambivalent, striving hearts are calmed and a
kind of universal torpor descends from the heavens to drug us.
</P>
<P>
   And I respond: ``Peace on Earth, goodwill to men? Over my dead
body!''
</P>
<P>
   We mouth the pieties, talk about universal brotherhood and
loving one's neighbor, but we have not thought this through very
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   If we had, we would never ask for peace and goodwill, except in
small, carefully controlled doses.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, we have never been in any danger of getting our wish.
</P>
<P>
   For perfect happiness is perfect inertia. We would be lumps
staring goofily at the ceiling like heroin addicts, incapable of
rousing ourselves: What for? We would be happy, totally satisfied,
in need of nothing. Hence, no need to get up from the chair. Very
much like Sunday afternoon watching the football games.
</P>
<P>
   This is not my idea of a desirable end.
</P>
<P>
   No, everything good in the world is driven into existence by
dissatisfaction. We feel a lack and we move toward it, and we are
kept in constant, productive motion.
</P>
<P>
   We should strive then, not for that warm holiday feeling which
may be only a little too much brandy in the eggnog, but rather for
that gnawing edgy hollowness in the pit of the stomach that tells
us to keep moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   And when we achieve a momentary respite, a brief piece of
happiness, we can then appreciate it all the more for its rarity.
</P>
<P>
   So, when I see jolly Saint Nick, I want to step up and knock his
hat off. When I hear the carolers outside my window, I want to turn
my stereo speakers out and blast rap music back at them.
</P>
<P>
   For my deity is Eris, the Greek goddess of strife and discord.
All the others are pretenders, and strife alone keeps the world
moving forward.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Christmas celebrates something meant to be
eternal, and therefore stultified. It is a Platonic world.
</P>
<P>
   Give me, instead the world of Heraclitus, where everything is in
constant tumultuous change.
</P>
<P>
   I could enjoy the older, pagan winter holiday, hidden in the
palimpsest of later religious rewriting. That original, with its
trees and lit fires, is a celebration of change, of dissatisfaction
with winter and a longing for the coming spring.
</P>
<P>
   That is something worth celebrating. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Richard Nilsen can be reached at richard.nilsen(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
