<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPERING CHOCOLATE WITH OIL  
 KEEPING THE COATING ON THE KOFFEE  
 WHAT GOES INTO VANILLA EXTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have heard that tempering chocolate can be speeded up by
adding a few drops of oil as you melt it. If so, does it affect the
taste or consistency? Which oil is best?
</P>
<P>
   A. You've heard right: a little bit of oil added to melted
chocolate can often allow you to forgo the exacting process of
tempering it.
</P>
<P>
   Tempering chocolate (melting it, cooling it and gently melting
it again) makes it lustrous and stable as a glossy coating for
candies, fruit, cakes and cookies or to create fanciful decorations
like ruffles, curls and lace.
</P>
<P>
   In tempering, the temperature must be carefully watched. But by
stirring 1 tablespoon of oil or other liquid fat (like melted
clarified butter or vegetable shortening) into every three ounces
of melted chocolate, you can create a mixture like tempered
chocolate, one that is colloquially called ``quick tempered''
chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Quick-tempered chocolate will usually do when a recipe calls for
tempered chocolate. But it is thinner (because of the added fat)
and may not work quite so well for some decorations.
</P>
<P>
   It may also not hold up as reliably if the chocolate is to be
stored. But for home cooks making chocolate to be eaten within
days, it's generally fine.
</P>
<P>
   You can use any type of oil to quick-temper chocolate, but
neutral oils, like canola, vegetable or safflower, won't interfere
with the flavor of the chocolate. On the flip side, butter and nut
oils (like hazelnut or walnut) can add a delightful nuance. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When enrobing a slab of toffee with chocolate, I pour the
cooked toffee onto a jelly roll pan lined with a Silpat (nonstick
silicon) sheet. When it cools, I invert the slab and pour melted
chocolate over it. When the chocolate sets, I break the slab into
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that sometimes the chocolate falls right off the
toffee. I have noticed that when the base cools, it's greasy to the
touch. Could this be the trouble, or is it the Silpat sheet?
</P>
<P>
   A. The culprit is that greasy film. Toffee is made with a
generous amount of butter, and often a small amount seeps out of
the hardened candy, creating a slick, slippery coating. When
chocolate is poured on top, it cannot bond with the toffee's porous
surface. It's similar to putting cookie dough on a greased sheet:
it won't stick.
</P>
<P>
   Many confectioners avoid the problem by blotting the top of the
cooled, hardened toffee with a clean kitchen towel to absorb excess
fat. Then you can pour on the melted chocolate without fear of its
separating. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I recently compared two brands of vanilla extract. Both were
labeled ``pure vanilla extract,'' but one label read ``extractives
of vanilla beans in water, alcohol (35 percent),'' and the other
said, ``water, alcohol (35 percent), vanilla bean extractives and
corn syrup solids.'' The first one was more expensive. What is the
difference between the more expensive and the less expensive brand?
</P>
<P>
   A. According to guidelines that have been established by the
Food and Drug Administration, pure vanilla extract must be made
from vanilla beans and alcohol. A small percentage of natural
flavorings, like corn syrup solids, may be added, but artificial
flavorings, like vanillin, are forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   As you would guess, less expensive brands tend to use the
minimum required quantity of costly vanilla beans, then heighten
the flavor with corn syrup. Makers of high-quality, premium brands
of vanilla extract, however, pride themselves on using more vanilla
beans than are actually demanded by law, thus creating a more
richly perfumed extract.
</P>
<P>
   But despite those differences, culinary professionals disagree
about whether expensive vanilla extracts are worth the money and
also whether their sweet scent translates into more flavor in the
final product. For this, there is no right answer, only a matter of
taste.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
