<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gourmet Garage in New York has cloned itself yet again. A fourth
market has just opened at 117 Seventh Avenue South (Christopher
Street), adding Greenwich Village to locations in SoHo, the Upper
West Side and the Upper East Side in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The chain has its no-frills formula down pat, with banks of
produce, cases filled with cheeses, an olive bar and shelves
stacked with packaged foods, some bearing the chain's own label,
like the olive oils and potato chips.
</P>
<P>
   What is new here, and will soon be added in the other stores, is
a small but serious fresh meat and fish department, with a butcher
and a fishmonger actually on duty. The prepared-food department is
the largest of any Gourmet Garage and includes fresh chickens
bronzing on a rotisserie. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The aroma of roasting chestnuts is inescapable in midtown
Manhattan these days, but there are better ways to sample that
seasonal flavor. The nutty-tasting fresh chestnut pasta that
Raffetto's, 144 West Houston Street (Sullivan Street), makes at
this time every year is worth buying to sauce with pancetta and
cream or with wild mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   It's $3.25 a pound, cut to the width you choose, and will be
available through the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnuts segue easily from savory to sweet. La Maison du
Chocolat, 1080 Madison Avenue (78th Street), is an excellent source
for succulent candied chestnuts. These marrons glaces are not
overwhelmed by sugar and don't crumble or fall apart like so many
others.
</P>
<P>
   They are $60 a pound (about 18 plump chestnuts wrapped in gold
foil) and will be available through January. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chasing down a Christmas goose in New York is getting easier.
The Quattro Farms stand, amid the bright pots of poinsettias that
fill the north end of the Union Square Greenmarket now, is taking
orders for its beautifully plump geese, $3.35 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   The birds weigh 9 to 15 pounds; because the meat is so rich, the
smallest bird will feed six to eight people. Roasting a goose is
also an Eastern European Hanukkah tradition, right down to frying
the latkes in the fat, and there's still time to buy one for a
final feast on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Quattro Farms is regularly at the Greenmarket every Saturday,
but during the holidays, the schedule will be Wednesday, Dec. 23
and Dec. 30 (and not on Saturday, Dec. 26 and Jan. 2). Geese can be
ordered through Dec. 21 for pickup at the Dec. 23 market by calling
(914) 635-8202 or (914) 635-2018.
</P>
<P>
   The farm also has a store on Route 44 off the Taconic State
Parkway in Pleasant Valley, N.Y. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
