<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORED? TRY UPGRADING THE PRINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Want more from your computer? &QL; 
PHOENIX - You could upgrade by adding more RAM, a bigger hard drive
or, well, you know the drill.
</P>
<P>
   But here's something you might not have considered: Get yourself
a printer! Already have one? Then get a better one!
</P>
<P>
   Back when I first started using computers, I thought about
printers the same way I once thought about microwave ovens: Yes,
they'd be nice to have, but who really needs one?
</P>
<P>
   Now, of course, you can't buy a house or rent an apartment
without finding a microwave in the kitchen. And just as microwaves
have become indispensable, so, too, have printers become a
necessary piece of the personal computing puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   And over the past year or so, printer makers and software
companies have worked hard to push the utility of color inkjet
printers well beyond the stage of spitting out nasty letters to the
landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Want proof? Look no further than some of the latest software
titles available in the stores.
</P>
<P>
   Palladium Interactive, for example, offers four new titles:
``Forever Fun Works!,'' ``Tattoo Time,'' ``Paper Play Studio'' and
``Dino Sticker Time.''
</P>
<P>
   The programs, which range in price from about $19 to $29,
illustrate a new wave of software that takes advantage of today's
printers. The titles allow kids to create their own stickers,
temporary tattoos, stationery, certificates, bookmarks _ the list
is endless.
</P>
<P>
   I tried ``Dino Sticker Time'' and found it well worth the $19.99
price tag. It loads easily, and comes with a supply of blank
Avery-brand stickers. The interface was simple enough for my
4-year-old son to use, and the Jurassic Park-style soundtrack kept
him entertained while he created his very own stickers (which he
then put all over the walls).
</P>
<P>
   Adults can get in on the fun, too. Printer maker Hewlett-Packard
recently offered a list of ways to use their new color inkjet
printers. The list included:
</P>
<P>
   - Gift bags (Create graphic, print it out and glue to outside of
any bag.)
</P>
<P>
   - Gift boxes (Same as above, but glue to outside of any box.)
</P>
<P>
   - Garden tags (Create custom tag for flowers, veggies or herbs,
print out and glue to Popsicle stick.)
</P>
<P>
   - Family recipe book (Create recipe-card size entries, complete
with images and instructions, then have local print shop bind it or
get a photo album and insert recipes where you would otherwise put
photos.)
</P>
<P>
   - Custom greeting cards
</P>
<P>
   - Personalized placemats for holiday dinners or other special
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   - Custom calendars
</P>
<P>
   - Custom T-shirts or aprons (Create image and print on T-shirt
transfers available in office-supply or computer stores.)
</P>
<P>
   - Holiday ornaments (Create and print image, then fold and glue
into desired shape.)
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Need more ideas and specific instructions? Check out ``The Color
Printer Idea Book'' by Kay Hall, published recently by No Starch
Press. The $19.95 book offers complete instructions and
illustrations covering some 40 projects all made possible with an
inkjet printer.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the book help you through the projects, but it
also offers tips that will help you through anything else you do
with your printer. For example, it teaches you how to avoid the
``computer-generated'' look when you create things, how to get the
best images from your printer, how to use special effects and lots
more.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? Today's software titles also include some fairly
fancy stuff _ programs with powerful capabilities that once were
available only to professionals or those interested in shelling out
$300 to $600 for a single title, such as Adobe's PhotoShop.
</P>
<P>
   Kai's ``Photo Soap,'' Microsoft's ``Picture It'' and other
similar titles give the user the ability to import images (either
from a scanner or directly from a digital camera), clean them up
(such as removing that annoying ``red eye''), crop them, add
backgrounds, special effects or text, and then print them out.
</P>
<P>
   Other programs, such as Broderbund's ``Print Shop 5.0'' or
Palladium's ``Ultimate Scrapbook Creator,'' provide the user with
power to create and print a wide variety of products, ranging from
professional-quality newsletters to customized photo pages you can
insert into photo albums or have bound together.
</P>
<P>
   We've come a long way since the days of the dot matrix printers.
Inkjets have opened doors for home and small-office computer users,
doors that were once too expensive to open or just didn't exist
just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   All fired up to go get a new printer? Great! But do a little bit
of research first. Computer magazines are full of printer
information and reviews. Got Web access? Then visit Yahoo! at
www.yahoo.com and search for printer information. Or, check out
``Family PC'' magazine's printer page at
205.181.113.18/familypc/content/970516/fth w/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   In general, you will get the best results from name-brand
printers, such as Epson, Hewlett-Packard or Lexmark.
</P>
<P>
   As with computers, you will get what you pay for. Some inkjets
are available for about $100. But the nice color units, usually
called ``photo-quality'' printers, will cost $300 to $400.
</P>
<P>
   If you can swing the cost of a photo-quality color inkjet
printer, and if you follow the instructions to get top-quality
prints, you will be amazed by the results. I've actually framed
some prints and have them displayed at home!
</P>
<P>
   When looking for a printer, pay attention to things like ``PPM''
and ``resolution.'' PPM, or pages per minute, tells you how fast _
or slow _ the printer will work. Resolution tells you how fine a
print you will get _ the higher the resolution numbers, the more
photolike your prints will appear.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the other costs involved with printers _ ink
and paper.
</P>
<P>
   The photo-quality printers produce great prints, but they tend
to really suck up the ink. And color ink cartridges can run as much
as $25 or $30 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Another tricky aspect of printers is paper. There's a lot of
generic printer paper out there that will work well if you just
print black-and-white letters. But to get the best-quality color
production, your printer might require a special paper, usually
something made by the printer maker.
</P>
<P>
   My Epson Stylus Photo printer has this requirement. I've tried
alternative glossy papers, but none work as well as the
photo-quality paper produced by Epson. Don't ask me how they do it!
But buyer beware!
</P>
<P>
   So, if you're looking to get more use out of your computer or if
you just want to have some fun, go get a new printer! &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1638EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PASTRY-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     12-15 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTRY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BAKING BIBLE, INSTALLMENT NO. 2 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Surrender'' is the word that comes to mind when I think of
Rose Levy Beranbaum's latest book, ``The Pie and Pastry Bible''
(Scribner, $35). Because that is what you must do in order to
appreciate this book.
</P>
<P>
   You do not pick it up and whip together a recipe, casually
adjusting it to the ingredients you have on hand. You do not begin
a recipe after work for dinner that night. No, you surrender to the
master, and you set aside a day to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beranbaum may be the most meticulous cook who ever lived. To
her, baking is not a free-form, spiritual act. It (italics)is(end
italics) about building rocket ships. Quantities are weighed to the
hundredth of an ounce, temperatures set to the degree, sizes
measured to the quarter inch.
</P>
<P>
   But what separates her from other perfectionists is that she not
only tells you in intricate detail how to make something, but also
tells why you take such pains. After several pages on pastry dough,
I understood why adding vinegar relaxes dough without its losing
flakiness, how baking powder aerates it and how butter keeps flour
from absorbing too much water and making it tough.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to following the instructions, I carefully weighed
my ingredients. I was reluctant to put a third of the cubed butter
and the dry ingredients in the freezer and the rest of the cubed
butter in the refrigerator for 30 minutes before even beginning the
recipe. It seemed to be taking home-baking a step too far.
</P>
<P>
   But once I had all the ingredients in the food processor and
pulsed it exactly six times, as Ms. Beranbaum instructed, what
formed was the lightest, most consistent pastry dough I have ever
felt.
</P>
<P>
   By the second time I made the pastry dough, it went much more
quickly. I remembered which portion of butter went in the freezer
and which went in the refrigerator, so I didn't have constantly to
refer to the instructions. And I had a better understanding about
how the small decisions you make when baking _ like chilling the
ingredients to counteract the heat produced by a food processor _
can have a profound effect on the results. Sure, baking pastry is
much about touch and feel, but as this book makes clear, there is
also chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   I made two very different desserts with that pastry. First, an
orange curd tart with chocolate meringue. The orange curd was
smooth and intense, the meringue fluffy and light, but the flavors
and textures fought one another. A pumpkin pie, however, was a
sensation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Beranbaum refined it by lining the pastry with crushed
gingersnaps and pecans, and filling it with a custard so light and
creamy it defied gravity.
</P>
<P>
   I was anxious to make her cream cheese pastry dough, which, she
writes, took her several years and more than 50 attempts to
perfect. It is as soft and velvety as old cotton sheets. In an
apple galette, the pastry is rolled into a 16-inch disk, lined with
paper-thin slices of tart apple and sugar, and baked free-form.
It's as thin as pizza and has more flavor than an apple pie five
times as thick.
</P>
<P>
   A scone dough took all of 10 minutes to assemble and baked into
tender triangles dotted with poppy seeds and lemon zest. In the
``Understanding'' section after the recipe, Ms. Beranbaum lays out
the various protein contents in brands of all-purpose flour:
Hecker's, Gold Medal and King Arthur. Hecker's, with its moderate
protein level, she says, is perfect for scones: you get both
tenderness and flakiness.
</P>
<P>
   It is this kind of detail _ the ``Understanding'' sections that
follow each recipe, the charts with both weights and measures, the
kitchen equipment guide _ that elevates this book above most others
on baking.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even perfectionists have occasional lapses: Muscadet
is listed as an alternative to dolce, spatlese riesling and
Sauternes in a recipe for an apple weincreme chiffon tart. Muscat
might provide a similar sweetness, but certainly not Muscadet.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I have come to feel dependent on the book. When I want
to make a classic pastry and I want it to be nothing less than
perfect, I will know the one place to go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   APPLE GALETTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Pie and Pastry Bible'' by Rose Levy
Beranbaum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours, plus 1{ hours chilling time &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-third cups plus 4 teaspoons pastry flour
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons ice water
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   4 Granny Smith apples, peeled, cored and sliced [ inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons milk, approximately
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup apricot preserves
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon apricot eau de vie or Calvados. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut 8 tablespoons of the butter into }-inch cubes. Wrap in
plastic wrap and freeze 30 minutes. Place flour and salt in a large
freezer bag, and freeze for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place flour mixture in a food processor, and process for a
few seconds to combine. Cut the cream cheese into 3 or 4 pieces,
and add to flour. Process 20 seconds. Add frozen butter, and pulse
until none of the butter is larger than a pea. Add water and
vinegar, and pulse until butter is the size of small peas. The
mixture will not hold together.
</P>
<P>
   3. Spoon mixture into freezer bag. Knead in the bag until it
holds together in once piece and feels slightly stretchy. Remove
from bag, wrap in plastic wrap, flatten into a disk and refrigerate
at least 45 minutes, preferably overnight.
</P>
<P>
   4. When ready to bake, preheat the oven to 400 degrees and set
rack on lowest shelf. Place the dough between two large sheets of
lightly floured plastic wrap. Roll out to [ inch thick and large
enough to cut a 16-inch circle. Use a cardboard template to cut the
circle. Transfer to a 12- to 14-inch round steel pizza pan or an
inverted baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   5. Sprinkle apple slices with lemon juice. Arrange slices on the
dough, cored sides facing toward the center, overlapping in
concentric circles, starting from the outer edge of the pan. Fold
the border of dough over the apples' edge, pleating it. Brush rim
with milk. Sprinkle apples and rim with sugar. Dot apples with
remaining butter, and bake 40 minutes, or until apples are tender
when pierced and dough is crisp. Cool tart on the pan on a rack
until warm.
</P>
<P>
   6. While it cools, in a saucepan over medium-low heat, heat the
apricot preserves until boiling, and strain them. Stir in the
liquor, and brush this glaze onto the apples.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
