<HEADLINE>
GAYS URGE BOYCOTT OF UNITED AIRLINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gay-rights advocates are calling for a
nationwide boycott of United Airlines until the carrier agrees to
drop its opposition to San Francisco's domestic partners ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This boycott is to send a message to United Airlines that
irresponsible corporate behavior cannot and will not be tolerated
by fair-minded citizens across this country,'' said David Smith,
senior strategist for the Washington, D.C.-based Human Rights
Campaign, the largest gay rights organization in the country.
</P>
<P>
   United, the largest airline operating at the San Francisco
International Airport, contends the city does not have the
authority to regulate air carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The city ordinance, which took effect June 1, 1997, requires
companies doing business with the city to provide the same benefits
to workers with unmarried partners as they give to married
employees. More than 1,700 companies have extended equal benefits
to workers with domestic partners.
</P>
<P>
   United joined a federal lawsuit filed by the Air Transport
Association _ the trade group for the nation's biggest airlines _
seeking to be exempt from the ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The American Center for Law and Justice, a conservative
organization linked to the Rev. Pat Robertson, filed a second
lawsuit seeking to overturn the law, citing moral opposition to
domestic partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines contend that only the federal government, not a
local jurisdiction, can force such a requirement on their industry.
</P>
<P>
   In April, U.S. District Judge Claudia Wilken issued a complex
opinion on the airlines' lawsuit that sided with the city on some
provisions and the airlines on others. For example, she said
federal law exempts air carriers from the health and pension
provisions of the equal benefits ordinance.
</P>
<P>
   The city, however, contends the airlines still must provide
other benefits such as bereavement and family medical leave,
discounts and free flights provided to married employees.
</P>
<P>
   Wilken still has several issues on which to rule. Both sides
expect the case to be appealed.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Tom Ammiano said he hoped the proposed boycott and
other market forces would compel the air carriers to provide
benefits to unmarried partners.
</P>
<P>
   United issued a news release Tuesday denouncing the boycott,
saying the company only joined the lawsuit to prevent the city from
following through on a threat to sever a lease United holds at the
airport for a maintenance shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this lease, United's operations at SFO would be
significantly disrupted, adversely affecting the 60,000 passengers
the airline carries to and from the Bay area each day and the
company's 18,000 Bay area employees,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, the statement said, ``is based on one essential
point: that a local government cannot regulate a national
industry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
