<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EVEN WITHOUT THE GREENHOUSE: TERRIBLE DROUGHTS AHEAD
 &HT;    450 words
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The costly ``Dust Bowl'' drought of the 1930s was
little more than a bad dry spell, compared to the kind of weather
that lies ahead, government scientists warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It has happened before.
</P>
<P>
   Records stored by nature in the bottom of lakes and the growth
rings of ancient trees show that in the late 1300s and again in the
late 1500s, withering ``megadroughts'' lasting at least 25 years
descended on western North America, said National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration climatologists Connie A. Woodhouse and
Jonathan T. Overpeck.
</P>
<P>
   Sand dunes rolled across much of the Great Plains _ and can be
found beneath now-fertile topsoil in some areas _ and Sierra Nevada
mountain lakes that today provide water for much of California
dried up completely.
</P>
<P>
   Though computer models that attempt to project ``greenhouse
effect'' climate changes suggest one result of a hotter Earth will
be more arid conditions to the U.S. Midwest, the two scientists
pointed out during an interview that droughts 400 and 600 years ago
had nothing to do with human-induced global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing, transportation, electric power generation and
other fuel-burning activities that pump tons of extra carbon
dioxide into today's atmosphere obviously weren't happening back
then.
</P>
<P>
   The droughts centuries ago occurred because of natural climate
variations and therefore will undoubtedly occur again, the
scientists said.
</P>
<P>
   But, Overpeck noted, the natural records provide troubling
evidence that Earth's climate responds abruptly to changing
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These abrupt shifts appear more likely when the climate is
changing,'' he said. ``As the Earth warms in the future, we could
get sudden, surprising shifts.''
</P>
<P>
   The two ``megadroughts'' were discovered in growth rings from
old trees, including post oaks in Arkansas and northern Texas and
ponderosa pines in California, Woodhouse said. During droughts,
trees grow more slowly, and the rings are narrower.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, lake sediments show corresponding shifts in the
kind of diatoms _ microscopic plants _ that lived in the lakes.
With less rainfall, lakes became more saline, and the changed
conditions caused diatoms that thrive on saltier water to increase,
while freshwater plants declined.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have tracked similar, though less dramatic, changes
in aquatic plant life in response to modern fluctuations in
rainfall, Woodhouse said.
</P>
<P>
   Overpeck is head of NOAA's paleoclimatology program, and
Woodhouse is a University of Colorado scientist working at NOAA's
National Geophysical Data Center in Boulder. Their report was
published in the Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
