<HEADLINE>
A WORLD OF PREMIUM CHOCOLATES AT THE CLICK OF A MOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By S.A. BELZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   High-quality chocolate _ good for last-minute gifts or
self-indulgence _ has found a richly deserved, tantalizing place in
the international bazaar of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Connoisseurs and chocaholics won't go away disappointed at
chocolatepicure.com. The site represents chocolate makers from
France, Italy, Belgium, Britain and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   They were chosen, Sheri Syler Adams, the president of the
company, writes by e-mail, for the high percentage of cocoa (which
is what makes chocolate taste like chocolate) in their wares, as
well as the cocoa butter and natural vanilla. Richard Donnelly's
bittersweet chocolate bar, made in California, for instance, is 67
to 70 percent cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   Donnelly, who studied his craft in France and Belgium, wraps his
bars in gold foil and handmade papers. They are sold in assortments
(6 1.75-ounce bars for $30, 10 1-ounce bars, $35.50, both with
shipping).
</P>
<P>
   An assortment ordered from the Web site _ it included dark
chocolate (bittersweet, five-spice and almond) and milk chocolate
(coconut, cappuccino and hazelnut almond toffee) _ arrived in New
York three days later.
</P>
<P>
   The Donnelly 7.5-ounce gift box ($38.50, with shipping) is an
appealing assortment of 20 to 24 truffles and other bonbons.
</P>
<P>
   Also available are chocolates from Wittamer of Brussels, a top
Belgian chocolate maker (a 1.65-pound box of mixed chocolates, no
alcohol in the centers, $97.50, shipping included; three to seven
days from Belgium), and Valrhona, the pride of France (for
instance, four 3.5-ounce Le Noir Amer dark bittersweet chocolate
bars, 71 percent cocoa, $22.25, with shipping).
</P>
<P>
   The site offers reading matter and recipes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Fran's Chocolates in Seattle (www.franschocolates.com) is well
worth a virtual visit. Fran Bigelow started with one shop in 1982
and now has three. Her chocolates are handmade and hand wrapped,
using Belgian Callebaut and Venezuelan chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   Among the containers in which she packs her chocolate are washi
paper boxes, handmade and screen printed. They were modeled on
Japanese tea boxes by a Northwest artist, and she uses them for
dark-chocolate truffles ($48 for 12 ounces, $60 for 16 ounces, plus
shipping).
</P>
<P>
   Fran's signature box, containing her truffle and chocolate-cream
favorites, comes in three sizes, from 7 ounces (14 pieces, $15) to
1 pound 2 ounces (36 pieces, $34); shipping is extra. But Fran's
Gold Bars are her big seller. A gift package of six bars with
almonds or macadamia nuts, for instance, is $10.50, plus shipping.
</P>
<P>
   To arrive in New York in time for Christmas, orders have to be
placed in the next day or so.
</P>
<P>
   Across the country in Tallahassee, Fla., is Pierre Vivier, who
began making chocolates in the early 1960s as an apprentice in
France to Maurice Jouvenal, a second-generation chocolatier
himself. Vivier went to Florida in 1974 and opened a French
restaurant and bakery soon after.
</P>
<P>
   On his Web site (www.pvchocolates.com), he writes, ``After 15
very successful years, I sold the restaurant, to pursue what I love
the most, making fine chocolates.''
</P>
<P>
   Vivier makes all his chocolate pieces himself by hand. He uses
top-grade imported chocolate like Valrhona and Callebaut, along
with cream and butter. The fillings include imported sour cherries
in alcohol: Cointreau, Cognac, amaretto and rum. Vivier sells his
chocolates in assortment boxes of 7 ounces for $15.95 and 14 ounces
for $29.95 (shipping extra). A box ordered from the site took a
week to arrive in New York. Vivier writes that Dec. 21 will be the
last day he can ship orders for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   While not strictly a Web operation (orders have to be phoned
in), Flyer candy bars, a far cry from the movie refreshment counter
variety, have a site (www.800candybar.com) to browse. The seeker
after chocolate can find descriptions of the Flyer bars, which are
made from Swiss chocolate, color-wrapped with a gold plane logo.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the varieties contain Flyer caramel, made, the company
says, ``the old-fashioned way, by caramelizing sugar with fresh
butter and heavy dairy cream.'' Boxes of 12 are $22 or $27,
depending on weight, plus $7.50 for shipping. Oh, yes, the numbers
are (800) 226-3922 and (877) 226-3922: the repeated theme,
``226-3922,'' spells ``candy ba(r).''
</P>
<P>
   Orders placed until early next week should arrive before
Christmas. For an urgent gift or treat need, it must be said that
Flyer bars can also be bought at Gourmet Garage, Dean &AMP; DeLuca and
Butterfield Market. (The folks at the toll-free numbers will
provide information on shops in other localities.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
