<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LORD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE LORD WILL GATHER ME IN': A SECULAR JEW FEEDS A HUNGER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The title of this very personal story of spiritual quest by
David Klinghoffer comes, we learn by reading his epigraph, from
Psalm 27: ``Should my father and mother abandon me, the Lord will
gather me in.'' Well, Klinghoffer's parents, who brought him up in
an affluent Reform Jewish household in Southern California,
certainly did not abandon him. But Klinghoffer, 33 and a senior
editor at the National Review magazine, was adopted at birth, so in
a way he was abandoned by his biological father and mother. And
when he says that the Lord gathered him in, he means that he sees
in the pattern of his life a plan for him to find meaning and
fulfillment in the strict and demanding practice of Orthodox
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   One can be skeptical that Klinghoffer's personal religious
journey was part of a divine plan and still find ``The Lord Will
Gather Me In'' rewarding. It recounts a transformation from a
wisecracking California boy born to an unknown Swedish immigrant
into an Orthodox New York Jew who wears fringes on his
undergarments (symbolic of the 613 biblical commandments) and a
skullcap, and whose most intense joy is to study Torah, the
documents and laws that form the basis of Jewish practice and
belief.
</P>
<P>
   Klinghoffer's account of this rebirth as a Jew is barbed at
times, poignant at others; it is modest in its religious learning,
but thoughtful and informed in those few places where Klinghoffer
does tackle theological questions. His brief disquisition on
``family purity,'' the Orthodox practice whereby spouses maintain
conjugal separation during the wife's menstruation, is a model of
clarity. Here and there Klinghoffer's text takes on an annoyed,
uncharitable, unkindly tone, especially when he speaks of the
varieties of the Jewish experience that he does not find authentic.
But he writes with integrity and insight, making clear and tough
demands on himself, and his story of struggle with God and identity
is moving.
</P>
<P>
   Klinghoffer did not come to his Jewish identity easily. He knew
that his birth mother was not Jewish and that technically that made
him a Gentile. (In his final chapters, he describes how he
discovered the identities of his birth parents and established a
warm relationship with his biological mother.)
</P>
<P>
   His life for years was a briar patch of contradictions. For
reasons too complicated to explain here but that are fully detailed
by Klinghoffer, he went through three separate conversion
ceremonies, including three symbolic circumcisions. Even as he
became absorbed by his Jewishness, he formed a serious attachment
to a young Roman Catholic woman who pleaded with him to accept
Jesus, leading an anguished and confused Klinghoffer to open
himself up to some sign of guidance from the Saviour. When no such
sign came, he took his first major step toward strict Jewish
observance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would guess,'' he writes, ``that not many Jews have tried to
strike up a conversation with Jesus one night and a few nights
later commenced observing the Jewish Sabbath for the first time in
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on Klinghoffer writes rather bitterly of the spiritual
thinness of the Reform Judaism in which he was reared, contrasting,
for example, the simple dignity of an Orthodox bar mitzvah with the
garish and vulgar displays he knew among the Reform Jews of
Southern California. He speaks disparagingly of the decision, made
by Conservative Jewry in 1950, to allow Jews to drive to the
synagogue on the Sabbath, something prohibited by the Orthodox.
Conservative observance, as a result, ``died by a hundred small
cuts,'' Klinghoffer writes in disapproval of what he sees as this
assimilationist backsliding.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt many Conservative Jews (including this critic) will
want to argue with much of this. Klinghoffer's complaint about
vulgarity really has to do with the shallow materialism of the
nouveau riche, not with a variety of Jewish practice. Vulgar
displays of conspicuous consumption have occurred among the
Orthodox as well as the Reform. And driving on the Sabbath might
have done more to save Jewish observance than inflict a death of a
hundred cuts. Suburban Jews are more likely to give up observance
altogether than to move back to the city so they can be within
walking distance of a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   Plainly, there are a lot of Jews who do not inspire
Klinghoffer's admiration, and, in some instances, his criticism is
well directed. (He writes, for example, of Orthodox groups whose
lack of appreciation for ``the privilege of living in America'' is
shown by their habit of holding their national conventions on
Thanksgiving.) But Klinghoffer is eloquent and stubborn as he makes
his case for orthodoxy as the only authentic Jewish practice and
identity. For him, true Judaism must be rooted in knowing Torah,
observing the commandments and believing above all that they come
from God.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that for many Jews living in America more freely
and more openly than Jews have ever lived in the Diaspora before,
Judaism has become an amalgam of things not necessarily dependent
on a belief in God. Judaism is a historical attachment; it is a set
of values, a music and a poetry, a collection of fables and
commentaries that make up a magnificently rich literature on
virtually every human situation.
</P>
<P>
   Not least, Jewish attachment is an unwillingness to forsake an
identity for which ancestors were persecuted and murdered. For many
Jews today, observance of rituals and holidays is less a matter of
divine commandment than it is an act of association, something that
gives form to their sense of belonging to a people and to a
history.
</P>
<P>
   One wonders exactly where these people stand in Klinghoffer's
Orthodox universe.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE LORD WILL GATHER ME IN
</P>
<P>
   My Journey to Jewish Orthodoxy
</P>
<P>
   By David Klinghoffer
</P>
<P>
   262 pages. Free Press. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
