A1169 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PETE-WILSON-HNS &LR;      12-15 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PETE-WILSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETE WILSON: A ONCE AND FUTURE PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ Gov. Pete Wilson sits at a long table in
the Ronald Reagan Conference Room just outside his private office,
thinking about the former two-term California governor who would
become president.
</P>
<P>
   In less than a month, Wilson will be renting space in Reagan's
Century City office. He is beginning what likely will be a long
year of dialing for dollars and attempting to find a voice among
the field of potential Republican presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think it's interesting,'' said Wilson, a portrait of
Reagan hanging behind him. ``I have identically the same approval
rating as Ronald Reagan when he left the office of governor. And I
think those who approved of him did so because they thought he
fought for principle. That's what I've tried to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Californians may feel the same way they did about an outgoing
Reagan as they do the departing Wilson, but repeating Reagan's
later success on the presidential campaign trail is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   If he decides to run, Wilson faces expensive, grueling campaigns
in states that hardly know him, and rivals that could include Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, former Vice President Dan Quayle, millionaire
publisher Steve Forbes, former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and
former vice presidential nominee Jack Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also leaves the state with a Republican Party weakened by
recent elections. Lt. Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, roundly defeated
Republican Dan Lungren in the Nov. 3 election to succeed Wilson,
who was barred by law from seeking a third term. (Reagan, too, was
succeeded by a Democrat _ Jerry Brown _ and the Democrats were as
strong as ever in the Legislature.)
</P>
<P>
   Wilson takes no blame for the spectacular, 20-point defeat of
Lungren, although Wilson did spend eight years antagonizing trade
unions and other interests that worked tirelessly against Lungren.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's embarrassing and brief run for president in 1995 _ a
move Wilson said he regretted _ and his own national party could
haunt him. Even though voters in November appeared to pick
moderate, pragmatic candidates, Wilson faces a Republican primary
system that favors conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem essentially for Pete is fundamental,'' said
Democratic strategist Bill Carrick. ``The Republican Party is more
conservative at its base than he is, by a long shot. ... He's just
a square peg in a round hole in the Republican primary process.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, 65, has not announced he is a candidate for president in
2000. Most of the political establishment expects the former U.S.
senator to enter the race, provided he can raise at least $15
million in 1999 and build his name recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson gave his potential campaign a boost this year, when he
signed a law moving California's presidential primary to March,
which will force candidates to campaign simultaneously in New York,
New Jersey and California. That can help Wilson, who already has an
organization and high name recognition here.
</P>
<P>
   After Wilson moves out of Sacramento and into his rented Century
City office, he plans to run a nonprofit advocacy group, the Bear
Flag Forum, which he recently established to promote his
educational and policy agendas. He may write a book or a newspaper
column.
</P>
<P>
   But fund-raising will undoubtedly be his most important task.
Wilson has not opened a federal presidential account or formed a
political action committee to accept donations, as have Forbes,
Quayle, Alexander, Kemp and others.
</P>
<P>
   But if and when Wilson does start accepting donations, he has a
rich donor list from 32 years in politics, but he must convince
them and hundreds of Republicans nationwide that he is a viable
national candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he knows it's going to be difficult,'' Republican
strategist Ken Khachigian said, ``and it's going to be even more
difficult because he's not a sitting governor. There are going to
be a lot of people who are not going to be as responsive as they
would have been. I think he'll find out in the first 90 days of
1999 if it's going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
