<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ornamental cookies give tree some class
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It never occurred to me to be sensitive about my
tradition of tacky Christmas trees. A misshapen pine or cedar from
the woods was as dear to my heart as the finest, most symmetrical
spruce imported from New England and sold at great price. And I
scorned electric lights and store-bought ornaments _ this to the
consternation of the children in the family who love bubbly,
on-and-off lights and a lot of sprayed-on snow.
</P>
<P>
   They decided to be tolerant after many years, telling one
another wisely that a taste for tacky Christmas trees was just one
of my foibles and easy to forgive. Loving them, I made a few
concessions, putting up the tree earlier than I like and leaving
off paper chains made from the colored pages in the Sears catalog.
</P>
<P>
   This year I have been vindicated. I gave the children the
strings
</P>
</TEXT>
