   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   AOL-LATINAM _ In a deal aimed at greatly boosting its Latin
American presence, AOL joins forces with a big media conglomerate
to expand its online and Internet services into Argentina, Brazil
and Mexico and other Latin American markets. (Katz/Kannell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BELLSOUTH-Q&AMP;A _ ATLANTA _ Q&AMP;A with Mark Feidler, president of
BellSouth's wireless division. What about the coverage controversy?
Is there room in the market for Sprint? What's happening to
wireless next? How does BellSouth compete against Nextel (whose
phone has more features) or AT&AMP;T (a company with national
coverage)? (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TECH-PATENTS _ ATLANTA _ A woman struggling to change a flat
tire on her car along the expressway sparked an idea for Ricky
Vann. ``Wouldn't it be nice if she could just push a button to lift
the car?'' He's got U.S. patent No. 5813661. (Tharpe, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-RADIODEAL _ ATLANTA _ 99x, Atlanta's alternative radio
station, has a promotion deal with totale.com, a Web music
retailer. Users can get a free CD if they order it from the 99x Web
page. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VENTURE-CAPITAL _ A roundup of the ways high-tech start-ups get
their money. (Clothier, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ Consultant Ted Fisher is looking for ``a
big mule,'' and Georgia Gov.-elect Roy Barnes said he'd consider
helping in the search. Translation: With the encouragement of the
Common Services Committee of the Atlanta Year 2000 Users Group,
Fisher and public relations man George Goodwim are scouting for
someone to form a volunteer project to help co-ordinate the Y2K
activities of government, business, and the general population.
(Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BEAZERHOMES _ Profile of Beazer Homes. It has no intention of
getting caught in a downturn. Just in case one happens next year,
the Atlanta-based builder is fine tuning a strategy that includes
gaining market share through acquisition; taking short-term options
on land rather than risking ownership; exploring niche markets;
avoiding duplications of competitors' products; and rewarding
employees for saving money internally. That sits well with analysts
such as David Dwyer of Salomon Smith Barney. He believes that
consolidations will overcome the effects of a 1999 slowdown,
assuming market fundamentals like interest rates and inventories
stay low and buyer commitments stay high. Beazer Homes' share price
has jumped nearly 50 percent during the past six weeks. When
stockholders receive their 1998 annual reports within the next few
days. (Harte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Over 25 years _ which includes the Grinch years of
1973-74, 1981, 1987 and others _ returns have averaged 13.1
percent. Take it back through 1926, and the record shows that
stocks will return 11 percent a year. The lesson: Santa Claus is
fun, but Wall Street is real. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
