<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1190 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-DONATIONS16-COX     12-15 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-DONATIONS16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For some, airline food never tasted so good
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ She's doing what couldn't be done by flashy
advertising campaigns or famous chef-consultants. Susan Powell is
making airline food look good.
</P>
<P>
   It all started as a dream four years ago when Powell, 41, an
Atlanta flight attendant for Delta Air Lines, realized the airline
was throwing away huge amounts of food left over from in-flight
snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, thanks to her persistence, Delta flight attendants
voluntarily collect a ton of packaged airline food a week for the
Atlanta Food Bank. And thousands of pounds more of muffins,
crackers, chips, cereal and peanuts go to food banks in 12 other
Delta cities. Other airlines, such as American and Continental, are
trying similar giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stuff we're getting is healthy,'' says Jane
Hayden, associate project director for Atlanta's Table, a project
of the Atlanta Food Bank, which collects and distributes donated
food to the city's low-flying poor and homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peanuts are good for you and the muffins are low-fat. And the
cereal, the way it's designed is perfect. Just take off the top and
pour in milk.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, says Hayden, the Delta snacks _ maybe sniffed at by
passengers _ find their way into bag lunches at the Atlanta Union
Mission.
</P>
<P>
   The idea wasn't Powell's. But she's the one who gave it wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flight attendants have been talking for years about what a
shame it is we throw away so much food,'' says Powell, who has been
with Delta since 1979. ``But Delta was reluctant to give the food
away because the company was worried about liability.''
</P>
<P>
   One day, between flights, Powell was watching CNN and saw that
President Bill Clinton had signed a federal good Samaritan law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It clicked in my head,'' she says. ``The next day I approached
Delta executives again with the proposal.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives signed off. So did the Delta legal department. Powell
spearheaded a pilot program in Atlanta, which began in April 1997.
Six months later, the airline expanded the program to 12 other
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Powell continues to lead Delta's program, trying to enlist all
of the airline's 19,000 flight attendants in the cause.
</P>
<P>
   During National Food Bank week in October, she organized pep
rallies around the country to promote the idea at other Delta hubs.
</P>
<P>
   What's been especially encouraging, she says, is the support
from passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we announce on the P.A. that we'll be collecting
leftover, unopened food for donation to food banks, you can hear
rustling in the cabin, people taking muffins out of their
briefcases.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
