<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WSB taking Boortz and Howard national
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Is the rest of America ready for Neal Boortz and Clark
Howard? WSB(AM750) thinks so.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Jan. 4, Atlanta's two top-rated radio talk hosts will
be dishing out opinion and advice in other parts of the country as
WSB officially launches its new radio syndication network _
starring none other than Boortz and Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what that means: The two will still do their shows from
Atlanta, same time (Boortz/8:30 a.m.-noon, Howard/3-6 p.m.
weekdays), same place (WSB's new studios on West Peachtree St.,
Atlanta). But for two hours each day, radio stations in other parts
of the country will air portions of the shows while the talk hosts
field calls from Atlanta and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   How will folks react outside our hometown?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big question,'' Boortz says in his trademark,
debate-team voice. ``Next year, I have been doing this nonsense 30
years in Atlanta. These people (in Atlanta) are used to me. I can
commit all sorts of high crimes and misdemeanors, and they say
'that's just Boortz.' But in Duluth (Minn.)? Stations might want to
take out an insurance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The talk host does point to one factor that might work in his
favor when it comes to joining Rush Limbaugh and G. Gordon Liddy in
the arena of national political jabber: ``Name one Libertarian who
is a nationally syndicated talk host. There isn't one,'' Boortz
says. ``I am an equal opportunity offender.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard has a head start. WSB has been providing his show to
other Cox radio stations since last February, including WHIO in
Dayton and WDBO in Orlando. The consumer adviser has taken his show
live to these cities, where he is apparently building an
enthusiastic audience. According to WSB general manager Marc
Morgan, Howard has increased WDBO's audience by 140 percent since
the show began airing in Orlando. Howard has also been picked up by
stations in Milwaukee, Kansas City, Los Angeles, Dayton, Tulsa and
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   The top-rated consumer adviser looks at the opportunity with his
usual, aw-shucks perspective. ``I have no idea what to expect, but
so far I'm thrilled,'' he says. ``I've not gotten any cracks on my
accent. . . . It really hasn't been nearly as hard as thought it
would be. The questions are so similar to what I'm used to. The
only hard part has been when somebody is dealing with something
where the rules may be different in their state.''
</P>
<P>
   (WSB radio is controlled by Atlanta-based Cox Enterprises Inc.,
which also owns The Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE COVER BOYS: Not many of us would want to appear on the
cover of the gay issues newspaper Southern Voice being accused of
homophobia. Neither did 96rock's new morning team known as the
Regular Guys (Larry Wachs and Eric Haessler). In the Dec. 10
edition of the publication, representatives from the media watchdog
group the Gay &AMP; Lesbian Alliance Against Defamation blasted the
team for homophobic remarks, including one bit in which the Regular
Guys allegedly suggested that parents keep their children away from
gay hairdressers. ``I was angry, really mad and offended when I saw
it,'' Haessler says. ``It's okay with me if they write a review of
the show every week that says it's terrible or not funny, but it's
wrong to say I'm anti-gay, because I'm not.'' Haessler and
WKLS(96rock) program director Pat Ervin conceded the Regular Guys
have used terms such as ``faggot'' on the air, but that ``it wasn't
cruel, it was a joke.'' Since they made their debut June 15, the
Regular Guys have brought an aggressive, in-your-face approach to
morning radio that is definitely a departure from the genteel
South. Their schtick is bawdy, irreverent humor that skewers
everyone, from women to blacks to Jews to bald guys. Do they go too
far? Ratings will tell.
</P>
<P>
   BEST AND WORST OF RADIO, 1998: Neal Boortz bashed Clinton, Dr.
Laura got nekkid, John Boy &AMP; Billy were run out of town while Gary
McKee sat on a billboard. In 1998, Atlanta radio was all over the
dial in terms of good, bad and ugly moments. What do you think was
the best and worst on the airwaves over the past year? Send us your
picks, in any category of your choosing _ best or worst show, DJ,
radio station, promotion, music programming, undiscovered programs,
or just something that you find especially good, interesting, dumb,
or irritating. Include your comments, and we'll post the best of
your picks in this column on Dec. 30, and on our Website. Here's
how: go to our Website at www.ajc.com, click on RadioActive, and
fill out the form.
</P>
<P>
   _ Have a question or comment about Atlanta radio? Send to
mlongino(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
