<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for Wed.,
Dec. 16, which is sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Bitterly cold air will continue to amass over Alaska and
northwestern Canada. However, much of the contiguous United States
will continue to have temperatures near or above the seasonal
average. Meanwhile, an unusually dry pattern will prevail across
the nation as a ridge of high pressure remains strong from the
Western States to the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds will gather over the Great Lakes and interior Northeast
as a flow of chilly air in the wake of a front draws moisture as it
passes over the warmer lake water. A few snow showers will occur
near the northern Great Lakes. The coastal Northeast will remain
partly to mostly sunny with afternoon temperatures several degrees
above normal.
</P>
<P>
   Morning clouds and patchy rain will occur near the Carolina
coast. Gradual clearing will occur in the afternoon as low pressure
moves offshore. Elsewhere in the Southeast, mainly sunny and mild
conditions will prevail, although cooler air will arrive from the
north late Wednesday and Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sunshine will cover a large area from the interior West
to the Plains. High clouds will dim the sun from the northern
Rockies to the northern Plains. Thicker clouds and a few snow
showers will occur along west-facing slopes in western Montana and
Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The West Coast States will be mainly dry. Gusty winds from the
northeast will persist in California, especially near mountain
passes in the south. Near record heat will occur in some coastal
areas as the offshore winds are further warmed as they descend from
the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Snowy Kodiak &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Eleven inches of snow fell at Kodiak, Alaska, on Monday,
smashing the date's long-standing record of 2.8 inches set in 1935.
The town's average snowfall for December is 13 inches, while the
annual average is close to 78 inches. But the measurement of snow
is often difficult, given the fierce winds that are generated by
intense low pressure systems over western Gulf of Alaska.
Snowflakes caught in strong winds near the surface move
horizontally, making them difficult to capture in a precipitation
gauge. On Monday, much of Kodiak's snow fell with winds between 20
and 40 miles an hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
