TANGO-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ Carlos Saura's latest dance-inspired
film, ``Tango,'' continues the great Spanish director's fascination
with how life, art and memory intermingle, and how that can be
expressed through a self-conscious display of cinema, music and
movement. By Bob Strauss. 
. 

<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1209 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGO-REVIEW-LADN     12-15 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGO-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TANGO' DOESN'T MISS A STEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Our rating: 3{ Stars. 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Carlos Saura's latest dance-inspired film,
``Tango,'' continues the great Spanish director's fascination with
how life, art and memory intermingle, and how that can be expressed
through a self-conscious display of cinema, music and movement.
</P>
<P>
   Set, for the most part, in a Buenos Aires film studio where an
ambitious tango picture is being prepared, the movie about making
the movie is as artful and passionate a work as its rich subject
demands. Saura brilliantly shows how both the choreography and the
director Mario's (Miguel Angel Sola) personal vision of the piece
grows through a demanding rehearsal period, while peppering the
piece with wonderful (illusion-or-reality?) tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Political points (Mario wants to include a harrowing number that
addresses Argentina's recent military dictatorship) and show-biz
problems (his producers don't want anything that dark and dangerous
threatening the project's commercial prospects) are deftly brought
into play. A May-December love affair that develops between Mario
and the young dancer Elena (Mia Maestro), who is the girlfriend of
a mobster who's the movie's primary investor, plays somewhat more
hackneyed.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, all of these influences result in glorious,
thrilling dancing, all bracingly accompanied by Lalo Schifrin's
(``Mission: Impossible'') intricate score and Vittorio Storaro's
(``Apocalypse Now,'' ``The Last Emperor'') gorgeous and inventive
cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights, where all of these marvelous elements come
together, are fanciful ballets that interpret key aspects of
Argentine history. These include an immigrant landing built around
a crime of passion, a gang war every bit as good as the ones in
``West Side Story'' (and featuring the rare, sublime experience of
ballet star Julio Bocca dancing the woman's part) and, most
impressive, that controversial, multiscene tribute to the
disappeared victims of the generals' regime.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Saura's recent work _ ``Blood Wedding,'' ``Carmen,''
``El amor brujo,'' ``Flamenco,'' ``Ay, Carmela!'' _ has leaned on
the old ``Shakespeare in Love'' gimmick, where backstage melodrama
bobs and weaves with the themes of the show being staged. The
concept is kind of rickety, but as long as it inspires work as
vibrant as ``Tango,'' there's obviously still abundant life in the
old idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1752EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
