<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1217 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFT-VIDEO-LADN     12-15 1862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFT-VIDEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GO FOR PRESENTS THEY'LL WANT TO WATCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There are plenty of new and old videos out there
that make great gifts this holiday season, and with the addition of
some terrific DVD titles you won't have to be held hostage to the
current dreadful network television season. Most of these titles
can be found at local stores like Best Buy, Circuit City and Fry's,
but for the more esoteric or high-end ones you can find them online
at sites like reel.com, amazon.com or videocollection.com. Either
online or in stores, you can also expect most of these titles to be
discounted, some by as much as 50 percent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DVD &QC;
</P>
<P>
   With the studios digging into their vaults, there is more and
more to choose from everyday; so we'll pick five somewhat
representative titles that have been released recently to show the
range of what's available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casablanca'' (MGM; $24.99), which won the 1942 Oscar for best
picture and was named No. 2 on the American Film Institute's
all-time list, will appeal to just about everyone. Included on this
DVD is the fascinating documentary ``You Must Remember This,''
hosted by Lauren Bacall and containing some unseen footage. The
documentary explains what can only be described as the happy
accident in the making of the film (there were four screenwriters
and numerous script changes). It also clears up some things. The
famous airport scene was shot on a soundstage, although the plane's
takeoff may have been filmed at a local airport. When you see
Humphrey Bogart tell Ingrid Bergman that he's staying behind,
that's a cutout airplane in the background with midgets playing
workmen to give the scene perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silence of the Lambs'' (Orion; $24.99), which won the 1990
Oscar for Best Picture, is one of the most chilling films ever
made. The DVD includes audio commentary from director Jonathan
Demme and stars Anthony Hopkins and Jodie Foster, all Oscar
winners. It also has seven deleted scenes, a film-to-storyboard
comparison and other features.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull Durham'' (Orion; $24.99) may not have won any Academy
Awards, but this 1990 romantic comedy about a love triangle between
a career minor leaguer, a hotshot rookie prospect and the team
groupie/guru has plenty of laughs and sex appeal with Kevin
Costner, Tim Robbins and Susan Sarandon in the respective roles.
The DVD includes an audio commentary by director/writer Ron
Shelton, who explains how he solved such problems as getting the
6-foot-5-inch Robbins standing on a pitching mound and the 5-foot-6
Sarandon in the same frame.
</P>
<P>
   This year's ``Lost in Space'' (New Line; $24.99) is included
here because it merges DVD technology with the computer. The DVD of
this fun sci-fi adventure contains two audio commentaries, deleted
scenes and featurettes on space travel and special effects,
synopses of all the original TV episodes, interviews with original
cast members, and for computer users with DVD ROM there are games,
trivia, other interactive content and a Web site to jump to.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Tomorrow Never Dies Special Edition'' (MGM; $34.99) is a
treat for James Bond fans. The DVD includes a 45-minute documentary
on the evolution of the most-successful film series ever, including
interviews with Sean Connery and others involved, plus commentary
from the director and stunt coordinator, Sheryl Crow's video of the
theme song and other features. Hong Kong martial arts star Michelle
Yeoh helps pump life into the 1997 film, which stars Pierce Bronson
as the latest Bond and has some spectacular special effects and
stunts. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VIDEO &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For something slightly different, you can get the ``Tomorrow
Never Dies Limited Edition'' (MGM; $39.99) on VHS. This version
includes a second video, ``The Highly Classified World of 007,''
hosted by Desmond Llewelyn, who plays Q, a copy of the final
shooting script and a set of photo cards.
</P>
<P>
   It's never too early to get into the end-of-the-century madness,
and Paramount Pictures has 10 of their top films in one pack, the
Millennium Collection (Paramount; $189.50). All the films,
including ``Breakfast at Tiffany's'' for the first time, are
presented in a wide-screen format. The collection includes five
Best Picture Oscar winners and films that took home an additional
33 Academy Awards. The pack features collector gift cards and a
booklet detailing the productions of all 10 films. Besides
``Tiffany's,'' starring a luminous Audrey Hepburn, the collection
contains: ``The Ten Commandments'' with Charlton Heston, ``Grease''
with John Travolta, Francis Ford Coppola's ``Apocalypse Now'' and
``The Godfather,'' the whale-saving ``Star Trek IV _ The Voyage
Home,'' Tom Cruise's hit ``Top Gun,'' the romantic ``Ghost'' with
Demi Moore, Mel Gibson's Celtic epic ``Braveheart'' and ``Forrest
Gump'' with Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   The 75th Anniversary Box-Office Superstars Collection (Warners;
$69.92) includes four hit films _ ``Batman,'' ``Gremlins,''
Twister'' and ``Robin Hood, Prince of Thieves'' _ plus ``The Warner
Story: No Guts, No Glory,'' a documentary on the history of the
storied studio.
</P>
<P>
   The restored version of ``Gone With the Wind'' (MGM; $26.95) may
be the all-time box-office champ when it comes to the number of
tickets sold. Nearly four hours in length, the 1939 winner of 10
Academy Awards may seem dated and even offensive by today's
standards but remains a monument to old-time Hollywood filmmaking
for those who give a damn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Frank Sinatra Collection,'' (MGM; $29.99) captures Ol'
Blue Eyes in some of his best musicals _ ``High Society'' (with
Bing Crosby and Grace Kelly), ``Anchors Aweigh'' (with Gene Kelly
and Kathryn Grayson) and ``On the Town'' (with Gene Kelly and Betty
Garrett).
</P>
<P>
   ``The Pam Grier Collection'' (Orion; $34.99) should excite fans
of the blaxploitation queen. Grier, who should be a bigger star in
Hollywood (what more do you need besides looks, talent and a
dynamic screen presence?), can be seen currently on the Showtime
series ``Linc's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My So-Called Life Collection'' (BMG; $39.98) includes three
videos (six episodes) of the cult series that starred Claire Danes
as a teen-age girl dealing with the pressures of high school.
</P>
<P>
   If George Miller's ``Babe: Pig in the City'' seems a bit dark as
a children's film, you may want to check out where he got his start
with the Mad Max Collection'' (Warners; $34.99). The special boxed
set contains the original ``Mad Max'' along with ``The Road
Warrior'' and ``Mad Max Beyond Thunderdome'' (notice the pigs).
Science-fiction and action fans will love this dark vision.
</P>
<P>
   If you missed some of the impressive productions on the A&AMP;E
network, you can catch up to them on video. If you're still seasick
for the ``Titanic,'' the 1994 documentary ($39.99) combines rare
footage, archival documents and photos, creative presentation and
eyewitness accounts to explore the creation of the ``unsinkable''
ocean liner and its fateful maiden voyage across the Atlantic in
1912. For fans of the sophisticated '60s television series ``The
Avengers,'' starring Diana Rigg and Patrick Macnee, there are three
box sets ($29.99 each), with six episodes per set. For the literary
minded, there's Thomas Hardy's ``Tess of the D'Urbervilles''
($29.99), which aired in September.
</P>
<P>
   PBS Home Video has three excellent documentaries from Ken Burns,
the master of historical filmmaking. ``Thomas Jefferson,'' ``Lewis
&AMP; Clark'' and ``Frank Lloyd Wright'' each contain two videos and
are priced at $29.98 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   BBC Video offers a number of interesting box sets, including
``Sister Wendy's Grand Tour'' ($19.95) in which the unlikely art
historian Sister Wendy Beckett tours the great museums of Europe.
Her enthusiasm somehow makes it all entertaining. ``Sister Wendy's
Story of Painting Gift Set'' ($99.99) is also available. And don't
forget ``Absolutely Fabulous: AbFab Moments'' ($19.99). The video
is a hilarious compilation of highlights from the cult British
comedy series, starring Jennifer Saunders and Joanna Lumley, about
two outrageously self-indulgent women.
</P>
<P>
   PolyGram has a couple of interesting musical offerings. Andrew
Lloyd Webber's ``Cats'' is inventively brought to video with a new
production, and fans of Michael ``Lord of the Dance'' Flatley can
catch him in ``Feet of Flames.'' Each goes for $24.95.
</P>
<P>
   For the little ones, ``Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer,''
``Frosty the Snowman'' and ``The Little Drummer Boy'' are available
from the video division of Golden Books for $12.98 each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Parr: As I Was Saying ...'' (White Star; $49.95) looks at
television's pioneering late-night host. Included in the
three-video pack are Parr's interviews with John F. Kennedy, Judy
Garland, Richard Nixon and the acerbic Oscar Levant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planet of the Apes: The 30th Anniversary Collection'' (Fox;
$49.95) features all five ``Apes'' epics with restored prints and
remastered THX soundtracks.
</P>
<P>
   For X-philers, there's ``The X-Files: The Movie Collector's
Set'' (Fox; $79.99 ). It includes a wide-screen edition of the
film, a special ``Making of the X-Files'' video containing
interviews with the director, the stars and creator Chris Carter;
three reproductions of the movie's poster art; a 128-page
collector's book about the film; the script of the film; and a
specially mounted strip of five frames from one of the theatrical
prints.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are two personal favorites, both BBC productions.
``I, Claudius'' ($129.98), based on Robert Graves' novel of Rome,
is a story of conspiracy, sexuality and corruption that makes ``The
Godfather'' look like schoolboy high jinks. Claudius, emperor of
Rome, nears the end of his life and writes his family's history.
The extraordinary memoir begins before his birth and traces an epic
of ruthless ambition, shocking debauchery and murderous intrigue
set against one of history's most fascinating eras. Claudius, the
stammering and half-lame grandson of the scheming empress Livia,
survives amid corruption and deceit by playing the fool. Starring
Derek Jacobi (Claudius), Sian Phillips, John Hurt, Patrick Stewart,
Brian Blessed and a host of distinguished actors, this special
edition features scenes omitted from the original public-television
broadcast. Also included is the famed 70-minute documentary, ``The
Epic That Never Was,'' about the ill-fated 1937 film version of
``I, Claudius'' that starred Charles Laughton and Merle Oberon. The
only place you're likely to find this magnificent seven-video set
is videocollection.com. ``Brideshead Revisited'' ($119.95) tells
the story of the difficult loves of insular Englishman Charles
Ryder (Jeremy Irons), and his peculiarly intense relationship with
the wealthy but dysfunctional Roman Catholic family that inhabited
Brideshead, a grand country manor. Based on Evelyn Waugh's 1945
novel, ``Brideshead'' is also a story of faith as each member of
the Marchmain family must confront his or her relationship with the
church. Anthony Andrews and the incomparable Claire Bloom also
star. The box set is offered at all three Web sites mentioned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
