<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1220 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFTS-BOOKS-LADN     12-15 2004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-BOOKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST WORD IN GIFT-GIVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Except for those who like living on the edge,
holiday shopping can be one of the most stressful endeavors in
life. For most men, it's even worse _ sort of on par with watching
their favorite team lose the Super Bowl for the fourth straight
time. But wandering through a bookstore such as Dutton's in North
Hollywood or a Barnes &AMP; Noble or any other one is a Zen-like
experience guaranteed to bring back some of your equilibrium. Even
if you go with the intention of picking up one of the titles listed
below, take some time out to wander among the aisles, pick up the
books, turn the pages and get lost in something other than the
madness. Of course, you can go online to places like amazon.com or
barnesandnoble.com, but the experience is nowhere near as
therapeutic. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BEST BETS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The American Century,'' by Harold Evans (Knopf; $50). It's not
surprising that this book is out there; with the millennium
approaching, there are already countless tomes dedicated to the
past century or even the last 1,000 years. What Evans does to make
``The American Century'' surprising is choose lesser-known archival
photographs and stories to illustrate the major events of the last
100 years. In it, there is a telling picture of John F. Kennedy and
Lyndon Johnson taken while they were campaigning in the 1960
election. In it LBJ is gesturing and shouting wildly at an unseen
plane to shut its engine down while JFK reaches over to restrain
him. The photo is obviously meant to contrast their political
styles, but as as you move farther in the book to a section on the
Vietnam War, the picture takes on a different meaning. Johnson, as
Evans points out, had his doubts about the war but did not want
America to be humbled by a ``damn little pissant country.'' You can
only wonder if the more restrained Kennedy would have taken a
different course. It's items like this that make ``Century''
fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Gogh's Van Goghs,'' by Richard Kendall (National Gallery
of Art/Abrams; $37.50). This book is the companion to the exhibit
of the Dutch painter's work that will be at the Los Angeles County
Museum of Art in January. The book contains glossy reproductions of
the 70 masterpieces from the Van Gogh Museum in Amsterdam that will
be on display. The collection encompasses all aspects of the
artist's career, including such famed works as ``The Potato
Eaters,'' ``The Bedroom,'' ``Self Portrait as an Artist,'' ``The
Harvest'' and ``Wheatfield With Crows.'' This handsome tome also
includes discussions of each work. A can't-miss for art lovers,
especially those thousands who already have bought tickets to the
LACMA exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ART BOOKS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackson Pollock'' by Kirk Varnedoe with Pepe Karmel. (Museum
of Modern Art, New York/distributed by Harry N. Abrams; $75.) This
is the accompanying volume to the current major Pollock exhibition
at the Museum of Modern Art in New York. It includes more than 200
color reproductions of the pioneering abstract expressionist works.
For those who only see Pollock as the man who created ``drip
paintings,'' this volume helps explain his radical experiments,
which were attempts to free himself from the formal concerns of his
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``A World History of Art'' (DK; $59.95). This 720-page volume's
survey of art ranges prehistoric to contemporary. It also
acknowledges works from non-Western cultures, including Oceania
regions and Africa. The color reproduction are sharp. The last
chapter, ``The Future of Art,'' attempts to predict directions the
art world may take. It's a solid general reference book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louvre: Portrait of a Museum,'' by Nicholas d'Archimbaud
(Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang; $60). The famed Paris museum was built as
a fortress in 1190, expanded into a palace, then became a museum in
1792 after the fall of the monarchy. This volume, conceived and
photographed by d'Archimbaud, traces the Louvre's history and shows
off its many treasures and architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Essential'' series are mini-books measuring 6 by 6 inches.
The first four titles are ``Jackson Pollock,'' ``Salvador Dali,''
``Edward Hopper'' and ``Vincent Van Gogh'' (Abrams; $12.95 each).
These small volumes give you quick and simple references to the
artists and make it easy for you to sound like you know something
when you're at a museum. Did you know that Van Gogh used a reed pen
to draw with because of his admiration for Rembrandt, who used one
200 years before, and that he thought the Japanese tool exotic. An
icebreaker if I ever heard one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Prince of Egypt: a New Vision in Animation,'' by Charles
Solomon (Abrams; $45). The title is the hype that you would expect
to be associated with the highly promoted new film on the biblical
story of Moses from DreamWorks. But those who have seen the film
know that much of the animation is stunning, and this book, besides
glossily reproducing frames from ``Prince,'' also explains its
complex and occasionally computerized animation process in detail.
Much of the rest of the text is typical movie fluff that can be
overlooked. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ENTERTAINMENT &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``It Happened on Broadway: an Oral History of the Great White
Way,'' by Myrna Katz Frommer and Harvey Frommer (Harcourt Brace;
$35). Included in this volume are stories, anecdotes, jokes,
recollections and love letters from more than 100 theater
professionals _ actors, directors, playwrights, composers and
choreographers _ who talk about the past 60 years of theater.
Illustrated with more than 100 black-and-white photos, such
luminaries as Celeste Holm, John Raitt, Marge Champion, Richard
Kiley, Leslie Uggams and Neil Simon share their memories of the
Great White Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Story of Opera,'' by Richard Somerset-Ward (Abrams;
$49.50). The former head of music and arts programming for BBC
Television has put together a readable and elegant reference work
on opera, from its origins in the 16th century to today. It
includes chapters on the great Italian, German, French, English and
Russian operas and a brief introduction by diva Kiri Te Kanawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: the Visual Dictionary'' and ``Star Wars: Incredible
Cross Sections'' (DK; $19.95 each). Excitement already is building
for the new ``Star Wars'' installment, ``The Phantom Menace,'' set
for May, but there is still plenty out there for fans of the first
three movies. These two volumes are at the low end price-wise, but
for those who want something more substantial, there's the ``Star
Wars Encyclopedia'' by Stephen J. Sansweet (Del Rey; $49.95), which
has hundreds of entries, or ``Star Wars Masterpiece Edition''
(Chronicle; $75), which traces the history of Darth Vader from
before the trilogy and comes with an action figure of the villain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlton Heston's Hollywood,'' by Charlton Heston (GT; $28).
The man who played Moses and Michelangelo looks at his 50 years in
film. The volume includes more than 200 photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce Springsteen: Songs,'' by Bruce Springsteen (Avon Books;
$50). The ultimate for fans of the Boss. This volume contains the
complete collection of Springsteen's recorded album lyrics over 25
years, as well as the rock star's discussion of his inspirations
and his relationship with his audience and the role music has
played in his life. ``Songs'' includes reproductions of handwritten
sheets, on which he drafted songs, and numerous photos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superman: The Complete History,'' by Les Daniels (Chronicle;
$29.95). A look at the history of the Man of Steel, from his birth
as a comic-book hero in the '30s to his TV and movies years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Great Rock Discography,'' by Martin C. Strong (Times
Books; $32). Comprehensive listings for music trivia buffs. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SPACE &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``NASA and the Exploration of Space,'' by Roger D. Launius and
Bertram Ulrich (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang; $60). This volume tells
the story of United States space exploration with paintings and
sketches from from the art collection of the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration. Among the artists are Peter Hurd, Jamie
Wyeth, Robert Rauschenberg, Robert McCall and Norman Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apollo: An Eyewitness Account by Astronaut/Explorer
Artist/Moonwalker Alan Bean,'' by Alan Bean with Andrew Chaikin
(The Greenwich Workshop Press; $45). The fourth man to walk on the
moon tells his story through his painting. Includes an introduction
by another space hero, Sen. John Glenn. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HISTORY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Illustrated Longitude,'' by Dava Sobel and William J.H.
Andrews (Walker; $32.95). This is the expanded version of Sobel's
critically acclaimed ``Longitude'' that tells the story of John
Harrison ``who solved the greatest scientific problem of his time''
by building a clock that kept precise time at sea (a chronometer).
The illustrations, photos and maps are a welcome addition to
Sobel's lively prose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis &AMP; Clark: Voyage of Discovery,'' by Stephen Ambrose,
photos by Sam Abell (National Geographic Society; $40). This book
retraces the explorers' expedition to open the American West. Noted
historian Ambrose retraced their footsteps 190 years later, and
Abell took some grand photos. The volume also includes dozens of
reproductions of historic photos, paintings and maps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Ships: The Discovery and Exploration of the Ocean's
Sunken Treasures,'' by Mensun Bound (Simon &AMP; Schuster Editions;
$35). Bound, a professor of marine archeology at Oxford University,
is both a diver and art historian, so many of his stories are
personal encounters with the shipwrecks. A fascinating account that
includes historic photos and illustrations as well as shots of the
ships' underwater graves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Endurance: Shackleton's Legendary Antarctic Expedition,''
by Caroline Alexander (Knopf; $29.95). Alexander tells the
compelling story of British explorer Sir Ernest Shackleton's doom
expedition to the South Pole. Among the crew was photographer Frank
Hurley, who took some startling shots of the men's ordeal that are
used to illustrate this book.
</P>
<P>
   ``America 1900: The Turning Point,'' by Judy Crichton (Henry
Holt; $29.95). This is the companion to the PBS documentary that
aired in November. It is a beautifully illustrated account of this
country as it moved into a new century. As we are about do so
again, the concerns of that time seem familiar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death in Paradise: An Illustrated History of the Los Angeles
County Department of Coroner,'' by Tony Blanche and Brad Schreiber
(GPG; $24.95). A little macabre for the holidays perhaps, but this
behind-the-scenes look at some to the cases _ from the Black Dahlia
to the murder of Nicole Brown Simpson _ that have passed through
the L.A. County coroner's office is luridly engaging. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PHOTOGRAPHY &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Photographers: What They Saw,'' by John Loengard
(Bulfinch; $35). Starting with Alfred Eisenstaedt, Life magazine
has employed some of the best photographers of this century. In
this volume, 38 of them tell their stories and the stories of many
of the most compelling photos in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twins,'' photographs by David Fields and essays by Ruth and
Rachel Sandweiss (Running Press; $27.50). A book for those who like
to see double. Includes photos of Muhammad Ali and his twin
daughters, as well as Jane Seymour's children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eye of the Beholder: Photography of James Stanfeld'' (National
Geographic; $40). More than three decades of extraordinary color
pictures from the award-winning photographer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
MISCELLANEOUS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The New York Public Library Desk Reference _ Third Edition''
(MacMillan; $34.95). It's been updated. Everybody could use one.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Emperor's New Clothes'' (Harcourt Brace &AMP; Co.; $35).
Celebrities from Steven Spielberg to Liam Neeson to Dr. Ruth to
Robin Williams retell the classic fairy tale by Hans Christian
Andersen in their own words. Includes an audio version on CD.
Proceeds go to the Starlight Foundation, a charity to aid
hospitalized children. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1227 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIFTS-BOXES-LADN     12-15 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIFTS-BOXES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SOUNDS COME IN SMALL PACKAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER and GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Two of music critics, Fred Shuster and Glenn
Whipp, put on their headphones and made their choices of some of
the best CD box sets out there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GLENN WHIPP'S PICKS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Look of Love: The Burt Bacharach Collection'' (Rhino,
three CDs; $50) This box could also be subtitled ``Music Your
Parents Listened to and You Thought You Hated Until Just
Recently.'' Bacharach's richly melodic music has actually been a
guilty pleasure for years, well before lounge chic reared its boozy
head. The best stuff pairs Bacharach's inventive arrangements with
Hal David's incisive lyrics. For the cream of the crop, add Dionne
Warwick's breezy vocals. Adult pop doesn't get any better.
</P>
<P>
   John Coltrane, ``The Classic Quartet _ Complete Impulse! Studio
Recordings'' (Impulse!, eight CDs; $90) The best jazz box of the
year, this excellent set traces the compelling evolution of the
music the saxophone legend made with his most famous band _ pianist
McCoy Tyner, drummer Elvin Jones and bassist Jimmy Garrison. Few
working outfits ever had the kind of musical telepathy that this
trailblazing quartet possessed. For evidence, listen to the
transcendent ``A Love Supreme.'' Or the lyrically evocative
``Crescent.'' Or any of the seven unreleased outtakes (including a
fascinating alternate of the second movement of ``A Love Supreme'')
contained on the eighth disc. You will believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The John Lennon Anthology,'' (Capitol, four CDs; $73)
</P>
<P>
   Much like the three Beatles anthologies, the music contained in
this beautifully packaged box contains the sort of stuff _
alternate takes, demos, live recordings and goofy outtakes _ that
true believers will love. Everyone else will be better served by
the single-disc highlights collection Capitol released. But for
those who love the sound of Lennon's voice _ and it's front and
center here, more so than on his studio recordings _ this is a (No.
9) dream.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Springsteen, ``Tracks,'' (Columbia, four CDs; $70).
Springsteen decided to rejoin the Professor, Miami Steve, the Big
Man and the rest of the E Street Band cats on a tour next year, and
he probably made the call while assembling the music for this
exhilarating collection. Many of these rollicking unreleased songs
capture the wild, the innocent and sweat-stained shuffle of the
Boss's early days, when the sheer exuberance of his music made you
believe in the transforming power of rock 'n' roll. Crank up the
volume, roll down the window and let the wind blow back your hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have a Nice Decade: The '70s Pop Culture Box'' (Rhino, seven
CDs; $100) Talk about recovered memory. I've had the melody of a
song bouncing around my head for years, and only now, listening to
this wonderful collection, did I remember that it's the
Moog-synthesized stylings of Hot Butter and its No. 9 hit
``Popcorn.'' This entertaining set, appropriately housed in a
pea-green shag-carpet container, contains all the sing-along
one-hit wonders you could ask for (``Put Your Hand in the Hand,''
``Cat's in the Cradle'') along with funky dance tracks (``Disco
Inferno,'' ``Brick House'') and outright classics (``Let's Stay
Together''). Box provides ample evidence that one person's travesty
(say, ``Disco Duck'') is another's treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Charles, ``The Complete Country &AMP; Western Recordings,
1959-1986'' (Rhino, four CDs; $50). Country and western. Rhythm and
blues. Soul. Swing. None of the labels matter. When Ray Charles
sings a song, it becomes a Ray Charles song. Period. This excellent
set collects all of Brother Ray's honky-tonk sides, including the
genre-busting ``Modern Sounds'' recordings and later duets with the
likes of Merle Haggard and Johnny Cash. The ``white man's blues,''
as Charles termed country music, have never sounded so good.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Newman, ``Guilty, 30 Years'' (Rhino/Reprise, four CDs;
$60). Newman receives a lot of critical respect because of his
sharp writing, keen ear and a knack for turning the unlikeliest of
subjects (Karl Marx, cultural imperialism) into pop ditties. His
Americana travelogue numbers _ there are songs here about
Baltimore, Birmingham, Cleveland, Omaha and, of course Los Angeles,
among many others _ are always evocative, and his work as a film
composer is unparalleled. So why hasn't he sold many records? Well,
his mushy drawl is an acquired taste, and his orchestrations can be
a little too Tin Pan Alley. Then, too, Americans might not ever be
ready for songs about political science. If you are, this sprawling
collection just might be for you.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Garland, ``Judy'' (32 Records, four CDs plus video; $80)
</P>
<P>
   This comprehensive box spans the tragic singer's career,
beginning with early recordings made when Garland was just 7 to a
heartbreaking, live rendition of ``Over the Rainbow'' taped shortly
before her death in 1969. There are several unreleased concert
duets with Tony Bennett, Peggy Lee and Barbra Streisand as well as
a nine-song video from Garland's 1960s variety show. The proverbial
pot of gold for Garland fans. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
FRED SHUSTER'S PICKS &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Miss Peggy Lee'' (EMI-Capitol, four CDs; $50) Every few years,
Peggy Lee is rediscovered _ most recently when Madonna covered
``Fever.'' Now with the popularity of lounge and swing music,
here's the definitive compilation for one of the most distinctive
big band and jazz singers in all of pop. This box, complete with
80-page booklet, collects 113 songs recorded during Lee's Capitol
career, including ``Fever,'' ``Big Spender'' and ``Why Don't You Do
Right?'' some never-before-released tracks and a handful of songs
reissued for the first time since they were available on 78s.
Incidentally, Lee's final hit, ``Is That All There Is?'' was
conducted by Randy Newman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louis Armstrong: An American Icon'' (Hip-O, three CDs; $50)
He's considered the greatest jazz musician of all, a world
ambassador of America's liveliest homegrown art form and a true
original. Just ask Brian Setzer or Big Bad Voodoo Daddy _ Satchmo
was a king of swing. This 60-song set offers a comprehensive survey
of Armstrong's finest recordings of the post-World War II era, from
1946 to 1968. This was the period of his biggest successes, when he
went from jazz superstar to a goodwill symbol of American music and
culture. Here are the hits _ ``Hello Dolly!'' ``Mack the Knife,''
``What a Wonderful World'' _ plus duets with Ella Fitzgerald,
Billie Holiday, Bing Crosby and musical summit meetings with Duke
Ellington, Oscar Peterson and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Note Years'' (Blue Note, 14 CDs; $250). These 149
tracks represent a remarkably broad roster of talents reflecting
the stylistic developments in jazz over the past six decades,
featuring such revered artists as Miles Davis, John Coltrane,
Thelonious Monk, Bud Powell and every other jazzer you've ever
heard of. This seven-volume, 14-CD box, issued in advance of Blue
Note's 60th anniversary next month, is broken into such headings as
``Boogie, Blues and Bop (1939-55),'' ``The Jazz Message
(1955-60),'' ``Organ &AMP; Soul (1956-67)'' and ``Hard Bop &AMP; Beyond
(1963-67),'' right through ``Blue Note Now as Then,'' which
highlights '90s stars like Cassandra Wilson, Dianne Reeves and Joe
Lovano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Transistor Blast,'' XTC (TVT, four CDs; $45). One of the
cleverest Britpop bands to emerge from the punk and new wave
explosion of the late '70s, XTC was known for tense, syncopated
riffs and lushly arranged, hook-laden pop gems. Titled after a
lyric from the 1978 single, ``This Is Pop,'' the 52-track box set
features a treasure trove of tunes culled from BBC Radio vaults and
performance tapes. Highlights here include ``I'm Bugged,'' ``Life
Begins at the Hop,'' ``Generals and Majors,'' ``Making Plans for
Nigel'' and ``Science Friction.'' Incidentally, XTC's first new
record in seven years, ``Apple Venus Vol. 1,'' is due in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie Parker: The Complete Live Performances on Savoy''
(Denon, four CDs; $50). This compilation includes three discs
devoted to recordings of live gigs by the Parker quintet originally
broadcast from New York's Royal Roost nightclub in 1948-49. The
fourth disc includes six performances from a jam session featuring
alto sax genius Parker in Chicago in 1950, plus five tracks from a
1947 Carnegie Hall show with Dizzy Gillespie. Although this
material has been reissued in the past, this dizzyingly good
56-track set offers the best sound available and puts the spotlight
squarely on the remarkable Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Is Tight,'' Booker T. &AMP; the MG's (Fantasy, three CDs;
$45). Although Hammond organist Booker T. gets his name in the
band's title, this marvelous Southern rhythm section could also
have been called Steve Cropper &AMP; the MG's. Guitarist Cropper is
equally crucial to the groove here and it's his simple yet sweet
fretwork that provides much of the tension in this terrific
compilation of mostly instrumental Stax Records classics like
``Green Onions,'' ``Hang 'Em High'' and ``Hip Hug-Her,'' plus more
recent work with Boz Scaggs and Neil Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy Boy's Greatest Beats (1981-96)'' (Tommy Boy, four CDs;
$70). While not sequenced chronologically, this 56-track, four-disc
set traces rap's history from Afrika Bambaataa to De La Soul to
Coolio and Naughty by Nature _ ``Planet Rock'' to ``Gangsta's
Paradise,'' in other words. The New York rap-dance label Tommy Boy
was there from the beginning, introducing urban space-funk, cheap
drum machines, electronic hand claps and turntable magic to the
masses. The four volumes here are available individually or in a
great packaging concept _ a mini replica of a plastic DJ crate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
