<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON _ JERUSALEM _ Mixing powerful symbols of
historic sacrifice and seasonal hope, President Clinton wrapped up
a difficult visit to this turbulent region on Tuesday, conceding
that the heart of the imperiled Mideast peace process is barely
beating and faces added strains in the weeks ahead. Hoping to gird
that process for further stress, Clinton pulled Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
together for a 90-minute meeting at the border town of Erez, south
of the capital. Nothing of substance could be resolved, however,
and the two men could agree only to activate a handful of
committees to take up a host of thorny security and law enforcement
issues and, ostensibly at least, to try to speed the flow of the
economic and social benefits of peace to some increasingly restive
pockets of Palestinians. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SCENE _ BETHLEHEM _ The scene as President Clinton tours
both Bethlehem and Masada on the final day of his historic visit to
the Middle East. In Bethlehem, Clinton fell to his knees in prayer
in the grotto where tradition says Jesus was born. Then he joined a
Palestinian children's choir in singing a hymn in Manger Square
against the backdrop of a towering Christmas tree. The sightseeing
stop in the biblical town of 50,000 just south of Jerusalem
provided a brief, joyful interlude for Clinton at the close of his
often troubled three-day effort to revive the Wye River peace
agreement. Developing. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). ETA: 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton lost critical ground in
his effort to stave off impeachment today as nearly a dozen
moderate Republicans turned aside White House appeals and came out
in favor of removing the president. ``No one is above the law, not
even the president,'' said Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn. She
announced she would vote for impeachment despite days of intensive
White House lobbying aimed at encouraging her to defect from her
party. (Carr/Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ Some of President Clinton's
advisers are urging that he make a bold move to avert impeachment
such as a personal confession from the well of the House and an
appeal for censure, former White House adviser Lanny Davis said
Tuesday. Clinton, who arrives back in the capital from Israel
Tuesday night, has not approved the plan, and a majority of White
House strategists oppose it, Davis said at a breakfast with
reporters. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   GOPMAVERICKS _ WASHINGTON _ Nine Republicans withstood the
pressure and ostracism of some of their colleagues two years ago
and opposed giving Newt Gingrich another term as speaker. Several
of those same lawmakers, perhaps not surprisingly, are among the
undeclared on impeachment. They face a different kind of pressure
this time. One of that group, Rep. Tom Campbell, declared his
support for impeachment Tuesday, saying this decision ranks with
his opposition to Gingrich and vote for war as the most difficult
of his career. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE _ WASHINGTON _ How the Senate is gearing up for a
possible impeachment trial. The latest developments and a
nuts-'n-bolts explainer. (Malone).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-FEMINISTS _ WASHINGTON _ Women's rights activits rally
in Washington in support of Clinton. (Foskett, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV _ Roundup of television plans to cover House
impeachment proceedings, which start Thursday. With comments on
what's been the trends and ratings so far. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Continuing spot coverage of the
Microsoft antitrust trial. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   DROUGHT _ WASHINGTON _ National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration scientists warned in a study released Tuesday that
global warming and land use practices in the Midwest have left
America vulnerable to droughts during the 21st century that will be
far more severe than the ``Dust Bowl'' conditions of the 1920s _ or
any drought in centuries. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 500)
</P>
<P>
   CYBERWAR _ WASHINGTON _ A committee of the Center for Strategic
and International said Tuesday the United States is not adequately
prepared for the kind of ``cyberterrorism'' that could disrupt
airliner landings, paralyze ``911'' switchboards, scramble hospital
records and generally create havoc in an increasinly
computer-dependent society. (Nesmith, Cox News Service 750)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHILES _ CENTURY, Fla. _ It was the kind of day Lawton Chiles
would have loved. A good day for hunting. The sun was cutting
through the fog hanging above a crisp, chilly morning. The leaves
were turning. Lawton Chiles was making his final journey. Retracing
the steps he walked 28 years ago from Century to Tallahassee. Along
the way were hundreds of watchers, a genuine, touching tribute to a
politician the likes of which the state will probably never see
again. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post). 30. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   DIARY (developing) _ Exerpts from the diary Chiles kept when he
made this walk 28 years ago. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   STATE (developing) _ Tallahassee, Fla. _ Hundreds of mourners
file somberly past the coffin of Lawton Chiles, lying in state in
the Old Capitol Tuesday. (Elmore, Palm Beach Post). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CHILES-WIDOW (developing) _ What will Rhea Chiles do now? (Reid,
Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-DIARY-DONATION _ Who bought the Alamo diary? The secret
may be out tonight. At a news conference at UT the buyers will
announce they will donate the diary to the university. We hope to
get a head start on the IDs for a story on who the donors are.
(McCleese/Thatcher, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   LOCKDOWN _ Convicts are being confined to their cells at all 105
state prisons, as officials conduct a systemwide security
crackdown. Reason is an upsurge in recent weeks in all kinds of
contraband, in the wake of escapes from death row and tensions.
(Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   OIL-WORRIES _ NEW ORLEANS _ While most drivers are rejoicing as
they fill their cars with the cheapest gas in memory, New
Orleanians have reason to worry, turning nervous eyes toward
Poydras Street. Low gas prices and giant oil company mergers have
spelled job losses along Poydras Street, the central business
district home to thousands of workers with Shell, Texaco, Exxon,
Mobil, Amoco and Chevron. And layoffs conjure the ghosts of the
1980s, when oil went bust and New Orleans prosperity went with it.
(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WORKERS _ Dayton has been chosed one of five cities to take part
in a workforce development for poverty reduction project, funded by
Kellogg, Ford and MacArthur foundations. (Bebbington, Dayton Daily
News). 8
</P>
