<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1239 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-ALTERNATIVES-     12-15 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-ALTERNATIVES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SUPPORTERS SEARCH FOR WAY OUT OF IMPEACHMENT PUZZLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL and MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House, searching for a way out of the
impeachment quandary, endorsed a compromise offered Tuesday by 1996
Republican presidential nominee Bob Dole for a quick, tough
House-Senate censure of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   While other proposals floated Tuesday were designed to sidetrack
Clinton's threatened impeachment in the House, Dole's blueprint
offered the White House an escape from a Senate trial if he loses
when the House votes Thursday on whether to impeach _ or indict _
the president.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal by Dole, who served as Senate Republican leader for
11 years before seeking the presidency, called for Senate Majority
Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., to introduce a joint congressional
resolution in the Senate that would incorporate the ``guts'' of the
articles of impeachment adopted by the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Dole said his proposal would require Clinton to publicly sign
the censure at a ceremony designed by GOP congressional leaders.
Clinton also would be required to forward copies of the signed
censure to his Cabinet, members of Congress and all heads of
government agencies within seven days.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, saying he wanted ``a tough but responsible'' outcome to
the impeachment struggle, said his proposal would permit speedy
disposition of the issue to enable Republicans to ``clear the decks
and move forward'' with the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine a better way for Republicans to start the new
year than by taking charge and producing just results at this
historic moment,'' Dole said in a proposal outlined in an opinion
article in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   While Dole's proposal offered an exit for Clinton after the
House impeachment vote on Thursday, two Clinton allies floated
additional trial balloons designed to sidetrack the threatened
impeachment by the House itself.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Castle, R-Del., a moderate Republican with close
ties to Clinton dating back to their days as governors of Delaware
and Arkansas respectively, urged that Congress adopt a censure
resolution requiring Clinton to ``personally'' pay $2 million in
restitution over five years.
</P>
<P>
   Castle said the restitution requirement would reimburse American
taxpayers for roughly half of the $4 million expense of special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr's eighth-month inquiry into the
president's cover-up of his affair with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not too late to seek agreement on a strong resolution of
censure with a tangible form of restitution by the president,''
Castle said.
</P>
<P>
   The third trial balloon came from former White House lawyer
Lanny Davis, who suggested that Clinton appear before the House to
address lawmakers and answer some of their questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president can make his case in person before the full
House better than anyone,'' Davis told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' proposal echoed one offered in October by former
President Gerald Ford, a former House GOP leader, who suggested
that Clinton appear in the well of the House to receive a ``harshly
worded rebuke'' in lieu of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No spinning, no semantics, no evasiveness or blaming others
for his plight,'' Ford wrote in an opinion article also published
in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals came as Clinton suffered fresh setbacks in his bid
to stave off the first House impeachment since 1868. Several
moderate House Republicans announced decisions to vote for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton planned to pitch his case personally at a White House
meeting Wednesday with Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn. That meeting
also could include other undecided GOP moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading home from Israel, Clinton was asked by a reporter
whether he was able to separate the impeachment challenge from his
efforts for Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Clinton replied. ``You need to show up for work
every day. It's not a complicated thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The House will vote on four impeachment articles charging
perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is the second president in U.S. history since Andrew
Johnson to face a House vote on impeachment charges. President
Richard Nixon resigned in 1974 before the House voted on articles
of impeachment that had been adopted by the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is impeached by the House, the Senate would convene a
trial. If convicted by a two-thirds vote, the president would
automatically be removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., a Clinton ally who raised the
possibility of a censure vote in September, said that the outcome
of a Senate trial could be unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, hardly any of my colleagues in the Senate
have said how they would vote,'' said Lieberman, a former attorney
general in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, the White House spokesman on the impeachment issue,
said the administration welcomes efforts to find a compromise short
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't embraced any particular proposal but we generally
do welcome any opportunity to bring this to some bipartisan
closure,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the proposal outlined by Dole was a ``serious
proposal that certainly deserves examination'' by the White House
and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do believe that a bipartisan solution short of impeachment
and removal from office is the best course for the country,''
Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has courted Dole ever since defeating him in the 1996
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton awarded the Kansas Republican the Presidential Medal of
Freedom at a White House ceremony on Jan. 17, 1997 _ three days
before the president's second inauguration. Clinton also invited
Dole to join the presidential entourage on a pre-Christmas visit to
Sarajevo in 1997 _ a joint appearance that helped symbolize
bipartisan support for U.S.-led efforts to prevent resumption of
fighting in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Dole helped quell conservative GOP criticism of
Clinton's controversial trip to China. Dole also has repeatedly
endorsed Clinton's efforts to expand free trade.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Dole's proposal lies with Lott, however. Lott could
not be reached for comment on Dole's proposal on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
