<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE16-COX     12-15 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENATE TRIAL WOULD BE SOLEMN BUT UNPREDICTABLE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If the House votes to impeach a president for the
second time in history, the scene will shift from the boisterous
partisanship of floor debate to a solemn yet unpredictable trial in
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the upper chamber, a code of rituals would transform the 100
senators into a jury, ordered to watch silently from their seats.
It would take two-thirds of them to convict and remove President
Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment that U.S. Chief Justice William Rehnquist
appeared to preside over the trial, the nation and world would
watch a spectacle not seen since President Andrew Johnson was
acquitted in a three-month Senate trial 130 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The process would start when representatives from the House
appear in the Senate chamber, bearing the articles of impeachment.
That would probably occur Jan. 6, the opening day of the new
Congress. The actual trial would begin some days or weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   As the trial opened, the president's lawyers would almost
certainly seek a prompt dismissal of the charges. One legal
argument advanced by the administration is that the impeachment
will have expired, since it was voted by a Congress that has
expired.
</P>
<P>
   However, few legal scholars support this argument, and the
Congressional Research Service has cited two cases of federal
judges who were impeached by the House in one Congress and
convicted by the Senate in the next.
</P>
<P>
   The senators would hold the trial six days a week, excluding
only Sundays, as the two sides made their case.
</P>
<P>
   A team of House members would manage the prosecution. They
probably would be led by House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, the 74-year-old Illinois Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ruff, the White House counsel, who tried to head off
impeachment in the Judiciary Committee, would be expected to lead
the defense.
</P>
<P>
   The president could appear in person, although that is not
required or anticipated. And Vice President Al Gore, normally the
presiding officer of the Senate with the power to cast tie-breaking
votes, would have no role in the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   As in any trial, both sides would give opening statements and
then call witnesses. That invites a public retelling on the Senate
floor of many of the seamy events that brought Clinton to
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Among those called could be former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky to testify on the sexual relationship with Clinton and his
alleged efforts to cover it up. Also on the potential witness list:
Lewinsky's former co-worker, Linda Tripp, and Clinton's secretary
Betty Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of this, the senators would be required to sit in
unaccustomed silence, passing along any questions or motions in
writing to the chief justice.
</P>
<P>
   Rules of evidence and other procedures are not settled for this
quasi-judicial, quasi-political proceeding. Instead, the chief
justice would make rulings, which are subject to being overturned
by a majority vote of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Little is certain in such a trial, despite predictions by both
sides. Democrats have said it would tie up the business of the
nation for several months. Some Republicans have countered that it
would be over in three months or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows the answer to that,'' said Robert Dove, chief
Senate parliamentarian. ``I could posit a scenario that it's over
in days, or in months.''
</P>
<P>
   Dove, who conducted a study of impeachment procedures in
anticipation of a possible trial of President Richard Nixon in
1974, is predicting surprises if a trial occurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of a courtroom trial and how many things that can
happen,'' he said. A Senate impeachment trial is far less
structured, he cautioned, and ``unexpected things will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, a majority of the Senate could vote to end the
proceedings at any time. Or the senators could decide to pass a
censure motion instead of seeking Clinton's removal.
</P>
<P>
   If the trial reaches the closing arguments, the senators would
shut the doors and deliberate under rules that strictly limit how
much time each member could talk.
</P>
<P>
   It would take a two-thirds majority _ 67 senators if all vote _
to convict the president, a margin that pundits say would be next
to impossible to achieve in a Senate of 55 Republicans and 45
Democrats. However, if even one article of impeachment passes, the
president would be immediately removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate rules and the Constitution provide for no appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
