<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TARKINGTON WORTH READING, DESPITE BEING `OLD NEWS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why do I keep coming back to Booth Tarkington? I suppose it's
because he never quite goes away. His once-lofty reputation has
long since diminished, but he still gets read, because reading him
is often pleasurable and never is sinful.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of sin in Tarkington is the key to both his low
profile with the critics and his eternal endorsement by the
constituency that made him popular. He was too nice. He played it
safe to retain the adoration of morally upright Middle America, of
which he was representative.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana-born Newton Booth Tarkington (1869-1946) was as
prolific as he was respectable, marking a half-century publishing
career; but today he is known primarily for two novels, both being
early Pulitzer winners _ ``The Magnificent Ambersons'' (1918) and
``Alice Adams'' (1921).
</P>
<P>
   Those may be his most famous entries simply because they're in
the Pulitzer roll call, but my reading acquaintance with Tarkington
is sufficient to know they really are his best books. He was, of
course, ideally constituted for the Pulitzer fiction plum, which,
as stipulated in Joseph Pulitzer's will, must present a favorable
impression of American life _ the condition that kept Hemingway,
Faulkner and other worthies from gaining the prize until late in
their careers.
</P>
<P>
   One may read ``Alice Adams'' and ask if that portrait of
insular, hypocritical small-town life is favorable in any way. It
is downright damning. But Alice herself, a duplicitous
social-climber and a snob within her own drab family group, never
gets in bed with the boys; and if she did, Mr. Tarkington would not
detail the activity.
</P>
<P>
   That he is doggedly decent is both a virtue and a liability; but
by any account, ``Alice Adams'' is far superior to Sinclair Lewis'
similarly constituted ``Main Street,'' which preceded it by one
publishing season. Lewis wrote with a sledgehammer, and Tarkington
was rather more delicate. ``Main Street'' delivers its message
savagely, satirically, causing Henry Louis Mencken to salute Lewis
as ``the American Voltaire.'' ``Alice Adams'' is more conventional,
a novel in the realistic Howells tradition, but it is higher art.
One may take up ``Alice Adams,'' turn to any page to read a
paragraph or two, and be charmed. Try reading ``Main Street'' a
second time. You can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magnificent Ambersons,'' possibly more famous today as
Orson Welles' first movie encore after ``Citizen Kane,'' is the
second installment of a now-forgotten trilogy of Midwestern city
life with the collective title of ``Growth.'' Preceded by ``The
Turmoil'' (1915) and followed by ``The Midlander'' (1923),
``Ambersons'' is such a novel as Henry James might have written,
were he an upper-middle-class product of the American Midwest
rather than a scion of aristocratic New England and life abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ambersons'' retains interest both as a picture of business
life and as a fugue of love stories rendered so realistically as to
transcend soap opera. Tarkington at his best was good, all right;
and again like Lewis, he would have a better name today if he had
written less.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly Booth Tarkington in wartime produced two quite good
novels _ ``Kate Fennigate'' and ``The Image of Josephine'' _ that
caused very little stir because its author was old news, critically
downgraded in his own lifetime. He was something of a feminist,
keen in his distaff portraiture, but these novels like ``Alice''
and ``Ambersons'' are penalized by the plethora of mediocrity in
the full Tarkington shelf. He wrote too much.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the early ``Monsieur Beaucaire'' (1900) endures as an
entertainment, and the Penrod stories would still have a place if
boys still read fiction. ``Seventeen,'' about ``Silly Billy''
Baxter, is still wonderful; Tarkington's contemporary tales have
value today as period pieces, and I don't believe he'll ever be
completely lost.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1824EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
