<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1282 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     12-15 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTY ANIMAL INSTINCTS FADE FAST WHEN REAL MATURITY ARRIVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Saturday evening, my husband returned home at 6 and caught
me taking a nap. I don't usually take naps, so he asked me, ``Are
you sick?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I replied. ``I have to rest because we're going to
dinner and a movie with some friends in a little while. If I don't
take a nap, I'll fall asleep in my soup like I did last time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I remember. You almost drowned before the waiter
rescued you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you really should have noticed long before I turned
blue. Apparently my head was in the bowl for several minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought you were looking for bugs. You know how you always
inspect your food before you eat it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was gurgling, for goodness sakes!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what you were doing? I thought you were blowing on
that hot soup to cool it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, before time was of the essence, I considered myself
something of an ``animus partivus.'' That's an obscure Latin phrase
for ``party animal.'' During the week, I was a dutiful student, but
on the weekends I unleashed the beast.
</P>
<P>
   I boogied until the lights came on and polished off the evening
with a stack of pancakes floating in syrup. No party was
off-limits. No dance floor too crowded. I slept until noon on
Saturdays and then got ready to outdo my Friday night escapades. On
Sundays, I recuperated and transformed myself back into a geek.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward past graduation, 100 headaches, and a never-ending
to-do list. I am now an official member of the prestigious
I.T.O.D.Y.K.W.M.P.I. Society. That's an acronym for ``It's 10
o'clock. Do you know where my pillow is?''
</P>
<P>
   I can stay alert from dawn until the evening news and then, as
if on cue, I start yawning. I feel like a kid in grade school
sometimes with my lack of stamina after dark. On countless
occasions, we've been enjoying a fun evening with friends for what
seems like hours and hours when I make the comment, ``Gee guys,
it's getting late. I'm exhausted. I'm ready to call it a night.''
</P>
<P>
   As I put the remainder of my celery sticks and grape skins
entree in a doggie bag, everyone glances at their timepieces _ it's
only 10:30.
</P>
<P>
   They laugh at me and tease, ``You party pooper. I bet you don't
even know who David Letterman is, do you? Are you afraid that your
carriage will turn back into a pumpkin?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' I reply, pointing at my friend Nicole, ``I'm afraid
she's going to drown in that bowl of tortilla soup.''
</P>
<P>
   Party poopers of the world; we are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sleep is good.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
