<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMAIO NURSING SORE ANKLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He is the type of guy anyone would want in their
foxhole. He's the kind of player who would crawl through broken
glass for a teammate, a friend, or to avoid missing a game.
</P>
<P>
   But as supportive as Rob DiMaio is to his Bruins teammates,
friends, and acquaintances, there was no alleviating the pain he
was feeling after Saturday's 4-1 loss to the Sabres. DiMaio's
giveaway early in the first period set up Buffalo's first goal, and
it was all downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   The feisty winger refused to offer any disclaimers as to why he
had such a difficult evening. But further delving reveals that
DiMaio is struggling with the same affliction linemate Tim Taylor
is _ a balky ankle.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio's injury occurred Nov. 3 in Buffalo. He hasn't felt like
himself since. Unlike last season, when the Bruins' top checking
line was among their brightest surprises, this year two-thirds of
that combination has been greatly hindered by bad ankles. Earlier
in the year, the third member of the line, P.J. Axelsson, suffered
two concussions and is just now beginning to find his game.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio doesn't have a goal, he made a key mistake that led to an
opposing goal, and he was as depressed as anyone could be after the
game. Two days removed from the game and after a talk with coach
Pat Burns on the ice Tuesday during practice before flying to
Detroit for Wednesday's game, DiMaio was trying not to bury himself
in unnecessary pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Robbie is putting pressure on himself pointwise,''
said Burns. ``I don't care if he doesn't get a point all year. He
has to play his kind of game. He'll find his game again.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio said his ankle problem is ``tolerable'' and his objective
is to relax a little bit more and not allow the weight of the world
to climb on his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You struggle a little bit, you start thinking way too much,
and you make a mountain out of nothing,'' said DiMaio. ``We've been
playing pretty well and winning, and that's the bottom line. Such a
big part of the game is the mental part. You have to look at
yourself and believe in yourself and know how you can play. (When
you're struggling) you blow little things out of proportion. A
mistake is made that you pretty much make every time on the ice,
you turn that into something worse than it actually is. Through my
career, I've always been strong mentally. For some reason, right
now I'm searching for it a little bit, but I'm a professional and
I'll get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he downplays his ankle injury, DiMaio has been hampered
by lack of strength. It prevents him from battling as hard in the
corners and along the boards, two of his signature assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not quite strong in situations where I'm normally at my
best _ in the corners and balancewise,'' he said. ``I seem to lose
edges more than I ever have. That's our game as a line. I'm not 100
percent doing that. I've got to find a different way to get there.
That's my game. It's been bad since the last time we played in
Buffalo. Every game, it seems like something twists. I know
injuries are part of the game. I've had a lot in my career and I
played through them and I'll play through this.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaio believes he's bothered by the psychological more than the
physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel strong with my ankle, but it's not an excuse,''
he said. ``I have to deal with that. I think it's more confidence.
It's more in my head. I'm searching for something. I've got to find
it. I'm not contributing the way I have in the past. It's been
frustrating because I've had a bad ankle. I haven't been able to
get going the way I'd like to go. My line has been banged up. Once
we seem to get going, something else happens. It's a team game, and
I'm not a guy who's ever made an excuse for the way I played. I'm
responsible for what I do, and I have to find it. There's no easy
way to do that, but I'll definitely do my best to find it. I've
always found a way to fight through tough times and adversity.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns said Taylor went to the doctor Tuesday and likely will
have another magnetic resonance imaging to gauge the condition of
his ankle. ``Putting him in for one game and losing him for two,
putting him in for two and losing him for four, it was frustrating
him,'' said Burns. ``He wants to play, I understand that, but it's
going to have to take the time it's going to take. We can't keep on
going like this.'' . . . Burns said forward Peter Ferraro,
sidelined by a chest injury, won't be back until after Christmas,
though he accompanied the club to Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
