A1308 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEHLERT-IMPEACHMENT-     12-15 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEHLERT-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. BOEHLERT, UNDECIDED ON IMPEACHMENT, IS BURIED IN LOBBYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a moderate Republican from
upstate New York, was the target of furious lobbying Tuesday as he
prepared to announce his view on whether President Clinton should
be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert is one of a dwindling group of undecided moderate
Republicans whose votes on Thursday will determine whether the
House impeaches Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   David Goldston, the congressman's legislative director, said he
expects Boehlert to announce his decision Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   To influence that decision, telephone callers from his district
and around the nation have inundated Boehlert's office. Since
Thursday, 1,400 callers have favored impeachment, 1,210 callers
oppose it and 79 callers urge censure for the president, according
to Renee Longacre, spokeswoman for Boehlert.
</P>
<P>
   Goldston said the calls are continuing to come in ``fast and
furious.'' Those callers from the district are evenly split on
whether the House should impeach Clinton. Calls coming from
elsewhere in country have lately been leaning against impeaching
Clinton, Goldston said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who are (against impeachment) are concerned that
Congress is rushing headlong into this and it is simply a (sexual)
affair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldston said the calls do not appear to be orchestrated by
political groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting calls from a lot of people who have never called
a congressional office before,'' Goldston said.
</P>
<P>
   For every caller from Boehlert's New York district, six dial in
from other states.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert aide Donnie DeMarco said the calls have included
tearful pleas from elderly ladies fearing ``the country will go
downhill'' if Clinton is impeached as well as appeals from
stockbrokers worried about the effect of impeachment on financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The pleas are also coming from cyberspace. Over the weekend,
Boehlert's office received 8,000 e-mails on the impeachment issue,
compared to 90 e-mails on a normal weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Boehlert said he has been looking for more contrition
from the president for his behavior in the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important in my mind to look at it and evaluate it and
make a judgment on what he is really saying,'' Boehlert said. ``Is
this a classic finesse, or does he really mean it? I don't know how
you judge that. I know how I judge it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, 62, who just won his ninth term, has so far declined a
Friday offer by White House officials to discuss impeachment and
another from actor Robert DeNiro as he struggles to make up his
mind, said Goldston.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert has been consulting legal and political experts in his
district, which includes Utica, Rome and rural stretches in Oneida
County, and he has participated in conference calls among other
undecided moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert, a moderate Republican who is a former congressional
aide and public relations executive, voted with his party 75
percent of the time in 1995, the most he has voted with Republicans
since he came to the House in 1993.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
