<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AOL-LATINAM-COX     12-15 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-LATINAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL sets sights south of the border
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Already established as the main way to reach the
Internet in North America, and with service in Europe, Australia
and China, America Online has now announced plans to bring the
online service to the fast-growing Latin American market.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest online service formed a joint venture to
create online services for South America with Cisneros Group, one
of South America's largest media companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros will invest $100 million for a 50 percent stake, while
AOL will provide its technology and brand for the remaining 50
percent stake. The venture will first target Brazil, Argentina and
Mexico, the companies said in a conference call with reporters
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's strategy for the overseas market has been to partner with
local media companies such as Germany's Betelsman AG to develop
local channels and services for its international versions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Latin America is poised to become the next great growth center
for the interactive medium,'' said Cisneros Group Chairman Gustavo
Cisneros. ``The market for this product is unlimited.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros predicted that within several years, Latin America
Online will post membership numbers as large the original AOL.
</P>
<P>
   The service will roll out next year in Mexico, Brazil and
Argentina. Cisneros said the Latin American market is fast
approaching 2.5 million computer users, with a projection of 5
million by 2000. Currently there are 1.3 million users in Brazil,
221,000 in Argentina and 328,000 in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   But for AOL or any Internet provider, the market in Latin
America is heavy on potential and light on short-run prospects.
</P>
<P>
   At least until the appearance of a cheap wireless solution,
phone lines are the key to Internet access _ and phone lines are at
a premium through most of Latin America. Not only are phone lines
scarce in under-developed nations, but the prevailing systems have
been run by state monopolies for decades and are often unreliable.
For example, Brazil represents a huge chunk of the region's
commerce with a population of about 165 million and a gross
domestic product approaching $1 trillion. Yet there are fewer than
10 phones for every 100 people in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Phones in Argentina, perhaps the wealthiest Latin nation, are
about twice as common per person as in Brazil _ and that still
falls far below the figure for the more-developed nations. For
instance, there are more than 60 phones per 100 people in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Brazil and other Latin countries have been privatizing their
phone networks, permitting billions of dollars in investment by
foreign companies. That cash injection is expected to mean more
phones _ and better technology.
</P>
<P>
   However, the process of expanding phone systems _ or improving
them _ is likely to take years.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is among the larger investors in the Latin American
telephone market, but has concentrated thus far on wireless phone
service.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Michael E. Kanell contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1311 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH-Q-AND-A-COX     12-15 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Important thing is word of mouth'
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As Mark Feidler completes his first year as president
of BellSouth Mobility, that wireless unit is an increasingly
critical part of BellSouth Corp.'s rosy financial picture.
BellSouth Mobility has sales of about $3 billion a year, yet faces
added competition from upstart companies, as well as national
powerhouses like AT&AMP;T. Feidler recently sat for a lengthy interview
with the Atlanta Journal-Constitution. Excerpts of their talk are
below:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Safety is a big reason a lot of people have wireless phones.
But there are holes in everybody's coverage, places where the
phones will not work....
</P>
<P>
   A: ``At a fundamental level, I think that any customers are
safer when they have access to telecommunications. The issue
becomes, did they (the sales staff) oversell the ability to make a
call? I think we have a fair balance on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you think of the idea of requiring phone companies to
cover the entire coverage area?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We've made a decision as a nation and an industry that that
is not the model that we like anymore. Wireless has never had the
model of government deciding what people want, what people pay _
that is the land-line telephone model.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And you know, the cell phone, as good as it is, is not going
to protect society from all the actions of some vicious people.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you need to succeed in the market?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``You've got to be in the ballpark on pricing, but after
that, the most important thing is word of mouth. It's interesting
that we, the wireless industry, seem to ... be a topic people talk
about. And that's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: One way or another, Atlanta is a pretty hot market for
wireless. What percent of people here have wireless phones?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``I've seen different estimates, mostly in the mid-30s. We
are actually pretty hip here (in Atlanta). We buy a lot of
wide-screen televisions and DVD players _ cutting-edge things. And
we also have some world-class commutes here. I don't want people to
have long commutes, but if you are in a car, using the phone is one
of the few things you can do and feel at all productive.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've said wireless can complement a land-line phone, that
you've got ways of taking advantage of each...
</P>
<P>
   A: ``For example, we put both on a single bill. We have
'complete choice cellular' where you pay a single fee and get both.
For the future, we are trying out something called ``Call Wizard''
in Jacksonville. You give people your mobile phone number and your
mobile phone rings. When you come home or to your office _ if
you're a small-business owner _ you put the phone back in the
charger. That action tells the network to forward all calls to your
landline phone. You do that and you don't pay any air time
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You've still got some wireless investments outside the
region, in Houston, Los Angeles, Indianapolis... What does that
mean for your core strategy?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We bought most of our out-of-region properties in the 1989
to '92 time frame. Wireless was less well-understood back then, and
we were able to buy some attractive properties at good prices. But
we can't win as a company without winning in the Southeast. We
won't be the only player, but we've got to be a successful player.
We have other options in Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does the future look like?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``AT&AMP;T did a study 15 years ago ... they predicted 1 million
wireless customers by 2000. (There are now about 65 million users.)
We are fortunate that 14 or 25 years later, we still have an
industry growing at 15 to 20 percent a year. Nobody knows exactly
what's going to happen in the next five or 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: There are six wireless companies in Atlanta now and Sprint is
going to launch soon. Does that affect the way you do your
business?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We are to the point where whether it's six or seven _ it's
hard to tell. It's like running in the Peachtree Road Race. Whether
you are running against 50,000 or 49,000 people, it just doesn't
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How about Nextel, which is selling not just the phone
function but the two-way radio idea of instant connection?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``We don't have that functionality. We looked at adding it
and decided against it. We think we have a higher quality circuit
switch, that gives us more reliability, better clarity. ... But in
a market with five competitors, you can't be all things to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Nextel and AT&AMP;T talk about national roaming. Is that hard to
compete with, when you are mostly a Southeast offering?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``First, they can offer national roaming only where they are.
That is, some cities and maybe just some downtown areas. If that's
all you need, you fly to some airport and then go downtown, fine.
But the fact of the matter is that most roaming dollars are people
just getting 80 or 100 miles away. You think that a phone is
valuable because now you can call Indonesia, but you call your
neighbor more times than anybody else. I mean, you could open up
the window and shout.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
