A1314 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-COX     12-15 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENTURE-CAPITAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanks to venture capital, tech companies find backing By Mark
Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like the stock market, the amount of money invested in
high-tech companies by way of venture funds is on the rise,
nationally and here in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The metro area which has experienced dramatic growth in the
number of high tech companies calling it home, is attracting an
increasing amount money from investors looking companies poised for
growth and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gray, a local venture capital investor, has seen
positive changes in the Atlanta investment community.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more money, a lot more money,'' Gray said. ``There's a
lot more money generally, I think, in the country. There's a
snowball effect. I'm not sure what comes first, the entrepreneur or
the capital, but they grow together. And the knowledge and
expertise has grown dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital is the financial water that helps companies
grow. The money typically is invested when the companies are young,
but before they go public or are sold, sometime between promise and
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Companies usually take venture capital from several sources.
Synchrologic, a recent graduate of the Georgia Tech's Advanced
Technology Development Center incubator, took $6.5 million in
September from a Maryland venture fund, the Boston University
Community Technology Fund and four local sources: Alliance
Technology Ventures, Noro-Moseley Partners, John Imlay and Gray
Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year-old company makes software that helps integrate
customers and employees who are connecting to a company's computer
system from off-site. Synchrologic is using the money for research
and development and to expand its sales and distribution
departments.
</P>
<P>
   In the three months that ended Sept. 30, $3.7 billion in venture
capital was invested nationally, according to the
PriceWaterhouseCoopers Money Tree survey. The Southeast got $336
million of that. Georgia companies received $87 million, third in
the region, just behind Florida's $88 million and North Carolina,
which had $112 million in investments. Of Georgia's $87 million,
$79 million was invested in technology, health care or
communications companies, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
   As Georgia's reputation as a hot investment market has grown, so
has the number of local venture funds and outside funds investing
locally. Boston's Battery Ventures invested recently in Witness
Systems, a company that makes software that helps run call centers.
Oak Investment Partners, which has offices in Connecticut and
Silicon Valley, has money in BT Squared Technologies, an Atlanta
company that makes software for sales staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova Ventures, the venture fund formerly known as Cordova
Capital, is part of a investment community blooming in Atlanta
suburban corridor. Live Oak Equity Partners, one of Atlanta's
newest funds, has an office one floor below. Alliance Technology
Ventures is building new offices nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Dalton heads Cordova's information technology practice.
The fund consists of $145 million invested in about 45 companies,
half of which are local. Overall, Cordova is invested in 60 small-
to medium-sized companies in information technology, health care,
telecommunications and financial services.
</P>
<P>
   Three of Cordova's four funds are devoted to information
technology companies. Cordova is raising money for two more funds,
one should be finished this month, the other by mid-1999.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova invests in a wide range of companies, from start-ups to
later-stage private companies. The deal sizes average between
$250,000 and $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton said he receives many of the business plans he looks at
by E-mail. Unsolicited plans rarely turn into deals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cordova recently put $3 million into CareLinc, an Atlanta health
care information technology company.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to companies, there are inviduals known in the
industry as angels who invest in high tech upstarts. Bernard Gray
took some of the money from the $340 million sale of Summit
Communications Group to Time Warner in 1994, and launched a vehicle
for angel investing.
</P>
<P>
   Gray Ventures has invested in 18 companies, 12 of which he still
has a stake in. Half of those are in the Atlanta area, the rest are
in Research Triangle Park, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Gray tends to invest in information technology companies. Angel
investors typically invest their money in companies early, but
before traditional venture capital is invested.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Gray has put money into Monorail, a Marietta firm that
introduced the sub-$1,000 PC in 1997, as well as Alpharetta's
Synchrologic and Advanced Charger Technology, a battery company in
Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   Gray receives many of the business plans by E-mail. Some are
handed to him by people he meets at entrepreneurial forums. But
most investment opportuniteis come through networking.
</P>
<P>
   Gray invests in less than 1 percent of the companies he studies.
Chemistry swings a lot of the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does he have the experience to be doing it, the proper vision?
Is the compass set properly in place?,'' he said. ``Technology
investors can get enamored with the technology, but you really
invest in the people and the combination of the technology and the
people. I dwell on what you can do with the technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Live Oak Equity Partners is one of Atlanta's newest venture
groups. The $70 million fund started in July. It is run by Jim
Gilbert, Murali Anatharaman and Chad McCall, son of Charles McCall,
Chairman and CEO of HBO &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   Live Oak's health care information technology focus reflects
Gilbert's background. He worked for HBO &AMP; Co. and Imnet, before the
latter company was bought by HBO this summer. HBO sells software to
automate some of the functions in doctor's offices and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Live Oak has made one investment, $3 million in a West coast
health care software company. A $3 million second-round investment
with an unnamed local company is in the works.
</P>
<P>
   Live Oak Equity raised its money from several sources, including
Wachovia, the Georgia Tech Foundation, Charles McCall and Lewis
Jordan, a ValuJet co-founder.
</P>
<P>
   At HBO, Gilbert evaluated companies for potential acquisition.
Now he evaluates them for investment. Gilbert and the fund managers
are looking at companies taking early-round investment. The group
invests between $2 million and $5 million per deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert said they have looked at 160 companies so far. They base
their decisions on the potential size of the marketplace, the stage
of the company and the diversity of the management team.
</P>
<P>
   Noro-Moseley Partners is one of Atlanta's oldest venture capital
firms. The first fund started in the early 1980s. Noro-Moseley is
on its fourth fund. As of Oct. 31, $22 million of the $112 million
fund has been invested.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a diverse fund in the 1980s has turned into one
focused heavily on technology and healthcare. Geographically,
Noro-Moseley tends to look at companies in Atlanta, Raleigh/Durham
and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Taetle left Internet access company MindSpring Enterprises
to join Noro-Moseley in May. He said it takes between one month and
three months to decide whether to invest in a company. Most of that
time is homework.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference (between investing your money and
someone else's),'' Taetle said. ``I feel like the weight of the
world sometimes. You're dealing with larger dollars, so you tend to
be more thorough with your due diligence.
</P>
<P>
   Taetle said connections are the key to getting a business
proposal read carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something comes in and it's highly recommended by some law
firm we know or someone we've invested with, it doesn't matter if
it's written on parchment and crayon,'' he said. ``We'll still take
a look.''
</P>
<P>
   Noro-Moseley recently invested in Talus, a revenue management
software company with an Atlanta office, and OpenSite, an online
auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
