<SLUG> BC-WEB-RADIODEAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Radio station goes interactiveBy Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta alternative radio station WNNX-FM, better
known as 99X, had 3,000 free Christmas CD's from its ``Deck the
Hall Ball'' to give away. Beginning Dec. 14 at midnight, users
could log to music retailer TotalE.com and request the disc. By
mid-afternoon, the CD's were gone, proving that in Atlanta, at
least, if you promote it, people will surf.
</P>
<P>
   The station's on-air personalities talked up the offer all
weekend as well as at the concert and by late Monday afternoon all
the CD's had been snapped up by 99X listeners. The ``Deck the Hall
Ball'' CD features the Squirrel Nut Zippers, Beck, Shawn Mullins,
Tori Amos and a host of others singing traditional Christmas songs
to benefit the Atlanta Community Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Mellas, TotalE's marketing director says the decision to
partner with 99X, was its first radio partnership. Mellas said the
station liked the idea of the event because ``we were tied in with
a part of community effort and charity event and (it) made us feel
like more of part of a community.''
</P>
<P>
   She also says building an intimate connection with radio
listeners and music lovers seemed obvious. ``We could go to Yahoo,
where you are paying for all these eyeballs, but they aren't
necessarily your customers. We decided to appeal directly to
customers who might really want to buy our products.'' Mellas said
that targeting local radio stations and seeking out events such as
the ``Deck the Hall Ball'' are ideal for getting the TotalE brand
out in front of music lovers who do purchase CDs, videos and DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've discovered that doing promos on the Internet has really
been an extension of our marketing,'' says 99x promotion director
Jennifer Nech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason we got into this arena is we found we had a
real expertise in targeting marketing direct to consumers (TotalE
is a division of music club Columbia House). We also know a lot
about where customers are seeking out their music purchases and
what drives them to make a purchase.'' In the very competitive
online music arena, Total E has decided to build brand recognition
in local communities, one market at a time. ``Partnership deals on
AOL and Yahoo are great for building a brand,'' Mallas says, ``but
we wanted to build a business.'' Put more simply, Total E wants to
attract shoppers, not just eyeballs. ``We're involved in this (CD
giveaway) because we are trying to build these people as customers,
even if right now they aren't making a hard dollar purchase,
they'll come to our site and get to know us,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Nech of 99x says 75 to 85 per cent of the station's listeners
have home computers and the station is using that to its advantage
to market and promote the station locally and world-wide
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a response from listeners from Japan and all
over the world,''Nech says. ``We now have the ability to have the
worldwide audience and we don't want our contests to be restricted
to just Georgia residents, so promotions like this one with TotalE
work really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
