A1318 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-COLUMN16-COX     12-15 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-COLUMN16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consultant begs: Take us to your leader
 &HT;    By Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Consultant Ted Fisher is looking for ``a big mule,''
and Georgia's Gov.-elect Roy Barnes said last week that he'd
consider helping in the search.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: With the encouragement of the Common Services
Committee of the Atlanta Year 2000 Users Group, Fisher, along with
public relations man George Goodwin, is scouting for a leader. This
person would help form a volunteer project to assist in the
coordination of Y2K activities of government, business and the
general population.
</P>
<P>
   While Barnes said he hadn't heard directly from the Users Group,
he said he might help.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something I'd be willing to talk about and consider''
and ``see if we couldn't get somebody distinguished to step
forward,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look back on the history of Atlanta, when problems
have risen, there's usually been some major business figure who
took the lead and who was able to recruit others to help solve the
problem. This was usually done quietly and behind the scenes,''
Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to a ``power structure,'' the term coined by
Floyd Hunter, author of a classic 1953 study of Atlanta's prime
movers.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher doesn't see any such leadership at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to get help from the chamber of commerce, but it's
not on their radar screen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a leadership gap,'' said Jim Jones,
managing director of the Information Management Forum Year 2000
Group. ``It's difficult to say where it should have come from.
Ordinarily, this kind of issue is one that the business community
should take the leadership position on. But with all the potential
litigation out there, it's easy to see why a business leader
wouldn't be out there on Front Street with Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be quite honest, this is not an issue'' that has until
recently ``captured the hearts and minds of most senior business
leaders, with exceptions such as Equifax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a technical issue at its root, and most CEOs don't feel
comfortable in that arena,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Government, Jones said, has ``come late to the party, to put it
mildly,'' and is so enmeshed in its own Y2K problems it can't offer
much in the way of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher believes that, apart from problems that might emerge from
lack of a coordinated effort, the leadership position of Atlanta in
the Southeast is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta,'' he said, has ``pulled significantly ahead of
Birmingham in the fight to become the hub of U.S. business in the
Southeast. Now we're locked in a duel with Charlotte to maintain
that leadership,'' and the issue ``might well be decided'' by which
city ``is most successful in dealing with the Year 2000 problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Chambers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
