 For Release WEDNESDAY AMs, December 16, 1998  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-INSPECT (New York) _ The chief U.N. weapons inspector
presents Secretary-General Kofi Annan a report on whether Iraq has
cooperated fully with weapons experts in the past month. By Colum
Lynch. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   LOCKERBIE-LIBYA (Washington) -- Libya agrees -- with conditions
-- to a trial for two of its agents outside the country for the
Lockerbie bombing. By David L. Marcus. 1200 words. (i and a coding)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-CLINTON (Erez Crossing, Gaza Strip) _ President
Clinton's effort fails to persuade the Israelis to stick to a
schedule to cede more West Bank land to the Palestinians. By
Charles M. Sennott. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   ASEAN-TRADE (Hong Kong) _ Southeast Asia leaders expected to
liberalize trade and investment in an attempt to lure money back to
Asia. By Indira A.R. Lakshmananm. 1200 words. (i and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IMPEACHMENT (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-MODERATES (Washington) -- Several moderate Republicans
turn aside White House appeals and come out in favor of
impeachment. By Bob Hohler. 1400 words.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) -- Democrats are turning toward the
possibility of heading off a Senate trial through parliamentary
maneuvers or a bipartisan censure vote. By Michael Kranish. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton was returning
to ever-dimming prospects that he will avoid impeachment by the
full House. By Ann Scales. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTS-MOVE (Hartford, Conn.) _ Lawmakers vote on A proposed
stadium in Hartford for the Patriots. Debate continues over
last-minute changes. By Tina Cassidy. 1200 words. (a and s coding)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTS-COMPARE (Undated) -- How the Patriots' Hartford deal
stacks up against other recent NFL stadium proposals. By Gregg
Krupa. 900 words. (a and s coding)
</P>
<P>
   HEART-BENEFITS (Undated) -- Coronary patients who made intensive
changes in diet, exercise, stress management had dramatically
reduced cardiac disease after five years. By Larry Tye. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEXACO-PATRICK (Undated) -- Deval Patrick, former head of the
Justice Department's civil rights division, named new general
counsel and vice president at Texaco. By Ross Kerber. 700 words.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-CUTS (New York) _ Citigroup, the world's largest
financial services company, to cut 10,400 jobs, or 6 percent of its
staff, to reduce costs. By Peter G. Gosselin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN (Hartford, Conn.) _ By Dan Shaughnessy.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-BRUINS (Boston) _ Feisty winger Rob DiMaio is struggling
with the same affliction linemate Tim Taylor is _ a balky ankle. By
Nancy Marrapese.
</P>
