<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT16-COX     12-15 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNMENT SAYS MICROSOFT USED SALES 'HIT TEAM' ON COMPETITORS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Government lawyers rolled more videotape of
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates' deposition Tuesday, trying to show
that the software giant attacked competitors with a ``hit team'' of
sales people as part of an effort to protect its market dominance.
</P>
<P>
   In a 45-minute slice of Gates' 20-hour pretrial deposition, the
government focused on a 1994 e-mail exchange. In one message, a
Microsoft employee proposed using the company's Windows operating
system monopoly to pressure a competitor, IBM Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail message, Gates asked his employees to look into
IBM's practice of helping Lotus Development Corp. with sales of
Notes, an e-mail program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does IBM help Lotus so much?,'' Gates wrote. ``Is there
anything we can do about this? ...I want us to figure out how to
solve this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Microsoft employee Joachim Kempin responded
that IBM was using its own people to sell Notes. ``I am willing to
do whatever it takes to kick them out, but strongly believe that we
need a WW hit team to attack IBM as a large account,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by Justice Department lead attorney David Boies for an
explanation, Gates said the term ``WW hit team'' referred to global
sales people.
</P>
<P>
   Boies asked, ``Are salespeople within Microsoft commonly
referred to as WW hit teams?''
</P>
<P>
   Hunched in a leather chair, Gates shot back, ``If they're
worldwide and they're trying to sell to somebody who is a large
account, you bet.''
</P>
<P>
   The testimony was intended to underscore the Justice
Department's allegation that Microsoft is using its market
dominance in operating systems to pressure competitors and gain an
advantage in new markets such as Internet browsing.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray discounted the e-mail messages _
which Gates said he couldn't recall _ as old and insignificant.
``That was almost five years ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The government showed several more videotaped depositions
Tuesday, though, to make the same point.
</P>
<P>
   In one, a Walt Disney Co. executive testified that Microsoft
pressured his company to avoid working with Netscape Communications
Corp., which markets a competing Internet browser, in order to
secure a coveted spot on the Windows desktop.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Wadsworth, vice president of business development at
Disney's Buena Vista Internet Co., told prosecutors that Microsoft
insisted his company avoid any cross-promotional deals with
Netscape if they wanted to protect their real estate on Microsoft's
desktop.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the frustrated Wadsworth wrote in an e-mail
message, ``We are being roughed up by the 1,000-pound gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth said he felt as though Microsoft was pressuring Disney
because of its market position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like they knew that we'd be making a mistake to choose
something over them,'' he said. ``Basically I agreed with them. But
I felt like it was a difficult way to get there. I felt like we
were being, you know, leveraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Lead Microsoft attorney John Warden dismissed the day's video
clips as examples of the government's insistence on misconstruing
Microsoft's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another example of a how hard-nosed business
negotiations are being presented by the government as wrongdoing,''
Warden said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the government plans to show videotaped
depositions from John Kies, of Packard Bell NEC, and David Limp, of
Network Computer Inc. Boies said he wants introduce all the
depositions, which must be played in court, before the court
recesses Thursday for a holiday break lasting until early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   Boies said he may play more Gates videotape Wednesday if edited
excerpts can be prepared for court submission by 10 a.m. EST
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
