<HEADER>
A1350 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-GASOUTH16-COX     12-15 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GASOUTH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Assistants deserve credit, Eagles coach insists
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ Paul Johnson, one victory from a national
championship, is the only Division I coach in the nation with a
14-0 team. But while many around Statesboro and the Southern
Conference in general are praising Georgia Southern's second-year
coach, he is quick to credit his assistants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, I had put together a staff before I took the
job,'' said Johnson, whose Eagles play Massachusetts (11-3) for the
1-AA championship Saturday in Chattanoooga. ``Most of the guys
either played for me, coached with me or I knew them well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing was to put together a group of guys who
could get along, individuals who would not let their egos get in
the way,'' he said. ``I've been around a lot of staffs, but this
one gets along better than any one I've seen, and it's done one
heck of job on and off the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a 41-year-old product of Southern Conference sister
Western Carolina (1979), was a member of Erk Russell's staff at
Georgia Southern when the Eagles won back-to-back national
championships in 1985-86.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years at Hawaii and two at the Naval Academy as
offensive coordinator, Johnson returned to Statesboro in November
1996 for his first job as head coach to replace Frank Ellwood who
went 4-7 as a one-year interim coach.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and his staff not only changed the attitude of the 1996
grouip but also have provided consistently sound game plans so that
Georgia Southern has won 24 of 27 games since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see how Paul has gone in there and turned that team around
from its worst season (in 1996) to a good season last year (at
10-3) and a great one this year has been remarkable,'' Furman coach
Bobby Johnson said. ``A lot of teams have done a lot of things to
try to stop their offense, but they have reacted well to everything
_ which shows how well prepared the team is. (Paul) got my vote for
Division I-AA coach of the Year.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Eagles' option offense is so flexible and potent is the
result of work and familiarity, not happenstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason we've been so successful on that side of
the ball,'' Georgia Southern's Johnson said, ``is because the
offensive staff includes a lot of guys who played or coach with me
before I came back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Two members of Johnson's staff, offensive coordinator Mike Sewak
and defensive line coach and recruiting coordinator John Pate, were
assistants at Georgia Southern with Johnson during the title years
in the mid-'80s. Secondary coach Giff Smith was a member of the
Eagles' 1989-90 championship squads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys knew what what it was like when we won back then,''
Johnson said. ``We had (former quarterback) Tracy Ham on our staff,
but (Montreal of the CFL) offered him a load of money to return as
a player, and he took it.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback coach Michael Carter played for Johnson at Hawaii.
Slotback coach Jeff Monken was a graduate assistant one year
Johnson was there. Johnson knew the fathers of defensive
coordinator Rusty Russell, Erk's son, and wide receiver coach Brian
Bohannon, whose father, Lloyd, was a long-time coach at Griffin
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive back coach Joey Houston worked with Johnsonat
Gardner-Webb, 1995-96. During the same period , defensive line
coach Bob Bodine and fullback coach Brent Davis from Georgia became
familiar with their future boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to be as successful as we've been,'' Johnson said,
``has required a lot of hard work from everybody. I'm proud of this
team and this coaching staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnest Reese writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
