<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '98 Falcons could be like '97 Bucs
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In at least one regard, the Atlanta Falcons see
themselves as this year's version of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers, and
when Pro Bowl rosters are announced today, they hope voters view
things the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Bay had a league-high seven players who were named to the
NFL's all-star game last season, a measure of respect afforded a
team that went 10-6 after years of futility.
</P>
<P>
   Several Falcons are having outstanding seasons. But the same
thing has happened in the past and the players didn't receive Pro
Bowl votes, in part because the team was weak and received little
media exposure.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case this year. The Falcons' 12-2 record ties the
franchise mark for victories, and the players have been media
darlings.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Jamal Anderson, quarterback Chris Chandler,
cornerback Ray Buchanan, linebackers Jessie Tuggle and Cornelius
Bennett, wide receiver Terance Mathis and defensive ends Lester
Archambeau and Chuck Smith merit consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is second in the NFL with 1,596 rushing yards and
second in the NFC with 13 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll get the windfall that Tampa Bay got last
year,'' he said. ``I'm really prepared for the worst, because of
the things that have happened here in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle was the only Falcons player voted into the Pro Bowl last
year, although Chandler went as an alternate. Many people
considered it an injustice that Smith and defensive tackle Travis
Hall were not selected.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan leads the NFC with seven interceptions and has a
team-high 15 pass breakups, but he knows how the system works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't control it,'' he said. ``I've been in a situation
where I had eight interceptions, three (returned) for touchdowns,
119 tackles and didn't even get mentioned because we (the 1994
Colts) were a losing team.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons players voted Monday. They're not allowed to vote for
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to go out of our way to be just, because we've been
wronged _ a la Chuck Smith last year,'' Anderson said. ``I would be
sad and shocked if Ray Buchanan doesn't go, and Jessie and
Cornelius. Chuck and Lester _ at least one should go.
</P>
<P>
   ``And (Minnesota's) Randall Cunningham and (San Francisco's)
Steve Young are having great years, but Chris should be the third
quarterback. It would be a travesty if one of our linemen didn't
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Injured players can be voted to the team as an honor and then
replaced by alternates. Anderson said Falcons fullback Bob
Christian, whose season end last Sunday when he tore knee
ligaments, should get the nod.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously, who has played the fullback position better?''
Anderson asked. ``People are going to say (Tampa Bay's) Mike
Alstott has rushing numbers and mention (Arizona's) Larry Centers
because he catches a lot of passes. But Bob plays the true
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
