<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-PROTEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ferreira rising among local pros
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _Ellis Ferreira, who finished in the top 10 of the world
doubles rankings for the second year in a row, and Richey Reneberg,
a Davis Cup hero, were the standout performers this year among
Atlanta's nine touring pros.
</P>
<P>
   Ferreira won three doubles titles _ including Atlanta's AT&AMP;T
Challenge _ and made the final of three others as he and former
world No. 1 Rick Leach wound up No. 5 in the team rankings.
Ferreira, 28, won a career-high $368,000 and eclipsed $1 million
for his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having two years in a row like this, it solidifies to yourself
and to your peers that you are a top-10 player,'' said Ferreira,
who finished No. 10 last year while teaming with Patrick Galbraith.
``And that I can do it with two different partners, that's very
encouraging. It shows I definitely belong in that crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Reneberg, the former top-ranked doubles player who moved to
Atlanta a year ago, became the first player to win a Davis Cup
match in his place of residence since Andre Agassi did it in Las
Vegas in 1995. Playing against the Russians at Stone Mountain Park
in March, Reneberg and Todd Martin ended a five-match losing streak
for U.S. doubles teams and gave the U.S. a 2-1 lead en route to a
3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   In singles, Reneberg, 33, dropped out of the top 100 for the
first time since 1988, but his doubles play rebounded. He was a
runner-up at Philadelphia with David MacPherson and at Indian Wells
with Martin and made seven semifinals. He finished No. 31 in
doubles, No. 154 in singles.
</P>
<P>
   Knee surgery in July kept him out of the U.S. Open, ending a
streak of 30 Grand Slam appearances in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Luke and Murphy Jensen, who finished last year No. 15 as a team,
had a 7-19 season and fell to No. 52 as a team, and the brothers
almost fell out of top 200 in individual doubles rankings. Luke,
appearing more comfortable as a tennis commentator these days, has
had two minor knee surgeries in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia player T.J. Middleton made one doubles final, in
Marseilles, France, with Mark Keil, and reached a career-high of
No. 63 in June, but he was slowed by knee surgery. Middleton fell
out of the top 100 of doubles by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flach beat Karol Kucera, ranked No. 12 at the time, while
making the quarterfinals of the Queens Club grass-court tournament
in London, but that couldn't keep him in the top 200. Flach did do
some damage in doubles, however, and finished at No. 99. Flach and
Sandon Stolle won an ATP Tour title in Newport, R.I., and Flach
also won USTA Challenger titles with Reneberg and David Witt.
</P>
<P>
   Wade McGuire's highlight was winning three matches to qualify at
Wimbledon. He didn't win a match in the main draw on the ATP Tour
for the year and finished No. 339.
</P>
<P>
   On the women's tour, Lindsay Lee won her first singles title in
three years, the USTA Women's Challenger of Burbank, Calif., but
her singles ranking fell for the third year in a row. Now age 21,
the former top-40 player stands at No. 186.
</P>
<P>
   The Jensens' younger sister Rebecca finished her second full
year on the tour and is No. 164 in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
