<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETANYAHU APPEARS UNLIKELY TO STICK TO PEACE PLAN DEADLINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ After the thrill of presiding over a moment in
Palestinian history on Monday, President Clinton sank into a black
Barcalounger between the Israeli and the Palestinian leaders
Tuesday to endure the heated volley of their mutual recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   By the end, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel made it
clear that he was unlikely to abide by the peace plan's timetable,
which calls for another troop withdrawal from the West Bank on
Friday, a decision that was a disappointment for both the Americans
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, concluding a three-day visit here, nonetheless
pronounced the mission a success in putting the peace effort ``back
on track,'' although a senior adviser later qualified the
statement, describing the track as ``bumpy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have achieved what I came here to achieve,'' Clinton said,
referring mostly to the vote on Monday to eliminate calls for
Israel's destruction from the Palestinian charter.
</P>
<P>
   The visit came at a time of great distraction for both the
American and the Israeli leaders. Clinton faces an impeachment vote
by the House of Representatives on Thursday, and Netanyahu a
no-confidence vote next Monday that could topple his government.
</P>
<P>
   For each, the distractions provided distinct motivations.
Clinton was eager to burnish his role as an essential world
peacemaker. And Netanyahu, who fractured his right-wing coalition
by signing the peace plan in the first place, apparently calculated
that his best course was to talk tough and make no new concessions
until the Palestinians met all his demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace you only get if you insist the way we are insisting,''
he said Tuesday. ``Like we insisted and achieved the abolishment of
the charter.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even two months after Clinton and his advisers heralded the
signing of the peace plan, they found themselves touting as an
accomplishment the fact that they had cajoled the Israelis and the
Palestinians into conversing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got them back talking to each other, which is
extremely important,'' Samuel R. Berger, the national security
adviser to Clinton, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the painstaking, cyclically backsliding reality of Mideast
diplomacy, even the fact of the three-way meeting was an
eleventh-hour accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Before singing ``Deck the Halls'' with Yasser Arafat, the
Palestinian leader, in Bethlehem and touring Masada, a monument to
the ancient Jews, with Netanyahu, Clinton met with both men early
Tuesday morning at an army base near the military checkpoint that
separates Israel from Palestinian-controlled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by advisers, each sat in a Barcalounger equipped with
a massage unit. But that was where the comfort ended.
</P>
<P>
   Haggling over why the peace effort had stalled, each Mideast
leader offered an assessment: The other did it. Netanyahu presented
a litany of 12 complaints, which his office later faxed to news
organizations. They ranged from what he said was the Palestinians'
failure to confiscate illegal weapons to their refusal to renounce
their intention to make a unilateral declaration of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis find Arafat's insistence on proclaiming Jerusalem
the future capital of the Palestinian state to be particularly
provocative. And, indeed, the supposed provocation was everywhere
in Gaza during Clinton's visit there on Monday. Banners spanning
streets read, in English, ``East Jerusalem is the capital of
Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu also protested the increased unrest in the West Bank
and Gaza, the most important issue for him. The unrest has grown
out of Palestinian discontent with the Israeli reluctance to
release people the Palestinians see as political prisoners. The
Israelis believe the Palestinian Authority foments the violence, in
which four Palestinians died last week after being shot by Israeli
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   On their end, the Palestinians demanded an end to the expansion
of Israeli settlements in the West Bank, the release of more
political prisoners, and the overdue opening of the safe-passage
corridor for Palestinians between the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, though, they pleaded for the freeze on the next
Israeli withdrawal to be lifted and the timetable kept _ something
the Americans reiterated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be very unfortunate if we got too far behind
schedule,'' Clinton said. He said that Secretary of State Madeleine
K. Albright will return within a few weeks to try to to keep the
peace efforts moving.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With no breakthrough in sight, the Palestinians expressed
exasperation with what they see as Netanyahu's determination to
sabotage the peace effort. After Monday's vote by the Palestine
National Council to cancel all clauses in its charter invoking the
destruction of Israel, the Palestinians felt they had made an
enormous concession to an Israeli demand and deserved something in
return.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians maintained that there was no reason to go
through the exercise of canceling the clauses, since they had
already done so in a meeting two years ago. Many said they did it
only to rob Netanyahu of an excuse to stall the Israeli withdrawal,
and then it apparently did not work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is intentionally crushing all efforts that Clinton exerted
and is stopping the implementation of an agreement he personally
signed,'' said Marwan Kanafani, a senior aide to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israeli analysts said Netanyahu could not concentrate on
peace when he was fighting so fiercely for his political life and
that he would take no further steps until he knew what lay before
him.
</P>
<P>
   In a new development Tuesday night, his finance minister, Yaakov
Neeman, a professional appointee, resigned from the deeply
fractured Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said he was not campaigning to survive the
no-confidence vote next week. ``I can tell you one thing,'' he
said, ``I don't run after any MPs,'' or members of Parliament.
``Whoever wants to join us, can join. Whoever doesn't want to,
that's his right.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton began his flight home, Israeli radio talk shows were
still debating his visit to Gaza, which many Israelis and
Palestinians alike saw not only as an endorsement of their
sovereignty but as a clear sign of a change in United
States-Palestinian relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of historical perspective, Clinton's trip will be
remembered for the Gaza part,'' said Uri Savir, a key negotiator of
the Oslo peace accord reached between Israel and the Palestinians
in 1993. ``It was almost an unbelievable event. And it made it
quite clear that the U.S.-Palestinian tie is based not only on what
is best for the peace process but on staking out a relationship
with the future state, on lining up a pro-American Arab partner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
