<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1371 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      12-15 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 STILL ONLY 50 STATES   (For use by New York Times News Service
clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Puerto Rico failed to endorse statehood on
Sunday, we were all spared a potentially inflammatory issue that
could have influenced the Hispanic vote in the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   A century after the United States took the island from Spain, a
majority of Puerto Ricans resisted their governor's campaign to
abandon their commonwealth status in favor of becoming our 51st
state. The outcome of the nonbinding referendum, however, was
sufficiently ambiguous that the question of Puerto Rico's future
has not been settled but merely indefinitely deferred.
</P>
<P>
   For several years there has been considerable bipartisan support
in Congress for an election in Puerto Rico to determine whether
residents want to be formally assimilated into the United States
with the full rights of citizenship. Congress has not officially
promised to accommodate the election results if statehood should
win, but political pressure to do so would be strong.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sunday's referendum offered confusing choices, it sends
a signal that the island is sharply divided over the question of
statehood. Half of the voters, 50.2 percent, opted for ``none of
the above'' while a slightly smaller 46.5 percent approved of
statehood. Supporters of the status quo went for ``none of the
above'' because they disagreed with the definition of the
commonwealth option offered elsewhere on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Pedro Rossello refused to concede defeat and promised to
continue his campaign to convince Congress that Puerto Rico should
be welcomed into the union. But his inability to muster
overwhelming local support means that Congress will follow its
usual cautious instincts and duck the hot potato for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Granting statehood to Puerto Rico is actually more popular among
our national political figures than it is at home. Presidents
Clinton, George Bush and Ronald Reagan as well as former House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt
endorsed the change. Support for it is included in both parties'
1996 presidential platform.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are more interested in appealing to the growing
numbers of mainland Hispanics _ expected to pass African Americans
as the largest minority group in 2005 _ than to the Puerto Ricans
on the island. Republicans in particular are nervous about their
poor showing with U.S. Hispanics, which stems largely from GOP
positions tightening immigration laws and weakening affirmative
action programs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats think the newcomers would be mostly Democratic, as
mainland Hispanics now tend to be. But Hispanics do not necessarily
vote as a bloc and are often more conservative than Democrats on
some social issues, which encourages the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Commonwealth status means Puerto Ricans are American citizens,
given legal rights and the freedom to move about our country. But
they cannot vote for president and are allowed only one nonvoting
delegate in Congress. Individuals get a big bonus denied residents
of the 50 states _ they do not pay federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   They are prosperous by Caribbean standards. But as a state,
Puerto Rico would be the poorest, with an annual per capita income
of less than $8,000 a year _ only half that of Mississippi,
currently the poorest state. Roughly 60 percent of the island
population gets federal welfare assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., a member of the House International
Relations Committee, promptly warned that Congress is getting
restless about Puerto Rico's financial drain on the rest of us. He
vowed to ``re-evaluate the present federal subsidy,'' about $10
billion annually in welfare payments. He prefers that the island be
financially and legally independent or a tax-paying entity.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiasm for statehood varies somewhat according to the
size of the state a legislator hails from. Puerto Rico would send
two senators and up to eight representatives to Congress, weakening
the clout of smaller states by the sheer addition of more members.
This is, in fact, no minor matter.
</P>
<P>
   But the toughest hurdle for Puerto Rican statehood is language.
An estimated 75 per cent of the island population does not read,
speak or understand English with any fluency. Spanish is pervasive
and has been the principal language of instruction in the schools
since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   This worries many folks. Two years ago, a House move to initiate
a plebiscite on the island died after a clause was added mandating
that statehood hinge on a shift to English as the primary language.
It was viewed as an attack on Puerto Rican culture, unenforceable
and probably illegal anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the specter of a state that cannot communicate with the rest
of the country in English is legitimately alarming. French-speaking
Quebec, which keeps threatening to separate from English-speaking
Canada, is an example of how competing languages can prevent the
growth of common ties that bind a country together.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello made English and Spanish officially equal in 1993, but
there is little evidence that Puerto Ricans are happily adapting to
new bilingual ways. Islanders are accustomed to their Spanish
culture. An evolution will take time _ a great deal of time.
</P>
<P>
   Yet language need not be a permanent barrier to the addition of
Puerto Rico as our 51st state. There is no urgency here. The
referendum indicates the island itself is not quite ready for the
change.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, this odd colonial relationship should end. It
offends like a dangling participle, untidy and out of whack.
Patience is required here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
