<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1379 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIDS-AFRICA-MOURNING-     12-15 1333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-AFRICA-MOURNING-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRICA'S CULTURE OF MOURNING ALTERED BY AIDS EPIDEMIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map/graphic is being sent to NYT graphcis clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr .  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BULAWAYO, Zimbabwe _ On Monday, Amos Sibanda died in Mpilo
Hospital here, and his body was moved to its morgue.
</P>
<P>
   The relatives gathered at his tiny house cannot say exactly what
the 40-year-old man died of, but his death certificate can:
``encephalopathy and AIDS.'' He is the fourth member of his family
to die in 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   Sibanda, who could not read or write, made do for his wife and
five children by selling tomatoes, old clothes and fried fish on
the streets and repairing radios. He even owned a couple of cows,
but sold them in the last year to help pay for the funerals of his
father and two brothers. Now his family, its meager funds
exhausted, cannot raise the $46 it needs to get his body out of the
morgue and into the city cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Their worst fear, says Thamsanqa Magonya, the local ward
councillor, is that he will lie there until the hospital is forced
to cremate him. Mpilo's morgue is so crowded that it sometimes has
250 bodies stacked in space meant for 60. But cremation ``is taboo
in African culture,'' Magonya said. ``People don't want to burn
their relatives. They say, ``I don't want ashes _ I must see the
bones.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Africa, as the AIDS epidemic has gnawed through people
like a conqueror worm, the number of the dying is so great that it
is changing the culture of death itself.
</P>
<P>
   There are 5,500 AIDS-related funerals every day in Africa,
according to the United Nations. On a continent where a death has
always been a communal rather than a private matter, poverty and
emotional exhaustion are taking their toll. The poorest go
unshrouded a shovelful of ashes into a common pit.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of graves are left with no markers grander than the
favorite cup and spoon of the deceased, smashed in loving memory of
them. And people in all walks of life shamefacedly confess that
they no longer have the money or energy to mourn as they feel
African tradition demands.
</P>
<P>
   Some businessmen have made the best of this, and in cities like
Bulawayo, the funeral business is a golden industry in a blasted
landscape. Two years ago, the city _ whose name in Ndebele means
``the Place of Killing'' _ had four funeral homes. Now there are 14
registered ones, all owned by one family, plus an unknown number of
freelancers with a truck or two. Touts for the freelance homes used
to wander the wards of Mpilo Hospital until the chief
administrator, horrified by their ghoulishness, chased them out.
</P>
<P>
   In Africa, funeral rites take on far more importance than they
do in the West. The poorest domestic worker with no savings account
or pension will have one investment _ her burial society, a sort of
neighborhood club that in return for monthly payments her whole
life guarantees members of her family a dignified burial, with a
coffin, flowers and a generous meal for the mourners.
</P>
<P>
   Their finances pressed by the soaring death rate, burial
societies are changing rapidly. Ratidzai Chaumba, who runs one in
her Bulawayo neighborhood, said her ``joining fee'' had risen from
$3 to $25. Aunts and uncles of members no longer qualify as family,
nor do children over 24 years old. And to prevent people from
joining only when they are at death's door, there is now a macabre
``waiting period'' _ no one dying in the first three months is paid
for.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, Magonya said, anyone who fails to join a burial
society ``becomes an enemy of the people he is living with. Because
when you have a death problem, it becomes their problem.''
</P>
<P>
   African funeral rituals vary, but they usually involve bringing
the body into the home for at least one night, washing it, a public
viewing, a graveside service, a big meal for the mourners and a
weeklong period of mourning in which friends and relatives sleep in
the widow's room and around the house.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the funeral itself, the family is expected to pay for
the food and firewood, and some mourners even demand busfare home.
</P>
<P>
   Largely for that reason, funerals in most countries have become
radically shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customarily, if my brother died, my uncles, cousins and
grandmother used to come over and sleep at my house for a week to
console me and keep me company,'' said Jean Ngwira of a U.N.
project for HIV-infected people in Malawi. ``Now they only stay a
day or so.''
</P>
<P>
   In Uganda, said Dr. Donna Kabatesi, head of the Theta
AIDS-education project, the custom of showing respect when a
neighbor dies by not working in one's garden for four days has been
dropped. ``You can't afford to do that now,'' she said. ``You'd
have no food.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rachel Baggaley, a World Health Organization AIDS specialist
who spent six years working with farmworkers in Zambia, said big
funerals had ``become completely overwhelming for them. You had to
pay for food, and drink and charcoal. It could easily cost a
month's wages.''
</P>
<P>
   When she first saw farmers refusing workers a week off, she was
shocked at their hard-heartedness. ``Then,'' she said, ``I realized
that some workers were just incredibly relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 5 p.m. Tuesday: The Red Flag Tells of a Death &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By 5 p.m. Tuesday, Sibanda's tiny house in the Emakandeni
township is surrounded by neighbors and relatives. Outside, a red
scrap of potato sack hangs from a tree branch, standing in for the
red flag raised when a house has had a death.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty men sit on benches outside, sharing a carton of sorghum
beer. The women sit inside with the widow, their bare feet forming
a tight circle on the floor of the two-room house as they silently
weave wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   Jecko Forbes Ndlovu, who lives next door, stands outside with a
small bowl and a sheet of paper, tallying the donations from
neighbors and visitors. Mrs. Chaumbai's burial society agrees to
donate $20 even though no Sibandas were members. That puts him over
the top: there will be enough for a coffin, so Sibanda's body can
be released.
</P>
<P>
   In rural areas, a few people are still interred the old way: a
man is buried sitting up, wrapped in a cowskin, deep beneath the
dung of his cattle kraal, or enclosure, while a woman is buried
next to her granary. That his how George Moyo, a wealthier neighbor
of Sibanda's, said he will be buried when his time comes. But Moyo
is the president of the Ndebele Cultural Society and a staunch
traditionalist. Sibanda's family, like most Africans nowadays,
wants a coffin.
</P>
<P>
   All across Africa, the coffin business has boomed. The roads out
of many cities are lined with trucks selling them. Furniture
companies have opened sidelines. Magazines advertise ``The Box,'' a
folding coffin that fits in a luggage rack.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the University Teaching Hospital mortuary in Lusaka,
Zambia, there is a row of corrugated iron sheds known as ``the
coffin showrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nguni runs one, greeting customers while dressed in a
yellow shirt and red paisley tie. ``My boss only says I must be
smartly dressed,'' he said. ``Only those who work with the bodies
must wear black.''
</P>
<P>
   His wooden coffins sell for $13 to $260. Even the best still has
a flimsy lid held on by decorative screws. Other outlets sell
cardboard coffins, which have limitations: funerals have stopped
when the bottoms fall out.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part, Nguni says, is dealing with big families.
``Someone is always drunk,'' he says, ``and their language is not
good. They tease you, saying, `You're happy when you see people
dying, aren't you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Makandauko, a builder unloading 40 coffins from his
truck, said he has a chemistry degree, but no chance of a better
job in Zambia. ``When I first started, I had nightmares of dead
bodies,'' he said. ``But after maybe one week, I was used to the
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   His boss, Shailesh Patel of St. Ann's Funeral Home, says most
Zambians can't afford even their cut-rate coffins. ``They buy wood
themselves and hire a carpenter,'' he says. ``Or they break their
own furniture to make one.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 8:30 a.m. Wednesday: The Mourners Hire a Bus &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By 8:30 a.m. Wednesday, about 70 mourners have gathered at the
Sibanda house.
</P>
<P>
   Sibanda was ``a sociable guy, always making jokes with
friends,'' says his half-brother, Menford Nkomo.
</P>
<P>
   He was a gambler but not a drinker, says the Rev. Joel Dube of
the nearby Truth-Faith Mission, who will lead the service. ``He was
a good member of the community _ we had no trouble with him.'' When
he became ill, he left his traditional beliefs and ``came to our
church,'' Dube says.
</P>
<P>
   Sibanda's wife, Norah, seems stunned into silence. She is thin,
but there is no discussion of whether she too is infected. Two of
their children, including the 5-month-old baby, are not well,
relatives say.
</P>
<P>
   It is Sibanda's 17-year-old daughter, Margaret, who weeps
openly. Now there is no one to pay her $25-a-year public school
tuition, she says. Three of her friends have seen their parents
die, and had to drop out. Now they are maids, earning $8 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had taken practical subjects at school, like
sewing,'' she says, staring hard at the ground. ``I could not,
because it cost more. You must buy your own materials.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the mourners have chipped in enough to hire a bus to
take them to the cemetery. A neighbor with a small truck comes to
fetch some male relatives. There are so many Sibandas in the
mortuary that the funeral service needs help picking out the right
one.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 10 a.m. Wednesday: The Undertaker Is Disgusted &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m., James Andrew of Future Funeral Services has
Sibanda's body in a cement back room of the African National Burial
Society, a small house across the street from Mpilo Hospital. He is
disgusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``What kind of people are these? They don't even provide a
pillow for his head. Look how it's wobbling. I can't fix this.''
</P>
<P>
   Sibanda's naked, skeletal body probably doesn't weigh 70 pounds.
But Andrew, who is working alone, doesn't even lift it out of the
coffin to the washing table. He wipes it perfunctorily with Lysol
and water, and calls for a blanket. The only one handy is wrapped
around the widow, who sits in a car outside. She wordlessly gives
it up.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew tucks it around the body and screws the lid on, pausing
at the last moment to spray in some air freshener.
</P>
<P>
   In the corridor, two women wail loudly, praying over the body
being washed in the next room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is so silly,'' he mutters. ``Talking to a dead body. God
knows he is dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's indifference betrayed the erosion of other rites once
held sacred. For generations, body washing was always done by the
eldest members of the family. Love and respect were part of the
reason, said Sylvester Mubengwa, a human resources counselor in
Zambia, but it also ``reassured people that witchcraft was not
involved.'' The assumption, he said, was that an aged relative
would never steal body parts.
</P>
<P>
   The fear of witchcraft bankrupted the first owner of the African
National Burial Society, said Thabo Kunene, a local journalist.
``He was the first black person to start a funeral parlor in
Bulawayo,'' Kunene said. ``And people said: `Don't let the old man
visit your home. He's a witch.' The rumor was he was using medicine
to kill people so his business would boom.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there are many small black-owned funeral homes, like Future
Funerals. And AIDS has made death so familiar that fear of
witchcraft is no longer an issue. In fact, said Justin Chingono,
assistant manger of the Family Funeral home here, ``Death is now
discussed with children. In the old days, no young person _ even up
to the age of 18 _ was told that someone had died, or allowed to go
to a funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   But AIDS has also made many families afraid of the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few years ago, said Charles Stephenson, a funeral
director in Lusaka, Zambia, ``it was a must that someone in the
family was there when the body was washed, even if our men did it.
These days they stay away and say ``Tell us when you're ready.''
</P>
<P>
   His own workers are scared, he said. ``Two years ago, my men
stayed in the same overalls all day. You had to battle to to get
them to have a bath every two or three days. Now, everybody's
become very hygenic. They wear their gloves. As soon as they do a
body, they want their overalls changed. You don't have to tell them
to have a bath before going home. Even the washbasins in our
changing rooms are sparkling.''
</P>
<P>
   Where there are unusual customs, they too have changed. Among
the Ganda, Uganda's largest tribe, mourners must bring a piece of
brown ``lubugo cloth'' made from the pounded bark of the mutuba
tree, to help wrap the body. But few artisans know how to make it,
so the cost has shot up to 10 times its pre-epidemic price, Dr.
Kabatesi said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 12:15 p.m. Wednesday: Eight Funerals at One Time &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By 12:15 p.m., the viewing at the house over, Sibanda's funeral
cortege heads for the cemetery. Other drivers ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, all oncoming cars stopped as a sign of
respect,'' said Peter Stevens, Bulawayo regional manager for Dove's
Funeral Group. ``Now a hearse is just another vehicle.'' He has
even been honked at, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the gate, there is a traffic jam. Eight funerals are starting
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Africans wish to be buried in their home villages,
that is often impossible. Refrigerated trucks willing to carry
bodies are rare and expensive, so desperate families try to bundle
relatives into long-distance taxis while they are still alive. But
other passengers often refuse to share a minivan with an
incontinent, sometimes tuberculotic invalid.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, all over Africa, urban graveyards are filling up.
Leopard Hill cemetery in Lusaka is full, as is Warren Park in
Harare, Zimbabwe. Municipalities are fighting to find land, and
warily suggesting cremation. The Mayor of Harare tried it, Magonya
said, ``and someone shouted, ``I think you're sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inside, five men climb off the bus to borrow shovels from
the main office. The grave is dug, but Future's fee does not
include filling it in.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the singing mourners are straining to make themselves
heard over a bigger chorus 200 feet away, which has a drum.
</P>
<P>
   By 12:50, the eulogies are over, Dube reminding mourners that
``Joining a burial society is joining Jesus Christ.'' The men take
turns filling the grave.
</P>
<P>
   There is no money for something that has become the newest
funeral expense for better-off families _ a layer of cement just
atop the coffin to keep thieves from digging it up to resell,
sometimes with the corpse's clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving to prepare the funeral dinner of cornmeal, stewed
mutton and onions, the women place their wreaths, already drying in
the sun, on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   They are the only marker. No one has brought Sibanda's favorite
eating utensils. The only headstone nearby is made of fresh cement.
On it, in the poorly spaced scrawl of a child on a new sidewalk, is
the deceased's name and age _ 35.
</P>
<P>
   It seems unlikely Sibanda will ever have even that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
