<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1383 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUTERS-WISHLIST-96     12-15 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-WISHLIST-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DR. BOMBAY'S WISH LIST FOR THE ULTIMATE HIGH-TECH HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to say a word. I can tell you're worrying
yourself to death, wondering what to get me for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose you could take the easy way out and send me the
customary $10,000 Hammacher Schlemmer gift certificate, but I know
you want to put more consideration into it than that. Why don't you
just pick out a few things from the following list? And please
don't feel obligated to get me everything. It's the thought that
counts.
</P>
<P>
   Don't listen to all the killjoys who say you should wait a year
or so before buying me an HDTV. Digital televisions with remarkably
clear pictures and booming stereo sound are here now, and I want
one. Sure, there may be next to nothing to watch on it, but what if
I miss something good?
</P>
<P>
   Buy it in stages. Start with the Panasonic TU-DST50 (about
$1,500), a set-top HDTV decoder that works with normal TVs. Slap
that on the old Philco (as long as it has video inputs), and the
box turns the digital broadcast into a regular TV signal with the
same quality as a DVD player's picture. That's handy, because I'm
not ready to toss my old-fashioned big-screen yet.
</P>
<P>
   The TU-DST50 will decode any of 18 kinds of digital signals a
broadcaster is likely to use, so don't worry about whether it will
work in my area. It also has an optical audio output so I can plug
it into the Digital Dolby stereo receiver you got me last year. I
know my neighbors will love hearing the ``Suddenly Susan'' theme
song at 120 decibels as much as they did ``Twister'' on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing this magic box doesn't have is a catchy
name. How about ``Bombay Box''? Just a thought. ...
</P>
<P>
   When you get your income-tax refund, you can spend it on the
second HDTV component, the digital-compatible TV. How about the
Bombay Box's stablemate, the Panasonic PT-56WXF90 (about $6,000)?
It's a 56-inch wide-screen projection TV with excellent resolution.
Plug the box into this set _ where there's no digital-analog
conversion to degrade the signal _ and I'll be watching ``Sabrina,
the Teenage Witch'' in wide screen in no time at all. Well, when
they get around to broadcasting it that way, that is.
</P>
<P>
   I guess if you had $15,000 to spare, you could get me the
Philips FlatTV to use as a monitor instead. That's the 42-inch TV
you hang on the wall like a picture. The box will plug into it,
too, and it's got a killer picture. In fact, the only thing wrong
with it is that it's not that easy to set empty beer cans or
pictures of Mama Bombay on top of it.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great things about Walkman-style headphones was that
I could pretend not to hear anyone I didn't want to talk to.
Unfortunately, those people could always stand right in front of me
until I was forced to notice them. Sony finally solves that problem
with the Glasstron Audio/Video Headset (900 bucks).
</P>
<P>
   OK, so I'll look like Geordi LaForge, but plug a video source
into these goggles, and it's supposed to be like watching a 52-inch
television from 6 feet away. To keep me from bumping into the wall,
there's an adjustment that will let a little of the outside world
in, but don't tell anybody. I don't want them to know I can see
them waving.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing spoils my television-watching experience like lukewarm
nacho cheese, so I'll always remember you fondly if you give me
GE's Mike (90 bucks), a tiny 500-watt microwave that would look
right at home on the end table next to my TV chair.
</P>
<P>
   There's only .3 cubic feet of oven space, but that's fine for
nuking a piece of pizza or a cup of coffee. You really should think
about getting me a second one for the office so I don't have to eat
this pastrami sandwich cold.
</P>
<P>
   I can't tell you how many times I've been sitting in a bus
station after midnight with the sudden urge to watch my ``Starship
Troopers'' DVD again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Panasonic's DVD PalmTheater (about $1,400) comes to the
rescue. It's a portable DVD player with a built-in 5.8-inch
wide-screen monitor. The whole thing is about 6 1/2 inches square,
not too much bigger than a Discman. It'll do about everything the
big DVD players will, but it does it on batteries. Just keep an
extra set handy for the director's cut of ``JFK.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I don't trust people. Really. I'd just feel a lot
better if I knew for sure they weren't blowing smoke. That's why I
want you to get me a Truth.Quest lie-detector phone from Sharper
Image (129 bucks).
</P>
<P>
   When somebody is lying, psychological stress supposedly causes
subtle changes in voice modulation. The Truth.Quest hears that and,
depending on the size of the whopper, lights up green, yellow or
red.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want to buy the dorky-looking phone, you can get a
stand-alone Truth.Quest for 79 bucks that works with any telephone.
Can you imagine if these were standard government-office issue? Ken
Starr could have wrapped up that whole sordid mess in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
