<HEADER>
A1389 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COMPUERS-WISHLIST-2nd     12-15 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUERS-WISHLIST-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: in two weeks. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you pay as little attention to driving as I do, you have a
tendency to crash through the back wall of the garage. This can be
terribly embarrassing, especially the fourth time it happens. Well,
my contractor will just have to find work elsewhere once you buy me
Park-Zone from Exeter Technologies (80 bucks).
</P>
<P>
   This thing hangs on the garage wall and uses sonar to ping your
car. As you get closer, lights change from green to yellow to red,
telling you when to stop. Unfortunately, if you're still not paying
attention, you'll crash through the wall anyway, plus you'll kill
the Park-Zone.
</P>
<P>
   James Bond shouldn't have all the best toys. I want you to go
get me Sony's high-end 8mm camcorder, the Handycam Vision CCD-TRV99
(about $1,400). It has a night-vision system that will allow me to
tape stuff going on in total darkness up to 10 feet away. I'll
finally be able to tell what those odd noises coming from my
neighbor's window every night are.
</P>
<P>
   If you really love me, you'll make sure they throw in the
optional infrared illuminator, which will let me spy on them from
up to 100 feet away, which should be much safer. I think they have
a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those crude, engraved brass nameplates you see on the
desks of Luddites everywhere, the LCD Name Plate from Brookstone
(45 bucks) has a rotating display: three screens of 16 characters
each. I can put my name on one, my title on the next and a cheerful
thought of the day on the third. And nobody says it can't be as
filthy as 16 characters will allow. I can get by with seven or
eight.
</P>
<P>
   Does your dog stink? My ex-dog Dave sure did, but who wanted to
wrestle a 100-pound lump of fur into the bathtub? I really wish
you'd been able to get me the Ionic Bath Pet Brush from Sharper
Image (49 bucks) last year while he was still around.
</P>
<P>
   Mysterious anti-stink rays are generated inside the handle of
this ground-breaking dog-hygiene tool. A five-minute brushing is
supposed to take the smell away. And nobody has said it can't be
used on humans. Think of it! I'll never have to take another
shower!
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure you've noticed how all those high-powered executroids
are waving their palm-sized personal organizers in each others'
faces. A lot of them are PalmPilots or Palm IIIs from 3Com, the
people who took Candlestick Park's name away.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather you get me Philips' Nino 320 ($499). It's got 8MB of
memory to keep track of my hundreds of important social
engagements, plus it uses Microsoft's Windows CE operating system,
so it should be easy to transfer stuff to and from my PC. It comes
with all the software you'd expect on an organizer, plus it has a
built-in modem, so I can E-mail threats to various heads of state
no matter where I go.
</P>
<P>
   But the coolest thing is the built-in digital voice recorder,
perfect for all those times when I may not be lucid enough to write
down whatever pithy thing I happen to mumble.
</P>
<P>
   You simply must get me the LitterMaid Deluxe (about $200 in most
high-tech adult toy catalogs), a self-cleaning cat box. An electric
eye senses when Fluffy has done her business. Ten minutes later, a
sifting rake moves through the litter, clearing the clumps and
depositing them in an air-tight container.
</P>
<P>
   The thing runs on batteries or AC, although I'm not so sure
about letting a cat loose near live current. A frayed cord mixed
with one bad aim might add up to kitty fritters. I don't actually
have a cat, but I thought LitterMaid might be a nice addition to
the master bedroom. My prostate's not getting any younger, you
know.
</P>
<P>
   It really is getting to be a chore, rolling down the car window
to see what the temperature is like outside. Why don't you get me
the Wireless Auto Thermometer (60 bucks) from Brookstone?
</P>
<P>
   It's got a sensor that mounts on the back window and transmits
the temperature to a receiver installed on the dash. That way I'll
always know if it's too cold to drive through Jack-in-the-Box.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a grueling four-hour workday, I like something to
liven up the drive home, which is why TeleMania's Star Trek
Communicator Garage Door Opener (50 bucks) would be perfect for me.
Modeled after the classic ``Beam me up, Scotty'' communicator, it's
supposed to open justabout any garage door, maybe even my
neighbor's when he's not home.
</P>
<P>
   I wish they had a phaser to go with this. Those ceramic ducks on
his lawn really do need to be vaporized.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Electronics' Furby (30 bucks, as if you could actually
find one in the stores) is this year's must-have toy. If you don't
get one of these for your kid, you might as well not come home from
the mall.
</P>
<P>
   In case you've been living in a cave, a Furby is what you'd get
if you crossed a Tribble and a Tamagotchi: a sickeningly adorable,
artificially intelligent ball of fur that speaks to you and other
Furbies in a grating gibberish designed to drive adults clinically
insane within six hours.
</P>
<P>
   Do not buy me one of these.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't stop yourself, though, please also pick up the
ultimate Furby accessory: the Air Attack 2 aluminum bat (around
$230) from Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby, the Louisville Slugger people. It's
pressurized with nitrogen, and a newly designed air chamber and
large sweet spot make it the perfect tool for pounding any Furby
into its component molecules.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay, the Fort Worth Star-Telegram's computer
know-it-all, has been a very, very good boy this year. E-mail:
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
