<SLUG> BC-MA-EMISSIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA THREATENS PENALTIES OVER BAY STATE AUTO EMISSIONS INACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Frustrated by Massachusetts' slow progress in setting
up a high-tech auto inspection program, the US Environmental
Protection Agency plans to punish the state within the next few
months, severely restricting the construction of new power plants
and other industrial facilities that pollute the air.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts officials admit they are unlikely to meet a May
deadline to begin the testing program, which will use both
highway-mounted sensors and garage inspections to get polluting
cars off the road. The Cellucci administration still is
negotatiating a contract for the testing equipment, and trying to
pay for it without raising annual inspection fees above $20.
</P>
<P>
   But, after four years of discussions with the state about
tougher vehicle inspections, EPA officials say their patience is
thin, and they may punish the state long before May if they are
convinced the Cellucci administration is deliberately stalling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very hesitant to initiate sanctions against the
Commonwealth. Of all the ways of solving this problem, it is the
least satisfactory,'' said John DeVillars, EPA's New England
administrator. ``But we will very soon be left with no other
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   More sophisticated vehicle inspections are a key part of the
national effort to curb summertime smog, but they have provoked
repeated showdowns between EPA and some states. Maine abruptly
closed its vehicle testing centers amid complaints about the cost,
inconvenience and high failure rate in 1995, prompting EPA to back
off on the issue for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the prospect of EPA sanctions alarms industry officials,
who fear that Massachusetts' economy will be punished for the
failure to crack down on motor vehicle exhaust. Up to 15 proposed
natural-gas burning power plants _ billed as a cleaner, cheaper way
to provide electricity than the coal- or oil-fired plants they
would replace _ could be delayed under EPA sanctions that would
require the state to eliminate twice as much pollution as the
plants would emit.
</P>
<P>
   EPA sanctions have ``significant implications on how clean the
air is and on the competitive electricity world we are all looking
toward,'' said Robert Ruddock, executive vice president of the
Associated Industries of Massachusetts. ``Frankly, we can't afford
to have that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   State officials say they aren't looking for a fight, and blame
the delays in the program on the changing technology of pollution
detection. They note that EPA has repeatedly changed its technical
requirements for the inspection programs, providing detailed
guidance on the use of highway-mounted sensors that analyze car
exhaust only last May.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officials in the Executive Office of Administration
and Finance are concerned at the estimated $215 million cost of the
contract being negotiated with Keating Technologies of Phoenix and
the possibility of a driver revolt if the cost of an inspection
sticker rises significantly from the current $15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely take EPA seriously about the issue of sanctions
and we are acutely aware of the timeline,'' said Assistant
Environmental Affairs Secretary John Rodman, who hopes the new
inspection program will start by summer, but would not promise it.
``We are not looking for a fight.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash between Massachusetts and federal regulators over car
inspections began in 1994 when EPA threatened to withhold highway
funding for the Central Artery/Third Harbor Tunnel project if the
Legislature didn't create a new emissions testing system where cars
would be sent to one of 50 testing centers equipped with machines
that detect chemicals in car exhaust far more accurately than
current technology.
</P>
<P>
   Before Massachusetts could set up the system, however, drivers
in Maine rebelled against similar testing centers, prompting the
governor to close them. EPA quickly backed away from the old
testing scheme and began looking for new options.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Massachusetts air has gotten cleaner, and regulators
have come up with more consumer-friendly ways to test vehicle
exhaust. Under the current Massachusetts plan, drivers would go
every other year to one of 600 to 1,200 inspection stations for the
high-tech emissions tests, as part of their annual safety
inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Up to 20 percent of drivers wouldn't need an emissions test at
all because their emissions would be checked by highway-mounted
pollution sensors using infrared or lasers to analyze exhaust
gases. The sensors would only record vehicles that meet the
standards, requiring vehicles that fail to be tested in inspection
centers.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiating the deal with Keating Technologies has been
tricky because state officials are unsure how many inspection
stations will want testing equipment, making it difficult to set a
contract price _ or to calculate how much motorists must pay to
cover the cost of the program.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rodman said state officials want ``no significant
increase for the motorist'' for an inspection sticker, which he
said would be no more than a few dollars increase.
</P>
<P>
   While Massachusetts deliberates, EPA officials point out that
many other states, such as Connecticut, have already begun the new
tests, reducing smog in the process. Said EPA's DeVillars, ``It's
time to get out of neutral and into the fast lane with an
economically and environmentally sound program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
