   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   These are the other stories in the package:
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 7:30 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-VOICES (Richmond Heights, Mo.) _ In nearly three-dozen
interviews conducted over two days around St. Louis, there was no
consensus on impeachment. What was striking was the hardening of
attitudes and the relative dearth of those occupying the middle
ground. Around the country in recent months, many people expressed
torn emotions, indecision and reluctance to take a stand. This time
the middle ground seemed to have all but evaporated. By Rick Lyman.
(1900 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-RULES (Washington) _ Charles Johnson, the 30-year
veteran who serves as Parliamentarian, finds himself on the hot
seat on the censure resolution. By David E. Rosenbaum. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS (Undated) _ The historically momentous votes
on articles of impeachment in the House Judiciary Committee did not
result in historically high ratings for any television news outlet
that was covering them, though Saturday's final day of debate on
the issue did produce a slight increase in viewing for the all-news
cable channels. By Bill Carter. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   Moving by  &UR; 8:00 &LR; :
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SENATE (Washington) _ Republican and Democratic senators
said Tuesday that it appeared increasingly unlikely that President
Clinton could avoid a trial in the Senate if the House voted this
week to impeach him. By Richard L. Berke. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ In the spirit of the Christmas
lyric _ ``Let nothing you dismay'' _ chairman Henry Hyde has
scheduled the Judiciary Committee's holiday party at the very time
Thursday when his fateful motion to impeach President Clinton is
scheduled to be debated by the House. ``It should do wonders for
holiday cheer,'' commented William D. Delahunt, a Massachusetts
Democrat on the committee, offended, like other Democrats, at the
coincidence of wassailing and impeaching on such a momentous day.
By Francis X. Clines. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-REPUBS (Washington) _ Developments among the
pro-impeachment forces. By Katharine Q. Seelye. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEMS (Washington) _ What the anti-impeachment forces are
doing. By Adam Nagourney. (800 words)
</P>
