<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-BENEFITS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW HEART-EXERCISE STUDY MEETS CONTROVERSY  
 STUDY DETAILS BENEFITS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eating a diet rich in vegetables and almost devoid of fats,
doing three hours of workouts a week, meditating, and making other
ambitious lifestyle changes can delay, stop, and even reverse the
course of heart disease, according to a controversial new report.
</P>
<P>
   And rather than diminishing over time, the benefits expand, says
the study, led by best-selling author and California cardiologist
Dean Ornish. The opposite was true for a control group of patients
pursuing more moderate treatments, many of whom saw their condition
worsen over the five years they were followed.
</P>
<P>
   Most subjects in what admittedly was a small study also were
able to sustain their ambitious lifestyle changes for the full five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing before has looked at lifestyle changes over this long
a period,'' says Ornish, who helped develop a line of foods that
adhere to his low-fat criteria. ``In our study, patients got better
and better in our experimental group but worse and worse in the
control group, which shows that conventional American Heart
Association guidelines do not go far enough unless you also take
drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of his fellow cardiologists, however, take exception to
Ornish's scientific methods, question the safety of some therapies
he recommends and, most of all, wonder how many patients will
participate in a program that requires such dedication. ``The
question is not whether or not it works, but how implementable it
is,'' says Dr. Thomas Pearson, chairman of community and preventive
medicine at the University of Rochester and a spokesman for the
American Heart Association.
</P>
<P>
   The study, published in the current Journal of the American
Medical Association, is a followup to one Ornish published after a
single year of monitoring the patients, all of whom had moderate to
severe heart disease. Twenty of 28 patients in the original study
receiving aggressive treatment stuck with it through the five-year
followup, continuing to eat a 10 percent fat vegetarian diet, walk
about a half an hour a day, meditate or use other stress-reduction
techniques, and not smoking. Fifteen of 20 patients lasted the full
five years in the moderate-response group, most of whom ate more
fat and did fewer workouts, while some took cholesterol-lowering
drugs and had angioplastic surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Patients getting intensive treatment fared better on most
measures considered: They suffered less than half the rate of heart
attacks and other cardiac events at the end of five years, recorded
twice the reduction in angina, and saw their blood vessels getting
healthier, whereas those on the moderate course saw their blood
vessels constricting.
</P>
<P>
   Even more telling, Ornish says, is the trend with coronary
artherosclerosis between the one-year study and this new five-year
one: It got better among those on the intensive therapy, and
worsened for those on the more moderate program.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Charles Hennekens, chief of preventive medicine at
Brigham and Women's Hospital, says much of what Ornish reported
already was known. He also worries that Ornish's report is based on
too few patients to draw meaningful conclusions, that the treatment
programs were so demanding it ensures many patients will drop out,
and that because all the lifestyle changes were lumped together it
is impossible to tell which were more beneficial.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Frank Sacks, a professor of medicine and nutrition at
Harvard who has overseen several major heart studies on diet and
drugs, has an additional concern: that Ornish's program could be
dangerous with untested recommendations, like the one recommending
exercise to patients with heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Ornish has his defenders, however, including Dr. James Morgan,
chief of cardiology at Beth Israel Deaconess Hospital, which
participated in the Ornish program until funding dried up several
years ago. ``There's no question in my mind that it works,'' says
Morgan. ``It really depends on a person's nature whether they can
prescribe to this very, very rigorous program.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Rennie Drummond, deputy editor of JAMA, also is intrigued by
what Ornish found: ``If the findings are true, and if they are
confirmed by others, they could by important, very important. . . .
This is an intervention that doesn't require drugs and doesn't
require surgery for one of the commonest and most disabling and
most death-dealing diseases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
