</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-MOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TRIP SEEMS TO DISTANCE CLINTON FROM IMPEACHMENT WORRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (htv) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Near the end of his uniquely stressful Middle
Eastern trip, with the second House impeachment vote in history
looming before him on his return to Washington, President Clinton
unaccountably grinned Tuesday when asked how he managed, as he
claimed, to insulate the peace effort from his deepening political
woes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You show up for work every day,'' he said, his eyes crinkling
up. ``It's not a complicated thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who accompanied Clinton here, said:
``He's boring in. It may well be that his collateral problems are
giving him more motivation for success here.'' On the flight here
on Saturday, Specter said the president ``projects obliviousness''
about impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was a puzzle during this trip, even to some of his
aides. He was clearly concerned about the impeachment vote,
occasionally checking on his position in calls to the chief of
staff, John D. Podesta, or one of his congressional experts, Steve
Ricchetti. But when forced by reporters to address the matter, he
seemed almost indifferent, and gave sullen answers that risked
tipping away the fence-sitters whose support he needs.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared able to put the matter completely out of his head.
Tuesday afternoon, his helicopter flew between tourist stops
commemorating Christian hope in the city of Bethlehem and Jewish
martyrdom on the mountaintop of Masada, where ancient Israeli
soldiers killed themselves rather than surrender to the Romans. The
president gave no outward sign that he absorbed the symbolism. In
transit, he sat quietly reading ``The History of the Jews,'' by
Paul Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three days, Clinton gave two powerful, if somewhat
controversial, speeches on reinvigorating the peace effort, while
patiently shepherding Benjamin Netanyahu, the Israeli prime
minister, and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, back to the
bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   James Zogby, the president of the Arab American Institute, spoke
with Clinton at lunch in Gaza City on Monday, and found him wound
up about his address later that day to the Palestinian National
Council. ``I think he was totally with the moment,'' Zogby said.
``He gets into that teaching mode, you know, that he gets into. He
was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Tom DeLay, the House majority whip, warned on Sunday
that the president was losing authority in foreign affairs,
Specter, a firm supporter of Israel, called the trip ``a
significant success.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long deflected scandal and sustained his popularity
by focusing on his official duties and generating appealing
television images of himself and his family. But that approach
seems unlikely to help him much with his critical constituency now,
perhaps 30 undecided members of the House.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides acknowledged that the signs from Congress were
not positive for Clinton. ``You've got guys that we thought we
could get that have come out against us,'' a senior aide said.
``There are some people who are with us who seem to be softening.''
But ``the bottom line,'' he added, was that many members of the
House still had not declared a position.
</P>
<P>
   While they were in the Middle East, Clinton never spoke to his
congressional delegation about the possibility of impeachment,
according to Specter and White House aides. Indeed, it seemed on
Tuesday night that Clinton might drop his seeming indifference to
impeachment upon returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   While he and the congressmen did talk about other matters,
ranging from steel prices to scientific discoveries regarding stem
cells, they dwelled mostly on the peace effort, as they did during
a meeting for more than an hour over coffee and dessert on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has focused,'' Specter said this evening as Clinton left.
``He's been very, very good.'' Of course, the deep hatreds, deadly
threats and freighted negotiations here would seem likely to focus
even an easily distracted mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly energized by the trip,'' one of Clinton's
senior aides said. But at the same time, said another of his
advisers, also speaking on condition of anonymity, ``he's quite
aware of what's going on back home.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's tourism Tuesday seemed calculated more to advance the
peace effort than anything else, though the images of family comity
might also have pleased some Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In Bethlehem, with Arafat, Clinton managed to squeeze himself
through the 4-foot-high ``Door of Humility'' to enter the Church of
the Nativity. The president and his family spent about 10 minutes
in the basement, by the 14-point silver star that is said to mark
the spot where Jesus was born.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking demonstration of the strengthening relations
between the United States and a man it once treated as a terrorist,
Arafat and his wife, Suha, then stood side by side with the
Clintons as a choir of children sang ``O Little Town of Bethlehem''
and ``Joy to the World.'' Standing between her parents, Chelsea
looked up at her father with a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons then flew to Masada, a stark mountaintop by the
Dead Sea that is one of the Jews' most revered monuments to their
ancient struggle. For several months beginning in A.D. 72, a group
of 967 Jewish zealots held out there against a Roman siege before
their eventual suicides.
</P>
<P>
   With Netanyahu and his wife, Sara, the Clintons toured the site,
taking in the view of the Dead Sea and the Moab Mountains, and had
a traditional Middle Eastern meal of small mezze dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then in the last three days, Clinton has seemed to
veer in his public remarks toward an observation that applies as
easily to his predicament at home as to the peril here. In a toast
here on Sunday night, he said that during the mid-1980s, his former
pastor told him that he might be president some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will make mistakes,'' he recalled the pastor as having
said, ``and God will forgive you. But God will never forgive you if
you forget the State of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   He closed with a remark that could easily be read as a plea to
the House. ``We are instructed that they who judge without mercy
will be judged without mercy,'' Clinton said. ``But mercy triumphs
over judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
