<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON16-COX     12-15 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME AIDES URGE CLINTON TO MAKE PERSONAL PLEA TO HOUSE
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some White House advisers are urging President
Clinton to make a bold move to avert impeachment, such as going to
the well of the House and delivering a personal plea for censure,
former Clinton aide Lanny Davis said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal came as Clinton, who was flying back from Israel on
Tuesday, prepared to spend Wednesday seeking compromise with a
rapidly dwindling number of Republican moderates.
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication that he or first lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton planned to speak publicly on the impeachment topic, though
aides refused to rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast with reporters, Davis said a Clinton trip to
Capitol Hill could be effective because ``the president can make
his case in person before the full House better than anyone. He
should expose himself to that process, answer questions and be
prepared to acknowledge the reality of what he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said such a move, which would include an admission that he
had been ``less than truthful'' in testimony about his sexual
liaisons with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, may be the
only way left for the president to avoid becoming the second
president in U.S. history to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   The House convenes Thursday to begin considering four
impeachment articles, but the president has not decided whether to
follow advice that he address the members, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't embraced any particular proposal, but we generally
do welcome any opportunity to bring this to some bipartisan
closure,'' said White House spokesman Jim Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported by CNN that White House aides negotiated on
terms of a censure resolution proposed Tuesday by Rep. Michael
Castle of Delaware, a moderate Republican with close ties to
Clinton dating back to their days as governors.
</P>
<P>
   That resolution would require Clinton to ``personally'' pay $2
million over five years to defray half the $4 million expense of
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's eight-month inquiry into the
president's affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republican House leaders have indicated they will not
allow a vote on censure as an alternative to the impeachment votes
expected Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was also unclear Tuesday whether the leaders would Clinton to
make the House appearance suggested by his aides.
</P>
<P>
   But ``there are a lot of things in motion,'' said Rep. John
Conyers of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what happens in the House may depend on the outcome of
the president's planned meeting Wednesday with Rep. Christopher
Shays, a Connecticut Republican who once opposed impeachment but is
now wavering.
</P>
<P>
   Shays has said he wants Clinton to confess that he lied under
oath. But as a practical matter, the president is unlikely to offer
any such statement unless Shays shows he can deliver enough
moderate GOP votes to block impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the president's advisers have given up hope of stopping
impeachment and are preparing to fight it out in the Senate, said
Davis, a former White House special counsel. But a dramatic and
unprecedented appearance in the House by the president could still
sway enough moderate Republicans to avert a Senate trial of the
House-approved articles of impeachment, he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
