<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS &LR;      12-15 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS LOOK TO SENATE TO THWART IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With an increasing number of House Republicans
supporting impeachment, Democrats are exploring the possibility of
heading off a Senate trial through parliamentary maneuvers or a
bipartisan censure vote.
</P>
<P>
   While much attention has been paid to the expectation that the
Senate would vote to acquit Clinton, White House aides in recent
days have become concerned that a trial, in itself, could
politically strangle the presidency and galvanize public support
for Clinton's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials and Democrats Tuesday seized on a
suggestion by Clinton's former rival, 1996 Republican presidential
nominee Bob Dole, that the House and Senate adopt a joint
resolution calling for Clinton's censure. Senate Democrats are also
studying if they could muster 51 votes for a motion to dismiss the
impeachment articles before a trial starts.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph Lieberman, the Connecticut Democrat, said the
Senate has ``no choice'' other than to start a trial, but he
suggested the articles could be dismissed shortly thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of doubt about the procedures in a trial in the
Senate,'' Lieberman said. But, he said, it ``is clear that a
majority of the Senate will determine what should happen. What I
mean is that the rules provide for a motion to adjourn. One or
another party, presumably the defense counsel, could move to
dismiss, and then that's up to a majority of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole, in an op-ed page column in Tuesday's New York Times,
suggested the Senate could suspend the impeachment rules and allow
a vote on a House-Senate resolution censuring the president.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether there is a way to cancel the Senate trial.
But Democrats have one thing in their favor in the Senate: It takes
67 of 100 votes to convict a president, and Republicans hold only
55 seats. ``There is scarcely anyone who believes that the required
67 senators would vote to convict the president on any of the four
articles of impeachment approved by the House Judiciary Committee,
notwithstanding what the full House might do,'' Dole wrote.
</P>
<P>
   If the Republican leadership is convinced there is no chance to
convict Clinton in the Senate, then it might want to avoid a
months-long trial that many analysts believe could hurt the
Republican Party as well as the president. But GOP aides said it
seemed unlikely that both the House and Senate of the outgoing
105th Congress could agree on a joint resolution of censure by Jan.
2, as Dole suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Other options are also being studied. For example, Senator
Joseph Biden, the Delaware Democrat, is among a group of Clinton
supporters examining Senate procedure for a way to dismiss the
impeachment articles by a majority vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a will, there's a way, as long as you are not
dumbing down the Constitution,'' said Senator John F. Kerry, when
asked if a trial could be avoided. But the Massachusetts Democrat
said a major problem for him and other senators is that little
information has been distributed about the procedures surrounding a
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to suggest something that is constitutionally
impermissible,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if there is a way for the Senate to dismiss the impeachment
articles, such an effort probably could succeed only if Senate
majority leader Trent Lott allows a vote. If Lott wants a trial to
proceed, there may be no way for Democrats to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, asked recently whether the Senate must have a trial, left
the door open a crack: ``Do we have to? I don't think absolutely,
but I think it would be hard not to do that if the House votes one
or more articles'' of impeachment, Lott said. At another point, he
said, ``I think the Senate will have a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even if there is a trial, a Republican leadership aide
said it appears that any senator could make a motion at any time to
suspend it. If there are 51 votes _ presumably all 45 Democrats and
six Republicans _ then the trial would be suspended indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could conceive of that 51 number, but I can't conceive it
right away,'' said the aide, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is looking at whether a Senate trial could be
averted by a plea bargain agreement in which Clinton admits
wrongdoing and accepts a Senate rebuke and penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is expected to meet with Senate Democratic leaders after
the House vote to discuss procedure for an impeachment trial. Under
the current plan, the Senate would meet around Jan. 6 and formally
receive the articles from the House.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the trial would depend partly on White House
strategy. While Lott has said he would like the trial to be over in
a few weeks, it could take longer if either side calls numerous
witnesses. Senators are discussing whether certain normal courtroom
rules apply, such as the ability of each side to participate in the
``discovery'' process, during which evidence would be examined and
depositions might be taken.
</P>
</TEXT>
