<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1418 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS &LR;      12-15 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON FAILS TO BUDGE ISRAEL FROM ITS ULTIMATUM DURING MIDEAST
TRIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ President Clinton claimed achievements for peace
Tuesday but failed to budge Israel from its ultimatum that no more
territory will be ceded to Palestinians until they renounce
statehood declarations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flew to the sandswept military outpost of Erez to meet
with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian Authority
Chairman Yasser Arafat in an attempt to get a U.S.-brokered peace
plan back on track.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's pronouncements before he returned to
Washington, the status of the Wye River peace agreement remained
uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   After the 90-minute session at the Israeli-Gaza Strip border,
Clinton said progress had been made but Arafat left hurriedly
without talking to reporters and Netanyahu reiterated his intention
to delay a troop withdrawal from occupied West Bank lands that was
supposed to take place Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be unfortunate if we got too far behind
schedule, and I hope we can keep pretty much to the schedule that's
there,'' Clinton said following the meeting. ``I do think that we
are back on track. We're going to see this through, and I feel good
about where we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
return to the region next week to continue negotiations. ``So I
have achieved what I came here to achieve ... and we'll just keep
at it,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Samuel ``Sandy''
Berger, later tempered Clinton's remarks, adding that ``I think
it's a bumpy track, but it's (the peace process) on track.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-way summit capped Clinton's visit to the Middle East
to revive the Wye River Memorandum that called on Israel to
withdraw troops from an additional 13 percent of the West Bank in
return for security guarantees from Palestinians. The marathon
negotiations at the Maryland retreat came after 18 months of
stalemate between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   The accord became unsettled last month as Israel refused to
release Palestinian prisoners it considered terrorists, prompting
several violent confrontations from stone-throwing Palestinian
youths.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Netanyahu faces a no-confidence vote Monday from
hard-liners opposed to the Wye River provisions, and several
Israeli media &UR;  &LR; reports indicated the prime minister wanted to delay
further troop withdrawals in hopes of averting his government's
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a redeployment speedily, as soon as the
Palestinians fulfill their part,'' Netanyahu told reporters. ``I
can't tell you how much time it will take, but the faster they do
it, the faster we will redeploy.'' He denied taking the stance to
help his political situation.
</P>
<P>
   During the Erez session, the prime minister gave Clinton and
Arafat a 12-point list of alleged violations to the Wye River pact
by the Palestinians. The list restated Netanyahu's demand that
Arafat renounce intentions to declare a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Netanyahu's office also listed demands that the
Palestinian Authority crack down on violence, stop incitements,
accept Israel's prisoner release criteria, seize weapons and reduce
the size of the Palestinian police force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are waiting for the Palestinians to respect the rest of
their obligations,'' Netanyahu said. ``All that they have done
until now is contrary to their commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians, who made a symbolic gesture Monday as they voted
to rescind charter provisions calling for Israel's destruction,
were angered by the turn of events.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat adviser Marwan Kanafani criticized Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is intentionally crushing all efforts that Clinton exerted
and is stopping the implementation of an agreement he personally
signed,'' Kanafani said. ``What Netanyahu constantly repeats in his
statements further reinforces the doubts of the Palestinian people
about his intentions to carry out the peace agreements.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton said he saw significant progress from talks
with Netanyahu and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the two sides agreed to create an informal channel
to deal with the difficult issue of prisoner releases as well as to
``vigorously pursue the security issue'' and ``energize'' the final
status talks. That last round of negotiations, required under the
1993 peace treaty, would attempt to resolve even more difficult
issues such as the status of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have fits and starts, there will be hard parts, but
we'll get though this. We'll get through this just fine and it will
come out where it ought to,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the president left the region with many Israelis also
upset that his historic journey to the Gaza Strip on Monday was a
tacit endorsement of Palestinian statehood. Many also are upset by
Clinton's speech to the Palestinians in which he equated the pain
of Palestinian children whose fathers were jailed to the pain of
Israeli children whose fathers had been killed in conflict. The
remark was part of a plea to end the suffering of children on both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made clear to the president that his remarks caused deep
shock among Israelis,'' said Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon, a hard-liner, refused again to shake hands with Arafat,
whom he refers as a murderer.
</P>
<P>
   After the session in Erez, Clinton flew to the West Bank city of
Bethlehem where he joined first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
daughter Chelsea for a tour of the Church of the Nativity, site of
Jesus Christ's birth. Arafat and his wife, Suha, escorted the
Clintons through the church.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons also flew to Masada where they joined Netanyahu for
a tour of the symbol of Jewish resolve. The mesa is where 960 Jews
chose death rather than surrender to Romans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
