<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASEAN-TRADE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIAN LEADERS EXPECTED TO EASE TRADE, INVESTMENT RULES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Over the last year and a half, everyone from Asian
prime ministers to American politicians to international fund
managers has offered solutions to a vexing financial crisis that
has ravaged what was the world's fastest-growing region.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Southeast Asian leaders are expected to liberalize
trade and investment rules to lure money back to Asia. Leaders of
the nine-member Association of Southeast Asian Nations meeting in
Hanoi will present a package of immodestly labeled ``bold
measures,'' including corporate tax exemptions, permission for
foreign ownership of certain ventures and tariff reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But beneath ASEAN's veneer of consensus lies a widely
contradictory set of economic policies, and a deep philosophical
divide over whether the best way to overcome the economic turmoil
is by opening markets or closing them.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, seventeen months into Asia's worst financial crisis in
half a century, leaders are still debating whether free markets
were not only the cause of record growth but also the root of
financial vulnerability and collapse. The lack of a coherent,
consistent response to the slump suggests that a reliable diagnosis
and region-wide recovery are a long way off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When consensus forms, there's stability. When there's no
consensus, there's volatility,'' said Christopher Lingle, an
economist and author of The Rise and Decline of the Asian Century.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over how to address the crisis also underscores
a clash of ideologies _ over free markets versus protectionism and
democracy versus authoritarianism. That debate has become a
generational tug-of-war, as many older and entrenched leaders have
tried to hold back modernization, while newly elected or younger
leaders have mostly pushed for reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The authoritarianism that everybody was praising for so long
as Asian values _ with leaders like (Singapore's) Lee Kuan Yew and
(Malaysia's) Mahathir Mohamad _ was just a way of justifying an
authoritarian government,'' said Ken Davies, an economist and chief
Asian editor of the Economist Intelligence Unit. ``Now the theory
is being disproved by Asians themselves _ by the Taiwanese, the
South Koreans and the Thais.''
</P>
<P>
   A dramatic dichotomy over how the address the crisis has emerged
between ASEAN members Thailand and Malaysia. Thai Prime Minister
Chuan, who last year unseated a government that presided over the
collapse of the Thai currency, has liberalized markets and
restructured financial institutions. Despite political opposition
at home, he has won praise for adhering to reforms demanded as
conditions of a multi-billion-dollar International Monetary Fund
bailout.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir has blamed
foreign speculators for his nation's problems, and three months ago
alienated international investors by imposing capital controls to
protect markets from outside influences. He also infuriated Western
governments by jailing his free market-oriented finance minister on
sodomy and corruption charges, a move Mahathir's critics say he
took to defend his dwindling authority.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Malaysia's much-maligned response to the crisis has not been
entirely one-sided. Even as Mahathir criticized foreign
stockbrokers, he liberalized foreign ownership of stock brokerages
and telecom companies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whether a government reacts in the main to the crisis by
turning inward or outward depends on what leaders see as the root
of their woes. ``Mahathir's view is that this is the result of
speculators, so his solution is to stop speculators. But if you
take the view that this is only part of it, and there were other
structural problems, then you will try to solve those structural
problems as Thailand and South Korea are trying to do,'' said Bruce
Gale, Southeast Asia regional manager for Political and Economic
Risk Consultancy.
</P>
<P>
   The divergence between Asian neighbors over how to solve the
crisis has repeated itself elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   After Hong Kong's government intervened in the stock market to
defend its currency in August, rival city-state Singapore cut
capital ratio requirements and investor incentives to capitalize on
Hong Kong's apparent backsliding on free-market principles. The
policy debate came into stark relief two weeks ago when the
Washington, D.C.-based Heritage Foundation warned Hong Kong that it
would lose its title as the world's freest economy to Singapore
because of the $15 billion stock buying spree.
</P>
<P>
   There are many investors, however, such as Giampaolo Guarnieri,
director of Asia Pacific equities for Salomon Smith Barney, who say
Hong Kong has done nothing to restrict capital or investment. Even
after Hong Kong's market intervention, he said, it is still a freer
and more transparent place to do business than anywhere else in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Singapore is a place where the government intervenes in
everything _ you can't even chew gum. Right now they happen to be
intervening to make the economy better, so that's good _ but it's
still intervention,'' Guarnieri said. Nevertheless, he praised
efforts there and elsewhere to open markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trend is for economies to basically open up, allow more
foreign investment in various sectors, which is new in certain
Asian countries. The trend for financial markets is to be better
controlled and regulated,'' he said, adding that Hong Kong's new
rules on short-selling stock merely mirror regulations in the
United States. ``Before, it was complete cowboy land here.''
</P>
<P>
   Policy debates exist not only between neighbors, but also within
countries. In Indonesia and South Korea, where new presidents have
tried to open markets and eliminate privileges, opposition from
entrenched business interests has made a consistent national policy
response impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Vvested interests and ideological differences have also
agreement on regional recovery plans elusive. A month ago, leaders
who gathered for the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in
Kuala Lumpur failed to agree on a plan for reviving the region. And
though ASEAN is expected to announce a regional free trade zone by
2002, analysts say policies implemented by each country will
influence investors far more than collective promises.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because ASEAN is seen by many as a toothless
tiger, allowing members to do as they like and fudge deadlines.
More importantly, agreement on what caused the crisis must come
before a regional blueprint for its solution.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Faber, managing director of his own investment firm here,
disagrees with those who say Asia will emerge from the crisis freer
and less feudal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the whole crisis will strengthen the old Asian system,
because it has created animosity to Western capitalism. Most
businessmen don't blame themselves for the crisis; they blame the
Western system or Western speculators,'' Faber said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Guarnieri says public opinion has been too harsh
on Asia. ``They expect Asian people and governments to take steps
that took the US and Europe decades,'' he said. ``We've got
economies who've built overcapacity in record time, and boom _ the
financial sector explodes and they have to reform. Give them time.
They've already implemented changes in record time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
