<HEADLINE>
PROFESSORS WIN BATTLE WITH MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Microsoft Corp. has lost again in its First Amendment
legal battle with two Boston-area business professors.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge federal appeals court panel in Boston Tuesday
upheld a lower court ruling that denies Microsoft access to tapes
and research notes generated by the professors, who have written a
book about Microsoft's rival Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Professors David Yoffie of Harvard Business School and Michael
Cusumano of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology conducted
lengthy interviews with Netscape executives while writing
``Competing on Internet Time: Lessons from Netscape and Its Battle
with Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft believed that information in these notes could help
the company prepare its defense in an ongoing federal antitrust
case.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has accused Microsoft of using its
dominance in personal computer software to unfairly undermine
competitors including Netscape, which was once the leading maker of
Internet browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft attorneys hoped that the notes collected by Yoffie and
Cusumano would paint a different picture, and so the company tried
to subpoena their notes.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoffie and Cusumano contested the subpoena, arguing that
Microsoft's action posed a severe threat to academic freedom under
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Yoffie and Cusumano warned that few prominent business
executives would give interviews to scholars if they feared that
the unedited interview notes could end up in court someday.
</P>
<P>
   In October, the federal district court agreed with the
professors, and Microsoft appealed.
</P>
<P>
   But the appellate court also sided with Yoffie and Cusumano.
While conceding that Microsoft had a legitimate interest in
obtaining the information, the court said that Microsoft was free
to subpoena the Netscape officials in order to get the information.
Forcing scholars to hand over their research notes ``would
hamstring not only the respondents' future research efforts, but
also those of other similarly situated scholars,'' the appellate
court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the court held that such an outcome would have a
chilling effect on the flow of information to the public, raising
serious First Amendment concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Tom Pilla said the company has not yet
decided its next move, but continues to believe it is entitled to
the information in the Yoffie-Cusumano notes. ``We believe that the
Cusumano tapes, which contain candid interviews with Netscape
executives, represents evidence with a direct bearing on the
antitrust case brought by the government,'' Pilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Albano, the attorney representing Yoffie, praised the
appeals court decision. ``To me the most significant thing about
the case is that the First Circuit Court of Appeals continues to
recognize that confidential sources, whether used by journalists or
by scholars, deserve protection,'' Albano said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
