<HEADLINE>
POP STANDARDS AND CABARET LOSING NEW YORK OUTLETS, LEAVING A
CULTURAL GAP
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In this town, birthplace of the Broadway musical, the
Brill Building, the Cotton Club, Carnegie Hall and the Copacabana,
the musical past and present continually refresh each other in a
way that happens nowhere else in the country. Nothing of musical
value ever really seems to die. That's why the thought of a New
York climate in which the voices of Frank Sinatra, Ella Fitzgerald,
Tony Bennett and a dozen others like them can't be heard regularly
on the radio is almost unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   But after midnight on Dec. 27, when WQEW (1560 AM), the only New
York outlet for popular music predating rock, closes shop after six
years to become a Disney-operated children's station, those voices
will have almost completely vanished from the local airwaves. The
station, owned by The New York Times Co., , has been leased for
eight years to ABC Inc., a Disney subsidiary that will provide the
new programming.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, almost simultaneously with the format shift,
Rainbow and Stars, the city's leading cabaret, will close its doors
forever, as its lease and that of the adjoining Rainbow Room pass
into new hands.
</P>
<P>
   WQEW is not exactly a temple of enlightened nostalgia; but with
its passing, a vital link to our shared cultural past is being
severed. What will be absent from the airwaves is an ideal of
civility exemplified by popular singers conveying the deepest
personal emotions in intimate voices.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you might hear Sinatra's ``Strangers in the Night'' now and
then on an oldies station, but nowhere will you hear his music
explored with anything close to the depth and passion that WQEW's
resident Sinatra-phile, the disk jockey and author Jonathan
Schwartz, has brought to his weekly Saturday show devoted to the
singer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there will be television specials celebrating vintage
American pop on PBS and biographies of pre-rock pop singers on the
A&AMP;E and E! networks. Sinatra will certainly not be forgotten in New
York or anywhere else, and Bennett will keep making records.
</P>
<P>
   But no longer will there be a place you can tune into any time
and find the world of Sinatra, Fitzgerald and the big bands, of
Rodgers and Hart, Cole Porter, Duke Ellington and the Gershwins.
This is the music Schwartz, the station's resident pundit, has
called ``American classical music,'' even if the station dilutes it
with kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   The closing of Rainbow and Stars is a stunning and unfortunate
coincidence. The club, on the 65th floor of the General Electric
building in Rockefeller Center, brought a touch of old-time
nightclub glamour to midtown. Since opening with a solo engagement
by Bennett in 1989, traditional pop singers like Rosemary Clooney
(who played there almost every year), Vic Damone and Margaret
Whiting have appeared there, as have worthy successors like Maureen
McGovern, Susannah McCorkle, Karen Akers, Mary Cleere Haran, Amanda
McBroom, Ann Hampton Callaway, Michael Feinstein and David
Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   The club also presented quite a few revues (of wildly uneven
quality) surveying the contributions of pre-rock American composers
from Irving Berlin to the Gershwins to Leonard Bernstein. I'll
never forget a brilliant Rodgers and Hart show in which Elaine
Stritch, drawling in her parched whisky voice, delivered
show-stopping performances of ``10 Cents a Dance'' and ``Zip'' that
turned these gems into sustained, profoundly witty wisecracks.
</P>
<P>
   During the six years they were operating at the same time, WQEW
and Rainbow and Stars cultivated a policy of mutual cooperation.
Artists who were appearing at the club were regularly interviewed
on WQEW, and this synergy benefited everyone. Devotees of
traditional pop could discern a continuity between older and
younger generations of performers, and a genuine if tenuous sense
of a traditional pop music community was established.
</P>
<P>
   As much as the station and the club will be missed, however, it
would be foolish to pretend that their simultaneous disappearance
will mean that paradise has been lost. Both institutions had to
operate in the tough real world of television-dominated media,
driven by ratings and box office. For all its commitment to
tradition, WQEW (with the exception of Schwartz's 25 hours a week
on the air) generally took the low and easy road in its
programming.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow and Stars, which had to struggle merely to break even,
lost money on many of its best shows. Like other cabarets in New
York, it found that the pool of significant younger talent and the
audience to support it were not large enough to guarantee financial
success.
</P>
<P>
   And high-end cabaret is very pricey. The biggest draws were
often television personalities with marginal musical talents like
Kathie Lee Gifford, Tony Danza and Cybill Shepherd who dipped into
cabaret as a lark.
</P>
<P>
   Television values also dictated which performers would get
invaluable free publicity on morning talk shows, with youth and
good looks often chosen over experience and artistic depth. But in
general, television bookers shunned the entire field of cabaret as
old hat. Even Rosie O'Donnell, the Broadway musical's most vocal
cheerleader on television, has rarely deigned to explore a cabaret
world that is to some degree an offshoot of Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   In its programming, WQEW played it safe by acting most of the
time like a Top 40 radio station. Instead of insisting on quality,
it relied on the pop charts of the 1940s and '50s. Even the most
cursory glance at the hit parades of four, five and six decades ago
finds them clogged with silly novelties and saccharine ballads. At
the same time, many of the pop songs we now call standards never
hit the upper reaches of the charts in their day.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perry Como and Patti Page, two of WQEW's most-played artists,
are certainly capable singers. But the roster of their hits amounts
to a dreary junk heap of disposable pop trinkets: Como's ``Hot
Diggity (Dog Ziggity Boom),'' ``Papa Loves Mambo,'' ``Wanted,''
``Round and Round'' and ``Catch a Falling Star,'' and Ms. Page's
``I Went to Your Wedding,'' ``Mr. and Mississippi,'' ``Changing
Partners,'' and ``Cross Over the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Although these trite ditties exert a certain nostalgic appeal,
as a steady musical diet they are about as tasty and edifying as
Wonder Bread served every day at breakfast, lunch and dinner.
</P>
<P>
   That diet has also included heavy doses of vocal groups like the
Four Aces, the Ames Brothers, the Four Lads and the McGuire
Sisters. Their vapid '50s hits remind you of why the rock-and-roll
upsurge was inevitable. When WQEW ventured into the '60s and '70s,
its taste veered toward the smarmiest pop by Barry Manilow, Helen
Reddy, Neil Diamond and Engelbert Humperdinck.
</P>
<P>
   With the notable exception of Schwartz, WQEW's reliance on
formula extended to its disk jockeys, who were little more than
announcers identifying the tunes they were given to play. When all
is said and done, Schwartz's vision of American classical music
remained sadly unrealized on his very own station.
</P>
<P>
   Already a search for a new radio outlet for traditional pop is
under way. The ideal solution would be the vintage pop and jazz
equivalent of a free-form FM rock station of the late 1960s and
early '70s. But would the public that supports traditional pop
music tune into a station that didn't concentrate on the hits? My
guess is that it would.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of WQEW and Rainbow and Stars hardly means that it's
all over for traditional pop in New York. The cabaret scene
flourishes at Cafe Carlyle, the Oak Room of the Algonquin Hotel,
the Firebird Cafe, Eighty-Eight's and other clubs. Tuesday night a
brand new mid-level Manhattan club, the Garrick Gaieties, opened in
the Mayfair Hotel (242 W. 49th St.), with Claiborne Cary and
Phillip Officer. City Center's Encores series of Broadway musical
revivals in concert is a huge success. The 92nd St. Y's Lyrics and
Lyricists series rolls on even after the death of its artistic
director, Maurice Levine. And the Mabel Mercer Foundation's annual
cabaret convention at Town Hall, a kind of clearing house of talent
from around the country, has become an October perennial, despite
the unwieldy length of its events and the amateurish quality of
many performances.
</P>
<P>
   In early February, Lincoln Center will unveil its American
Songbook series, the pop music equivalent of Classical Jazz, which
later evolved into Jazz at Lincoln Center. When tickets went on
sale for the first four shows of the American Songbook in February
and March at Alice Tully Hall, they were sold out in a matter of
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The roster of singers for the first program, devoted to the life
and music of Harold Arlen, is a potent mixture of Broadway and
cabaret talent. Schwartz, the series' artistic director and host,
will bring to the stage the same mixture of erudition and
enthusiasm that have earned him a loyal following (and some
detractors who dislike his tendency toward pomposity). But the
instant demand for the American Songbook series suggests that the
market for traditional pop is larger and hungrier than many like to
imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Here are two New Year's wishes, neither of which seems an
impossible dream.
</P>
<P>
   The first is for the establishment of a new traditional pop
station that is not so hit-oriented. Instead of Ms. Clooney's
novelty hits ``Botch-a-Me'' and ``Come On-a My House,'' you'd be
able to hear her little known masterpieces like her album ``Love,''
recorded with Nelson Riddle. Instead of the incessant repetition of
Bennett's ``Rags to Riches,'' you would get generous helpings from
his two brilliant duet albums with pianist Bill Evans. There would
be a lot more Billie Holiday, Ella Fitzgerald, and Sarah Vaughan
(not singing her trite ``Broken-Hearted Melody'' but the Gershwin
songbook). Alongside Glenn Miller and Artie Shaw, you would hear a
lot of Count Basie, Claude Thornhill and Miles Davis. And
absolutely no Guy Mitchell, ever.
</P>
<P>
   The other is for the return of a top-of-the-line cabaret of
Rainbow and Stars' caliber that would combine the best of the old
while bringing jazzier artists into its fold. Musical quality, not
television, would determine the booking policy. And New York would
finally have the supreme nightclub it deserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
