<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIEDEN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `NOT NEW YORK' SHOP SWITCHES TACTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., Ore., Pa.)  (rl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of America's most creative agencies is hoping
that the coming-out party for its New York office will be a beer
blast.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, which is seeking to raise the
profiles of the larger offices beyond its headquarters in Portland,
Ore. As part of those ambitious efforts, the agency's New York
office has been assigned an important task: leading the pitch for
the creative portion of the Miller Lite beer account, with billings
estimated at $150 million, in a review now being conducted by the
Miller Brewing Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for that is to give us a clean look at that
challenge,'' said Dan Wieden, president of Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, in a
telephone interview from his office in Portland. ``And it's a
pretty intense challenge.'' The Wieden creative presentation is
scheduled for Friday; a decision is expected in January.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's increased attention to New York is intriguing
because it was a pioneer in the decentralization trend of the 1980s
that significantly reduced New York's hegemony in the advertising
world.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful advertising centers emerged in cities like Portland,
Minneapolis and San Francisco, where Wieden and other shops
including Fallon McElligott and the Goodby, Silverstein &AMP; Partners
unit of Omnicom Group competed against _ and often beat _ the
longtime giants of Madison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   From its main office, Wieden poured out high-energy,
high-profile campaigns for marketers like Nike, Microsoft, ESPN and
Coca-Cola. Even when the agency made an earlier foray onto the East
Coast, to handle the Subaru of America account, the office was in
Philadelphia, not New York.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Wieden &AMP; Kennedy bandwagon encounters speed bumps,
particularly in its relationship with Nike, the agency is pressing
to expand by landing new business at its other major offices, which
include Amsterdam, London and Tokyo in addition to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether it was contradictory for an agency that was a
primary force in the ``not New York'' movement to begin promoting
its presence there, Wieden replied, laughing: ``I remember all my
old speeches about `the belly of the beast.' It's hard to eat my
own words and save some sense of dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because the industry is decentralized doesn't mean New
York is no longer a player,'' Wieden said. ``New York is a huge
player.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to wrestle with this business,'' he added,
``you might as well wrestle where the main stage is.''
</P>
<P>
   The top managers of the New York office, all longtime employees
of the agency, agreed with Wieden's assessment in an interview last
week at their office on lower Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the Amtrak into New York from Philadelphia, we always
felt we were going into the nerve center of advertising,'' said
Stacy Wall, 31, co-creative director.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wasn't a question of `Now we have to tackle New
York,''' he added, ``because the work we were doing was already
tackling the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Wall said, ``as the years have gone by, we've gained a
certain amount of confidence in our abilities'' to vie for
assignments in the overcrowded New York market.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added with a smile, ``it's nice to use Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy experience to help build Wieden &AMP; Kennedy, because a lot of
other people here in New York and elsewhere are using Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy experience to build other agencies.''
</P>
<P>
   The office opened in April 1995 to buy commercial time for Nike
and Microsoft. Two years later, it was upgraded to a full-service
office with the transfer of the ESPN account from Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't have some clients if we didn't have a presence in
New York,'' said Tom Winner, 52, broadcast media director, who
described himself as ``employee one'' there.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the New York office handled creative assignments with
billings estimated at $30 million out of an agency total of $875
million. This year, the figure has increased to about $50 million
of $835 million, lower because of cutbacks by Nike. There are 30
employees in New York and 257 in Portland; the worldwide total is
457.
</P>
<P>
   The work from New York for ESPN, a unit of the Walt Disney Co.,
includes the hugely popular campaign for ``Sports Center,'' offbeat
ads for the new ESPN Magazine and a campaign for the network's
coverage of the Women's National Basketball Association that
features a band paying homage to 1970s funk music.
</P>
<P>
   Other accounts include Suretrade Inc., an online brokerage
service, and the CK One fragrance marketed by Unilever and Calvin
Klein; that campaign, in collaboration with CRK Advertising,
Klein's in-house agency, is centered on tales told through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it would be great to have Miller Lite at Wieden &AMP;
Kennedy,'' said Tom Blessington, 36, managing director of the New
York office. ``It's fair to say the agency has rededicated itself
to new business, which was something we were not actively seeking
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   And ``it has taken us some time to assemble the team,'' he
added, such as the recent hiring of Lisa Welch-Nehring, 29, as
strategic planning director, from the TBWA/Chiat/Day unit of
Omnicom.
</P>
<P>
   Wieden has been an agency for Miller, owned by the Philip Morris
Cos., since late 1996, handling the creative duties for the Miller
Genuine Draft and Miller High Life beer brands from Portland.
Miller Lite, the best-selling Miller brand, has been at Fallon
McElligott during that same time; that agency is also taking part
in the review, as are three other shops.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to have the New York office take part in the Miller
Lite review serves two purposes, Blessington said: to focus
attention on the office and to reassure Miller executives that
Portland employees ``managing the other two brands will not take
their eye off the ball to pursue Lite.'' The Portland office is
working on revamping ads for Miller Genuine Draft.
</P>
<P>
   Wall and Michael Prieve, 35, the other co-creative director,
declined to discuss specific aspects of their pitch for Miller
Lite. The review comes after critics castigated the brand's ads as
too unconventional and too narrowly focused on men in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   Wall compared the agency's ideas to the ideas behind ``the work
we do for ESPN, which is really smart but really inclusive, across
a range of demographics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to return Miller Lite to being the brand of Sunday
afternoon football,'' he added, ``to get America laughing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Wieden be able to thrive in New York, where the intensity
of competition is no laughing matter?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard market,'' Wieden said. ``I'll tell you that. It
doesn't take kindly to outsiders, especially to those who have
mouthed off a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have a lot of work to do,'' he added, ``and New York is
clearly critical to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
