<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RULES-NYT &LR;      12-15 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT VOTE COULD TURN ON PARLIAMENTARIAN'S RULING 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT).  
(nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The vote on impeachment in the House of
Representatives this week could turn in part on a ruling on an
arcane point by the scrupulously impartial parliamentarian, Charles
W. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 59, a lawyer who has worked in the parliamentarian's
office his entire professional life, was appointed to the top
position in 1994 when Democrats still controlled Congress. He is
only the third person to hold the job in the last 70 years.
</P>
<P>
   What the public will see on television at the end of the
impeachment debate will look spontaneous, but it will have been
carefully scripted.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat, probably Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the
minority leader, will get recognized and offer a motion to send the
impeachment measure back to the Judiciary Committee with
instructions to the committee to produce a resolution of censure,
not impeachment. This is called a motion to recommit with
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats believe they will have the best chance to defeat the
impeachment resolution if wavering lawmakers have the alternative
of voting to censure President Clinton. But the House Judiciary
Committee rejected a censure proposal last week.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders have the authority to bring up the
impeachment resolution in a way that would permit a direct vote on
censure. But they have declined to do so because they fear it could
drain crucial votes from the impeachment side.
</P>
<P>
   After the motion to recommit is offered, a Republican will make
a point of order that the motion is, in parliamentary language, not
germane to the impeachment resolution. Clause 7 of House Rule XVI,
written in 1789, states that ``no motion or proposition on a
subject different from that under consideration shall be
admitted.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where Charlie Johnson comes in. A tall, round-faced man
with short gray hair, Johnson will advise the presiding officer,
Rep. Ray LaHood, R-Ill., on how to rule on the motion. LaHood, as
presiding officers always do, will take Johnson's advice.
</P>
<P>
   No one involved will be surprised by the ruling. Democrats were
still working Tuesday night on the wording of their recommittal
motion. They have been consulting with Johnson extensively about
what would be germane and what would not.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will know in advance what the Democratic motion will
say. When LaHood rules, he will read a statement that Johnson will
have written ahead of time. Democrats may disagree with the ruling.
But in a House riven by partisan discord, it is safe to bet that no
one will attribute the ruling to partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview Tuesday, Johnson would not say how he might
rule. He is the archetype of a civil servant who shuns the
spotlight and would not allow himself to be photographed for this
article. When he registered to vote in his hometown, Bethesda, Md.,
he declined to state his party affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson joined the parliamentarian's office in 1964 right out of
the University of Virginia Law School. He said today that he wanted
``nonpartisan legal work in Congress.'' He rose to deputy
parliamentarian in 1974 and was appointed parliamentarian in
September 1994, when Democrats still controlled the House.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, he was reappointed by Speaker Newt Gingrich in 1995
and again in 1997. By custom, the position of parliamentarian does
not change hands when party control of the House changes. Johnson's
predecessor, William H. Brown, served from 1974 until he retired in
1994. Lewis Deschler was the parliamentarian from 1928 until 1974.
</P>
<P>
   The expectation in the House is that Johnson will not allow a
recommittal motion that uses the word ``censure'' because it is not
directly pertinent to impeachment. But students of parliamentary
procedure say he almost certainly will allow a motion stating that
impeachment is not warranted. The question is whether the Democrats
can find something in between that would swing undecided votes.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling on germaneness would not be final. It could be
appealed by the Democrats and overturned by a majority vote of the
House. And if a motion involving censure is termed nongermane,
Democrats will probably make such an appeal and pose it as a chance
to vote for censure.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospects for success are poor. In the last 60 years,
Johnson said, the chair's ruling has been reversed only four times,
never on a matter of national importance.
</P>
<P>
   It is easier to find votes for the impeachment of the president
than it is to overrule the parliamentarian.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1952EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
