A1448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCKERBIE-LIBYA-BOS &LR;      12-15 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCKERBIE-LIBYA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OF LOCKERBIE SUSPECTS A STEP CLOSER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Days before the 10th anniversary of the bombing of
a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, Libya's legislative body has
taken a step toward allowing two suspects to be put on trial in a
neutral country.
</P>
<P>
   Libya's General People's Congress has approved of a request by
the United States and Britain to hold a trial in the Netherlands,
according to a Libyan TV broadcast Tuesday. The legislators also
called on Libya, Britain, and the United States to ``remove any
obstacle'' blocking the start of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the US government and the United Nations said the
reports were a good sign, but academics who specialize in
international law said the trial in the Netherlands raises tricky
legal questions. Once such international prosecutions in third
countries begin, US officials and agents involved in covert actions
might face similar proceedings, said Al Rubin, a professor of
international law at the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at
Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is very weird,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Under a plan that UN Secretary General Kofi Annan presented 10
days ago in a visit to Libya, the country's leader, Moammar
Khadafy, must surrender the two suspects for a trial. The United
Nations has kept an air and arms embargo on Libya, and has frozen
the country's assets abroad over the Dec. 21, 1988, bombing, which
many US officials say Khadafy masterminded.
</P>
<P>
   Years of wrangling, negotiations, and accusations have failed to
solve the crime, which killed 270 people, including 23 from New
England. Relatives of the victims are angry and US officials warn
that those behind the bombing must be convicted and imprisoned if
potential terrorists are to be deterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice has been delayed for almost 10 years . . . It is time
for Libya to meet its obligations,'' said a White House spokesman,
P. J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   At the United Nations, a senior official expressed hope tinged
by skepticism that the trial of the two men is imminent. ``We'll
believe it when we see them on the airplane'' coming to the
Netherlands, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sketchy news from Libya left Khadafy room Tuesday to maneuver
and backtrack. The General People's Congress, composed of about 500
representatives from lower level assemblies, is controlled by
Khadafy but he has not publicly endorsed the decision. And the
announcement did not answer logistical questions, such as how Libya
would deliver the two suspects, who are believed to be government
agents.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, detectives tracked a suitcase with a bomb on the plane
to two men, Abdul Basset Ali Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah. US
officials indicted them. Their lawyer, Frank Rubino, says they are
innocent. Libya has refused to deport them.
</P>
<P>
   If the suspects are sent to trial, ``it is a major development,
clearly a victory for international adjudication and the
possibility of the victims' families getting some sense of
justice,'' said Christopher C. Joyner, a professor of international
law at Georgetown University. Also, he said, any capitulation by
Khadafy would be a sign that sanctions are squeezing Libya.
</P>
<P>
   But Joyner, too, voiced doubts. ``The major question that is
unanswered: Why would Khadafy want to go forward with the trial,
allow these two individuals to speak out in public and perhaps
implicate him?''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin and other specialists say it will be difficult to set the
rules for a trial for a crime that allegedly was committed by
Libyans in international air space, involving an American airliner
that took off from British soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are going to be the judges?'' asked Rubin, the Tufts
professor, who has served as chairman of a terrorism committee of
the 130-year-old International Law Association. ``Does the Scottish
law apply in the case? How are these two guys supposed to get to
Netherlands, and what happens to them if they are convicted?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the men would be tried under Scottish law
and serve time in Britain if convicted. But Libya's foreign affairs
minister, Omar Mustapha al-Montasser, has said that his country
wanted the two suspects to be jailed in Libya if found guilty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
