<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1449 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PALESTINIANS-     12-15 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PALESTINIANS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS CALL FIRST FAMILY'S VISIT `GOOD FOR US' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHLEHEM, West Bank _ Down crumbling alleyways so narrow a car
can't pass through, electric banners flash neon Manger scenes above
tiny shops where Christmas trees and plastic Santas are sold.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the maze of alleys that is Old Bethlehem opens up into
Manger Square, under construction for celebrations in the year
2000. Near the church built over the traditional birthplace of
Jesus, President Clinton on Tuesday lit a candle on a Christmas
tree decked in red and white velvet ribbons for the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   He had just emerged from the fourth-century grotto with his
wife, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, and their daughter,
Chelsea, to sing Christmas carols with a Palestinian choir. Yasser
Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and his wife, Soha, stood by his
side.
</P>
<P>
   The visit, just before Christmas, was the symbolic part of
Clinton's pre-holiday trip to the Holy Land _ and his first to
Palestinian-ruled soil _ and thousands of Palestinians crammed into
the square to get a glimpse of the presidential family.
</P>
<P>
   ``His visit here is good for us,'' said Issa Sallah, a
Palestinian construction worker standing on tiptoe to get a better
look. ``We hope that Clinton can help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how it felt to be in Bethlehem, Clinton said:
``Magnificent, thank you. I'm very grateful for the chance.``
</P>
<P>
   But for Palestinians, it didn't matter what the president said.
To them, his visit, first to Gaza and then to Palestinian-ruled
Bethlehem on the West Bank, signals a new-found friendship that
most here hope can bring substantive gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want Clinton to help free Palestinian prisoners,'' said
Mohammed Odeh, a vegetable vendor standing amid the crowd. ``We
want him to pressure Israel to open the safe passage (route to the
Gaza Strip) and to withdraw the (Israeli) army from the West
Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   To drive the point home, Palestinian strung banners on the main
road leading to Manger Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a dream same as yours _ freedom and independence,''
one banner read. ``We ask you to release the Palestinian
prisoners,'' read another.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton expressed sympathy for the children of
Palestinian prisoners during a meeting with four prisoners' young
daughters who had come to meet the president during his visit to
Arafat's office in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   But in Bethlehem, he avoided politics, rarely speaking as he
stepped onto the stage to sing with the choir. Afterward, he shook
the singers' hands and pushed his fist into the air as if to show
appreciation for their songs.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Palestinians said they hoped Clinton's visit
would give a boost to the city's tourist-based economy, which has
suffered for years from a perception among travelers that it's not
a safe place to go.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, Clinton's visit may have been timely.
Palestinians are hoping to see as many as four million tourists
pass through the city during the year 2000 to celebrate the two
millennia &UR;  &LR; since the birth of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Since August, the Palestinian Authority has been giving Manger
Square a face lift. By the beginning of January, the square, once a
smog-filled parking lot that housed the headquarters of the Israeli
army, will be filled with white sandstone blocks, Cypress trees and
water fountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economy here has been so bad for so long,'' said Mona
Issa, a worker at Fatima's Souvenir Shop. ``We hope Clinton's visit
will show people that Bethlehem is a beautiful place to come.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
