<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1450 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      12-15 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR ACCOMPLISHMENT MISSING IN CLINTON TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT AND ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EREZ CROSSING, Gaza Strip _ After three days of extolling the
benefits of peace to Israelis and Palestinians, President Clinton
returned home Tuesday without major breakthroughs to face the
threat of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House says the visit succeeded in reinvesting people
from both sides in the peace process, but it failed to persuade the
Israeli government to stick to an agreed-upon schedule to cede more
West Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   This had much to do with the fact that Clinton is not the only
one whose political life is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu faces intense pressure
from far-right members of his coalition who have threatened to
topple his government if he carries out any further Israeli troop
withdrawals from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline for the next phase of the Israeli troop pullbacks
is Friday under an interim land-for-security deal. The
no-confidence vote that could bring down Netanyahu's government is
scheduled for Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, Clinton tried to close a deal that would get the
halted process back on track, meeting with Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat at the Erez Crossing, which
straddles Israel and Palestinian-controlled Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear from the way the 90-minute meeting concluded _
without any joint statement or even the three men posing for a
photo _ that the leaders had not overcome many of the sticking
points. Arafat left the building first.
</P>
<P>
   Still Clinton said he felt things had gone well partly because
they ``got beyond people stating their own positions to actual
conversation, and I'm quite hopeful.''
</P>
<P>
   But Netanyahu was already on the attack, telling reporters that
the Palestinians needed to do much more before Israel would
transfer more land as laid out in the interim accord, which Clinton
helped the two sides hammer out two months ago at the Wye River
Plantation in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did our share in the first stage of the Wye agreements,
what is important now is for the Palestinians to fully do their
share,'' Netanyahu said in a news conference after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In the meeting, Netanyahu refused to agree to live up to the
timetable for the next redeployment and instead handed Clinton and
Arafat a list of 12 alleged Palestinian violations or unfulfilled
obligations of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do it, I cannot tell you how much time we would take.
The faster they do it, the faster we will redeploy,'' Netanyahu
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the 12-point list was Arafat's repeated assertions
that he would unilaterally declare a Palestinian state on May 4,
which marks the end of the five-year timeframe established in the
historic peace accord signed in Oslo in 1993. The 12-point list
also included claims that the Palestinian leadership was inciting
violence on the street directed at Israeli troops and civilians.
</P>
<P>
   After one Palestinian attack earlier this month, Netanyahu
issued an ultimatum saying no more West Bank land would be given
until Arafat clearly rejected his claims to unilaterally declare a
state.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Wye land-for-security accord, Israel is supposed to
redeploy from another 5 percent of West Bank land on Friday. But
the agreement has been implemented in fits and starts, with Israel
accusing the Palestinians of trying to renege on the clauses
calling for them to confiscate illegal weapons, reduce the size of
their police force and halt incitement against Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said the Palestinians had successfully deleted the
anti-Israel clauses in their national charter during the vote on
Monday in Gaza attended by Clinton. But for the prime minister,
this was just one small part of the many things they must do before
getting more land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tuesday, they did one part, they voted down the charter
because we insisted even though they refused at first,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mainly shows that we must demand compliance with the
other parts of the agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Palestinians, who are in the weaker position right now,
are very concerned about any slowdown in the Wye accord. Arafat is
struggling to maintain quiet on the street amid growing anger over
the state of the peace process and Israel's refusal to release
political prisoners involved in militant attacks on Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   To convince his people that peace works, Arafat needs to show
real gains. The warm handshakes with Clinton, the first US
president to visit Palestinian-ruled areas, was seen as a symbolic
step in Washington support of Palestinian hopes for an independent
state. But in the meanwhile the Palestinian Authority needs to give
its people more than symbols.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the main reason for Clinton's visit was to restore
hope that peace is doable, and the next morning you hear the Prime
Minister of Israel, who is supposed to be a partner, say the
opposite,'' said Saeb Erekat, chief negotiator for the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   After the morning meeting at Erez, Clinton, his wife Hillary and
Chelsea, spent the day visiting the sites of the Holy Land. In
Bethlehem's Manger Square, the site of the birth of Jesus, they
decorated a Christmas tree and listened to carolers.
</P>
<P>
   They then traveled via helicopter north over the Jordan River
valley to Masada, the ancient fortress where the Jewish Zealots
committed mass suicide rather than live as slaves under the
conquering Romans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton often evoked theological and religious imagery in his
speeches to Palestinians and Israelis on this trip, underscoring
the president's deep interest in spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   In his Monday speech on the benefits of peace, Clinton said,
``In this small place, the home of Islam, Judaism and Christianity
_ the embodiment of my faith was born a Jew and is still recognized
by Muslims as a prophet. He said a lot of very interesting things.
But in the end he was known as the Prince of Peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed genuinely taken by the significance of the
spiritual sites _ and did advance reading on pertinent biblical
passages from the Jewish Torah and the Christian New Testament,
according to Menachem Genack, a New Jersey rabbi who has become a
friend and counselor to the president on matters of faith and spent
time with the president on his trip to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a spiritual trip for him. I think he is
thinking about his faith especially with all that is going on
around him,'' said Genack. ``For example, Masada emphasizes the
fragility of life here on this earth, the tenuousness we all have.
I think there will be some symbolism there for the President in
terms of his political existence as well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
