</P>
<P>
   Rubin and other specialists say it will be difficult to set the
rules for a trial for a crime that allegedly was committed by
Libyans in international air space, involving an American airliner
that took off from British soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are going to be the judges?'' asked Rubin, the Tufts
professor, who has served as chairman of a terrorism committee of
the 130-year-old International Law Association. ``Does the Scottish
law apply in the case? How are these two guys supposed to get to
Netherlands, and what happens to them if they are convicted?''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the men would be tried under Scottish law
and serve time in Britain if convicted. But Libya's foreign affairs
minister, Omar Mustapha al-Montasser, has said that his country
wanted the two suspects to be jailed in Libya if found guilty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
