<HEADER>
A1465 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TV-cox     12-15 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Networks _ some more than others _ set to broadcast history By
Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The networks will be there. But will the viewers?
</P>
<P>
   As TV prepares to cover impeachment proceedings that begin
Thursday in the House of Representatives _ the first such event in
the electronic media age _ there is serious doubt as to whether
anything approaching a large audience will tune in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a time to start paying attention, now is it,''
says Frank Sesno, CNN's Washington bureau chief.
</P>
<P>
   When the debate begins at 10 a.m. Thursday, at least eight TV
networks (broadcast and cable) will snap to attention. The ``Big
3'' anchors _ Tom Brokaw, Dan Rather and Peter Jennings _ will all
be in Washington, D.C., along with their corps of analysts and
correspondents. And when the House takes its definitive vote,
possibly late Thursday or Friday, coverage should be significant.
</P>
<P>
   But while CNN and C-SPAN are touting gavel-to-gavel live
coverage, the big broadcasters _ ABC, CBS and NBC _ will not make
that commitment in advance. When independent counsel Ken Starr
testified last month, all three started out with live coverage in
the morning, then switched back to soap operas in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell how the day is going to go,'' says ABC News
spokeswoman Eileen Murphy. ``Certainly we'll cover the vote live,
no matter when it happens.''
</P>
<P>
   If a House vote occurs in early evening or prime time, it's
possible an audience in the tens of millions might watch. But if it
happens during the day, it's unlikely the nation will come to a
standstill and gather around TV sets, the way it did for the O.J.
Simpson criminal trial verdict, when Nielsen Media Survey estimated
150 million Americans watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no good guys in this story,'' says Mary Ann Watson,
author of ``Defining Visions: Television and the American
Experience Since 1945.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In O.J. and Watergate, there was someone to root for. Even if
you thought O.J. was guilty, you could root for Christopher Darden.
That might be part of the ambivalence,'' she adds
</P>
<P>
   Watson says television (and its audience) has changed so much
since coverage of the Watergate hearings in 1973 (Senate) and 1974
(House Judiciary) that it's impossible to compare. During
Watergate, ABC, CBS and NBC rotated coverage, and PBS aired re-runs
of the hearings during prime time.
</P>
<P>
   The year-long Clinton scandal will be remembered not so much for
the live coverage, but for the outpouring of partisan spinners and
analysts filling talk shows such as ``Larry King Live'' and
``Geraldo Live'' every night, frequently speculating over one tiny
leak.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is so different from Watergate,'' Watson says.
``Professors stopped classes and said this is something important
we have to watch and discuss. That idea of a common sense of we're
all in this together is missing this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the schedule of upcoming TV coverage. It is subject to
change.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABC will pre-empt ``20/20'' at 10 tonight for a special
anchored by Peter Jennings, ``A Presidency at the Crossroads.'' At
11:35 p.m., ``Nightline'' is expected to devote its time to the
House vote tonight and Thursday; guests have not been determined.
ABC, CBS and NBC all plan to begin live coverage at 10 a.m.
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ CNN will air a special at 10 tonight, ``Investigating the
President: A Question of Impeachment,'' anchored by Bernard Shaw,
Judy Woodruff and Jeff Greenfield. Gavel-to-gavel coverage will
begin at 9 a.m. Thursday. Another CNN prime-time special will air
at 10 p.m. Thursday. ``Larry King Live'' guests at 9 tonight
include Ben Bradlee, Leon Panetta and Judge Robert Bork. King's
guests Thursday include Brokaw and Alan Dershowitz.
</P>
<P>
   _ PBS plans extensive live coverage, anchored by Jim Lehrer.
Both Atlanta PBS member stations _ WGTV/Channel 8 and WPBA/Channel
30 _ will carry PBS coverage.
</P>
<P>
   _ C-SPAN: Live gavel-to-gavel coverage begins at 10 a.m.
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ MSNBC and Fox News Channel both plan heavy coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga. Miriam Longino contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
