<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1466 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OIL-WORRIES-COX     12-15 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-WORRIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oil company exodus worries New Orleans
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ While most drivers are rejoicing as they fill
their cars with the cheapest gas in memory, New Orleanians have
reason to worry, turning nervous eyes toward Poydras Street.
</P>
<P>
   Low gas prices and giant oil company mergers have spelled job
losses along Poydras Street, the central business district home to
thousands of workers with Shell, Texaco, Exxon, Mobil, Amoco and
Chevron. And layoffs conjure ghosts of the 1980s, when oil went
bust and New Orleans prosperity went with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you use the word `bust?' Yeah, I think you can,'' said
Brian Schwarner, spokesman for the New Orleans and the River Region
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   In August, when British Petroleum PLC agreed to buy Amoco for
$53 billion, Amoco promptly announced it was pulling all of its 280
jobs out of Louisiana, including 200 workers from Poydras Street.
In October, Shell cut 700 jobs from its U.S. division, most in
Louisiana and Houston. And most recently, Exxon Corp. agreed to buy
Mobil Corp., placing in jeopardy 6,000 Exxon and Mobil workers in
Louisiana, more than 600 of them in New Orleans. Texaco has cut
jobs here as well.
</P>
<P>
   But is this 1986 all over again, when stores boarded up, oil
service industries went belly up and the city almost buckled under
spiralling debt?
</P>
<P>
   ``It has the potential to be, but I don't think so,'' Schwarner
said. ``In the 1980s, New Orleans was pretty much a one-horse town
and the horse was oil. But the economy has done a little
diversifying, and it's significant enough to keep an oil bust from
repeating itself on the magnitude it had in the late eighties.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, 40 percent of the state's budget came from oil
companies. When they suffered, so too did the state. Today, only 14
percent of the budget comes from oil. The state now relies more
heavily on sales taxes and other fees from conventions and tourism,
riverboat gambling and video poker.
</P>
<P>
   And in the '80s, it took five years, from 1981 to 1986, for
prices to fall to their lowest levels. This time, oil prices went
into freefall, falling from more than $20 a barrel to around $10 a
barrel in just 14 months. Analysts say a steeper decline means a
more rapid recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is the prices can't go much lower,'' said Larry
Wall of the Louisiana Mid-Continent Oil and Gas Association.
</P>
<P>
   Wall and others say that New Orleans will continue to be an oil
town for a long time to come, but it's going to be a different kind
of oil town.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the future of this area's oil industry lies far out
in the Gulf of Mexico, where new technology is enabling deep-water
drilling in previously unexplored regions. These are enormously
expensive, long-term projects that could pay off in the discovery
of vast new reserves of oil. Deepwater drilling in the Gulf gives
oil companies a reason to maintain a presence in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   However, two of the leaders in deep-water drilling, Chevron and
Shell, are rumored to be discussing a merger. If that occurs, it
seems certain they will consolidate their New Orleans headquarters,
spurring yet more job losses.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, deep-water drilling so far has not been as
successful as expected, said Lewis Ropp, an analyst with Howard,
Weil, Labouisse, Friedrichs in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of deep-water has gone up considerably,'' he said.
``And reliability issues are just starting to surface, so there are
additional costs there. Some people are wondering if in this price
environment they want to be in deep-water.''
</P>
<P>
   Drilling and equipping one well in waters thousands of feet deep
costs about $8 million, compared with $500,000 for a land well.
That kind of expense will be hard to justify as long as oil prices
remain low.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is certainly a very ugly environment,'' Ropp said.
</P>
<P>
   And as if all that weren't bad enough, earlier this month,
Texaco dropped $70 million worth of equipment from a crane into the
Gulf. Whether the company can retrieve it is uncertain, but it is
certain the accident will delay deep-water exploration.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all these recent setbacks, deep-water exploration is
a long-term project that may be delayed but not abandoned. And as
long as there is Gulf oil to be found, New Orleans will have a
future as an oil town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people have said that once the majors like Amoco move out
of New Orleans, they won't return,'' Ropp said. ``But frankly from
a logistical perspective, New Orleans will continue to be an
important focal point for the industry. It just may be more a place
for smaller field offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Rochell Konigsmark writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
