<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLASSROOM-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVICS AND HISTORY CLASSROOMS DEBATE THE PRESIDENT'S FATE  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACQUES STEINBERG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Their textbooks in their backpacks, the 28 seventh-
and eighth-graders in Jonathan Foy's Harlem classroom pushed their
desks out of the way Tuesday morning and arrayed their chairs in
the center of the room as if it were the floor of the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we're going to do in two periods what Congress can't do
in over a month's time,' Foy told his social studiesclass at the
Adam Clayton Powell Study Center for Law and Peace, a middle
school. ``We're going to figure out what to do with President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, they began voting with their feet: those who believed the
president should be impeached were sent to sit on the right side,
those who disagreed were dispatched to the left and any undecided's
sat in the middle. The students were free to move as their opinions
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand he lied,'' said Terranie McKenzie, 13, rising
from her seat on the left as if at a New Hampshire town meeting,
her finger jabbing her colleagues. ``That has nothing to do with
his work and how he's doing his thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton Hardee, 13, stood tall on the right, countering that the
president had become irrevocably distracted. ``His head isn't on
straight,'' said Carlton, a yellow sweatshirt serving as his sober
blue suit. ``How's he going to take care of all the people in
America? If he goes to pass a bill or law, people are going to be
skeptical about why he's doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not since communism fell and rendered Cold War-era textbooks
passe have social studies and civics teachers faced a target that
has shifted as rapidly as the Lewinsky matter _ a subject whose
enormity could not possibly have been anticipated by the course
materials that they selected at the beginning of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Charged with becoming authorities on a subject that even the
most authoritative scholars have yet to agree on, many of the
nation's middle school and high school teachers have had little
choice but to adopt the approach of Foy: opening up their classes
to passionate debate, with freshly clipped copies of the Articles
of Impeachment and excerpts from the president's various statements
serving as guideposts.
</P>
<P>
   At Los Angeles High School Tuesday morning, Jennifer Azure's
fourth-period government class should have been working on a draft
of a new student body constitution, one that stipulates that bad
grades and poor attendance are grounds for removal from the student
council. But instead, the talk was of the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should we impeach him?'' said Sara Iraheta, born in 1981,
``when that Reagan guy gave or sold weapons to that other country.
He could have put us in danger of getting bombed or killed.''
</P>
<P>
   At New Trier High School in Winnetka, Ill., Kerry Hall has taken
to bringing a transistor radio to class to keep his students
abreast of the latest news. Last week, he asked them to listen to
live debate by the members of the House Judiciary Committee and to
try to pick out whether a Republican or Democrat was speaking.
(``It usually took them at most 20 seconds,'' he said.) Since then,
they have been writing letters to their representative, John
Potter, a moderate Republican believed to still be on the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a textbook on how to teach this so it's
unprecedented,'' Hall said during a break. ``But it's also very
exciting and ground-breaking. I'm a historian, so I don't think the
kids appreciate some of the historic significance as much as I do.
But they certainly recognize its importance.''
</P>
<P>
   For many social studies teachers, the time spent on the subject
of constitutional crisis has represented a marked shift from the
past, when impeachment might have rated only a sentence or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would mention Andrew Johnson and say he was saved by one
vote,'' said Nancy Cohen, an eighth-grade social studies teacher at
Day Middle School in Newton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, though, Ms. Cohen's students spent much of the period
marking up the articles of impeachment, labeling the charges
``political'' or ``personal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We discussed whether that's what the founding fathers had in
mind,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For teachers, there is always a dilemma over how much of
themselves to inject into classroom discussion, but in her Los
Angeles classroom, Ms. Hazure told her students up front how she
believed the Republicans had treated the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are upset with the fact that he is very creative with the
truth,'' she told her class. ``They are mad because they can't
catch him in a lie. They've been trying to get him for so many
years, and when they finally thought they had him, there was a
technicality in the way he said it.''
</P>
<P>
   Joey Cabrera, a 16-year-old, wasn't buying that logic, though,
and wasn't afraid to tell his teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have thought about what he did before he did it,''
Joey said. ``He must have been a total idiot to think he is the
president of the United States and that whatever he did wouldn't
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   As class got underway Tuesday at the Study Center for Law and
Peace in Harlem, a small public academy of 200 students that is
sponsored by New Visions for Public Schools, Foy was circumspect
about his opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he began with a recitation of some of the facts, asking
the students to read various quotations from the president that he
had downloaded from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Question: Did you have an extramarital sexual affair with
Monica Lewinsky?'' asked Derrell Thomas, reading an excerpt from
the president's Jan. 17 deposition in the Paula Jones case.
``Answer: No. Question: If she told someone that she had a sexual
affair with you beginning in November of 1995, would that be a lie?
Answer: It's certainly not the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the next 90 minutes, Foy's students would
arrange themselves in various configurations. First he asked them
to seat themselves based on whether they believed the president had
lied in that deposition. Their positions were fluid: At one point,
there were 15 who contended the president lied, 11 who disagreed
and 2 in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he lied,'' said Derrell, 13, weathering the rising
heat in the room in a simple white t-shirt. ``When you swear on a
bible, you are supposed to tell the truth, the whole truth and
nothing but the truth. He didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Foy: ``That's a good point.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ronald Jarvis, 14, was less impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he do anything to abuse his power?'' Ronald asked. ``This
is what goes on in his bedroom. It's his business.''
</P>
<P>
   By 11:20, when Foy called the vote, 14 said the president had
lied, 10 said he hadn't and 4 remained undecided.
</P>
<P>
   But when Foy asked the students to rearrange themselves based on
whether the president should be impeached, the turnaround was
swift: 25 lined up against impeachment, two in favor of it and only
one undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you lie up on the stand, you have to restore that
trust,'' said Stephanie Campusano, 13, speaking for the minority.
``I think he can't.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was drowned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should he have to restore his trust to us,'' said Seretta
Stilley, 13. ``He didn't do anything to us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
