<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET RALLIES AS DOW, BUOYED BY GE, RISES 127.70
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks broke a four-session losing streak Tuesday, a
reversal traders and analysts said was a rebound from a selloff
that had gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had a lousy three or four days in a row, and we were
oversold,'' said Andrew Brooks, a vice president in charge of
equity trading at T. Rowe Price Associates in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Market sentiment was bolstered by an upbeat meeting that General
Electric had with analysts late Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, GE chairman and chief executive John F. Welch
said earnings for the current quarter and for all of 1999 would
meet expectations. In the wake of recent profit warnings from other
big companies, the forecast from GE provided some reassurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a technical reversal that General Electric was part
of,'' one equity trader, who spoke on the condition of anonymity,
said of Tuesday's market move. ``There is still a lot of bearish
sentiment, but I like the market at these levels. I am not a
roaring bull, but I think by the end of this week we will be back
above the 9,000 level'' for the Dow Jones industrial average. The
Dow rose 127.70 points, or 1.5 percent, Tuesday, to 8,823.30.
</P>
<P>
   Broader market measures did even better. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index gained 21.63 points, or 1.9 percent, to 1,162.83.
And the Nasdaq composite index, which fell sharply Monday, regained
a good deal of the ground it lost, rising 45.68 points, or 2.32
percent, to 2,012.60. The Russell 2000 index of smaller-company
stocks, however, gained just 1.63 points, or four-tenths of a
percent, to 389.57.
</P>
<P>
   GE was the engine driving the Dow higher. The stock jumped 6
7/16, to 93[.
</P>
<P>
   But other big-name Dow components also posted hefty gains.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola, which issued a fourth-quarter earnings warning last
week, rose 2{, to 65 15/16. Procter &AMP; Gamble, which also expects to
report lower-than-expected earnings, rose 2~, to 89{. And American
Express gained 3\, to 94}.
</P>
<P>
   Takeover news helped lift several issues, including General
Instrument, Coltec Industries and Enron Oil &AMP;d Gas.
</P>
<P>
   General Instrument gained 3 11/16, to 34\, on word that Royal
Philips Electronics, Europe's largest consumer electronics maker,
was in talks to buy or form a joint venture with the company, which
is the largest U.S. maker of cable television set-top boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Coltec rose 2, to 18 11/16, after Crane offered to buy the maker
of airplane parts for $1.6 billion and filed a lawsuit to block a
takeover bid by B.F. Goodrich .
</P>
<P>
   Enron Oil &AMP; Gas gained 2|, to 15{, after Enron Corp. said it had
received an offer to buy its stake in the oil and gas production
company. Enron would not identify the potential buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The day's gains in the overall market were not broad based: 16
stocks rose for every 15 that fell on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some analysts said they thought the
biggest-capitalization stocks, which have been driving the market's
advance for the last several years, could rally further.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the market was between 500 and 600 points
undervalued when the Dow was trading around 8,600,'' said Stuart
Freeman, chief equity strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are going to have a year-end rally that will
continue into the first few months of next year,'' he added. ``We
think there is a good chance the Dow will hit 10,000 by early
March.''
</P>
</TEXT>
