<HEADER>
A1471 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BODY-XRAYS-ART-2TAKES     12-15 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BODY-XRAYS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART AND SCIENCE SING THE BODY TRANSPARENT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late in the 19th century, writers and artists, harassed by
realism and the tyranny of fact, began to call for introspection,
reliance on emotion, investigation of fantasy and dream. As early
as 1858, Baudelaire railed against photography and art's slavish
reproduction of nature. ``Each day art further diminishes its
self-respect by bowing down before external reality,'' he said,
adding that ``nevertheless, (italics)it is a happiness to
dream.''(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   In 1881 another Frenchman called for ``a poetry that would be
psychology in the form of a dream.'' Shortly afterward, yet another
said, ``Thus we carry the analysis of the Self to the extreme.'' A
desire to explore the interior of the mind was in the air, and it
may not be sheer coincidence that Freud (who had worked in Paris in
1886) wrote his ``Interpretation of Dreams'' (published in 1900)
while the Symbolist movement in art and literature was in full cry.
</P>
<P>
   But it (italics)was(end italics) mere coincidence that at the
same time, it became possible for almost anyone to see the interior
of the body. In late 1895, Wilhelm Roentgen, a German physicist,
discovered by chance that invisible rays made certain compounds
fluoresce.
</P>
<P>
   Testing to see what materials these strange rays could pierce,
he held up a piece of lead before his apparatus; no rays went
through. Yet to his amazement, he saw the silhouette of the bones
of his thumb and finger that were holding the metal. He had
stumbled onto the X-ray.
</P>
<P>
   The Julie Saul Gallery in SoHo has had the piquant idea of
displaying together early medical X-rays and more recent works of
art that borrow from X-rays and Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI).
The exhibition, ``Skin/Deep: A Survey of Interior Imaging From
X-Ray to MRI'' (through Jan. 16), assembles approximately 40 images
from 1896 to the 1990s _ not exactly a survey but proof once more
of how eager art has been to pilfer from the treasury of science
and how readily scientific images seen in an art context assume
some of the characteristics of art.
</P>
<P>
   Bones are familiar enough by now and anyway were cleverly enough
designed to have a certain elegance themselves (at least if they
belong to someone else). Anomalies in the early examples of X-rays
on view are particularly interesting: two shirt buttons perfectly
visible between the bones of an arm; the care that a medical
scrapbook from World War I takes to point out that an X-ray of six
fingers and six toes is not like X-rays of normal hands; a blurry
X-ray that looks like nothing so much as an Abstract Expressionist
charcoal drawing. Three 1950s cyanotypes (blueprints) are not only
blue but distort the human torso, having been made from slices cut
longitudinally through a frozen corpse.
</P>
<P>
   MRI, which was not widely used until the 1980s, also makes
slices through the body but leaves it intact, mapping it by
coordinates that can then be converted into images. This slicing
effect is made beautifully clear in Justine Cooper's ``Self
Portrait,'' a series of clear plastic plates suspended an inch or
so apart in a stack.
</P>
<P>
   Each plate has a flat image of a ``slice'' through Cooper's
skull, starting with the top of her head and descending to the
neck. Viewed from the front, the images coalesce into what looks
like a dark, fully three-dimensional head encased in parallel
planes of glass.
</P>
<P>
   A more startlingly sliced-up body appears on a video of the
Visible Human Project, the world's first computerized library of
human anatomy, available on the Web and in the gallery, in which a
cadaver that was mapped by modern technology in every dimension and
system can be viewed as its skin, muscles, blood supply route,
organs, whatever, are quickly peeled away.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the corpse, lying with its head facing the viewer, is
cut through horizontally slice by slice and each cut swiftly
discarded _ ``like we're nothing more than bologna,'' as Julie Saul
remarked one day with a laugh. After the last slice, the screen
goes blank.
</P>
<P>
   When the press published pictures of X-rays in 1896 within weeks
of the announcement of Roentgen's discovery, the world became
instantly aware that it was witnessing a kind of miracle. The
nature of the miracle was clear enough, but not the details. A
photography magazine wrote: ``I hear they'll gaze/Thro' cloak and
gown _ and even stays,/These naughty, naughty Roentgen Rays.''
</P>
<P>
   (Roentgen refused to name a force of nature after himself or to
patent the phenomenon that he thought belonged to humanity. He was
awarded the first Nobel Prize in Physics for the discovery.)
</P>
<P>
   The hand-held camera was at that period threatening people's
sense of privacy by catching them in ungainly positions or unseemly
situations; some thought the X-ray would threaten the mind's
privacy as well (just as its secrets were being vaunted by artists
and investigated by Freud).
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we tell,'' another photography magazine asked, ``that
one's very thoughts may not be laid open to this new power which
passed through all fleshy disguises as easily as light does through
glass.''
</P>
<P>
   It is almost impossible to comprehend how great the change was
between the unquestioning acceptance of the physical law that eyes
cannot see through opaque solids, including flesh, and the sudden
exposure of the body's structure beneath the skin.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat earlier in the century, photographs had been made of
the interior of dissected corpses, even of a few interior areas of
the living body, but the lay public had not seen them. It was
because X-rays could produce photographs and photographs could be
reproduced in the press that people everywhere had such an
immediate understanding of what these peculiar rays could do.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Photography had already revealed movement too swift for human
perception; now the medium, joined to a new instrument, affirmed
that what was visible was far from the entire reality.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment this happened, science was already altering the
human paradigm and the concept of the physical world past
recognition. Objects like metals that everyone knew stood still and
human bodies even in peaceful slumber were said to be composed of
atoms constantly moving about.
</P>
<P>
   The visible world had once been all that anyone had; now there
was incontrovertible proof that there was more, and that human
beings had been handed a new key to profound secrets.
</P>
<P>
   And under the impact of X-rays, this too too solid flesh had
melted. One could prefigure one's own death, seeing the skeleton
that represented death itself in painting and sculpture, or
contemplate a lurking sentence of death and the possibility of
rescue in the image of a tumor.
</P>
<P>
   But the imaging system could bring not only the news of death
but the fact itself. No one knew for a couple of years how
destructive the side effects of X-rays were, and the facts were not
generally acknowledged until much later.
</P>
<P>
   In Bloomingdale's as the century began, a man demonstrated the
apparatus for two or three hours every day, until his fingernails
stopped growing, his skin began scaling, the hair on his face and
head fell out and his vision was impaired. Even after the dangers
were evident they were sometimes ignored: as late as the 1950s and
1960s, shoe stores had fluoroscopes where customers could check the
fit and children could play by watching the bones of their toes
wiggle.
</P>
<P>
   Bettyann Holtzmann Kevles, in a thorough study titled ``Naked to
the Bone: Medical Imaging in the 20th Century'' (Rutgers University
Press), writes that early in this century, artists, many of whom
followed the breaking news in science, quickly incorporated the
idea of X-ray vision into their art.
</P>
<P>
   The futurist artist Umberto Boccioni wrote, ``Why should we
continue to create without taking into account our perceptive
powers which can give results analogous to those of X-rays?'' Among
work influenced by X-rays, Ms. Kevles mentions Naum Gabo's glass
and plastic sculpture _ Gabo studied medicine and took a course
with Roentgen _ and Picasso's ``Girl Before a Mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   X-rays themselves, and the more recent MRIs and
computer-assisted tomography (known as CAT or CT scans), have found
their way into art. In 1967, Robert Rauschenberg used a full-scale,
full-body X-ray of himself in ``Booster,'' the largest lithograph
anyone had made to that date.
</P>
<P>
   A slightly later replay of that X-ray is on view in
``Skin/Deep,'' as are imaginative uses of medical imaging
techniques in photographs by Michael Spano, Annie Leibovitz, Helmut
Newton (who draped a Cartier bracelet over an X-ray of a foot in a
high heel), Kunie Sugiura and others. Justine Cooper's art video
made from MRI scans of her body is also at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the body's interior is in its way as significant today as
it was at the turn of the century. Many contemporary artists
concentrate on the human insides, working with bodily fluids,
displaying their AIDS X-rays, videotaping operations performed on
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Married couples put sonograms of their babies in utero on the
mantelpiece. PET scans (positron emission tomography) reveal what
happens inside the brain when someone thinks, as if to ratify the
early fears that X-rays could read minds.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays, MRIs, CT and PET scans unite several of the major
preoccupations of the day: fear of death (heightened by AIDS and an
aging populace), an accompanying obsession with a healthy body, an
addiction to images, and a voyeuristic drive to reveal everything
and to know everyone's secrets.
</P>
<P>
   There already exist infra-red scopes for night vision and a
camera that can see through clothing. If only we had X-ray vision,
too, we could all be Supermen, and plumb the heart and darkness of
the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
