<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Dec. 20,
1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category)
</P>
<P>
   FEATURE story &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TAYMOR-TITUS-FILM (Rome) _ The vast white marble piazza before
the Palazzo della Civilta del Lavoro, is a solemn building of
marble arches that looms over EUR, the grandiose exhibition park
Mussolini ordered built in the 1930s to fuse Roman Empire and
Fascist might. And that was what drew the theater director Julie
Taymor to select it as a site for ``Titus,'' her film adaptation of
Shakespeare's tragedy ``Titus Andronicus.'' Whatever its quality is
eventually judged to be, this is no ordinary venture. It is Ms.
Taymor's first feature film, with a starry cast headed by Anthony
Hopkins in the title role, Jessica Lange and Alan Cumming. This is
Ms. Taymor's first major venture since her extraordinary success
last year with Disney's ``Lion King'' _ a show that she transformed
with her direction, design and musical choices from a potentially
potted theatricalization of a cartoon movie into Broadway's biggest
hit. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-UNDERSTANDING (Undated) _ Present an unfamiliar piece of
music to a randomly chosen audience member, ask an opinion, and I
challenge you to get a simple expository sentence in response. The
body language will be one of retreat; the words will be quick to
equivocate. ``That was interesting,'' or ``I didn't understand it,
but maybe I will next time,'' or ``I should know more about it
before I tell you what I think.'' One longs to hear, ``That was
beautiful,'' or ``I hated it,'' or ``It bored me to death,'' for
this is what those answers really mean. The crucial word here is
``understand,'' for the fear of not understanding is great. Failing
to understand marks the unhappy listener as dense, out of the loop,
ill educated. By Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   FILM AND VIDEO
</P>
<P>
   GEENA-DAVIS-FILMS (Los Angeles) _ The Academy award-winning
actress Geena Davis is back, or at least working at a comeback
after a two-year hiatus and a divorce. And she has made it clear
that she is willing to play just about anything _ except a
weakling. Her new movie ``Stuart Little,'' based on E.B. White's
classic 1945 children's book about a family whose new son turns out
to be a mouse, symbolizes the critical juncture where Ms. Davis,
who is 41, stands. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   GLEESON-GENERAL-FILM (Dublin, Ireland) _ Brendan Gleeson bears
an uncanny resemblance to Martin Cahill, the maverick Dublin
gangland boss whom he plays in John Boorman's new movie, ``The
General,'' which opened Friday in New York. Yet there was another,
more subtle, reason for casting the burly Irish actor as the
mobster. In order to convey why Dubliners came to admire this
hardened criminal, murdered by the IRA in 1994, Boorman needed a
likable Cahill. And Gleeson is very likable. But he also has what
the veteran director calls ``essential goodness,'' which is why he
almost turned down his biggest movie role to date. By Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   DAVID-KELLEY-TV (Undated) _ Jerry Seinfeld put it as well as
anybody. ``I mean,'' he said of David E. Kelley, ``this guy has
done actual things.'' Kelley may be this decade's dean of the
quality series, but when the Museum of Television and Radio in Los
Angeles honored him and Seinfeld on the same night two months ago,
the speakers seemed to have trouble describing the essence of the
Kelley greatness. Dylan McDermott, of Kelley's ABC law series,
``The Practice,'' used the words ``quirky, idiosyncratic,'' because
somebody had to. Calista Flockhart, of Kelley's Fox law series,
``Ally McBeal,'' went for the sentimental, describing Kelley as one
who ``tells us what it's like to be people.'' By Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ANTIQUES
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CHU-ART (Paris) _ In the fifth century B.C., Confucius
questioned the practice of burying people alive alongside the dead
in funerary rituals, calling it a waste of human life. But it was
not until 100 years later that the Chu people of Southern China
abandoned human sacrifice, replacing the living in such rituals
with carved and lacquered wooden figures. Chu artists produced
haunting effigies of concubines, slaves, deer and tigers, all
common in the retinues of Chinese rulers during the late Warring
States period (fourth century to third century B.C.) and the Han
Dynasty (206 B.C. to 220 A.D.). A large number of Chu works have
been excavated over the past 20 years, and recently such works have
become more visible in the market. The Chu figures are now both the
subject of scholarly study and are being actively collected by
museums. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
