<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REEVES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves bouncing back well, out of ICU
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons coach Dan Reeves was moved from
intensive care to a private room at Piedmont Hospital on Tuesday
afternoon, and his recovery from Monday's quadruple-bypass heart
surgery is going ``beautifully,'' team physician Charlie Harrison
said.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, 54, had been suffering chest pains for several weeks
before mentioning to Harrison after Sunday's game at New Orleans
that they became worse during the game. After an angiogram Monday
morning, he underwent four hours of surgery in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After coming out of surgery about 3:30 p.m. Monday, Reeves had a
breathing tube inserted in his esophagus. It was removed about 7
p.m. He is not expected to return full-time to the Falcons until
the playoffs. The team has two regular-season games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has just gone beautifully,'' Harrison said. ``He
had a good night. His EKG and vital signs are stable, and he was
able to eat breakfast (Tuesday) morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a little bit hoarse, which would inhibit his ability to
converse with officials the way he likes to, but he's doing quite
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves' sore throat, a byproduct of the breathing tube, did not
prevent him from talking. Andrew Bishop, one of the team's doctors,
said the first words out of the coach's mouth about 6:30 a.m.
Tuesday were, ``How's Bob Christian?''
</P>
<P>
   Christian, the Falcons' fullback, was injured during the Saints
game, and at the time Reeves went into surgery, he did not know
that Christian was out for the season with torn knee ligaments.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves also spoke by telephone with interim head coach Rich
Brooks and running backs coach George Sefcik. Brooks and staff
began installing the game plan for Sunday's game against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually spread my stuff out,'' Brooks said. ``The offense
usually has longer Tuesday, and we (the defensive staff) usually
have longer Wednesdays and Thursdays.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who will remain in the coaches' box at the Silverdome
Sunday, was involved Tuesday in both offensive and defensive
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is I just confer a little bit more with
(general manager) Harold Richardson and George Sefcik and talk to
trainers to get medical reports,'' said Brooks, who was head coach
of the Rams in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: The Reeves family has asked that, in lieu of flowers,
donations be sent to the Falcons Youth Foundation at One Falcon
Place, Suwanee, Ga. 30024.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
