<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-FEMINISTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Democratic core rallies round the president
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As support for the president eroded on Capitol Hill
Tuesday, core constituencies of the Democratic Party rallied to his
defense outside the Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of more than a dozen women's organizations joined
AFL-CIO executive vice president Linda Chavez-Thompson to demand
that Congress censure rather than impeach Clinton over his efforts
to conceal his relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impeachment process is neither serious nor fair,''
Chavez-Thompson said. ``It's a partisan political stampede which
promises to trample all of the issues that really matter in the
everyday lives of the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The labor leader said the AFL-CIO has received hundreds of calls
from people volunteering to lobby members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Planned Parenthood and women's groups such as the National
Organization for Women and the Feminist Majority are also
mobilizing their members to lobby Congress with letters, phone
calls, faxes and e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me send out a warning to those who call themselves
moderates,'' said Kim Grandy, NOW's vice president. ``You are in
jeopardy if you vote for impeach- ment.''
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders failed to move Rep. Bob Livingston (R-La.), the
man the GOP has selected to be speaker of the House. Livingston
told them at a meeting following their morning news conference that
he won't retreat from his decision to prevent a vote on censure on
the House floor, Grandy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so dismissive,'' Grandy said. ``I don't know why he met
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston spokesman Mark Corallo accused the women's leaders of
mischaracterizing the meeting. ``He was very gentlemanly,'' Corallo
said. ``I think they couldn't take the fact that he didn't agree
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   At a separate event to promote a new book, Clinton's Washington
minister also came to the president's defense, saying Congress
should reprimand Clinton but not impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way to deal with something like this, without
discarding a person who really is a very gifted public leader and
who in so many aspects of his life has been morally sensitive and
committed,'' the Rev. J. Philip Wogaman told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also received some unlikely support from supporters of
perennial presidential candidate Lyndon LaRouche. About two dozen
LaRouche supporters picketed outside the Capitol demanding that
Congress not impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a coup to overthrow the United States government and
disenfranchise the American electorate,'' said Angela Vullo of the
Schiller Institute, a LaRouche-affiliated organization.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
