<HEADLINE>
SNYDER'S SUCCESSOR NAMED 
ASSESSING LOCAL NEWS 
MURDOCH ON `SIMPSONS' 
`ALLY' ANOREXIA?
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: Bylines at end of articles) 
(bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS Names `Late Late' Host
</P>
<P>
   CBS has announced the starting date for the latest entry into
the late-night competition. It said Tuesday that Craig Kilborn
would take up the host's duties on a revamped ``Late Late Show'' on
March 30.
</P>
<P>
   He will replace Tom Snyder, who will end his version of the
show, with a straight interview format, on March 26. Kilborn will
actually start on a Tuesday because the previous night will be
filled by the final game of the NCAA basketball tournament, which
is expected to extend past 11 p.m., backing up the network's
late-night lineup. CBS did not want Kilborn's first show to be
delayed past its normal 12:35 a.m. starting time.
</P>
<P>
   But the date was chosen in an effort to take advantage of what
CBS hopes will be an unusually large contingent of younger male
viewers, who will be watching the college basketball Final Four on
the network that weekend and seeing a large number of promotional
spots for Kilborn's show. His appeal as host of ``The Daily Show''
on Comedy Central has been skewed toward younger men.
</P>
<P>
   Kilborn will be finishing his stint on ``The Daily Show'' this
week. The show will offer reruns until he is replaced there by Jon
Stewart on Jan. 11. In the meantime, Kilborn will work on
developing his new CBS show.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that Kilborn and the show's production company,
David Letterman's Worldwide Pants, will fashion the new late-night
show as an hour built around Kilborn's quirky approach to comedy,
with a style designed to separate it from the current
desk-couch-band setup that dominates the late-night shows, from
Letterman's on CBS to Jay Leno's ``Tonight'' show and Conan
O'Brien's ``Late Night'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   One big change being planned in the format is to eliminate the
band completely. Kilborn is also expected to have a smaller,
perhaps deskless set, with a modest-sized studio audience.
</P>
<P>
   And as Letterman did when he moved from NBC to CBS, Kilborn will
attempt to bring some of his signature comedy pieces with him,
including a segment called ``Five Questions.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   Rating the Local News
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom has it that news on local television is
superficial and crime-obsessed: ``If it bleeds it leads,'' the
cliche goes.
</P>
<P>
   But the public doesn't necessarily share that conventional
wisdom, according to a study by researchers at the University of
Connecticut for the Radio and Television News Directors Foundation.
Two-thirds of those surveyed rated the news they got from their
local stations as good (52 percent) or excellent (14 percent), with
24 percent calling it fair and 8 percent poor.
</P>
<P>
   And most (55 percent) said the amount of coverage devoted to
crime was about right.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stop and think about it, it's not so surprising,'' said
Barbara Cochran, the foundation's president. ``Local news is closer
to people. And you can see that in the survey, because the public
and station news directors are in marked agreement on what stories
they think the public likes to see on local news.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers polled 1,007 randomly chosen American adults, in
October, and 300 news directors, in November. What people said they
most wanted to see jibed with what news directors thought their
viewers most wanted to see: weather reports first and foremost,
followed by (in this order of interest) news about education, local
crime, community happenings, world developments and health and
fitness. Lowest on the list was religion news.
</P>
<P>
   ``This certainly confirms that people do tune in to find out
about local crime and expect that,'' Ms. Cochran said. ``But they
also said they would like to see more coverage of crime prevention
and solutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet when asked whether it was important for local television
news divisions to act as watchdogs on local government, only 62
percent of the public said yes, while 92 percent of news directors
said they believed they should have such a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hear this in focus groups, too,'' Ms. Cochran said. ``
`Tell us the facts; don't tell us what to think or how to act.' I
think news directors need to do a better job of explaining to the
public what that watchdog role means.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, 66 percent of adults thought journalists should not be
allowed to use hidden cameras or microphones (22 percent of news
directors agreed); 57 percent of adults said if a reporter could
not find a source willing to be named, that story should not be
reported (29 percent of news directors agreed); and 48 percent of
adults said local news goes too far into public figures' private
lives (only 11 percent of news directors agreed).
</P>
<P>
   The survey was part of a larger, two-year Journalism Ethics and
Integrity Project partly underwritten by the Ford Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LAWRIE MIFFLIN
</P>
<P>
   An Animated Murdoch
</P>
<P>
   Does Rupert Murdoch have a sense of humor? Apparently he does,
because he signed on to do a scene with Homer Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox chairman will appear, both in cartoon form and in voice,
on a Super Bowl edition of ``The Simpsons'' on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   That is the same night of the premiere of a new animated Fox
series, ``Family Guy,'' directly after its Super Bowl coverage
ends. The game has traditionally provided a huge sample audience
for a new show, and Fox executives believe they have a potential
breakthrough hit with ``Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But animation of the show's other episodes will not be finished
in time to follow up the premiere immediately. So the series will
not be seen again until March.
</P>
<P>
   But as a partner for ``Family Guy'' that night, Fox announced it
would broadcast a special episode of ``The Simpsons.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where Murdoch comes in. The show's writers came up with
an idea that takes Homer to the Super Bowl, where he contrives to
get himself into a luxurious sky box. His party is interrupted,
however, by a ``distinguished-looking older gentleman with an
Australian accent,'' whom Homer calls ``Gramps'' and tries to throw
out of the box.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch lets Homer know exactly who he is: ``The billionaire
tyrant Rupert Murdoch.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's producers said Murdoch readily agreed to take part in
the show and delivered all the takes they asked for.
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
<P>
   An On-Screen Retort
</P>
<P>
   Though he hasn't said anything publicly about the
much-talked-about anorexia rumors surrounding Calista Flockhart,
who plays the painfully thin title character on ``Ally McBeal,''
David E. Kelley, the show's creator, has clearly been listening.
</P>
<P>
   He used this week's episode to have a little fun with the rumors
about Ms. Flockhart, and another of his stars, Lara Flynn Boyle,
who plays the painfully thin Helen Gamble, an assistant district
attorney on Kelley's other series, ``The Practice.'' Ms. Boyle's
name has come up in similar rumors about her eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   She made an unbilled cameo appearance on Monday's ``Ally
McBeal'' with her character accidentally bumping into Ally at an
office Christmas party. The two characters, who apparently don't
like each other, eyeballed each other for a moment before Helen
told Ally she was admiring her outfit.
</P>
<P>
   Then she suggested to Ally: ``Maybe you could eat a cookie.''
</P>
<P>
   And Ally replied: ``Maybe we could share it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BILL CARTER
</P>
