<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1494 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATRIOTS-COMPARE-BOS &LR;      12-15 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-COMPARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT DEAL WITH CONNECTICUT BEST-EVER FOR NFL OWNER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite some changes over the weekend that decreased
elements of the deal, the New England Patriots and owner Robert
Kraft are the beneficiaries of the most generous stadium financing
agreement ever offered to an National Football League franchise,
most experts agreed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even in an era when several mid-sized cities _ including
Nashville, Charlotte, St. Louis and Tampa _ have offered NFL owners
lavish terms to secure the status and allure of bigtime
professional sports for their communities, the deal approved by the
Connecticut General Assembly Tuesday to move the Patriots to
Hartford outranks them all, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ought to recognize it's the worst publicly-financed
stadium deal ever done,'' said Mark Rosentraub, director of the
Center for Urban Policy and the Environment at Indiana University.
``And anyone doing it ought to realize that by doing it they have
succeeded mostly in making one owner very wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The provisions that makes the agreement on the $375 million
stadium project so strikingly generous are the state guarantees for
premium seating _ potential costs that are not financed as part of
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The state has agreed to pay for as much as $13 million in luxury
box fees and club seating tickets annually for at least the first
10 years of the Patriots' lease. That potential exposure was
lowered from $17.5 million over the weekend, in a move that
provided some momentum for the vote Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Of all of the recent stadium deals done in the NFL _ some 14
since 1992 _ two provide a guarantee of revenue from admissions.
</P>
<P>
   But in one of the deals, for the Rams in St. Louis, the
guarantee was financed by a private civic group, not the state,
county and city governments that paid for the $280 million RCA
Dome. And unlike the Patriots' deal, the public St. Louis Regional
Conventions and Sports Complex will garner portions of the revenue
from stadium advertising and concessions.
</P>
<P>
   In the other deal, San Diego agreed to buy unsold tickets for
some regular seats as part of an agreement in to refurbish Qualcomm
Stadium, the home of the NFL's Chargers, in 1995. But those tickets
are all for non-premium seats, and the maximum exposure for the
city is less than $2 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kraft and his son Jonathan have said, at a legislative
hearing in Hartford last week and elsewhere, that they have done a
poor job of explaining their deal with Connecticut. They say, in
part, that a 10 percent ``tax'' on all tickets is expected to
generate as much as $8 million annually for the state. In a sense,
Kraft said, the team is sharing its revenue stream with its
partner.
</P>
<P>
   But some observers say the tax exists only to provide money for
the state' borrowing costs and doesn't really represent a
willingness on Kraft's part to share revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that it is priced that way to raise the
revenue for the 10 percent tax, rather than taxing the admission
price that the market will bear,'' said Dean Bonham, of the Bonham
Group in Denver. ``Especially if you are guaranteed the price of
many of the tickets, why not charge as much as you can?''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Kraft has argued against that, saying that the ticket
prices and luxury box fees were calculated independently of the
agreement to provide the state with 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can only charge what the market will bear,'' Kraft said.
``This isn't 10 percent added on top of what we're charging.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting $8 million annual payment to Connecticut is more
than some owners are contributing to the cost of their new
stadiums, but far less than some others. Georgia received no
payment from the NFL's Falcons when it built the $214 Georgia Dome,
that opened in 1992. And the Rams put up no money when the state of
Missouri, and the county and city of St. Louis paid for the RCA
Dome.
</P>
<P>
   However, Charlotte's $187 million Ericsson Stadium is financed
entirely by the sale of seat licenses and other private sources. In
Washington, D.C., the NFL's Redskins paid $180 million for the $250
million Jack Kent Cooke Stadium project, with public dollars
covering the remaining $70.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Krafts cite two other expenditures, which they say are
significant financial contributions to the deal: $50 million for
the construction of a hotel near the stadium and in the proposed
Adriaen's Landing development and $20 million for an NFL activities
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never has an NFL team contributed so significantly to the
redevelopment of a city,'' Robert Kraft said, recently.
</P>
<P>
   But observers point out that the Krafts stand to profit
substantially from the spending which, they said, is more in the
nature of an investment than a payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, building a hotel directly connected to a convention
center, near and new NFL stadium, amid a lot of redevelopment and
new activities in a city is tantamount to writing a blank check,''
Bonham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all things are considered _ the land being for free, the
facility built for free, the state paying for renovations and
maintenance, the naming rights going to the team, the annual
guarantees, and the obvious potential for revenue from the hotel
and the activities center _ there has never been anything like
this,'' he said. ``There is nothing in the NFL, there is nothing in
professional sports, that compares with this deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
