<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PLAN TO EXTEND DEBT ANGERS LENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov approved a plan Tuesday
to restructure nearly $14 billion in defaulted Russian treasury
bonds, but the move quickly drew criticism from foreign creditors,
who complained that they had not been consulted about the details
and that Russia was forcing a bad deal upon them.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiations over Russian treasury debt have been
overshadowed in recent months by President Boris Yeltsin's ill
health, food shortages and back wages. The debt talks, however, are
significant. At stake is Russia's credibility with foreign lenders
and its long-term access to the financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, the talks have not gone smoothly. Western bankers
say the plan outlined Tuesday is no better _ and perhaps a bit
worse _ than the position Moscow took in August shortly after the
ruble collapsed and Russia defaulted on its domestic debt .
</P>
<P>
   The Russians' approach to the negotiations has aroused ire.
Credit Suisse First Boston, a member of the 19-bank committee that
represents foreign holders of the treasury bonds, warned Moscow
last week not to impose its position by fiat. ``Russia will
aggravate its financial isolation if it unilaterally imposes unfair
restructuring terms on foreign investors,'' Credit Suisse said
then.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials contend that they had no choice but to press
ahead. Deputy Finance Minister Oleg Vyugin said in an interview
that the Russian government had to act now to be able to use funds
set aside in the 1998 budget for the debt restructuring plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're not able to do it this year, our 1998 allocation
would have been liquidated,'' he said, adding that creditors had no
basis to complain since the parameters of the deal had been known
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   In approving the plan Tuesday, Primakov left Western creditors
in the dark over key details. Russia plans to redeem only 10
percent of its treasury bills for cash in the form of rubles, and
the provisions for converting the rubles to dollars remain unclear.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 20 percent of the bills will be exchanged for
Russian zero-coupon bonds. Western creditors have wanted to know if
they could use these bonds to pay taxes or buy state property in
privatization auctions. That, too, remains somewhat murky, although
Russian officials said Tuesday night that they could be used to pay
tax arrears.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 70 percent is to be exchanged for four- to
five-year bonds. The interest rate on the bonds will be 30 percent
the first year and then decline gradually to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The government says the 30 percent interest rate is based on the
inflation projection for 1999. But many economists expect Russian
inflation next year to exceed 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, some creditors complain that the Russian plan does
not offer investors any improvement in the terms of the
restructuring deal, should the economy unexpectedly begin to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   The origins of Tuesday's decision were laid out several years
ago, when Russia began to finance an enormous budget deficit by
selling treasury securities. Economists say the decision to issue
the treasury bills was sensible enough, but that Russia carried it
to an extreme, using it as a crutch to make up for failure to
collect tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners and Russian banks initially profited from the high
interest rates on the bills. But they were caught short this summer
when the ruble plunged, and Yeltsin's government defaulted on debt.
</P>
<P>
   The government later promised to restructure 281 billion rubles
($13.9 billion) in treasury debt, and the negotiations with Western
creditors were begun.
</P>
<P>
   While Primakov had nothing to say about his decision Tuesday
night, finance ministry officials promised a fuller explanation
this week when they go to London to meet with Western bankers.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not known if the Russian officials plan to dictate
additional terms, negotiate or simply promise that more details
will be forthcoming at a later date.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are separate issues connected with the repatriation of
foreign currency and with the status of investment securities,''
Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov said last week. ``These issues
are important, but from our point of view they can be discussed and
resolved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
