<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PINOCHET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINOCHET LAWYERS, IN APPEAL, CHALLENGE LAW LORD'S IMPARTIALITY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Lawyers told a House of Lords hearing on Tuesday that
one of the Law Lords who ruled against Gen. Augusto Pinochet had a
concealed bias against the former Chilean dictator and that the
verdict keeping him from returning home should be set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In the first formal challenge ever to a decision of the Law
Lords, England's highest court, the lawyers said Lord Justice
Leonard Hoffmann, who cast the decisive vote against Pinochet,
erred in not alerting the court to his links to Amnesty
International.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the Lords agreed to accept the request for a
review is seen as a reflection of the seriousness with which the
question is being treated. Lord Browne-Wilkinson, head of the Law
Lords, said he would summon a new panel of judges to reconsider the
case if the appeal succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare extension of privilege, Amnesty was permitted to
present its argument against Pinochet to the five-man tribunal that
decided, 3-2, on Nov. 25 that the general did not enjoy immunity
from arrest in England. Because of that ruling, the general will
have to remain in England for what might be more than a year as a
Spanish petition to extradite him to Madrid to face charges of
crimes against humanity goes forward.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffmann, it has emerged, is a director and former chairman of a
charity that raises money for Amnesty. His wife, Gillian, has been
an administrative assistant in the London-based human rights
group's press and publications division since 1977.
</P>
<P>
   His failure to declare that association, aside from provoking
Tuesday's request for an appeal, has aroused concern in the British
legal establishment, which regards Hoffmann as one of its most
capable and learned members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three weeks ago, the case of Gen. Pinochet propelled the
British judiciary to the pinnacle of global admiration,'' Hugo
Young, a columnist for The Guardian, wrote Tuesday, reflecting a
widely held view among lawyers here. ``Through the folly of a
single judge, the Law Lords, from being the heroes, may soon become
the villains.''
</P>
<P>
   As two days of hearings opened Tuesday, the task of a panel of
five Law Lords, separate from the five who ruled last month, was to
determine whether the relationship between Hoffmann and Amnesty
International was ``so clear and obvious'' that there was a ``real
danger'' that he could have been even unconsciously influenced.
</P>
<P>
   Clare Montgomery, Pinochet's lead lawyer, noted that it was a
judge's duty to reveal any links of kinship, friendship, employment
or financial relations with any parties in a case.
</P>
<P>
   She argued that Amnesty published a report in 1993 with
Hoffmann's knowledge ``which was highly critical of Senator
Pinochet and the failure to prosecute anyone in connection with his
period of rule.'' The group's purpose, she said, was to secure the
abolition of ``torture, extrajudicial execution and
disappearance,'' the very crimes Pinochet, who is a
senator-for-life in Chile, was accused of in the hearing before the
Lords about whether he was entitled to immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The links we suggest are so great and so many that any
reasonable person looking at this would say we have a reasonable
apprehension that there may be bias,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that Hoffmann had been a particularly ``active and
hostile interrogator'' of counsel for Pinochet during the six days
of hearings in November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2013EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
