<HEADER>
A1499 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILES16-COX     12-15 1035
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILES16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Residents line streets to say goodbye to Chiles
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CENTURY, Fla. _ Stopping for a moment from the grimy work of
road building, they put down their shovels, removed their hard hats
and formed a line of respect for the passing funeral procession of
Gov. Lawton Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   One man, alone on the side of the road, dropped to his knee and
made a sign of the cross. A high school honor guard dipped the
state flag as the 20-car motorcade went by. A little child held a
sign saying, ``thanks for walking into our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Caps over their hearts, small American flags in their hands,
waving signs promising never to forget him, Florida's rural
community lined 200 miles of Highways 4 and 90 Tuesday to say
goodbye to Gov. Lawton Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Here more than anywhere else in the state, among the rolling
hills, deep forests and rural towns of the Panhandle, Chiles felt
most connected to the state he loved. And it was here where he
began his 1,033 mile walk across the state 28 years ago to win a
seat in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Coming back to where it all began, the flag draped, plain,
unvarnished pine coffin of Florida's 41st governor, arrived in
Century just as the sun was rising on a brisk morning with
temperatures in the 40s. Slowly the residents of this town on the
Alabama border began lining the road waiting for the funeral
procession to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came here to start that walk of his it was something
we'd never seen before,'' said Bert Carrilla, 57, as he stood in a
parking lot watching the funeral procession form in front of the
Post Office. ``We just didn't know what to make of it. But he sure
surprised a lot folks.''
</P>
<P>
   With two Florida Highway Patrol cars leading the way, the 1999
black Lincoln hearse pulled away. Chiles sons, Ed and Bud, were in
the car behind the hearse. His daughters, Tandy and Rhea stayed at
the governor's mansion in Tallahassee with their mother Rhea who
was married to Chiles for 48 years. They would join the procession
in its final miles to the Old Capitol where Chiles will lie in
state until his funeral this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In his diary at the time, Chiles would remember the start of his
walk this way: ``The first fellow that I saw I had to lure down off
a power pole. He kept trying to get a word in and I kept talking to
him about my running for the United States Senate and finally he
got an opportunity to break in and tell me he was from Alabama. I
just told him I sure hoped he had some Florida friends to pass the
word to.''
</P>
<P>
   From Century, Chiles walked through towns with picturesque names
like Jay, Munson, Mossyhead, Ponce de Leon, Bonifay, Chipley,
Marianna, Mt. Pleasant and Qunicy. Along the way he made memories
for himself and the people who lined the roads Tuesday to honor
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came right by my house with his coat over his shoulder,''
said Edsel Brooks, 74, of Ponce de Leon, a two-store, one gas
station town. ``I thought he was a real common person. I really
liked him and I have voted for him every time since. I'm a
Democrat, full blooded and he kept the faith with the people.''
</P>
<P>
   As the funeral procession entered a new county, local sheriff's
deputies would provide escorts. Other deputies and police officers,
blocking intersections, stood with stiff white gloved salutes. A
woman in Munson held a sign saying, ``Now you walk beside God. Your
memory will be with our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Local ambulances and fire trucks parked on the side of the road,
lights flashing and crews standing at attention. Cars along the
road coming in the opposite direction would pull over and stop out
of respect. Men and women cried.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a man who was connected to the people,'' said Robert
Hill of Crestview. ``He was a man of the people and I'm afraid he
may be the last one.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking off his cap as the hearse went by, Ray Fox, 68, said he
thought Chiles was an amazing man. ``He didn't just walk. He
stopped and he talked to people and he listened. I didn't agree
with him all the time but I knew he cared about doing the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   One man wore a coonskin cap. Another wore a coonskin vest.
``Walkin'' Lawton in his final 1994 campaign for governor had
dubbed himself the ``he-coon,'' and his followers found it
endearing. In Cottondale, the sign said, ``Gov. Chiles. Working men
and working women will miss you.''
</P>
<P>
   During his nearly eight years as governor, he died just 23 days
from leaving office, Chiles worked to improve health care and
education for children. Along the 200 mile procession, hundreds of
school children lined the road in silent homage. Teachers whispered
prayers. One child held a sign that said, ``Sleep in heavenly
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the state Capitol, the procession went to the
governor's mansion where the First Lady and Chiles daughters had a
few private moments before beginning the final journey to the Old
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks from the Capitol, the procession stopped and Chiles
four children and 10 grandchildren got out of their cars to walk
behind the hearse. The grieving First Lady remained in the car.
Then, the hundreds of people lining the procession route grew
still. The only sound the chatter of television news helicopters
hovering overhead.
</P>
<P>
   As the hearse pulled into the plaza between the old and new
Capitols, state employees, lobbyists and average Floridians watched
as an Army honor guard removed the pine coffin from the hearse and
at 2:53 p.m., more than six hours after leaving Century, carried it
up the Old Capitol steps into the rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades ago, after ending his now famous walk in Key
Largo, Chiles penned his last diary entry: ``Well it's over!
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when I dreamed I was an old man and I was
still walking, like maybe this was going to go on forever. But
surprisingly, the several days since Miami went extra fast and when
the finish line slipped up on me, I wasn't really ready. I
certainly faced the end of the road with mixed emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley is a political editor for The Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
