<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-AUTOS-POINTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURANCE POINT SYSTEM UNCHANGED AFTER REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Insurance Commissioner Linda Ruthardt Tuesday rejected
bids to change the way the state rewards good drivers and punishes
bad ones, while reversing herself and going along with an industry
proposal that would treat drivers from out of state more toughly.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt was supposed to issue her final decision on 1999 auto
insurance rates Tuesday, but that was delayed indefinitely.
Instead, she issued a partial ruling on three proposed changes to
the state's point system, a sore spot for many motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Her decisions left the system pretty much intact. She rejected a
proposal that had backing from the auto insurance industry and
Beacon Hill to provide some relief for drivers involved in minor
fender-benders.
</P>
<P>
   She also rejected a separate proposal from a watchdog group
within her own agency to increase the number of points assessed for
violations but remove them from a driver's record faster. The
proposal would have allowed penalized drivers to recover faster to
take advantage of discounts available to good drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry had suggested increasing the lower
threshold for a minor accident from $500 to $750 to keep pace with
inflation. Many motorists have complained that even a minor
fender-bender exceeds $500 and bumps up their driver step ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Each increase in the ranking translates into a 6 to 7 percent
price increase on most coverages. And the loss of the best Step 9
ranking means the loss of good-driver discounts, which are granted
at the discretion of insurance companies and have cut driver
premiums anywhere from 10 to 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt said she didn't want to raise the threshold to $750
because it would exempt about 15 percent of all accidents from
surcharge points. She said the surcharges from those accidents help
pay for the credits that reward good drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt instead suggested drivers raise their deductibles, a
move that would reduce their premiums and limit exposure to points
since damage claims for point purposes are based on the amount paid
out by the insurer after a deductible is applied.
</P>
<P>
   Ruthardt endorsed the premise of removing points from a driver's
record faster, but said the plan, proposed by the State Rating
Bureau, needed refinement.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ruthardt flip-flopped on how drivers moving into
Massachusetts should be treated. Earlier this year she endorsed the
current policy of allowing out-of-state drivers to receive a Step 9
ranking if they sign a statement saying their driving record had
been clean for six years.
</P>
<P>
   Insurers, led by Trust Insurance of Taunton, said drivers from
several foreign countries were obtaining Step 9 rankings knowing no
one would check. Immigrants from Russia and Southeast Asia were
particularly suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Trust sued Ruthardt in August. Noting the overall point system
is revenue neutral, the company argued that good drivers were
receiving smaller credits on their premiums because foreign drivers
were lying about their driving histories and improperly being
lumped in with them.
</P>
<P>
   Under Tuesday's ruling, Ruthardt said drivers from out-of-state
will automatically start out at a neutral Step 15 ranking unless
they can provide documentation of a clean driving record or their
insurer can verify that record independently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
