<HEADER>
A1502 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-MAVERICKS-COX     12-15 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-MAVERICKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nine Republican mavericks are veterans of tough decisions
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Tom Campbell (R-Calif.) reflected Tuesday on
the toughest votes of his House career as he declared he would vote
to impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the Persian Gulf War vote in 1991, Campbell cited a
1997 decision ``to vote against my party's nominee for speaker.''
</P>
<P>
   The nominee was Newt Gingrich, and Campbell was one of nine
Republicans who withstood pressure and, in some cases, ostracism,
to withhold their vote for Gingrich during an ethics investigation
that led to Gingrich's reprimand by the House and a $300,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell is one of several lawmakers from that group of mainly
moderate Republicans who, in a reprise of two years ago, have
agonized over the impeachment vote.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the nine Republicans, Rep. Michael Forbes of New
York, also announced his support for impeachment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes has recounted cold shoulders and withdrawn invitations
after he became the first Republican to call publicly for Gingrich
to step down as speaker two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's decision to leave office after this year's elections
has led to a rapid rise for Forbes in Republican ranks.
</P>
<P>
   An ally of Rep. Robert Livingston (R-La.), Forbes has been
tapped to be an assistant to the incoming speaker.
</P>
<P>
   He said his decision on impeachment had nothing to do with his
rehabilitation or any pressure from Republican leaders.
``Absolutely not,'' Forbes said at a Capitol news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Both Campbell and Forbes eventually supported Iowa Republican
Rep. Jim Leach for speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Leach, the chairman of the House Banking Committee, also did not
vote for Gingrich. With a district that tilts Democratic and
handily voted for Clinton in 1996, Leach remains uncommitted on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Two Washington area lawmakers voted ``present'' in the speaker's
election two years ago. One, Rep. Frank Wolf of Virginia, intends
to vote for Clinton's impeachment. The other, Rep. Connie Morella
of Maryland, has not stated her position.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the nine are leaving Congress at the end of the year.
Rep. Linda Smith of Washington and Rep. Mark Neumann of Wisconsin
lost races for the U.S. Senate in their respective states. Both
have said they intend to vote against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Hostettler of Indiana also is undecided, but both pro-
and anti-impeachment forces count him as a vote for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Scott Klug of Wisconsin is retiring after four terms in the
House, and a Democrat won his seat in November. Klug also is
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
