<HEADER>
A1503 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILES-WIDOW-COX     12-15 1437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILES-WIDOW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawton Chiles paid tribute to `angel' Rhea
 &HT;    By Paul Reid
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ They're saying Lawton Chiles left behind
a government in good order, left his mark on education, left
tobacco in ashes. They're saying he left a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles would relish the accolades.
</P>
<P>
   But he left something else behind, something that occupied a
far, far greater place in his heart than all the laurels of
political life. He left behind his family.
</P>
<P>
   They have just memories now _ memories and letters and
presidential condolences and fading photos. Memories and an empty
place at the table and old gifts that will elicit with a look or
touch more memories of a husband and father.
</P>
<P>
   This was _ is _ a family in the dictionary sense, a social unit
bound by ancestry, marriage, children and the children's children,
united by common interests, strengthened by healthy conflict,
secure in its love.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton Chiles was a fourth-generation Floridian, which is three
more than most Floridians his age. One of his great-grandfathers
was a field surgeon for the Confederate army, another a
circuit-riding preacher in North Florida. Chiles family roots reach
deep into Florida soil. His father, a railroad man, died of heart
disease at age 59. Lawton Chiles' death was foretold in the genes.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight years ago, Chiles married Rhea Grafton,
granddaughter of Florida pioneers. They had met at the University
of Florida, settled in Lakeland. Rhea dropped out of college, where
she had been studying art, to help Chiles get his law practice off
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The role of a '50s wife was to help her husband. Rhea embraced
that role. In 1958, when Chiles ran for the state legislature, Rhea
told their three children: ``This is Daddy's time, we're going to
help him. Your time will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Years later, Rhea went back to UF to finish her art studies. Her
time had come. She has since backed galleries from Florida to New
York and Washington. Art, its perspective and transcendence offered
Rhea Chiles the outlet she needed to express herself while she and
her family were living in the political universe of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Her selflessness and artistic leanings are both evident in 700
North Adams Street, the coffee-table book she wrote about the
history of the governor's mansion in Tallahassee. It is a
beautifully crafted book. And Rhea never succumbs to any temptation
to inflate her role as the latest occupant of that house. She
writes of her tenure as first lady in a distant third-person voice.
</P>
<P>
   Art was her counterweight _ just as she was Lawton's.
</P>
<P>
   When his official portrait was unveiled last week in the
governor's mansion, Chiles gave a speech that included the usual
political acknowledgements. Then he veered into a tribute to Rhea,
his ``angel.'' It was a warm speech, the pace was perfect, the
language silken. The speaker, clearly, was a man in love.
</P>
<P>
   And the children's time did, indeed, come. Tandy, 46; Bud, 45;
Ed, 43, and Rhea, 32, sculpted independent lives of their own
creation, lives surely influenced by the career choices of their
parents, but distinct, unique.
</P>
<P>
   Rhea, the youngest and her mother's namesake, was adopted. She
lives now in Tampa and has three children of her own. She does not
lead a political life, but she has made clear that her views on
abortion are opposite those of her father. Still, whereas Ronald
Reagan's daughter, Patti Davis, aired her family and political
laundry on the same line, Rhea Chiles MacKinnon separates the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am my father's daughter, and I love him,'' she said during
the abortion debate. In the Chiles' household, as in Chiles'
political career, honest disagreement never got personal, was never
exploited.
</P>
<P>
   Lawton ``Bud'' Chiles III has taken the most political heat over
the years. Like many sons of politicians, Bud chose a career close
to politics: public relations. As a lobbyist for Citicorp from 1988
to 1990, and TGV, a high-speed rail company, Bud left himself and
his father open to political attack. But the senior Lawton never
apologized for or tried to distance himself from Bud. Any mud
thrown their way slid down the wall without sticking.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Bud, his wife and three children moved to New York,
where he is chairman of Hope For Kids, a national foundation
dedicated to education and health care. He is still an investor in
the Governor's Inn, a small hotel near the state Ccapitol in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Chiles operates the Sandbar restaurant on Anna Maria Island
in Manatee County. He helped his father campaign, spending time at
the governor's mansion when Bill Clinton was a guest. He lobbied as
an unpaid volunteer for tax increases his father proposed and made
one unsuccessful foray into elective politics. He lost a state
Senate race in 1990 and says he's not going to run again. His
father never lost a race. Ed has two children.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy Chiles Barrett, the oldest child, may have had the most
spiritual relationship with her father. She is legally blind. He
was known for his ability to see, take aim and bring down game,
literally and in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy's experiences forced Lawton Chiles to see the world
differently, especially the world of education. He said often that
Tandy guided him to a greater, consuming interest in children's
health and education issues.
</P>
<P>
   Tandy has two children, Tandy and Joe, and lives in Winter Park.
``Giving daughters our names is something we do in this family,''
she says. ``It's a way of showing respect for who we are and where
we came from.''
</P>
<P>
   She clearly has her father's political instincts. Soon after the
state won an $11 billion settlement against Big Tobacco in 1997,
Tandy organized the photo-op that brought the suit into national
perspective. She bused dozens of schoolchildren to a Joe Camel
billboard near Orlando. Her father appeared on the scene and led
the children in a chorus of ``Goodbye, Joe,'' as cameras rolled.
The image of children waving bye-bye to the icon of the tobacco
industry served to connect the lawsuit to families on terms
understood by all.
</P>
<P>
   The family will surely pass these stories on to grandchildren,
tales of insight, strength, political savvy, just as the Chiles'
family Bible has been passed down now for five generations.
</P>
<P>
   The L.L. Bean boots that Chiles wore during his first campaign
will become part of public legend, along with our image of the
he-coon bringing down his opponents with one well-placed verbal
shot.
</P>
<P>
   We'll have our memories of Chiles, the public man, but his
family will have something more. They'll have the private memories,
to be sure, will have known the man who walked in those boots.
</P>
<P>
   But they will have this: He is part of them. They completed him.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles' wife spurred the walk
</P>
<P>
   Rhea Chiles called herself her husband's ``corporate memory.''
During the 1990 race she accompanied him on campaign stops, often
taking notes and asking questions as they met with community
groups. Throughout his tenure as governor, Chiles would often
bounce ideas off her and she would help him gauge which direction
he needed to go.
</P>
<P>
   Chiles often credited Rhea with suggesting he walk the state to
help get his name out in his underdog race for the U.S. Senate in
1970. But while the gimmick has now become legendary, there were
moments when Rhea Chiles wondered if Lawton, then a little-known
state senator from Lakeland, would ever get the name recognition
they needed to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled recently how she and a handful of supporters would
follow Chiles in a motor home as he walked his route. To help
spread his name, the vehicle displayed a large sign that read:
Camper of ``Walkin' Lawton'' Chiles. Early on the journey, when the
group stopped for refreshments in one small Panhandle town, a local
woman approached Rhea and asked: ``Hello, are you Mrs. Camper?''
``Yikes,'' Rhea said she thought. ``Mission Control, we have a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   As a U.S. senator, Chiles was a frequent supporter of children's
issues but he credits his greater understanding of the issue to the
birth of his son Bud's first child, Lawton IV, who was born
prematurely, weighing 1 pound, 3 ounces. The only permanent damage
Lawton IV, now 17, suffers is some eye damage but the experience
brought his grandfather to chair the National Commission on Infant
Mortality and sparked his interest in the Healthy Mothers/Healthy
Babies movement.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Reid writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
