</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-CUTBACKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP TO CUT WORK FORCE BY 10,400 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Citigroup Inc., the newly created _ and troubled _
financial giant, said Tuesday that it will cut its work &UR;  &LR; force by
10,400 in a bid to boost profits.
</P>
<P>
   The firm, formed earlier this year through the merger of
Citicorp and Traveler's Group Inc., will take a $900 million charge
to pay for the 6 percent staff cut. The company is scrambling to
make good on forecasts of its co-chairmen Sanford Weill and John
Reed to boost profits of the combined operation by $1 billion
within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The cutbacks are likely to fall particularly hard on New York,
where Citicorp and Travelers are headquartered. But analysts said
the city is better able to absorb the losses than at any time in
recent years because of a recent burst in new job creation.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup shares jumped 2 11/16, or 5.8 percent, to 48 3/4 on
news of the cutbacks, a welcome reversal from the long slide the
stock has suffered since announcement of the merger last April.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup executives said in September that they were
considering cuts of 8,000 jobs, but apparently concluded that
deeper cuts were needed. About 35 percent of the cuts will be from
the US work force with the rest overseas. The company declined to
provided details of the cuts Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When the merger was unveiled, Weill and Reed said they believed
they could increase revenues by selling Traveler's insurance and
brokerage services from Traveler's Salomon Smith Barney subsidy to
Citicorp customers.
</P>
<P>
   But trading losses following Russia's August default and
devaluation and internicine warfare between executives of the
merging companies have forced the combined company to focus on
cost-cutting rather than revenue-boosting as a means of raising
profits.
</P>
<P>
   The company ousted James Dimon, the president of the Salomon
Smith Barney unit and a man who was initialy touted as a likely
successor to Weill and Reed, in the wake of the trading losses,
which totalled more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup officials said that $525 million of the savings they
are seeking will come from the firm's consumer businesses like
retail banking and insurance, much of it through the merger of back
office functions like telephone service centers. They said $350
million in savings will come from corporate businesses like
emerging markets and investment banking, and an additional $15
million will come from asset management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
