<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1510 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-OSU-ELIGIBILITY-C     12-15 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-OSU-ELIGIBILITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OSU player wants one more year in college-level sports
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ As the seniors on this year's Ohio State
football team prepare for their final college game in the Jan. 1
Sugar Bowl, at least one among them may not have to say goodbye so
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Senior tailback Joe Montgomery, a backup to junior Michael Wiley
this year, is petitioning the NCAA for another season of
eligibility. Montgomery, a 5-11, 216-pound running back from
Illinois, believes he was wrongly declared academically ineligible
his freshman season after the NCAA Clearinghouse did not approve an
economics course he took in high school. That class is now accepted
by the Clearinghouse as a core course, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a possibility that I can come back,'' Montgomery said
Tuesday during an interview at OSU's Woody Hayes Athletic Center.
``Right now I'm weighing those options heavily.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU coach John Cooper said he expects Montgomery to return if
the NCAA gives the OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was under the impression that if (his petition) is granted,
he's going to come back,'' Cooper said. ``I mean, why would he file
a petition if he's not going to come back?
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's approved, there's no question in my mind he should
come back. And I think it should be approved. I think Joe is what
college football's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery, who has become sort of a poster man for overcoming
adversity while at OSU, has become a fan favorite as much for his
hard-nosed, physical running style as for his upbeat attitude and
his perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   After practicing with the team during the first few days of fall
camp as a freshman, Montgomery learned he had not been cleared by
the NCAA to play. He had to quit the team and lost his scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   He rejoined the team in 1995 and redshirted. In 1996, he blew
out his knee halfway through the season and had to undergo major
reconstructive surgery. More knee trouble cut his 1997 season short
and forced him to undergo additional knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the setbacks, he continued to rehab vigorously and never
lost hope that he'd return.
</P>
<P>
   This season, as the No. 2 tailback, Montgomery played in all 11
of the Buckeyes games and rushed for 682 yards and six touchdowns.
His 6.1 yards per carry average is second on the team behind Wiley
(6.3).
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery said because he believes he was wrongly denied the
opportunity to practice or play with the team as a freshman, he
deserves another season. He said the high school economics course
that the NCAA didn't recognize in 1994 was ``ruled a core course by
the state of Illinois, the Board of education, by my high school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of other athletes at my high school took the course and
went on to play Division I football,'' he said. ``But I took it and
I was a casualty of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery said he doesn't know when a decision will be made on
his petition. An OSU administrator would not comment other than to
say the request was still in its ``very early stages'' and a lot of
questions have yet to be answered.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA does not comment on pending petitions, an NCAA official
said.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Vinella writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
