A1525 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NUHN-COLUMN-COX     12-15 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NUHN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Baseball's problems only worsening with free-agent frenzy
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Baseball's owners and general managers bidding
against each other are like 8-year-olds in a toy store with all the
adults locked in the backroom.
</P>
<P>
   Except 8-year-olds have more self-control.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last month, and especially the last five days in
Nashville, baseball teams have once again written checks against
the future of the game. Five players _ Mike Piazza, Mo Vaughn,
Bernie Williams, Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown _ have signed
contracts for a total of $453.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   As Alexander Hamilton wrote in The Federalist Papers: ``This is
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   (Actually, Hamilton wrote nothing of the sort; this was a
gratuitous attempt on my part to tie in baseball with actual
important issues of the day, and I beg your forgiveness.)
</P>
<P>
   If you think all the teams aren't at fault, you are missing the
big picture.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Dodgers giving Kevin Brown $105 million plus access to
the Fox Corporate jet redefines the word, ``absurd,'' but only
slightly more than the local team, the Dayton-Cincinnati Red and
Black Hats, signing Steve Avery for a million-5.
</P>
<P>
   I hate to be the one to bring this up, but Steve Avery has been
a batting practice pitcher for four years. He is no longer the boy
wonder who threw 92-mph speedballs by Pittsburgh batters in the
playoffs of 1991 and '92. Now he's a puff-ball thrower whose record
since 1994 _ all spent with clubs (Atlanta and Boston) that won big
_ is 30-37.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying Avery will flop. I'm saying he should be paid the
minimum with incentives. Instead, if Avery makes the Opening Day
roster _ which in itself is a 50-50 proposition _ he is guaranteed
$1.5 million with a chance to make $2.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is, of course, why there is no pro basketball being played
right now. The NBA owners saw destruction coming, locked the doors
and headed for the storm cellar until something rational could be
worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball's owners handed their checkbooks to the agents and
said, ``Fill in the blank.''
</P>
<P>
   The funniest quote in the post-Brown wailing was from Padre
owner John Moores, whose team lost Brown. ``It's a truly tragic day
for baseball,'' he said. ``I think the system is at the point of
absolutely breaking down. We're on the verge of destroying the
competitiveness of many, many ballclubs.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same man who was reportedly offering Brown around
$80 mill.
</P>
<P>
   So the guy up north, Rupert Murdoch, Australian megalomaniac and
megamillionaire, offered him a little more and the system is
``breaking down.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear John: Here's some news from Siege Headquarters: The system
has been broken for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Only the rich franchises make the playoffs. The poor teams stay
home. The question thus becomes, if a team starts a season with no
chance to win, and its fans know it, what will get them to the
park?
</P>
<P>
   That's the stark, corrosive reality baseball faces through the
next several years as long as King Donald Fehr and his players
association refuse to acknowledge the problem and the solution (a
salary cap).
</P>
<P>
   Brown will be 34 when next season starts. His guaranteed $105
million will be paid over seven years. What are the odds that at
the end of the contract, in the years 2004 and 2005, he will be
worth 15 million beans?
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa helped us immerse ourselves in the
game again last summer, and for a couple of months forget the
problems at the core of the beast.
</P>
<P>
   But those problems are still there, and getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
