u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARS-PARTY-COX     12-15 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARS-PARTY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The $7 Million Party
 &HT;    By Cheryl Blackerby
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas _ The party for the humongous Royal Towers
Hotel, which opened last weekend on Paradise Island, reportedly
cost $7 million.
</P>
<P>
   So what do you get when you're invited to that kind of bash?
</P>
<P>
   You get Michael Jackson, with ghoulish white face, heavy black
eyeliner and red lipstick, singing Heal the World in a wispy voice.
</P>
<P>
   You get Grace Jones, dressed like a flamboyant fairy with huge
wings, sliding down a wire from a 17-story-high bridge connecting
two buildings.
</P>
<P>
   And you get a barefoot Jimmy Buffett singing Margaritaville with
KC and the Sunshine Band under a starry sky on a sandy beach.
</P>
<P>
   It's not every party that has a lineup of Natalie Cole, Stevie
Wonder, James Ingram, Patty Austin, Tevin Campbell and an orchestra
conducted by Quincy Jones. (Whitney Houston, scheduled to arrive
Friday, was a no-show.)
</P>
<P>
   The 1,200-room hotel, built by billionaire South African
casino-hotel owner Sol Kerzner, is part of the Atlantis hotel
complex, which opened in 1994. The Royal Towers features a 70-foot,
domed, gold-gilded rotunda worthy of a cathedral. The ``Mayan
Temple'' supports a 60-foot slide that propels guests through a
clear acrylic tunnel submerged in a shark-filled lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   The new hotel brings the total number of rooms of Atlantis to
2,300 and the total cost to $800 million. There are almost 40
restaurants and bars, a marina and an enormous casino. The resort
is the country's biggest employer outside of the government.
</P>
<P>
   Even the wealthiest of guests were awed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sol is a visionary. He has brought the ocean into the resort.
It's incredible,'' said Ivana Trump. The resort has the largest
outdoor aquarium in the world. The new hotel features a labyrinth
of aquariums giving a peek into ``The Lost Continent of Atlantis''
_ sharks and tunas? swimming past ancient-looking fallen columns
and stones carved with Mayan art.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, the Royal Towers was filled with 2,000
invitation-only guests, many of them famous, including Denzel
Washington and Leonardo DiCaprio. They were joined by throngs of
the semi-famous, all posing for interviews with Entertainment
Tonight and Extra.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian-born actor Sydney Poitier mingled with the crowds,
putting his arm around bartenders and housekeepers and shaking
hands with Bahamian politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Marisa Tomei, sleek and sexy in skintight lime pants and
pink tank, strolled around comfortably alone, smiling brightly for
photographers and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Others didn't feel obliged to rub elbows with the masses, even
if the masses were invitation-only. Oprah walked through the
gardens with an entourage of 50 people who formed a wall around
her. Fiance Stedman Graham stayed 100 feet behind, with no
entourage.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts walked slightly hunched over, gripping the arms of
two women on either side of her. She brought her boyfriend,
Benjamin Bratt, but he wasn't in sight when she arrived at the
Saturday night bash. She looked pale, thin and a little frightened.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the couples ...
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump, in a dark suit, danced with model Melania Knauss 6
feet from former wife Ivana and her fabulous white-suited Italian
boyfriend. In the afternoon, Ivana and her beau, Roffredo Gaetani,
were kissing in the casino.
</P>
<P>
   Former Baywatch babe Yasmine Bleeth and former 21 Jump Street
star Richard Grieco cruised the party holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night set the tone for this estimated $7-million
wingding. (Atlantis publicists won't confirm the figure.) The 350
members of the press, including TV crews from Europe and Japan,
were stationed behind black ropes on a blocklong corridor for three
hours as guests, most in skinny gowns, swept past.
</P>
<P>
   It became a game of Trivial Pursuit trying to guess some of the
B- and C-level celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Million-dollar man!'' shouted a WGN (Chicago) TV producer,
unable to place The Six Million Dollar Man, Lee Majors.
</P>
<P>
   Next came a singing duo. An Associated Press reporter could come
up with only the song, not the names: ``Solid as rock ...'' she
sang. They were Nick Ashford and Valerie Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Leach, dapper in a white suit and vest, was all business
as he searched out famous faces in the opulent public rooms, thick
with cigar smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Free Bacardi rum and Dom Perignon flowed as guests discussed
whether this hotel would continue to attract high rollers to its
expensive rooms _ the least pricey is $430, dropping to $330 Jan.
3.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one ugly moment: A member of Michael Jackson's
entourage yelled ``Get the f--- out of the way'' in front of a
children's choir and a group of appalled Bahamian mothers.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel opened for business Sunday afternoon. The first
customers, unknowns dressed in unglamorous tank tops and shorts,
seemed awed by the hotel. They immediately snapped photos of the
lobby while waiting for rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ODD-O_METER BOC
</P>
<P>
   Who's weird and who's normal? How the beautiful people behave:
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jackson was surrounded by 20 prize-fighter-type goons
who swore within earshot of Bahamian children and their shocked
mothers. Jackson also plucked children from the crowd to join him
while he sang. Their mothers looked nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump had a model on his arm and a constant scowl on his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney Poitier strolled through the crowd, shaking hands with
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts walked through the crowd hunched over and gripping
the arms of two young women.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey kept a wall of 50 handlers around her. (Fiance
Stedman Graham followed 100 feet behind _ with no entourage.)
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Cole, elegant and serene, sang like a dream and chatted
with the common folk.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Buffett, barefoot and happy, roamed through the crowd
joking with fans.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Blackerby writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
