<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL OF MAN ACCUSED IN DRAGGING DEATH TO BE HELD IN JASPER, JUDGE
RULES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD STEWART 
and PATTY REINERT 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ The capital murder trial of one of three white
men charged in the brutal dragging death of a black man last summer
will be held in Jasper, a state judge ruled Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden also denied a defense
attorney's request for sweeping restrictions of the news coverage
of the trial of John William ``Bill'' King.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, of Jasper, is charged with dragging James Byrd Jr.,
49, by the ankles behind a pickup for almost three miles along back
country roads early June 7. Along the way his head and one arm were
ripped off. Jury selection is scheduled to start Jan. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Golden said the motion to move the trial could be reconsidered
any time prior to the jury being seated, meaning that if lawyers
have difficulty selecting jurors in Jasper County, the trial may
still be moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what was anticipated,'' said court-appointed defense
attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs Jr. of Beaumont. ``If we get one
(a jury), we have a good appeals point and if we don't, we'll go on
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs said during a hearing Monday that the case has gotten too
much publicity in Jasper County. He also said potential jurors in
that county might be biased because a property tax increase of two
cents per $100 was instituted to pay for trials of the three
defendants in the Byrd death and two other unrelated killings last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The case has garnered more media attention than any trial in
Jasper history, with news crews from as far away as Australia
arriving to cover the story.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also rejected a Dallas television station's request to
have a television camera in the courtroom. Golden said no
television or still cameras will be allowed on the second floor of
Jasper's 109-year-old courthouse. The courtroom is on that floor.
He said that if the ``first floor of the courthouse becomes
congested or the media impedes the normal use of the courthouse
offices, then we will deal with that if it occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth attorney Roger Diseker said television station KTVT,
Court TV and other stations were hoping to have a pool camera to
provide live video of the trial. He said he doesn't know if
television stations or networks will appeal the ruling to the Texas
9th Circuit Court of Appeals in Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   Golden set aside 24 of the 100 seats in the courtroom for the
media. He said the media could pay to have an audio feed from the
trial wired to a basement lunchroom and kitchen, but none of the
audio could be broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   He also prohibited photographing or releasing the names of
jurors.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs had asked the judge to prohibit the media from
photographing King as he was brought into and out of the
courthouse, from photographing or interviewing witnesses, from
having sketch artists in the courtroom or reporting any of King's
criminal history. Golden overruled those motions.
</P>
<P>
   Four Texas newspapers filed an answer asking the judge to rule
against the restrictions requested by Cribbs. Cribbs said he hadn't
expected the judge to adopt many of the media restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Golden directed both sides in the case to provide
representatives at the end of each day for a news briefing to be
held at a gazebo on the courthouse's picturesque grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbs jokingly predicted that the outside news conferences may
be brief if the weather in late January and February turns bitterly
cold.
</P>
<P>
   Golden has not ruled whether the jury will be sequestered after
it is picked.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called King the ringleader of the three men accused
of what they have called a racially motivated murder. They said
they also are seeking the death penalty for Lawrence Russell Brewer
Jr., 31, of Sulphur Springs, and Shawn Berry, 23, of Jasper. Dates
for those trials have not been set.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
