<P>
   &UR; APPLE &LR;  _ Apple Computer will soon buff up its top-of-the-line
Macintoshes with new models that meld the elegant design of the
iMac with blur-fast speed, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company may debut the new Macs at the Macworld
Expo trade show in Moscone Center next month, and ship them by the
end of January. Apple is positioning the new machines, code-named
Yosemite, as successors to the popular Power Mac G3 models for
publishers. Sources said they will come in blue, sport a curved
look and boast microprocessing speeds of up to 333 and 400 MHz. By
Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUC  &LR; _ When Mary Maldonado moved from Fremont to Newark in
October, Pacific Bell promised a speedy transfer of phone service.
But it took until Dec. 8 to get two lines working, following eight
weeks of missed appointments and installation snafus.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints like Maldonado's about substandard service _ missed
appointments, shoddy repairs, lack of available lines, rude service
_ in Pacific Bell's service territory that spans 52 of the state's
58 counties prompted the state Public Utilities Commission to open
an investigation into telephone service quality on June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow morning, the investigation climaxes with a vote on new
proposed standards. By Rebecca Smith
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ENTREPRENEURS PACKAGE &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SMALLBIZ _ &LR;   &LR; Plagued by aggressive street people and annoyed
customers, Cody's Bookstore owner Andy Ross figures his well-known
Berkeley business lost $200,000 in the first 10 months of this year
as sales slipped 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The problems along the busy shopping corridor south of the
University of California campus went beyond rudeness. Ross recalls
one day a 64-year-old woman was bitten by a dog in front of his
store. Another afternoon, two women stripped and started whipping
each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months, though, the Telegraph Avenue retail
scene has improved a lot thanks to greater police patrols, drug
busts and a new city ordinance banning lying on the sidewalks. By
Peter Sinton
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GROW  &LR; _ QUESTION: I own 60 percent of a business and want to
break up with my partner who is nonresponsive to my messages, has
not followed up on leads and has bounced two checks in our business
account. I have offered to reimburse her out-of-pocket expenses to
end our S Corp. but she says I also need to pay for her 40 percent
share. The company has not made a profit, so theoretically it is
worthless. My question is how can I end this partnership and move
on? Columnist Peter Sinton has the answer
</P>
