<HEADER>
A1542 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-2NDTAK     12-15 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SENATE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: has done.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet senators did not rule out the possibility that the Senate
would settle on a compromise short of impeachment after a trial was
under way. Under Senate rules, a trial could be abandoned at any
point by a majority vote. That could happen if members decided to
censure Clinton or rebuke him in some other fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they anticipate a trial, Democratic and Republican
senators said it still appeared unlikely that there was the
two-thirds majority necessary under the Constitution to remove a
president from office. Still, many senators have refused to say how
they might vote, citing their roles as jurors in a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom is probably right: that there are not
two- thirds,'' said Specter, speaking by telephone as he was
returning on Tuesday from the Middle East with Clinton. ``But it's
conceivable that in a trial attitudes could be changed.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not likely reassuring to White House officials that many
Democrats, rather than speaking up for the president, are standing
by silently, refraining from saying they would oppose any drive to
remove him from office. ``As far as I know,'' Lieberman said,
``hardly any of my colleagues in the Senate have said how they
would vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole's proposal for a censure measure appeared in an Op-Ed
article published on Wednesday in The New York Times. He wrote that
a bipartisan censure agreement, possibly including a fine, ``will
be seen as a blending of responsibility and justice'' and enable
the Senate to dispense with the matter before the new Congress
convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Dole has provided a beginning point for a debate of
alternatives where senators can register their displeasure with
President Clinton, hold him accountable but avoid a formal trial,''
Torricelli said. Officials at the White House and in the Senate
Democratic leadership also said they welcomed the Dole plan.
</P>
<P>
   But several Republican senators said Dole was guilty of wishful
thinking in proposing, in the words of Hagel, to halt the process
``at the edge of the water.''
</P>
<P>
   That sentiment was echoed by Sen. John Ashcroft, R-Mo., who
earlier this year called on Clinton to resign.``Especially after
the House bites the bullet, I don't think we'll be susceptible to
deal-making,'' Ashcroft said. ``My view is that the House should do
its duty. Then, if there are articles of impeachment, the
responsibility of the Senate is to sit as a juror.''
</P>
<P>
   Describing the Dole proposal as ``out of the blue,'' McCain, who
is close to Dole, his party's presidential nominee in 1996, said it
might be too late to galvanize support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever Bob Dole says something or recommends something, I
always try to examine it very carefully,'' McCain said. ``But I
think you're going to have an environment where the Republicans
don't want to feel like they've been tricked again.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials close to the Senate Republican leadership said it was
unlikely that Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader, would go
along with the deal envisioned by Dole _ or any compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point it's not realistic _ at the very least it's very
premature,'' one aide said of the Dole proposal, speaking on the
condition of anonymity. ``This will be a bitter, brutal fight on
the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   While several Democrats have for weeks held informal discussions
about possible compromises and rebukes intended to avoid a trial in
the Senate, no single option has gained particular momentum,
according to lawmakers and their aides.
</P>
<P>
   While senators insist that no decisions have been made, they
said a trial would probably get under way in early January. They
said they hoped the process could be handled briskly; Lott has said
his goal was for a trial lasting ``three days to three weeks.'' But
there is little precedence for a trial, and other senators said
their worst fear was a prolonged process that could take months.
</P>
<P>
   Lott has also said he hoped the Senate, to avoid becoming
preoccupied with impeachment, could function on a dual track: the
chamber would consider legislation in its morning sessions and take
up impeachment in the afternoons. Some Democrats have suggested
that they would oppose such a plan, and press for the entire matter
to be handled as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
   A trial would be presided over by Chief Justice William
Rehnquist.
</P>
</TEXT>
