</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRANT-HUNGERSTRIKE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hunger strike takes aim at INS deportation ruling
 &HT;    By Bill Douthat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A former Lake Worth, Fla. resident is
pleading with immigration officials to deport him to his native
Honduras so he can help his family recover from Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ricardo Reyes could be deported , the U.S. Department
of Immigration and Naturalization Services has stopped deporting
all Central Americans until at least January. The agency took the
action last month to spare Central America the burden of absorbing
more people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the United States passed this rule because they are
trying to help,'' Reyes, 22, said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
``But there is no way I can help my family by sitting in
detention.''
</P>
<P>
   Reyes is one of 12 Central Americans in custody at Krome
Detention Center near Miami who began a hunger strike last week to
protest the INS rule. Ten of the detainees ended their fast Monday,
but Reyes and a Nicaraguan, Noel Balladares, 35, were still
refusing food Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes is in detention because he was convicted of burglary of a
Lake Worth home in 1995. He said he served three years in prison
and has been at the Krome camp for three months.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes and Balladares are being monitored by nurses and will be
given forced, intravenous feeding if the hunger strike becomes
life-threatening, said Dan Kane, an INS spokesman at Krome.
</P>
<P>
   Balladares said he won't start eating again until he is given a
promise of release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be deported,'' Balladares said. ``My whole family is
in Nicaragua and my mother is very sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Kane said 12 of the 55 Central Americans at Krome have been
freed so they could find jobs and send money back to their
homeland. The 43 others have felony convictions and are not
eligible for release.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel they are living in a state of limbo here,'' Kane
said. ``They want to go back to their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-15-98 1818E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
