<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five cities chosen for poverty project
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The city of Dayton is joining four other cities
to share ideas and work on projects to move people from poverty to
well-paying jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Staff from the National League of Cities will consult with
officials in Dayton; Flint, Mich.; Oklahoma City; Pasadena and
Modesto, Calif. during the two-year project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been working diligently to aid our residents in moving
off the welfare rolls and into living-wage jobs,'' said city
commission member Idotha Bootsie Neal.
</P>
<P>
   The joint effort is funded through grants made to the league of
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Valley's experiences with projects such as the Job
Center and the effort to consolidate training for the tool and die
industry are expected to be part of the region's contribution to
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the (other cities) may have done some innovative
public employment programs, innovative things helping women and
minorities entering the skilled trade,'' said Kathy Emery, manager
of the division of community affairs. ``We hopefully will learn
from the other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bebbington writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
