<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-INSPECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN INSPECTION TEAM TO CITE IRAQ'S LATEST INTERFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The UN's chief weapons inspector has concluded
Iraq has consistently obstructed teams seeking to eliminate its
most lethal weapons, fueling the possibility of US-British air
strikes against Baghdad, according to diplomats Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration said Tuesday that it is awaiting the
release of Richard Butler's report, which was turned over to
Secretary General Kofi Annan Tuesday night, before deciding whether
to use military force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   However, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said: ``We don't have
to wait for the report to know that Iraq's cooperation was less
than full and unconditional.''
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 14, with bombers already in the air, President Clinton
called off an air strike on the condition that Iraq would honor its
promise to resume full cooperation with the weapons inspectors.
Washington and London have said military strikes remain an option
to compel Baghdad to cooperate with inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton called off the bombing raid, Iraq has repeatedly
blocked the UN inspectors. The Iraqis have prevented the inspectors
from conducting unannounced searches of a number of sites,
including the political headquarters of the country's ruling Baath
Party and a rebel camp housing Iranian guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Baghdad blocked a team of chemical weapons experts
because Friday was a Muslim holy day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts are clear. This is not full cooperation,'' said one
European diplomat familiar with the report, who spoke on condition
of anonymity. He and a senior UN official say the Iraqis also have
harassed the inspectors by buzzing them with a helicopter and
turning over one of 12 key documents requested by Butler, the
Australian who leads the UN Special Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the US force that has remained in the Persian
Gulf has been placed on alert for possible acts of terrorism
following ``significant'' reports of an attack against American
servicemen, diplomats and civilians, said Bacon, the Pentagon
spokesman. Bacon said 24,100 military personnel remain in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Any American calculation on the use of force will have to take
into account the beginning of the Muslim religious holiday Ramadan,
which begins on Friday and lasts for a month. Observers say that
leaves American military planners with the option of striking in
the coming days or waiting until after the New Year.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Iraq released its own report of the UN inspections
of Iraq. It accused the UN inspectors of conducting intentionally
``provocative'' searches, ignoring previous agreements to take
special precautions when inspecting politically sensitive sites.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq said that its own detailed analysis of inspections Monday
demonstrated that the UN teams ``were able to interview all
individuals required and to reach all the sites they wished to
inspect.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Butler's report would undermine Iraqi
attempts to get the Security Council to conduct a comprehensive
review of its relationship with the United Nations _ a step that
Baghdad hoped would lead to an end to eight years of economic
sanctions. US Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said last
week that Baghdad's intransigence was hurting its chances for such
relief.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to prevent another military confrontation, the UN
chief urged the Clinton Administration to let Iraq begin the review
process even if Butler rules that Baghdad has not fulfilled its
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Annan appears to have been moved by Iraqi charges that Butler
has been provocative in his dealings with Baghdad, accusing him on
Monday of practicing ``megaphone diplomacy.'' ``I know that his
language, which sometimes is undiplomatic, has irritated many
people around the world and I have discussed this with him,'' Annan
said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Annan will study the report and turn it over to the UN Security
Council. Previous reports then have been made public.
</P>
<P>
   US officials, while privately annoyed by Butler's blunt public
diplomacy, has publicly defended him from the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Butler has done an excellent job under difficult
circumstances,'' said White House foreign policy spokesman David
Leavy. ``The Iraqis have lied, cheated and concealed at every turn.
Anybody, whether it's Richard Butler or Mother Teresa, is going to
clash with the Iraqis.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Trevan, a former adviser to Butler's predecessor, Rolf
Ekeus, said Butler is not the problem. He said that Iraq has sought
for years to impugn the reputations of UN Special Commission
leadership. ``The fact of the matter is it doesn't matter whether
it is Richard or not. They tried very hard to assassinate Ekeus'
character.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has inspected Iraq since Baghdad agreed to
destroy its weapons of mass destruction as a condition for ending
the Gulf War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the 1991 cease-fire agreement ending the Gulf
War, Baghdad is obliged to destroy its long-range missiles and all
of its nuclear, chemical and biological weapons. The last
diplomatic confrontation ignited on Oct. 31, when Iraq announced
that it would no longer cooperate with the United Nations, an
action it renounced two weeks later under threat of attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
