u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT &LR;      12-15 0890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CAPITOL HILL, A NOTABLE ABSENCE OF HOLIDAY SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mass., Calif., La., Conn.)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS, IMPEACH-SENATE,
IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(mk) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the spirit of the Christmas lyric _ ``Let
nothing you dismay'' _ the office of Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.,
chairman of the House Judiciary Committee, has scheduled the
committee's holiday party at the very time on Thursday when his
fateful resolution to impeach President Clinton is scheduled to be
debated by the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should do wonders for holiday cheer,'' commented Rep. Bill
Delahunt, D-Mass., a committee member who was offended, like other
Democrats, at the coincidence of wassailing and impeaching on such
a momentous day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people will be in a very festive mood,'' a
member of Hyde's staff conceded, in commenting on the faxed
invitations sliding into invitees' offices across Capitol Hill amid
a continuing avalanche of constituents' views on impeachment:
``Holiday Party! Chairman Hyde invites you to join in celebrating
the holiday season.'' As questions were raised about the party, the
staff member hurried to add, ``It could very well be canceled.''
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Hill seemed far removed Tuesday from any wisp of holiday
spirit _ whether Christmas, Hanukkah or, for that matter,
Saturnalia, Rome's ancient December feast of unrestrained merriment
in the face of life's mortal defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Two days from the opening of the impeachment debate, gangs of
television crews moved through mostly deserted corridors on their
appointed rounds, doling out their 15 minutes of fame as individual
congressman stepped up to batteries of microphones. Bathed in
individual attention, they shed the status of being formally
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a complicated decision. The president chose to make
it that way,'' said Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., coming out for
impeachment. He spoke in a small office stuffed with 15 TV cameras
and a horde of news workers _ a raucously crammed tableau more out
of the Marx Brothers' ``A Night at the Opera'' than Allen Drury's
``Advise and Consent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rumors were rampant that Clinton would, nay must, attempt some
last-minute stratagem, appeal or even personal visit to save
himself from impeachment. Outside Campbell's office, a few House
aides gossipped, estimating Clinton's case was lost. ``I hear
Clinton will do another `I-apologize' when he gets off the plane
from Israel,'' said one gloomy Democratic staffer. ``That will only
put this thing over the top and kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   As sound bites and photo-ops tattooed the city, the anticipation
of history _frenzied one minute, enervating the next _ seemed to be
burying any promise of holiday festivity on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Franken, a CNN correspondent who has stood and talked
through all four seasons of the sex-and-mendacity scandal, from
courthouse to Capitol, was competing in his noon report with more
than MSNBC. A boombox blasted out ``Oh Tannenbaum'' from the
Capitol's east staircase behind him as he was trying to address his
camera on the Capitol lawn. (``There are two ways of looking at
this ... '')
</P>
<P>
   The music pealed forth incongruously from Rita Warren's annual
Christmas creche of life-sized statues that she has set up for the
past 19 years on the steps, a ritual in celebration of her First
Amendment rights as much as the Almighty. ``I expect a lot of
coming and going here Thursday,'' Mrs. Warren said warily, standing
between the three kings and the Senate. ``But I've got my permit
and I'm not moving.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the Capitol, a few tourists paused in a Senate corridor
at a history display entitled ``Rich, Rare and Racy.'' But it was
not another burst of this-just-in. It displayed the 19th century
diaries of the Senate's gentlemanly doorkeeper, Isaac Bassett,
jottings hilariously and mercifully more tepid than Linda Tripp's
furtive tapings a century later.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, intense battles were under way over the shape
of history Thursday. Democrats were intent on extending the
impeachment debate beyond a single day. News photographers were
furious that they would not be allowed to record the scene Thursday
for the nation. As usual, the only graphic coverage will be the
in-house television cameras that have limited leeway under
leadership rules designed to display civics more than the
cut-and-thrust of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Outside in the late afternoon sun, Rep. W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin,
R-La., offered the president just a sliver of comfort at a news
conference by noting that he remained undecided. But he was
pessimistic about Clinton's ability to prevail in the House. ``The
people want some consequences for it,'' he said in frustration at
the president's misbehavior.
</P>
<P>
   Down at the White House, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who
sparked a storm of criticism of Clinton last September in terming
the president's behavior ``disgraceful'' and ``immoral,'' emerged
from a meeting. ``Honestly, I didn't think we'd be here,'' he said,
looking as surprised as anyone else in the city.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
