<SLUG> BC-FBO-HIGH-SCHOOL-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEPHENVILLE'S COMEBACK VICTORIES REVEAL QUICK-STRIKE CAPABILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEPHENVILLE, Texas _ Stephenville's run to a third championship
game berth has provided a glimpse of the current Yellow Jackets'
instinctual capability to strike when backed into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nasty,'' was how one observer described Stephenville's
quick-strike ability last Saturday in a 31-28 semifinal victory
against Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville (14-1) meets three-time defending state champion La
Marque (13-0) at 4 p.m. Saturday at Texas Stadium in Irving for the
Class 4A Division II championship.
</P>
<P>
   As effortless as Stephenville's five-week run has appeared, the
pressure-filled moments were similarly evident. Despite averaging
40.1 points in the playoffs, potential land mines existed.
</P>
<P>
   Against Andrews, then the state's No. 3-ranked team,
Stephenville trailed, 21-17, at halftime but overcame buzz-saw
running back Shaud Williams' 275 rushing yards to win a 41-35
thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks later, upset-minded Wichita Falls Hirschi threw two
100-yard rushers at the Jackets. Leading, 21-14, Stephenville
needed halftime adjustments to pull away and win, 42-21.
</P>
<P>
   Neither night compared to Saturday's extravaganza against
Carroll, after which Stephenville's offense and defense both
deserved game balls. Stephenville scored the winning touchdown with
1:04 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got together and had to get our strength together,''
linebacker Keith McCormick said. ``It was time for all the work
we've done in the weight room to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   McCormick tackled Carroll running back Clay McNutt six inches
short of a first down on fourth-and-three to force a change of
possession. One drive before, Carroll had sacked Stephenville
quarterback Kelan Luker on fourth down to take possession.
</P>
<P>
   But Carroll couldn't protect its 28-24 lead, and Luker did his
defense one better, throwing the game-winning 52-yard score to Cody
Cardwell. The latter left a trail of Carroll cover men slamming
fists on the Texas Stadium carpet.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, even Stephenville had to ``find a way'' sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   Most offenses, Luker pointed out, need more time and less
distance to engineer winning drives than Stephenville needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can score from the 10 \Rin multiple plays\S or in one
play,'' Luker said. ``It doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the pressure Stephenville endured against Carroll was
self-inflicted. Gambling on fourth-and-17 from its own 35,
Stephenville hoped to convert or gain enough yards to put the game
in its defense's hands.
</P>
<P>
   The play lost nine yards on the Luker sack to set Carroll up at
the Jackets' 26. Feeling it needed more than a seven-point lead,
Carroll passed up a field-goal attempt and was stopped on downs
when McCormick tackled McNutt.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenville took over needing to cover 83 yards in 1:33 to win.
Had Stephenville punted earlier and then forced a Carroll punt, the
Jackets' final field position would have been similar, coach Art
Briles said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never really know what's right or wrong in those
situations,'' Briles said. ``We might have made the first down and
kept it going. If our defense got on the field, we had two timeouts
and we could hold them and get it back.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning drive was as unexpected as it was sudden, McCormick
said. ``We knew it would be an offensive battle,'' he said. ``But
to have it come down to the defense at the end the way it did, I
just didn't expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Troy Phillips writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7397. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's high
school site on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com/sportszone) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
