<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS DIM FOR RETURNING PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: President was to land at Andrews AFT at 10:10 p.m.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton returned Tuesday night from the
Middle East to the fight of his political life and to dimming
prospects that he will avoid impeachment by the full House this
week.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said Clinton is prepared to take whatever
steps were necessary to save his embattled presidency. But they
said two things were off the table: He will not resign or admit
that he lied under oath, as some Republicans have insisted.
</P>
<P>
   As a steady stream of moderate Republicans Tuesday added their
voices to the chorus of ``yes'' votes on impeachment, disappointed
White House aides struggled to staunch their panic and devise a
strategy for swaying the dwindling number of undecided lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite so little to cheer about, White House aides said they
had not thrown in the towel and thought Clinton still has a chance
to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It think there's still hope lingering around this place,''
said one administration official. ``But I don't think anybody is
going to bet their life's earnings'' that Clinton will not be
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are realistic, but we have not given up hope,'' said a
senior White House official. ``We are going to fight it out to the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to meet Wednesday with as many as a dozen
moderate Republicans, led by Representative Christopher Shays of
Connecticut, who originally planned to vote for impeachment but has
grown wobbly on the subject in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   But Shays and his Republican colleagues may be disappointed if
they are waiting for a public admission by the president that he
lied in his Aug. 17 grand jury testimony about his sexual
relationship with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky and
a January deposition in the now-settled Paula Jones sexual
harassment case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will do a lot to resolve this, but two things we won't do:
One is to admit to doing something he says he didn't do and, two,
he won't resign,'' said the senior White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, a Democratic from Connecticut,
echoed those sentiments as he left the White House Tuesday, saying
he was unsure it would help Clinton even if he did admit to lying
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the response of the Republicans in the House
would be if the president admitted to the behavior that they'd like
him to admit to,'' Lieberman told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a lot on the line here, his presidency and his history,
they are asking a lot and it's not clear what will be offered in
return,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although some administration officials fear that independent
Kenneth W. Starr might try to prosecute Clinton for perjury when he
leaves office in 2001, that may not be the president's paramount
worry.
</P>
<P>
   Some officials said the biggest concern is he would lose support
among House Democrats who have clung to the same legal technicality
as Clinton to defend their opposition to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he makes such an admission, it makes the vote more
difficult not less,'' said Ann Lewis, the White House
communications director.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of whether to impeach should be based on whether
his act met the constitutional standard, not whether people did or
didn't like the speech he gave,'' she added. In a Rose Garden
statement on Friday, Clinton apologized for putting the country
through the Lewinsky ordeal but stopped short of admitting he lied,
angering many moderate Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's former Labor secretary, Robert B. Reich, said the
president was not admitting to pejury because he also has ``one eye
on the history books.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were to confess to having perjured himself, the
admission of outright perjury to a grand jury may be the greater
offense in the eyes of future historians than being impeached by a
Republican Congress,'' said Reich, who now teaches at Brandeis
University.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is getting no shortage of advice on what he should do,
as a broad array of aides and outside advisers have chimed in.
Several have urged him not to go before the American people with a
confession, saying it's now too late.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides, instead, seized on a flicker of good news _
proposals by two Republicans to censure the president, raising
hopes that a bipartisan solution can still be found.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Michael Castle, an undecided Republican from
Delaware, wrote the GOP leadership urging a toughly worded censure
resolution. The resolution would require Clinton to pay at least $2
million in restitution to cover part of the cost of Starr's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton's 1996 Republican presidential opponent,
Bob Dole, proposed in a New York Times opinion column that Congress
move expeditiously to approve a joint resolution of censure by the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are thoughtful and serious proposals,'' said James
Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House special counsel. ``While
we haven't endorsed any specific plan, we welcome efforts to find a
bipartisan solution that will allow us to put this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some White House aides are urging the president to focus
directly or indirectly on wavering House Republicans and Democrats,
though they leave open the possibility Clinton may offer some
public comment before the House impeachment debate begins Thurdsay.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, however, said Clinton ``should follow his own
instincts and his own conscience. This is, you know, an
unprecedented moment. But this president's been through an awful
lot in his life, and he seems to always find reserves of
strength,'' Lieberman added. ``So he is going to be tested in the
next few days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
