<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0355 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH16-COX     12-15 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    President ponders appeal to undecided members of Congress
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman and Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton headed home Tuesday night to an
increasingly grim political situation made worse by the decision of
several moderate Republicans to support his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president is considering whether he
could make a dramatic, last-minute appeal that would include an
explicit admission of wrongdoing to avoid impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The targets of such a statement would be the dwindling number of
uncommitted Republicans. Democrats estimate that roughly 15
Republicans would have to vote against impeachment to spare Clinton
the infamy of becoming the second U.S. president to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee released the
introduction to their report, which will provide the foundation for
four articles of impeachment against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has disgraced himself and the high office he holds. His
high crimes and misdemeanors undermine our Constitution,'' the
introduction reads. ``They warrant his impeachment, his removal
from office, and his disqualification from holding further
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a three-day trip to the Middle East, Clinton is
scheduled to meet at the White House today with Rep. Christopher
Shays, a Connecticut Republican who said his early opposition to
impeachment has been shaken by the president's unwillingness to say
he lied about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats and Republicans will meet today in closed-door
party caucuses to discuss strategy for Thursday's momentous,
televised debate in the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are trying to devise a way procedurally to allow the
House to vote on a censure, a formal denunciation of Clinton, that
appears to have broad support among Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Among the few pieces of good news for the White House Tuesday
was a proposal by Republican Rep. Michael Castle of Delaware for
Clinton to make a $2 million payment and accept a toughly worded
censure resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at this late date, there are compelling reasons to pursue
a different course with a better solution for our nation,'' Castle
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Robert Livingston (R-La.), the incoming speaker of the
House, restated his opposition to censure as an unconstitutional
means of rebuking Clinton. Censure and other forms of punishment
are ``issues for the Senate to determine,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said he expects party loyalty to prevail on the
procedural votes Democrats may try to force the censure option to
the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders representing more than a dozen women's organizations
rallied to Clinton's defense Tuesday and then met briefly with
Livingston to urge a censure vote.
</P>
<P>
   But Livingston rebuffed the request, telling the women that he
believed Clinton's alleged transgressions were worse than those
committed by President Nixon, said Kim Grandy, executive vice
president of the National Organization of Women.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Watergate, Nixon didn't do anything,'' Grandy said
Livingston told the group. ``He just covered up for the people that
did. Clinton did everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Corallo, a Livingston spokesman, denied that Livingston
characterized Clinton's misdeeds as worse than Nixon's.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day at a news conference, Grandy and leaders of
other women's groups warned moderate Republicans to respect the
wishes of the majority of the country and censure, rather than
impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if he did what is alleged, what's the big deal?'' said
feminist author Betty Friedan. ``It doesn't threaten the
government. . . . Where's the sense of proportion?''
</P>
<P>
   ``To have our will overthrown by a bunch of dirty old white men
. . . is really a disgrace,'' Friedan said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same news conference, AFL-CIO executive vice president
Linda Chavez-Thompson said the powerful labor union was urging
volunteers to lobby members of Congress against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for the Republican House leadership to stop playing
politics and get back to work on issues that are important to
average families,'' Chavez-Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   But the moderate Republicans who spoke out Tuesday largely
ignored the women's warnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I conclude that the president intentionally, on more than one
occasion, did not tell the truth in a federal criminal grand jury.
That is very serious. That is impeachable,'' Rep. Tom Campbell
(R-Calif.) said at a news conference on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Johnson (R-Conn.) said, ``No one is above the law,
not even the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other moderates who the White House hoped would vote
against impeachment instead announced their support for
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   They include three New Yorkers: Michael Forbes, Sue Kelly and
John McHugh.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also lost a Republican vote Tuesday when Rep. Jack
Quinn, another New Yorker, reversed course and said he would vote
for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans who joined the pro-impeachment ranks included
Reps. Gil Gutknecht of Minnesota, Jim McCrery of Louisiana, Roy
Blunt of Missouri, Anne Northup of Kentucky and Herbert Bateman of
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said he would support each of the four articles of
impeachment that accuse Clinton of perjury, obstruction of justice
and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is anything more that the president or the
White House can do on this issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whether enough members remain undecided to give Clinton a way
out of impeachment is anyone's guess, although Democrats insisted
Tuesday the fight has not been lost.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston also predicted the votes would be close.
</P>
<P>
   An Associated Press telephone survey of House members found 150
lawmakers said they would support impeachment, 163 said they would
oppose it, 88 remained undecided, and 34 wouldn't answer or didn't
return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The urgency of the situation was clear at the White House, where
Vice President Al Gore cancelled a trip to New Hampshire and
Clinton chief of staff John Podesta met with House Democrats to
discuss strategy.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Barry Toiv said Clinton aides were still
searching for a bipartisan compromise. But he also criticized House
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The partisan nature of this becomes clear with each member who
steps up to the microphone to make their announcement,'' Toiv said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole suggested a way to avoid
a lengthy trial in the Senate, assuming Clinton is impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who lost the 1996 presidential election to Clinton, said
Congress should vote to censure Clinton and force the president to
sign the censure document in the presence of national leaders,
including the vice president, members of the Cabinet, congressional
leaders and members of the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman and Ken Foskett write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
