<HEADER>
A1567 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-COX     12-15 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmaker proposes more frequent testing of TAAS
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas students will be required to take the
state achievement exam nearly every year, beginning in the third
grade, and will have to pass a tougher exit exam to graduate, under
a bill Senate Education Chairman Teel Bivins said he will file this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' bill aims to raise the educational stakes for students
and schools in the wake of dramatic gains on the state achievement
test. This year, a record 77 percent of students passed the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills, up from 55 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has proved that setting standards and asking students to
achieve works,'' said Bivins, R-Amarillo. ``But we cannot rest on
our laurels. It is now time to raise the bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The bar goes up, starting in school year 2002-03, under Bivins'
proposal. For the first time, ninth-graders would be tested and
science and social studies _ currently not included on the exam _
would be added to TAAS tests at various grade levels. A new exit
level TAAS would be created for 11th-graders, who currently are not
tested unless they fail the 10th-grade exit TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, students in grades three through eight take the TAAS,
which measures basic skills in reading, writing and mathematics.
Tenth-graders take an exit TAAS, which they must pass by the time
they graduate to receive their diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' bill closely resembles a proposal announced two weeks
ago by Texas Education Commissioner Mike Moses. About 600,000 new
students would be assessed under Moses' plan. It was not known how
many new students would be tested under Bivins' proposal.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 1.9 million students took the TAAS. Texas, with the
nation's second-largest enrollment, has about 3.9 million
schoolchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said his plan would cost about $50 million a year. Moses'
proposal is more expensive, about $102 million a year, because he
wants to include cash bonuses for teachers whose students fare well
on the TAAS. That component would cost about $55 million. When that
is subtracted, the two plans cost about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Several teachers groups welcomed Bivins' plan, just as they
complimented the one offered by Moses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said for some time the TAAS was too narrow a measure of
the curriculum and broadening the test to cover more of the
curriculum will reduce teaching to test,'' said John O'Sullivan, a
spokesman for the Texas Federation of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly favor moving (the exit TAAS) to grade 11 and
expanding the test to cover more of the curriculum,'' said Larry
Comer, a spokesman for the Association of Texas Professional
Educators.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said his bill delays using scores of new students in
grades 9 and 11 and science and social studies TAAS exams in the
state accountability system, which annually ranks individual school
districts and campuses.
</P>
<P>
   Those scores will be phased into the accountability system after
a few years, Bivins said. The accountability system annually grades
schools and districts as ``exemplary,'' ``recognized,''
``acceptable'' or ``low-performing,'' based largely on how well
students perform on TAAS tests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is my goal to make sure that students, parents, teachers,
schools and districts have plenty of lead time and no surprises,''
Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   A. Phillips Brooks writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
