<SLUG> BC-FBC-CLOUD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC STAR CLOUD VOTED TO AP FIRST-TEAM OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The accolades continue to pour in for Mike Cloud.
</P>
<P>
   After being recognized as a first-team All-America selection by
the Football Writers Association of America and the American
Football Coaches Association, the Boston College senior running
back made yet another honor roll Tuesday when he was voted to the
Associated Press All-America first-team offense.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud, a 5-foot-11-inch, 201-pounder from Portsmouth, R.I., who
despite falling short of his goal of 2,000 yards this season became
BC's all-time leading career rusher (3,597 yards) and established
Big East season records for attempts (308) and yards (1,772), was
the only conference player to make first-team honors. He joined
Heisman Trophy-winning running back Ricky Williams of Texas and
UCLA quarterback Cade McNown in the AP's All-America backfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really exciting,'' said Cloud. ``I got the first message
over the Thanksgiving break that I had made (the Football Writers)
All-America team, and I thought they were playing a joke on me. I
was really surprised. But it all started way back last summer.
That's when I began working out about a year ago to get ready for
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled because all the hard work paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach BC coach Tom O'Brien, who was on the road
recruiting, were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Cloud becomes the eighth BC player overall, and the first Eagles
running back since Mike Holovak in 1942, to be named a consensus
All-American. The last time the Eagles landed a player on the AP
first-team offense was in 1994 when tight end Pete Mitchell, now
with the Jacksonville Jaguars, made it.
</P>
<P>
   As his spoils, Mitchell joined the rest of the AP All-America
team in California to tape a segment for Bob Hope's Christmas
special, which, as it turned out, was the last for the aging
entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that,'' Cloud said. ``I remember watching Pete on
that show. Too bad it was Bob Hope's last time. It would've been
nice to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud said he met with Williams during ESPN's college football
awards show earlier this month in Orlando, Fla. Both were up for
the Doak Walker Award as the nation's top running back, which
Williams won. ``He was a real classy guy,'' Cloud said. ``That's
the way all the guys were down there, but everyone knew he was
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud provided the Eagles with the only silver lining in their
4-7 season by leading the Big East in rushing from box to finish.
He rushed for more than 100 yards 10 times, gaining a season-high
200 in a 41-31 season-opening victory Sept. 5 at Georgia Tech. He
wound up as the nation's No. 3 rusher, averaging 156.9 yards per
game (another Big East record).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the credit goes to the offensive line, definitely,''
Cloud said. ``Guys like (Doug) Brzezinski, (Damien) Woody, (Dan)
Collins, and (Mike) Cook, and all the others _ they were the ones
who made it possible. They did a great job in pass protection and
they opened up a lot of big holes for me.''
</P>
<P>
   What will be his fondest memories of his senior year?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess breaking the record with that touchdown run against
West Virginia,'' Cloud said, referring to the 21-yard jaunt that
helped him surpass Troy Stradford (3,509 yards, 1982-'86) as BC's
rushing leader.
</P>
<P>
   As for the not so fond memories, he said, ``Coming so close in
the Notre Dame and Virginia Tech games'' _ he was stuffed at the
goal line in both losses _ ``those games will stick in my mind for
a long time, but hopefully, I'll be able to erase them soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloud will not participate in the Blue-Gray All-Star Game
Christmas Day but instead will focus on the Senior Bowl Jan. 22 in
Mobile, Ala., where he hopes to make an impression on the numerous
NFL scouts in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I'll get ready for the (NFL scouting) combine,''
he said. ``My goal is to go back there and do some things that no
tailback has ever done before at the combine. And you know me and
my lofty goals _ once I set my mind to do it, I try to go after
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
