<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-MOURNING (Bulawayo, Zimbabwe) _ Across Africa, as
the AIDS epidemic has gnawed through people like a conqueror worm,
the number of the dying is so great that it is changing the culture
of death itself. There are 5,500 AIDS-related funerals every day in
Africa, according to the United Nations. On a continent where death
has always been a communal rather than a private matter, poverty
and emotional exhaustion are taking their toll. The poorest go
unshrouded into a common pit. Thousands of graves are left with no
markers grander than the favorite cup and spoon of the deceased,
smashed in loving memory of them. And people in all walks of life
shamefacedly confess that they no longer have the money or energy
to mourn as they feel African tradition demands. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
