<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIC VOTES DO NOT DRAW HISTORIC TV RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The historically momentous votes on articles of impeachment in
the House Judiciary Committee did not result in historically high
ratings for any television news outlet that was covering them,
though Saturday's final day of debate on the issue did produce a
slight increase in viewing for the all-news cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   CNN, for example, was seen on Saturday in about 1.3 million
households during an average minute, up slightly from the 1.1
million households that watched on Thursday and Friday. MSNBC also
had a modest increase in viewing, from about 240,000 homes to about
262,000 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But increased public interest in the push for impeachment was
not reflected in the ratings scored by any of the three network
newscasts last week. Two of the three, NBC and CBS, recorded lower
ratings than the week before, while ABC was up just one-tenth of a
ratings point. Overall, the three network newscasts lost about
280,000 homes last week from a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   And a comparison to the same week one year ago, when Monica
Lewinsky's name was unknown to the American public, shows even
steeper declines. CBS' ratings are off 12 percent this year from
the same week a year ago; NBC's are off 10 percent, and ABC's
ratings are off 5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
