<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1575 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXACO-PATRICK-BOS &LR;      12-15 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXACO-PATRICK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CIVIL RIGHTS CHIEF ACCEPTS TEXACO LEGAL POST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Boston attorney Deval Patrick, formerly the nation's top civil
rights enforcer, is leaving his corporate law practice to join
Texaco Inc. as general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, which Texaco said it plans to announce
Wednesday, could help the big oil company recover from embarrassing
revelations about its attitudes toward black employees.
</P>
<P>
   In taking the new job, Patrick, 42, said he will also step down
as chairman of a task force overseeing Texaco's progess in
improving its working environment for minorities. Some lawyers
familiar with Patrick's work on the task force questioned his
appointment as the company's general counsel, saying it could cast
doubt on the oversight group's independence.
</P>
<P>
   But Patrick said he consulted Charles Brieant, the federal judge
who presided over the Texaco case, and won his approval before
accepting the new post. In any case, Patrick said his new job will
build on the anti-discrimination work he has done lately in the
Boston office of the Hartford, Conn. law firm of Day, Berry &AMP;
Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked with a lot of corporations that are trying in good
faith not to turn into what Texaco once was. But few of those
companies have made the kind of progress that Texaco has made,''
Patrick said in an interview Tuesday. ``I'm not saying that Texaco
is the promised land. But they've taken this crisis as a platform
for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions at Texaco have been under scrutiny since 1994, when a
group of black employees accused Texaco of racial discrimination in
a class-action lawsuit filed in Federal District Court for New
York's Southern District. Among other things the employees alleged
they were unfairly passed over for promotions because of their
race.
</P>
<P>
   The case received a boost in 1996 with the release of tapes of
Texaco executives making disparaging remarks about minorities. To
settle the matter, Texaco agreed when? to pay $176 million and to
promote minorities within the company.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1997, Patrick was appointed to chair a seven-member task
force of outsiders to oversee Texaco's compliance with the terms of
the settlement. The company has made satisfactory progress,
according to the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick said minorities and women now account for 70 percent of
Texaco's new hires and about half of promotions. He added that the
company has awarded more than $400 million in contracts to firms
owned by minorities and women. The target is $1 billion by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Before announcing the move, Patrick said he also received the
blessing of other task force members.
</P>
<P>
   John Gibbons, a retired federal appeals court judge in New
Jersey, who is a task force member, said Tuesday he had no
objection to Patrick's move. But added that ``now we'll be watching
him (Patrick) as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Texaco said Patrick will become the company's first black vice
president. As general counsel, Patrick replaces the retiring
Stephen M. Turner.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Texaco chairman and chief executive
Peter Bijur said Patrick became a candidate over the summer after
he asked the Boston attorney to review some resumes of candidates
who might replace Turner. Instead, Patrick himself expressed
interest. ``I don't care what he had done with the task force or
the Justice Department or what. I was interested in him because of
his management experience,'' Bijur said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of Patrick's acquaintances say he probably shouldn't
have taken the new job while the task force's work continues.
</P>
<P>
   Boston civil rights attorney Margaret Burnham sees the move as
``a complete revolving door that raises questions about the
impartiality of any investigations'' done by the task force Patrick
oversaw. The move, she says, makes it more difficult for the public
to have confidence in Texaco's reform efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Merrick Rossein, an employment law specialist at the City
University of New York, said the change at least creates ``the
appearance of a conflict of interest'' for Patrick.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick says such concerns are moot because he has stepped down
from the oversight body.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard Law School graduate who grew up on Chicago's tough
South Side, Patrick had become a partner at the Boston firm of Hill
&AMP; Barlow in 1994 when President Clinton named him assistant
attorney general for civil rights enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick was Clinton's second choice for the job after the
president withdrew his backing of a prior nominee, Lani Guinier,
who Republicans sharply criticized for her views of racial
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   Partly through the enforcement cases he brought, Patrick became
known as one of the administration's chief defenders of affirmative
action. When he left Washington in 1997, he cited a desire to spend
more time with his family in Milton.
</P>
<P>
   But instead he took on a heavy workload consulting on diversity
efforts at companies around the country and taking on teaching
stints at Harvard, Boston College and Stanford University. His
schedule will hardly be lighter at Texaco, where he will oversee a
legal staff of 80 at the company's White Plains, N.Y. headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Charles E. Walker Jr., a friend of Patrick's and chairman of the
Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination, said the move
convinces him that Texaco is sincere in its diversity efforts.
Since 1994, he has avoided Texaco service stations, Walker says,
noting that that Patrick's new job ``makes me prepared to go back
there to buy gas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
