<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-715     12-15 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-MODERATES-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERATE REPUBLICANS COME OUT FOR IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT, IMPEACH-BOEHLERT,
IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT).  
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For weeks now, the small and besieged wing of the
Republican Party known as moderates has been huddling in hallways,
sharing conference calls and doing a lot of ``hand holding,'' as
one of their aides put it, to help each other decide how to vote on
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   So when one of their own, Rep. Jack Quinn, from Buffalo, N.Y.,
who is friendly with Clinton and who had been firmly against
impeachment, announced Tuesday morning that he now plans to vote
for it, a collective shudder went through the group.
</P>
<P>
   Before the day was done, at least eight other undecided
Republicans, several of them Northeastern moderates like Nancy
Johnson of Connecticut, and Michael Forbes and Sue Kelly of New
York, had joined the snowballing impeachment ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Though the moderates deny orchestrating their announcements,
there is little question that they have been sending each other
signals about how they would vote, quietly letting their fellow
centrists know that if they wanted to jump into the impeachment
abyss, they could jump together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Quinn did it, I think that opened the floodgates for the
others,'' said Rep. Peter King, a Long Island Republican who has
been a leading opponent of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as another New York moderate Republican member of Congress
said, speaking on the condition of anonymity: ``You don't want to
be the one who tips it either way.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason that Republican moderates often act in concert has,
of course, much to do with the similar nature of their districts,
which tend to be heavily Democratic and supportive of labor unions,
abortion rights, environmental regulations _ and Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But the moderates also try to stick together because of their
marginal status in their own party, which is dominated by
conservatives from the South and West who tend to oppose them on
social, labor and environmental issues _ and who sorely want
Clinton impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Republicans captured control of Congress in 1994, many
of the moderates have found themselves whipsawed between the
demands of their conservative congressional leaders and their more
centrist constituents. Impeachment presents the same conundrum:
Polls showed that Clinton remains popular in moderate swing
districts while impeachment is not.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden swing of moderates to the impeachment camp on Tuesday
_ there are still about 10 moderate Republicans who say they remain
undecided _ prompted Democrats to assert that the moderates had
been strong-armed by their party leadership and bullied by
Christian conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democrats and a few Republicans said that Quinn had been
told by House leaders that he would lose his chairmanship of a
subcommittee and that Forbes had been pushed by the House
Speaker-elect, Rep. Bob Livingston, R-La., to support impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn and Forbes denied such pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and political analysts also said that many of the
moderates may have feared primary challenges from conservative
candidates. Republican primaries tend to be dominated by
conservative voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent much of the time since 1995 being disappointed by
the moderates' unwillingness to stand up to the right wing,'' said
Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass. ``And since then, I've just been
expecting it. The right wing dominates Republican primaries. And
they made it clear they would make an issue of this.''
</P>
<P>
   But several Republican moderates responded angrily to Franks'
remarks Tuesday, saying their decisions were made independently,
without pressure from their leaders and without consideration of
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me angry that Barney would demean the rest of us that
way,'' said Mrs. Johnson, who almost lost in the Clinton landslide
of 1996. ``This is not about politics, and it is not about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   Like several other undecided members who came out for
impeachment Tuesday, Mrs. Johnson said that what swayed her was the
belief that Clinton had perjured himself. ``Lying about marital
infidelity in private is not impeachable,'' she said. ``What has
made this of concern was his raising his right hand, swearing to
tell the whole truth and not telling the whole truth. There are
very few rights we give up in a democratic society, and one of
those is the right to lie under oath.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Though he says Livingston never asked him to vote for
impeachment, Forbes was clearly facing the kind of institutional
pressure that causes many members of Congress to follow their
leadership without being explicitly ordered to do so.
</P>
<P>
   An outcast among the House leadership for the past two years
because of his outspoken criticism of Newt Gingrich, the outgoing
Speaker, Forbes has suddenly gained influence because of his close
personal ties to Livingston. Several Republican officials said that
Forbes keenly understood that he would embarrass Livingston, who
has been criticized by conservatives for making Forbes part of his
inner circle, by voting against impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, who suggested that he was against impeachment just a
week ago, said he was moved purely by moral considerations. ``What
do you tell your children about the highest elected official in the
land being allowed to lie under oath?'' he said. ``It's wrong to
say it doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said the battle for the hearts and minds of
the moderates was lost when House leaders made clear they would
block any effort to censure Clinton, the preferred alternative for
many moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a straight up or down vote on impeachment, many
moderates felt that they would have appeared to be not only defying
their leadership but also to be defending Clinton's behavior if
they voted no. Quinn and King, Republicans official said, were
accused by friends, family and constituents of endorsing immoral
behavior after they announced their opposition to impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But the failure of many centrist Republicans to buck their
leadership on censure has dismayed not only Democrats but also some
Republicans, who contend that the moderates could be a powerful
force next year because the Republicans will hold just a six-vote
margin and the leadership will need their help passing bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just seemed to duck it,'' said King. ``They had the ideal
opportunity to assert themselves and didn't do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
