<SLUG> BC-NY-SMOKE-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE STRIKES DOWN CITY LAW BANNING CIGARETTE ADS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge on Tuesday struck down a New York
City law that would have banned cigarette advertising from almost
every street and sharply limited it in stores, saying that only the
federal government could impose such restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came almost a year after the City Council voted
overwhelmingly to pass the law, which prohibited store owners from
placing tobacco advertisements on doors and awnings and in windows.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani initially opposed the law on the ground that
it might be unconstitutional, but he ultimately signed it, saying
he hoped it would decrease cigarette sales to minors.
</P>
<P>
   The law also barred outdoor tobacco advertisements within 1,000
feet of schools, playgrounds, day care centers and amusement
arcades. But since most outdoor cigarette advertising is to end
under the nationwide settlement with tobacco companies, that part
of the law would have been largely irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of small grocery stores sued the city immediately
after Giuliani signed the law, saying that it violated their right
to free speech and predicting that it would jeopardize some of the
$30 million that store owners in New York City receive from tobacco
manufacturers for placing tobacco displays in their windows. Under
the law, such ads would still be allowed only if they could not be
seen from the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue we are dealing with is our right to advertise
perfectly legal products,'' said Howard Tisch, president of the
Metropolitan Food Council, a trade group representing 1,200
independent supermarkets in the tri-state region. ``This was an
attack by the health police who were willing to destroy us to
accomplish their goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration refused to comment Tuesday on the
ruling by Judge Deborah Batts of U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
saying it was still reviewing the decision. But the City Council
speaker, Peter Vallone, the bill's main sponsor, said he would
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's decisionis a setback for the children of New York
City,'' Vallone said. ``All research shows that teen-age smoking is
skyrocketing, and one of the biggest reasons is the advertising
targeting young people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
