<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEMS-NYT &LR;      12-15 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRASS-ROOTS LOBBYISTS COME TO CLINTON'S DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-SENATE,
IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(rl) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a day marked by a frenzy of electronic and
in-person lobbying, 20 feminist leaders Tuesday held a news
conference in support of President Clinton and than marched
unannounced on the office of the incoming House speaker, Robert
Livingston. They were granted a 20-minute session with the
Louisiana Republican. It ended swiftly and sourly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was extremely insulting to the modern American women's
movement,'' said Betty Friedan, the feminist who earlier dismissed
the entire constitutional crisis as the work of a ``bunch of dirty
old white men trying to use sexual issues wrongly.''
</P>
<P>
   The women complained that Livingston had insulted their feminist
credentials, questioning how they could defend Clinton's conduct
with a young woman intern.
</P>
<P>
   The interaction between Livingston and the women was probably
one of the least successful examples of grass-roots lobbying in
Washington Tuesday, no matter how colorful it proved to be. (``I
did not insult one of them,'' Livingston said. ``I resent that.
They marched over without an appointment, and I said I thought my
mother was as much a feminist as anyone in the crowd.'')
</P>
<P>
   In what may be remembered less as an effective exercise of
political power than as a last gasp of frustration, a host of
supporters of Clinton have turned to personal lobbying, telephones,
e-mail, electronic petitions, rallies, prayer vigils and letters,
embracing modern variants of some old-fashioned political
techniques to try to save Clinton from becoming the second
president to be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   It is an effort that even some of its leaders say may prove
futile, and some of Clinton's friends worry might even be
counterproductive, as the meeting with Livingston suggested, given
the particular ideological bent of the advocates. But it is also a
way in which hundreds of thousands of people have taken a direct
role in trying to affect a struggle that has, until now, been
played out mostly on television, in grand jury rooms and in a
congressional committee hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet Tuesday, any American who opposed President
Clinton's impeachment could, with a few clicks on a keyboard,
``sign'' an electronic petition and dispatch it to wavering members
of Congress, courtesy of two software entrepreneuers in Berkeley,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A toll-free anti-impeachment hot line, set up by People for the
American Way, toggled calls right into the Capitol switchboard into
the night. Once connected, callers could read from a prepared
script urging a vote against impeachment, available on the
organization's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   There was a rally by academics and writers in New York on Monday
night. Another one, with more than a few promised celebrities, is
planned at the Federal Building in Los Angeles on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, in one penultimate example of the kind of
grass-roots organizing that has rumbled to life in response to this
threat to Clinton's presidency, the Rev. Jesse Jackson plans to
lead a four-hour prayer vigil on the steps of the Capitol. Unions
are to bus in members from New York and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, it is clear that we have to beat down the doors
of Congress to remind them that they represent the people,'' said
Carole Shields, president of People for the American Way, the
liberal advocacy group which, with Jackson, is at the heart of
organizing, from city hall rallies to hyperlinks on Internet sites.
``I don't think we have a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the White House, in contrast to past
legislative battles, has played no active role in stirring up the
lobbying. Geraldine Ferraro, the 1984 candidate for vice president,
said she began calling former colleagues in Congress on Clinton's
behalf after watching an interview with some of the moderate
Republicans on the morning news.
</P>
<P>
   And much of this is being done on-the-fly. Wesley Boyd and Joan
Blades, software developers in Berkeley, started their Internet
petition with an investment of $89.95 (plus $39.95 a month to
maintain the site). Boyd said he now had more than 325,000
signatures from that original investment.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate effectiveness of all this is another question. For
one thing, the organizations that have rallied behind Clinton are
not exactly the kinds that tend to have much sway with Republicans.
Ken Sunshine, a New York City consultant who was involved in union
efforts there on behalf of Clinton, said he wished that ``other
moderate types'' were involved in the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great majority of Americans seem to be against impeachment
and many of them would be pretty good at influencing these
congressmen,'' Sunshine said. ``Where are they? I mean, it's the
activists that flex their muscles.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Kim Gandy, the executive vice president of the National
Organization for Women, had trouble mustering much optimism after
returning from the encounter with Livingston. ``You know, it's not
over until it's over,'' Gandy said. ``People can change their
votes. But I think it's difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
