A1586 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CRISIS-BOS &LR;      12-15 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CRISIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE STRATEGISTS SEEK LAST-MINUTE SOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House clung to a rapidly fraying strand
of hope Tuesday as moderate Republicans deserted President Clinton
at a staggering pace and many of his top allies predicted the House
will impeach the embattled president Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary turnaround, Clinton's strategists
frantically searched for a last-minute solution to the crisis, just
weeks after the president appeared all but certain to avoid such a
fate.
</P>
<P>
   The situation grew so desperate that some of Clinton's allies,
resigned to his impeachment, already were examining proposals to
extricate him from the historic proceedings before the Senate
launches a full-blown trial into charges stemming from his
consensual sexual affair with the former White House intern, Monica
S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that impeachment is going to pass,'' said
Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a Massachusetts Democrat who is a
Clinton ally and dean of the New England delegation in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Moakley's sentiments were echoed by numerous lawmakers in both
parties, as a swarm of GOP moderates across the country abandoned
the president despite a new, Republican-sponsored censure plan that
would require Clinton to pay a $2 million fine out of his personal
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Amid frenzied, grass-roots campaigns and lobbying efforts by
forces on both sides of the issue, all signs indicated the
pro-impeachment momentum will gain speed Wednesday unless Clinton
defies political logic and expands his portfolio as the ``Comeback
Kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be something he can do to turn this around, but it
certainly doesn't look very good,'' said Representative Martin T.
Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat on the House Judiciary Committee.
``The trend is certainly disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   In one possible last-ditch scenario, Clinton could meet at the
White House with a dozen undecided GOP lawmakers to try to persuade
them to oppose impeachment and enlist colleagues to join them,
according to a congressional source.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is aimed at how we can affect those undecided
moderate Republicans, and how much further the president can go in
addressing them,'' the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton already has agreed to meet Wednesday with one key
moderate Republican, Representative Christopher Shays of
Connecticut, who had vowed to oppose impeachment but announced on
Monday that he was reconsidering his position. In a town meeting
with his constituents Tuesday night, Shays said he will not make a
final decision until he votes Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The developments unfolded as Clinton flew home from a historic
visit to the Middle East to confront the grimmest challenge to his
tattered presidency. Hour by hour on the day-long journey, one
moderate Republican after another turned against the president,
announcing plans to vote for at least one, if not all four, of the
impeachments charges: two counts of perjury and one each of
obstruction of justice and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   The group included several highly influential GOP lawmakers,
including Representatives Nancy L. Johnson of Connecticut and Fred
Upton of Michigan, who co-chair the Republican moderate caucus
known as the Tuesday Group.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was chairwoman of the House committee that last year
fined Speaker Newt Gingrich $300,000 for ethics violations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president does not have the right to commit perjury when
it is convenient or when he thinks the charges against him are
frivolous,'' Johnson said. ``No one is above the law, not even the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton suffered damaging setbacks in the critical battleground
of New York, whose nine GOP holdouts were seen as so crucial to the
president that Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of Housing and Urban
Development and son of former New York Governor Mario Cuomo, was
enlisted Tuesday to appeal to the group.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, four of the ``New York Nine'' had vowed to vote
for impeachment, including Representative Michael P. Forbes, a
renegade Republican from eastern Long Island who had been seen as
likely to support Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Even worse for the White House, Representative Jack Quinn, a New
York Republican who had indicated he would oppose impeachment,
announced he will recommend removing Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joseph P. Kennedy II, a Massachusetts Democrat
who did not seek reelection this year after six terms in the House,
portrayed the pro-impeachment juggernaut as a potential danger to
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people really have to know this is a runaway
train at the moment,'' Kennedy said in a news conference in Boston.
``The amount of damage that will be sustained to our country and to
the leadership of America throughout the world if we move forward
on this is going to be very, very substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   But even many prominent Democrats believe Clinton has lost his
final opportunity to avoid impeachment. Most of the moderate
Republicans who have turned against Clinton said he has failed to
acknowledge that he lied under oath in court proceedings, as they
believe he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president would have been well served if he had offered up
a strong statement,'' Senator John F. Kerry said during an
interview in Boston, where he spent an hour ringing a bell for the
Salvation Army. ``He did not do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 435-member House is expected to begin debating the four
charges against Clinton Thursday at 10 a.m. The rules permit only
an hour debate on the impeachment resolution, but GOP leaders said
they will seek an agreement to extend the debate to six to eight
hours. Separate votes on each article of impeachment will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton needs 218 votes to avoid impeachment, but the chances
dimmed drastically as nearly half of the 38 undeclared GOP
moderates announced in the last two days that they would recommend
removing him from office. There are 228 Republicans and 206
Democrats in the House, with one independent who has said he will
oppose impeachment: Representative Bernard Sanders of Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have scheduled caucuses for their House members
Wednesday to develop strategies for the climactic showdown. But
Democratic leaders have made no secret that they plan to use every
parliamentary and rhetorical tactic available to try to force a
vote on a censure alternative, no matter which party proposes one.
</P>
<P>
   Even though GOP leaders have vowed to block such a move, an
undeclared Republican moderate, Representative Michael N. Castle of
Delaware, Tuesday proposed a beefed-up censure plan that would
require Clinton to pay at least $2 million as restitution for the
cost of the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at this late date there are compelling reasons to pursue
a different course with a better solution for our nation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the speaker-elect, Robert L. Livingston of Louisiana,
reiterated Tuesday that he will not allow a censure vote and that
he expects GOP members to remain unified if Democrats try to force
the issue with parliamentary tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the authors of a Democratic censure plan, including
Representative William D. Delahunt of Massachusetts, asked
Representative Gerald B.H. Solomon of New York, chairman of the
House Rules Committee, to clear the way for a censure vote. The
request was given little hope of being granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look like we're going to have a shot at a censure
vote,'' Moakley said. ``It's a long, long shot.''
</P>
<P>
   As the last uncommitted lawmakers prepare to vote, the Judiciary
Committee was due to release its report to the House on the
Lewinsky matter early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Republicans, in their majority report, advised the
House to impeach Clinton because he ``disgraced...the high office
he holds.''
</P>
<P>
   In the minority response, committee Democrats said the
impeachment charges are based on evidence that is ``shaky, at
best.''
</P>
<P>
   (Doris Sue Wong and Paul Langner of the Globe staff contributed
to this report from Boston.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2112EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1588 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-3RDTAKE-NYT &LR;      12-15 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: impeach him.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Members of the public have consistently said they would prefer
that Clinton finish his term. According to the latest New York
Times/CBS News Poll 69 percent of respondents continue to say it
would be better for the country if Clinton remained in office,
while only 28 percent say he should resign, according to the latest
New York Times/CBS News Poll. That sentiment has held steady since
September when the question was first asked.
</P>
<P>
   But public sentiment for resignation jumps when a different,
hypothetical question is asked about possible resignation if a vote
by the House sends articles of impeachment to the Senate for a
trial. In that situation, 40 percent say it would be better for the
country for Clinton to resign, while 56 percent oppose resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House reacted favorably to the censure options offered
by Dole and Castle as a means for members of Congress to condemn
the president's behavior without provoking a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Dole's proposal, made in an op-ed article in Tuesday's New York
Times, calls for the House to complete its vote on impeachment.
Regardless of the House action, the Senate and House would
immediately draft a strong joint resolution of censure
incorporating the charges against Clinton _ perjury, obstruction of
justice and abuse of power. The bill could also include a financial
penalty. Clinton would have to accept the censure resolution at a
public signing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Castle said that he was seeking a solution that would respond to
the majority of the public that abhors the president's actions but
does not want to see him removed from office. His proposal would
repeat the charges against Clinton and affirm that he remains
liable to criminal prosecution after he leaves office.
</P>
<P>
   Castle said that he believed the Senate was unlikely to vote to
convict Clinton and eject him from office. ``Would not the country
be better served if we took action now _ in the next 48 hours _ to
bring this matter to the same conclusion that is likely to occur
even after months of a Senate trial?'' Castle said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official, speaking not for attribution, said that
Clinton would be reluctant to sign anything that forces him to
confess to serious crimes and constitutional offenses. But if the
House votes to impeach, Clinton might consider such a step to spare
himself and the nation the agony of a protracted Senate trial, the
aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As the stream of previously undeclared Republicans announced
their intentions to vote for impeachment, at least two
rank-and-file Republicans reserved judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've announced I won't announce,'' said Rep. Jim Greenwood of
Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, the newly-elected chairman of the
House Republican campaign committee, at first ignored questions
from reporters as he walked to a leadership meeting on the Capitol
Tuesday. Finally, he snapped, ``The committee report isn't even
printed yet. I'd like to read that before I make up my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the House Judiciary Committee's summary
report of the articles of impeachment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
