<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-MUSIC-490&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDING INDUSTRY PLAN AIMS TO SELL MUSIC VIA INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By JON PARELES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If all goes according to plan, music fans will be
able to buy top hits for electronic delivery through the Internet
by Christmas 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In a press conference Tuesday, at the Sony Building in midtown
Manhattan (and cybercast through the Internet at www.riaa.com),
leaders of the Recording Industry Association of America and chief
executives of the five major recording companies said they would
work with major technology companies to develop the Secure Digital
Music Initiative, a standard for delivery of music over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The standard would let copyright owners control the distribution
of their music while making it easily available for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative intends to create technological specifications
for music distribution that would be as widely used as formats like
compact disks or VHS tapes. Those specifications would be available
to any company wishing to distribute music through the Internet.
Microsoft, Sony Corp., AT&AMP;T, IBM, Toshiba and America Online are
among the companies that announced support for the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   With the standard in use, consumers would need only one kind of
software ``player'' for all the music released by the major
companies, which control about 90 percent of the recorded-music
market in the United States. The Recording Industry Association of
Japan and the London-based International Federation of the
Phonographic Industry, which represents companies in 70 countries,
have also joined the initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Those companies have been reluctant to sell music directly
through the Internet for fear of piracy. ``We need copyright
protection,'' said Hilary Rosen, the chief executive of the
Recording Industry Association of America, ``but we must not stifle
technology to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The features of the standard, Ms. Rosen said, await the
decisions of the initiative, which will begin full-time work in
February. But they would be likely to include copy protection
(limiting the number of copies that can be made), encryption (a way
of making sure that only an authorized consumer can play back the
music) and watermarking, which would show the source of the music,
a way to trace back pirated music to its source. (Two current
methods of digital distribution that incorporate those features,
Liquid Audio and AT&AMP;T's a2b, are incompatible with each other.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether consumers would be buying individual songs, full albums
or other formats would be up to recording companies and musicians
once the standard has been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   BMG Entertainment chief executive Strauss Zelnick said he did
not envision lower prices, even if consumers bought their music as
electronic impulses rather than physical CDs. ``The cost of a CD is
related to the creative effort that goes into making the music,
which is a lot more than the plastic that goes into a disk,'' he
said. ``What's driving the costs is rewarding the artists for their
creativity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While the major labels have waited to create a digital
distribution system, a de facto technological standard has arisen,
known as MP3. MP3 compresses digital audio information to a size
that makes it relatively practical to send over the Internet, and
hundreds, perhaps thousands, of Web sites offer free MP3 music
files ready for downloading. Software that plays MP3 files, with
names like WinAmp and FreeAmp, is available on the Internet, and
the Netshow software in Windows 98 includes an MP3 player.
</P>
<P>
   ``The genie is out of the bottle,'' said Rob Glaser, the
chairman and chief executive of Real Networks Inc., a leader in
delivering music and video over the Internet. ``As MP3
demonstrates, when the industry doesn't come together and create a
solution, things happen anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3 files offer no protection against copying. There are
hundreds, and perhaps thousands, of MP3 sites on the Internet, many
of them offering free MP3 copies of music released by the major
recording companies. Ordinary music CDs are digital master copies
that can be easily copied or turned into computer- sound files. And
performers, songwriters, publishers and recording companies receive
no income when computer users download those files. On college
campuses in particular, where many students have fast Internet
access, music in the MP3 format is extremely popular.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Diamond Multimedia began selling the Rio PMP300, a
portable MP3 player, allowing listeners to hear MP3 files when away
from their computers. The recording industry association had tried
to block sales of the player. Some independent music companies have
begun selling music in the MP3 format, among them Goodnoise
(www.goodnoise.com), which generally charges 99 cents a song.
Robert Kohn, the chairman of Goodnoise, said: ``MP3 is unstoppable.
Any initiative now is like launching Betamax two years after VHS
has become the standard. The real solution to piracy is to make
music cheaper to buy than it is to steal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
