<SLUG> BC-FBN-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADEIU TO THE TEAM FORMERLY KNOWN AS THE N.E. PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WANNABE, Conn. _ We knew this was a bag job when we walked into
the Connecticut State House and saw a legislator wearing a hard hat
with a Patriots logo on the side.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Angelo Fusco, a Republican from Southington, was
standing in the grand lobby of the State House Tuesday morning, and
like most of his brethren, he could not wait to line Robert Kraft's
pockets with 375 million pieces of silver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hartford needs this badly,'' said Fusco, adjusting his Pats
helmet. ``Ralph Nader called us all whores. He is obviously
ignorant of this project. I'm certainly not a whore. He offended
the dignity and respect that 3.2 million people in Connecticut have
in this process.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone was thereby set for Tuesday night's slam-dunk vote in
the Legislature, a motion which forever should stand as a monument
to Hartford's inferiority complex (this place makes Worcester look
like Paris).
</P>
<P>
   And so the Team Formerly Known as the New England Patriots,
founded by the late Billy Sullivan in 1959, moved a giant step
closer to playing football games in the New York suburb that has so
long served as the term-life capital of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Yeesh. Wait till the Big Boys of the NFL get a load of this
place. Think there was Boston outrage when Providence was selected
as the host city of the 1997 AFC Championship Game in Foxborough?
If Kraft's team ever makes it back to the championship game while
playing in Hartford, the league no doubt will be forced to
headquarter in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a day here in the Old File
Cabinet-by-the-Connecticut. The Hartford Courant greeted its
morning readers with an editorial penned by the
desperate-to-be-loved Kraft. Remember that love letter ad Bob sent
readers of the Globe last month? Well, Tuesday he told these folks,
``In hindsight, relocating to Hartford is something we should have
done years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, Bob. No doubt you were all teary-eyed when you wrote
that one.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was quiet at nearby Yo-Adriaen's Landing (courtesy,
WEEI). The power plant was still operating full steam ahead, and
hundreds of cars covered the space which someday may be patrolled
by Drew Bledsoe. This means that when/if the stadium is built,
we'll be able to say that the Connecticut Legislature took a
parking lot and put up paradise. Kraft should dump the limo and
arrive in a Big Yellow Taxi.
</P>
<P>
   There was no traffic downtown early Tuesday (why would there
be?), and parking was free at the State House. Try doing that in
the Hub of the Universe.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Governor John Rowland, perhaps the only politician
on the planet who can shine Kraft's shoes with more gusto than
Massachusetts congressman Marty Meehan, read his annual Christmas
poem to the local Chamber of Commerce and concluded, ``To the
whining masses in Boston, I just have to laugh . . . We may be a
bunch of Yahoos, but we managed to land the Krafts.''
</P>
<P>
   Oooh. That one hurt. They landed the Krafts. Are we supposed to
be jealous? These nitwits would brag about getting home video
rights to ``The Postman.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kraft may be indebted to those who've ripped this deal
in the Boston. It is believed that some of those on the fence for
the vote were swayed by the darts and arrows slung from the media
Blue Meanies in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Mike Peters, an affable sort who apologized for calling
one Boston sports columnist a ``chia pet'' (no offense taken, Your
Honor), said, ``Unlike what's been written, we've got a lot to
offer. And I believe in Bob Kraft. I don't think anyone would pull
on the emotion of these people and then pull the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the State House, there was a lone protester, Clifford
Glasberg, who said he had a master's degree in community
development but was working as a convenience store clerk in Storrs.
Glasberg's sign read, ``Welcome to Giveaway City.''
</P>
<P>
   Glasberg said, ``I'm here today because I feel that the
democratic process is being subverted by powerful leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the chambers, a surprisingly lucid rep named John Wayne
Fox made a Finneran-like case against the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something we can go back to our people and be
proud of. What's the matter with us?'' asked Fox. ``This does
nothing for Hartford.'
</P>
<P>
   But for every clear-headed Fox, there was a guy in a Patriots
hard hat.
</P>
<P>
   So now Hartford has its stadium deal. And among bad ideas of
this century, it's right there alongside the Edsel, New Coke,
``Ishtar,'' and Dan Rather signing off his newscast with
``Courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Courage and good sense were in short supply here Tuesday. And
all evidence to the contrary, I still say the Pats never will play
a game in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
