<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ARABS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE ASSERTS JORDAN'S INTERESTS IN PEACE SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME JR.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan _ Crown Prince Hassan of Jordan Tuesday praised
President Clinton's ``personal commitment and dedication'' to the
Israeli-Palestinian peace effort. But he said the talks should be
broadened to include direct consultations with Jordan and other
neighboring Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are important issues like Jerusalem, refugees, water and
security-related issues that cannot be discussed solely in an
Israeli-Palestinian context,'' said Hassan, who has taken an
increasingly visible role in the prolonged absence of his brother,
King Hussein, who has been stricken with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The crown prince made his comments on a three-hour visit by
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Though careful to reiterate Jordan's support for the peace
negotiations that his brother has so passionately endorsed, Prince
Hassan repeatedly stressed that any lasting settlement has to take
into account the interests of Jordan and Egypt and, eventually,
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Here, as in much of the rest of the Arab world, President
Clinton's visit on Monday to Gaza was hailed as a historic
breakthrough not just in U.S.-Palestinian relations, but also for
U.S. policy throughout the Middle East. The speeches by Clinton and
Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, were broadcast live on state
television and dominated the headlines this morning. ``Clinton
Gives the Green Light for Palestinian Independence,'' Al-Aswaq
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like statehood,'' The Jordan Times said in an
editorial. ``It sounded like statehood. Clinton's words _ `the
Palestinian people and their elected representatives now have a
chance to determine their own destiny on their own land' _ finally
articulated the inevitable: a Palestinian state on Palestinian
national land.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassan refrained from joining the praise. His remarks conveyed
an undercurrent of unease about the Palestinians' concluding an
American-backed peace deal with Israel without substantive
Jordanian input or mediation.
</P>
<P>
   That unease was also apparent in Egypt, the other chief patron
of the Palestinian cause. While Clinton toured Gaza with Arafat on
Monday, Foreign Minister Amr Moussa of Eygpt said in Cairo,
``Coordination between the Palestinians, Jordan and Egypt on the
next stages'' of the talks ``is a must.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Egypt is ready to cooperate and coordinate without imposing
anything on the Palestinians,'' Moussa said after having met in his
office with Foreign Minister Abdallah al-Khatib of Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   So-called final status talks between Israel and the
Palestinians, scheduled to end in May, are starting now, Albright
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan noted that the talks would affect Jordan's border
relationships, its trade patterns and the status of 1.1 million
residents, more than one-fourth of the population, who are
registered with the United Nations as Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. policy makers have been quite open about their hopes that
U.S. support for Palestinian national aspirations will further
their other strategic goals in the region, including efforts to
court Arab support for diplomatic pressure and possible military
strikes against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the reactions in Jordan and Egypt suggest that the
repercussions of closer U.S.-Palestinian ties could be more complex
for the two countries that have become the chief regional patrons
of the Palestinian cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, with all due respect to President Clinton, to
the American administration and to the government of Israel and,
indeed, to our Palestinian brethren, when you talk about issues
such as refugees, water, security and Jerusalem you are, by
definition, talking about an overarching issue,'' Hassan said.
``The Jordanian peace treaty calls upon us to invoke Jordanian
interests when it comes to many of these issues. For comprehensive
peace to be truly comprehensive you need to encourage the
involvement of all parties concerned, including, clearly, the role
of Syria and Lebanon at a given moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright traveled here on a Marine Corps helicopter immediately
after the meeting this morning among Clinton, Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Received by a Jordanian honor guard in kaffiyehs and
ankle-length olive tunics, she was accompanied to the meetings with
Hassan by Undersecretary of State Martin Indyk; a spokesman, James
Rubin, and other State Department officials. The delegation
returned to Ben-Gurion Airport in Israel for the flight back to
Washington on Air Force One.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
