<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1597 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-REPORT-NYT     12-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL REPORT OUTLINES PROS AND CONS OF IMPEACHMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(bl) 
By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House Judiciary Committee has produced a
500-page report that summarizes the major arguments on both sides
and is meant to be a primer for this week's House vote on four
articles of impeachment. Parts of it were made public Tuesday
night, reflecting the same partisan divisions that marked last
week's debates and votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican majority said President Clinton ``has disgraced
himself and the high office he holds.'' It continued: ``His high
crimes and misdemeanors undermine our Constitution. They warrant
his impeachment, his removal from office and his disqualification
from holding further office.''
</P>
<P>
   But committee Democrats said that the founding fathers ``would
shake their heads in puzzlement at both the process undertaken and
product produced by the committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The document breaks no new ground. Rather, it attempts to both
sum up the salient points on each side, including excerpts from the
testimony of witnesses, and provide a point-by-point defense of, or
attack on, the articles: two perjury counts, obstruction of justice
and abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on the Judiciary panel Tuesday night released only a
four-page introduction to their 400-page argument, which borrows
phrases and themes that Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., the panel's
chairman, used throughout the hearings and debate to indict
Clinton's attempt to conceal his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than work with the judicial and legislative branches to
uphold the rule of law, he directly attacked their fundamental
truth-seeking function,'' the Republican introduction concludes.
</P>
<P>
   But a 93-page draft of the entire Democratic dissent asserts
that the charges against Clinton are not impeachable offenses. Even
if they were, the dissent continues, the evidence presented fails
to back up the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the committee Republicans ``essentially
rubber-stamped'' the independent counsel's report that became the
basis for the panel's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   With only a handful of the 435 House members still officially
undecided going into Thursday's debate, the committee's report is
unlikely to sway many of them, especially if they even the
slightest familiarity with the pros and cons of the argument.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Republican introduction's overarching theme is that the
president flouted the rule of law by lying under oath in
depositions to the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit and again
before the federal grand jury, and again in answers to 81 questions
from the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Although the full text of the Republican report was not
available tonight, aides involved in the drafting said it would
cite specific evidence to support each point in all four counts.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic dissent, echoing the White House defense,
challenged the Republican version at every turn. For instance, the
report said, the president did not commit perjury when answering
questions about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky because he was
using a definition of sexual relations given to him in the Jones
deposition ``not to include oral sex performed on him.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic dissent also attacks Ms. Lewinsky's truthfulness,
citing several examples from sworn testimony, ranging from her
false claims that the Secret Service brought the president to her
apartment one night to her claim that she had lunch with Hillary
Rodham Clinton.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the Democrats recommended that the House censure
Clinton, not impeach him, and denounced the House Republican
leadership for forbidding lawmakers to vote on that alternative.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority has put the country on a collision course with
the Constitution by insisting that impeachment of the president is
the only means to address conduct that is serious but falls below
the standard for removal. There are, unfortunately, partisan
reasons behind the Majority's insistence that the House be given an
impeachment-or-nothing option.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a wide consensus among Americans that the president's
conduct should not go without some form of rebuke. There is also
wide agreement that impeachment is too severe a penalty. Rather
than ignoring the will of the people, Congress should find a way to
embody their sentiment.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The complete report is to be available on the Judiciary
committee's web site (www.house.gov/judiciary).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
