<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SAGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 VIEWPOINTS ON A VOTE TO IMPEACH
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT).  
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   William F. Buckley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Author, commentator, publisher
</P>
<P>
   ``The arguments in favor of impeaching President William
Jefferson Clinton _ to follow the idiom of the articles voted by
the House Judiciary Committee _ come down to this:
</P>
<P>
   ``One, his behavior was disreputable. He deceived the courts and
the American people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two, the gravity of his offense is best measured by the
disgusted attention that has been given to what he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three, the arguments in his defense have been semantic and
legalistic. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Four, the objection that the American people are opposed to
impeachment ignores culture lags of historical frequency, including
general opposition to the liberation of the slaves. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Five, the true test of the stability of the Constitution is in
its usefulness in liberating the country from miscast faith in a
failed leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``And six, the profiles of courage, in the contemporary scene,
will highlight the Republican and Democratic congressmen who summon
the courage to do the right things.''
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Sorensen
</P>
<P>
   Aide to President Kennedy
</P>
<P>
   ``Lying under oath about even sex is indefensible. But it
doesn't justify one party that lost the last presidential election
trying to nullify the votes of 43 million people. The partisanship
in Washington is out of hand. I blame a lot of it on the Gingrich
influence and the religious right and such _ to be partisan myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have no doubt that a lot of blame also lies with the
president. His words got him into this and now he's trying to use
words to get out. ... It takes courage to be bipartisan. I recall
talking once to Ev Dirksen when he was leading the Republicans
about how to get a civil rights bill passed. It was hard for him to
move toward us on that one. But he did and we got a bill and the
country was spared a really mean debate. Now that was courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Cronin
</P>
<P>
   President of Whitman College
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see in part is Republicans using this as a payback for
a lot of things, Nixon, of course, being a major one. Another thing
I see is that House Republicans view a vote to impeach Clinton as
sort of a free vote in that they get to hammer him with an
indictment, knowing full well that it's almost a certainty that the
Senate will go along with the expressed wishes of the American
people and not convict him and throw him out of office. Still, it's
a scenario that would send a pretty powerful message about
unacceptable behavior _ indictment as adequate punishment for the
deed done. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most fascinating is that so much of the American public
doesn't seem all that worried or, for that matter, even
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbra Streisand
</P>
<P>
   Entertainer
</P>
<P>
   ``Who could have imagined that we would be living in a time when
those we elected to office would turn off their phones and unplug
their faxes in order to ignore the voices of the American people?
...
</P>
<P>
   During the next few days, our elected officials have an
opportunity to show the American people that they can rise above
partisanship and do honor to the Constitution, the founding
document of our great country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
