</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVES SENSING VICTORY AS IMPEACHMENT BEGINS TO APPEAR
LIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-DEMS, IMPEACH-SENATE,
IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(JT) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The conservatives are picking up the scent of
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never underestimate the ability of Bill Clinton to
turn something around,'' said Howard Phillips, chairman of the
Conservative Caucus Inc., based in Vienna, Va. ``But clearly at
this hour, the trend is in favor of impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of impeachment is even drawing a conservative
presidential candidate to insert himself into the action. Steve
Forbes, who has not officially announced his candidacy but has been
trying to build alliances among conservatives, plans to running
radio commercials on Washington-area stations on Wednesday and
Thursday, urging listeners to tell their representatives to vote to
impeach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president lied to the people and is guilty of perjury by
lying under oath to a federal grand jury,'' Forbes declares in his
commercial. ``This is a matter for trial in the U.S. Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   If the House votes to impeach Clinton, conservatives are ready
to take credit. Conservative members of Congress, led by Rep. Bob
Barr of Georgia, have been pushing impeachment for months. With the
backing of the House Republican leadership, they picked up steam
and by Tuesday garnered the support of many previously undeclared
moderates, pushing the House closer to voting in favor of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, they have been backed by an extensive network
across the country of conservatives whose moral outrage _ and
prodding by their leaders, and missteps by Clinton himself _
galvanized them into action.
</P>
<P>
   The most elaborate network is that established by the Christian
Coalition. With less money than the labor unions and the People for
the American Way, which are running television commercials opposing
impeachment, the coalition has relied instead on phone trees, blast
faxes and instantaneous e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Tate, executive director of the coalition, which claims
2.1 million members, said Tuesday, ``We have circulated petitions
for the last month and a half. I quit counting signatures when we
broke a quarter of a million about two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The petitions continue to arrive on Capitol Hill, as do tens of
thousands of e-mails and faxes, since many of those who are trying
to call their representatives cannot get through the overloaded
Capitol switchboard.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Giersch, 67, owner of a civil engineering firm in Madera,
Calif., said he faxed a pro-impeachment letter to several members
of Congress after a friend showed him a letter from Gary Bauer,
head of the conservative Family Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should be impeached because he has totally eroded the
morals of this country, then lied about it and eroded our legal
system,'' Giersch said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said that another of his organizations, American Renewal,
sent out faxes to about 6,000 conservatives who are also business
owners. ``Business organizations are neutral on impeachment or are
worried about the effect of impeachment on the economy,'' Bauer
said. ``But a lot of small-business owners are just beside
themselves that the guy might get away with it, and their overall
philosophical concerns are trumping any business concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Like hundreds of other people around the country who faxed their
views to Congress, Giersch wrote on his company letterhead. He said
in the interview that his views represented those of the 20
employees in his firm, Giersch &AMP; Associates Inc. ``I am the
company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Jack DeWitt, president and majority owner of Request
Foods, in Holland, Mich., also wrote to several members of Congress
on his company stationery and said he was speaking for his 360
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our people are conservative, pro-family, pro-life, and
we try to promote that type of business,'' he said. ``This is such
a black-and-white issue of right and wrong. I have five married
children and eight grandkids, and it's important to me that they're
going to live in a country that has a good family foundation. I've
been praying that Clinton resign.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
