<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-DIARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALAMO DIARY' DONATED TO UNIVERSITY OF TEXAS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A rare and controversial Mexican memoir
detailing the fall of the Alamo and the death of Davy Crockett is
being donated to the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   UT Regent Thomas O. Hicks and his business partner, Charles W.
Tate of Houston, on Tuesday donated to UT the so-called ``Alamo
Diary,'' which they purchased for $350,000 last month at a Los
Angeles auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a dream come true,'' said Don E. Carlton, director for
UT's Center for American History, which will be the new home of the
document.
</P>
<P>
   The memoir had been on loan to the John Peace Collection at
UT-San Antonio until recently when Peace's descendants put it up
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very concerned that after being on loan at a public
institution for 20 something years and then being sold on the open
market, we were afraid that this document ... would wind up in
private hands and disappear,'' Carlton said.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks and Tate both received their undergraduate degrees from
UT.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks is the chairman of the investment banking firm Hicks,
Muse, Tate &AMP; Furst Inc. of Dallas. Hicks was appointed to the UT
board of regents by former Gov. Ann Richards. Last year, he bought
the Texas Rangers baseball team from a group of investors that
included Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Tate in 1997 was named president of Hicks, Muse, a firm he
joined in 1991 after 19 years of work with Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co.
Tate was responsible for establishing the firm's New York presence,
for raising capital and for originating investment activities in
Mexico and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said he was happy to take credit for donating the
manuscript to UT, but he said it was Tate's idea to purchase it.
Tate said he was afraid someone else would buy it because they were
unhappy that it destroys a myth about Crockett.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a concern that a detractor of the diary might buy it
and destroy it,'' said Tate, a native of San Antonio who wore
cowboy boots with the Alamo on them to the donation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The memoir was written by Jose Enrique de la Pena, a junior
officer in Santa Anna's army when Mexican troops stormed the Alamo.
The document has been controversial because de la Pena said
Crockett did not die fighting but surrendered and was tortured to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton had represented the history center at the auction, but
dropped out of the bidding when it passed the $300,000 mark. He
said he thought he had lost the document until the donors called
two hours later to say they were giving it to the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were an unhappy two hours for me,'' said Carlton, who
explained that the university was unaware any potential donors were
bidding on the documents.
</P>
<P>
   Tate and Hicks said they decided to buy the document on the day
of the auction while flying to Boston on a business trip. They said
they arranged to have a professional buy it for them and had no
idea that UT was bidding.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a win-win for the university,'' Hicks said. ``The
university gets the diary and they still have $300,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton said the document _ which has been published by Texas
A&AMP;M University under the title ``With Santa Anna in Texas: A
Personal Narrative'' _ is important source material for scholars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very complex series of documents written in Spanish,''
he said. ``It's one of the best eye-witness accounts of the Texas
revolution. What makes it even more extraordinary is it's from the
Mexican point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlton said the controversy over Crockett's death is a
``tempest in a teapot'' that does nothing to harm Crockett's record
of bravery.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-written manuscript has been on loan to UTSA since the
late 1970s. It was published in Spanish in the 1950s and in English
20 years later. Many historians and laymen have claimed the memoir
was a 20th-century forgery.
</P>
<P>
   But an examination authorized by the Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield
auction house determined the paper had been made in Portugal in the
early 19th century and was a variety used by the Mexican army. Much
of the memoir was written by de la Pena when he was imprisoned for
opposing the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   The document was removed from the UTSA collection last year by
John Peace III, a rare book dealer who put it up for sale. Peace
had predicted the book would sell for $385,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
