<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAHLER-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RICH MAHLER TRADITION IN A PHILHARMONIC SET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the New York Philharmonic released ``The Historic
Broadcasts, 1923-87,'' a remarkable archival set of 10 CDs, a year
ago, an obvious question arose: Among the 26 composers represented,
why no Mahler? The Mahler tradition of the orchestra is, after all,
uniquely rich. Like those of the Vienna Philharmonic and the Royal
Concertgebouw Orchestra of Amsterdam, it was set in motion by
Gustav Mahler himself as conductor, but unlike those others, it was
not short-circuited in the 1930s and 40s by the anti-Semitic
fallout from Nazi annexation or occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The Philharmonic, the answer came back, was holding the big gun
in reserve, hoping to follow with a set consisting entirely of
Mahler's music. Now that release has impressively materialized on
12 CDs as ``The Mahler Broadcasts, 1948-82'' (NYP 9801/12), and the
obvious question becomes: Among the 10 conductors represented, why
no Bernstein? Leonard Bernstein, after all, though he did not
single-handedly revive the Philharmonic's Mahler tradition, as is
often supposed, certainly took it to its loftiest heights in a
series of performances throughout his tenure as music director,
from 1958 to 1969, and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Philharmonic is quick to reply. Bernstein's omission,
it turns out, is not for lack of trying. Sedgwick Clark, the set's
producer, explains in booklet notes that of all the Mahler works
the maestro performed with the Philharmonic, all but two are
represented among Bernstein's commercial recordings with the
orchestra, which remain in more or less continual circulation.
</P>
<P>
   One of those absentees, the Eighth Symphony, was not broadcast,
and the orchestra's hopes to release the other, ``Das Lied von der
Erde,'' from 1967, foundered, Clark writes, when it was discovered
that ``rights for the release of Bernstein's Mahler broadcasts are
not available at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the set's conductors are all Mahlerians of substantial
achievement, including notable like John Barbirolli, Dimitri
Mitropoulos, Georg Solti, Leopold Stokowski, Klaus Tennstedt and
Bruno Walter. And some of the performances are certified classics,
of particular value for the light they shed on that murky
pre-Bernstein era of Mahler performance at the Philharmonic, even
if that light is not entirely new.
</P>
<P>
   It is good, for example, to have authorized and excellently
restored issues of Mitropoulos's Sixth Symphony, of 1955, and
Stokowski's Eighth, of 1950, which were previously represented only
by unauthorized or ancient releases of almost identical vintage.
</P>
<P>
   And the ``Lied von der Erde'' finally included, conducted by
Walter in 1948, differs most tellingly from his other indispensable
Philharmonic recordings of the work by including the great English
Mahler contralto Kathleen Ferrier, as she made her American debut,
at 35.
</P>
<P>
   Other landmarks in the orchestra's Mahler history are
represented as well. From its first Mahler festival at Carnegie
Hall, in 1959 and 1960, which commemorated the composer's
centenary, comes the Andante of the unfinished 10th Symphony,
conducted by Mitropoulos; from its second such festival, in 1976,
comes a Third Symphony conducted by Pierre Boulez, with Yvonne
Minton as the mezzo-soprano.
</P>
<P>
   Zubin Mehta's performance of the ``Resurrection'' Symphony, with
Kathleen Battle and Maureen Forrester as soloists, celebrated the
orchestra's 10,000th concert, in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the set offers a wealth of valuable information,
both on disk and in print. William Malloch's two-hour collection of
interviews ``I Remember Mahler,'' originally produced in 1964 for
KPFK radio in Los Angeles, is presented complete, alongside spoken
recollections by Walter, Stokowski and Barbirolli.
</P>
<P>
   Two lavish booklets offer program notes, artist biographies, a
guide to the shifting orchestral roster, lists of Mahler's own
performances with the orchestra and of the orchestra's Mahler
recordings, and groups of essays on Mahler's work as conductor and
composer and on the orchestra's relation to both.
</P>
<P>
   Most fascinating perhaps is the complete list of Mahler
performances by the orchestra (as Philharmonic or New York Symphony
Society, with which it merged in 1928). They range from the
Symphony Society's American premiere of the Fourth Symphony,
conducted by Walter Damrosch in 1904, to the First Symphony
conducted last July by Kurt Masur.
</P>
<P>
   Mahler himself led the American premieres of his
``Resurrection'' Symphony in 1908 with the Symphony Society and of
the First Symphony in 1909 with the Philharmonic, among other
performances. Bernstein took up the cause in 1959 with the funereal
third movement of the First Symphony in a televised Young People's
Concert, and he gave his last Mahler performances with the
orchestra in the ``Resurrection'' Symphony in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   In all, this set may well be a model of its kind. But in the
wake of all the Bernstein explanations, the question remains, Just
what kind is that? Without Bernstein, the collection cannot
remotely be said to represent the Philharmonic's Mahler tradition
in full or even at its best. It can only vaguely be called
historic, on the strength of those few older recordings. There was
evidently not a great deal of pre-Bernstein material from which to
choose.
</P>
<P>
   (According to the performance list, radio broadcasts of Mahler's
music began in 1925, with the second movement of the
``Resurrection'' Symphony conducted at a students' concert by
Willem Mengelberg, but the earliest surviving copy is from 1941, a
First Symphony led by Mitropoulos. In addition to that Mitropoulos
First and the early material in the set, there exist 12 other
copies of pre-Bernstein performances, of whatever quality,
conducted by Walter, Mitropoulos, Artur Rodzinski and Efrem Kurtz.)
</P>
<P>
   What the set amounts to is a collection of good, in some cases
excellent, performances, which are mostly not otherwise available,
at least in reproductions of such high quality. That is no small
thing, and in truth the set does not pretend to be more. Both
Mahler specialists and inveterate fans of the Philharmonic can only
be grateful.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But the casual listener would do well to consider the package in
a broader context. (It is available only from the New York
Philharmonic at 800-557-8268 or on line at
www.newyorkphilharmonic.org, for $225 plus handling and shipping,
and at Tower Records stores.)
</P>
<P>
   For this motley armada, with elements both antique and modern,
sets out in perilous waters, crowded with well-organized fleets and
sleek vessels. At a time when classical-recording companies have
largely given up on new projects and fallen back on reissues of
venerable recordings, American orchestras have tried to make up
their losses by mining their archives to claim a share of the
``historical'' market.
</P>
<P>
   And they have had some success, as the Philharmonic did with its
wildly mixed package last year. But in the case of Mahler, the
major labels offer strenuous competition, with a steady diet of
reissues as well as occasional new recordings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the conductors in the Philharmonic package, two were
recently featured in major Mahler reissues. Walter's classic 1954
Columbia recording of the First Symphony with the Philharmonic was
just released in Sony Classical's Masterworks Heritage series (MHK
63328; CD). And EMI has repackaged Tennstedt's complete survey of
the symphonies and ``Das Lied von der Erde'' with the London
Philharmonic in a box commemorating the conductor's death this year
(EMI Classics 5 72799 2; 12 CDs).
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Bernstein, the commercial labels have the
goods. Deutsche Grammophon has just reissued Bernstein's
magisterial late survey of the symphonies and other works with the
Vienna Philharmonic, the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra and the New
York Philharmonic in a digitally remastered edition (459 080-2; 16
CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Sony, meanwhile, is embarked on its latest reissue of
Bernstein's 1960s Columbia cycle of the symphonies, mostly with the
New York Philharmonic, in its Bernstein Century series.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, in fact, Bernstein's 1966 recording of the
First Symphony arrived (Sony Classical SMK 60732; CD), and a
listener who was long ago weaned on this version of the work, as on
other Mahler recordings by Bernstein and the Philharmonic, returned
to it for the first time in many years.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was utterly refreshing, revealing a remarkably
detailed approach to rhythm and articulation and a mercurial relish
for contrasts, all of which had been eroded in the memory by
decades of routine performances of the work in lesser hands and by
Bernstein's own later tendency toward grand visions. Now as then,
those lively qualities contrast fascinatingly with the ineffable
warmth and mystery of that Walter First, another early favorite
given new life.
</P>
<P>
   But between those two benchmarks in the Philharmonic
discography, the orchestra's new set inserts a relatively bland
version of the First Symphony, conducted by Barbirolli in 1959,
shortly before Bernstein's televised analysis of the work's third
movement.
</P>
<P>
   The Barbirolli account is by no means bad, despite a sluggish
tempo in the scherzo and some tenuous intonation in the funeral
march. (Through glasses of a different color, Clark, the producer,
sees ``rustic weight'' in the scherzo and ``deliciously seedy
tone'' in the march.) Yet even without relentless coughing from an
audience ridden with flu or boredom, this version would pale
between its inspired neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Not every case is so clear-cut. Barbirolli's version of the
Ninth Symphony, from 1962, is better than his First, admirable
especially in the intensity of the finale, if still no match for
the eloquent Ninths of Bernstein and Herbert von Karajan with the
Berlin Philharmonic, both on Deutsche Grammophon.
</P>
<P>
   And some comparisons fall in favor of the Philharmonic set. The
Tennstedt recording of the Fifth Symphony, from 1980, carrying the
excitement of live performance in full measure, surpasses the 1978
account in the Tennstedt EMI set, though it is similarly marred by
a maddening inconsistency of focus from this intermittently
brilliant interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining items in the Philharmonic set are a surprisingly
genial Fourth Symphony from Solti in 1962, with Irmgard Seefried as
soprano soloist; a vibrant Seventh from Rafael Kubelik in 1981; the
``Purgatorio'' from the 10th Symphony, led by Mitropoulos in 1958,
and the ``Songs of a Wayfarer,'' conducted by William Steinberg and
inimitably sung by Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   This is all worthwhile material that will thrill any serious
Mahlerian, as on many levels it did this one. But it should not be
anyone's only experience of these works. A Bernstein set, either
Deutsche Grammophon's or Sony's, would be the perfect complement.
But if, on the level of these hefty investments, it must be one or
the other, it should probably be Bernstein, with hope kept alive to
add the Philharmonic set later.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, it should be fascinating to see what the
Philharmonic, with this inevitable mission satisfactorily if not
ideally accomplished, and with lessons learned in dealing with
recalcitrant record companies and estates of dead maestros, dreams
up next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
