<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-MOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT LAWMAKERS APPROVE PATRIOTS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Accomplishing in just four weeks what the
Massachusetts Legislature could not in several years, the
Connecticut General Assembly Tuesday night agreed to build and
furnish a new $375 million stadium for the New England Patriots as
part of massive revitalization effort for this struggling city.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly five hours of debate during which the decision to
lure the Patriots away from Massachusetts with the richest deal
ever carved for an NFL team appeared to be losing ground, house
lawmakers finally voted 97-49 in favor, handing Patriots owner
Robert Kraft both a financial and philosophical victory. Kraft, who
tried unsuccessfully to build a stadium in Massachusetts, had said
he would be forced to sell the team if he could not find a home for
the club in New England. With this deal, he could become one of the
richest owners in the league, sports analysts have said.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming show of support in the Connecticut house came
after many legislators rose to criticize the unusual speed which
the deal was constructed and put before them as well as its
enormous cost.
</P>
<P>
   But apparently swayed by last-minute changes in the bill, and
desperate for a way to remake this insurance capitol, lawmakers
surprised observers who had been predicting a close tally and
embraced the ambitious plan to have professional football here by
the fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the General Assembly's debate began Tuesday Senate
Minority Leader Louis DeLuca, a Woodbury Republican who was
critical of the proposal, seemed to symbolize the feelings of
several colleagues as he pinched his nose, and said he was going to
vote yes.
</P>
<P>
   The final bill, approved at by the House at 7:25 p.m.,
authorizes the state to borrow $274 million for the stadium,
infrastructure improvements and cleanup on the site along the
Connecticut River. Another $100 million in cash from the state's
projected budget surplus was also earmarked to help pay for the
development, part of a $1 billion downtown revitalization effort
known as Adriaen's Landing.
</P>
<P>
   The state Senate was expected to follow suit and approve the
bill later Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the day unfolded, lawmakers scrambled Tuesday to make some
changes in the bill, which has been on an unprecedented fast track
here since Governor John Rowland signed an initial agreement with
Kraft on Nov. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Among the last-minute alterations in the legislation:
</P>
<P>
   _ The short time frame for construction and environmental
permitting was stretched from 10 days to more than a month,
compared to a more typical 18-month process;
</P>
<P>
   _ Kraft's tax exempt status for the NFL retail and virtual
reality pavilion he has committed to build as part of the proposal
was revoked;
</P>
<P>
   _ The cap on a state guarantee to pay for unsold luxury seats
was reduced by 25 percent, limiting Connecticut's liability to a
maximum $13 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   While many lawmakers raised objections to the project, even some
who didn't like all the terms said they would vote for it
expressing a seemingly widespread feeling among lawmakers that the
city's economic and psychic needs outweighed the hundreds of
millions the state will pay for just 10 pro football games a year.
</P>
<P>
   With a single protestor standing in the cold outside the state
Capitol carrying a sign that said ``Welcome to the giveaway city,''
the House plowed ahead, asking questions, trying to answer
questions, and struggling with quantifying the value -- financial
and otherwise -- of a football franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers conceded that they did not know how much the
environmental cleanup costs would be for the proposed stadium site,
which is contaminated from a coal gasification plant that once
stood there. Nor could they guarantee that the 68,000-seat open-air
facility could be built on that site, now occupied by a steam
plant, because costs of moving the facility that heats and cools
many downtown office buildings could run too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know that's not the responsibility of Mr. Kraft,'' said
Representative John Wayne Fox, a conservative Democrat from
Stamford. ``This is not a process I'm proud of. What committee
reviewed this? How many public hearings did we have? One? With all
due respect, it was a dog and pony show....What's the matter with
us?''
</P>
<P>
   Hot dog sales jobs, Fox added, will not be enough to bridge the
widening gap between rich and poor in Connecticut, a state with one
of the highest per capita incomes and three of the poorest cities
in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Mushinsky, a Wallingford Democrat, said she was swayed not
to vote on the project by constituents who called her office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing Kraft will want to sleep in Mark Twain's bed,'' she
said, referring to the famous one-time Hartford resident and
author.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, Republicans and fiscal conservatives joined with
liberal Democrats to vote for the enormous project.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reasonable risk,'' said Representative Edward
Graziani, an Ellington Democrat. ``This is not reckless gambling.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Representative Dominic Mazzoccoli, a Newington Republican:
``Mayor Mike, this vote's for you. Merry Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Mike, as Hartford's leader and civic booster Michael
Peters is affectionately known, took an honorary seat on the
chamber rostrum next to House Speaker Thomas Ritter during the
debate, which stretched for hours into the night.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the chamber erupted in applause and Ritter,
who just cast his final vote before vacating post, lifted a
Patriots T-shirt in celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut, a state desperate to retain more of its young
people and become more than a stop along the way to Boston or New
York, is looking for a linchpin to make Hartford known more for
than the dry business of insurance.
</P>
<P>
   In an interesting twist, some undecided legislators, angered by
spirited cracks against greater Hartford from Massachusetts media,
cast votes for the stadium in spiteful fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking what became a wave of anti-Boston sentiment during
Tuesday's Special Session, Representative Robert Ward, the House
Minority Leader, said the city, which had been dubbed ``the filing
cabinet of the world'' by Globe sports columnist Dan Shaughnessy,
was gladly opening its drawers. Mayor Peters called the
curly-haired Shaughnessy a Chia Pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the filing cabinet of America,'' a jubilant Peters
said after the House vote. ``We're not
Chernoble-on-the-Connecticut. If Boston can't deal with it, I'm
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, at a Chamber of Commerce breakfast at the start of the
momentus day, read a poem to the tune of `Twas the Night Before
Christmas': ``To the masses in Boston, I just have to laugh, we may
be a bunch of yahoos, but we managed to land the Krafts.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kraft, in an opinion piece in Tuesday's Hartford
Courant, wrote: ``In hindsight, relocating to Hartford is something
we should have done years ago.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
