<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-REPLAYS-NYT     12-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-REPLAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL PANEL REJECTS FOR PLAYOFFS BUT BACKS IT FOR NEXT SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instant replay for the playoffs is dead, but upon further review
the National Football League's competition committee wants it back
for the 1999 regular season and playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   After a one-hour conference call with commissioner Paul
Tagliabue, the eight-member competition committee, made up of
owners, general managers and coaches, voted by 7-1 against using
instant replay in the playoffs. Only Jerry Jones, the Dallas owner,
wanted replay for the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee also voted, by a 6-2 margin, to bring back
instant replay next season. The members not in favor of replay were
the Cincinnati owner Mike Brown and the Tampa Bay general manager
Rich McKay.
</P>
<P>
   The competition committee will now examine all forms of replay,
from the coaching challenge system to a more expeditious form of
the replay system used in the late 1980s, then make a
recommendation to owners at meetings in March.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said he believed that the officiating in the NFL is
solid, but because of the number of replays that fans see on
big-screen televisions in stadiums, as well as multiple replay
angles at home, replay has almost become a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we have great officiating,'' said Tagliabue, who
favors replay for next year. ``I don't think we've had a decline in
officiating; we've had an increase in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the committee wants instant replay back next season, it
did not want to experiment with it during the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is made up of the owners Jones and Brown; the
general managers McKay, Bill Polian of Indianapolis, and Charley
Casserly of Washington, and the coaches Dennis Green of Minnesota,
Bill Cowher of Pittsburgh and Mike Holmgren of Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The league had a chance to institute replay before this season,
but a proposal was rejected by owners. Then came several recent
embarrassing calls, and the idea of replay for the playoffs burst
to the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   Jets quarterback Vinny Testaverde scored the winning touchdown
on a run against the Seattle Seahawks on Dec. 6, yet television
replays showed Testaverde's knee had touched down before the ball
crossed the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   One week earlier, there were two erroneous calls in Buffalo's
loss to New England.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the calls changed the complexion of the entire
division. The Jets, at 10-4 and in first place in the American
Football Conference East, need only one victory in their last two
games to win the division. If there was replay, the Bills would
likely be leading the division with the Jets in second place
heading into the rematch at Rich Stadium on Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   There is an assumption among many in the NFL, including
Tagliabue, that instant replay will return for the 1999 season. But
it is by no means a lock to do so.
</P>
<P>
   For that to happen, 24 of 31 owners must vote in favor of it.
There have indeed been defectors to the pro-replay camp, including
Buffalo owner Ralph Wilson, who was fined $50,000 for criticizing
the officiating after the Bills' loss to the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the competition committee in favor of replay are
worried because there isn't a consensus among league owners,
general managers and coaches on what form of replay they want. Some
owners want a system that allows a coach to challenge two calls a
game.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one version of the proposed system involves the use
of timeouts, and there are coaches like Bill Parcells of the Jets
who hate using them for replay. Tagliabue said no one should
``declare the coaching challenge system dead today,'' but added
there is growing sentiment against it.
</P>
<P>
   Other owners and team executives like the system used from
1986-91, when a replay official in a booth reviewed the play and
communicated his ruling to officials on the field, who then
announced if a call was reversed. While that process was heavily
criticized as too cumbersome, some owners think it can be trimmed
to a more efficient procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue added he intends to ask former referees to see if the
system of grading officials can be improved. Officials recently
told players and coaches that the grading system is too harsh.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco quarterback Steve Young said that during a game
this year, an official told him that he was forced to call a
penalty against the 49ers because he would receive a stern memo
from the league office if he did not.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2132EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
