<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1618 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      12-15 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEIBOWITZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE CARD NO DUNK IN THIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID LEIBOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Finally, truly, the country's basketball war has turned absurd.
Finally, hopefully, we fans in the not-cheap-enough seats will find
the gumption to say to the players and owners both exactly what
demands saying.
</P>
<P>
   Not, ``Oh, please settle the lockout.''
</P>
<P>
   But instead, ``Dear Lord in heaven, please stay out!''
</P>
<P>
   For a season, at least. Or, even better, until the end of time.
</P>
<P>
   America needs these two sets of self-important, whining
greedheads, determined slayers of the golden goose, about as much
as Rep. J.D. Hayworth needs a second mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Or Bill Clinton, the Confessor in Chief, needs to hike his
Viagra dosage.
</P>
<P>
   The backbreaking moment for the NBA came Sunday night, when the
latest issue of ``Newsweek'' hit the street. Until that point, the
basketball lockout had been characterized mostly by fan apathy,
boring news reports and negotiating ineptitude. Enter Alonzo
Mourning of the Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Who can't play hoop well enough to win a title or a big game,
but who certainly plays the race card like a champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a perception from the owners even to some
fans that we're Blacks who should be happy with what we got, fair
or not,'' Mourning said. ``I'm not saying it's all about race
because it's not _ but it plays a factor.'' &QL; 
ANALYSIS BAD AS SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   This was seconded by noted sociologist Sam Cassell, who's
enslaved by the New Jersey Nets when he's not busy conducting
psychosocial analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the owners look at us as Black, ghetto guys with tons
of money that we don't deserve,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage. Not as bad as Cassell's shot selection most nights, but
close.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's lily-White ownership may be a lot of things _
arrogant, cash-obsessed, short on common sense, lacking in
self-restraint, corporate-hearted _ but racist doesn't make the
list. Give the owners some credit: They may be in the midst of
killing their sport, but not before they built a multibillion-buck
business from a game with 90 percent minority players, each earning
an average of $2.6 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   That same business discriminates against Alonzo Mourning to the
tune of $105 million over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   We should all be so painfully indentured.
</P>
<P>
   So disrespected. So kept down.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as a side effect, we might all suffer from Mourning's
disease: Nine digits of separation.
</P>
<P>
   From reality.
</P>
<P>
   What Mourning and his cohorts see as race-tinged, the rest of us
see as lunacy _ not ``Blacks who should be happy,'' but ``fools who
are unhappy,'' with riches and adulation, unfathomable job security
and inestimable perks. &QL; 
NO LOSS IF NBA DIES
</P>
<P>
   No thinking fan dislikes you for your skin, Alonzo. They dislike
you and the owners for seeming so small and so ungrateful in the
face of such plentitude.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same reason no one can find a side to root for in this
fiasco. The same reason basketball ought to just go away.
</P>
<P>
   We would lose nothing tangible in its absence, nothing vital.
Only some entertainment, a commodity already much overvalued
America-wide.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood would fill the minuscule void, if there was one. You
could buy two good novels instead of your one nosebleed seat. Or,
hell, go to a college game. Most of those players get paid in cars
and cash, not in checks that resemble the gross national product.
</P>
<P>
   Though I've loved basketball since childhood, it is still only a
game, merely a sport. Not a reflection of society, or an addition
to it, but, increasingly, an aberration, a drain of money, time and
attention.
</P>
<P>
   With the NBA, there is so much not to like, and all of it has to
do with avarice and priority and values.
</P>
<P>
   Not skin color.
</P>
<P>
   The only race in basketball is to see how far away we can get
from the game, and how fast. Every last fan should run like the
wind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
