<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Macs: iBlinking Swiftness  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Apple Computer soon will buff up its &LR;   &LR; top-of-the-line Macintoshes
with new models that meld the elegant design of the iMac with
blur-fast speed, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino company may debut the new Macs next month at the
Macworld Expo trade show in Moscone Center, and ship them by the
end of January. Apple is positioning the new machines, code-named
Yosemite, as successors to the popular Power Mac G3 models for
publishers. Sources said they will come in blue, sport a curved
look and boast microprocessing speeds of up to 333 and 400 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The new desktop models are expected to be priced in line with
Apple's current G3 machines, which range from $1,600 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apple is making a dramatic bid to court its core audience of
creative professionals with these new machines,'' said Matthew
Rothenberg, content director at MacWEEK.com in San Francisco.
``After greatly shoring up its consumer market with the iMac, it's
time to address the high end.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Apple officials declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But interim Apple CEO Steve Jobs has repeatedly said Apple is
simplifying its product line so that it can introduce new Macs
every nine months _ rather than the customary 18 months it used to
take. The Power Mac G3 line debuted in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Apple is even dropping hints on its Web site ( &LR; store.apple.com &LR; )
of possible new desktop models. Customers who click on the picture
of the Power Mac G3, receive the following message: ``Due to
extremely strong Q1 sales, Apple has sold all Power Mac G3 systems
available, including servers and displays, through the quarter end.
Not to worry, in early January there will be plenty of Power Mac G3
systems, from entry to high-end configurations, including servers
and displays, to meet your demands.''
</P>
<P>
   The message tacitly acknowledges that current G3 models are out
of production and new ones are on the way, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The new computers are expected to dominate product news at the
semiannual Macintosh trade show, where Apple also is expected to
ship an update of its QuickTime multimedia technology and show off
Final Cut, a digital-video editing system it acquired from
Macromedia.
</P>
<P>
   What is less likely is a glimpse of WebMate, a portable version
of the iMac, due in the first half of next year. Expected to cost
about $1,500, it would be aimed at the same type of consumers who
have snapped up iMac, Apple's all-in-one Internet Mac. Also waiting
in the wings is a turbo-charged iMac, which would come with more
memory and computing power than its aquamarine-colored predecessor.
Sources said it may appear in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   But the new G3 Macs could spice up interest at Macworld Expo and
help further aid a financial turnaround, observers said.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent phone interview, Jobs cringed when recalling the
state of the company he inherited as interim CEO last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mess,'' he said. ``People were told they were losers,
and they believed it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But things have changed, and Apple is back on track,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the credit goes to Steve (Jobs),'' said analyst Charles
Wolf of Credit Suisse First Boston in New York. ``He knows the
company better than anyone else and has made the right strategic
and product decisions. He has that company focused.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Jobs considers himself a ``talent scout.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is team sports,'' he said in an interview last month at
his modest Pixar Animation Studios' office. ``It's about getting
the best people. The collection of talent we have at Apple is as
good as it's ever been. That has as much to do with Apple's success
as anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Jobs' command, the company has streamlined its product
line and cut costs to put Apple back in the black. A good deal of
the company's recent good fortunes are due to brisk sales of the
high-margin Power Mac G3 and the iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Apple rang up profits of $309 million ($2.10 per share) on sales
of $5.9 billion in its 1998 fiscal year, which ended September 25.
In the previous year, it lost $1 billion ($8.29) on sales of $7.1
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock, in the meantime, is hovering near a
three-year high. Yesterday, it closed at $33.56, up $1.06. A year
ago, Apple shares were trading in the low 20s.
</P>
<P>
   In late October, Apple held its first meeting with financial
analysts in nearly two years to outline a five-step ``renewal
process,'' according to a report by Gillian Munson of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   At the New York briefing, Munson wrote, Apple CFO Fred Anderson
said the PC-maker currently is working on stages three through five
of the following comeback plan: 1) survival, 2)
stability/profitability, 3) setting a product strategy, 4)
regaining application support for Apple platforms and 5) driving
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs described such a ``hierarchy of survival'' _ based on
Abraham Maslow's ranking of societal needs _ at the Macworld Expo
trade show last summer in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
