<SLUG> BC-CHEVRON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Chevron Plans Job Cuts  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
To combat sinking oil prices and boost profits, Chevron Corp.
announced yesterday that it will reduce expenses by $500 million
next year, in part through ``modest'' job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Like other oil giants, San Francisco's Chevron has been under
pressure to cut costs as the price of crude oil has slumped to
$11.55 a barrel from close to $19 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron has 34,000 employees, including about 8,000 in the Bay
Area. Sources close to the company expect that about 1,500 jobs
could be cut in the United States while 500 new positions are added
at such hot prospects overseas as Kazakstan and West Africa. That
would result in a net reduction of about 1,000 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with security analysts in New York, Chevron Chairman
Kenneth Derr said Chevron would cut its 1999 capital to $5.1
billion _ 8 percent below this year's projected budget _ and focus
more on attractive overseas prospects than ones in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Derr declined to comment specifically on the merger plans of
Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., or rumors that Chevron might be
talking with Royal Dutch/Shell Group.
</P>
<P>
   Restating his company's position that it ``will consider mergers
or acquisitions as one possible way to improve business results,''
Derr declared, ``It is not necessary for Chevron to merge with a
competitor to continue to provide top returns to our shareholders.
We need to &UR;  &LR; execute our business plan.''
</P>
<P>
   That means slashing about 10 percent of the $5 billion operating
budget of the fourth-largest U.S. oil company. Capital spending
cuts will occur primarily in Chevron's North American production
and exploration business, where the budget is being slashed to $1.1
billion from $1.3 billion this year. The company expects to make
other major cuts in refining, marketing and chemicals and sell off
some assets like its P&AMP;M coal business in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Chevron named Dave O'Reilly vice chairman to
spearhead the expense-reduction drive. O'Reilly indicated that
since 1991, Chevron has cut more than $2 billion in annual
operating expenses. Along the way, it reduced its payroll from
52,000 to 34,000, in part by selling off businesses like Ortho
consumer products and agricultural chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   During the past seven years, the number of Bay Area employees
has been cut by more than a third to about 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron spokesman Mike Libbey could not say where layoffs might
occur. He noted that the company eliminated about 400 of 1,700
jobs, many of them in San Ramon, when it decided to ``outsource''
much of its information technology business a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron currently has 2,700 employees at its Richmond refinery
and research labs, 2,400 working for chemical and other operations
in San Ramon, 1,400 in San Francisco, 1,300 at the Concord data
processing center and about 250 in Walnut Creek working on trading
and finance.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron said it plans to invest 73 percent of its capital budget
to look for and produce oil and gas, including $2.6 billion
overseas and $1.1 billion in the United States. The major U.S.
projects are in the Gulf of Mexico, including the half-mile deep
Genesis platform that is expected to start production in January.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron also plans to spend $870 million on refining and
marketing, including $540 million in the United States, where it is
upgrading its 7,899 service stations.
</P>
<P>
   Chevron shares lost $2.69 to close at $83 yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
