A1628 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GROW-SFCHRON &LR;      12-15 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Breaking Up A Firm Is Hard to Do  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; QUESTION: &LR;  I own 60 percent of a business and want to break up with
my partner who is nonresponsive to my messages, has not followed up
on leads and has bounced two checks in our business account. I have
offered to reimburse her out-of-pocket expenses to end our S Corp.
but she says I also need to pay for her 40 percent share. The
company has not made a profit, so theoretically it is worthless. My
question is how can I end this partnership and move on? In the
meantime I have started a new sole-proprietor company so that I can
continue to try to make my concept work.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  In business as in marriage, breaking up is hard to
do and many partners don't spend enough time planning for the worst
instead of the best.
</P>
<P>
   As the majority shareholder in a corporation, you can elect
unilaterally to dissolve the corporation, says San Francisco
attorney Michael Casey Walker. But that doesn't mean there won't be
a fight over the remains.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders holding at least 50 percent of a corporation may
voluntarily decide to dissolve at any time. Your corporate by-laws
may spell out procedural requirements for dissolution and notice.
Typically, all shareholders and creditors must be advised. The
secretary of state or other state agency responsible for
establishing your corporation must be notified, too.
</P>
<P>
   You will need to file a certificate showing that the election to
dissolve was made by the shareholders and signed by the majority of
voting shareholders. A California corporation cannot be dissolved
until the California Franchise Tax Board certifies that all
corporate taxes have been paid.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate creditors must be paid off and if there are assets
left, they should be distributed to the shareholders based on their
ownership position and contribution to the business.
</P>
<P>
   Just because your business is not making money doesn't mean it
it is worthless. Nor does it mean that your partner deserves to get
back exactly what she put in.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps your corporate agreement sets out procedures for
appraising the business in case of dissolution. It should. But if
it doesn't, you will have to try to reach an agreement with your
partner or go to court.
</P>
<P>
   Walker offers one other warning. You may be on thin ice
establishing a sole proprietorship before dissolving your current
business. ``A director of a corporation owes a duty of loyalty to
the corporation and cannot usurp opportunities by competing with
the corporation in the same business lines,'' he warned. Your
partner could sue you for keeping business for yourself that should
go to the corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Pension Planning
</P>
<P>
   Q:  &LR; My previous employer provided a pension plan that allowed &LR; 
 &LR; up to half of contributions to be used for certain investments. &LR; 
 &LR; (I borrowed $30,000 to pay the deposit on my home and pay &LR;   &LR; myself
back at 6 percent interest.) Last December, I &LR;   &LR; incorporated (S
Corp) and my previous employer would prefer &LR;   &LR; that I remove the
funds from his plan but has given me some &LR;   &LR; leeway in timing. How
do I move these funds while retaining the &LR;   &LR; ability to borrow
against them, and how do I handle the amount &LR;   &LR; I still owe to my
fund? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A: Your former employer should continue to grant you leeway
about withdrawing your funds. Pension plan participants with more
than a $5,000 balance cannot be forced out unless they reach
retirement age, die or the plan terminates, says retirement
planning expert Stephen Dobrow, president of Primark Benefits in
Burlingame. Most likely, you can leave your account with the prior
employer until you reach age 591/2.
</P>
<P>
   However, if your former employer doesn't want the hassle of
handling your loan payments, it can adopt a provision that requires
you to either repay the loan or be taxed on the outstanding
balance. A careful review of the plan and the loan documentation
may reveal these details.
</P>
<P>
   If you elected regular C Corporation status for your new company
and adopted an appropriate profit sharing plan, your loan could be
directly transferred to the new plan and you can enjoy
contributions, withdrawals and payments as before. (This new plan
must be qualified under Section 401(a) of the federal tax code; a
Simplified Employer Pension or SEP allows neither transfers nor
loans.)
</P>
<P>
   Unsolicited warning: The 6 percent interest rate you have been
charging yourself on the borrowed funds is too low; it should be
the prime interest rate plus 1 percent or 2 percent, according to
Dobrow. ``You can't give yourself a sweetheart deal with a pension
loan,'' he says. ``Cross your fingers you don't get caught by the
Department of Labor or the IRS.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, you can borrow half of the total in your plan, but only up
to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Part-Time Help
</P>
<P>
   Q:  &LR; We're a start-up Internet software company with an &LR;   &LR; opening
for a part-time business and marketing position and &LR;   &LR; would like to
offer a competitive salary without going &LR;   &LR; overboard. How do we
find the right person and pay the right &LR;   &LR; price? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Many small-business experts believe understanding your
market and knowing how to address it is one of the primary
responsibilities of the founding team. ``This skill is difficult to
find on a part-time basis,'' says San Francisco attorney Rob
Dellenbach. In the short term he suggests checking consultants who
assist Internet companies with marketing. Be sure to check
references and ask about prior successes.
</P>
<P>
   You might contact friendly Internet companies that offer
complimentary services and find out who they use and what they pay.
Also check the classified ads or help wanted sections of
information technology trade books. But be warned: listed salaries
are not always the final salaries.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Brandt, president of the San Francisco consulting firm
Strategic Technologies Inc., suggests that headhunters can give you
an idea of how much it would cost to fill your position. Beware
that executive search firms usually fill permanent positions and
extract a significant fee.
</P>
<P>
   If you are looking for a seasoned veteran, someone who has been
VP of marketing for a successful startup or the entrepreneurial
division of a larger company, be prepared to pay $120,000 to
$180,000 or half that for a half-time position, Brandt says.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation schedules for particular positions are scarce but
you might know someone at an accounting/consulting firm like Arthur
Andersen or Coopers &AMP; Lybrand that conduct periodic surveys of key
personnel and are familiar with compensation packages.
</P>
<P>
   Granting stock options to employees and stock warrants to
consultants is one way cash-starved startups can conserve money.
Someone who has been successful in the past may not have urgent
cash needs and might be willing to forgo current compensation for
future stock benefits. Dellenbach says you can protect yourself
from giving away too much by making sure that employees and
consultants serve ``at will.'' That way, their grants are
structured in such a way that they receive increasing portions as
long as they remain with the company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1630 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SFCHRON &LR;      12-15 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Recording Industry Tries Out New Tune  &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The recording industry yesterday launched a new attempt to stamp
out music piracy, but quickly drew fire from Internet music fans.
</P>
<P>
   The heads of five major record labels, as expected, launched a
new coalition of music and technology firms to decide how to
distribute digital music while protecting artists' royalties and
industry revenues.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The Secure Digital Music Initiative, or SDMI, coalition hopes
to devise a way to protect copyrighted music in time for next
Christmas, though further details about how the new standard will
work were scarce.
</P>
<P>
   The move, announced at a New York press conference, comes in
response to a spate of new digital-music technologies that allow
consumers to reproduce and distribute CD-quality music over the
Internet without paying royalties to the $13 billion music
industry. Most prominent is MP3, a free audio compression format
that has gained popularity through a grassroots Internet movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In computer-speak, we would call (the plan) `vapor-ware,'
because there was no meat there,'' said Michael Robertson, founder
of a popular Web site, MP3.com, that offers songs in the MP3
format.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said he think the music industry is trying to force
the Internet community to adopt its anti-copying standard. ``For 50
years, the music industry has had a lock on (music distribution)
and for the first time, the Internet is breaking up that
stranglehold.''
</P>
<P>
   The record companies said they weren't necessarily trying to
stamp out MP3.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition will start meeting next month. Technology
companies like Microsoft, Toshiba, Lucent and America Online will
join with music companies like Sony Music Entertainment, Warner
Bros., BMG Entertainment, EMI Recorded Music and Universal Music
Group, to create standards that can be applied to any existing
digital audio technology, including MP3, Liquid Audio and a2b.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the recording industry imposing a standard on
technology companies,'' said Hilary Rosen, president of the
Recording Industry Association of America. ``We'll simply provide
guidance on the needs of our industry and its customers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``SDMI will enable all of us to continue business in a safer and
much more secure environment,'' said Sony CEO Tommy Mottola.
</P>
<P>
   Liquid Audio, a two-year-old Redwood City company that is
promoting its own proprietary digital technology, hailed the
development.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that's long overdue,'' said Bill Woods,
Liquid Audio marketing director. ``We want to get our music to the
fans, but in a way that's legally responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mark Hardie, a senior entertainment industry analyst with
Forrester Research of Cambridge, Mass., said the recording
industry's new coalition ``was extremely disappointing because they
didn't say anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is facing a new distribution channel where they
have no control,'' said Hardie, who noted there are already about
20 million MP3 players and other related programs in use.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1631 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     12-15 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOYFUL NOISE: A KID TALKING WITH SANTA  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I could understand the mother's reluctance. After all, a
stranger was calling with a deeper-than-normal voice and asking to
speak with her 4-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, may I ask who's calling?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Claus.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh. Well that's different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason!'' she yelled, ``There's a really important phone call
for you!''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone knows that this is the busy time of year for Santa. Big
run on toys and all that. But wouldn't it be great _ to say nothing
of reassuring _ for a kid to get a personal call from the jolly old
elf?
</P>
<P>
   That's the idea behind Santa's Calling, a program sponsored by
Tempe Parks and Recreation and the Retirees of Tempe As sociation.
Of course, Santa himself was too tied up to yak on the phone, but,
much like the Santa's helpers who sit in at malls everywhere,
volunteers came to the Pyle Adult Activity Center over the weekend
and called kids for him.
</P>
<P>
   Parents knew about the calls and had filled out forms with some
pertinent facts about the kids and their Christmas wishes. Hey,
it's Santa who knows who's been naughty and nice and all that, not
the rest of us. &QL; 
THAT'S `DASHER,' WITH A `D'
</P>
<P>
   Armed with that information, as well as a cheat sheet that
included the names of all eight reindeer, a handful of people
manned the phones. I did, as well, and I've got to say, if you're
looking for a heavy dose of Christmas spirit, I can't think of a
better place to find it.
</P>
<P>
   Take the call to Jason, for instance. He was so excited, he
nearly hyperventilated. Sure, he told me what he wanted: a game,
some Christmas money and (maybe a lit tle embarrassingly) a teddy
bear _ but it was the way he told me that made me want to hang
stockings by the chimney with care.
</P>
<P>
   Every word was fraught with impor tance, since it was crucial
that I under stand exactly what he wanted. If there weren't visions
of sugar plums dancing in his head, he certainly faked it well.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite Christmas carol is The Lit tle Drummer Boy, he
said. Could he sing a little? Sure, but the only part he could
remember was, ``fum, fum, fum.''
</P>
<P>
   The volunteers had worked out a plan for exiting the
conversations. We had sleigh bells, which we jingled; the rein deer
were restless and needed to be fed. So after a while, I gave the
bells a shake, and BAM! Jason was in Christmas over drive,
shrieking about the reindeer and Santa to his sisters, who would
soon come to the phone.
</P>
<P>
   You just can't beat sleigh bells for blasting a kid into the
holiday strato sphere. If Jason got a lick of sleep Satur day
night, I'd be surprised. &QL; 
HONESTLY GOOD
</P>
<P>
   A standard question, of course, was asking the children if
they'd been good. I expected Clinton-like answers, avoiding the
real issue. But I was happily surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' 9-year-old Ari said. ``Have I been good?''
</P>
<P>
   What are you going to say to that? I had just enjoyed her
warbling the sweetest two-line version of Silent Night I've ever
heard. ``Yes'' was the only answer I could think of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goody!'' she squealed.
</P>
<P>
   As for honesty, it's hard to beat 6-year-old Jeremy's response.
Of course he's been good, he said _ ``I know you've been watching
me.''
</P>
<P>
   When it came time to hang up with Jeremy, he turned the tables
and started asking the questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where are the elves?'' In the work shop, ho, ho, ho.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you in the workshop?'' Uh, no, in my office. I had to give
the sleigh bells another quick jingle before we got into questions
I couldn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   Not every call was so successful, at least from Santa's
perspective. Four-year-old Kalina asked one question: ``Are you
Santa Claus?'' Of course. And with that she dropped the phone and
left. Her mom coaxed her back, but only for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so excited,'' her mom said, laughing, after the
happy-but-shy Kalina bolted for the second time.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Going to be a long wait till the 25th at their
house, I'll bet.
</P>
<P>
   I'm glad I could help. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
