<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1632 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLBIZ-SFCHRON &LR;      12-15 1545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cleaning Up the Streets  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Plagued by aggressive street people and annoyed customers, Cody's
Books owner Andy Ross figures his well-known Berkeley business lost
$200,000 in the first 10 months of this year as sales slipped 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Telegraph Avenue has had its ups and downs but this has been
the worst year ever,'' said Ross. ``The way things were going, we
couldn't continue to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems along the busy shopping corridor south of the
University of California campus went beyond rudeness. Ross recalls
one day a 64-year-old woman was bitten by a dog in front of his
store. Another afternoon, two women stripped and started whipping
each other.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two months, though, the Telegraph Avenue retail
scene has improved a lot thanks to greater police patrols, drug
busts and a new city ordinance banning lying on the sidewalks. Ross
and his fellow retailers expect things to get even better in
February when the new Telegraph Avenue Business Improvement
District begins to shell out $269,000 a year for ``broom
brigades,'' ``graffiti tag-out teams'' and other services.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign in Berkeley is not unique. To combat vandals and
vagrants, a growing number of merchants, property owners and city
governments are mounting campaigns to clean up specific shopping
districts.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,200 North American cities have created business
improvement districts, where land owners and their tenants assess
themselves to pay for extra services like cleaning streets and
sidewalks, removing graffiti and providing additional security and
social services.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern California a few dozen cities including San Jose and
Sacramento have had BIDs for years. Now more communities are
jumping on the bandwagon:
</P>
<P>
   _ Two weeks ago, the San Francisco Supervisors' Finance
Committee endorsed proposals to spend nearly $1 million annually
over five years to spruce up a 10-block area around Powell Street
from Market to Sutter. The Union Square Business Improvement
District comes up for a full vote by the board of supervisors next
month.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last January, Oakland neighborhood merchants initiated a
business improvement district along a two-block stretch of
Lakeshore Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent survey, 42 percent of small businesses in the Los
Angeles area said graffiti and vandalism were a problem. There has
been no similar poll of Bay Area merchants, who also have to deal
with homeless in their doorways, aggressive panhandlers, sprayed
walls, etched windows, litter and shoplifting. But the sentiment
appears to be much the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of customers don't want to endanger themselves,'' said
Deepak Singh, owner of Kathmandu Imports, who continually battles
graffiti and street people in his doorway at Telegraph near Dwight
Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is slow,'' added Yoon Kwon, manager of Pier Luggage
on Powell Street in San Francisco. ``The Asian economy hasn't
helped the tourist business and the tourists who do come are
bothered by people asking them for money.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, it increasingly has fallen on property
owners and merchants to deal with these problems. ``Redevelopment
agencies have been running out of money,'' said BID consultant
Nancy Hormann of Sherman Oaks (Los Angeles County). ``Business
improvement districts that assess themselves have been filling the
gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Merchants can take individual action, Hormann noted, but BIDs
``create a unified voice and economies of scale.''
</P>
<P>
   New York city alone has more than 30 BIDs, including the much
publicized one that cleaned up Times Square. In California, there
are close to 200 BIDs, including about 20 based on property
assessments and devoted to making areas clean and safe. The
majority of BIDs, like the one started in San Jose a decade ago,
are financed by a surcharge on business license fees and designed
primarily for marketing and promotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``BIDS have become ubiquitous because they are incredibly
effective in cleaning up cities and reducing anti-social
behavior,'' said Elizabeth Jackson, president of the International
Downtown Association, a Washington, D.C., organization that
publishes a variety of guides from creating a BID to ``Responses to
Panhandling and Homelessness.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  While Los Angeles already has 17 business improvement
districts and 27 more on the drawing board, according to the Los
Angeles Times, San Francisco is still just approaching the launch
pad. That is due in part to political infighting and opposition by
a homeless coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In San Francisco you put three people in a room and they find
something to protest,'' said Linda Mjellem, executive director of
the Union Square Association. But after three years she anticipates
approval of the Union Square BID soon and major returns.
</P>
<P>
   She notes that one BID in Portland reportedly reduced crime 20
percent. One in Phoenix contributed to a 26 percent gain in sales
tax revenues over three years. One in Denver helped reduce office
vacancy from 31 percent to 13 percent. Another in Houston cut
litter by 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many BIDs, like the one in Baltimore, have hired their own
radio-equipped but unarmed security personnel. Even without a BID,
several San Francisco businesses and property owners including
Nordstrom, Macy's, Hilton Hotel and the Flood building have hired
10 sweepers and ``ambassadors'' in red jackets to walk their
sidewalks, keeping them clean and safe.
</P>
<P>
   One recent evening, ambassador Danny Rodriguez politely told a
panhandler named Ron that he was sitting too close to Walgreen's
front door on Powell Street (within eight feet). He asked another
homeless person if he wanted a free token for one of the
coin-operated public toilets.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's BID would double or triple Union Square's
current efforts to clean up the city's premier retail area.
</P>
<P>
   Another tactic cities have used to tune up their shopping
districts is to establish minimal standards of public conduct such
as forbidding sleeping in doorways and blocking sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Seattle was one of the first cities to pass an
ordinance against ``pedestrian interference,'' says Rob Teir,
president of the Center for Liveable Cities in Washington, D.C.
Seattle also was among the first to ban sitting and lying on
sidewalks in commercial districts during business hours.
</P>
<P>
   Teir notes that San Francisco &UR;  &LR; 50-foot ``zone of prohibition''
is one of the most aggressive ordinances against loitering near
automated teller machines. Meanwhile, Los Angeles and Orange
counties were among the first to ban camping in urban parks. And
Beaufort, S.C., and Madison, Wis., passed noise ordinances that
create a ``reasonable person standard'' rather than a single
decibel-level benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Berkeley's city council banned people from lying,
but not sitting, on sidewalks and passed a rule against more than
two stationary dogs within 10 feet of each other to help disperse
dogs and drifters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Many people familiar with street crime and other problems
insist that invoking new laws should be the last resort, not the
first. Marc Weinstein, owner of Amoeba Music on both Telegraph
Avenue and Haight Street in San Francisco, acknowledges that
``oppressing people who already are oppressed'' is not politically
palatable in liberal communities like Berkeley. But with
increasingly angry street people, it has become tougher for
merchants to negotiate their way out of problems as they have in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Nona Smith, director of the Lakeshore BID in
Oakland, says it is important to talk with people who may hang
around your store. She also recommends public education campaigns
to discourage giving directly to panhandlers and contributing
instead to homeless shelters and other programs that support them.
</P>
<P>
   Portland's successful BID, which has an annual budget of $3
million, has taken just such an approach with its ``Real Change NOT
Spare Change'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Some tactics to regain control of sidewalks may be effective but
not worth the backlash. For example, some merchants in Portland's
Old Town put up drip irrigation pipes on the edge of their roofs
about 15 years ago to discourage vagrants from leaning against
their buildings. The watering worked but was abandoned due to a
flood of negative publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Teir notes that merchants in some Atlantic seaboard communities
such as Charleston and Virginia Beach piped in ``easy-listening
classics'' to break up disruptive youth packs. Other merchants have
recommended Mahler or Barry Manilow. Such music may be ``an
effective crowd-abatement device,'' said one BID official. But it
is risky. ``Your outside speakers may get trashed,'' he warned.
``And you might also drive away potential customers who don't like
the music either.''
</P>
<P>
   One favored way to keep sidewalks clean and safe seems to be
eternal vigilence. ``The best solution is zero tolerance,'' said
Greg Keiser, owner of Graffiti Control Services, which has three
offices in the Bay Area. But that tactic doesn't guarantee cleaned
buildings stay clean. Even after 10 years, the Association for
Portland Progress removes about 4,000 graffiti tags each month over
a 220-block area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
