<HEADER>
A1646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-2NDTAKE-NYT     12-15 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: cruise missiles. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The timing of any strikes could be complicated by Ramadan, the
Islamic holy month, which begins this weekend. Officials have in
the past speculated that the United States would be unlikely to
have a confrontation with Iraq during the holiday, for fearing of
stoking anti-American sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   The United States would also be unlikely to launch a strike
until the United Nations has had time to remove the remaining arms
inspectors from Iraq. That could take a day or so, leaving a
rapidly narrowing window of opportunity this week if Clinton
decides on an immediate response.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in the midst of Washington's roiling debate over
impeachment, the latest confrontation will inevitably raise
accusations that Clinton may use Saddam as a diversion.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday, Rep. Tom DeLay, the
majority whip leading the House's impeachment effort, responded
bluntly when asked about the prospect of a strike on Iraq, accusing
the president of manipulating foreign policy to divert attention
from his personal and political crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, about the time he was supposed to give the
deposition in January, he sent the troops and rattled his sabers at
Saddam Hussein?'' DeLay said. ``Nothing happened. Remember in
November _ I mean in June, he went to China after moving that trip
from November to June, when he thought he was going to be in trial
with Paula Jones? And then again in August, he starts rattling his
saber again and backs off. That's what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in August, Clinton did order cruise missile strikes
against paramilitary camps in Afghanistan and a pharmaceutical
factory in the Sudan _ on the day Monica Lewinsky appeared for a
second time before the federal grand jury investigating Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Clinton angrily dismiss the notion, pointing out that
the periodic confrontations with Iraq have been driven by Saddam's
defiance.
</P>
</TEXT>
