<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-CHILDREN-ART-     12-15 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CHILDREN-ART-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REMARK ON CHILDREN CAUSES FLAP IN ISRAEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
(With MIDEAST-CLINTON, MIDEAST-CLINTON-MOOD, MIDEAST-ARABS) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ It was a classic Bill Clinton rhetorical parallel,
and to American ears perhaps an apt, even poetic, one.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on Monday in Gaza City to a meeting of Palestinian
leaders, Clinton compared the children of Israelis slain by
Palestinians to the children of Palestinian prisoners in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to find a way for both sets of children to get their
lives back and to go forward,'' he said, in an exhortation that
like much of his speech was improvised, his aides say.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had met them in reverse order I would not have known
which ones were Israeli and which Palestinian,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the parallel _ a result of Clinton's reaction to two
meetings with children, here and in Gaza City _ resounded like a
thunderclap in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon strongly protested what they thought smacked
of moral equivalence between murderers and their victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult comparison that caused deep shock in
Israel,'' Sharon told reporters after a meeting Tuesday morning of
Clinton, Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu said, ``Some of those murderers murdered children.''
</P>
<P>
   Protesters rallied outside Clinton's hotel here Tuesday, the
last day of his three-day trip intended to restart the peace
effort. Israeli radio filled with chatter about Clinton's remark,
with many commentators finding naivete in his symmetry.
</P>
<P>
   The commentary reflected the widely held Israeli view that
outsiders simply do not understand what it was like to live in a
country burdened by the daily threat of suicide bombings and other
attacks aimed at civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ``equation of children whose parents are in Israeli
prisons and children who lost their parents in acts of terror is
unjust,'' one commentator, Nahum Barnea, whose son died in a bus
bombing three years ago, wrote in Tuesday's issue of the daily
Yediot Ahronot. ``Clinton is too intelligent not to know that not
all tears are equal.''
</P>
<P>
   The uproar, which sounded a sour note for a trip that Clinton on
Tuesday called successful, showed how his careful sensitivity to
others' pain and his facility with words can occasionally land him
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have repeatedly praised the president for
understanding their fears while doggedly driving the parties
forward. But this time, as he tried to thread the needle of Middle
Eastern sensitivities on the highly charged issue of Palestinian
prisoners, he may have slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement negotiated in October at the Wye River
Plantation, the Israelis agreed to release some Palestinian
prisoners. But Netanyahu says, and the Americans agree, that he
never said he would release prisoners who have blood on their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, disappointment over the Israeli releases of car
thieves and other criminals rather than the men Palestinians regard
as heroes has led to violence by Palestinian protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers said a powerful, emotional appeal by the
president was being misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Berger, the national security adviser, said Sharon raised
the comment with Clinton Tuesday morning ``in a very friendly
way.'' The president, Berger said, noted that he had denounced
terrorism in his speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point he was making is that continued conflict between the
parties produces pain and hardship in which many of the victims are
children,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said the president was
trying to point out that ``there were tears by both groups of
children,'' but that ``in no way did he draw any parallel about the
cause of the pain.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same speech on Monday evening, Clinton said, ``No matter
how sharp a grievance or how deep a hurt, there is not
justification for killing innocents.''
</P>
<P>
   From long days negotiating with the American president,
Clinton's hosts have clearly learned what moves him. At an official
dinner here on Sunday night, Netanyahu introduced the president to
the family of Assam Assam, an Israeli being held by Egypt, which
accuses him of being a spy. He also introduced him to children
whose parents had been killed by Palestinians, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a banquet in Gaza City on Tuesday, Arafat surprised the
president and his aides with an unscheduled meeting: He introduced
him to some young girls whose fathers, he said, were prisoners in
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need my father to come home,'' wept one girl, according to
an interpretation for the president by a Palestinian official with
one arm over her shoulders. ``You have a daughter and you know the
feeling.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She said she had not seen her father in 10 years, and as she
cried into a handkerchief, Clinton clasped her right hand in both
of his and stared down at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we have peace without the release of all our
prisoners?'' she asked. ``How can you expect me as a girl to live
without my father?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton thanked the girl for coming to see him. ``Your father
would be very proud of you,'' he said as Arafat stood nearby with
his arms around two other sobbing girls. ``You did a wonderful job
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that two of the Palestinian girls
who met with the president had fathers who were serving life
sentences, one for killing an Israeli and one for killing a
Palestinian collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was not on Clinton's schedule, and some of his aides
said the president had been ambushed. American reporters were not
admitted, but the exchange was covered by Palestinian television.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Clinton addressed the Palestinian leaders after they held
a show of hands ratifying the removal from their charter of clauses
that called for the destruction of Israel. He described the two
groups of children he had met. ``Those children brought tears to my
eyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must acknowledge that neither side has a monopoly on pain
or virtue,'' he said. The audience applauded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
