<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1652 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINN-RED-CROSS-NYT &LR;      12-15 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINN-RED-CROSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED CROSS CRITICIZED FOR SITTING ON FLOOD RELIEF DONATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., N.D.)  (rl) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Minnesota attorney general has accused the
American Red Cross of mishandling disaster relief assistance in the
floods that ravaged the Red River Valley in Minnesota and North
Dakota in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a report issued Tuesday, Attorney General Hubert Humphrey III
criticized the Red Cross for not disbursing all of the donations it
collected for flood victims, even though, the report said, there
continue to be people who need help recovering from flood damage _
everything from corroded basements and foundations to medical
problems caused by flood-induced mold and mildew.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report shows how the Red Cross, by withholding millions
of dollars in donations, has failed in its responsibility to
donors, to survivors and to the public at large,'' Humphrey said in
a statement. ``When people gave the Red Cross their hard-earned
money, they expected it would promptly get to those whose lives
were devastated by the floods _ not sit in a bank account for a
year and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Blaul, a spokesman for the Red Cross in Washington, said
the agency did nothing wrong in the way it handled the relief
effort and distributed the donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response in this disaster has been quick and compassionate
and professional across the board,'' Blaul said. He said the
attorney general's office betrayed ``just a basic lack of
understanding of how the American Red Cross provides disaster
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the report is the $16 million in donations that
the Red Cross collected specifically for victims of the Red River
Valley floods in April 1997, which prompted the country's largest
flood-related evacuation and damaged much of Grand Forks, N.D.
</P>
<P>
   After months of inquiries from the attorney general's office,
the report said, the Red Cross acknowledged in June 1998 that it
still held $4.3 million of that money. The report said that after
the attorney general's office pressed the agency and said there
were still people who needed help, the Red Cross announced a plan
to distribute the remaining money.
</P>
<P>
   But Humphrey's office said the Red Cross was slow to carry out
the plan and that about three months later, in late August and
early September, he held public hearings so that flood victims and
local flood relief agencies could make their demands to the Red
Cross directly. At those hearings, Red Cross officials said they
had so far made specific commitments to give victims about $100,000
of the $4.3 million, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Blaul said the Red Cross had been following a timetable proven
to work in disasters and would have announced its distribution plan
in June without the pressure from the attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Between the June announcement and today, Blaul said, the Red
Cross has distributed $750,000 of the $4.3 million to 435 flood
victims. It has rejected the claims of 370 other people and is
considering the requests of 305 additional cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saying the American Red Cross has withdrawn before the job was
completed _ that is completely untrue,'' Blaul said.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey's report does not criticize the Red Cross response in
the immediate aftermath of the Red River Valley floods, when
thousands of people were given emergency shelter and assistance.
</P>
<P>
   At the public hearings, people complained about long-range
problems _ damaged basements, loss of income from jobs and mounting
debt to creditors for home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Roberta Cordano, an assistant attorney general, said Tuesday
that the Red Cross did not effectively publicize that it was still
taking applications and that the application process for people
suffering long-term flood damage was more burdensome than the
process followed by other relief agencies, in part because the Red
Cross often requires victims to exhaust opportunities for federal
and state assistance before it will grant aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we've got elderly people coming out of the woodwork who a
year ago thought they could handle this on their own,'' Ms. Cordano
said. ``Now they've got homes rotting with mold and mildew and they
can't qualify for Red Cross assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also said the Red Cross, asserting that its charter
made it answerable only to Congress and the federal government,
refused to give the attorney general's staff much of the
information they sought. Humphrey wants Congress to make the Red
Cross accountable to state governments, as other charities are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
