<HEADER>
A1660 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-CHU-ART-$ADV20-     12-15 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CHU-ART-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PLACE OF PEOPLE BURIED ALIVE, WOODEN EFFIGIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the fifth century B.C., Confucius questioned the
practice of burying people alive alongside the dead in funerary
rituals, calling it a waste of human life. But it was not until 100
years later that the Chu people of Southern China abandoned human
sacrifice, replacing the living in such rituals with carved and
lacquered wooden figures.
</P>
<P>
   Chu artists produced haunting effigies of concubines, slaves,
deer and tigers, all common in the retinues of Chinese rulers
during the late Warring States period (fourth century to third
century B.C.) and the Han Dynasty (206 B.C. to 220 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
   They created images as stark and simple as the Cycladic figures
of ancient Greece and the modernist sculpture of Brancusi and
Nadelman. They lacquered the surfaces in brilliant colors or, in
some cases, dressed the human figures in silk robes.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces ranged in height from one foot to four feet and
predated by a century the spectacular life-size terra cotta
warriors that were excavated in 1974 at Xian. An army of these
figures was removed from the tomb of China's first emperor, Qin Shi
Huang, and has since been exhibited in museums throughout the
world.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chu figures _ as well as horses and mythological
creatures produced at the time elsewhere in China _ are less well
known than the terra cotta pieces, even though museums and
galleries have exhibited examples for a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, the Metropolitan Museum of Art was given three such
figures _ two standing attendants and a kneeling one _ by Mathias
Komor a New York dealer in ancient art. Two years later, the
British Museum acquired an animal figure with a long tongue and
antlers that served as a guardian.
</P>
<P>
   A large number of Chu works have been excavated over the past 20
years, and recently such works have become more visible in the
market. The most prominent dealer in this material in the West is
Jacques Barrere, who has sold about 60 of the figures at his Left
Bank gallery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Barrere exhibited five Chu figures at the first Asian
Art Fair in New York, where he sold a two-foot-tall Han guardian
figure of a deer to a collector of modern art for about $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Five months later, he brought 17 figures to the Biennale
Internationale des Antiquaires in Paris. He sold them to collectors
from many parts of the world as well as to Noriyoshi Horiuchi, a
Tokyo dealer in ancient art. Horiuchi, an adviser to the Miho
Museum near Kyoto, said recently that he was planning an exhibition
of Chu works in Asia. This fall, Barrere exhibited 18 other figures
at his gallery; most of them were bought.
</P>
<P>
   Now because of the soaring prices for Asian art and the
increased cost of conserving them, Barrere would not give the
prices he asks for those he stocks. These include figures of
guardians, attendants, dancers, prancing horses, a unicorn and a
deer with spectacular antlers, which are centuries older than the
carving itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Chu figures are now both the subject of scholarly study and
are being actively collected by museums. Last year, the Brooklyn
Museum acquired an androgynous figure, and the Guimet Museum here
added a phoenix, a deer and two attendants to its holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Museum of Art will present ``Ringing Thunder: Chu
Treasures from Ancient China,'' an exhibition of ritual bronzes,
jades, gold, glass and lacquer wares, from June 12 to Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1990, when Barrere and his wife, Marie, first saw the
figures in Asia, they were stunned by both their simplicity and
rarity. But their beauty was diminished by water damage; most had
been found in tombs that had been flooded.
</P>
<P>
   Barrere said the figures represented the greatest risk he had
ever taken since he had become an art dealer in 1966 because there
was no guarantee they could be restored.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Barrere said the pieces looked ``shrunken, like bad
Giacomettis.'' Rescuing them, she said, proved to be a daunting
challenge: ``We had one disaster with a wet piece. We removed it
from the plastic film in which it was kept in a box filled with
water. Within a day it began to split and seven days later it had
crumbled into bits and pieces of shrunken wood.''
</P>
<P>
   The Barreres investigated several art conservation laboratories
and finally selected the new commercial division of the Nucleart
Regional Conservation Studio in Grenoble, France, formerly a
government research laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   To restore the figures, they are dried and injected with
polyethylene glycol, a polymer plastic. In a process that takes
eight months to two years, the vivid lacquer colors are muted and
the loose silk garments on some figures wrinkle and skrink, looking
like a skin of crushed taffeta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The figures had to be saved,'' Barrere said. ``They were going
to be lost forever, and we couldn't let that happen without making
an effort. Never mind who owns them now. They belong to something
eternal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
