<HEADLINE>
`SPRINGER': GLIDING FROM MAYOR TO RINGMASTER
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes at end. Time, channel are for New York
area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I cannot promise that a biography of Jerry Springer is worth an
hour of anyone's time, but there is within ``Jerry Springer: In the
Center Ring'' the lesson that the talents that bring success in
politics may smoothly be turned to making a television superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's hourlong edition of ``Biography'' on A&AMP;E goes
over the high and low spots of the activities of this son of
Holocaust survivors: anti-Vietnam War and civil rights causes in
the 1960s; local political office in Cincinnati, leading to a term
as mayor; an apparent taste for prostitutes that brought career and
marriage difficulties (lesson is, don't pay by check); and
ascendence as a talk-cum-commotion-show prodigy, with 25 million
fans around the world.
</P>
<P>
   There may seem to be a dissonance between the ideals of the
onetime Stevenson Democrat (``Jerry was driven by the right
things,'' says a colleague) and the man who presides over ``My
Wife's Sleeping With My Aunt,'' but when has that ever stopped a
smash hit?
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning, when the physical encounters for which his
program became famous may have been more or less impromptu, our
host can be seen saying, ``I don't want to be part of anything that
brings violence into the home.'' But once the revelation dawned
that it was the violence that drew audiences, he evidently
rethought his position. In show business as in politics,
flexibility makes life easier.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Springer is not one of the talk show hosts who
make grand claims for the edifying qualities of their offerings. He
grants that they are silly and advises critics, ``If you don't like
the show, don't watch it.'' And on screen, he manages to keep his
distance from the less restrained participants without discouraging
them from acting out.
</P>
<P>
   But how does his current give-the-folks-what-they-want principle
accord with the principles that moved him to do battle for minority
rights? Well, it doesn't. What Springer evidently learned is that
talent has diverse uses: The amiably audacious style that worked
for the local campaigner has worked in a big way for the television
performer. The values involved are incidental or irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   One may lament that high-mindedness has little to do with
success on television, but that seems a touch pointless at this
stage. More disheartening than the fact that Jerry Springer has
become a multimillionaire by giving his abilities to what he agrees
is silly stuff or worse is the news that his program is aimed at
college students. Yes, viewers, the fans who whoop up shows like
``Confronting One-Night Stands!'' are America's brightest and best.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIOGRAPHY: Jerry Springer: In the Center Ring'
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Wednesday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   Tom Seligson, executive producer; Randy Martin, producer; Brett
Alexander, senior producer. For A&AMP;E: Michael Cascio, executive
producer; Maryellen Cox, supervising producer. Produced by CBS News
Productions for A&AMP;E. Paula Zahn, narrator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
