<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: CLOCK TICKING ON FREQUENT-FLIER MILES
</HEADLINE>
 (duplication notice : also sent with `t' code) 
(bl) 
By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Certain miles accumulated in United Airlines and American
Airlines frequent-flier programs are scheduled to expire Dec. 31,
but there is still time to use or preserve them, while miles
originally scheduled to expire in Delta Air Lines' and Northwest
Airlines' programs have been extended a year. As always, miles in
the Continental Airlines and U S Airways programs do not expire at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The miles that will soon expire in the United and American
programs are those that were earned in 1995. But members of either
program who lack enough miles for a free flight may be able to
qualify by transferring miles from their Diners Club Club Rewards
or American Express Membership Rewards programs.
</P>
<P>
   Or they can use their accumulated miles for a rental car or free
hotel stays or upgrades. Or they can donate their miles to a
charity sponsored by the airline. Trans World Airlines' frequent
fliers, for example, have donated more than 5 million miles to the
Salvation Army, which sent 75 volunteers on TWA flights to the
Caribbean to repair homes that were destroyed by Hurricane Georges,
and to provide food to hundreds of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Members with enough miles for a flight but not enough time can
redeem them for a specific flight in 1999 or for an award
certificate. Since a certificate is good for a year from date of
issue, it can be redeemed anytime next year for reservations on a
flight as much as a year in advance.
</P>
<P>
   TWA's miles expire after three years, unless a member makes at
least one round- trip flight every three years. Three-year-old
miles in Delta's frequent-flier program were scheduled to expire at
the end of this year, unless the member made at least one new
flight in the last three years, but the airline extended the
deadline until the end of 1999. Because of the recent pilots'
strike against Northwest Airlines, that carrier is also giving a
year's grace for miles that were scheduled to expire at the end of
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines, which often marches to a different drummer,
does so with its frequent-flier program: A free ticket on Southwest
requires 8 round trips or 16 one-way flights within a 12-month
period, and the ticket (which is transferable) is valid for one
year from the date of issue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Out of Commission
</P>
<P>
   After striking a reef Monday while leaving St. Maarten in the
French West Indies, Royal Caribbean's Monarch of the Seas has
canceled its scheduled voyage this Sunday and may cancel others,
pending assessment of the damage. Meanwhile, all 2,557 passengers
aboard were safely evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Caribbean said Tuesday that those passengers, as well as
those who were booked on next Sunday's cruise, would receive a full
refund plus a free cruise within a year on a similar itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise Ship Delays
</P>
<P>
   Disney Cruise Line's second ship, the Disney Wonder, will be
delivered next spring, but its maiden voyage is not scheduled until
Aug. 15. Because of the construction delay, not only will the ship
miss most of the traditional summer cruise season, but it has had
to cancel 44 sailings that were scheduled beginning next March. The
first Disney ship, the Disney Magic, had to cancel 40 cruises this
year when construction delays forced it to push back its inaugural
voyage twice _ from March to April, then to July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the size and number of new ships being built, delays
and cancellations are becoming more common, if not yet routine.
Carnival's Holland America had to cancel several sailings of its
Rotterdam VI last fall when the ship was delivered six weeks late,
while the 2,600-passenger Grand Princess, owned by the Peninsular
and Oriental Steam Navigation Company, had to delay its maiden
voyage 12 days this May.
</P>
<P>
   No Smoking. Seriously.
</P>
<P>
   A recent passenger aboard the Carnival Paradise, the industry's
first smoke-free cruise ship, was put off in Nassau, where he had
to pay his own way home. `'All passengers have been warned that
it's a ship for nonsmokers,'' said Jennifer De la Cruz, a Carnival
spokeswoman, ``and we're serious about keeping it that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
