<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TESTAVERDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE'S ABILITY TO AVOID SACKS HAS JETS ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These days, Vinny Testaverde is leading the life of luxury. He
stands in what has become one of the safest places in the National
Football League _ the New York Jets' pass pocket _ and fires away.
And when pass rushers actually do get close to him, he sidesteps
them with a mobility that is quite surprising for someone who is 6
feet 5 inches and 238 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Testaverde has now gone 15 quarters _ or nearly
four straight games _ without being sacked. No wonder the Jets
suddenly find themselves a victory away from their first division
title since 1969, a feat they can accomplish by beating the Buffalo
Bills on the road Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In his first 11 seasons, many of them with inferior teams,
Testaverde was sacked an average of once for every 14 passes. This
year, he is being sacked just once every 20 attempts. Contrast this
situation with the one a year ago when Neil O'Donnell, who would
rather hold than run, got dumped once every 10 passes as the
primary Jets quarterback. Just when the Jets' attack was getting
started, someone would come along and throw O'Donnell down, and it
would be third-and-20.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't happening with Testaverde, who rarely puts the Jets
in a tough situation. His ability to sense pass pressure and
sidestep it, combined with a Jets offense that has a crew of good
pass blockers and good-hands receivers, has allowed Testaverde to
star on third down, which is when opposing defenses normally load
up on the pass rush and tear after the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, Testaverde has become the most dangerous third-down
passer in the game. His quarterback rating, which factors in
various passing statistics, looks like a misprint: it is 128.3. By
contrast, the No. 2-rated passer in the league, the Green Bay
Packers' Brett Favre, is at 110.7. The Denver Broncos' John Elway
is at 96.1.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde is the only quarterback who hasn't thrown an
interception on third down. And only the Miami Dolphins' Dan Marino
has thrown as many touchdowns on third down _ 9 _ and he has thrown
56 more passes than Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for all this success is that Testaverde runs
better than people think. Indeed, in his career he has scored 12
rushing touchdowns _ including the phantom winning score against
the Seattle Seahawks two Sundays ago on the quarterback sneak that
actually ended up a foot short. Testaverde also had the option to
pass the ball on that play but chose to try to make the yardage
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, he has a mobile quarterback's rushing statistics: he
came into the season with 297 carries and a 4.7 yards-a-run
average, and he actually once scored on a 48-yard jaunt. This
season, he has produced an 18-yard run and in Sunday night's 21-16
victory over the Dolphins, he ran twice in a row in one offensive
sequence, including a 9-yard sprint on a third-and-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to run when I have to,'' he said Tuesday. ``But in our
offense, with the options we have, I can get rid of the ball
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2158EST &QL; 
