<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1675 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      12-15 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LOSING POTENTIAL SUPPORTERS IN IMPEACHMENT VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: optional ending included) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
and BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's chances of winning a House
impeachment vote dimmed Tuesday as key Republican moderates,
including several from the Democratic-friendly Northeast, announced
plans to vote against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Buffeted by a steady loss of potential supporters, Clinton,
flying home from the Middle East, was weighing advice to again
publicly apologize, but to include a full confession of any
wrongdoing in his effort to conceal his affair with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Speaker-elect Bob Livingston, a New Orleans
Republican, said Clinton should quit in order to end the crisis
engulfing his presidency. ``If the president wants to stop putting
the country through this, he has options available to him, one of
which is resignation,'' Livingston said in an interview with the
New Orleans Times-Picayune.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston's advice to the president makes it unanimous among
top House Republicans who are preparing for only the second
presidential impeachment vote in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrives in Washington early today on the eve of the
House impeachment showdown, he will find he has lost the support of
several of the two dozen Republican moderates he had hoped would
side with him against GOP conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Rep. Jack Quinn, a New York Republican who last
week said he would oppose impeachment and on Tuesday reversed
course. Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., an early impeachment opponent,
softened his position Monday and is to meet with Clinton on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   New York Reps. Michael Forbes, Sue Kelly and John McHugh all
held news conferences to announce their belief that Clinton
committed impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Also declaring her intent to support impeachment was Rep. Nancy
Johnson, a Connecticut Republican who has been supportive of
Clinton. ``The president does not have the right to commit perjury
when it is convenient or when he thinks the charges against him are
frivolous,'' Johnson said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Other moderate Republicans who said Tuesday they would support
impeachment are Reps. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., Ann Northrup, R-Ky.,
Clay Shaw, R-Fla., and Fred Upton, R-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic House Caucus Chairman Martin Frost of Texas said
White House and Democratic efforts to win over enough moderate
Republican votes to stave off impeachment have all but failed.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans ``have got the votes'' to impeach, Frost said.
``Republicans are cracking the whip and they're trying to get all
their moderates in line, and they`re going to get most of them.
They're leaning on them pretty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hold 228 of the 435 House seats; Democrats hold 206,
and four of them have announced plans to side with the GOP. The
lone House independent has said he will side with Clinton. So far,
three moderate Republicans have said they will oppose impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House welcomed proposals from one undecided Republican
moderate, Rep. Michael Castle of Delaware, and from former GOP
presidential nominee Bob Dole for rebuking Clinton but not removing
him from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even at this late date, there are compelling reasons to pursue
a different course with a better solution for our nation,'' said
Castle, who urged the House leadership to allow a vote on a tough
censure resolution that would require Clinton to pay at least $2
million toward the costs of the Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, a former U.S. senator who unsuccessfully challenged
Clinton's re-election in 1996, proposed that Congress end the
impeachment battle by passing a joint resolution of censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot imagine a better way for Republicans to start the new
year than by taking charge and producing just results at this
historic moment,'' Dole wrote in the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The Castle and Dole proposals were characterized as ``thoughtful
and serious'' by White House spokesman Jim Kennedy. ``While we
haven't endorsed any specific plan, we welcome efforts to find a
bipartisan solution that would allow us to put this behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some White House advisers are urging Clinton to make a bold move
to avert impeachment. Aides confirmed that strategy discussions
include the logistically difficult and politically hazardous
appearance before the full House to deliver a plea for censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president can make his case in person before the full
House better than anyone,'' former White House special counsel
Lanny Davis told reporters. ``He should expose himself to that
process, answer questions and be prepared to acknowledge the
reality of what he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost was pessimistic about the prospects of turning enough
Republican votes. ``The Republicans are pushing their people so
hard that I'm not sure there's anything the president could do that
would satisfy them,'' he said. ``They've decided for political
reasons that they want to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Livingston late Tuesday reaffirmed his opposition to allowing
House members to vote on anything other than an impeachment
resolution, which seeks to terminate Clinton's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   A House vote for impeachment Thursday would formally charge
Clinton with ``high crimes and misdemeanors,'' the standard set by
the Constitution for removing a president once two-thirds, or 67
members, of the Senate vote for conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Only one other president, Andrew Johnson, has been impeached by
the House. He went on trial in the Senate in March 1868, and after
74 days of testimony and arguments, which Johnson never attended,
he was acquitted by one vote.
</P>
<P>
   The four articles of impeachment, approved on a party-line vote
last week by the House Judiciary Committee, accuse Clinton of
perjury in the Paula Jones sexual harassment lawsuit, perjury
before a federal grand jury, obstructing justice and abuse of
power. All four stem from the president's efforts to conceal his
White House affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A CBS/New York Times poll released Tuesday evening found that 58
percent of adult Americans believe the president should not resign
if he faces a Senate trial. The survey contradicts an ABC
News/Washington Post poll, which on Monday reported that 58 percent
of adult Americans say Clinton should quit if the House votes to
send his case to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, feminist leaders Betty Friedan and Eleanor Smeal held
a news conference to express outrage at the impeachment drive.
Friedan, a women's movement pioneer, blamed the president's
troubles on ``a bunch of dirty old white men,'' trying to overturn
an election result.
</P>
<P>
   Friedan and Smeal emerged from a hastily scheduled meeting with
Livingston to report that he rebuffed their plea for censure rather
than impeachment. Livingston ``compared Clinton to (Richard) Nixon
and said Clinton was worse,'' said Smeal, president of the Feminist
Majority Foundation. ``After this, the impression you have is
there's no stopping and there's no pausing'' on the way to
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
