Other firings were in the Times' finance, human resources and
administrative services divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The total of 500 cuts will cover 130 full-time and 370 part-time
positions. They amount to about 8 percent of the paper's payroll.
</P>
<P>
   No positions were eliminated in the news department during this
round of cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unfortunate time because we are disrupting people
during the holidays and we are disrupting families during the
holidays and I would prefer it not be at this time,'' Downing said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper's new strategy calls for creating two new regions for
business purposes: Los Angeles and the Inland Empire/San Gabriel
Valley region. The Times has Orange County and San Fernando
Valley/Ventura County regions.
</P>
<P>
   Downing said the paper's regular metro edition will continue to
be included in the new regions' editions while management decides
whether to offer readers a regionalized news product similar to
those produced for the Valley and Ventura, and Orange counties.
</P>
<P>
   Full-time employees being fired will receive 18 weeks to two
years of pay, depending on their length of service, while part-time
workers will get from 12 to 18 weeks of pay.
</P>
<P>
   Times Mirror will take a charge of up to $225 million this year
to pay for the restructuring. Its stock closed Tuesday at $55.25,
up 6.25 cents. The cuts were announced after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   The firings come a week after the company announced it was
giving $1 million to Columbia University's Graduate School of
Journalism to fund a visiting professorship to study diversity in
media issues.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper spokesman Mike Lang said the paper also is planning to
introduce up to 12 ``Our Times'' community news editions next year
throughout Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper industry analyst John Morton said large newspapers
like the Times ``are trying to both broaden and deepen their
franchise and one way to do that is create regional or zoned
editions and attempt to be more than just the big metro paper.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Times Mirror has shed assets to focus on its
newspapers, which include the Baltimore Sun and Newsday on Long
Island, N.Y. But high costs and a soft advertising market,
particularly for classified ads, have led to reduced expectations
for the company and a 10 percent decline in the company's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Downing said it is ``critical'' to cut costs wherever possible
to improve the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
