<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PATRIOTS SEEK GREENER PASTURES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having siphoned off all the loose funds in one small town, that
charming cinematic scamp known as the Music Man was asked where he
was moving next.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever the people are as green as the money,'' he announced.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of Music Men in sports, which is why peripatetic
teams leave their trail of tears from time zone to time zone,
seeking their pie in the sky box.
</P>
<P>
   In the spirit of Prof. Harold Hill, we now have Robert Kraft
trying to slip his New England Patriots across the Massachusetts
border. Tuesday night the Connecticut legislature was debating
whether to give the Patriots an extravagant gift to put Hartford on
the big-time map.
</P>
<P>
   The zeal of Gov. John Rowland would be hilarious if it did not
have such crushing implications for the citizens, who would build a
stadium at the edge of downtown for $375 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is the normal sports boondoggle. What made Rowland's deal
so generous is that taxpayers would subsidize up to $13 million a
year for unsold luxury boxes and club seats _ a bargain, whittled
down from $17.5 million the governor had been willing to give.
</P>
<P>
   Sports franchises and major events are usually a good deal for
everybody but the locals who pay the bills. The 68,000-seat stadium
would be used mainly for two exhibitions and eight regular-season
games of the Patriots and five games of the University of
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League points out that the Patriots had
been willing to stay in Massachusetts in a privately financed
stadium, but House Speaker Thomas Finneran would not approve a $72
million package in land and improvements around Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, it also looks as if the league would lose status
in the transition from Boston, the 20th largest city in the
country, to Hartford, which has lost 18.1 percent of its population
since 1990, and has fallen to 184th in population.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have lived off the considerable aura of Boston
since their early days in the 1960s, when they scuttled around like
some rogue MTA train, from Harvard to Fenway Park to Boston
University to Boston College. In reality, there is precious little
urbane about the Patriots, who have been playing, since 1971, in a
rickety stadium in Foxboro, Mass., closer to Providence, R.I., than
to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clubs are not necessarily going to think of this as a move
from Boston to Hartford, but rather a move from Massachusetts to
Connecticut,'' said Joe Browne, the senior vice president of
communications and government affairs for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all visiting teams fly into Providence before a game,
which essentially means that for 27 years no professional football
players have been roaming around downtown Boston, which is just as
good.
</P>
<P>
   As franchise shifts go, this is no biggie. The Rams left
populous Orange County in California for St. Louis, the
49th-largest city; the Raiders fled Los Angeles, the nation's
second-most populous city, to return to Oakland, the 44th-largest;
and the Oilers left Houston, the fourth-largest city, and moved to
Nashville, the 25th-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   One could even make the point that the most-populous city in the
country does not have a team, since the Giants and Jets both play
in another state to the west, but the double triumphs last Sunday
were surely felt in the city itself.
</P>
<P>
   The league smarts at not having teams in L.A. and Houston, and
will surely fill one gap with an expansion team in the next few
years. However, market size is not a gigantic problem in the NFL
since the stadiums are essentially television studios, beaming
games for free.
</P>
<P>
   The league can tolerate some small markets, which is why Green
Bay, the 207th market at 104,500 residents, is a jewel of a
franchise, locally owned, able to afford stars and win Super Bowl
XXXI. For every Packer home game, fans drive from all over
Wisconsin, and there is every reason to assume that most current
Patriot fans will do the same in New England _ and if they don't,
there are always new fans. Besides, the stadium in Foxboro is a
dump, with the worst access roads in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The league can tolerate small markets because of the current
television contract for $18 billion over eight years. Under the
most intelligent revenue-sharing policy in professional sports,
each of 30 teams makes an identical $58 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts can console itself that losing 10 home football
games a year is nothing like losing a baseball team, with its 81
home games. The Bay State can celebrate its stand against giveaways
Wednesday _ the 225th anniversary of the Boston Tea Party. Wonder
what the real patriots in Boston Harbor would have thought about
the proposed giveaway one colony away.?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
