<SLUG> BC-BBO-MEETINGS-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL AGENTS' NEGOTIATING TACTICS CRITICIZED
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ An executive involved in record-setting
contract talks for Kevin Brown said Tuesday that serious problems
exist in the way teams and agents negotiate, and that corrective
action is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Brown signed a seven-year, $105 million contract with the Los
Angeles Dodgers at the beginning of the winter meetings, which
ended blandly here Tuesday with several minor free-agent signings.
Brown turned down offers from the San Diego Padres, for whom he
played this past season, and others.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Brown's agreement, Larry Lucchino, the San
Diego president, contacted high-ranking members of other
organizations to review the negotiations. He is convinced that the
teams reacted to what he called misinformation from Brown's agent,
Scott Boras.
</P>
<P>
   The best evidence of this, Lucchino said, is in the offers teams
say that they made to Brown. Lucchino said that the Padres offered
Brown a six-year, $60 million deal _ $8 million in 1999, $9 million
in 2000, $10 million in 2001, $11 million in 2002, $12 million in
2003 and $10 million in 2004. The Baltimore Orioles offered Brown a
five-year, $55 million contract, according to two high-ranking
members of that organization who spoke on the condition of
anonymity. The St. Louis Cardinals never made Brown a formal offer,
according to the general manager, Walt Jocketty.
</P>
<P>
   Lucchino said that the Colorado Rockies offered Brown a six-year
deal with the final year of the contract partly guaranteed; Jerry
McMorris, the Rockies' owner, would not confirm Lucchino's
contention or divulge the exact nature of his offer. Reportedly,
Colorado's offer would not have surpassed $81 million if the sixth
year was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   If all the figures are accurate, then the Dodgers' final offer
surpassed that made by any other team. Lucchino contends this is
partly because they were led to believe the offers from other teams
were higher than they actually were. Lucchino suggested that the
Dodgers offered Brown one more year and perhaps $35 million to $40
million more than any other team ``and that certainly puts an
interesting perspective on the negotiations, certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucchino would not comment directly on how Boras negotiated.
Boras could not immediately be reached for comment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about the objective facts about the
negotiations,'' Lucchino said, ``and whether there are flaws in
structure of the process that allows for blindman's bluff. There is
a growing concern about the process that allows for this type of
misinformation circulating.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Peter Angelos, the Orioles' owner: ``This is a many-faceted
problem that needs to be addressed in a number of specific ways.''
</P>
<P>
   McMorris added: ``I don't see anything but good in looking for
ways to improve the system. I know where Larry's coming from, and I
share most of his concern. But it's over and done with and the
player has gone to the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams are not permitted to collude and share directly what
offers they are making. But Lucchino believes teams should somehow
be able to verify that offers have been made. One method being
discussed, Lucchino said, would be to reveal all offers through the
news media. Another would to be to require that all offers be made
in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Lucchino is intrigued by an another owner's proposal that all
offers would have to go through a third party, a verifier. ``If an
agent says that there is an offer from another team, you could then
go to the verifier and determine if there was indeed such an
offer,'' Lucchino said.
</P>
<P>
   Boras also represented Bernie Williams, the Yankees' center
fielder, in his free-agent negotiations this off season. During
talks last month, Boras repeatedly told the Yankees that he had
multiple offers of seven and eight years for Williams, and some
within the Yankees' organization did not believe the agent. George
Steinbrenner, the Yankees' owner, challenged Boras to reveal his
offers, but Boras would not. ``I don't think he has anything,''
Steinbrenner said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yankees signed Williams to a seven-year, $87.5 million
contract, baseball officials say, the Yankees were told by the
Player Relations Committee that the Arizona Diamondbacks offered
Williams an eight-year, $100 million contract _ confirmation of
Boras' contention. Boston also offered a seven-year deal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Brown's signing was the highlight of the generally uneventful
winter meetings. The Blue Jays had hoped to trade Roger Clemens
here, but Toronto officials left here Tuesday afternoon not really
sure in what direction those negotiations would turn. The Texas
Rangers seem willing to renegotiate Clemens' contract but unable to
produce the players wanted by the Blue Jays; Houston, Cleveland and
the Yankees are balking at the idea of trading players and then
giving Clemens a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland General Manager John Hart said Tuesday that the
chances of his team landing Clemens were remote, but the Indians
may have forwarded the most intriguing offer _ outfielder Manny
Ramirez. Cleveland reportedly offered Ramirez for Clemens, one for
one, but Toronto asked for at least three additional players.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable trade of the meetings was St. Louis'
acquisition of shortstop Edgar Renteria; in return, the Cardinals
sent pitcher Braden Looper, shortstop Pablo Ozuna and the
left-handed reliever Armando Almanza to the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
