<HEADLINE>
COLTEC SHARES RISE AS CRANE TRIES TO BLOCK GOODRICH DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By SHARON R. KING   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of Coltec Industries rose $2 on Tuesday, or 12
percent, as Crane Co. pursued its attempt to block a planned $1.3
billion merger between Coltec and B.F. Goodrich.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich said it had no plans to drop its offer to buy Coltec, a
maker of aerospace components and industrial products in Charlotte,
N.C. But several Coltec shareholders expressed interest in hearing
Crane's offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to pursue the completion of the merger,'' said Rob
Jewell, a Goodrich spokesman. ``B.F. Goodrich has a binding
agreement with Coltec Industries to merge.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Crane filed a surprise lawsuit against Coltec and
Goodrich, contending that Coltec, by accepting the Goodrich offer,
had broken a 1995 promise to notify Crane of any offers to buy the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which was filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
seeks to allow Crane to present its offer, which had never been
publicly disclosed, to Coltec's board. It also asks the court to
prohibit the companies from enacting anti-takeover provisions in
their agreement that make it prohibitively expensive for another
company to make an offer for Coltec.
</P>
<P>
   No hearings have yet been scheduled in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Goodrich agreed to acquire Coltec, offering 0.56
share of Goodrich common stock for each Coltec share. The deal also
calls for Goodrich, which is based in Richfield, Ohio, to assume
$610 million in debt. The transaction would be accounted for as a
pooling of interests and would be tax-free to Coltec shareholders.
As of Tuesday, the Goodrich offer was worth about $1.3 billion,
excluding debt.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich, which left the tire business in the 1980s,
manufactures aircraft-landing gear systems and other aerospace
components.
</P>
<P>
   In letters sent to Coltec chief executive John Guffey, Crane had
offered 0.80 share for each outstanding Coltec share. Coltec has
about 70 million shares outstanding, a company official said.
Crane's offer was worth about $1.6 billion Tuesday, excluding the
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Coltec's stock traded as high as $19.4375 a share Tuesday before
closing at $18.6875. Crane shares fell 25 cents, to $27.75, while
those of Goodrich rose 56.25 cents, to $33.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Gabelli, the chief investment officer of Gabelli Asset
Management, which owns about 2.6 million shares of Coltec and 1.4
million shares of Crane, said that Coltec shareholders should be
presented with Crane's offer.
</P>
<P>
   Gabelli also said he was waiting for Coltec to respond to the
suit to determine whether the company had accepted an inferior
Goodrich bid while knowing about the Crane offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
