<SLUG> BC-MAINE-FOREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURE CONSERVANCY BUYS MAINE FOREST TRACT  
(JT) 
 &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an effort to preserve a chunk of Maine wilderness,
an international conservation group announced Tuesday that it was
buying 185,000 acres of forest from a paper company.
</P>
<P>
   The $35.1 million purchase by the Nature Conservancy, the
largest of its kind ever in Maine, comprises two tracts in the
remote northwest corner of the state on the Canadian border. It
includes about 40 miles of the renowned Upper St. John River, an
ecological powerhouse that has one of the highest concentrations of
rare plants in Maine. International Paper Co. has owned most of the
land since the 1920s, using the timberland as a working forest, but
preserving the river area as part of a voluntary agreement with the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a river that you can put your canoe in and paddle 120
miles without seeing a single house or development,'' said Kent
Wommack, executive director of the the Nature Conservancy in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper St. John, the longest free-flowing river east of the
Mississippi, was threatened with inundation in the 1960s by the
proposed Dickey-Lincoln dam project. A bitter fight on the part of
conservation groups saved it.
</P>
<P>
   The Nature Conservancy plans to keep the lands open for fishing,
hunting, canoeing and other recreation. The woodlands may continue
to supply timber for Maine's paper mills.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a week after environmentalists cheered a
purchase of 300,000 acres of forest land in New York, Vermont and
New Hampshire from the Champion International paper company for $76
million.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Maine's forest land has changed hands, with about 15
percent of the state going up for sale this year. More land on the
market means more preservation opportunities for conservation
groups, Wommack said, but more openings for land developers .
</P>
<P>
   ``Once land is sold for development, it can never really be
recovered,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nature Conservancy already owns 10 million acres in North
America. Buying means less dependence on land owners to voluntarily
protect their environmentally important holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gentlemen's agreements are great, and we have many with many
landowners, but for a resource that is as nationally significant as
this, it really deserves to be permanently protected,'' Wommack
said.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Hutchinson, executive director for the Forest Society of
Maine, said the area is a home to deer, bears, osprey, great herons
and the Furbish lousewort, a wild snapdragon that grows nowhere
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Maine we've become very spoiled in thinking that these
wonderful things we find in the North Woods would be here
forever,'' Hutchinson said. ``I think they've guaranteed that these
attributes that we've taken for granted for so long will be in
place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
