<SLUG> BC-CHILES-DAYOFF-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Day off to honor Chiles
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE _ The closing of state offices for the funeral of
Lawton Chiles today has officials scrambling to reschedule events
and in some cases deciding reluctantly to stay open despite Gov.
Buddy MacKay's executive order.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's 206,485 employees will be given the day off,
at a cost of $21 million for their salaries, according to the state
Comptroller's office.
</P>
<P>
   No one in the governor's press office could remember the last
time state government was shut down for a day or mourning. The last
governor to die office was Dan McCarty in 1953. State government
has been closed as recently as this year, however, for weather
reasons including hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   The state court system will be closed, though individual judges
will have the discretion to make exceptions for matters previously
scheduled or for emergencies, Chief Supreme Court Justice Major
Harding ordered Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harding and the other six justices on the state Supreme Court
will not work so they can attend the funeral Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to honor Gov. Chiles,'' Harding said, ``and we will
do it in a way that does not cause needless legal problems for
Florida's people.''
</P>
<P>
   All court deadlines will be extended by a day, so Dec. 16 will
not count toward time limits imposed by rule and statute.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Florida Department of Law Enforcement's 1,500
employees will be given the day off, though an emergency crew
handling criminal-justice information and records will remain on
duty, a spokeswoman said. A number of FDLE officials will attending
or participating in the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Highway Patrol officers will be on the road, though office
workers in the department will be off, and an extra 30 to 35
officers will be assisting with the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Final examinations will go on as scheduled today at the
University of Florida and the law school at Florida State
University, the state's Board of Regents has decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``We mean no disrespect in keeping the exam schedule, but after
discussing the matter with UF and FSU administrators, it became
clear that final exams simply will have to continue at these two
institutions,'' said Acting State Chancellor James Mau in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students, parents and other family members make holiday travel
plans around the final exam schedule, which is set months in
advance,'' he continued. ``To change that schedule now has the
potential to cause undue problems for thousands of students,
including those who graduate this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
