<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0424 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TALISMAN-SUGAR-RULING     12-15 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALISMAN-SUGAR-RULING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last-gasp block of sale to appease growers
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in General News (a) and Financial (f) categories.)
 &HT;    By Larry Lipman and Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Less than 48 hours before the federal government
planned to buy a Glades sugar empire in a crucial step toward
restoring the Everglades, a judge temporarily blocked the sale
Tuesday at the behest of growers who say the deal could hurt the
environment and the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling that surprised state officials and environmental
activists, U.S. District Judge Thomas F. Hogan stayed Thursday
morning's scheduled $133.5 million sale of Talisman Sugar Corp.'s
50,960 acres to the Interior Department. Hogan scheduled further
hearings Jan. 22, saying he still knows too little about the sale
to decide which side is right.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan made no decision on an injunction the growers had sought,
and he left open the opportunity for either side to seek an
emergency hearing today. He also said the government and Talisman's
parent, Jacksonville-based St. Joe Co., can put the money and title
in escrow. That would allow a neutral party _ such as a bank or a
title company _ to hold them until he makes a ruling.
</P>
<P>
   That means moneycan change hands at Thursday's scheduled closing
in suburban West Palm Beach, involving St. Joe, the Interior
Department and the government's middleman, The Nature Conservancy.
But the sides can't finish the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling ``doesn't cause harm to either side,'' said Interior
Department negotiator
</P>
<P>
   Curtis ``Buff'' Bohlen. ``All sides are committed to the sale.
We just have to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ruling surprised environmentalists, along with the South
Florida water managers who hope to end up owning much of the
Talisman land.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a death knell,'' said Thom Rumberger, attorney for
the Everglades Foundation. ``It's simply that the court is going
slower.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Miedema, spokeswoman for the Sugar Cane Growers
Cooperative of Florida, called on the government to ``follow its
own rules.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to take into account the economic and human and
environmental consequences'' of the sale, said Miedema, whose group
filed the lawsuit last month along with the farming area cities of
Pahokee and Belle Glade and three subsidiaries of Palm Beach-based
Florida Crystals Corp.
</P>
<P>
   They argued that the Interior Department has failed to conduct a
legally required study of how the sale would affect the Everglades
and the economy. But federal officials say the study is unnecessary
because the land will remain in farming for several years while the
government decides how exactly to use the tracts.
</P>
<P>
   Many hopes are riding on the sale of Talisman's holdings in Palm
Beach and Hendry counties, which Vice President Al Gore announced
with much fanfare last year at the 50th anniversary of Everglades
National Park.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers has said the land could form
the heart of 60,000 acres of reservoirs needed to replenish the
Everglades. The proposed reservoirs are a fulcrum of the federal
government's $7.8 billion Everglades restoration plan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Interior Department has offered to swap some of
Talisman's scattered parcels to other sugar companies, which could
wind up with land more fertile than their own. In return, the
government would end up with a solid block of land near the
Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Water managers, meanwhile, hope the swaps would give them land
for a separate, $763 million project aimed at cleaning up farm
drainage flowing into the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   But the talks have stalled over the details of the swaps. The
sugar companies say federal proposals would force them to give up
too much land. Meanwhile, the federal government has resisted a
proposal supported by the state and the South Florida Water
Management District; that deal wouldn't have left the federal
government with enough land, Bohlen said.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Lawton Chiles tried to unravel the tangle during a trip to
Washington on Friday, the day before he died. But the growers
rejected the government's latest offer Sunday, Interior Department
counsel Bill Leary said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Chiles) would have made a difference,'' Leary said
Tuesday. ``It's just going to be a little bit more difficult
without his presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohlen, the federal negotiator, said no further talks will take
place until Hogan rules. But Bill Malone, the water district's land
management director, said he hopes the feds reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tantalizingly close to a solution,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman and Robert P. King write for the Palm Beach Post,
West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2209EST &QL; 
