<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-ARENA-COX     12-15 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-ARENA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposal for new arena rejected
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A plan proposed by the San Antonio Spurs to have
a new basketball arena built northeast of downtown has been
rejected by a local school board whose approval was necessary, most
likely killing the project.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting that started Monday night and did not end until
after 1:30 a.m. Tuesday, the North East School District voted 5-2
to withdraw from discussions of a plan that would have dedicated
all property taxes generated by new development in part of the
district as well as increased property appraisals to pay for the
$157 million arena. The arena would have been paid for in 20 to 30
years.
</P>
<P>
   For the plan to reach fruition, approval was needed from the
City of San Antonio, Bexar County and the school district. The
arena would have been located on the abandoned Longhorn Quarry,
which is within the district's boundries.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection ultimately could result in the Spurs moving to
another city, although they have made no such threats. The Spurs
have played in the Alamodome since 1993. But their ownership
believes that the Dome, which was built primarily with hopes of
attracting a National Football League team, is not suitable under
current economic conditions in professional sports. The escalating
salaries of pro athletes are often funded with revenue from luxury
boxes. Though the Dome has 32 luxury boxes available for
basketball, the Spurs say they are too far from the court. Only 14
of the 32 boxes were rented last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Spurs are not the enemy, and I hope we're not the enemy,''
said board member Bill McCabe, who voted to pull out of the
discussions. ``This is an issue about how to finance the arena,
period.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council is scheduled to vote Thursday on whether to
create the 3,200-acre tax-increment finance (TIF) district needed
to fund the arena. Mayor Howard Peak has said that without the
school board's approval, the project will die.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Spurs' Chairman Peter Holt nor any of his high-level
subordinates were available for comment Tuesday. Team spokesman Tom
James said they would not comment until assessing their options for
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we believed the proposal on the table would work,''
James said. ``All we can do at this point is sit down with the
ownership group and consulting staff and figure out what the next
step will be. Until we've had those discussions, we can't
speculate.''
</P>
<P>
   Among possible options for the Spurs are remaining in the
Alamodome; building an arena financed by a sales tax increase, as
was the Dome; selling the team; or moving to another city. Public
opinion surveys taken by the Spurs have indicated local citizens
would be unwilling to support a sales tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, school board president Bruce Bennett, a vocal opponent
of the TIF, said he will offer his support to the Spurs should they
seek alternate financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go out and tell people how important the Spurs are to San
Antonio,'' Bennett said. ``I just don't think education dollars
should be spent for an arena.''
</P>
<P>
   The school board voted Monday after time was allotted for imput
by the Spurs, the City of San Antonio and the school district.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs' financial consulting firm, Paine Webber Inc., has
estimated the arena will cost between $369 million and $519 million
after interest on the bonds issued to finance it is taken into
account.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Moak, a former Texas deputy commissioner of education hired
by the Spurs and Bitterblue Inc., the project's developer,
predicted the school district would lose no revenue and might gain
$7 million over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Wess Robinson, the school district's superintendent for business
and technology, gave a presentation along with consultants hired by
the district. They concluded the school district would lose $18.5
million, or perhaps a lot more, over 25 years if it joins the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was attended by an estimated 300 people, 50 of whom
signed up to speak to the board, but about half of them left before
trustees began listening to the public imput at 11:30 p.m. Those
who remained were evenly divided among supporters and critics.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
