the Leopard Hill cemetary in Lusaka. Across Africa, as the AIDS
epidemic has gnawed through people like a conqueror worm, the
number of the dying is so great that it is changing the culture of
death itself. There are 5,500 AIDS-related funerals every day in
Africa, according to the United Nations. (Lori Waselchuk/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW BEDFORD, Mass. -- Dec. 15, 1998 -- TRAVEL-WHALE,
12-15 -- Andrew and Jean Konnerth examine the skull of a 66 ft.
Blue Whale that they are assembling at the New Bedford Whaling
Museum. The skull alone weighs 3,470 pounds and the blue whale
skeleton is expected to be the biggest such exhibit in the world, a
fitting addition to this city so steeped in the history of whaling.
(Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 15, 1998 -- IMPEACH-DEMS-2, 12-15 --
Speaker-elect Bob Livingston greets leaders of various women's
groups at the door of his Capitol Hill office on Tuesday. The women
met with Livingston in an effort to presuade him that President
Clinton should be censured, not impeached. The House is to vote on
impeachment on Thursday. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) REDWOOD CITY, Calif. -- Dec. 15, 1998 --
