<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-BOEHLERT-NYT &LR;      12-15 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-BOEHLERT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSMAN FROM UPSTATE N.Y. PONDERS THE VOTE OF HIS CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS,
IMPEACH-REPORT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWICH, N.Y. _ Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., kept his
breakfast date with the Chenango County Chamber of Commerce Tuesday
morning, but he spent only a few minutes on the scheduled subject
of worker training.
</P>
<P>
   One of the last holdouts in the House who has not announced a
position on impeachment, Boehlert told the gathering, about 75
people at Fred's Inn, that he was hoping for some last-minute
action, giving him middle ground to plant his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are asking me, `Aren't you under a lot of pressure?'''
Boehlert said. ``Yes, I am. It's not pressure from the White House,
promising me something. It's not pressure from the leadership,
threatening. It's pressure from within.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Mohawk River Valley, where everyone calls him
Sherry, Boehlert faces little political pressure. He won election
to his ninth term in November with 81 percent of the vote,
defeating a Right to Life candidate; the Democrats did not even
enter the race.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading environmentalists in the Republican Party,
Boehlert has built a bridge between liberals in the 19th-century
industrial towns of Utica and Rome and the conservatives who
dominate the rural stretches around them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite casting unpopular votes, he has managed to stay
immensely popular by remembering people's names and bringing
federal money home. At 62, he is comfortable in his job, facing no
apparent threat.
</P>
<P>
   And as a sometime maverick moderate from a region of nine rural
counties that fill most of the triangle formed by Albany, Syracuse
and Binghamton, Boehlert also has no realistic ambitions for higher
office or for a position in the House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   So he has little to lose. Yet after a lifetime of public service
_ in the Army, as an aide to two congressional predecessors and as
Oneida County executive before his election to the House in 1982 _
Boehlert feels the pressure of history. He said he was worried that
his work for the environment, and his opposition to gun control,
would be overshadowed by one ``yea'' or ``nay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of my record,'' he said at the breakfast. ``I'm
saddened by the fact that my legacy might well be, `How did he vote
on the impeachment question?'''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress like to say they make decisions based on the
facts rather than sticking their fingers in the wind, but here in
New York's 23rd Congressional District, public opinion is not much
help. Calls to district headquarters in Utica since Thursday have
been almost evenly split: 1,502 for impeachment and 1,323 against,
as of 4:30 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who disagree with Boehlert's decisions _ his
controversial vote, for example, for Clinton's 1993 budget, or
against the ban on the procedure opponents call partial-birth
abortion _ say they respect him and trust his deliberations. And,
as a practical matter, they appreciate the perquisites that come
with his seniority, like the money he got for his district in last
year's transportation bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sherry is so comfortably entrenched, and I mean that in a very
positive sense, one vote is not going to hurt him,'' said John
Zogby, a national pollster who is based in Utica and has worked for
candidates in both parties. ``He has very good political skills.
And he doesn't thumb his nose at any group.''
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert collects contributions from abortion-rights activists
and unions as well as from banks and business groups. And he has
sometimes abandoned his party on controversial votes _ for the
Brady Bill and the minimum wage increase, for instance _ yet enjoys
a good relationship with Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Boehlert has spent the recent days, weeks and months listening
more than talking. He listened to Shaw Dallal, a retired
businessman who has contributed to Boehlert's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not condone what Clinton has done,'' Dallal said in an
interview, ``but I think that the way the Republicans have gone
over this is unconscionable.''
</P>
<P>
   Another opinion came from Michael Evans, a financial adviser who
has worked in Boehlert's campaigns. ``He is a dishonorable man,''
Evans said of Clinton. ``He doesn't deserve to sit in the highest
office.''
</P>
<P>
   At Boehlert's parish, St. John the Evangelist Catholic Church in
New Hartford, churchgoers said a prayer on Sunday for him and his
colleagues in Congress to have the virtues of wisdom and courage.
</P>
<P>
   The most helpful sounding board, Boehlert said, is his wife,
Marianne, who plays devil's advocate to him.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, and a bit on Tuesday, he answered some of the
thousands of telephone calls streaming into his offices. Between
conference calls with members of the Tuesday Group, moderate
Republicans still trying to arrange a compromise for censuring
Clinton, there was not much else to do. And the staff was swamped.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phones have been ringing and ringing,'' Janet Parilla, a
volunteer, told one caller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what: You deliver the pizza and I'll put in your
opinion,'' Ms. Parilla said after ordering lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Then she hung up, and asked, ``Does anyone want to know my
opinion?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
