<HEADER>
A1706 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-KELLY-465&AMP;ADD     12-15 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-KELLY-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PULLED ON ALL SIDES, A REPUBLICAN MAKES UP HER MIND
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT).  
(nk) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ To appreciate the wrenching choice Rep. Sue
Kelly faced before deciding Tuesday to support impeachment of
President Clinton, it helped to listen to the moral ferocity with
which constituents like Eva Coots, John Piccoli and John Farrell
made their feelings known.
</P>
<P>
   As a girl growing up in Nazi Germany, Mrs. Coots saw firsthand
the folly of not taking a political groundswell seriously. So Mrs.
Coots, a 76-year-old retired nurse, convinced that all Clinton did
was tell a ``a stupid lie,'' drove from Ossining to Mrs. Kelly's
Mount Kisco office to voice her view that the ``ridiculous''
impeachment bandwagon must be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought Hitler would disappear because it seemed so
absurd,'' she said, standing in a windbreaker and sneakers in Mrs.
Kelly's district office. ``We should not expect that the Senate
will go around impeachment and it will go away. Nothing goes away
after so much effort is used to stir it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Mrs. Kelly was also being tugged _ and threatened _
from the pro-impeachment side by Farrell, a retired mathematics
teacher, and Piccoli, a retired police officer, both of whom also
felt strongly enough to visit her district office.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I, as a police officer, was before the grand jury and lied,
I'd be put in jail,'' Piccoli said.
</P>
<P>
   And Farrell fairly thundered to a young Kelly aide: ``If Mrs.
Kelly votes against impeachment, I will never vote for her again in
my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately the visits and telephone calls that her aides
registered meticulously on yellow legal pads came down to a wash.
So Mrs. Kelly had to fall back on other factors, her aides and
Republican district leaders said, in deciding to support
impeachment: her own philosophical views, an assessment of the
evidence against the president and the reality that opposition to
impeachment would be bucking practically the entire corps of
congressional Republicans, particularly the leadership that
determines her committee assignments, the fate of pet bills and
district allocations.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday ending the mystery about her view, Mrs.
Kelly said she based her decision to vote for impeachment on the
fact that the United States is a country of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton is not the first president who lied to the American
people,'' she said. ``He is the first in modern times to perjure
himself in front of a grand jury. He lied not to protect the safety
of American soldiers, to save the Republic nor to trick a foreign
despot in a game of political poker. He lied to thwart a court
proceeding in a sad attempt to conceal. He broke his oath of
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``A CEO in my district would be fired for this; an attorney in
my district would face disbarment; a member of my staff
dismissed,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Mrs. Kelly, 62, represents a patchwork district that embraces
contrasting symbols like West Point, the dairy farms of Dutchess
County and the gleaming headquarters of IBM. It takes in the
estates of Bedford, but also the mean streets of Poughkeepsie. Gov.
George Pataki lives in her district.
</P>
<P>
   She also is pulled on by strong abortion rights advocates and
conservative Catholics who dislike her support for the right to
abortion and the Hudson Valley's army of environmentalists, who
laced into her during her first term for caving into the Republican
leadership on issues like clean water. It is a historically
Republican area, but one that gave Clinton 48 percent of its vote
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the district's motley profile, Mrs. Kelly has
never had a free ride. She was elected in 1994 after winning the
Republican primary as the lone woman in a field with half a dozen
men; in 1996 she beat off a vigorous primary challenge from Joseph
DioGuardi, a former congressman. She won a third term in November.
</P>
<P>
   As a relative newcomer, Mrs. Kelly, who before heading to
Washington was a real estate broker, is more vulnerable to
retribution from Republican leaders. She has counted on those
leaders for support in the past and has received fund-raising
visits from Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
