<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-CENSUSCOUNT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hispanic group pushes for correct census count
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hispanic leaders will have to convince distrustful
immigrants that the census is confidential and relevant to their
future if they hope to avoid an undercount in 2000, the head of a
national Mexican civil rights organization said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make sure this community is counted,'' said Antonia
Hernandez, president and general counsel of the Mexican American
Legal Defense and Educational Fund, based in Los Angeles. ``They
are the ones who stand to lose the most if they are not counted.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, more than 1.5 million Latinos were not counted
nationwide, MALDEF says, resulting in the loss of millions in
federal funds to the cities where they live. Census figures are
used to determine how federal money is spent on housing, health
care, education and transportation. The information also is used to
determine how many seats each state will have in the U.S. House of
Representatives. The 2000 census is especially important for
Latinos because they are projected to become the nation's biggest
minority group shortly after the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said her group will open a Southeast regional office
in Atlanta by February in an effort to get every Latino to fill out
a census form. MALDEF is working with officials from the local
Latin American Association.
</P>
<P>
   When it was considering where to open a southeastern office,
MALDEF picked Atlanta over Miami and Orlando because the Hispanic
community here is cohesive and well-organized, Hernandez said.
``The community leaders here work well together. We were really
impressed.''
</P>
<P>
   MALDEF will launch a national advertising campaign to convince
Latinos that the census is confidential and important to the future
of their children, Hernandez said. The ads will run in Spanish and
English on TV, radio and newspapers that cater to Hispanics. Many
ads will run during Spanish soap operas, which have a large
audience, she said. MALDEF also is asking utility companies, banks
and private businesses like Blockbuster and Wal-Mart to include
census information in shopping bags and on billing statements. The
campaign slogan is ``Make Yourself Count!'' Immigrants
traditionally have been undercounted because they do not trust the
government and they think the information may be used against them.
Hernandez acknowledged that it will be difficult to get immigrants,
especially undocumented ones, to fill out census forms.
</P>
<P>
   She stressed that the census forms are confidential and the
information is not shared with any agency, including the INS or the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   The method used to count people still is in question. The
Clinton administration plans to use a scientific method of
estimating portions of the population, called statistical sampling,
to take account of the millions who might be missed in a
traditional headcount.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court is considering two cases by opponents who
say a statistical sampling is illegal, prone to political
manipulation and not necessarily more accurate than a traditional
head count.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Kurylo writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
