<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Japanese-American Museum Is Expanded  
 The Peninsula Hotel: A Touch of Hong Kong  
 Signing Up for Camping In the National Parks  
 Christmas in the Home of the Reindeer   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pavilion opening next month at the Japanese American National
Museum in Los Angeles will feature galleries and a library where
visitors will have computer access to photographs and documents.
The addition triples the amount of exhibition space at the museum,
which is in the Little Tokyo Historic District downtown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pavilion will open Jan. 23 with the exhibition ``Common
Ground: The Heart of Community,'' which traces the
Japanese-American community in the United States over the past 130
years. Using artifacts, letters and film, the show will describe
Japanese-American pioneers of the 19th century, the internment of
Japanese-Americans during World War II and the adoption of Western
traditions by Japanese immigrants in America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $6, $5 for seniors and $4 for students and children
over 5. Information: (213) 625-0414. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors to the Peninsula New York who crave a sense of the
hotel's former Beaux-Arts trappings can gaze up at the lobby's
magnificent wedding cake ceiling. But not much else from the past
is on view at the 23-story hotel, which closed for renovations in
January and reopened quietly last month.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby, lined with marble floors and Oriental carpets, is
still grand. But with paintings by Helen Frankenthaler and Robert
Motherwell and a new palette of creams, blacks and pale golds, the
hotel has become more contemporary.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years as part of the Peninsula Group, the building that
started life in 1905 as the Gotham Hotel on 55th Street just west
of Fifth Avenue bears a striking resemblance to the Peninsula Hong
Kong, provided you don't look out the windows. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Furnishings in the 241 rooms are traditional, with silk
bedspreads, classic French furniture and the handsome Art Nouveau
headboards retained from the previous decor. But the electronic
system is high tech, from the mood lighting to the bedside panels
that regulate the lighting, air conditioning, Do Not Disturb light,
and television and stereo system. Larger rooms have an upholstered
luggage shelf, like those in the Hong Kong Peninsula. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic difference is in the bathrooms, which feature
hand-free telephones, stereo speakers and, in the larger rooms,
separate stall showers and bathtubs, with built-in
remote-controlled television for viewing from the tub.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the 48 simplest rooms, which cost $535 a night,
have more conventional combination showers and tubs. But these,
too, are larger than most in the hotel's pre-renovation days. And
all guests can use the hotel's rooftop spa and pool.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Trucco &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starting Jan. 1, reservations for the 22 most popular camping
areas in the National Park System may be made up to five months in
advance. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to make the process operate more smoothly, camping
reservations and reservations for three Park Service tours will
stagger their openings for the next period over three dates: the
5th, the 15th and the 25th of each month. Here is a breakdown of
the reservation dates and telephone numbers for the camping areas
involved: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Yosemite in California, reservations open on the 15th of
each month for camping up to five months later; call (800)
436-7275. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Acadia in Maine, Assateague in Maryland and Virginia, Cape
Hatteras in North Carolina, Channel Islands in California,
Chickasaw in Oklahoma, Death Valley in California, Everglades in
Florida, Glacier in Montana, Grand Canyon in Arizona, Great Smoky
Mountains in Tennessee and North Carolina, Greenbelt in Maryland,
Gulf Islands in Florida and Mississippi, Joshua Tree in California,
Katmai in Alaska, Mount Rainier in Washington, Rocky Mountain in
Colorado, Sequoia-Kings Canyon in California, Sleeping Bear Dunes
in Michigan, Shenandoah in Virginia, Whiskeytown in California and
Zion in Utah, reservations open on the 5th of each month for
camping up to five months later; call (800) 365-2267. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For tours of Carlsbad Caverns in New Mexico, Mammoth Cave in
Kentucky and Frederick Douglass Historic Site in the District of
Columbia, reservations open on the 25th of each month for tours up
to five months later; call (800) 967-2283. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reservations for camping at other federal areas are made on a
first come, first served basis at the individual parks. A basic map
and a few free leaflets can be obtained by calling (202) 208-4747.
The park service's Web site is www.nps.gov. For the National Park
Index for 1997-99 ($6.50), write the government Printing Office,
Superintendent of Documents, Post Office Box 371954, Pittsburgh,
Pa. 15250. The stock number is 024-005-01182-0. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Wade &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Christmas enthusiasts who wish the holiday didn't come but
once a year, Santapark, a Christmas-themed amusement center that
opened last month on the Arctic Circle in Finland offers jingle
bells no matter what the season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 500 miles north of Helsinki, outside the town of
Rovaniemi, the unofficial capital of Finnish Lapland, Santapark is
housed in a huge manmade cavern in a hill known as Syvasenvaara
Fell. The $8 million attraction is owned by a group of investors
that includes Finnair. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visitors enter Santapark by walking through a 650-foot
passageway connecting the outside entrance with a plaza _ 36 feet
high and 108 feet across _ at the heart of the cavern. From there,
four corridors lead to a 56-foot circular hall that surrounds the
plaza. Together, the hall and plaza can handle up to 1,000 visitors
at once. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The hall and plaza contain half a dozen rides and attractions,
including a carousel and a multimedia show that traces the story of
Santa Claus. A Magic Sleigh Ride takes visitors through the far
northern landscape and its seasonal changes, from the deep snows
and dark days of winter to the sunny nights of midsummer.
</P>
<P>
   Santa makes appearances, accompanied by elves and reindeer.
There are also a puppet theater, games, a cafeteria and a gift
shop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Santapark is open year round. Single tickets are $18.50 and
$12.75 for children ages 4 to 11. Information: (358-16) 333-0000,
fax (358-16) 333-0020.
</P>
<P>
   For a high-tech approach to a letter to Santa, the e-mail
address is santapark(AT)santapark.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hall
</P>
</TEXT>
