<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1717 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-UNDERSTANDING-2     12-15 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-UNDERSTANDING-2TAKES-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISTEN WITH THE EAR, NOT THE MIND  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 20) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Present an unfamiliar piece of music to a randomly chosen
audience member, ask an opinion, and I challenge you to get a
simple expository sentence in response. The body language will be
one of retreat; the words will be quick to equivocate. ``That was
interesting,'' or ``I didn't understand it, but maybe I will next
time,'' or ``I should know more about it before I tell you what I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   One longs to hear, ``That was beautiful,'' or ``I hated it,'' or
``It bored me to death,'' for this is what those answers really
mean. The crucial word here is ``understand,'' for the fear of not
understanding is great. Failing to understand marks the unhappy
listener as dense, out of the loop, ill educated.
</P>
<P>
   One of the major achievements of 20th-century composition has
been the intimidation of listeners. The same concertgoer will be
reminded of history's rabble: the insensitive contemporary
audiences that persecuted or ignored great composers during their
lives, only to find themselves demonized by victorious posterity.
</P>
<P>
   Music lovers play a kind of futures market; commitment is scary
when next year's prices might go up or down. To put it another way,
sneering at old rabble is a risk when you yourself might be new
rabble in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Yet I wonder whether we understand music any more than we
understand something that grows in the ground. We look hard at
wisteria, and we like it or we don't. It is the same with Milton
Babbitt and company, who can cite the modern listener's lack of
culture all they want.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the more you stand in front of wisteria, the more roots
and tendrils you notice. But ``understanding wisteria'' implies
that one investigates it, and then judges according to the
findings. That process may work in the courtroom or the laboratory,
but when the senses and not the powers of induction preside, the
order is backward.
</P>
<P>
   In art, one decides what one likes, then finds out why. Knowing
more about trees may give more new details and new responses to
them, but the love is not in the knowing.
</P>
<P>
   My personal experience with ``understanding'' has been the music
of Schoenberg. An ardent admirer of ``Pierrot Lu-naire'' from
youth, I found most of his other music unpleasant. ``I don't
understand it,'' I told myself, while playing Schoenberg records at
breakfast or puzzling through the mysteries of retrograde
inversion. Now I know that I understand Schoenberg reasonably well;
I just don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't like the density. The compositional resourcefulness is
unassailable, but so many ideas packed so close together make my
stomach queasy. Schoenberg's music emits a claustrophobia that
reminds me of Vienna, the city of his roots, and my home for too
many years. I can sort out the 12-tone techniques; I can follow the
counterpoint. But just as we meet immediately dislikable people or
animals _ sometimes even the youngest of children _ so I can hear
the qualities in Schoenberg's music and feel only fleeting
fondness.
</P>
<P>
   You can waste a lot of time and anguish on music you don't like.
As with other people interested in music, there is much that I
don't know or get, but the case of Schoenberg makes me distrust
those who tell me that their music is not beloved because the
public is illiterate and lazy, that its members are descendants of
the mob that drove poor Berlioz crazy.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that immediate esthetic judgment isn't dead
wrong some of the time, but at least it is real. It tells us that
the people out in the seats are alive. Sometimes further exposure
to something we hate the first time changes our mind. But may I
emphasize, sometimes. Posterity as redeemer is, like patriotism, a
last refuge of scoundrels.
</P>
<P>
   I don't suppose I liked Beethoven's last F major Quartet half as
well 40 years ago as I do now. On the other hand, the ``Grosse
Fuge,'' another late-Beethoven string-quartet piece, is as
impenetrable to me today as it was on first hearing.
</P>
<P>
   When patrons at the Metropolitan Opera boo, let your blood race.
Audiences have been browbeaten into a kind of esthetic terror, and
it is splendid to see them take a chance on themselves. Audiences
may be exasperating for coughing, whispering and foot-shuffling,
but given a little distance, one feels respect for them. Listeners
can be conned for a time, but with acquaintance (and not
necessarily new knowledge) they almost infallibly end up knowing
what is good and what isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Are audiences dumber today? They certainly have less first-hand
experience making music. Before the electronic age, people were
their own television sets, record players and radios. With fewer
opportunities to go to concerts or operas, domestic households
engaged in do-it-yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone, or almost everyone from the lower middle class up,
played the piano or the violin a little. Beethoven and Haydn
symphonies were experienced in four-hand versions played in the
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   The proliferation of upright pianos into American homes was as
explosive at the turn of the century as that of the compact disk
and laptop computer are today. Just as every major American city
had at least two breweries, it had its piano manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the old catalogs of the French publisher Durand, and you
will find Debussy and Ravel arranged and rearranged for various
combinations of duet, trio or quartet. A familiarity with music
back then depended in large part on the listener's own facility at
one instrument or another, a phenomenon perhaps even more intense
prior to the 19th century, when music was (rightly) taught as a
corollary to mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   Today listeners are more passive. Listening to first-rate
performances of a vast repertory depends no longer on sight-reading
abilities but on the less demanding tasks of switch flipping and
dial twiddling. That is not to the good, and indeed, some blame the
faltering of the classical-music establishment on the quality of
its employees: well-intentioned people who collect records but have
no real connection with the problems of how music is made.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners today, on the other hand, are vastly better informed
than their counterparts of the past. The world's repertory is a
record bin away for any curious shopper. I doubt that the ardent
Viennese concertgoer of 1900 knew that Faure existed. Rachmaninoff
expressed surprise that Schubert had written piano sonatas.
</P>
<P>
   Read no diatribe against new music into all this. Schoenberg was
a genius. Elliott Carter is a brilliant and authoritative composer.
Babbitt is a fascinating geometrician. Think of the paragraphs
above as a modest bill of rights. Its first article guarantees
freedom from intimidation, and it is followed by such propositions
as the inviolability of the personal instinct and the limited power
of the intellect to make esthetic decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Open ears and curiosity are suggested, for there is much music
in our time to love. Learn, for knowing more can enrich judgments,
just as a frame and mat set off a picture we have been drawn to.
Don't ruin your breakfasts with guilt. Feel free to be offended; it
might be the best thing to happen to living composers in a long
time. Honest dislike loosens the limbs and limbers the spirit. From
chemistry like this comes true love as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
