<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMAP-PETERSEN-NYT &LR;      12-15 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAP-PETERSEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH COMPANY BUYING PUBLISHER OF MOTOR TREND, SNOWBOARDER
MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Petersen Companies Inc., publisher of Motor Trend, Hot Rod,
Guns &AMP; Ammo, Snowboarder, Inline and dozens of other magazines for
readers whose hormone of choice is testosterone and whose speed of
choice is zoom, is being purchased by a British magazine publisher,
Emap PLC, in a deal valued at $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, which has been one of the fastest-growing magazine
companies _ with a particular focus on the young male audience _
will continue its search for acquisitions as a division of Emap,
according to its current chairman and chief executive, James
Dunning Jr. This insures its continued rivalry with Primedia Inc.,
which has also been picking up niche magazines for young readers at
a fast clip.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, shortly after Petersen started faxing out the news of
its deal, Primedia followed suit with the news that it had acquired
Sterling/Macfadden Teen Network, publishers of Teen Beat, Tiger
Beat, Sixteen and Teen Machine, and the Laufer Publishing Co.,
publishers of BOP and BB (also known as Big Bopper). A company
spokesman said the purchase price was more than $35 million.
</P>
<P>
   William Reilly, Primedia's chairman and chief executive, said in
a prepared statement that Primedia's new stable, coupled with its
2.4-million-circulation magazine Seventeen, gave the company ``an
unmatched authority in the teen category across all ages.''
Primedia is controlled by Kohlberg, Kravis, Roberts, a leveraged
buyout firm.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal gave Petersen's shareholders a different sort of
bragging right. Many of them doubled or even quadrupled their
investment. Under the Emap deal Petersen shareholders will receive
$34 a share in cash. Last year, Petersen sold 8 million of its 32.5
million shares outstanding to the public for slightly more than
$17.50 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The deal meant that a company purchased in 1996 for $165 million
in equity and $300 million in assumed debt, then recapitalized with
its $141 million public offering in 1997, is passing on the debt to
the new owners while getting $1.2 billion in equity. Willis Stein &AMP;
Partners LP, a Chicago-based private equity firm, is Petersen's
largest single shareholder, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The company has had its circulation successes, too; Motor Trend
has a circulation of 1.25 million, while Hot Rod has 700,000
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Kummerfeld, president of the Magazine Publishers of
America, said that Emap had its roots in outdoor publications like
Angling Times, but that most of its titles _ Nursing Times,
Insurance Age _ belonged to the prosaic trade press.
</P>
<P>
   Emap has also moved briskly into consumer magazines in Britain,
publishing FHM, an upscale men's magazine with a circulation of
750,000. Dunning, who will head Emap's Petersen's Division, said an
American edition of FHM was likely.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kummerfeld said, Emap has ``a big online operation
in the United Kingdom, and quite a lot of Web sites.'' He added:
``They also have a very profitable radio division. It's become one
of the more aggressive international companies.'' Including the
Petersen magazines, Emap will now publish more than 600 titles.
</P>
<P>
   The keenness of the competition for younger readers in America
is underscored by a recent survey _ sponsored by Primedia _ that
showed that 12- to 19-year-olds have $500 million in spending money
available every week.
</P>
<P>
   Dunning said Tuesday that the new, magazine-rich Emap stable of
publications, with its emphasis on outdoor sports, engines and
electronics, hoped to provide one-stop shopping to advertisers who
want to reach readers of several magazines with a single buy.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of package has already been offered in conjunction
with the ``Gravity Games'' scheduled for broadcast by NBC on
several weekend afternoons next fall. Dunning said advertisers were
offered package deals including TV and 14 different Petersen
magazines that focus on the Gravity Games sports, like
skateboarding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
