<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEE-DAVIS-ANNIVERSARY     12-15 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEE-DAVIS-ANNIVERSARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUBY DEE AND OSSIE DAVIS: A 50-YEAR MARRIAGE MADE IN REALITY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By KATHRYN SHATTUCK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On an early afternoon in a sun-dappled corner of their stately
home in New Rochelle, N.Y., Ruby Dee and Ossie Davis were admiring
an enormous poinsettia, its vibrant red leaves shooting out into
all four corners of an otherwise coolly subdued living room.
</P>
<P>
   The plant _ ``the largest, most beautiful, most expensive we
could find,'' said Miss Dee _ was a gift from the couple to each
other on Dec. 9, the day of their 50th wedding anniversary. It will
be the only gift they exchange this year, a symbol for the only
gift they need at this juncture of their lives: each other.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the event has gone unheralded. In November the
couple published a joint memoir, ``With Ossie and Ruby: In This
Life Together'' (William Morrow), an assessment of their
experiences together and apart. Tuesday night they celebrated with
a benefit at the Grand Hyatt Hotel in Manhattan to raise money for
12 regional theaters like the ones in which they got their start.
(``We're giving back,'' said Miss Dee, who is 74.) Wednesday night
they are to join trap drummer Max Roach in ``Theater Pieces,'' an
evening of poetry, prose and music that is part of ``Max Roach's
America,'' a three-concert series at the 92nd Street Y.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the performance is ``Solo on the Drums,'' an
adaptation of a short story by Ann Petry described as ``a jazz
triangle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a day in the life of a drummer who has just been
told early that morning by his beloved wife that she's leaving him
for the pianist in the band,'' Davis, who will be 81 Thursday, said
in his resonant bass. ``So they go downtown to perform and sitting
right across from him is the man who has taken his wife. And his
anger and his passion to murder fuse into a moment of such high
professionalism that when it's over he no longer feels the need to
kill but is satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We read the short story,'' he added. ``And as we read it, the
music aids and abets. And there we are, as we say, Max on drums,
James Williams on piano, and Ruby and Ossie on words. So we just
sort of jam a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The trio had been clamoring to rework the piece for the stage
since they first performed it for a PBS broadcast in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max is one of the icons in a field that is gradually growing
thinner,'' Davis said. ``He is still solid, still there, still
creating a statement. The honor to work with that man, oh my God,
it's hard to put into words. Nobody I know has been as insistent on
the dignity of black music.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are professionals who are out of this world, the way they
do things,'' Roach said of Miss Dee and Davis. ``They can come
right in and deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a self-educated railroad construction engineer, Davis
was raised in rural Georgia, eventually leaving the countryside to
live with his grandmother in Waycross, a larger town, so that he
could receive a better education. After graduating from Howard
University in Washington, he traveled to New York, where he began
his acting career with the Rose McClendon Players in the basement
of the 124th Street Library in Harlem while attending drama classes
at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of a waiter on the Pennsylvania Railroad, Miss Dee
graduated from Hunter College and went on to work with the American
Negro Theater, in the basement of the 135th Street Library, now
known as the Schomburg Center for Research in Black Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Though they insist their paths surely must have crossed in the
years they traversed the neighborhood, the couple met in 1945 when
they were both cast in the Broadway production of ``Jeb'' at the
Martin Beck Theater: he as the male lead, she as the understudy to
the female lead, a role she eventually took on. Neither can
remember the moment they met; they recall having felt as if they
had always known each other. They married three years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's here so fast,'' Miss Dee said of the landmark
anniversary. ``And I'm a little embarrassed to talk about it yet
I'm happy to talk about it. Because when you get there it can sound
very smarmy, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis interjected: ``And icky.''
</P>
<P>
   Miss Dee added, sighing, ``And sentimental, and oh, my God,
oh.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, the marriage has been a good one, producing
three children, seven grandchildren, two successful careers both
apart and in tandem, and an unflinching activism for causes social
and civil. Agreeing to disagree, they say, was often the key to
surviving. They are frank in their discussion of marriage, even, on
the topic of infidelity, which has crept into their safe haven.
</P>
<P>
   ``That we arrived at 50 years together is due as much to luck as
to love, and a talent for knowing, when we stumble, where to fall,
and how to get up again,'' they wrote in ``With Ossie and Ruby.''
``We two scavenged among the changes thrown up by the sexual
revolution that swept across the country, to find what suited us,
and what could be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, after 15 years of marriage and with every
intention of staying married but with work that took them away from
each other, putting them in intimate contact with attractive people
for long periods, they decided to give themselves permission to
sleep with other partners ``as long as what we did was honest as
well as private, and that neither of us exposed the family to
scandal or disease,'' they wrote. ``We had to be discreet and, if
the word can be apt, honorable in our behavior, both to ourselves,
to whomever else might be involved, and most of all, to the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea was hers, Davis said. She felt compelled to suggest the
arrangement for her own sake, Miss Dee replied, instead of
wondering where her husband had been and where he would go. She was
angry when he agreed to it. It was an arrangement not unlike many
of its time, and it had its points, like taking the sting out of
the loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   Each had a relationship that sent them looking homeward: she,
with a classical musician with a wife and children; he, with a
nurse on a movie set in Spain. Ultimately, they decided, the
arrangement was not appropriate for them.
</P>
<P>
   That they should share such a personal story with the public was
not out of character with the couple's philosophy of life. Their
marriage, their memoirs, their oral history, all are a part of a
broader picture that Miss Dee and Davis believe will serve future
generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange new time coming, and we need to somehow get out
there and test the waters for the people coming after,'' Miss Dee
said. ``We need to make the changes, do the revolutions and make
things right that will make it easier for our children and
grandchildren.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added: ``If we leave children to explore their own
sexuality unguided, then we end up with unwed mothers by the bushel
who haven't the slightest idea what they're doing or of the
consequences of their sexual actions. So now we cannot do without
absolute sexual frankness, whatever our previous reservations might
have been.''
</P>
<P>
   That the couple put their commitment to the test and survived
does not strike Miss Dee as odd or remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just staying together is not a real virtue, if you're not
happy,'' she said. ``Or you're being denied. Or one person is being
squashed. Or you really don't love each other; you're just there
out of habit. That doesn't work, no matter how many years you stay
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
