<HEADLINE>
NATIONS AGREE BOSNIA NEEDS CONTINUED INTERNATIONAL SUPPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain _ The United States and other countries that
support the Bosnian peace accord met in Madrid Tuesday and agreed
to press for deeper economic and governmental reforms to prepare
the nation to survive on its own.
</P>
<P>
   A Western official attending the third Bosnian Peace
Implementation Council, a periodic meeting of donor nations, said,
speaking on the condition of anonymity, that ``interventionism has
won out'' for at least two years, despite some objections from
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A key goal of nations helping to carry out the peace accord is
the safe return home of Bosnian war refugees, who are estimated to
number more than one million.
</P>
<P>
   It has been particularly difficult to bring about the return of
refugees to areas controlled by members of other ethnic groups.
They have often met hostility or violence and have found their
homes occupied by members of the controlling group.
</P>
<P>
   The donor nations agreed that they would like to reduce their
aid to Bosnia, but no one here seemed willing to predict when the
international troops and civilian advisers would be sharply
reduced. Javier Solano, NATO secretary general, said an unspecified
number of troops might be withdrawn after June.
</P>
<P>
   Strobe Talbott, the U.S. deputy secretary of state, said, ``An
intensification of our effort in Bosnia is actually crucial to our
exit strategy.'' He added that no nation wants Bosnia to become a
permanent ``ward or protectorate of the international community.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikola Poplasen, who was recently elected leader of the Bosnian
Serb republic and is considered a hard-liner by the United States,
said at a news conference in Madrid Tuesday that the Bosnian people
did not need much outside help to fulfill the 1995 peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Under the accord, reached in Dayton, Ohio, that halted the
nearly four-year civil war, Bosnian Serbs control one part of the
country, and Muslims and Croats control the remainder, with a
tripartite presidency over both entities.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting here received a 39-page proposal, expected to be
approved on Wednesday, that says international assistance in Bosnia
``is at its height'' and ``will inevitably begin to reduce in the
near future.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal includes a detailed plan for refugee return and for
reforms in such areas as fostering economic competition _ in part
through privatization, reducing corruption and creating multiethnic
police forces and an independent judiciary and a free press.
</P>
<P>
   Poplasen said he was concerned that the measures being
considered here would give even more power to the top civilian
international official in Bosnia under the Dayton peace plan,
Carlos Westendorp, to dictate to Bosnian officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States and other Western powers, which have
34,000 peacekeeping troops in Bosnia and are providing about $1.5
billion annually in aid, remain skeptical about whether Bosnia is
ready do do without international support and supervision and were
making plans in Madrid to stay deeply involved for at least two
more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peace in Bosnia remains fragile _ it still cannot survive
without substantial international support,'' Westendorp told
representatives of the 47 nations at the conference. ``We must use
the next crucial two-year period to devote all the energy we can
muster to building a modern, democratic Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Bosnian leaders are reported to be quite willing to adopt
reforms, but Western officials remain doubtful about Poplasen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's anti-democratic and anti-Dayton,'' said Robert Gelbard,
President Clinton's representative for carrying out the Dayton
accords. ``He is going to have to prove himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Westendorp, a Spanish diplomat, has used his office to enact
measures like a common Bosnian currency and a flag. But many
Western experts say the proposed deeper reforms may prove tougher
to carry out.
</P>
</TEXT>
