u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-U.S.-1STLD-WRITE     12-15 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-1STLD-WRITETHRU--NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: cruise missiles. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Iraq did not provide the full cooperation it promised,'' the
report concluded. ``In addition, during the period under review,
Iraq initiated new forms of restrictions upon the commission's
work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq's conduct insured that no progress was able to be made in
either the fields of disarmament or accounting for its prohibited
weapons programs,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   The report catalogs a series of Iraqi refusals to extend full
access to inspectors or provide requested documentation since
inspections resumed in Iraq on Nov. 17, three days after Saddam
Hussein backed away from a total ban on inspections in the face of
an American military attack.
</P>
<P>
   While many monitoring operations were allowed to resume, Butler
said, routine inspections were being blocked by early December and
special surprise visits to new sites also met hurdles. Moreover,
there were places that appeared to have been ``cleaned'' before
inspectors arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of the clear evidence that Iraq had taken advance
actions at certain of the locations planned for inspection in order
to defeat the purposes of inspection, the executive chairman
decided not to conduct the full range of inspections the team had
planned,'' Butler wrote. ``No inspections of presidential sites
took place.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, however, the International Atomic Energy
Agency, which monitors the Iraqi nuclear program, said that the
level of cooperation from Iraq since Nov. 17 has been satisfactory.
Independent nuclear experts said that this will lead to pressure
from Iraq's supporters to ``close the file'' on the Iraqi nuclear
program.
</P>
<P>
   In his report, Butler describes Iraqi policies on cooperation
with the inspectors that he considers to be fundamentally out of
line with the disarmament framework and regulations laid down by
the Security Council in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iraq's current claims that it has fulfilled all of its
disarmament obligations in each weapons area; ceased concealment
policies and actions; and that it has neither proscribed weapons
nor the ability to make them, cannot be accepted without further
verification,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Butler details recent incidents that demonstrate Iraq's
unwillingness to give the inspectors the access that Hussein's
government has promised the Secretary General and the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that given Iraq's resistance, the special
commission cannot conduct full inspections and therefore cannot say
with any assurance that Iraq has met its disarmament requirements.
</P>
<P>
   At the State Department, the deputy spokesman, James Foley, said
that Butler's report was ``a very serious matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect that the President will review Chairman Butler's
conclusions with his senior advisers,'' Foley said. ``I can't
speculate on what decisions the President will make. We believe we
have all the authority we need under relevant Security Council
resolutions to act. All options remain on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the report on Iraqi compliance triggers military
action, it will provide the basis for making decisions about how to
proceed diplomatically with Iraq in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Butler report is, first of all, the key to Iraq's hopes of
getting a comprehensive review of its relations with the United
Nations and the progress or lack of it Baghdad has made in more
than eight years since sanctions were imposed after the August 1990
invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, in a covering letter to the Security Council,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan appears to acknowledge that Iraq has
not met the test of full cooperation, but sets out three possible
ways to proceed with the comprehensive review: cancel it, give Iraq
more time to meet its obligations or hold it anyway for the sake of
the Council.
</P>
<P>
   Coming in the midst of Washington's roiling debate over
impeachment, the latest confrontation will inevitably raise
accusations that Clinton may use Saddam as a diversion.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on Sunday, Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas,
the majority whip leading the House's impeachment effort, responded
bluntly when asked about the prospect of a strike on Iraq, accusing
the president of manipulating foreign policy to divert attention
from his personal and political crises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, about the time he was supposed to give the
deposition in January, he sent the troops and rattled his sabers at
Saddam Hussein?'' DeLay said. ``Nothing happened. Remember in
November _ I mean in June, he went to China after moving that trip
from November to June, when he thought he was going to be in trial
with Paula Jones? And then again in August, he starts rattling his
saber again and backs off. That's what's happening.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in August, Clinton did order cruise missile strikes
against paramilitary camps in Afghanistan and a pharmaceutical
factory in the Sudan _ on the day Monica Lewinsky appeared for a
second time before the federal grand jury investigating Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Clinton angrily dismiss the notion, pointing out that
the periodic confrontations with Iraq have been driven by Saddam's
defiance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
