<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEVRON PLANS TO CUT JOBS AND CAPITAL SPENDING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joining the list of major oil companies that are retrenching in
the face of low crude oil prices, Chevron announced cuts in capital
spending and employment, primarily in North America.
</P>
<P>
   The company intends to reduce costs by $500 million in 1999 and
cut capital spending by 8 percent, to $5.1 billion, next year,
mostly in its older exploration and production, refining and
marketing and chemical businesses in North America. The cuts in its
work force of 34,000 will be modest, the company said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A SHIFT IN CASE AGAINST MICROSOFT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government's antitrust case against Microsoft turned from
evidence supplied by competitors to allegations of cajoling and
threatening from companies that for the most part posed no obvious
competitive threat, ranging from IBM and MCI to Walt Disney. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Denying Microsoft access to the research of two business school
professors, a federal appeals court ruled that scholars should be
granted First Amendment privileges similar to those of
journalists. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MAGAZINE PUBLISHER IS SOLD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Petersen Companies, the publisher of Motor Trend, Hot Rod, Guns
&AMP; Ammo and dozens of other magazines, is being bought by a British
magazine publisher, Emap, in a deal valued at $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, which has been one of the fastest-growing magazine
companies _ with a particular focus on the young male audience _
will continue to seek acquisitions as a division of Emap, according
to its current chairman and chief executive, James D. Dunning Jr. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BERTELSMANN TO RESEARCH ITS PAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann, the German conglomerate that owns Random House and
is a partner with Barnes &AMP; Noble in its Internet bookstore, is
appointing a committee of scholars to investigate its activities
during the Nazi era. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS REBOUND AFTER SELLOFF &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stocks broke a five-session losing streak in a reversal traders
and analysts said was a rebound from a selloff that had gone too
far. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 127.70 points, or 1.5
percent, to 8,823.30. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index gained
21.63 points, or 1.9 percent, to 1,162.83, and the NASDAQ composite
index rose 45.68 points, or 2.32 percent, to 2,012.60. In the bond
market, Treasury prices fell as the yield on the 30-year issue rose
to 5.02 percent. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the Tokyo Stock Exchange will return part of their
salaries to take responsibility for recent computer problems, the
head of the exchange said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NO SIGN OF HIGHER INFLATION &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Labor Department data showed inflation remained subdued in
November. The Consumer Price Index, the government's main inflation
gauge, rose 0.2 percent, matching the October increase. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COLTEC SHARES RISE IN MERGER FIGHT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Coltec Industries rose $2, or 12 percent, to $18.6875,
as Crane pursued its attempt to block a planned $1.3 billion merger
between Coltec and B.F. Goodrich. Goodrich said it had no plans to
drop its offer to buy Coltec, a maker of aerospace components and
industrial products in Charlotte, N.C. But several Coltec
shareholders expressed interest in hearing Crane's offer. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PACT ON INTERNET MUSIC SALES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America and five major
recording companies said they would work with technology companies
to develop a standard for delivery of music over the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
