<HEADLINE>
JUSTICE DEPT. WARNS GROUP AIDING IRAQ THAT IT NEEDS PERMIT 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An American group opposed to sanctions against
Iraq has run into trouble with the federal government for taking
medicines and toys to Baghdad to give to Iraqis who are suffering
from the effects of the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Voices in the Wilderness, plans to announce at a news
conference Wednesday in Chicago that it and four members had
received a warning from the Office of Foreign Assets Control in the
Justice Department that the organization might be fined more than
$160,000 for taking goods to Iraq without authorization in 1996 and
last year.
</P>
<P>
   An organizer of the campaign, Kathy Kelly, said in an interview
Tuesday that the group intended to reject the warning, which it has
30 days to contest, and instead to demonstrate against sanctions
this month in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't pay any penalties. That's certain,'' Ms. Kelly said.
The group, which has sponsored 18 trips to Iraq, was formed to
oppose sanctions and has made its trips to Iraq public displays of
defiance, saying the dangerous nation is not Iraq, but the United
States. In Baghdad the group has picketed the headquarters of the
United Nations Special Commission, the agency charged with
disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biological warfare is being waged against Iraqi children,''
Ms. Kelly said. ``I've seen a child die before my eyes from a
waterborne disease. And this offensive is being waged by our
country, as our country accuses Iraq of possibly having a huge
threatening arsenal of weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   She cited Iraqi figures, reflected in U.N. reports, that 6,000
children were dying in Iraq monthly because of malnutrition and
treatable diseases that were not treated because of the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kelly said the primary goal of her group was to convince
Americans that Iraqis were paying too high a price for U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups have taken medicine, food and other goods to Iraq
without encountering legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Office of Foreign Assets Control said
Tuesday that it was not against the law to take essential civilian
goods to Iraq, if the group applies for a license. Other groups
have done so, the spokesman said, but Voices in the Wilderness has
not.
</P>
<P>
   Some administration officials and diplomats here say, though,
that Voices in the Wilderness has deliberately provoked
controversy, a contention that the group does not deny, while other
relief organizations have quietly notified the government and U.N.
officials and traveled to Iraq with less publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go very much for spiritual and humanitarian reasons,'' a
spokesman for one group said Tuesday. ``We respect our government,
even if we don't agree with everything they do. We have not gone to
Iraq simply to defy a law.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Ms. Kelly said that her group had taken nearly
$500,000 worth of goods into Iraq on its 18 trips and that it was
also helping Iraqis. She said her passport was impounded in
February 1997, when she returned from a trip. It was returned to
her, and she made a trip last month.
</P>
<P>
   Many items have been confiscated from the four members named in
the warning when they returned from trips to Baghdad, for violating
a rule against importing goods from Iraq. The items included
videocassettes, tapes and objects as small as souvenirs, a stamp,
the label from a water bottle, a necklace and a wood drum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
