<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-WEBBER-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY VINDICATES ANDREW LLOYD WEBBER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rl) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A day after hearing Andrew Lloyd Webber play excerpts
from his music at the piano, a federal court jury in Manhattan
Tuesday denied a claim by another composer that Lloyd Webber had
stolen a musical passage for use in ``The Phantom of the Opera.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury had been asked to decide if Lloyd Webber used a section
of a 1978 song by Ray Repp, a composer of religious folk music, in
the main theme of ``Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a charge that the British composer denied in testimony on
Monday. He played selections of his music on a piano moved into the
courtroom to illustrate the genesis of his song.
</P>
<P>
   The jury took little more than an hour to rule in Lloyd Webber's
favor.
</P>
<P>
   For Repp, the verdict was the end of a long legal battle that
began after he first heard the ``Phantom'' theme in 1989. Saying he
was struck by the theme's similarity to his Bible-inspired ballad
``Till You,'' Repp filed a copyright infringement lawsuit a year
later.
</P>
<P>
   After eight years of legal machinations, Repp was granted a jury
trial in January by a federal appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very personal song for me,'' Repp said of ``Till
You.'' ``I am particularly upset at the way it's been used.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the verdict, Repp voiced doubt about overcoming the
reputation of Lloyd Webber, who has won several Tony Awards and was
knighted by Queen Elizabeth II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phantom of the Opera,'' which opened in New York in 1988, has
grossed more than $1 billion worldwide. The recorded version of
``Till You,'' on the other hand, had not yet earned $100 when its
sales were last reported in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   As for Lloyd Webber, the verdict allowed him to return to London
victorious Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been totally vindicated,'' he said in a statement.
``Perhaps we will now see the end of these money-grabbing spurious
cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2245EST &QL; 
