<HEADLINE>
ENDEAVOUR LANDS AFTER 12-DAY SPACE STATION MISSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Endeavour astronauts ended their 12-day space station
assembly mission late Tuesday, landing at the Kennedy Space Center
in Florida after a fiery re-entry through the Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle crew touched down at 10:53 p.m., EST, skirting
earlier threats of cloudy skies and rain showers that could have
forced postponement.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the 10th time in the shuttle program's 17-year
history of 93 flights that a shuttle crew has landed in darkness.
With commander Bob Cabana and pilot Rick Sturckow at the controls,
the shuttle crew made its long glide and approach from the
southwest and over the Gulf of Mexico with electronic navigational
aids but no lights.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt it is great to be home after such an exciting
mission,'' said Cabana as the shuttle stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Horowitz of mission control said, ``Thanks a lot for an
awesome job starting our space station adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrilled with the success of their difficult flight after more
than two years of training, the astronauts were eager to get back
to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all packed up and ready to come home,'' said Cabana as
his crew made final preparations to return to Earth. ``We can't
wait to get back, see our families and have a great Christmas''
</P>
<P>
   Cabana and fellow astronauts Nancy Currie, Jim Newman, Jerry
Ross, Sturckow and Russian cosmonaut Sergei Krikalev blasted off
Dec. 4 with the second large component of the new international
space station, a module called ``Unity.''
</P>
<P>
   They rendezvoused with the first component, a Russian-built and
launched power and propulsion module called ``Zarya,'' Russian for
``sunrise.''
</P>
<P>
   Using the shuttle's robot arm and three spacewalks by Ross and
Newman, they linked the two modules, creating a single uninhabited
35-ton, 75-foot-long structure that circles the Earth at more than
240 miles high. The new spacecraft is monitored by ground control
teams in Houston and suburban Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle astronauts are to return to the fledgling outpost with
more components and equipment in May. All told, the full assembly
will require six years and 45 assembly missions. The first resident
crew is scheduled for launching in January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Endeavour's crew planned to rest Wednesday in Florida, following
routine medical exams and reunions with their families.
</P>
<P>
   They were to return Thursday to Houston about 2 p.m., CST. The
space agency planned a brief welcoming ceremony at Ellington Field.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
