<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPITZER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LAST, IT'S OFFICIAL: SPITZER DEFEATS VACCO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After six weeks of rancorous, highly partisan
dialogue regarding its outcome, the race for state attorney general
was officially settled in a quiet meeting Tuesday at a rest stop
along the Gov. Thomas E. Dewey Thruway.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the other winners of statewide offices, the state
Board of Elections certified Eliot Spitzer as the state's 63rd
attorney general. The meeting _ held a day after Dennis Vacco, the
Republican incumbent, conceded defeat _ was at a conference center
at a rest stop in Sloatsburg, about 35 miles north of New York City
in Rockland County.
</P>
<P>
   The board has often used the site because it does not require
extensive travel for either the members from the New York City
metropolitan area or for staff members based in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   The board certified Spitzer the winner by a margin of 25,186
votes _ 2,084,948 to Vacco's 2,059,762 votes.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, it was unclear whether the certification would take
place by Dec. 15, the date required under state law. Vacco charged
that widespread voter fraud in New York City had affected the
results and had asked a judge either to declare him the winner or
to order a new election.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Vacco failed to substantiate his allegations and the
matter was dismissed by a state Supreme Court justice on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   While the certification of the candidates took all of 15 minutes
and went smoothly, some issues were raised. The two Republicans on
the four-member board, while voting to certify the results, asked
to have the record reflect their desire to have Vacco's allegations
investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the record,'' said Lee Daghlian, a spokesman for
the state Board of Elections, ``and I'm assuming they will ask the
New York City Board of Elections to take a closer look at the
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer said he was ``thrilled and gratified'' that the election
was now settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm looking forward to a two-week transition that
will be compressed and exciting,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2313EST &QL; 
