<HEADER>
A1900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-SHAYS-NYT &LR;      12-15 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-SHAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDECIDED REPUBLICAN HOLDS A BIG TOWN MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-VOICES,
IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS, IMPEACH-REPORT,
IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD, IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(rl) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORWALK, Conn. _ About 2,000 people packed an auditorium to
overflowing Tuesday night in a passionate, sometimes raucous town
meeting to give their views on impeachment to their congressman,
Christopher Shays, one of the few Republicans who has opposed the
charges against President Clinton, until now at least.
</P>
<P>
   Shays told the audience that he would still vote not to impeach
if the vote were held immediately, but he might reconsider his
opposition after a meeting with the president on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shays said he did not believe that the charges against the
president were impeachable offenses. ``But it is darn close,'' he
said, ``and that's the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays hastily called the town meeting Tuesday in part to help
him come to terms with how he should vote when the full House takes
up the matter as early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Shays' suspenseful position did not seem to disturb the more
than 1,100 people in the auditorium in Norwalk City Hall and the
800 people who were forced to mill about the City Hall lobby after
the local fire officials ruled that the auditorium was filled to
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many praised the congressman for being so deliberative.
With Shays moderating with a wireless microphone and the aplomb of
a television talk show host, the audience _ about evenly divided
between supporters and opponents of impeachment _ responded
enthusiastically, with more than 400 speaking. Many broke into
jeers or boos _ or even hoots when some of the racier aspects of
the Monica Lewinsky affair were mentioned. Several also waved
placards stating slogans such as ``Impeach Clinton The Liar'' or
``Vote No.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the short speeches were impassioned, although sometimes
muddled, pleas to impeach or not to impeach, invoking everyone from
Solomon to Nixon to Machiavelli to Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lying under oath to a grand jury, to the American people, is
indeed a high crime and misdemeanor,'' said Victor Kotiadis, 73, a
retiree from Trumbull, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Haffner of Norwalk said she came to the meeting to
``encourage Chris Shays to stay the course and oppose
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Monica Lewinsky broadcast into my home for the
next nine months,'' Ms. Haffner added. She said she wanted her
congressman `to stand up to Gingrich and Livingston'' and
conservative Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him to vote his conscience,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Newman, who lives in nearby Westport, said he might have
addressed the crowd, but he could not get into the main auditorium.
``I didn't give up my citizenship when I became an actor,'' Newman
said from the city hall lobby. He added that he opposed
impeachment. ``I don't think this is what the framers of the
Constitution had in mind when they said `high crimes and
misdemeanors,' '' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, 53, a moderate Republican first elected in 1987, said he
began thinking about whether he should reconsider his opposition to
impeachment after talking with Lowell Weicker, the former
Connecticut senator and governor, who was a prominent member of the
Watergate hearings and supports the impeachment of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the certainty that I did a week ago,'' Shays told
the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman's office said it had received 14,000 e-mails
over the weekend about the impeachment issue. And on Monday, 1,060
calls came into Shays' office. Fifty-two percent supported
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, a heavy but uncounted number of calls came into Shays'
Bridgeport office and were running about 60 percent against
impeachment, he added.
</P>
<P>
   That division was quite apparent in the remarks at the town
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Morris, 16, of Greenwich, said: ``President Clinton is an
American citizen and should be treated as one, and lying in front
of a grand jury is a crime. And therefore, he should be impeached,
without a doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Manning, 54, said ``We should look at him,'' referring to
Clinton, ``as we look at ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays, who kept the town meeting going until late in the night,
said he would digest what he had heard and not divulge how he would
vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
