<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HARVARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RALLY AGAINST IMPEACHMENT AT HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (See also IMPEACH, IMPEACH-SCENE, IMPEACH-REPUBS, IMPEACH-DEMS,
IMPEACH-SENATE, IMPEACH-RULES, IMPEACH-LOBBY, IMPEACH-SHAYS,
IMPEACH-VOICES, IMPEACH-MODERATES, IMPEACH-TV-RATINGS,
IMPEACH-REPORT, IMPEACH-BOEHLERT, IMPEACH-KELLY, IMPEACH-HARVARD,
IMPEACH-TEXT). 
(mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ In what was billed as ``an old-fashioned New
England town hall meeting,'' a group of academics and Democratic
lawmakers rallied to President Clinton's defense at Harvard
University Tuesday night, urging Americans to take a stand against
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Martin Meehan and Edward Markey, both Massachusetts
Democrats, were joined by the Harvard professors Cornel West, Alan
Dershowitz and Phillip Heyman; former Labor Secretary Robert Reich,
and others in condemning the Republican Party for its drive to
impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., a member of the House Judiciary
Committee, told the rally by phone that ``today we begin an effort
to repudiate the right wing and to take back the country from this
small, angry, hateful group.''
</P>
<P>
   Markey said: ``Today GOP stands for `get our president.'''
</P>
<P>
   About 500 students, faculty members and others packed the
Science Center auditorium while a few hundred more listened to
loudspeakers outside. Some carried pro-Clinton signs while others
had banners that read, ``Impeach the liar.''
</P>
<P>
   Reich, now a professor at Brandeis University, stood before a
banner that read ``Listen to the people'' and urged voters to hold
Republicans accountable for allowing an impeachment when they are
up for re-election in two years.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton was not spared from attack by the speakers. Robert
Brustein, the artistic director of the American Repertory Theater,
upbraided the president for his domestic policies and his personal
infidelities, but saw no legal basis for an impeachment. Brustein
said, ``Perhaps President Clinton should tattoo a scarlet letter
onto his forehead and get back to work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2315EST &QL; 
