<HEADLINE>
SCHOLARS REQUEST ALGER HISS GRAND JURY RECORDS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fifty years after Alger Hiss was indicted for perjury
in an espionage case that stirred fears that Communists had
infiltrated the federal government, a group of scholars asked a
federal judge in Manhattan on Tuesday to unseal the grand jury
records in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The petition not only seeks to shed light on one of the most
divisive issues of the Cold War, it is also aims to establish a
legal precedent that would allow for the release of secret grand
jury testimony in certain investigations of historical importance.
</P>
<P>
   The historians requesting access to the Hiss records said that
despite new disclosures from American and Soviet archives, the New
York grand jury materials remain one of the last significant
repositories of secret information about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Hiss, a former State Department official, was convicted of
perjury in 1950 for lying about whether he passed secrets to
Whittaker Chambers, an agent of the Soviet Union. He served 44
months in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The historians seeking the grand jury evidence said that the
materials, only parts of which have become public, could shed light
on Hiss' activities and those of his opponents, including Richard
Nixon, then a congressman, who testified before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The historians called their effort bipartisan, and cited wide
support, including the backing of Hiss' son, writer Tony Hiss, and
critics, like William F. Buckley Jr., the editor and columnist who
was a friend of Chambers, Hiss' chief accuser.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father believed that vindication would come to him only
when ever fact was spread out in front of everyone,'' Tony Hiss
said at a news conference Tuesday, adding that his father had tried
for years to have the materials made public, and that he was
confident the records would support his father's innocence. Alger
Hiss died in 1996 at age 92.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, speaking by phone later Tuesday, said he agreed there
was ``a legitimate historical interest'' in making the records
public, but said they would add only ``historical embellishments''
to the case.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley said in a court submission that he thought Chambers
would have supported release of the grand jury records, ``as they
would present all the evidence upon which the grand jury relied in
indicting Hiss, and would provide another counterpoint to what
Chambers believed were the false and incomplete accounts of the
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The group seeking the records was represented by the Public
Citizen Litigation Group, which was founded by Ralph Nader and has
been involved in other suits seeking access to government records.
</P>
<P>
   One of the group's lawyers, David Vladeck, said it hoped to
surmount the courts' reluctance to lift the veil on grand jury
secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   The group lost a similar lawsuit in a different case in 1997, he
said, but the federal appeals panel that ruled against it did lay
out certain circumstances under which such records might be made
public.
</P>
<P>
   Vladeck said the Hiss case met those standards. They included
the wide interest in the matter, the length of time since the grand
jury investigation ended and the death of most of the principals in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that grand jury secrecy does foster important
values,'' Vladeck said, ``but at some point those values erode and
historical interest in seeing those documents takes precedence.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the U.S. Attorney's office in Manhattan, which
opposed release of grand jury records in the 1997 case, said the
office had not yet seen the new petition and would have no comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Those requesting the Hiss records included the American
Historical Association, American Society of Legal History,
Organization of American Historians and Society of American
Archivists.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hiss said records are being sought from the FBI and the
House Committee on Un-American Activities.
</P>
<P>
   One scholar, Sam Tanenhaus, author of ``Whittaker Chambers,''
said that the grand jury records were unlikely to exonerate Hiss,
but they might illuminate other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The records could offer a fuller account of what Hiss and
Chambers told the grand jury and present a clearer picture of the
underground Communist movement, which remains mysterious in many
respects to this day,'' said Tanenhaus, who is an editor of the
Op-Ed page of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Weinstein, author of ``Perjury: The Hiss-Chambers Case,''
said many new details would become available should the grand jury
materials be opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``But as to whether this is going to somehow transform our
understanding of the case, I think the answer would be no,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
