<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT LEGISLATORS APPROVE DEAL FOR A PATRIOTS STADIUM
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE, Senate also approves deal;
Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``This is ... ; SUBS 11th graf, Under the ...,
to delete dollar-figure for stadium, which appears higher in
story.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo and graphic on proposed stadium are being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Concluding that big-league status was worth an
expensive gamble, the Connecticut General Assembly voted Tuesday
night to build a $375 million stadium for the New England Patriots
in downtown Hartford and committed millions more to help fill it
with fans.
</P>
<P>
   The approval came after eight hours of debate during a one-day
special session, with opponents complaining that the bill had been
rushed and that crucial details remained unknown. Gov. John G.
Rowland has said he wil sign the bill in the next several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will give Hartford one of 31 National Football League
franchises, which even local boosters had considered to be a pipe
dream just a month ago. ``This will change the landscape of
Hartford and the way we look at our capital city for the rest of
our lives,'' Rowland declared.
</P>
<P>
   The House approved the measure by a 97-49 vote, and the Senate
followed with a 27-8 vote. Rowland, a Republican, got solid support
from his own party, while Democrats were divided.
</P>
<P>
   Several leading sports economists said the package was
unnecessarily generous to the Patriots and constituted the most
lucrative lease ever won by the owner of a professional team. In
Tuesday's debate, opponents worried that the stadium would tie
legislators' hands for years to come and load more debt onto a
state with a below-average credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fleecing of Connecticut,'' said state Rep. John
Wayne Fox, a Democrat from Stamford. ``It is unconscionable that we
would incur this unknown expense. We don't have answers to our
liability, to certain basic questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who favored the stadium countered that it was a chance to
transform Hartford's blighted riverfront and generate excitement in
the city, the nation's insurance capital, which has had little to
cheer for in the decades that manufacturing plants have been moving
out and corporations have been consolidating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a message to out-of-state businesses that Hartford is
not a city that's going to lay down and die,'' Rep. Edward C.
Graziani, a Democrat from Ellington, said during Tuesday's debate.
``You will have tens of millions of people seeing on their screen
the city of Hartford.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of House Democrats failed in their effort to retain the
rights to sell the stadium's name, which will go to the Patriots
and can be worth tens of millions of dollars. ``We are funding the
stadium 100 percent, but we're not recognizing any of the
benefits,'' said Rep. Stephen Dargan.
</P>
<P>
   Renee A. Boicourt, managing director for state ratings at
Moody's Investors Service, said the vote moved Connecticut in the
opposite direction of many states during the current economic boom
by adding debt instead of paying it. ``This move will compound an
already weak financial picture, and take away some of the long-term
upside potential,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the state will build an open-air stadium on
the Connecticut River and provide it to the team rent free for 30
years. The team is assured a profit by a provision that requires
the state to pay as much as $13 million a year if luxury seats or
suites go unsold.
</P>
<P>
   State budget officials estimate that, considering inflation,
those guarantees will amount to $1 billion over the 30 years of the
lease. But the state and Patriots owner Robert Kraft have vowed to
work together to sell the seats so that few, if any, guarantees
will ever have to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium, which will have 68,000 seats and a grass field, is
supposed to be ready by the fall of 2001, but state officials have
told the Patriots that the completion date could well slip by a
season. The stadium, which will be shared with the University of
Connecticut, will provide a centerpiece for a long-dreamed-of
development known as Adriaen's Landing, which is to include a
hotel, shops and a convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Connecticut officials had feared that they were being
used as a bargaining chip by Kraft, who had spent years trying to
negotiate a subsidy for a new stadium from the Massachusetts
legislature. But Kraft said Tuesday that he would not give
Massachusetts a chance to match the Connecticut offer. ``If it's
passed, we're coming,'' he said Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The project faces several more hurdles. A steam plant is now on
the land and moving it could cost as much as $100 million _ none of
which is included in the budget for the stadium. The ground is also
contaminated with coal tar left over from a gas plant that operated
there from the late 1800s until 1950.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
