COLTS vs. GIANTS, DEC. 28, 1958: THE MOST IMPORTANT GAME EVER? 
 (bl) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The National Football League calls it the Greatest
Game Ever Played. Wellington Mara, an owner of the New York Giants
then and now, said Pete Rozelle, later the NFL commissioner,
``always told me that the reason pro football took off was because
that game happened just at that time, in that season, and it
happened in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Frank, a television executive, said, ``It was the moment
when sports became something the networks had to carry.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the NFL championship game on Dec. 28, 1958, a game in
which the Baltimore Colts beat the Giants, 23-17, on Alan Ameche's
1-yard plunge in sudden death. To touch off the 40th-anniversary
celebration, the NFL conducted a teleconference Tuesday with four
Hall of Fame players from that game _ Johnny Unitas and Artie
Donovan of the Colts, and Frank Gifford and Sam Huff of the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Their hourlong byplay sounded like four guys standing around a
bar remembering the good old days. Not all seemed convinced it was
the best football game ever played.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played better games,'' Unitas said. ``We came back once
from 28-7 at halftime against San Francisco and scored 28 points
and beat them. But I think this game accelerated football into what
it is now. It was going to happen anyway, but the way the game was
tied and then with the first overtime ever played, all the things
added up.''
</P>
<P>
   As Gifford recalled: ``It was a great game and had a lot of
drama to it. It brought great focus to pro football that wasn't
there before. And maybe it had the best personnel ever accumulated
on a football field at once until that time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 12 players and three coaches in that game were elected
to the Pro Football Hall of Fame. The players are Unitas, Donovan,
Gino Marchetti, Raymond Berry, Jim Parker and Lenny Moore of the
Colts, and Gifford, Huff, Roosevelt Brown, Andy Robustelli, Emlen
Tunnell and Don Maynard of the Giants. The coaches are Weeb Ewbank,
the Colts' head coach, and Vince Lombardi and Tom Landry, the
Giants' coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   Tunnell, Ewbank and Lombardi are dead. The 12 others are being
invited to take part in the coin flip for next month's Super Bowl
XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   Huff's memories of the game are not that fond. For him, the
villain was the 25-year-old Unitas, a quarterback two years removed
from the Pittsburgh sandlots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny knew where to attack,'' Huff said. ``He found the
weakness in our defense and exploited it to perfection. It was
Unitas to Berry, Unitas to Berry. After 40 years, that still rings
in my ears. Unitas to Berry.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was doubly disappointing, Huff said, ``because it was a
championship game and I needed the cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Each winning player earned $4,718.77, each losing player
$3,111.33. And the post-game celebration was modest, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see guys pouring champagne over each other now,'' Donovan
said. ``You know what we had? Orange soda. A lot of us went through
a war, and we get orange soda.''
</P>
<P>
   They also got a piece of history. Gifford said the game brought
tremendous attention to professional football. Huff said it helped
bring recognition to the defenses. Donovan called it ``a game that
put the NFL on the way to bigger and better things.''
</P>
<P>
   Others remembered the game, too. One was a 17-year-old
high-school player named Bill Parcells, who slipped away from a
skating party on Lake Hopatcong in New Jersey and sat in a car for
three hours listening to the game.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Bert Bell, the NFL commissioner, had tears in
his eyes because he knew what this event would mean to his sport.
Buzz Nutter, the Colts' center, chased a security guard to retrieve
the game ball and presented it to Marchetti, who broke his right
leg in the fourth quarter. Ameche bolted from the locker room to
appear for $500 that night on ``The Ed Sullivan Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Colts and Giants agreed that today's game was much
different. Huff, who does interview shows on radio before and after
Washington Redskins games, told this story about an off-the-air
chat with Michael Westbrook, the Redskins' 26-year-old wide
receiver:
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Hey, man, you ever play this game?' I didn't
want to show him the Hall of Fame ring on my finger, so I said,
`Michael, I played this game, and some people thought I played it
real well.'''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
