<HEADLINE>
JOUSTING FOR A SONG 
WEIGHTY MATTERS 
WANTED: MONICA'S DRESS
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By JAMES BARRON WITH BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He signed his affidavit with his full name, James Paul
McCartney.
</P>
<P>
   The former Beatle, who scribbled some of the rock era's most
famous hits in the same hard-to-read handwriting, sent his lawyers
to court hoping to force the return of the original lyric sheet for
``Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band.'' He said the lyric sheet,
which has several splotchy cross-outs that suggest that McCartney
reworked the words as he was going along, had been stolen from his
house in London 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The brouhaha began in August, when a collector, Gary Zimet of
Washingtonville, N.Y., offered to sell the lyric sheet page to
McCartney for $550,000.
</P>
<P>
   Zimet denied that the lyric sheet was stolen. ``This is par for
the course,'' Zimet said. ``As a musician, he's a genius. As a
human being, he's beneath contempt. He's a $900 million dollar
gorilla throwing his weight around.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimet said he did not own the lyric sheet. He maintained that it
belonged to a collector he would not identify, adding that he had
got in touch with McCartney without telling the collector he was
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   The collector's lawyer, Peter Cane, who also refused to identify
the collector, said the collector had obtained the lyric sheet
legitimately. ``As far as I know,'' Cane said, ``the first claim he
made that it was stolen was after he was alerted to how much it was
worth.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer representing McCartney, Alan Friedman of Manhattan,
did not return a call seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral Diet Tips
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is continuing what might be
called a City Hall tradition of diet consciousness. After all, Ed
Koch appeared in commercials for the diet drink Ultra Slim-Fast
(though not until after his term was over).
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Giuliani said he had lost 28 pounds in the last four
months.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor made the disclosure in response to a question from
Rafael Martinez Alequin, a regular at City Hall news briefings who
publishes a newspaper called The Free Press. Martinez observed that
the mayor appeared to have lost weight, and asked if he was
slimming down in preparation for running for something.
</P>
<P>
   And he did not mean next year's New York City Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diet's great,'' the mayor declared. ``I may write a book
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Diet? What diet? Pritikin or Scarsdale, perhaps, or Bronx? Or
Weight Watchers or Jenny Craig?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken, fish, lots of salad,'' he said. ``Limit the amount of
bread you eat.''
</P>
<P>
   No pizza? ``Well,'' the mayor acknowledged, ``every once in a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Pasta? ``Every once in a while, but not too much,'' Giuliani
said, ``and exercise every morning for about 20 minutes or a
half-hour.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not elaborate on what kind of exercise he favored. Nor
would aides say what his weight and height are these days.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit A, Maybe
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was inevitable: Someone wants to buy the notorious Gap
dress that Monica Lewinsky turned over to the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalie Osias, a Long Island lawyer, said she wanted the dress _
and the T-shirt the president brought back from the Black Dog
restaurant on Martha's Vineyard _ for a traveling exhibit
``dedicated to showing the realities of women in the 20th-century
workplace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important that we preserve the historical record intact,
especially from Monica's point of view,'' said Ms. Osias, adding
that her Osias Foundation had given Ms. Lewinsky $10,000 several
months ago when one of Ms. Lewinsky's lawyers appealed for
contributions.
</P>
</TEXT>
