<HEADLINE>
ALUMINUM BATS FACE REVISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The ``ping'' that has defined college baseball for 24
years may endure for another season after an NCAA committee Tuesday
came to a different conclusion about the future of aluminum bats
than other members of the governing body.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA Championship/Competition Cabinet voted to decrease the
diameter of aluminum bats and reduce the length-to-width
differential for the 1999 postseason. But it opted not to limit
batted ball exit speed as suggested by the Division I baseball
committee, a proposal that bat manufacturers insisted would render
them incapable of creating an acceptable product in time for the
postseason and force a return by college teams to wooden bats.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA says balls coming off aluminum bats achieve such speed
_ up to 113 mph _ that they are dangerous, especially to pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that point, we were uncomfortable setting that standard,''
said Jean Lenti Ponsetto, the cabinet's chairwoman and senior
associate athletic director at DePaul. ``But we still feel we're
minimizing the risk for the student-athlete. And that was our
priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee voted to decrease bat diameter from 2} inches to
2| and reduce length-to-width differential from five to three. In
other words, a 34-inch bat could be no lighter than 31 ounces, a
change that would reduce bat speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the best compromise,'' ASU Coach Pat Murphy said.
``It was their way of saying, `Let's show our interest in making
the game more safe.' I think eventually you'll see the bats play
more like wood and have the game the way it was meant to be
played.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision now goes to the Executive Committee, which is one
of numerous committees to attack the issues in the past five
months. A verdict is expected soon because most teams open formal
workouts in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA said it initiated bat standard changes because of
concern for player safety, but the integrity of the game also has
come under scrutiny. Sixty-two home runs were hit in this year's
College World Series, 14 more than the previous record. ASU lost to
Southern California, 21-14, in the title game.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the bats beyond the 1999 postseason is
undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Executive Committee's decision will not impact the
regular season, it likely will prompt moves by individual
conferences. The Pac-10 Conference Council already forwarded a
proposal on bat standards for the 1999 regular season to the
league's chief executive officers on the heels of the NCAA's
decision. The proposal is similar to the NCAA
Championship/Competition Cabinet's suggestions, plus it states that
league teams shall use only aluminum bats by companies that will
provide to the league ``a defense and indemnification from
lawsuits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent an exhaustive amount of time on this,'' Pac-10
Commissioner Tom Hansen said. ``Because of the legal issues, we
have had long conversations with manufacturers, coaches, lawyers
and officials at each university.''
</P>
<P>
   Money and legalities are as much at the heart of this issue as
anything.
</P>
<P>
   The return to wooden bats, which still is a possibility, would
hit coaches hard. About 150 Division I coaches are under contract
to bat companies, which pay them up to $80,000 and provide free
aluminum bats to their teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a lot for our programs and do a lot for our coaches,''
Murphy said. ``We probably wouldn't all be under contract with
woods because the wooden bat market is the pros, and the aluminum
bat market is college baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy admitted the possible return to wooden bats has made him
``take a good, hard look at what I'm doing, and the reasons I feel
the way I do about wooden bats. Is it money? Or is it the game? The
integrity of the game is what should matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Easton Sports, one of the two biggest manufacturers of aluminum
bats, is suing the NCAA for $267 million, alleging restraint of
trade. Chairman Jim Easton was in Europe on Tuesday and could not
be reached for comment. &QL; 
Cedric Dempsey, NCAA executive director, has alerted university
executives to potential legal risk if they use the previously
allowed bats this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
