<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-GARDENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES MAKE FINAL APPEAR ANCE AT GAR DENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ One by one, they have toppled like a house of cards,
historical landmarks that painted indelible memories for one
generation to the next and so on, plowed away, stripped down and
forgotten in the name of progress, luxury suites and revenue
streams.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL has said goodbye to many of its famous old arenas in
recent years. See ya, Chicago Stadium. Later, Boston Garden. Adieu,
The Forum in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Coyotes will pay their final visit and respects to
the great Maple Leaf Gardens, the oldest remaining hockey building
in the league, when they meet the Toronto Maple Leafs at 5:30 p.m.
The Maple Leafs are moving out of the 68-year-old building later
this season to play in a new arena several blocks away called the
Air Canada Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough, there's a ton of history in that
place,'' said Coyotes forward Keith Tkachuk, who might not even be
able to play because of slight groin pull. ``All the old buildings
are coming down, though, and this is the last one. It's a little
sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The fabled Gardens, which opened its doors on Nov. 12, 1931 _ a
2-1 Toronto loss to the visiting Chicago Blackhawks _ will close on
Feb. 13. Ironically, Chicago will be the visitor in the final game.
Ticket scalpers reportedly are getting as much as $5,000 a seat for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin and Jimmy Waite, the Coyotes' two goalies,
wanted to draw straws for the honor to get today's semi-historical
start. Alas, Coach Jim Schoenfeld isn't one to let his goalies make
those decisions. He will go with Khabibulin, who has stopped 75 of
the past 77 shots he has faced in his past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most famous building left in the NHL,'' said
Khabibulin, who is 9-5-1 with a 2.22 goals-against average lifetime
against the Maple Leafs. ``I've always loved playing there. The
fans are so close to you, so loud, and the boards there seem to
make everything faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone on the Coyotes has a favorite story or
special moment about Maple Leaf Gardens. From rookie Bryan Helmer,
who as a kid, used to take a train here from his small hometown
outside of Ottawa to come watch the Maple Leafs play the Canadiens.
To veteran Jyrki Lumme, who first skated on the arena's ice as a
teenager for Finland in the 1986 Junior World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Simmer, the Coyotes' color commentator on television
broadcasts, said he had one of his best and one of his worst
experiences in The Grand Ol' Dame during his illustrious NHL
playing career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played there when I was in juniors with Sault Ste. Marie,''
Simmer, 43, said, ``and when I turned pro the next year, I was able
to get in there in my third game and score a goal, get an assist
and get a second star award. Growing up in Canada, to skate out
after the game for a second star, or any star at all, was something
I'll never forget. I was shaking for days after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Simmer, who hails from nearby Terrace Bay, Ontario, won't forget
another particular moment here some years later. He entered that
particular game with 56 goals under his belt with a month and a
half remaining in the season. That night, he broke his leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I walk into that building now, I look just inside
the blue line and go, `A lot of pain happened right there,' ''
Simmer said. ``It had been such a good year for me up to that
night. It was disappointing that way in that it took me at least
three years to get back to form. That was the downside, but just to
get in there and play that one game and to skate out for a second
star one time, I could have quit right after that.''
</P>
<P>
   What if ``that'' had been the night he shattered his leg?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still would have walked out there for that second star _
without crutches, too,'' he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Waite's fondest memory of the Gardens had nothing to do with
hockey at all. It happened a year ago, on Nov. 8, and he spent most
of the game in the visitor's locker room talking on a cell phone to
someone thousands of miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the night my son (Brendon) was born,'' Waite said.
``We were playing here and I couldn't get home, and since I wasn't
playing, I spent most of my time in the dressing room talking to
(wife) Nancy while she was in labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Brendon arrived about an hour after the game, while Waite and
the rest of the Coyotes were on a bus ride to the Toronto airport
for a flight back to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there many times and played a few games in that
building, and it's one of the greatest places to play,'' Waite
said, ``but that night will still always be my best memory of Maple
Leaf Gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how center Jeremy Roenick must feel. The former Chicago
Blackhawk has had some of his finest moments ever at Maple Leaf
Gardens. His 36 goals and 74 points against the Maple Leafs are by
far his most against any other NHL team. He also recorded his first
career hat trick here nine years ago this month. And today,
appropriately enough, will mark his 700th career NHL game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be fun,'' Roenick said. ``Hopefully, I can do
big things like I have there in recent years. I'll miss that
building probably more than I'll miss any building.''
</P>
<P>
   More than old Chicago Stadium, where he was the last Blackhawk
to score a goal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no,'' Roenick said. ``I was going to say, `Except for
Chicago Stadium.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
