<DOCNO> NYT19981215.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 23:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1920 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-COACH-STRES     12-15 0793
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-COACH-STRESS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIM TOBIN KNOWS HEALTH RISKS  
 DITKA, REEVES SERVE AS EXAMPLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin used to jog until bad
knees forced him to quit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he rides a stationary bike, not just to keep a boyish
figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good therapy to get the poison out of your system,''
Tobin said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, 55, is under a lot of stress these days as the Cardinals
(7-7) try to reach the NFC playoffs for the first time in a
non-strike season since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   He was just arriving for work Monday morning when Atlanta
Falcons Coach Dan Reeves, 54, checked into a hospital because of
heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hits home,'' Tobin said. ``Here's a guy who was very
healthy, very vibrant, coaching one day, and the next day, he's at
the hospital getting ready for an operation for four bypasses. It
puts you back to reality. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``You are well aware that it can strike you very quickly. Life
can change very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years earlier, Tobin became interim coach of the Chicago
Bears when Coach Mike Ditka suffered a mild heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin will meet Ditka's New Orleans Saints on Sunday at Sun
Devil Stadium in the most meaningful game the Cardinals have played
since moving to Arizona in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka began feeling poorly after working out at the Bears' Lake
Forest, Ill., practice facility on Nov. 2, 1988. The team had just
come off a 30-7 loss at New England.
</P>
<P>
   Paramedics were called, and Ditka was taken in an ambulance to a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike always worked out,'' Tobin said. ``He took it to a point
where he you would think he was dying, he worked out so hard. He
had a rubber sweat suit he used to wear. He used to drive himself.
He was obsessive in the way he did things.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ditka didn't lose his sense of humor. He told former teammate
Ed O'Bradovich after the heart attack, ``Damn, I thought I was
going to die, and I hadn't gotten my hole-in-one yet.'')
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, defensive coordinator of the Bears at the time, was put
in charge and ran the Bears for two games, guiding them to
victories over Tampa Bay and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Former St. Louis Rams Coach Rich Brooks, now defensive
coordinator of the Falcons, will guide the team in Reeves' absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rich has been a head coach,'' Tobin said. ``For me, it was
uncharted waters. I never dreamed I would be named (interim coach).
There were a lot of coaches on that staff who had been there a lot
longer than I had been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to bring to the fore what your strengths and
attributes are. But you know it's on an interim basis, so you don't
throw out the baby with the bathwater, so to speak. It's your job
to do the things you think are necessary to give you the best
chance of winning because it's your ship you are steering at that
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka was in intensive care when the Bears, under Tobin, beat
the Buccaneers. Ditka was on the sidelines the next week in
Washington but sat on the bench and didn't get involved in
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said he doesn't fear that he could suffer a similar fate
of Ditka and Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   He works out two to three times a week, lifting weights and
riding the stationary bike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps (combat) stress, and he does his workouts
religiously,'' said Cardinals trainer John Omohundro, who has been
with the team for 32 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Cardinals defensive coordinator Chuck Drulis
suffered a fatal heart attack on the team's chartered plane flight
from St. Louis to Houston. The plane made an emergency stop in
Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Now, team medical officials carry a defibrillator and a cardiac
crash kit on the plane for such emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think coaches are different than other people in
high-pressure situations in regular society,'' Omohundro said.
``The thing that's beneficial is they work in an area in which they
are subjected to a lot of opportunities to work out and have some
level of physical fitness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals require their coaches to have an annual physical
examination. As part of that exam, the coaches take cardiac stress
tests and have their blood fat and cholesterol levels checked.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin, whose team has played seven games that have been decided
by four points or less, said he is able to get over tough losses
fairly quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a pretty good way of enjoying the moment the night of
the game,'' he said. ``The next morning, you still are hanging over
from it a little bit, but I can get rid of it and go on to the next
(game). Some people have a hard time ever turning loose a game that
it lost in the last few seconds. I've really never had that
problem. I'm ready to go to the next game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-15-98 2334EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
