<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-15 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1923 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SAINTS-DITKA-AZR &LR;      12-15 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SAINTS-DITKA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MELLOWING OF MIKE  
 DITKA SUCCEEDS AFTER GETTING HANDLE ON SELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS - Here in the Big Hangover, in a city where you can
find anything and most of it trouble, the face of football has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   It happened long after the heart attack that sidelined him for,
oh, seven days. After he threw his gum at a fan in San Francisco.
After inviting Doug Flutie to Thanksgiving dinner, infuriating the
rest of his team. After foolishly siding with his replacement
players during the 1987 strike. After challenging a listener to a
fight during his weekly radio show, issuing his address over the
air.
</P>
<P>
   It happened long after he started opening beer bottles with his
teeth. After climbing into the stands trying to attack a heckler in
Tampa. After publicly humiliating Jim Harbaugh on the sidelines in
Minnesota. After selling his image to every taker, and inevitably,
buying it himself.
</P>
<P>
   And it happened shortly after paying off a bet on the sidelines.
After lambasting his new city for its lack of hygiene. After a
roller-coaster debut season in which he wept in his wife's arms
after a loss, threatening to surrender before the season was over.
</P>
<P>
   But it happened.
</P>
<P>
   After 11 years in Chicago, where Mike Ditka was more myth than
reality, after taking a job that had people questioning his sanity,
Ditka is revealing the fiber lining the legend. And across the
country, people are raving about the job he's done resurrecting the
New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very sympathetic,'' Ditka said with a gleam in his
eyes. ``They know I'm getting old and weary. That I'll be done one
of these days and they want to say he was a good chap.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's something different.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things have changed in his heart,'' Saints
quarterback Danny Wuerffel said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Ditka will bring his Saints to Sun Devil Stadium.
They are 6-8, an average team with no offense, yet a team still
alive in the playoff hunt. They play hard and with enthusiasm.
Their defense is in constant attack mode and has scored eight
touchdowns. They are the only NFL team to have never won a playoff
game, but suddenly, there is a future. And much of it comes from
Ditka, who is producing his best season ever as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in it,'' Ditka said. ``If we win two games, we
might be in it. We've got to win this football game. That's all
that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, something has changed. Ditka is 59, in the autumn of life,
and there is much fodder for the reincarnation. His father died in
November. He is now deeply religious, and after every home game
last season, he would drive 30 miles to a seminary and pray. He no
longer yells at players in public. He's sworn off swearing and
alcohol, and any time he breaks his new vow, he contributes money
to a special fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been pretty good,'' Ditka said. ``I might say heck or
darn once in a while, but I don't say very much. I gave them a
couple of bucks early in the year because I said a couple of
things. But the word I've tried to stop saying, I've stopped
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he is coaching with great maturity and perspective.
Spreading his will and belief without letting his intensity
scramble the signal. He is in control of his team because he's in
control of himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see someone that's intense and competitive,'' Wuerffel said.
``That isn't going to change because that gives him the edge. But
what people don't see is a guy who has really got a big heart. A
guy who is extremely loyal and fair, and extremely compassionate,
believe it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another reason, too, and it's probably the biggest
trigger in the return to prominence. It's called denial, and five
years after a painful termination to an act gone stale, Ditka is
finally over the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   See, it didn't matter that he should've won multiple Super Bowls
in Chicago, that he dramatically underachieved with great talent,
that from 1984-91 his regular season record was 90-37 while his
playoff mark was a suspicious 6-6. Or, by his own admission, how
anyone could've coached the Bears to a title in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Point is, he was handpicked by George Halas, thereby directly
linked to the origin of the game. He was everything Chicago craved
in a football coach, from the bravado to the mouth that roared. He
was the tough kid from Pennsylvania, son of a railroad worker, the
coach who pulled no punches yet was more than willing to throw a
few. He even looked like a bear, eerily resembling the team logo.
</P>
<P>
   For over a decade, he was king. He was Chicago. And to lose all
of that was more painful than he ever realized.
</P>
<P>
   It is why he took four years off, refusing to interview for
jobs. Why he was an emotional wreck in his rookie season with New
Orleans. Why his wife threw out a room full of priceless
memorabilia last fall _ including the game plan from Super Bowl XX,
the one Ditka had in his hand as he was carried off the field _ and
ordered a trash collector to take it all away.
</P>
<P>
   (The stunned garbage man did just that. He took it right to an
auctioneer, who began selling the items via catalog.)
</P>
<P>
   And it is why, as recently as last summer, Ditka trashed New
Orleans in a ``Sports Illustrated'' cover story, calling the city
``filthy,'' and how he cut short his only visit to Bourbon Street
because he ``couldn't stand the riot of drunks spilling out of
nightclubs and strip joints.''
</P>
<P>
   It is why the mayor of New Orleans responded with the obvious,
that Ditka was homesick for Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But somewhere along the line, that changed. Ditka finally let go
of the past and embraced the new challenge. He signed a five-year
extension in August. He's committed himself to the Saints, to
finishing what he started.
</P>
<P>
   For all his tough talk, it took a while, longer than he
realized. But Ditka is finally liberated from the baggage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other colors don't look like they ever belonged to me,''
Ditka said. ``That's the way I feel. I want to prove to the people
of New Orleans that I am them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ditka is now a Saint. In more ways than anyone ever thought
possible. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
