<HEADLINE>
GAME'S IMPORTANCE OUTWEIGHS INJURIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - The availability of several Cardinals' injured
players could be affected by the enormous stakes of this week's
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are ready to help us, we certainly will use them,''
Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin said. ``There is no sense saving them
for the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals enter Sunday's game against New Orleans trying to
secure an NFC wild-card playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   They hope to get the return of middle linebacker  &UR; Ronald
McKinnon (knee), cornerback  &UR; Tom Knight (hamstring) and defensive
tackle  &UR; Mark Smith (ankle).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, offensive guard  &UR; Matt Joyce and running back
 &UR; Michael Pittman will try to practice today despite still not being
fully recovered from broken hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to practice with a ball (cast) on their
hands,'' Tobin said. ``We will have to determine whether they can
help us playing one-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce hasn't played since Nov. 15 against Dallas. Pittman
suffered his injury 10 days ago against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon has been out for the past two games. Knight has missed
three straight games, and Smith sat out last week's 20-17 overtime
victory at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon and Smith likely could start if they are healthy.
Knight would play behind rookie cornerback  &UR; Corey Chavous, who has
started three consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to risk their health if they come back and play
before they are ready,'' Tobin said. ``We need to see if they can
play better (in their condition) than the guys who have been
playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can't run or move, no matter how willing the heart is,
I don't know how much they could help us.'' &QL; 
Elite company
</P>
<P>
   Running back  &UR; Adrian Murrell needs only 48 rushing yards in the
next two games to become the eighth active player to gain 1,000
yards in three or more consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's  &UR; Barry Sanders has done it 10 consecutive years, two
more than Dallas'  &UR; Emmitt Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Three players _  &UR; Terrell Davis of the Denver Broncos,  &UR; Curtis
Martin of the New York Jets and  &UR; Ricky Watters of the Seattle
Seahawks _ have rushed for more than 1,000 yards the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jamal Anderson of Atlanta and  &UR; Eddie George of Tennessee have
broke the 1,000 barrier each of the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Murrell has gained 952 yards and six touchdowns on 237 carries. &QL; 
Little pressure
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have gone without a sack in their past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Tobin thinks that's related to the struggle their injury-riddled
defense has had in stopping the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're holding for life trying to stop the run, it's hard
to rush the passer,'' Tobin said. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Ticket sales for Sunday's game have been steady the past two
days, but the team had sold only 38,396 as of early afternoon
Tuesday, more than 34,000 shy of a sellout.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the second week of the season, the
Cardinals aren't in the plus-category in turnover ratio. An
interception and lost fumble against the Eagles dropped them to
even. They have 33 takeaways and 33 giveaways.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver  &UR; Frank Sanders has dropped out of the NFC lead in
receptions. He has 71, two behind leader Jerry Rice of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are ranked 15th in the NFL on offense and 19th on
defense.
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans is 29th on offense, 30th in rushing. They are 27th
on defense, last against the pass. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
